<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REMEDY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT OFFERS TO CHANGE SOME BUSINESS PRACTICES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RICHMAN  
 and CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Microsoft on Wednesday said it would change some
business practices to avoid what it called the government's
``draconian'' proposal to split the company in two.
</P>
<P>
   The Redmond, Wash., software giant rejected the breakup proposed
by the Department of Justice and 17 of the 19 plaintiff states,
consenting instead to ease controls it had imposed on computer
makers, share more technical information, and stop trying to
control whether customer companies can also sell non-Microsoft
software.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's proposal contained few surprises, largely conforming
to media predictions over the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also laid out a range of timetable options for future
proceedings that could postpone into 2001 a judge's order on how
Microsoft should be curbed from continuing to break federal
antitrust laws.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs quickly dismissed Microsoft's proposal as
inadequate, while Washington state politicians jumped to defend a
company that is vital to their region's economic well-being. One
legal expert said it reflects ``a number of wise choices'' and is
``well thought-out.''
</P>
<P>
   In an eight-page document filed with Judge Thomas Penfield
Jackson after the close of the stock markets Wednesday, Microsoft
agreed to refrain from some of the conduct that the judge on April
3 ruled violated the Sherman Antitrust Act.
</P>
<P>
   It agreed to let computer vendors display icons for
non-Microsoft software, offer their own Internet sign-up process,
delete the Internet Explorer icon from pre-installed copies of
Windows, and permit buyers to choose any browser as their default
and to remove the IE icon if that's not their choice. IE will
remain part of the operating system, however.
</P>
<P>
   The company also said it won't promote any product to induce
another party to limit how much non-Microsoft software it
distributes. And it said it will share with any commercial software
vendor some technical information _ not the source code the
plaintiffs' proposal demands, but only ``information already made
available to the development community at large'' on how to write
applications that run under Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Even that disclosure, Microsoft said, must protect the company's
intellectual property, and may be subject to fees. Microsoft says
the plaintiffs' proposal ``confiscates'' Microsoft's intellectual
property, which chairman Bill Gates has long maintained is
essential to competition in the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's proposal is far less drastic than that of the
Justice Department and 17 plaintiffs, which seeks to split
Microsoft into two companies, one dealing with the Windows
operating system and the other with applications such as Office.
The two companies would be limited in their interactions.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the 19 states joining in the suit, Ohio and Illinois,
advocate steps short of a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Under the governments' proposal, Microsoft would also be
required to widely disclose source code and other information about
how applications connect to Windows. And the plaintiffs impose more
stringent restrictions than Microsoft on how it can deal with
computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate 16-page filing, Microsoft on Wednesday also set
out five timing scenarios, keyed to which pieces of whose proposal
Jackson is considering.
</P>
<P>
   The quickest resolution would be reached if Jackson accepts
Microsoft's proposal, either as a final decree or as an interim
measure that would be put in place while Microsoft appeals
Jackson's ruling that it broke the law.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, if Jackson rejects Microsoft's proposal
and fully accepts that of the plaintiffs, Microsoft said it will
need until December to prepare its case.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Jackson accepted the least extreme remedy in the
antitrust case, Microsoft would appeal his conclusions that it's a
lawbreaker, chief counsel Bill Neukom said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever it begins, the remedy hearing will likely resemble a
full-blown trial, with witnesses called and cross-examined,
documents admitted into evidence, and its own set of deadlines,
experts said.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs are scheduled to respond to Microsoft's proposal
by May 17, and a hearing on each side's proposals _ not the remedy
hearing _ is still scheduled for May 24.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs lambasted Wednesday's filing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's proposal is ineffective and filled with
loopholes,'' the Justice Department said in a prepared statement.
``It would not have prevented Microsoft from engaging in many of
the illegal acts found by the District Court, nor would it prevent
the company from using its monopoly power in the future to engage
in the same kind of illegal behavior to crush new innovations.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft officials defended their effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has invited the court to destroy or hobble an
American company that is a model of success in the high technology
arena and to do so explicitly to reshape the single most productive
and envied industry in the United States. In contrast, Microsoft
has filed with the Court (a proposal) that fully addresses the
antitrust violations found by the Court in a manner consistent with
the law,'' Microsoft said in its legal papers.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Kovacic, an antitrust expert who teaches at George
Washington University in Washington, D.C., praised Microsoft's
filings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they made a number of wise choices Wednesday: making
an alternative proposal instead of saying `Nothing will do; all
this is nonsense'; writing a strong memo in support of their
proposal, and setting out their timetable in an appropriately
cautionary way.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the sliding-scale timetable ``is one way of saying `A
rush job won't do; breaking up the world's most significant
business enterprise is not something to approach casually,' and
that's an important point to make.''
</P>
<P>
   Kovacic predicted Jackson won't rule out any possible remedy and
will set the hearing to begin in September.
</P>
<P>
   Most of Washington state's most prominent political figures,
including Sens. Slade Gorton and Patty Murray, remain firmly behind
a company that is important to the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft's objections to the proposed break-up and
restrictions on their business practices are justified,'' Murray,
D-Wash., said. ``I remain confident that Microsoft is right on the
facts and ... am hopeful that a reasonable outcome will be found
without breaking up Microsoft.``
</P>
<P>
   Gorton, who has long complained about the Justice Department's
handing of the case, was even more blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on the Department of Justice and Judge Jackson to
listen to reason and leave the high tech industry alone,'' the
Republican senator said. ``The job growth fueled by Microsoft has
been phenomenal. Microsoft's hard-working employees have changed
the face of technology and positively impacted the daily lives of
millions of Americans who reap the benefits of their innovative
products. Why do we want to crush that success?''
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash., also came to the
company's defense, saying that public opinion remains behind
Microsoft and complaining that advancement in the fast moving
software world would suffer if the government prevails.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government should not do anything to hamper
innovation and the government would do that'' if it broke the
company apart, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
