<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCFLAG11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Carolina to move rebel flag
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Columbia, S.C. _ On South Carolina's Confederate Memorial Day, a
day the battle flag of the Confederacy burned literally and
figuratively, the state House voted to remove the controversial
banner from the capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
   As the votes were tabulated at 10:11 p.m. _ more than 12 hours
after the day's session convened _ legislators looked up anxiously
at the two large voting boards on either side of the chamber, like
nervous bettors watching the tote board at the track. The bill
passed 63-56.
</P>
<P>
   Just minutes before the vote, House Speaker David Wilkins
(R-Greenville) sighed and said to one of his colleagues, ``We're
right on top of it. It's tied.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilkins had taken the well to personally encourage support for a
compromise the Senate approved last month. The House slightly
modified the bill during two full days of debate.
</P>
<P>
   The principal remaining difference between the House and Senate
versions is how high the flag will fly and whether it will be
illuminated. The House bill approved Wednesday calls for a 30-foot
flag pole and lights at night. The Senate version says 20 feet for
the flag pole and no illumination.
</P>
<P>
   In the lobby between the House and Senate chambers, almost
directly below the capitol dome, Wilkins said he was proud of the
way his 123 members conducted themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment for our state,'' Wilkins said. ``I
think it's a giant step forward. This is a very decisive and
dignified action on the part of the South Carolina House. There
will be those that criticize this action, this compromise, some
that say we went too far, some saying we didn't go far enough. The
bottom line is we got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would remove the battle flag from the capitol dome and
move it to a prominent soldiers' memorial on the grounds July 1.
</P>
<P>
   It's expected South Carolina's decision will heat up a similar
debate in Georgia, which incorporates the Confederate battle emblem
into the state flag. Civil rights groups have threatened economic
boycotts of the Peach State if legislators don't change Georgia's
flag next year.
</P>
<P>
   In South Carolina, House Democrats struggled throughout the day
to find a compromise that black House members would support. But
their last-ditch efforts failed Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   That left many in the black legislative caucus in the ironic
position of having to vote to leave the Confederate battle flag _
co-opted as a symbol by some white supremacists groups _ over the
dome, where it has flown since 1962.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the Republican-controlled House passed a bill that
removes the battle flag from the dome and both chambers of the
General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of 26 black House members voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's great failing, according to many black legislators,
is that the battle flag would move to an even more prominent place
on the capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, at best, sends a mixed message and, I think, even a bad
message,'' said House Speaker Pro Tempore Terry Haskins
(R-Greenville). ``If the black members didn't vote for a plan that
takes the flag off the dome, that's hard to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan includes flying a square battle flag at the 38-foot
granite Confederate Soldiers Monument on the north mall of the
capitol, a highly visible intersection of Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not heal. This does not come close to healing,''
said House Minority leader Gilda Cobb-Hunter (D-Orangeburg), a key
black legislator. She voted against the bill. ``I'm tired of
sacrificing and giving all the time,'' Rep. Leon Howard, a black
Democrat from Columbia, said during a party caucus meeting before
the formal House debate. ``I'm not willing to sacrifice anymore. We
need to stop sacrificing principles.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
launched a tourism boycott of South Carolina on Jan. 1 and vowed to
keep it in place until the battle flag comes down. Officials from
the state NAACP monitored House debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can say is that not much there excites us,'' Dwight
James, South Carolina NAACP executive director, said outside the
House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   During a lunch recess, a Columbia activist _ Kevin Gray _ burned
a Nazi banner and a Confederate flag outside the capitol. The Nazi
flag burned quickly; the Confederate banner wouldn't ignite at
first. A group waving Rebel flags began signing ``Dixie.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a sign _ a sign the flag shouldn't come down,'' said
56-year-old mailman Marion Hutson, who stood at the Confederate
memorial all day, dressed in the gray, woolen Civil War uniform of
a Charleston infantryman.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, vandals spray-painted in red a message on
the Confederate Soldiers Monument: ``Take it down. Don't put it
here.'' In tempered disagreement, legislators argued about
heritage, honor, respect and racism.
</P>
<P>
   Most black legislators rejected the Democratic war memorial
compromise because it would fly the Rebel flag over the dome once a
year, on Confederate Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Joe Neal (D-Hopkins), head of the black
legislative caucus, said the battle flag over the dome perpetuates
an insult against people of color in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want the flag to fly,'' Neal said from the House
floor, ``even for a day, even for a minute, even for an hour
because we think it's inappropriate,''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
