<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-HENDERSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENDERSON WILL BE STAYING WITH METS, AT LEAST FOR NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Twenty-nine teams had a chance to get a Hall of
Fame leadoff hitter over the past two days, and every one passed.
So the Mets held on to Rickey Henderson, and he started in left
field and led off against the Pittsburgh Pirates on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have no intention of releasing Henderson now, and
because no other team was willing to pay the $20,000 waiver price
to claim him and pay him the remainder of his $2 million salary
this year, the Mets are essentially stuck with the contract. The
Mets had placed Henderson on outright waivers, as it turns out,
meaning that if another team claimed him, the Mets would have had
to let him go. Henderson cleared waivers at 1 p.m. Wednesday when
no team made a claim.
</P>
<P>
   That the Mets risked losing him in such a manner is an
indication that the club no longer believes the slumping Henderson
is worth having at the salary he makes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they've been trying to move him for some time, and
they probably just weren't able to,'' an official from another team
said. ``A lot of times clubs will run even superstars through
outright waivers to see if someone will claim him for $20,000.
Basically you're saying: `I'm giving this guy to you for $20,000. I
get $20,000 and get rid of his contract.'''
</P>
<P>
   With no team agreeing to do that, the Mets plan to hold on to
Henderson in hopes that he will start producing. Baseball's career
stolen-base king, Henderson entered Wednesday night's game with
only two stolen bases and a .207 batting average.
</P>
<P>
   ``The perception that anything's been done to release Rickey is
not accurate,'' said Mets General Manager Steve Phillips, who is
prohibited by baseball rules from acknowledging if he has put a
player on waivers. ``If we wanted to release Rickey, we would
release Rickey. If you want to release a player, you release a
player. You don't have to wait for anything else to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The 41-year-old Henderson is struggling, but the Mets have no
players on their major league roster who are proven leadoff
hitters. They do have a prototype leadoff man at Class AAA Norfolk,
23-year-old Jason Tyner, a former No. 1 draft pick, but he is not
considered ready for the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are not too many true speed guys out there,'' a
different official from another team said. ``The Mets have two of
them, but one's too young and one's too old.''
</P>
<P>
   There is always the possibility that Henderson will rediscover
the form he showed last year, when he hit .315, his highest batting
average in nine years, and had a .423 on-base percentage.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson has been working on limiting the movement in his head
when he hits, and he said he is feeling better at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think he has anything to prove,'' Manager Bobby
Valentine said. ``He has a lot to improve, and I think that's what
we're dealing with. He's working and that's what we're hoping
for.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson said he did not know exactly what happened with the
waiver situation, but said that nothing about it would bother him.
</P>
<P>
   But Henderson bristled when asked if the Mets may have been
trying to send him a message, setting off a lengthy monologue on
what he perceives to be the negative news-media coverage of him. He
said he has been hurt by stories suggesting he does not play hard
and is a bad influence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's negative always,'' he told reporters. ``Y'all want me out
of New York? I'll go play somewhere else. I've been playing 21
years. I've done more than most anybody in this ballpark has done.
But the only thing is negative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get in the paper and put some headlines positive about Rickey.
Because this is ridiculous. This is a joke to me. I don't play this
game with my dignity and my heart for it to be a joke.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
