<HEADLINE>
HARRAH'S POPS BACK INTO LEAD AMONG KC AREA CASINOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Kansas City's white-hot casino market cooled
slightly in April to a merely red-hot $44.7 million _ the
second-richest month in riverboat gambling history.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime market-share leader Harrah's North Kansas City Casino &AMP;
Hotel seized back the lead from Station Casino Kansas City, which
had been out front four of the previous six months.
</P>
<P>
   And the Flamingo Hilton Casino, which could be operating under
new ownership as soon as June 1, posted its biggest market share
ever while grabbing a piece of the monthly ``loosest slots'' title.
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's executives were in Atlantic City, N.J., for corporate
meetings this week and could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to give up the market-share lead,'' said John V.
Finamore, Station's Midwest president. ``But it was a good month
for us. We had a great first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that's encouraging is we grew year over year,
and Harrah's didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite grabbing the monthly market-share honors, Harrah's was
the lone casino operation in Kansas City that failed to outperform
itself from April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   While Harrah's turnstile admissions were up 7 percent from a
year ago, revenue was down 2 percent, to $15 million from $15.4
million. Rival Station saw attendance blossom 21 percent while
revenue grew a modest 2 percent, to $14.7 million from $14.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got spoiled a little bit,'' Finamore said, after Station
posted $16.3 million in revenue in March, a record for the Kansas
City market.
</P>
<P>
   Finamore and others had predicted some market shrinkage after
local boats' $48.2 million performance in March, which shattered
all records for revenue and admissions. March and July
traditionally are Kansas City casinos' strongest months.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue figures represent gamblers' combined net losses after
all winners have been paid.
</P>
<P>
   The Flamingo finished the month with a 16 percent market share,
the largest slice of the pie it has claimed since January 1997,
when Station Casino opened and filled out the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   The Flamingo's $7.2 million April and 435,000 admissions were
both second best in the boat's history. The Flamingo's house
records were set a month earlier, when 471,000 patrons left $7.4
million behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working really hard on customer service issues and
marketing,'' said acting General Manager David Miller. ``Hopefully
it will continue to pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   Open boarding, which began in Kansas City last winter and
eliminated restrictive casino entry times, has benefited one-boat
operations such as the Flamingo far more than twin-vessel
facilities such as Station and Harrah's, which had staggered
boarding hours and shorter waits.
</P>
<P>
   But the Flamingo also has heavily promoted its ``loosest quarter
slots'' status since briefly capturing The Star's six-month-average
award for 25-cent machines in November while posting the best
payback rates for players three of the past six months.
</P>
<P>
   Each month the Missouri Gaming Commission reports revenue and
admission figures for the prior month, but slot-machine and
table-game payback rates are not reported until 40 days after the
end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   For March, Flamingo and the Argosy Riverside Casino finished in
a dead heat for the best quarter-slots average over the past six
months _ 94.253 percent of all 25-cent tokens wagered were paid
back to players in the form of small and large jackpots.
</P>
<P>
   Quarter-denomination slots are the most popular and plentiful
machines and typically generate around 45 percent of all gambling
revenue.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Mississippi-based Isle of Capri Casinos Inc. will go
before the Kansas City Port Authority seeking approval of its
proposed $33.5 million purchase of the Flamingo and assignment of
the city's riverfront land lease.
</P>
<P>
   If the Port Authority agrees, the Missouri Gaming Commission
could grant a state gambling license before the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   Isle executives have said they expect to spend around $15
million redecorating the casino in the company's trademark
Caribbean themes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
