<HEADER>
A1694 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-WELFARE-NYT &LR;      05-11 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-WELFARE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELFARE CONSULTANT WITH NO CONTRACT SAYS NYC RENEGED ON DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Va.)   By ERIC LIPTON and CHRISTOPHER DREW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A top city welfare official agreed to pay a Wisconsin
company $1.1 million for consulting services it provided last year
even though no written contract existed and no competitive bidding
for the work had taken place, an arrangement the city comptroller
says violated standard contracting procedures.
</P>
<P>
   From April 1999 until last week, city welfare officials asked
Kaiser Group, of Waukesha, Wis., to provide advice on placing
welfare recipients in jobs, gave the company an office and promised
to find a way to pay it retroactively, said Peter E. Kaiser, the
company's president.
</P>
<P>
   But Kaiser said that the city had ultimately never paid his
company for the work, and that last week, after a review of the
arrangement by the mayor's office, his staff was ordered to vacate
its city office.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser said he could not explain why the city had reneged on the
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were told to continue on, and it would be worked out,''
Kaiser said this week.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said Wednesday that they had intended to pay
Kaiser for its work but that the mayor's office reversed that plan
in December.
</P>
<P>
   City Comptroller Alan G. Hevesi, who has not formally reviewed
the city's dealings with Kaiser, said that no company should be
providing services to the city unless it has a contract to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The latest contracting problems come as City Hall lawyers and
contracting officers are scrambling to review a series of
multimillion-dollar welfare-to-work contracts awarded by the Human
Resources Administration that are now the subject of investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney's office in Manhattan in the last week has
subpoenaed bid documents, e-mail messages and other city
correspondences involving other welfare contracts, a city official
said. The city has until Friday morning to turn over its records
related to $104 million worth of these contracts it intended to
give to Maximus, a McLean, Va., company, the city official said.
</P>
<P>
   Wisconsin officials said this week that they were also auditing
records about Maximus. The company also is major welfare-to-work
contractor there, and it recently acknowledged that it mistakenly
charged Wisconsin's welfare-to-work program for an unspecified
amount of bills associated with pursuing the New York City
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Maximus and Kaiser Group are among the handful of consultants
hired by the New York City Human Resources Administration after
Jason A. Turner, a former Wisconsin state official, was appointed
commissioner by Mayor Rudolph Giuliani in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who built himself a national reputation in Wisconsin
while helping lead that state's welfare-to-work effort in the
mid-1990s, was hired by Giuliani to figure out a way to encourage
thousands of able-bodied adults on welfare to leave city assistance
programs by finding jobs in the private sector.
</P>
<P>
   The city has long hired outside consultants to help it provide
services to the poor and disadvantaged. What differed after Turner
arrived, several former and current city officials said, is that
the new commissioner felt that he needed to retain several outside
experts quickly to provide him advice on how to reorganize the
agency's operations.
</P>
<P>
   A New York University political science professor, Lawrence
Mead, was brought in one day a week to provide advice for about
$1,000 a day, city officials said. An executive at a conservative
social-services research organization, the Hudson Institute of
Indianapolis, was retained. That executive, Andrew Bush, ultimately
was selected for a permanent high-level job as an agency
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser Group began providing advice to the Human Resources
Administration in October 1998, when the company was hired under a
contract with the State University at Albany. The university had
access to state and federal financing aimed at helping local
governments tackle the challenge of welfare reform.
</P>
<P>
   Eugene J. Monaco, special assistant to the provost at the Nelson
A. Rockefeller College of Public Affairs and Policy at the State
University at Albany, said that the state hired Kaiser Group after
the company was highly recommended for the job by Mark Hoover, the
city's first deputy welfare commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, his staff and two subcontractors were assigned to assist
a city effort to convert its welfare enrollment centers into
so-called job centers, which put more of an emphasis on finding
employment than simply distributing benefits for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   But after the company completed $541,300 worth of work, the
arrangement with the State University expired at the end of March
1999. The city officials asked the state to extend the deal, but
the state said that any further work would have to be paid for by
the city through its own contracting process, Monaco said.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser said his company was advised by city officials to not
worry about the financing issues. And he said his project manager,
Grant Collins, continued to work out of an office at the city
agency's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   But by late 1999, Kaiser said, he became concerned about delays
in payment and how much the city owed him, and he said he asked
Hoover for assurances that he would be paid.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser said he received a letter from Hoover last Dec. 8,
notifying him that the company would be paid $1.1 million for its
work from April through the end of the year. Kaiser said the letter
promised that the payment would be made as part of more than $3
million in business the agency was expecting to give Kaiser's
company over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Sproles, a spokeswoman for the Human Resources
Administration, did not dispute this account in her statement,
noting that the agency had initially ``intended to reimburse Kaiser
for services performed in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   But she added that under advice of the Mayor's Office of
Contracting, city officials, in mid-December 1999, changed their
minds, deciding that the proposed new contract with Kaiser Group
should cover only services starting this year. Kaiser said he was
not informed about the reversal until last week.
</P>
<P>
   Hevesi said the entire episode with Kaiser reflected a
widespread laxity in the contracting procedures at the city's
welfare agency. In recent months, the Giuliani administration has
dismissed Hevesi's criticisms of the agency's contracting
procedures as politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is improper to have vendor work without a contract,''
Hevesi said. ``Such work would be unauthorized.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It means that an agency is spending taxpayer money
without going through the legal procedures that insure that money
is spent properly.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
