<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS SUFFER A BAD CASE OF THE SHOULD'VE-BEENS 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ There were so many positives that could have come
from the Mets' game against the Pittsburgh Pirates on Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, they were getting the best of Rickey Henderson. The
middle of their order produced a big inning that gave one of their
most reliable starters, Rick Reed, a five-run lead. They knocked
out one of the National League's most effective starters and got
into the Pirates' bullpen in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the Mets lost, 13-9, and in the process allowed
20 hits in a game for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   The five-run lead was the largest the Mets have blown this year.
Reed wound up allowing six runs. The bullpen was even worse. And
when things unraveled in a gruesome seventh inning, Henderson was
at the center.
</P>
<P>
   Six hours before game time, the Mets learned they still had the
41-year-old left fielder because every other team had passed on him
in the two days after the Mets put him on outright waivers. It
would be the Mets' responsibility to pay Henderson's $2 million
salary, which he earns to do such things as he did in the first
inning against the Pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Henderson singled, stole second _ it was just his third steal
this year _ went to third on a ground out and scored on another
grounder. It was a manufactured run, vintage Henderson. He later
drew two walks and singled again.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Mets trailing by 8-7 in the seventh, John Vander
Wal of the Pirates sliced a high fly down the left field line.
Henderson gave chase as if he could make the catch, then stopped as
the ball landed a few feet in front of him and bounced over his
head, into the Mets bullpen. Two runs scored and the Pirates
widened their lead to 10-7.
</P>
<P>
   That was the fourth hitter the reliever Pat Mahomes faced, and
the fourth hit he surrendered. The fifth came one batter later,
when Luis Sojo drove in another run with a single. Mahomes had
relieved Dennis Cook, who allowed a single and hit a batter to
start the seventh. In all, seven Pirates reached base and five
scored before Rich Rodriguez came in and got three outs in a row.
</P>
<P>
   That inning wiped out a rally in the top of the inning that had
given the Mets a 7-6 lead. Mike Piazza and Robin Ventura singled
with one out _ the two had hit consecutive home runs earlier _ and
Todd Zeile stroked a run-scoring double to left, his first hit in
19 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   But with runners at second and third, Manager Bobby Valentine
called for a suicide squeeze, and Melvin Mora missed on the bunt
attempt against Jose Silva's first-pitch curveball. Ventura was
trapped and thrown out at third, and after Mora was walked
intentionally, the light-hitting Rey Ordonez struck out to end the
inning.
</P>
<P>
   That rally was cut short, but in the third inning the Mets had
sustained their rally, off the Pirates' starter, Todd Ritchie.
Ritchie, a right-hander, had been solid this year, going at least
six innings while allowing three earned runs or fewer in each of
his six starts. But he was not sharp, hitting Reed in the third and
then walking Henderson.
</P>
<P>
   With two out, Edgardo Alfonzo doubled to right-center, scoring
two runs, and Piazza followed with a two-run homer deep into the
seats in left-center. With a 2-0 count, the next hitter, Ventura,
pounded a homer to right, giving the Mets consecutive homers for
the second game in a row, and a 6-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Normally, a five-run lead is safe with Reed, who went 3-0 in
April. But he lost a one-run lead against the Giants in San
Francisco in his last start, and the Pirates pulled to within 6-3
through five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Young, who had four hits including a homer, opened the
sixth with a single. Reed then fell behind Wil Cordero, 2 and 0,
and Cordero crushed the next pitch into the upper deck in left
field, the third of his five hits. That brought Pittsburgh within
6-5, and Turk Wendell relieved Reed after Pat Meares singled.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell had allowed only one inherited runner to score this
year, and he got two quick outs. But Adrian Brown lofted a fly to
center that sent Mora racing back _ then, suddenly, shifting
directions to move sideways and in. On the misplay, Mora trapped
the ball off the AstroTurf, Meares scored the tying run, and Brown
had a double.
</P>
<P>
   Cook came in and struck out Warren Morris to end the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
