<SLUG> BC-LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE PUSHED BY WIND FORCES EVACUATION OF LOS ALAMOS 
</HEADLINE>
   (subs 3rd graf to correct disaster area: Los Alamos, not New
Mexico; subs 4th graf to insert `east'; subs 11th graf to give name
of fire; subs 12th graf to insert `that'; subs 16th graf to change
`tonight' to `Wednesday night'; subs 1th graf to change `go for' to
`cost')  
(ART ADV: Locator map Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KENNETH CHANG    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Public safety officials ordered everyone out of Los Alamos,
N.M., Wednesday as intensifying winds sent a week-old fire into the
town of 11,000. But officials at the Los Alamos National Laboratory
said they were confident that the nuclear material and chemical
explosives were protected, even if the laboratory itself started
burning.
</P>
<P>
   Police, sheriff's and fire department officials went door to
door urging people to pack up and get out as quickly as possible.
No injuries were reported, but about 200 homes were near the fire
or already burning early Wednesday evening. The fire command post
itself was forced to leave.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton declared Los Alamos a disaster area.
</P>
<P>
   A plume of smoke 17,000 to 20,000 feet high was covering all of
northern New Mexico and moving east into Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be in Houston by tomorrow,'' said Jim Paxon, a fire
spokesman with the U.S. Forest Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire blew up, basically,'' Paxon said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not safe and there are constant winds,'' he said, `` so
all air operations have been grounded and all hand crews have
pulled back into safe zones.'' He said crews could not fight the
blaze at the line of fire, but will continue to work on its
periphery.
</P>
<P>
   The fire is ``pretty close to the lab, and it may be on it right
now,'' Paxon said Wednesday afternoon, but the fire remained
several miles from the laboratory's main buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Wind gusts up to 41 miles per hour pushed the fire to the east
and southeast, toward the town of the laboratory. Winds were
expected to die down somewhat overnight, then kick up to 50 miles
per hour Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bad fire,'' said Jim Danneskiold, a Los Alamos
laboratory spokesman. ``The wind situation is not good.''
</P>
<P>
   The fire, called the Cerro Grande fire after the mountain where
it started, was set a week ago by the National Park Service in the
northwest corner of Bandelier National Monument to clear brush, but
flared out of control over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Fire is always a worry in the dry pine forests that surround the
town of Los Alamos and Los Alamos National Laboratory, whose
thousands of buildings _ most modern, but a few wooden structures
that date to the Manhattan Project of the 1940s _ occupy 43 square
miles of canyons and mesas. In 1977, the La Mesa fire burned part
of the laboratory grounds, and a 1996 fire, accidentally ignited by
campers, devastated some 15,000 acres of nearby forest.
</P>
<P>
   A main area of public concern was Technical Area 55, where the
laboratory keeps most of its nuclear materials. The surrounding
area was virtually free of trees and other burnable fuel,
Danneskiold said, and was about five or six miles from the nearest
firefighting line, and even further from any blaze.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's also a building built to nuclear standards, virtually
bomb proof,'' he said. ``It supposedly can survive earthquakes,
huge fires, airplane crashes and disasters in general.''
</P>
<P>
   He said there have been no intact nuclear weapons at the
laboratory for 15 years. Non-nuclear explosives are stored in
concrete bunkers buried under a couple feet of earth. ``We're
pretty confident in those bunkers,'' Danneskiold said. ``The La
Mesa fire burned over the same bunkers and nothing happened.''
</P>
<P>
   But the outlook was critical for the town itself, where
residents continued to stream out Wednesday night. The western end
of town, evacuated initially Sunday, included 500 homes. A northern
section evacuated Wednesday moments before the blowup also
contained 500 homes, firefighters said.
</P>
<P>
   In Santa Fe, upscale hotels where rooms often cost $300 a night,
were offering evacuees rooms for $25.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Siegfried Hecker, a former director at the Los Alamos
Laboratory who now leads Russian cooperative studies there, was
packing his car late Wednesday to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's serious for the town,'' he said in a telephone
interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about the people, but I think we have everything
else in good shape. At this point, the lab looks in good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   Members of Concerned Citizens for Nuclear Safety, an
environmental group in Santa Fe, worried that toxic and radioactive
fumes could be released into the air if the fire spread to drums of
waste stored at the laboratory. ``We are concerned the lab is not
fully knowledgeable of what is in each drum,'' said Suzanne
Westerly, the group's acting executive director.
</P>
<P>
   She also said that plants around the laboratory have absorbed
radioctive contaminants over the years, which are now being
released into the air as the plants burn.
</P>
<P>
   But Danneskiold said that the laboratory continually monitored
the air around it and ``there was no evidence of airborne
contamination'' after the last major fire, in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The laboratory's radioactive-contaminated waste is stored on a
barren area eight to nine miles from the from the fire, Danneskiold
said. ``There's no vegetation in the area to burn.''
</P>
<P>
   Danneskiold said that while the laboratory has been closed
because of the fire since Monday, power was on at the labs, and
guards and emergency personnel remained on duty. Security in
top-secret areas was being maintained, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He acknowledged that there was an old lab dump site known as
Acid Canyon near a part of town that was evacuated on Sunday, but
said he had no idea of conditions there. He said environmental
restorations had removed from the canyon old wastes dating from the
1940s and 1950s.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 0017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0009 </DOCNO>
