<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 00:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1701 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MTV-DOCUMENTARIES-ART     05-11 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MTV-DOCUMENTARIES-ART-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITS NOT ALL DAZZLE: MTV HAS A CONSCIENCE, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sun., May 14) 
(ART ADV: NYT Photos 26,27 of 5/10 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JOSEPH HOOPER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since its founding in 1981, MTV has gotten plenty of mileage out
of young people's fantasies about sex, drugs and rock 'n' roll. But
if the staple of the channel's programming, the music video, often
conveys an unbridled hedonism, the channel's documentary programs
can be regarded as the proverbial dropping of the other shoe.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, MTV's ``True Life'' documentary series takes its
audience to some pretty rugged places, including two public
restrooms. On ``I'm on Crystal Meth,'' which was first broadcast in
February, the MTV reporter Serena Altschul keeps up a concerned
patter as Amber, 19, shoots methamphetamine into a vein. Two years
ago, on ``Fatal Dose,'' about a heroin epidemic in Plano, Tex.,
Altschul shared the facilities with two affluent addicts, Allen,
19, and Eric, 22, who was painfully struggling to find an
injectable vein. ``If anybody still has any doubts,'' said Allen,
taking over the narration of this cautionary tale about heroin,
``Eric is proof as to whether it's really glamorous.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, producers working mostly out of MTV's corporate
offices in Times Square will make from 50 to 75 television
documentaries. Many will be about music or the music business _
subjects that account for most of the channel's programming. But
roughly a third of the documentaries tackle social problems that
affect younger people: drug addiction, school violence, sexually
transmitted disease. (Next on the schedule, on May 22, is ``Gun
Fight,'' on the politics of gun control, part of the network's
``Choose or Lose'' documentary series about young people and
political involvement.) But unless you happen to fall within the
channel's 18-to-24 ``core demographic,'' this is probably news to
you. In the minds of older television viewers, MTV's involvement in
documentary filmmaking about nonmusicians begins and ends with
``Real World.''
</P>
<P>
   For the past eight years, that MTV series has offered its
audience what amounts to a hugely popular lab experiment in which
successive sets of seven college-age kids live together for a
television season under the constant surveillance of a resident
film crew. ``Every year we ask, `When are we replacing it?''' said
Judy McGrath, president of the MTV network. ``But you can't beat it
to death.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Real World'' bills itself as ``a real-life soap opera'' and
producers at MTV's News and Docs division are quick to point out
that they have nothing to do with it. ``Even in the documentary
film world,'' said Lauren Lazin, the vice president for news and
documentaries, ``I've had people discount our department because
they think it's just `Real World.' That's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   At MTV, reality is a concept that's parsed very fine. ``Real
World'' and ``True Life'' both make their differing claims on it.
Then there is Tom Green, of the outrageous ``Tom Green Show.'' A
one-man lab experiment who regularly leaves the television studio
to assault real-life bystanders with his own twisted Andy
Kaufmanesque persona, Green won't be interviewing teen-age drug
addicts for a ``True Life'' documentary anytime soon. But he is
currently working on an episode of his own show about his recent
experiences with testicular cancer. ``It will definitely have a lot
of the elements of `True Life,''' Lazin allowed.
</P>
<P>
   The average adult might lose his balance in such a slippery
world. But according to Lazin, the younger generation, the most
media-saturated in history, doesn't have a problem. ``They get the
difference clearly,'' she said. For instance, the ``True Life''
episode first shown in August, ``I'm a Pro Wrestler,'' never
bothers to state the obvious, that professional wrestling is a
choreographed spectacle, not a competitive sport. Dave Sirulnick,
35, MTV's executive vice president of news and production, which
oversees News and Docs, said: ``For our audience, it would be like
saying, `Well, you know, an episode of ``Felicity'' is not true.'
It gets at the way young people watch it.'' McGrath, alluding to
the mix-and-match aesthetic of hip-hop music, sums up her network's
nonmusic programming this way: ``I look at it as the world remixed
by MTV.''
</P>
<P>
   For the last 14 years, Lazin has had the job of figuring out the
documentary portion of the mix. She came to the network with a
Stanford master's in film and her own well-received documentary
about young women in the 1920s, ``The Flapper Story,'' to her
credit; and her film peers were more than a little puzzled. ``The
attitude,'' Lazin said, ``was, `If you want to be a documentarian,
why aren't you at PBS?''' And even she admits that when she first
arrived at MTV, ``the word `documentary' probably sounded like
homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Her seemingly odd career choice paid off. In the intervening
years, Lazin noted, relatively cheap-to-produce documentaries on
cable channels like Discovery and Lifetime rushed in to fill the
programming needs of the cable universe. ``That created an audience
for reality filmmaking that I don't think was nearly there 20 years
ago,'' she said. In the meantime, MTV was growing from a fairly
small independent player in the television world into a crucial
member of the Viacom corporate family. ``Sometimes I feel like I
have my own independent film production company at this big
multinational entertainment conglomerate,'' she said, though her
personal style is more bohemian than corporate.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Lazin does not completely disown the influence of ``Real World''
on her documentary division. ``On the pro side,'' she said, ``it
has really groomed an audience to appreciate real-life drama. I
think viewers get that real life can be as engrossing and engaging
and challenging, as entertaining as actors and actresses and sets
and make-up and costumes and all the artifices of narrative
storytelling.''
</P>
<P>
   After the third season of ``Real World,'' in 1994, the
HIV-positive Pedro Zamora died, occasioning an outpouring of grief
from the small televised circle of his San Francisco housemates and
from the larger circle of 1.3 million young viewers. ``That to me
was a wake-up call that our audience cared deeply about this
disease,'' Lazin said.
</P>
<P>
   If the robust documentary culture at MTV has drawn a measure of
inspiration from ``Real World,'' it is also attuned to the real
real world. Sirulnick's news department aggressively covers stories
that involve youth culture or the music industry or both. Coverage
of the 1990 Florida obscenity trial of 2 Live Crew grew into the
1994 documentary ``Gangsta Rap,'' exploring censorship and rap.
Coverage of the 1998 case of Matthew Shepard, murdered in Wyoming
for being gay, led to the Emmy-nominated ``True Life: Matthew's
Murder.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The great moments have come back and forth,'' Sirulnick said,
``between the daily news organization covering something right now
and the longer documentary analysis.'' In the case of the Columbine
school shootings, MTV was, sadly, ahead of the curve, having just
completed work on a documentary that addressed earlier high-profile
school shootings. After the body count came in from Colorado,
``Warning Signs'' was rushed to air.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were amazed,'' Lazin said. `` `How did you know? How
did you get this?' It was like, `That's what we do.' We're in the
business of taking that pulse.'' Last year, MTV's ``Fight For Your
Rights'' campaign, which included ``Warning Signs,'' won a special
Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   Lazin is pushing the channel to explore quieter, artier avenues
in the documentary film world. This kind of film is represented by
``The Travelers,'' which was shown for the first time on April 19
(the channel regularly rebroadcasts its documentaries), concluding
the current season of ``True Life.'' Shot in black-and-white with a
cinema-verite sensibility, ``The Travelers'' tells the story of
teen-age hobos entirely in their own words. Only gradually, in
accordance with the languid, folk rhythm of the film, does the
desperate nature of the traveling enterprise become apparent. On
the evidence presented, hard-core travelers either quit the life
or, in travelers lingo, wind up as ``dead frogs.'' ``A lot of
`Travelers' is very traditional storytelling,'' Lazin said.
``Filmmakers don't have to come in with this bag of tricks of what
they think MTV wants.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oscar-nominated filmmaker Liz Garbus made ``The Travelers.''
And if Lazin has her way, Garbus will be only one of many
established artists to take advantage of MTV's documentarian safe
haven. ``I would love to do a documentary with D.A. Pennebaker or
Barbara Kopple,'' Lazin said, referring to two stars of nonfiction
film. ``I don't think you have to be 24 to make a film about
24-year-olds.'' Lazin herself harbors ambitions of taking
documentary films (including her own) into theaters, to be
distributed by the MTV Films division responsible for ``Election''
and ``Varsity Blues.''
</P>
<P>
   If ``The Travelers'' represents one future for documentaries at
MTV, the present seems to belong to Serena Altschul, the
29-year-old ``True Life'' reporter-producer who wades through the
carnage of youth culture with the swagger of a seasoned war
correspondent. On a recent ``True Life'' episode, ``I'm a Hacker,''
when Altschul is told that a particular teen-age computer hacker
has an attitude problem, she replies in her best Lauren Bacall
voice: ``That's OK I have an attitude problem too.'' Sirulnick
said, ``When you see our show, you know it's not the way ABC would
do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Altschul's aggressively hip persona and MTV's relentless
focus on young people's stories can add up to unusual television.
``People are like, `Come to our party, we're all going to be
sniffing heroin here,''' Lazin said. For the ``Fatal Dose''
documentary, Altschul left a teen-age heroin party to get in a car
driven by one of her obviously addled teen-age subjects. ``Serena's
up with every bit of it,'' Sirulnick said, ``whereas with Stone
Phillips or whoever, it would be, `How's school, junior?'''
</P>
<P>
   For those not of the MTV generation, the whole notion of
fearless MTV documentaries takes some getting used to. In the
middle of ``I'm on Crystal Meth,'' Altschul asks Sheriff Joe Arpao
for the lowdown on crystal meth use in Maricopa County, Arizona. He
takes a close look at her and her punkishly short blond hair and
wonders aloud: ``MTV, what is that, a music station? You want me to
sing?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
