<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-INFANT-DEATH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN WHO KILLED HER BABY RETURNS HOME FROM PRISON  
 BY ROBERT HANLEY  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYCKOFF, N.J. _ Asking for privacy, a young woman returned to
her parents' suburban home Wednesday after serving 22 months in
prison for manslaughter in the widely publicized death of her
newborn son.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike her former boyfriend, who publicly expressed his sorrow
after he was freed from prison in January, the woman, Amy
Grossberg, referred only obliquely to the death of her child in a
Delaware motel in November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today, I am still reflecting on the past, but I am also
looking forward to the obligations and opportunities that lie
ahead,'' she said in a hand-written statement that a family lawyer,
Robert Gottlieb, read to reporters. She also said she was thankful
to be reunited with family and friends and was grateful for the
support she had received.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg and her parents had planned to speak at an afternoon
news conference near their condominium, the Wyckoff police said
Wednesday morning. But the family changed their minds shortly after
arriving about noon from Delaware and did not appear.
</P>
<P>
   After reading the two-sentence statement, Gottlieb added only
that Grossberg hoped to continue her college education.
</P>
<P>
   After her former high school sweetheart and the infant's father,
Brian Peterson, 21, returned to his mother's home here four months
ago, he spoke at a news conference and said he was sorry for his
role in what he called the tragic events of November 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After Grossberg gave birth Nov. 12 in a motel near the
University of Delaware, Peterson put the infant in a plastic bag
and left him in a trash bin. Grossberg collapsed hours later in her
dorm. Shortly afterward, the police found the baby's body, and an
autopsy determined that he had died of a fractured skull.
</P>
<P>
   The case attracted national attention, partly because of
Peterson's and Grossberg's affluent suburban upbringing and partly
because Delaware prosecutors initially talked of seeking the death
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   During pretrial hearings in early 1998, Grossberg's lawyers
argued that Peterson acted alone in discarding the baby. His
lawyers responded that she had told him to ``get rid of'' the
infant. Then, in a plea deal, Peterson gave the authorities a
statement about the birth, agreed to testify against Grossberg, and
was allowed to plead guilty to manslaughter. Soon afterward,
Grossberg also pleaded guilty to manslaughter. Both said they
thought the baby was born dead.
</P>
<P>
   Grossberg's 30-month prison sentence was reduced to 22 months.
She must now serve two years on parole and do 300 hours of
community service counseling young, unmarried women who are
pregnant. Peterson is also on two years parole and is working in
his family's video business and counseling troubled teen-age boys
to tell their parents and outside experts about personal problems,
said his lawyer, Russell M. Gioiella.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
