<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILL IN NO MOOD TO TALK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- Pitcher Ken Hill had not yet gone to the doctor for
an MRI, but he was in no mood to talk about his latest injury,
waving off a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Results of Wednesday night's MRI won't be available until today,
but Hill initially has been diagnosed with a strained intercostal
muscle, which is located in the upper ribcage below his right
armpit. Hill (3-4, 7.41 ERA) fell to his knees in pain after making
a pitch in the third inning Tuesday night, was taken out of the
game and placed on the 15-day disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems 15 days won't be enough to heal the injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously it's a great concern of ours,'' manager Mike
Scioscia said. ``When you're talking about a torso injury with a
pitcher, it's as devastating as an arm injury. It's safe to say
it's going to be a while, more than two weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have been careful with Hill all season because of an
arthritic right elbow, but his elbow is fine.
</P>
<P>
   Losing Hill from the rotation isn't the only pitching change for
the club. Ramon Ortiz, struggling at 2-2 with a 6.90 ERA, was
optioned to Triple-A Edmonton and replaced by left-hander Jarrod
Washburn.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Washburn had an injury similar to Hill's both last
season and in spring training this year, though Washburn's strain
was below the ribcage. Washburn missed seven weeks last season, but
just three weeks this year before reporting to Edmonton, where he
went 3-0 with a 3.52 ERA in five starts.
</P>
<P>
   Washburn will start Saturday's game against the Rangers in
Ortiz's spot. Hill's spot in the rotation comes up Sunday, when the
Angels are expected to activate Jason Dickson (strained hip) from
the DL to start that game against the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   As for the highly-touted Ortiz, the move could be seen coming
weeks ago because of his inconsistency, and not because of the
small tear in the cartilage of his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ramon has the potential to be a premier pitcher in this
league,'' Scioscia said. ``We wracked out brains and talked about
it, but we think this is the best course to take.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's nobody in the world who would feel good about going
back to the minor leagues. But Ramon absolutely understands what he
has to work on to reach his potential. He's the first guy to say he
has not been pitching well. ... Here's a guy trying to throw 98 mph
when he throws 92-94 mph. He gets out of whack and loses command.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I don't feel good but I understand what I need to
do,'' Ortiz said through Preston Gomez, the Angels' assistant to
the GM. ``I'm not surprised. I understand it's part of the
business.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Gary DiSarcina had an MRI on his ailing right shoulder
Tuesday night, but results were not released by the Angels. In past
instances regarding a delayed announcement, the results many times
have revealed serious injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Adam Kennedy was not in the starting lineup
Wednesday for the first time this season. Kennedy simply needed a
day off. Trent Durrington, called up Tuesday to replace DiSarcina
on the roster, got the start at second. ... A's center fielder
Terrence Long was scratched from the lineup Wednesday after getting
hit in the mouth by a ball during batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   DAILY BOX
</P>
<P>
   ANGELS VS. TEXAS
</P>
<P>
   Time: 7:05 at Edison Field
</P>
<P>
   TV/Radio: FSN; KLAC-570, XPRS-1090
</P>
<P>
   Matchup: Kent Mercker (0-1, 5.06 ERA) will make his second start
of the season, but not his last. Mercker replaced the injured Jason
Dickson in the rotation, and threw five scoreless innings against
Seattle five days ago. But Ken Hill is hurt and Ramon Ortiz is in
the minors, creating a spot for Mercker. Kenny Rogers (3-3, 4.76)
will start for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   -- Joe Haakenson
</P>
</TEXT>
