<HEADLINE>
UC, GRAD STUDENTS REACH LABOR DEAL
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By MEREDITH MAY 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nearly 10,000 University of California graduate teaching
assistants are set to ratify their first contract, ending a 16-year
campaign for labor representation and a threat to strike during
this semester's finals.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year agreement, announced Wednesday, covers pay,
workload and sexual harassment policies for the assistant teachers
and tutors, who conduct an estimated 60 percent of the teaching on
the UC system's eight campuses with undergraduate programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ecstatic,'' said Christian Sweeney, a UC Berkeley
graduate student and president of the Association of Graduate
Student Employees, which is an affiliate of the United Auto Workers
union.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long, hard road, but we're finally there,'' said
Sweeney, adding that the contract should be ratified by teaching
assistants at all eight campuses within two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If the contract gets the green light, graduate teaching
assistants will notice immediate bumps in their salaries, which
average $13,800 for a nine-month, half-time gig.  &LR; job.
</P>
<P>
   Over three years, salaries will rise 7.5 percent. Teaching
assistants will receive an immediate 1.5 percent salary increase
and a proposed 2 percent raise this October and the following two
Octobers.
</P>
<P>
   Last October, their salaries were increased 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the cost of attending the University of California
will be waived for graduate student teachers by 2002. Teaching
assistants now are allowed to waive $2,175, or 60 percent of the
cost of attending the UC system. The rebate will increase to 75
percent this fall, 85 percent next fall and 100 percent by fall of
2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great contract, and we're happy to offer it,'' said
Brad Hayward, spokesman for the UC system.
</P>
<P>
   For 16 years, teaching assistants fought to unionize, facing
opposition from UC officials. They struck systemwide in December
1998, walking out for four days. Eventually, the state Public
Employment Relations Board ruled that students are entitled to
collective bargaining.
</P>
<P>
   The Association of Graduate Student Employees affiliated with
the UAW in the spring of 1999 to represent approximately 9,400
academic student employees at UC campuses.
</P>
<P>
   That prompted union negotiations with the UC system to hammer
out a contract. One of the final sticking points was how to handle
workload and sexual harassment policies between professor and
student.
</P>
<P>
   The graduate students wanted guarantees to keep workloads close
to the 20-hour-per-week standard, but the university wanted to keep
hours more flexible to allow professors to tailor their classes as
they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides agreed to bring in a neutral arbitrator if
disputes over workload or sexual harassment arise.
</P>
<P>
   On April 25, the two sides met with state Senate President Pro
Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco, and Marty Morgenstern, a mediator
appointed by Gov. Gray Davis. They reached agreement on several
issues that had been holding up a contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign was really important, because while 20 other
universities in the country have union representation for teaching
assistants, UC becomes the largest,'' Sweeney said. ``It's a
bellwether for union organizing, and a lot of other campuses were
watching us to see what would happen before trying it themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
