<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SCOTT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
C.A. SCOTT, 92, VOICE OF BLACKS AS PUBLISHER OF ATLANTA WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga., Ala., Miss.)   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cornelius Adolphus Scott, editor and publisher of The Atlanta
Daily World from 1934 until 1997 and a strong voice for the
interests of its black readers, died on Sunday at an Atlanta
hospital. He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   Widely known as C.A. Scott, he became head of The World, a
family business, on the death of his brother William Alexander
Scott II, who had founded The World in 1928 as a monthly.
</P>
<P>
   C.A. Scott was succeeded by M. Alexis Scott, granddaughter of
W.A. Scott II, as he was known.
</P>
<P>
   Among the newspaper's goals, as Scott recalled in 1978, was ``to
give constructive and inspiring news'' to blacks. Under him, The
World spoke in favor of voting rights for blacks and racial
integration of schools and businesses. His daughter Portia A.
Scott, a former editor of The World, recalled in an interview
Wednesday that her father's outspoken pro-civil-rights views did
not lead to any violence against him, although she said there might
have been threats in letters.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was chairman of the Public Affairs Committee of the
National Association for the Advancement of Colored People for a
time.
</P>
<P>
   A chain of Scott-owned papers included about 50 papers around
the country in the mid-1930s. But by 1970 all had closed except The
World and one in Birmingham, Ala., which the family later sold.
</P>
<P>
   After the victories of the civil rights movement in the 1960s,
many older black newspapers suffered sharp declines in circulation.
The World's circulation fell to 16,500 by the mid-1980s from 22,000
in the early 1960s. The World, which became a daily in 1932, is now
published twice a week, on Sunday and Thursday. Its circulation is
10,000, about the same as when Scott retired.
</P>
<P>
   Cornelius Adolphus Scott was born in Edwards, Miss., and studied
at Morehouse College in Atlanta and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Scott, said that in 1952 her father switched from
supporting the Democratic Party to backing the Republican Party. He
saw the necessity of having both parties running candidates in the
South, she said, and he resented that the history of the Democratic
Party in the South had been anti-black.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Ruth, died in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his daughter, who lives in Atlanta, survivors
include a sister, Ruth Scott Simmons of Atlanta; four
grandchildren, and a great-grandson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
