<SLUG> BC-YOUTH-AUTHORITY_SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA YOUTH AUTHORITY CHARGED WITH TREATING INMATES
AT  UNLICENSED MEDICAL FACILITIES
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ Already under investigation for brutality against
inmates, the California Youth Authority is facing new charges that
its 7,300 inmates are being treated in unlicensed medical
facilities that do not meet state standards.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit, expected to be filed Thursday in San Francisco,
seeks an order that the department get licenses for its medical and
mental health treatment centers which it has failed do since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They haven't gotten licensed because they really can't,'' said
Susan Burrell, a lawyer with the Youth Law Center in San Francisco,
which prepared the lawsuit. ``They don't meet these standards in
any way, shape or form.''
</P>
<P>
   Sarah Ludeman, a spokeswoman for the Youth Authority,
acknowledged that none of the medical or mental health treatment
facilities are licensed by the state but said the authority has
``been working for some time to bring our sites into compliance.''
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit is the latest in a series of problems for the
authority.
</P>
<P>
   A probe last year that uncovered abuse and brutality by
correctional officers at one of the authority's 11 facilities led
to the resignation in December of Gov. Gray Davis' first appointee
to head the agency, Gregorio S. Zermeno, 10 months after being
named to the post.
</P>
<P>
   Two other top deputies also left the authority.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Davis named Jerry Harper, a 37-year veteran of the Los
Angeles Sheriff's Department, to head the authority. Next week he
will appear at a hearing of the Senate Public Safety Committee on
the authority. Committee chairman, Sen. John Vasconcellos, D-Santa
Clara, has been one of the authority's sharpest critics.
</P>
<P>
   After the investigation last year into prison guard brutality,
Davis called for an overhaul of department policies.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Corrections is conducting an audit and
investigation of the Youth Authority including visits to its
largest facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Among the things investigators are examining are the medical
care of inmates in general and the care for mentally ill inmates.
</P>
<P>
   Since January 1, 1996, medical facilities in prisons, jails and
the Youth Authority have been required to be licensed by the state
Department of Health Services.
</P>
<P>
   The department maintains a 40-page list of the minimum standards
for what are known as `'correctional treatment centers.''
</P>
<P>
   Those include the required staffing levels for doctors and
nurses, the proper use of clinical restraint and the giving of
drugs to inmates.
</P>
<P>
   The Youth Authority was been  &LR; told by Health Services that its
facilities needed to be licensed in December 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, the Youth Authority has sought more money to improve
its medical services but has yet to secure licenses.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the Youth Authority was told by Health Services that,
among other things, its Stockton facility's pharmacy services
failed to meet state standards and that there appeared to be not
enough nurses on duty nights and weekends.
</P>
<P>
   The authority was reminded again in December 1998 that its
treatment centers needed to be licensed.
</P>
<P>
   The authority has acknowledged some of its own treatment
problems.
</P>
<P>
   In a request for $1 million for the state's current fiscal year
to create a mental health treatment center at one of its
facilities, the authority said there were more wards needing mental
health care than available beds.
</P>
<P>
   ``While waiting for an available bed, the severely disabled
wards must be managed in general population units by staff who have
little or no training in delivering mental health treatment
services.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, eligible offenders (for mental health treatment)
are often assigned to lock-up or high control housing units based
on their bizarre behaviors, poor reality contact and tendency to be
unreasonable,'' the authority wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The request for money said there were five suicides of authority
inmates in 1996. Of those, four ``were in serious need of mental
health treatment'' but not in a program.
</P>
<P>
   Its unclear whether the $1 million request was approved by Davis
although his budget for last year and this one make no mention of
it.
</P>
<P>
   A previous year's budget request sought eight pharmacists and
seven assistants because at those facilities which contract with
outside pharmacists, prescriptions are not available at night or
over weekends, making it impossible to get needed drugs in an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Adding the pharmacists would help bring the Youyh Authority into
state licensing compliance, the request concluded.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1998 budget, Davis' predecessor, GOP Gov. Pete Wilson,
included the new pharmacists.
</P>
</TEXT>
