<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROCKOVICH-DELAY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROCKOVICH, BOSS TALKED OF MONEY FIRST, LAWYER SAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID GREENBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   VENTURA, Calif. _ The lawyer for Erin Brockovich's ex-husband on
Wednesday accused the recent movie subject and her lawyer-boss of
initiating the money talks that led to the arrest of his client and
two others on extortion charges.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn William Brown was simply discussing the negative portrayal
of him in the Julia Roberts blockbuster ``Erin Brockovich'' when
the real-life legal researcher and her boss, Ed Masry, brought
money into the discussion, the attorney said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offers and conversations of what to say and not to say
started from the Brockovich-Masry camp,'' said defense attorney
Joel Isaacson, who stopped short of calling the April 26 arrest a
set-up.
</P>
<P>
   Brown ``felt like he wanted to respond to (the movie.) We feel
he has the right to do that. He wanted to tell the truth _ the way
he saw it occur,'' Isaacson said.
</P>
<P>
   Isaacson's remarks outside the Ventura County courthouse came
after lawyers for the three defendants delayed until June 19 their
arraignments on felony charges of conspiracy to commit blackmail
and attempted blackmail.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities say Brown, 38, of Simi Valley, Jorg Lawrence Halaby,
46, of Costa Mesa and Century City attorney John Jeffrey Reiner,
53, threatened to portray the legal duo in an unflattering light if
the two did not pay them $310,000.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, they were going to tell the tabloid media that
Brockovich and Masry _ both married to others _ had an affair and
that Brockovich was a poor mother to her three children,
authorities said. Brown is the father of Brockovich's two older
children.
</P>
<P>
   Brown was to receive $280,000 while Halaby, an ex-boyfriend of
Brockovich's who is portrayed by actor Aaron Eckhart in the movie,
was to receive $30,000, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   But Isaacson said the April 26 meeting _ where money exchanged
hands under police surveillance _ took place on the advice of
Reiner.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Extortion) did not happen,'' Isaacson said. ``We think the
whole picture's got to be looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutor Bob Calvert would not comment on the case.
</P>
<P>
   Brockovich, the 39-year-old director of research at Masry &AMP;
Vititoe, a Westlake Village law firm, was in New Orleans, and
through her assistant refused to comment on Isaacson's allegations.
</P>
<P>
   Masry, however, laughed off the claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why would I initiate a talk to give Shawn money?'' he said.
``My mother may have raised an ugly child but she didn't raise a
stupid one. That's ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   In the critically acclaimed movie, Roberts portrays Brockovich
as a down-on-her-luck, twice-divorced single mother of three, who
is hired as a file clerk by Masry (played by Albert Finney). She
becomes interested in a case in which residents of Hinkley, Calif.,
are suffering devastating illnesses because of a contaminated water
supply, and helps Masry's law firm win a record $333 million
judgment from the powerful utility Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is not depicted in the movie, although the title character
implies that he is a deadbeat father who was never around. But in
an interview following his arrest, Brown maintained that he has
always been a caring father to his son and daughter, who are now 16
and 15.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
