<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VINEYARD-BUG-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PREDATORY BUG FOUND NEAR LODI HAS VINEYARDS ON ALERT  &HT;     By GLEN MARTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A voracious sap-sucking bug that infects grapevines with a
deadly bacterium has been found near Lodi, raising fears that the
pest could be homing in on the vineyards of Northern California.
</P>
<P>
   The discovery of a glassy-winged sharpshooter in a trap on
Monday was the second find in San Joaquin County in less than a
year, and it made no one happy.
</P>
<P>
   The nearly inch-long insects have already hammered vineyards in
Riverside County, and they could do the same if they get into the
vineyards of San Joaquin County and the premium grapes of Napa and
Sonoma.
</P>
<P>
   Glassy-winged sharpshooters first showed up in the state in
1989, probably imported on nursery stock from the American
Southeast or Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   They have since spread throughout most of the southern part of
the state and into the southern San Joaquin Valley. Although the
Monday discovery may be an isolated incident, agriculture experts
consider any sign of the insects in the northern San Joaquin Valley
ominous because it could mean that they are implacably expanding
their range.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have had a devastating impact on the wine industry in
Temecula,'' said Matthew Blua, a research associate in the
entomology department at the University of California at Riverside,
``and in all likelihood, they will probably establish themselves at
some time at some population level in the North Coast (counties of
Napa, Sonoma and Mendocino).''
</P>
<P>
   The sharpshooters are part of an invasion of ``exotic'' insect
pests that have bedeviled California during the past 25 years. Such
species include Mediterranean fruit flies, fire ants and killer
bees.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of agricultural California has the two main things
the sharpshooters need to spread, said Blua _ host plants and
enough heat to allow two generations of bugs a year.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the sharpshooters that kill the vines. But by doing
what they do naturally _ feeding placidly on sap _ they transmit a
bacterium, Xyella fastidiosa, to their host plants.
</P>
<P>
   The bacterium causes Pierce's disease, which interferes with the
flow of nutrients throughout plant vascular tissue.
</P>
<P>
   There is no cure for Pierce's disease _ once a vine is infected,
its demise is certain.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce's disease was already a problem for the state's $33
billion wine industry before the glassy-winged sharpshooter first
showed up in the late 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   But at that time, the disease was primarily spread by the
blue-green sharpshooter, an arthropod decidedly smaller and less
robust than its glassy-winged cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Blue-green sharpshooters can only fly a few feet and subsist on
a limited number of plant species.
</P>
<P>
   Glassy-winged sharpshooters, on the other hand, can fly as far
as one-half mile and will suck sap from practically anything.
</P>
<P>
   The Davis administration is so concerned about the threat that
it recently committed $14 million over a two-year period to
fighting the bug.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Cooper, a spokesman for the California Department of Food
and Agriculture, said the sharpshooter found Monday probably
hitchhiked up from Southern California on nursery stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're investigating now and trying to trace it back to its
origin,'' said Cooper. ``It's probably an isolated individual _ we
don't think we're dealing with a (sizable) population, though we're
increasing our trapping in the area to be sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Northern California growers and vineyard managers are closely
monitoring the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned, but this (the San Joaquin Valley discovery)
isn't a total surprise,'' said Martin Mochizuki, the vice president
and director of viticulture for Walsh Vineyard Management in Napa
County, a firm that farms about 2,000 acres of vines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're watching the importation of nursery stock very closely
up here,'' said Mochizuki. ``And we don't think we have as much of
a problem as people do in the San Joaquin Valley, primarily because
we have very little citrus up here. Citrus appears to be an
important host plant for glassy-wings.''
</P>
<P>
   If the sharpshooters do get established in Northern California,
growers will probably increase pesticide spraying _ at least in the
short run. But that is not a desirable long-term solution, say
experts, because of both the economic and environmental expense.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the money cut loose by the state to fight sharpshooters
is going into research for long-term solutions, including vine
stock that is resistant to X. fastidiosa, micro-nutrients that may
inhibit the bacteria once they are in the plant, and insects that
prey on glassy-wings or their eggs.
</P>
<P>
   Mochizuki, who serves as chairman on a regional task force on
Pierce's disease, says the development of resistant vines looks
particularly promising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're also supporting a genome project for X. fastidiosa,'' he
said. ``By sequencing its entire genetic structure, we hope to find
some points where it's vulnerable.''
</P>
<P>
   The basic strategy, said Mochizuki, is to fight an effective
holding battle with the sharpshooter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep it out of here for 10 years or so, we're pretty
optimistic we'll have some effective tools for dealing with it,''
he said.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
