<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROP21-COURT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 STATE HIGH COURT DENIES HEARING ON PROP. 21 CHALLENGE  &HT;     By STACY FINZ 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The state Supreme Court refused Wednesday to
hear a claim by the League of Women Voters and two children's
advocacy groups that challenged Proposition 21, a new law that
imposes stiffer penalties on juveniles who commit crimes.
</P>
<P>
   As is customary, the high court gave no reason for its decision
to deny review. The court also turned down the groups' request to
block the law, which went into effect April 9.
</P>
<P>
   The League of Women Voters, Children's Advocacy Institute and
Coleman Advocates for Children and Youth wanted the court to deem
the law unconstitutional because, they claimed, the proposition
illegally covered more than one subject and confused voters.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Kim, a lawyer with the American Civil Liberties Union who
is representing the three organizations, has said Proposition 21
improperly overhauled the juvenile and criminal justice system and
in the process amended two other laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a miscarriage of the electorate system that we would
like to stop,'' said Dorothy Ehrlich, the executive director of the
ACLU's Northern California office. ``We thought it was a case of
such state importance that we should start with the highest
court.''
</P>
<P>
   Ehrlich said Wednesday's decision does not bar them from filing
the challenge in a lower court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now have to figure out what our next step is,'' she said.
``But this probably isn't the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposition known as the Gang Violence and Juvenile Crime
Prevention Act imposes tough new penalties on juvenile criminals
and increases penalties for gang-related crimes. It passed with 62
percent of the vote last November.
</P>
<P>
   The law was championed by former Gov. Pete Wilson and is part of
a longtime effort to reform the juvenile justice system. For years,
law enforcement and political leaders, victims' and children's
advocacy groups have debated over how to best deal with juvenile
crime.
</P>
<P>
   Critics call the measure draconian.
</P>
<P>
   The new law requires that anyone 14 years or older who commits a
violent sex crime or a special circumstance murder, including
killing multiple victims or slaying someone during a robbery, must
be tried and punished as an adult. California law, however,
precludes anyone younger than 18 from getting the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Proposition 21 gives prosecutors discretion to try
as adults minors who have committed other serious and violent
felonies. Previously, Juvenile Court judges made that decision
after conducting in-depth hearings into whether the child could be
rehabilitated in the juvenile system.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Keane, dean of Golden Gate University Law School and the
former second-in-command at San Francisco's public defenders
office, says it's unwise to take such sensitive decisions out of
the hands of judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``If prosecutors have discretion to be harsh or less harsh,
they're going to use the extreme measure allowed to them,'' Keane
said. ``That's just the nature of being a prosecutor. And no matter
how much judges are looking over their shoulders to the next
election, they'll want to follow their oath to mete out justice in
a fair and even manner.''
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Gaffey, a gang prosecutor in the Santa Clara County
District Attorney's office, the first to use the new law in the Bay
Area, said some juvenile criminals are more dangerous than others
and deserve to be treated accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are a number of kids who grow up very fast,'' he
said. ``If they're sophisticated enough to get their hands on guns
and kill someone, they should be treated severely.''
</P>
<P>
   Gaffey says that Proposition 21 puts several new laws on the
book that will help his office and other prosecutors around the
state combat a growing youth gang problem.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the measure now makes any gang-related murder a
capital crime. And it's now a felony to use or threaten violence to
coerce someone into joining or staying in a gang. Sentences range
from 16 months to five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The law also enables prosecutors to seek felony sentences in
gang-related graffiti cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us new tools that we didn't have before,'' Gaffey
said. ``We're hoping that it will have a detering effect.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
