r a BC-COLLEGE-PREZ-LADN     05-11 0929
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-PREZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER PRESIDENT OF EL PASO COMMUNITY NAMED TO HEAD MISSION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT MONROE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Adriana Barrera, a former president of El Paso
Community College in Texas, was named president of Mission College
on Wednesday, a decision hailed by community activists disappointed
when a previous attempt failed to hire a leader for the northeast
San Fernando Valley campus.
</P>
<P>
   Barrera, 49, impressed Los Angeles Community College District
trustees with her vision for Mission's future and her
``toughness,'' board President Kelly Candaele said. She also was
the top pick of a coalition of Northeast Valley residents that had
formed nearly a year ago, following the earlier controversial
president search.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased to join the Mission College family,'' Barrera
said, following a brief announcement ceremony during a board
meeting at Trade-Tech College in downtown Los Angeles. ``Hopefully,
I'm a quick enough learner.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Benavides, Texas, a hamlet of 1,800 residents about
90 miles west of Corpus Christi, Barrera will succeed interim
President Tom Oliver on July 1. She will earn $121,264 a year
administering a college campus that often sees itself as the most
neglected in the city's nine-campus system.
</P>
<P>
   With 7,000 students, Mission is bursting at the seams but has
botched previous expansion attempts. There has been infighting
among faculty and administrators, stemming from myriad issues such
as campus overcrowding and unpopular personnel changes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the problems, many consider the college an anchor of the
northeast San Fernando Valley. Members of the selection committee
said Barrera has the potential to transform Mission into a
first-class campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``She seems like she is going to take over a college, which is
on the verge of greatness, and just run with it,'' said Fern
Reisner, a Mission College American Federation of Teachers staff
guild representative who was on the committee that selected Barrera
and three other finalists for the post.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce College President Darroch ``Rocky'' Young headed the
search committee that had pared down the initial list of 30
contenders. Of the four finalists, he said, Barrera was the only
one with experience as a college president who had grappled with
issues similar to those she could face at Mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had been president in a very challenging political
environment,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   After earning a doctorate in psychology from Texas Tech
University, Barrera began her community college career as a
part-time instructor at Austin Community College in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later she was named president of El Paso Community
College, becoming the highest-paid female community college
administrator in Texas. She left in 1998 to become a grant writer
and consultant, after a majority of the El Paso Community College
District board of trustees refused to renew her contract.
</P>
<P>
   Barrera described her departure from El Paso as a tough
experience rooted in a difference of opinion over power-sharing
between her and some board members.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board and I weren't working together,'' she said,
declining further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Olga Mapula, a former board chairwoman who left her post the
same year Barrera resigned, said she disagreed with the majority of
her colleagues at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As times change, people on the board sometimes want somebody
different,'' said Mapula, who declined to provide further detail.
``It was just a difference of opinion on some issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Current board chairman Chuck Silva said the board and Barrera
``just parted ways.'' But he praised Barrera as an effective
administrator and predicted she would do well at Mission.
</P>
<P>
   In the San Fernando Valley, the naming of Barrera was met with
relief from residents observing the selection process. Some
expressed hope for the campus, saying it would receive greater
attention under a permanent president.
</P>
<P>
   ``A permanent president will get all of the attention and all of
the support they need to advance our issues effectively,'' said
Xavier Flores, a member of the original selection committee that
produced three candidates, all of whom the district's board of
trustees rejected last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Barrera's appointment ends a troubled yearlong selection process
that incensed some participants to such a degree they forced a
state audit of the district's selection policies. Others suggested
splitting up the nine-campus district.
</P>
<P>
   The Valley Coalition for a Responsible Community College
District was formed in July after the district's board of trustees
rejected the three candidates. Several coalition members, including
Flores, had been part of the first search committee and they
complained the board was ignoring them and, by extension, the
Northeast Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest search, Flores said the coalition recommended
Barrera as its first choice after seeing all four finalists at a
series of community forums two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had all the experience we deemed necessary,'' Flores said.
``She had worked with very similar communities in the past (and)
she had experience seeking resources, which we think was a critical
aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrera said she will spend her time between now and July 1
making frequent visits to the campus to get to know administrators,
the faculty and students at Mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dream was to come back to a community college,'' Barrera
said. ``Not to be egotistical, but I was a good president.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
