<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 00:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1742 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-E-CONTRACT-GOP-SFCHRO     05-11 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-E-CONTRACT-GOP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE OKS LONGER BAN ON INTERNET TAXATION AS PART OF
REPUBLICANS'  `ECONTRACT'
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Driving to seize the high ground on high tech
Wednesday, House Republicans pushed through a five-year extension
of the popular but controversial moratorium on new Internet taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed by a resounding 352-to-75 vote, despite
opposition by the White House and 39 of the nation's governors.
</P>
<P>
   It also marked the opening round of the House GOP's new
``eContract 2000,'' an agenda that all but mirrors Silicon Valley's
legislative wish list _ from opening trade with China to increasing
the number of H-1B work visas for skilled immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assert that freedom is the answer, not government
intervention,'' declares the ``eContract,'' which includes a list
of proposals from tax and litigation relief to protection of
intellectual property and employee stock options.
</P>
<P>
   Modeled on the 1994 Contract With America that helped usher in
the House GOP majority, the manifesto is designed to freshen the
Republicans' election-year agenda and flatten opposition from
Democrats loath to cross the wildly popular high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   The initial success of the GOP initiative was apparent Wednesday
as many Democrats voted for the moratorium despite their
misgivings. The White House issued a statement opposing the bill,
but backed off a veto threat.
</P>
<P>
   The White House said the extension would ``in effect enact a
five-year hold on any further consideration of Internet tax issues,
creating uncertainty in a vital and rapidly growing industry.''
</P>
<P>
   The moratorium bans new taxes on Internet access, or  &LR; as well as
taxes that single out the Internet for discriminatory or multiple
taxes. The extension also would ban some existing Internet taxes in
a handful of cities and states.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chris Cox, R-Newport Beach, who sponsored both the original
moratorium and its extension with Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., predicted
the ``landslide'' bipartisan vote would melt White House
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no question in this election year where the supposed
father of the Internet will wind up,'' Cox said, referring to Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, has said
he supports the current moratorium, but thinks state and local
governments face a ``fiscal catastrophe'' if they are denied sales
taxes on online commerce. Texas Gov. George W. Bush, who has been
reluctant to endorse a permanent Internet tax ban out of fear of
lost state tax revenue, applauded Wednesday's House action.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's probable GOP opponent said the moratorium ``will provide
time to analyze the full impact of e-commerce and ensure that the
rapid growth of the Internet is not slowed by new taxes.'' Bush
said his position is ``consistent,'' because it refers to Internet
access taxes.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; States Fear Losses
</P>
<P>
   Beyond its political implications, the tax moratorium extension
also serves a strategic aim in the huge battle between state and
local governments and online retailers over sales taxes on Internet
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   States contend that they stand to lose billions of dollars in
sales tax revenue from online commerce and say that extending the
moratorium _ set to expire next year _ could delay attempts to
address the issue. They are backed by traditional ``brick and
mortar'' retailers such as Kmart Corp. and Home Depot Inc. that
must charge sales taxes and argue they face a disadvantage against
online retailers.
</P>
<P>
   The Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce, established
under the original moratorium to study the sales tax issue, failed
to agree on a recommendation despite a year and a half of work.
</P>
<P>
   Cox argued that state sales tax revenues have been booming,
despite dire predictions. ``What we now find,'' Cox said, ``is that
we have nothing to fear from good policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither the current moratorium nor its proposed extension
actually bans sales taxes on Internet purchases, a point of much
confusion even among House members. Online purchases already fall
under a 1992 Supreme Court ruling on catalog sales, which require a
retailer to have a physical presence in a state before a sales tax
can be charged.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers are supposed to report out-of-state purchases and pay
a ``use tax,'' but this is widely ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argued that extending the moratorium would create a
disincentive for states to simplify their admittedly byzantine tax
laws in order to ease collection of taxes on Internet and catalog
sales.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Conservative Opposition
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Ernest Istook, R-Okla., a conservative renegade, denounced
Cox's bill. By 2006, he said, ``it may be too late to do anything''
about online sales taxes, and he accused supporters of ``scrambling
to show who can be `friendliest' to the Internet community, even if
it means turning a deaf ear to other businesses and ignoring common
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox scoffed at the argument, calling it ``a disconnect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The best that can be said is that it's the same subject _
they're both about the Internet,'' Cox said, accusing opponents of
trying to ``take this perfectly good bill hostage for an extraneous
issue which is admittedly important.''
</P>
<P>
   The House Judiciary Committee has scheduled hearings on Internet
sales taxes for May 17.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans turned back Democrat-led attempts to shorten the
extension to two years. Rep. Anna Eshoo, D-Atherton, voted for the
five-year extension, but said it avoids ``the very heavy,
complicated lifting work'' that is needed to resolve the sales tax
issue for states and localities.
</P>
<P>
   Cox insisted that states are awash in money, with California tax
revenues rising 20 percent last month alone, partly as a result of
the Internet tax moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growth in the new economy is fueling the rest of the
economy,'' Cox said. ``By adopting a policy of not killing the
goose laying the golden eggs, we have had some great successes.''
</P>
<P>
   Governors and mayors, along with large traditional retailers,
are lobbying hard to stop the bill in the Senate. Senate Commerce
Committee Chairman John McCain, R-Arizona, recently postponed his
permanent Internet tax ban _ an issue he campaigned on in his fight
for the GOP presidential nomination _ after confronting stiff
opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, the House GOP will continue its ``eContract 2000''
with a bill to repeal the 3 percent federal telephone excise tax,
originally imposed in 1898 to finance the Spanish-American War. The
tax is widely ridiculed as a tax on Internet use that falls
especially hard on low-income households. Repeal has strong
bipartisan support, including sponsorship by Rep. Robert Matsui,
D-Sacramento, who sits on the House tax-writing committee.
</P>
<P>
   The House also will consider a bill to increase the number of
H-1B temporary visas for skilled immigrants from the current
ceiling of 115,000 a year to 200,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
