<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STERN SHRUGS OFF COMPLAINTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The arrival of the NBA postseason has seen a
return of low-scoring games, new complaints over elongated playoff
series and the usual gripes over television dictating the schedule.
But commissioner David Stern, attending Wednesday night's game at
Staples Center, was typically unmoved by any concerns raised over
the status of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA this season installed a few refinements to the rules and
ordered officials to crack down on some physical defensive play.
The league got the desired result - seven of 29 teams averaged 100
points per game (only one team did last season), the league average
was 97.5 and no team averaged below 90 per game.
</P>
<P>
   But of the 16 playoff teams, only the Lakers (104.4) are
averaging triple digits, the league average is 90.9 and seven teams
are under 90 per game. And then there's the Miami-New York series,
which produced a decidedly ugly 82-76 Knicks win on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A cause for worry?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' Stern said. ``You know, what would be nice
is for us to allow personalities in either teams or series or
games. There was a time when you knew that Washington, they were
the bruise brothers and they would be slow, and San Antonio would
run, and if there was a series between two slowdown teams, it would
be something else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have time to study the other team, and the playoffs
give you the time, our teams know other teams' moves better than
the other team does.... There's always a huge drop in the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   On other issues:
</P>
<P>
   -Stern said the league would not bend the salary cap rules to
grandfather in massive contracts like Shaquille O'Neal's $121
million deal. Lakers owner Jerry Buss and others have asked for an
exception to avoid the league's luxury tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a possibility,'' Stern said. ``Actually, if he'd (Buss)
like to, there are other teams that would be happy to relieve him
of those contracts, if they're causing a burden.''
</P>
<P>
   -Stern said the drawn-out first round, which featured five games
over 13 days, would probably be repeated in future years. The
schedule drew criticism from coaches and players but provided the
league additional revenue from its TV partners. NBC gained five
additional weekend games, and TNT and TBS were able to televise
games without overlapping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every game on NBC instead of a cable network gets two and a
half times the number of viewers,'' Stern said, ``so more people
saw it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ratings were up 9 percent, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   -On the seemingly endless string of timeouts during playoffs,
Stern said, ``We're working on that one ... so that the last two
minutes (of a game) doesn't have to take 25.''
</P>
<P>
   One more time: Stern presented O'Neal with the MVP trophy before
the game and O'Neal got a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to thank Phil Jackson, the real coach of the year, my
teammates and most of all the Staples Center fans,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson finished second to Orlando's Doc Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Ouch report: Derek Fisher, suffering from a viral infection, was
sent home before the game, leaving the Lakers with just three
guards in uniform.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
