<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOMEWORK PAYS AS SEGUI HOMER IN NINTH SINKS MARINERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON, Texas _ The grapevine got to Kazuhiro Sasaki
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui had never seen Sasaki throw, not one pitch. But
Segui seemed to know all about the Mariners closer, who spent the
past 10 seasons in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Segui is plugged into the baseball network. Players talk all the
time, swapping notes. Have cell phone, will travel. Segui converted
all of that knowledge into a game-winning two-run homer, taking
Sasaki deep with one out and one on in the ninth for a 7-6 Texas
victory over Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knows Sasaki has a great forkball and an average
fastball,'' Segui said, spilling no secrets as he gave the
five-second scouting report on the Mariners closer. Sasaki hasn't
faced many major leaguers yet but confirmed Wednesday that those he
has faced have gotten the word out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I wasn't going to hit the forkball,'' Segui said. ``I
wanted to get in a situation where he had to throw me a fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   That he did. Sasaki faced Segui after making his first defensive
gaffe of the season, allowing the limping Rafael Palmeiro to beat
out an infield hit to set up the game-winner. Segui came to the
plate with Seattle holding a one-run lead and Tom Evans
pinch-running for Palmeiro.
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki threw a forkball. Ball one. He threw another forkball.
Ball two. He threw a fastball. The rockets' red glare blanketed The
Ballpark In Arlington just seconds after Segui lit the fuse on his
second homer of the season. The vapor trail ended in the right
field bleachers as the Rangers stormed home plate, waiting for
Segui, the conquering hero. Sasaki hung his head briefly, then
walked off the mound with his first blown save and his first loss
in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't think he could pull the ball like that,'' Sasaki said
through an interpreter, although the way he ran his hands through
his hair and the way he rubbed at his chin needed no interpretation
_ he was perplexed. ``The location of the ball was good, outside.
At the most, I thought he might get the ball in the gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised he was able to pull the ball like he did.''
</P>
<P>
   The grapevine has also gotten around about Segui, who was with
the Mariners at this time last year. He has the look of a Q-Tip
with the dyed blond tuft of hair on his scalp, but he has the swing
of a tornado _ he's crushing everything in his path and is leading
the AL in batting. He owns a glistening .387 average after a
5-for-12 series against the Mariners, helping the Rangers take two
of three.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's hot, no question about it,'' Seattle manager Lou Piniella
said of Segui. ``He's hitting everything.''
</P>
<P>
   Piniella then took the time to scold Sasaki, ever so gently.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't cover first base,'' Piniella said, shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   The play in question was a liner hit toward right field by
Palmeiro with Segui in the on-deck circle. The Mariners had taken
the lead in the top of the ninth on a two-out Royce Clayton
throwing error, and Sasaki was two outs away from his fifth save
and a 6-5 Seattle win.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Mark McLemore broke quickly on the Palmeiro
liner, but Sasaki didn't. When McLemore knocked the ball down and
popped up, ready to fire a throw to first base, there was no one
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't think I could get to the ball,'' McLemore said. ``I
didn't think I could get to it, either.''
</P>
<P>
   If McLemore was willing to let Sasaki off the hook easily,
pitching coach Bryan Price wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never assume anything on a ball hit to the right side of
the infield,'' Price said. ``You go until you see that the first
baseman has the base. If he doesn't, you keep going. Particularly
with Palmeiro right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro is playing with a bad hamstring and gets down the first
base line about as quickly as the Mariners' designated limper,
quad-stressed DH Edgar Martinez. Even though McLemore tracked the
ball down on the outfield grass, the Mariners would have had an out
had Sasaki covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' Sasaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the mistake, Segui faced Sasaki with a chance to win
the game, not just tie it. And the Rangers, for all their troubles
in a 15-18 start to the 2000 season, have been good at winning
games in crunch time. They did it to Oakland Friday and Saturday,
and Wednesday the defending AL West champs made it three
last-at-bat wins in six days.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of leaving the Rangers stewing five games out of the
lead, the Mariners gave Texas a little boost of confidence. And
because of the two-game swing when teams face each other in the
division, Texas is just three games out. Last place seldom looks so
good. And first place could look better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that most people tend to forget is that this isn't
football,'' McLemore said. ``We don't play just 16 games. We play
162 game. So you can't get too wrapped up in a game like this. And
you can't get too wrapped up in it when you win like we did
(Tuesday, a 13-3 Seattle victory).
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing matters except tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Tomorrow'' is now today. And the Mariners open a four-game set
in Oakland Thursday night against the team many picked to win the
West this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're disappointed with what happened here today,'' catcher
Dan Wilson said. ``You don't want to rally to take the lead into
the bottom of the ninth and lose it. But we play again tomorrow. We
can't carry this game with us tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 0107EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
