u s BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI     05-11 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER'S GAME SHAPE WON'T CUT IT SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; rr &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Come September, Vin Baker will enter the Olympic
Stadium in Sydney, Australia. The mind pauses to wonder who he'll
most resemble:
</P>
<P>
   Will the Sonics' big man be transformed by then into a sleek and
steely eyed gold-medal hunter, like the cyclists, track runners and
fencers?
</P>
<P>
   Or might it be best for Baker to slink to the back of U.S.
contingent during Opening Ceremonies and parade with the guys from
table tennis, shooting and Greco-Roman wrestling?
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, Baker runs the risk of sticking out in that
crowd, too.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, nearly every single Olympian who will represent the
U.S. in the 2000 Summer Games has a chance to be better fit and
more professional than the formerly fabulous Mr. Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Just the other day, a United States Olympic Committee dispatch
brought forth news of the feats of one U.S. swimmer named Neil
Walker.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Wisconsin native won five gold and two silver in
the World Swimming Championships and has set himself up for a
monster run in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   A picture of Walker showed the oxygen-rich holder of five world
records with his bevy of medals _ all splayed across the smoothly
muscled chest of a world-class athlete.
</P>
<P>
   That subject _ world-class athletes with hard bodies who deserve
to be rewarded for their hard work _ is what brings us to the
question du jour:
</P>
<P>
   What should Baker do this summer?
</P>
<P>
   Should he hit the pool with Walker and do sprint laps until he
swears off late-night excursions to Wild Ginger for jazz and good
times?
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe Baker could work out with two-sport wonder Chris Witty.
</P>
<P>
   Witty, you may remember, is the gold-medal winning speed skater
who is now attempting to make the U.S. Olympic cycling squad again
(she was an alternate in Atlanta.)
</P>
<P>
   Witty has thighs the size of Hoh Rain Forest Douglas fir.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a guarantee: If Baker worked out with Witty this summer,
he would never, ever cheat and run foul line-to-foul line during an
NBA playoff game again.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Tommy Lasorda. The Dodger Blue hall of famer was
just named manager of the U.S. Olympic baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we all know about Lasorda's love of pasta. But maybe Baker
could get a few tips from Lasorda on the Slim Fast or whatever it
was diet on which Lasorda shed layers of his carbo-loaded gut.
</P>
<P>
   If Lasorda can't get through to Baker, there's always a chance
Mary Lee Tracy could be the answer.
</P>
<P>
   At her gym in Cincinnati, Tracy is whipping 80-pounders like
Dominique Moceanu into shape for the U.S. Olympic gymnastic trials,
set for August in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy is no Bela Karolyi. She won't be locking Baker in his
bedroom with a slice of apple, calling him ``my little piglet.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the U.S. gymnasts can call 4 ounces of broiled chicken
dinner, hey, it's an option for the Sonics' big man.
</P>
<P>
   The point is, Baker needs to do something. As a card-carrying
member of the U.S. Olympic basketball team, Baker was chosen to win
a gold medal this summer in Sydney. That was way before his long
and stunning slide into oblivion.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until the end of a horrific second half of the season
that Sonics coach Paul Westphal finally benched Baker. It took two
other Sonics starters to go down with Baker to soften the blow.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are certain that Baker and his handlers are
soft-peddling the criticism. If Baker has some issues with
Westphal, they still cannot be egregious enough to warrant such a
display of unprofessionalism. Depression is indeed a serious
whirlpool, but Baker has the talent and support to work out of it.
</P>
<P>
   But it is clear that for much of the second half of this past
season, Baker could hardly be taken seriously as an NBA player.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this 28-year-old whose ability to handle eating, partying
and constructive criticism seems non-existent is going to be an
Olympian?
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics have no official reason to wish for Baker to withdraw
from the U.S. Olympic squad. Perhaps they believe that performing
on a world stage with the NBA's elite will be the impetus for Baker
to get it together.
</P>
<P>
   That theory could backfire, however.
</P>
<P>
   In case anyone missed it, the real point of a Dream Team
excursion to the Olympics is for the NBA's elite to have themselves
a party on the way to winning their gold.
</P>
<P>
   Baker doesn't need a party. He doesn't need to roll into
training camp next October like he threw too many shrimps on the
barbie.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't his summer of love. By September, he should go to
Sydney only as a reward for getting back to being the old Vin
Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, while Gary Payton and Co. are quaffing some good
times Down Under, Baker should be getting his priorities and his
game in order _ for the real season.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Laura Vecsey can be reached at 206-448-8011
</P>
<P>
   or lauravecsey &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
