<SLUG> BC-PLAYSTATION-TWO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT ONLY FUN AND GAMES FOR SONY'S NEW PLAYSTATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ With music blasting and demonstrations
projected on two giant screens, Sony Computer Entertainment America
Inc. gave North America its first peek at the PlayStation 2 game
console during a media preview Wednesday in a downtown Los Angeles
studio.
</P>
<P>
   The second in a new generation of game systems driven by 128-bit
processors, PlayStation 2's North American version will be slightly
different from its Japanese counterpart on sale since March. Sega's
Dreamcast _ which also uses a high-performance 128-bit processor _
hit the market last September.
</P>
<P>
   Sony's console goes on sale Oct. 27 for $299, in time for the
holiday shopping season. It carries the same price tag as the
original PlayStation introduced in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The company said it will be the biggest consumer electronic
launch in history, with 1 million units initially being shipped
into North America. An additional 2 million units will ship by
March 2001.
</P>
<P>
   PlayStation 2 is expected to command the attention of
professionals attending the Electronic Entertainment Expo, which
begins Thursday at the Los Angeles Convention Center and features
400 exhibitors.
</P>
<P>
   It is expected to attract 55,000 interactive entertainment
professionals and an estimated 1,900 software titles will be on
display at the show, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony estimates 50 game titles for PlayStation 2 alone will be
introduced at the show.
</P>
<P>
   With its improved graphics, Internet connectability and the
ability to play digital video discs, PlayStation 2 is being billed
as the hub of the wired entertainment center.
</P>
<P>
   ``PlayStation 2 is not the future of video game entertainment,
it is the future of entertainment, period,'' said Kazuo Hirai,
president and chief operating officer of Sony Computer
Entertainment America. ``It's an entirely different platform that
will serve as the catalyst for the broadband revolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the Japanese version, the PlayStation sold in the United
States will have a port for a 3.5-inch hard disk drive. The
American version also is able to play DVD video without the need
for additional memory.
</P>
<P>
   Sony officials denied the addition of the port was a reaction to
Microsoft's proposed game console, X-Box, which will have a
built-in hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there is a PlayStation in one of every four U.S.
households, said Andrew House, the company's vice president of
marketing.
</P>
<P>
   The target audience for PlayStation 2 is broader than that for
the original system, House said.
</P>
<P>
   PlayStation 2's audio and video capabilities will appeal to
music and film buffs, and its Internet connectability will bring in
people interested in the cutting edge of technology, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And the system's compatibility with existing PlayStation games
will encourage users to graduate to the new system, House said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're able to bridge the gap between hardware that has dogged
our industry in the past. It's absolutely crucial that we validate
the platform with content,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sony has encouraged outside game publishers such as THQ Inc. of
Calabasas to develop titles for the new system. THQ enlisted the
help of game developer Volition Inc., which normally builds games
for the more powerful personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   But the more powerful processor in the new generation of game
consoles is making it possible to develop higher quality games,
said Jim Boone, senior producer for the role-playing game Summoner,
the first game THQ plans to release for PlayStation 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have to compromise on any of our technology. It's
been a lot of fun to develop the console game,'' Boone said.
</P>
<P>
   He said Summoner will lend itself well to multiplayer online
play, making it a good match for the PlayStation 2, which in the
future will connect to the Internet via a broadband connection.
</P>
<P>
   The type of broadband connection by which players can connect
has not been determined.
</P>
</TEXT>
