<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE'S SHOT SAVES LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal rocked and rolled, but the
Phoenix Suns did not roll over. The MVP filled up his shiny new
trophy with all the points and rebounds his team could possibly
need, but the Lakers proved they could not thrive on Shaq alone.
</P>
<P>
   Even Superman needs an occasional assist from Wonderboy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal celebrated his MVP award with 38 points and 20 rebounds,
but it was Kobe Bryant's breathtaking jumper from the top corner of
the key with 2.6 seconds left that carried the Lakers to a dramatic
97-96 victory over the Suns on Wednesday in Game 2 of the
conference semifinals at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took a 2-0 lead in the series, but they very nearly
let the homecourt advantage slip away.
</P>
<P>
   After leading for most of the game, the Lakers let the Suns pull
within 93-92 with just over 2 minutes remaining.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal missed a pair of free throws, Ron Harper made only 1 of
2, Bryant coughed up a turnover and suddenly the Suns had seized
the lead, 96-94. Bryant made 1 of 2 free throws to pull within a
point, but it took one more defensive stand from the MVP to set up
the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal blocked Penny Hardaway to get the Lakers one last
possession. Bryant made the most of it, crossing up Jason Kidd near
the top of the key, dribbling to his left, then sinking the jumper
over Kidd and Rodney Rogers for the 97-96 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns got an opportunity for a go-ahead basket, but Hardaway
missed a running jumper at the buzzer, with Harper hanging on him.
No foul was called.
</P>
<P>
   After a 28-point rout in Game 1, the Lakers expected a different
look or two from the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a game that takes a great deal of concentration for a
basketball club to come back and play, be prepared for a team
that's going to make changes,'' coach Phil Jackson said before the
game. ``We can't expect it to be the same type of game at all. I
anticipate that Phoenix will have some remedies for Shaq in the
hole. And when the ball goes in, they'll probably try to get it out
of his hands. And we'll have to wait an decision as to how we're
going to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the other end of the floor, I thought just some miscues,
obviously timing-wise, probably led to (the Suns') high turnover ra
game. I think that will be remedied too. Obviously, their 3-point
big guys, (Clifford) Robinson and (Rodney) Rogers, we have to be
prepared for them to make some shots tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was partially correct. The Suns did start putting guards
in O'Neal's lap with some regularity, Phoenix cut way down on its
turnovers, and Rogers and Robinson started to contribute a bit.
</P>
<P>
   It was evident from the first possession that the Suns would
throw every available body at O'Neal. But the occasional
double-teams had little effect, and the league's new MVP made 9 of
17 shots in the first half, scoring 21 points to stake the Lakers
to a 50-46 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   And the Lakers needed everything O'Neal gave them. After a fast
start,Bryant was slowed by foul trouble, picking up his first two
fouls in a 36-second span midway through the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   With Bryant on the bench, the Suns outscored the Lakers down the
stretch, took a brief 4-point lead and settled for a 26-24 edge at
the end of the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Plagued by 23 turnovers in their Game 1 loss, the Suns started
to unravel a bit in the second quarter. Their five turnovers led to
6 points by the Lakers, who rode the momentum, and 13 points from
O'Neal, to the halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant played just 11 minutes in the half, scoring 6 points, but
he made an impact on defense, with two blocks and a steal.
</P>
<P>
   With Glen Rice also starting slowly (4 points in the first
half), the bench picked up the slack _ Robert Horry scored 7
points, and Brian Shaw added 6.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson and Hardaway scored 11 points each for the Suns.
</P>
<P>
   With Bryant in foul trouble and Derek Fisher home with a viral
infection, the Lakers were thin at guard.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was hopeful that the Lakers' first-round experience with
the Sacramento Kings _ who fought back from a 2-0 deficit to tie
the series _ would be ``a process that hopefully we can learn
from.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this day-to-day, game-to-game type thing is really
what a series is all about,'' he said. ``Stay focused from game to
game and not worry about what's going on anywhere else in the
league, not worry about Shaq's MVP and just concentrating on what's
really important today now, and the next play as it goes along
makes teams have the ability to win championships.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
