<P>
   SHANGHAI-NOVELIST (Shanghai, China) _ Zhou Weihui had gathered
her friends and acquaintances on a veranda overlooking this city's
famous 1930s-era waterfront, ostensibly to say goodbye to society
for a while. She wanted to drop out of sight, she said, because she
was under too much pressure from China's formidable propaganda
machine, which was busy trashing her best-selling novel, ``Shanghai
Baby.'' Already, her publisher had destroyed the page proofs and
all of the books in stock, arguing _ after having sold at least
80,000 copies _ that the novel was in poor taste and that Zhou, 27,
was too outlandish. By Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-GUARDS (Maden, Turkey) _ Sipping tea in the sun and
looking down from their clay bunker at a placid field full of
wildflowers, Irfan Ozay and his cousin Remzi should be happy. With
their help and that of 95,000 other village guards, the Turkish
army has finally won its war against Kurdish rebels. But like many
other village guards, the Ozay cousins are worried and becoming
angry. They fear they will soon be cashiered and find themselves
without jobs or prospects. What to do with these village guards is
one of the most urgent questions that suddenly confront Turkey now
that peace has broken out. By Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
