<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-TURNER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS' TURNER SERIOUSLY ILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Oakland Raiders safety Eric Turner, a former
All-American at UCLA, is suffering from a serious stomach illness
that is believed to be career-threatening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible, terrible situation,'' said a high-ranking
Raiders official. ``We're going to respect the family's wishes on
this, but people should really be concerned for this kid.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked if Turner's illness is life-threatening, Raiders
officials declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It started out as an ulcer and it's developed into something
worse,'' the Raiders official said.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, a nine-year pro who lives in Westlake Village, did not
attend the Raiders' minicamp last week for personal reasons. It was
the second team gathering Turner missed over the last two months.
He has not been treated by team doctors since the end of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Attempts to contact the 31-year-old Turner, his family and agent
were unsuccessful over the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I saw him at the end of last year, he told me he
was having trouble keeping food down,'' said Willie Shaw, Kansas
City Chiefs assistant head coach/defensive-back coach who was
Oakland's defensive coordinator last year. ``He told me he was
going to get it checked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner is believed to be under a doctor's care at a Ventura
County hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who attended Ventura High, was an All-American safety at
UCLA and the second overall pick by the Cleveland Browns in the
1991 NFL draft. It was the highest draft position for a defensive
back in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   He spent six years with the Browns/Baltimore Ravens, earning Pro
Bowl honors in 1994 after tying for the NFL lead in interceptions
with nine. He also returned an interception for a 93-yard
touchdown, second longest in team history.
</P>
<P>
   Turner signed with the Raiders in 1997, leading the team in
tackles his first year with 111 and returning a fumble 65 yards for
a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, Turner played in just six games before a
foot injury sidelined him the remainder of the season. Over the
last two years, Turner has missed 16 games because of various ankle
and leg injuries. He also missed most of 1995 with the Browns after
suffering a back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Turner finished his UCLA career fourth on the all-time tackles
list with 369.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 0229EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1771 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-SUNS-LAKERS-HNS &LR;      05-11 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-LAKERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
LOS ANGELES _ The comparisons to Michael Jordan just keep piling
up.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kobe Bryant, who has often been compared to the former Chicago
Bulls star, provided more material for such talk by nailing a
14-foot jumper with 2.6 seconds remaining to give the Lakers a
97-96 victory over the Phoenix Suns on Wednesday in Game 2 of the
Western Conference semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The game, played before 18,997 at the Staples Center, gave the
Lakers a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series, which resumes Friday
at America West Arena in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't feel like I was in a Laker uniform or even at the
Staples Center,'' said Bryant of his Jordanesque game-winner. ``It
felt like I was on the playground. That's how it felt.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't ask the Suns how it felt.
</P>
<P>
   It's bad enough that the Lakers have everything under the, well,
sun.
</P>
<P>
   They have Shaquille O'Neal, the newly crowned Most Valuable
Player who once again proved he is the game's most dominating
presence by piling up 38 points and 20 rebounds in Wednesday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   They have Phil Jackson, generally considered to be the NBA's
best coach. And it seems they have all the talent in the world with
guys like Bryant and Glen Rice suiting up with O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   But do they have to have all the luck, too?
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's jumper, a pull-up from 14 feet over Jason Kidd and
Rodney Rogers for his only basket of the fourth quarter, squeezed
the last breath out of a Suns team that refused to die.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix had rallied from a 12-point third-quarter deficit,
taking a two-point lead on a layup by Penny Hardaway, the last of
his 27 points, with 47 seconds to play. And when he knocked down
only one of two free throws three seconds later, the Suns had to
feel good about their chances.
</P>
<P>
   But Hardaway's next shot was blocked by O'Neal, giving the
Lakers one last possession with 23 seconds remaining. Bryant
dribbled the clock down before pulling up for the game-winner.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal then blocked a desperation shot by Hardaway to preserve
the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said O'Neal, who added five blocks to his
night's work. ``We didn't play very well. We didn't bring our `A'
game tonight. But Kobe saved us with a fabulous shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he did. Just like Jordan would have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking that I just had to make it,'' said Bryant, who
finished with 15 points. ``I tried to read the defense and see
where everybody was. I just felt like I was in the back yard. I had
a flashback to when I was a kid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to go right, but Jason cut me off. I cut left and went
up for the jump shot. I had to pull the shot back a little bit
(because of the defense), and thank God it fell.''
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have to be wondering what they did to insult the
basketball gods, letting this one slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give credit to a great player,'' said Hardaway,
who finished with eight assists. ``He made a tough shot _ a
double-clutch shot on the way down with two seconds left on the
clock. That's something you want him to take.''
</P>
<P>
   But making it?
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game, you would have thought the Suns didn't have a
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Lakers enter with a 15-2 record in games played
on Wednesday, they had a 5-0 record against the Suns this year,
including a sweep of four regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the fact that O'Neal was psyched up after NBA
commissioner David Stern handed him the Maurice Podoloff Trophy,
signifying the MVP, in a brief pre-game ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   But there were signs this might not be the Lakers' night after
all.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant was limited to 11 first-half minutes because of foul
problems, and O'Neal was forced to pick up the offensive slack,
scoring 21 points to stake the Lakers to a 50-44 halftime lead.
</P>
<P>
   But the Suns just couldn't capitalize, though Rice had another
mediocre game (13 points) and Bryant had those foul problems (34
minutes).
</P>
<P>
   Cliff Robinson (30 points, 13 in the fourth quarter) and
Hardaway did all they could, but there was precious little help for
them. Kidd (13 points, six assists) still isn't 100 percent after
coming back from a broken ankle suffered six weeks ago, and Sixth
Man of the Year Rogers had his second straight poor game (eight
points on 3-of-11 shooting).
</P>
<P>
   And the Suns still have no answer for O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, O'Neal recently dubbed himself ``The Big Aristotle,''
but it's the Suns who have to be doing all the deep thinking: How
to stop O'Neal?
</P>
<P>
   So far, Phoenix coach Scott Skiles has yet to find a plan to
even slow O'Neal, who entered the game averaging 30.7 points and
16.8 rebounds in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have tried single coverage, double teams and going
small in an effort to force O'Neal to come out on defense, but
nothing has worked, as evidenced by O'Neal's two-game averages of
37.5 points and 17 rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   So, how do you stop a 7-1, 335-pound center who has the moves of
a much smaller player?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an (unanswerable) question,'' O'Neal said. ``An X-Files
question.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
