<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-ROCKIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON 
  c. 2000, Houston Chronicle  
The sensation of winning a series at home had become such a distant
memory, the Astros almost didn't recognize it.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Is that what that was?'' Astros second baseman Craig Biggio
wisecracked.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed it was. The Astros, led by the precision pitching of
Shane Reynolds, bumped off the Colorado Rockies 5-1 Wednesday night
at Enron Field. They took two of three from the Rockies to win
their first home series since they took two of three from the
Dodgers in the final series in Astrodome history.
</P>
<P>
   Considering they've managed only a 5-10 record at their new
ballpark, some Astros no doubt long for the Astrodome, but don't
count Reynolds among them. He has mastered the art of pitching at
Enron, compiling a 2-0 record with a 3.15 ERA at the
hitter-friendly yard.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps more impressive is the fact he has allowed only one home
run in 20 innings at the ballpark often referred to as Home-ron
Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made good pitches, kept the ball down, worked in and out and
got key outs,'' said Reynolds, who allowed four hits and a run in
seven innings. ``We scored some runs early, and that always gives
you some confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   If Reynolds, whose five-game winning streak matches his career
best, could pitch every day, the Ar~stros would be )z?~9yH3irst &LR; 1
</P>
</TEXT>
