<HEADER>
A1778 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-     05-11 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE'S SHOT SAVES LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Shaquille O'Neal rocked and rolled, but the
Phoenix Suns did not roll over. He filled up his shiny new trophy
with all the points and rebounds a team could possibly want, but
the Lakers for once needed more than just an MVP performance.
</P>
<P>
   Even Superman needs an occasional assist from Wonderboy.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal celebrated his MVP award with 38 points, but it was Kobe
Bryant's jumper from the top corner of the key with 2.6 seconds
left that carried the Lakers to a heart-stopping 97-96 victory over
the Suns on Wednesday, in Game 2 of the conference semifinals at
Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers took a 2-0 lead in the series, but they nearly let
the homecourt advantage slip away. Bryant wouldn't let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't bring our `A' game today. Kobe saved us,'' O'Neal
said.
</P>
<P>
   He did it with flair. O'Neal blocked a Penny Hardaway jumper
with 22.9 seconds left to set up the final play. Coach Phil Jackson
did not call timeout, leaving the show to the Lakers' 21-year-old
playmaker. Bryant crossed up Jason Kidd at the top of the key,
dribbled to his left and pulled up for a 14-foot jumper over Kidd
and Rodney Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   Pandemonium erupted among the 18,997 in attendance as the ball
swished cleanly through. In Bryant's mind, however, all was calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just felt like I was in the backyard, I honestly did,'' he
said. ``Just kind of flashed back to when I was a kid and I just
tried to go right, (Kidd) cut it off, so I came back to the left. I
was going up for the jump shot. I think I saw his hand out of the
periphery, so I had to kind of pull the shot back a little bit,
then guide it through.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant had won games at the foul line before, but this was his
first game-winner from the field, and he didn't hesitate to say it
was the biggest shot of his four-year career. How did it feel?
</P>
<P>
   ``Feels like doing it again,'' Bryant said with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe is known to make shots like that,'' said teammate Glen
Rice. ``Thank God it went in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers outshot the Suns 53.4 percent to 43.5 percent, but it
took one last defensive stand to secure the win an O'Neal block of
Hardaway, with Ron Harper also in his face, at the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody knew who was going to have the ball,'' Harper said.
``He was playing good all game long, so our main thing was to slow
him down some.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite getting shut down in the final seconds, Hardaway
finished with 27 points and eight assists. Clifford Robinson
carried the rest of the load, scoring 30 points for the Suns, who
also outrebounded the Lakers 43-37.
</P>
<P>
   It was Hardaway and Robinson who sparked a 31-23 fourth quarter
for Phoenix, erasing what was once a 13-point Laker lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed in the players today,'' Jackson
said. ``We had a real good third quarter, we had a 15-point chance
opportunity, to extend the lead when we were up by 12, with seconds
to go and we gave up a 3-point shot (by Robinson) at the end of the
quarter, and started the fourth quarter in a daze.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they came out with a lot of energy and put the game in
jeopardy. And we were lucky to pull it out, actually probably
didn't deserve that win, other than the fact we were able to play
some defense down the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   Several offensive miscues nearly doomed them. O'Neal badly
missed a pair of free throws, Harper made only 1 of 2, and Bryant
coughed up a turnover in traffic as the Lakers watched a 1-point
lead turn into a 2-point deficit in the final minutes. Bryant also
uncharacteristically missed 1 of 2 from the line.
</P>
<P>
   Until the end, it had been an off-night for Bryant. He got in
early foul trouble and finished with just 15 points. The Lakers
bench made the difference, with Brian Shaw and Robert Horry scoring
12 points each.
</P>
<P>
   So the Lakers head to Phoenix having preserved homecourt
advantage but having given the Suns reason for hope.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gained a ton of confidence,'' Hardaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson was not concerned about that possibility, saying,
``There is no such thing in this kind of a situation. You play for
what it's worth, and every game is different, has it's different
personality.... (The Suns' comeback) in itself might give them a
hope, but who cares? They're going back home, they've got to have
that kind of ability or else they're in jeopardy anyway.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
