<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 03:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1779 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU     05-11 0697
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS LOSE PITCHERS' DUEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - In the era of power and offense and bandbox ballparks,
a classic pitching matchup remains possible. The ingredients needed
are a couple of quality pitchers, and Randy Johnson and Kevin Brown
fit neatly into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   They dueled for eight intensity-filled innings in their highly
anticipated matchup, before pitch-count and circumstance got them
both.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, it was Tony Womack's RBI single off reliever Terry
Adams with none out in the ninth that gave Arizona a 2-1 win over
the Dodgers at Bank One Ballpark on Wednesday to sweep the
three-game series.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers tied their season-high with four straight losses,
three of which have come in the opposition's last at-bat. Arizona
tied a club record with its seventh consecutive win.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating any time you lose,'' said Brown, who is 1-1
with a 1.20 ERA in four starts since returning from the disabled
list. ``It all boils down to the fact we lost the game. We had a
lead and didn't hold it.''
</P>
<P>
   After Brown allowed six hits in eight innings, Adams (2-3) was
brought into a situation that became too familiar for the Dodgers
in this series. Onan Masaoka joined the club before the game,
making him the lone lefty in the bullpen, but a 1-1 game in Arizona
two days after throwing 74 pitches in a minor-league start isn't
the ideal situation. So Adams got the call.
</P>
<P>
   He then faced three left-handers, each of which singled. Andy
Fox began the rally with a single to right, Travis Lee moved him to
third with a single to right and Womack hit a ball to deep right-
center to score Fox for the win. Lefties were hitting 9 for 39
(.231) against Adams.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes a difference,'' said catcher Todd Hundley, whose
second-inning homer accounted for the Dodgers' only run. ``It's a
big difference when (manager) Davey (Johnson) has some other
options.''
</P>
<P>
   Byung-Hyun Kim (1-1) struck pinch hitters Dave Hansen and Todd
Hollandsworth out with two runners on in the ninth for the win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though I haven't seen him, I have to be a professional
hitter and be prepared,'' Hansen said. ``I got some good hacks on
him, but didn't get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who entered the game 7-0 with a 0.93 ERA in seven
starts, tied a season high with 13 strikeouts in eight innings.
It's the seventh time in eight starts he's hit double digits in
strikeouts. He's done it 132 times in his career, second to Nolan
Ryan's 215.
</P>
<P>
   But for the first time this season Johnson didn't win his start.
He had a no-decision, allowing a season-high eight hits and one
run. His ERA rose to 0.95.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Green had three hits off Johnson and Jose Vizcaino had a
three-hit night, including two off Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at it now, I guess it was what everybody was hoping it
would be,'' Johnson said. ``Going up against someone of Kevin
Brown's caliber, you don't have a whole lot of room to make
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundley's third right-handed homer (eight overall) gave the
Dodgers an early lead, but they couldn't come up with the big hit
that could create a rally.
</P>
<P>
   In the first they had two on and one out and Gary Sheffield and
Eric Karros struck out. In the sixth, Karros doubled with one out
but Adrian Beltre and Hundley struck out, and then there was the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   In total, the Dodgers were 1 for 10 with seven strikeouts with
runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the guy on the ropes a couple of times and couldn't get
him,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said. ``Brownie pitched a
great game and we couldn't get him any runs. It was a tough
series.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown yielded one run, struck out six and walked three. But it's
the two-out walk in the seventh inning to Jay Bell that he'd like
to have back. Luis Gonzalez followed with a double to the
left-center field gap to tie it 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure it was a that bad of a pitch (to Gonzalez),
the walk ahead of that is what set it up,'' Brown said. ``I slipped
on one pitch and the last pitch was pretty darn close. I thought it
was pretty darn close.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
