   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO IS FODAY SANKOH AND DOES HE CONTROL SIERRA LEONE? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO-IS-SANKOH?-INDEPENDENT? &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As fighting erupted Monday outside the Freetown home
of Foday Sankoh, the leader of the rebel forces in Sierra Leone,
diplomats in New York continued to struggle with a conundrum that
is pivotal to the prospects for peace in the country: What should
they do with this man whom they know to be a beast?...By David
Usborne, The Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BRITISH FORCES PITTED AGAINST RUTHLESS BUSH GUERRILLAS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSHMEN-SIERRALEONE-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MONROVIA, LIBERIA _ The looming battle for Freetown will pit
Sierra Leone's small army, subtly backed by British forces, against
some of the most ruthless bush guerrilla fighters in Africa. They
are armed by renegade leaders of surrounding states, motivated
purely by greed for the small West African country's diamonds...By
Alex Duval Smith, The Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (575 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SIERRA LEONE: A CHRONOLOGY OF TERROR &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PRIMER-SIERRALEONE-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Sierra Leone's Revolutionary United Front is a
byword for unmitigated terror in a country that has known eight
years of brutal civil war. The guerrillas' grisly calling card is
amputation _ sometimes double amputations _ often offered in a
choice of ``short arms'' or ``long arms.''...By Stephen Castle, The
Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (425 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DOH! ANOTHER RECORD YEAR FOR `BACK-BACK-BACK-BACK!'S &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOMER-SLUGFEST-BASEBALL-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The hits just keep on coming. Baseball is in the
middle of a home-run heat wave, and it shows no signs of letting
up. ``We're off on a record pace for dingers, dongs and
back-back-back-backs,'' wrote Sports Illustrated's Leight
Montville. ``The ball is juiced, the strike zone is about the size
of a sheet of Xerox paper, the fences in the new parks are as close
as the kitchen telephone. Everyone is hitting home runs.'' All of
this ought to bring joy, one would have thought. But the home-run
bonanza has longtime fans uneasy, and the commentators are
worried....By Andrew Marshall, The Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Commentary Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (850 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GIANT ARTICHOKE TO FUEL SPANISH POWER STATIONS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ARTICHOKE-ENERGY-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   MADRID _ Spain has pioneered a revolutionary way of producing
energy from genetically-modified artichokes, and will shortly set
up two artichoke-fuelled power stations. These are not your common
garden globe artichokes, mind you, eaten section by section with
melted butter or perhaps a vinaigrette. These souped-up monsters,
``Cynara cardunculus,'' or cardoons, are capable of heating and
lighting a small town....By Elizabeth Nash, The Independent,
London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `JUDGE RAM' DELIVERS SPEEDY ROADSIDE JUSTICE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JUDGE-ON-WHEELS-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ It's not quite Judge Dredd, the comic-book hero who
dispensed rapid (and often nasty) justice from his motorbike. More
like Judge RAM: an intelligent computer program that sorts out
roadside disputes. The device, now being used in Brazil, uses an
artificial-intelligence computer program called Electronic
Judge....By Charles Arthur, The Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (400 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; `SWITCH OFF OR GET LOST': SAN FRANCISCO BANS CELL PHONES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CELLPHONE-BACKLASH-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Ed Moose knew the cell-phone craze had gone too
far when one customer at his trendy San Francisco restaurant picked
up the phone to talk to another customer sitting at the other end
of the bar. This was more than Moose could stand, so he took
action: he banned cell phones from his establishment altogether.
The cellular crowd has now been banished to the pavement, along
with that other group of Californian outcasts, smokers. ``There's a
total backlash going on,'' said the bar manager at Dine, a
restaurant in San Francisco's so-called Multimedia Gulch area,
where everyone has a cell phone but nobody is allowed to use them
anymore....By Andrew Gumbel, The Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; AND NOW...POKEMON ON YOUR MOBILE PHONE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POKEMON-CELLPHONES-INDEPENDENT &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Just when you thought it was safe to pass a shop
with your child, here comes the latest craze: Pokemon on your
mobile phone. Bandai, the Japanese toymaker which unleashed
Tamagotchis and Power Rangers on the world, is now testing its
latest scheme on Tokyo schoolchildren, many of whom own mobile
phones....By Leo Lewis, The Independent, London &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (275 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STEPHEN KING'S ONLINE BOOK MARKS DAWN OF DIGITAL PUBLISHING &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; E-BOOKS-ONLINE-WORTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ Until now, electronic books were an idea whose time
might have never come. But thanks to author Stephen King and his
66-page novella, ``Riding the Bullet,'' publishing houses and
electronics manufacturers are taking a second look at a market they
have long been content to ignore...By Dave Califano, Worth
Magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (500 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; RETOOLING THE OLD `GERMAN MODEL' ECONOMY &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GERMANY-REAGANOMICS-WORTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) _ When Bill Clinton campaigned in 1992, he applauded
the ``German model,'' highlighting the intimate links between
banks, unions, corporations, and government. But after Clinton
moved into the White House, he soon learned that the German
economic model was falling apart, and that the U.S. economy was in
fact far healthier and sturdier than Germany's. Eight years later,
Germany may be getting its economic house back in order. Under the
left-wing government of Chancellor Gerhard Schroder, the German
economy should grow at least 3 percent in 2000. This is
Reaganomics, twenty years after Reagan, albeit with a Teutonic
tilt...By Todd G. Buchholz, Worth Magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Business Editors) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (600 words) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SWEDES' SMELL OF SUCCESS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SWEDEN-STOCKMARKET-WORTH &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (UNDATED) - Sweden is beautiful. The land is beautiful. The
people are beautiful. The economy is beautiful. And yes, the stock
market is beautiful. So far this year, Sweden is winning the race
among major countries for the strongest stock market. It's no
wonder; Sweden is among the most tech-savvy countries in the
world....By Todd G. Buchholz, Worth Magazine &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (ATTN: Business Editors) &QL;
</P>
