<HEADER>
A1783 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-     05-11 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS LOSE IN NINTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM -- The Oakland A's scored four runs in the ninth inning
to break a 3-3 tie and beat the Angels, 7-4, Wednesday night before
15,300 at Edison Field, but it was a play as early in the fourth
inning that had at least one Angel steaming mad.
</P>
<P>
   The A's won the game against Angels reliever Mark Petkovsek, who
gave up all four runs in the ninth after pitching a scoreless
eighth. Ben Grieve had an RBI single, Jeremy Giambi drove in two
with a single and Eric Chavez scored the fourth run with a single
as the A's batted around.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels scored once in the ninth on Darin Erstad's third hit
of the night, an RBI single. However, they wasted opportunities
early in the game, and had one potential rally thwarted by a
third-base ump Mike VanVleet.
</P>
<P>
   What started out as a promising fourth inning for the Angels
turned to frustration and anger, most of it coming from Angels
hitting coach Mickey Hatcher.
</P>
<P>
   Garret Anderson led off the inning with a single to center, then
scored on a double to left by Troy Glaus. Anderson, though, was
ordered back to third base after VanVleet ruled Glaus' double was
touched by a fan.
</P>
<P>
   Replays showed clearly the ball short-hopped the short fence in
left and stayed in the park without fan interference, and the bad
call cost the Angels at least one run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't need to see a replay,'' manager Mike Scioscia said.
``I wouldn't have argued if I wasn't positive. But that call didn't
win or lose the ballgame. We can't hang the loss on an umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson compounded the ump's bad call with a baserunning
mistake of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Edgard Clemente hit a sharp grounder to Eric Chavez at third,
but Anderson was caught between third and home and was tagged out
by catcher Ramon Hernandez. Matt Walbeck followed with a single to
load the bases, but Trent Durrington grounded into a double play to
end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Hatcher drew the ire of crew chief Al Clark, who was
the second-base ump. Clark began moving toward the Angels' dugout,
then tossed Hatcher out of the game. Scioscia came out to argue,
but he soon found himself trying to keep Hatcher away from Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn tried to restrain Hatcher and the
two fell to the ground on the infield dirt at the shortstop's
position. Hatcher eventually left the field as Scioscia continued
his argument, albeit more controlled, with Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher was still upset after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get thrown out because I was arguing that play,''
Hatcher said. ``Our guy hits into a double play and they get out of
it, and I say 'That lucky SOB,' talking about their pitcher.
(Clark) starts hollering at me. I wasn't talking to him, it had
nothing to do with him. That's terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to tell me I can't talk to my players. What's he
looking in our dugout for in the first place? ... I'm doing my job
as a hitting coach, hollering at my guys to get 'em going and he's
going to tell me I can't do that? That's not right.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Kent Bottenfield did not have his normal good
command, walking four to match a season-high. But he managed to
work his way through 6 2/3 innings, giving up three runs and
keeping the game close.
</P>
<P>
   A's starter Mark Mulder, making only his fifth major league
start, stifled the Angels before leaving the game with a 3-1 lead,
two out and Erstad on first base in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Mulder allowed only six hits in 7 2/3 innings and retired nine
in a row at one point, but he was helpless when the bullpen entered
the game and blew the lead. First, T.J. Mathews gave up an RBI
double to Tim Salmon, then closer Jason Isringhausen yielded an RBI
double to Anderson, tying the game at 3.
</P>
<P>
   By winning two of the three in the series, the A's (17-17) moved
ahead of the Angels (17-18) in the A.L. West standings, both teams
still trailing the first-place Mariners (17-14). It may be early,
but the A.L. West teams are in a cycle of playing each other for
the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have now lost two of three to both Seattle and
Oakland, with Texas in town for a four-game series beginning
tonight.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
