<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 03:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1787 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     05-11 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOBE GAINS TEAMMATES' CONFIDENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In the opening moments of the fourth quarter of
Wednesday night's playoff game at Staples Center, with the Lakers'
lead down to three points thanks to back-to-back turnovers and the
unexpectedly hot shooting of the Phoenix Suns' Clifford Robinson,
Kobe Bryant dribbled the ball near the right baseline.
</P>
<P>
   He began a drive to the basket, hesitated when Jason Kidd joined
Penny Hardaway in a double team, then jumped and heaved an
off-balance shot that crashed into the edge of the backboard and
caromed into a Sun's hands.
</P>
<P>
   Out-of-control moments like these are still part of the life of
young Kobe. In years - or months - past they might have resulted in
a scolding from the coach, eye-rolls by the veterans and a few
minutes on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   But these days, Phil Jackson and the Lakers veterans have
another way of dealing with the 21-year-old Bryant's tendency to
shoot wildly. They tell him to keep shooting. That approach paid
off again.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment that counted most Wednesday, with the Lakers down
by a point and seconds left in the game, Bryant dribbled, dribbled,
dribbled, crossed over from right to left, then pulled up in front
of defenders Kidd and Rodney Rogers and nailed an 18-footer.
</P>
<P>
   The difficult shot with 2.6 seconds on the clock gave the Lakers
a 97-96 victory and a 2-0 lead in their second-round series.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a kid who makes some mistakes but comes out and just
plays hard. That last shot was definitely a hell of a shot,'' said
the Lakers' Ron Harper. ``Kobe Bryant is one of them guys, you just
sit back and see what he's going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   That clutch jumper will be replayed over and over on television
until the Lakers and Suns meet again Friday night in Arizona. But
it won't tell you as much about Bryant's improvement as some of his
misses.
</P>
<P>
   Bryant came into this game having turned in back-to-back-to-back
sub-.500 shooting performances: 13 for 30 in the Game 4 loss to the
Sacramento Kings, 7 for 16 in the Game 5 victory over the Kings,
and 8 for 17 in the Game 1 victory over the Suns. Not disastrous
but not sharp.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 4, a drive and errant pass in the closing minutes had
sealed the Lakers defeat.
</P>
<P>
   But those mistakes are more easily shrugged off now, by coaches,
teammates and fans. The fact Bryant is allowed to keep misfiring,
to keep testing the defense, until he finds the range, is a
positive sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think guys on the team have more confidence in me than in
the past. They have more confidence I'll come through,'' Bryant had
said before the game. ``I think it just clicked all of a sudden.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it happened after that long East Coast trip.''
</P>
<P>
   That trip was in February. The Lakers went 6-0 and Bryant was
their leading scorer twice. He had a Lakers season-high five steals
one night in Chicago, and a 26-point, seven-rebound, six-assist
game at Charlotte the next night.
</P>
<P>
   It was around that time that Bryant's defense began to get
notice. His all-around excellence and more responsible handling of
the ball changed everything.
</P>
<P>
   If it wasn't a case of Bryant maturing, it was the Lakers taking
a more mature view of his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Now) I might turn the ball over or make a mistake, and he
(Jackson) might whistle to let me know,'' Bryant said, contrasting
that with the abrupt benchings of years past. ``I'll (look over
and) say, `Yeah, I know.'''
</P>
<P>
   The best part is, he does know.
</P>
<P>
   He spent the season's first 15 games on the injured list with a
broken right hand. The Lakers won 11 of them. That might have been
the best thing to happen to Bryant and the team.
</P>
<P>
   They learned they could win without Kobe. More important, he
learned they could win without Kobe. When he returned, early in a
stretch in which the Lakers went 23-1, he seemed intent on fitting
in with a winning program.
</P>
<P>
   Before Wednesday's game, Bryant seemed surprised to hear he'd
received a fourth-place vote for the NBA Most Valuable Player award
that went to Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' Bryant said. ``I didn't expect that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson spoke of the possibility Bryant will be the Lakers' -
and the league's - MVP some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Shaq matures and grows older, whatever his limitations will
bring to him, he may take the roll that Kareem (Abdul-Jabbar) took
in the later part of his career,'' the coach said. ``Play part of
the game, concentrate on one area, loaf down court like Kareem did
... and let Kobe take the prime (role). I don't see that happening
for a number of years, though.''
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't an MVP-type night for Bryant. His minutes limited
after he picked up his third foul midway through the second
quarter, he finished with 15 points, on 6-for-11 shooting, and six
assists. The scoring total was his lowest since March.
</P>
<P>
   But on the night O'Neal became the first Laker since Magic
Johnson in 1990 to receive the MVP trophy, Bryant showed again why
he'll be the next. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 0344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0053 </DOCNO>
