<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 03:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1788 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     05-11 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORDS FROM THE WISE FOR LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ We now know Shaquille O'Neal, er, (begin ital)Big
Aristotle(end ital), does not live by Nietzsche alone, that his
other book is ``Bartlett's Familiar Quotations.''
</P>
<P>
   So we're pretty sure he already knows what the world's deepest
thinkers would have said if conjured up for a few comments after
the Lakers' 97-96 victory Wednesday over Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   The great philosophers wouldn't have wasted much breath noting
how the Lakers didn't merely defeat the Suns in the first two games
of their best-of-seven Western Conference semifinal series, they
toyed with them.
</P>
<P>
   Phoenix has to be fit to be fried, losing Game 1 by 28 points
and coming within three seconds of taking Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   For the Lakers, now is no time to step back and admire the
carnage. As John Dryden said, ``Fortune befriends the bold.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' mandate this weekend is clear: Don't let the recent
past be a prologue.
</P>
<P>
   It's all very quaint that O'Neal celebrated his first MVP crown
by carving up his counterpart. That would be the commoner, Luc
Longley, whom O'Neal outscored 38-4.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal skewered the Suns for 37 points in Game 1, so it would
appear he is intent on practicing what Aristotle preached about
excellence not being a singluar act but a habit.
</P>
<P>
   As the Lakers head to Phoenix for Friday's Game 3, they should
remember what Henry Wadsworth Longfellow said: ``The greatest
firmness is the greatest mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   It won't look good if the Lakers let the Suns back into the
series as they did Sacramento in the first round. It is better for
all involved that the Lakers put Phoenix away posthaste.
</P>
<P>
   Suns guard Jason Kidd covered the Staples Center court better
than he did in Game 1, but it's obvious his gimpy left ankle is far
from completely healed. At this point, he doesn't need Kobe Bryant
harrassing him, he needs rest. The least the Lakers can do is lend
an assist to the Suns' assist man.
</P>
<P>
   In the name of being humane, the Lakers ought to put Longley out
of his agony. After trying unsuccessfully to slow O'Neal, Longley
likely has a few choice quotes for CNN broadcaster Fred Hickman,
the only voter not to see the 7-foot-1 as the clear MVP.
</P>
<P>
   Longley might start with Alexander Pope's observation that
``fools rush in where angels fear to tread.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of Longley's nine misses were short, a sure symptom
of chronic tightness of the muscles and an anemic morale. Rest
would be the best medicine. The Lakers ought to see that he gets it
pronto.
</P>
<P>
   Except for the flu-addled Derek Fisher, the Lakers are fairly
hale. If anything is beaten up, it's their collective aura. They
looked bulletproof in forging the league's best regular-season
record (67-15). Then they lost twice at Sacramento and chinks
appeared in their armor where there had been spikes.
</P>
<P>
   Portland will be watching closely to see if it should cower in
the Lakers' presence. O'Neal and Co. shouldn't give the Trail
Blazers or any other possible playoff opponent any reason to feel
optimistic. The Lakers would be prudent to remember the Chinese
proverb, ``The greatest conquerer is he who overcomes the enemy
without a blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant, who shut Kidd down and stepped up for 25 points in Game
1,took his licks Wednesday. Midway through the second quarter,
Bryant found himself with more fouls (three) than assists (two). He
had six points in 11 minutes in the first half and finished with
15.
</P>
<P>
   Three days after being hailed for playing with controlled
abandon, Bryant looked a little reckless. With the score tied at 94
with a little over a minute left, Bryant drove into traffic and
lost the ball. Penny Hardaway's putback at the other end put the
Suns, who never led in Game 1, ahead 96-94.
</P>
<P>
   Sent to the foul line with under a minute to play and a chance
to tie it, Bryant made his first attempt and missed his second.
However, with the game on the line Bryant clearly remembered the
words of Elbert Hubbard, who said, ``Don't make excuses, make
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant's last shot was his best: a fearless lean-away jumper
with 2.6 seconds to play that found nothing but net and sank the
Suns. It figures. As Edward Gibbon said, ``The wind and the wave
are always on the side of the ablest navigators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 0354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
