<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 09:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1874 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-ELIAN-CROWD-COX     05-11 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CROWD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fight over Elian arrives in Atlanta
 &HT;    EDS: PHOTOS FOR THIS STORY AVAILABLE BY 10:35 AM EDT
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The doors of the 11th Circuit Court of Appeals swung
open today to let in 100 people _ most of whom spent the night on
Forsyth Street _ eager to see lawyers argue the fate of 6-year-old
Elian Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think Elian should go back to a Communist country,''
said Hazel Nunn Gaines, 78, who had been waiting in her wheelchair
since 11 p.m. Virtually all of those in line to get into the
stately old one-time Post Office were fiercely opposed to the
government's effort to return the child to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Television remote trucks lined the east side of Forsyth Street
from Walton to Luckie. Atlanta police in black battle dress guarded
the other side, where those hoping to get into the courthouse lined
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing Fidel could do for his country is to drop
dead,'' said Gaines, who told reporters she spent the night
outdoors because she thinks it's important for Americans to express
their opinions on major issues.
</P>
<P>
   Grace Vazquez, 54, of Tampa came to the United States from Cuba
14 years ago and never went back. She's been going back and forth
to Miami to join the protests there, and came to Atlanta with her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian should stay. His dad could stay, too,'' she suggested.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about retaliation against the Cuban family of Elian's
father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, she said, ``Everybody on the island
is under repression because Fidel is a devil.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she and her husband, a trustee of the Cuban-American
National Foundation, spent the night on lawn chairs ``because I
don't really want to miss this show.''
</P>
<P>
   Griselle Alejandre flew in from Miami late Wednesday to assure
she would get a seat in the courthouse today. ``I came here to
support the Gonzalez family for justice and liberty for Elian,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only interest is that the child live in liberty, not
necessarily in Miami, but somewhere else in the United States ...''
</P>
<P>
   Alejandre spent the night in front of the courthouse equipped
with a Cuban flag and a blanket.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Calderon, 38, of Miami, who said he came to Atlanta two
days ago, carried a hand-written sign that said `` God sent him
here, let's not send him back to the devil.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of those in line were reporters, or stand-ins for reporters
who did not win one of the media seats in the small courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Two University of Georgia seniors were first in line. Michael
Phelan, an English major, said his father, who works at CNN, hired
him and a buddy to spend the night on a downtown Atlanta street
corner.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan said he passed the hours ``sitting around watching the
bums on the street.''
</P>
<P>
   Cox writers Jingle Davis, Lyda Longa, Rhonda Cook and Mark
Bixler contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
