<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 09:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1875 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV14-C     05-11 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: STAR WARS IN CYBERSPACE
 &HT;    Moving in (k) commentary and (f) financial categories for
release
 &HT;    Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ You don't have to be a Star Wars fan to sense how a
struggle between good and evil pervades the cosmos of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   A plethora of technologies enables open networks, like the
Internet, to supplant closed systems, like cable outlets and TV
shows. As these new links become ever faster and cheaper, today's
commercial gatekeepers and government regulators are at risk of
being pushed aside in a world in which virtual communities
distribute a wide range of useful content.
</P>
<P>
   But the unifying force of an open Internet that empowers
billions of people remains under continual threat from the powers
of the Dark Side. They were on display anew when the ``Love Bug''
e-mail virus went on a worldwide wrecking mission, only to morph
into an invidious ``Mother's Day'' message from a Darth Vader
clone.
</P>
<P>
   Today's carefree Internet users no longer need to fathom the
plumbing that runs underneath their mouse clicks, just as
movie-goers need not know that the final battle sequence in which
the Death Star is destroyed was based on a 10-minute montage of
films from the two World Wars.
</P>
<P>
   There's a price to be paid, however, for ignorance among
customers and arrogance among vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Love Bug'' was written in Microsoft's Virtual Basic, a
programming language that underpins the Windows operating system.
Its aim, at which it largely succeeds, is to enhance ease of use.
Hackers write Windows code for the same reason criminals rob banks:
that's where the money is.
</P>
<P>
   It's quite possible to defend yourself against cyber-attacks.
Just ask the folks at the National Security Agency, the computing
colossus that sits astride the global high-tech communications
frontier.
</P>
<P>
   The agency volunteers that were it to be viewed as an
enterprise, in terms of dollars spent, floor space used, and people
employed, it would rank in the top 10 percent of the Fortune 500
companies.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no public tours. There's no e-mail address book.
There are no classified computers hooked to the Internet. And so,
lo and behold, no viruses choke agency traffic or erase its
databases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because we work with highly sensitive information, we are
frequently the subject of speculation _ and highly imaginative and
creative fictitious pieces in the media,'' the super-secret agency
allows on its modest unlinked Web site.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not put off by such movie lore and still yearn to work
there, then don't try to apply online to one of the world's
foremost wireless-tapping ventures. In fact, you must send an
ordinary letter to a post office box.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, we could also achieve a full measure of protection
from the Dark Side by emulating the intelligence agency and cutting
our Internet cords. And, even if we decide to dabble a bit, we
could still refrain from becoming ``interactive'' and always back
up our fresh data before it turns sour.
</P>
<P>
   But such strategies also rob us of the true promise of the
digital future _ an open society where millions of content
providers toil in a peaceable kingdom. Maybe in his next Star Wars
adventure, George Lucas can figure out how to make it all work.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 0942EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
