<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1880 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN14-COX     05-11 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Pawns in Iran's game
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   By landslide margins in preliminary and now in runoff elections,
Iranians have voted themselves a moderate government, but it is
very much an open question whether powerful Islamic conservatives
still in control of key institutions will let them have it.
</P>
<P>
   The early signs are not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have shut down 16 reform newspapers in recent weeks.
Reform figures have been arrested on disloyalty charges. And now
the reactionary clerics are charging fraud at 10 percent or more of
Tehran's polling places, a potential precursor to annulling the
election.
</P>
<P>
   And, in one of the crueler barometers of Iran's political
atmosphere, the courts have tightened the screws on 13 Iranian Jews
charged with spying for Israel, displaying three who are said to
have confessed.
</P>
<P>
   To say the charges are implausible is to put the matter mildly.
Dozens of capitals have protested the arrests, many in strong terms
rare to diplomatic lingo. French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin
called the charges ``totally fabricated.''
</P>
<P>
   By any common understanding of the word ``justice,'' it is
impossible to take the Iranian claims of a spy ring seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The teachers, store clerks, students and merchants don't appear
to have been in espionage-worthy positions or locations. They have
been imprisoned for 15 months. They are being tried in secret in a
Revolutionary Court where the judge is also the prosecutor and sole
juror, the ultimate legal stacked deck.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, the 13 are hostages in Iran's political struggle,
tokens of the conservative ayatollahs' credentials as keepers of
the Islamic faith, and burdens _ as evidence they are supposedly
soft on Israel _ to reformers who disavow the trial.
</P>
<P>
   There is the potential for unconscionable tragedy here. One
hard-line Shiite cleric has said the 13 should be ``sentenced to
death _ not once but several times.''
</P>
<P>
   The source of such hysteria among the conservative clergy is not
the defendants but the Iranian people themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Reform candidates allied with President Mohammad Khatami swept
the preliminary elections and then, despite seeing 12 provincial
victories annulled by the Council of Guardians, went on to dominate
the recent runoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic Iran Participation Front won 79 percent of the vote,
52 of the contested 66 legislative seats.
</P>
<P>
   That is an overwhelming mandate in any republic, as Iran claims
to be despite its ``Islamic'' modifier. The legitimacy of that
claim hangs in the balance as the hard-line ayatollahs decide
whether they want to take the risks that would go with voiding a
hugely popular democratic outcome or cede some level of power
through a peaceful, electoral transition.
</P>
<P>
   The rattled clerics are deciding, too, whether they want to take
Iran out of the world community. Its place there already tenuous,
Iran would become even more widely anathematized and more deeply
isolated as a theocracy that suppresses manifest popular will and
toys with judicial murder.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He writes from
Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1019EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
