<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, May 12,
2000, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   PRACTICAL-MAN _ This week, the practical man has a promise to
keep. Be happy. It happened during a conversation with a reader.
This woman, peeved by his proclamation that males befriend only
attractive females, lingered at length over three pungent points:
The practical man is a) an insensitive idiot, b) an arrogant idiot
and c) merely an idiot. (Palm Beach Post). 40.
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS _ CLEVELAND _ Daily coverage, as merits, of United
Methodist General Conference in Cleveland. Issues coming up this
week are same-sex blessing, a new TV ad campaign to rival the
Mormons, legislation apologizing for the denomination's past racism
and trying to raise a huge amount of money for historically black
Methodist colleges that include Clark Atlanta U., some
denominational reorganization, and possible resolutions on Elian
and gun control, to name a few. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY _ LIVE OAK, Fla. _ It all started with bluegrass. Opened
in 1985, the Spirit of the Suwannee Music Park was founded by
lifelong bluegrass lovers Bill and Jean Cornett of Kentucky as a
place for Southern pickers and fiddlers to gather. Since then, it
has blossomed into a multi-use campground that hosts events of all
stripes, from traditional bluegrass festivals to hot-air balloon
races, gospel jubilees, auto shows and hippie-rock weekends.
Beginning with a huge Memorial Day blowout (coinciding with the
nearby Florida Folk Festival), this summer promises to be the
park's busiest yet. (Hamilton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35.
</P>
<P>
   GETAWAY-FESTIVALS _ Southern happenings. (Thrasher, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Travel page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET TRAVEL 0509 -- There is a lot more than horses, whiskey
and baseball bats to the venerable river town of Louisville, Ky.
Although those ageless items make for a pretty good visit right off
the, um, bat. But just when you think you have Louisville pegged as
an old-timey, tradition-bound burg, it throws you a curve.
(Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art includes a 4-column
color photo of tourists walking along the Ohio River and a 18-pica
color photo of a historic district.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: IF YOU GO BOX -- A list of places to see when visiting
Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: BOURBON DISTILLERY -- Jim Beam, the largest bourbon
distillery in the world, features a promotional film laced with
company propaganda and several good displays about the history and
process of the drink. More than anything you'll see there, it's
nice to smell the charred oak housed in huge warehouses. (Bierman,
Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 2-column color photo of tourists
visiting the distillery.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: TRAVEL BRIEFS -- Chicago is eagerly anticipating the
opening of a new dinosaur exhibit, others. (N.Y. Times News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   FASHION
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-FRANCE _ PARIS _ What Switzerland is to timekeeping and
Great Britain is to ceremony, France is to fashion. The French
didn't simply write the book on style, they built the Library de la
Mode. Hermes, Chanel and Dior donated their design services. The
French language contributed entire sections to the global fashion
dictionary (see chamois, chapeau, chenille, chic, chiffon, chignon
...). (Sturrock, Palm Beach Post). 60. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-ROWAN _ PARIS _ Lisa Rowan loves the convenience of Palm
Beach _ the always good-to-go weather, the discount retailers
stocked to the ceiling with everything a home needs, the beach just
down the street from her Chilian Avenue home. And she loves the
culture of Paris _ the art museums, the fragrant flower stalls, the
world-famous gardens and the flea markets practically at her back
door. So why choose between them? Rowan splits her time between the
two cities, jetting back and forth according to the school schedule
of her 6-year-old son, Krystofer Kimmel. Her career in the fashion
industry _ she calls herself a ``creative consultant'' _ has taken
Rowan around the globe. A Pennsylvania native, Rowan became
public-relations and advertising director for the late designer
Willi Smith shortly after college graduation. (Sturrock, Palm Beach
Post). 160. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH ROWAN-SIDE _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What does it take to score
the perfect headboard or a dinette to die for? ``There's something
that clicks, and it's just destiny,'' says fashion consultant Lisa
Rowan, who has decorated her Palm Beach and Paris homes with
purchases from flea markets and thrift stores both here and abroad.
``I don't find anything. It finds me.'' (Sturrock, Palm Beach
Post). 25. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   FASHION-GIRLZONE _ There aren't any perfume samples to spritz at
the cosmetics counter, greasy slices of pizza to munch in the food
court, or cute boys to scam on at Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch. (Sturrock,
Palm Beach Post). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SWIMSUITS-ONEPIECE _ Designers have poured as much imagination
and innovation into one-piece styles this year as they have devoted
to bikinis and tankini looks in the past. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, May, 14.
</P>
<P>
   BUCHMAN-QA _ Designer Dana Buchman can do without the runway
glitz and the glamour of celebrity clientelle; all she's focused on
is supplying ``the women who run the country'' with fine,
up-to-date classic clothing. Q&AMP;A. (Walton, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, May, 14.
</P>
<P>
   SWIM-TRUNKS _ A look at the three most popular styles of mens
swim trunks: board shorts, short shorts and competition style
Speedos. (McFarland, Atlanta Journal-Constiution). 6. WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, May, 14.
</P>
