<P>
   SUMMER MOVIES PAGE
</P>
<P>
   COXNET LIFESTYLES 0510 -- The summer box-office battle started a
little early this year with ``Gladiator'' arriving in theaters
weeks ahead of the Memorial Day holiday. It's survival of the
fittest, funniest or most exciting, with billions of dollars at
stake. Here's a look at this summer's wide-release films. (Larson,
Dayton Daily News) Art includes a 3-column color photo from
``Gladiator,'' a 1-column color photo from ``Battlefield Earth,'' a
1-column color photo from ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps,'' a
1-column color photo from ``Mission Impossible 2,'' a 2-column
color photo from ``Gone in 60 seconds,'' and a 2-column color photo
from ``The Perfect Storm.''
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   HAMILTON-JORDAN _ Twenty years ago, Hamilton Jordan was the
gatekeeper who controlled access to the most powerful man in the
country, a brash newcomer to Washington who moonlighted as
Georgetown's most notorious pubcrawler. Today, former President
Carter's chief-of-staff has no power than any other Little League
assistant coach. Between one life and another, he went through a
divorce, has survived cancer three times, run for the U.S. Senate
and lost, and gone from a thirtyish Beltway climber to a sedate
middle-aged father of three young children. In his book ``No Such
Thing As a Bad Day,'' Jordan reflects on the bumps in the road and
what he's learned in a life out of the public eye. We profile
Jordan at 55, a political has-been who believes he's never been
more alive. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (p) Politics and (l) Lifestyle cateories.
</P>
<P>
   HEMPHILL _ A visit with Paul Hemphill, who shares his thoughts
about his latest book, ``The Ballad of Little River.'' (O'Briant,
Atlanta journal-Constitution). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, May 14.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-SKUBE _ ``At the end, a nurse stripped the neck brace,
pressed her fingers against the carotid artery, and felt for the
faintest sign of a pulse. The Velcro made a sound like stitches
ripping.'' Rodger Kamenetz's remembrance of his mother in ``Terra
Infirma: A Memoir of My Mother's Life in Mine,'' originally
published by the University of Arkansas Press and reissued by
Shocken Books, is both tender and bittersweet, with none of the
false sentimentality of a Mother's Day card. In both its lyricism
and its emotional subtlety, it recalls Russell Baker's opening
sentence in ``Growing Up'': ``At the age of 80 my mother had her
last bad fall, and after that her mind wandered free through
time.'' Sons more often than daughters seem to hear a parent's
admonitory voice from beyond the grave, and seek redemption through
words that went unspoken when there was still time. But settling
accounts can be painful. Oscar Wilde's unsparing observation is
true in more instances than we like to acknowledge: ``Children
begin by loving their parents. After a time they judge them.
Rarely, if ever, do they forgive them.'' (Skube, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 23.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Embargoed until Sunday, May 14.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS PAGE
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is the CoxNet Books page for the current week.
</P>
<P>
   COXNET BOOKS 0509 -- Until the collapse of the Soviet Union,
foreigners could visit only five towns along the Trans-Siberian
Railway, and then only under supervision. ``Siberia itself,''
Author Colin Thubron says, ``receded into rumor.'' In the late
summer of 1997, Thubron strapped on a 20-pound rucksack and set out
to experience ``a place where white cranes dance on the permafrost,
where a great city floats lost among the ice floes, where mammoths
sleep under glaciers.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Siberia'' (HarperCollins, $26) completes a trilogy that
Thubron began in 1983. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) Art
includes a 3-column color photo of author Colin Thubron.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW EXPLORERS -- Author David Roberts rates Kit Carson
ahead of John C. Fremont as both pathfinder and human being. Anyone
caring about Carson and Fremont may seem to have too much time to
think these days, but in their day _ the 1840s and 1850s _ their
names were known to every American. (Blackburn, Palm Beach Post)
Art includes a 6-pica color photo of book jacket .
</P>
<P>
   WITH: PUBLISHING NOTES -- I had hoped that Arthur Lennig's
``Stroheim'' would serve as a worthy companion piece to last year's
restoration of ``Greed'' that was broadcast on Turner Classic
Movies. But this book may have been in the works too long. (Eyman,
Palm Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: SPRING PREVIEW -- Here are some nonfiction titles coming
to bookstores in coming weeks. (Weaver, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   WITH: REVIEW RAVELSTEIN -- It's a pleasure to report that Saul
Bellow's unmistakable Catskill rhythms are back in ``Ravelstein.''
(Eyman, Palm Beach Post) Art includes a 6-pica color photo of book
jacket.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: N.Y. TIMES BEST SELLERS LIST
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-KIDS _ Roundup of the latest children's books. (Bookman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Walter Sorrell's gender change (in name only) has
paid off. The Atlanta author, who had trouble selling his mysteries
as a male writer, has won the Edgar Award for Best Paperback
Original Mystery as Ruth Birmingham... Toni Morrison is a
three-time winner in the Oprah Sweepstakes. Winfrey has chosen
``The Bluest Eye'' for her next TV book club discussion . . .
Jeffrey Lent's ``In the Fall'' may be the next ``Cold Mountain.''
Also, the Independent Booksellers recommend four books for Mother's
Day. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 18.
</P>
