<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Thursday, May 11, 2000 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS:  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service will file these stories for Friday. If
you have questions, please call Eric Rosenberg at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (``HNS'' appears in all sluglines.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-PROBE (San Francisco) _ Charles B. Renfrew's resume is
heavy reading. It goes on for three pages, single-spaced, small
type, documenting a 50-year professional career with highlights
that include a federal judgeship, an appointment as the U.S. deputy
attorney general and an executive post at Chevron. In his newest
assignment in his hometown of San Francisco, the former Army
artilleryman will head an internal review of the editorial policies
of The Examiner. By PETER HARTLAUB.
</P>
<P>
   EXAMINER-SALE (San Francisco) _ Under withering cross
examination, the head of the company that publishes the San
Francisco Chronicle and the San Francisco Examiner admitted passing
inside information from a member of the Chronicle's board of
directors to a Hearst executive about the sale of the Chronicle. By
SETH ROSENFELD. (1STLD-WRITETHRU expected.)
</P>
<P>
   EBAY-SUSPENSION (San Francisco) _ A lawyer from Sacramento,
Calif., was suspended from trading on the auction house eBay after
allegedly using an online alias to drive up bids for a painting he
was selling _ a piece some believe could be a lost masterpiece by
late Bay Area artist Richard Diebenkorn. By ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-MEDICINE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Advocates for New York senior
citizens plan to begin running trips to Canada to help Medicare
patients buy cheaper medications. Two politically-tinged trips
bound for Montreal are planned for early June. The trips,
organizers say, are aimed at highlighting the high cost of
prescription drugs in the United States. Drugs sold in Canada can
be 40 to 50 percent cheaper than those sold in New York, said one
organizer. By JAMES M. ODATO.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-HMOS (Sacramento, Calif.) _ Democrats in the California
state Legislature have rejected an attempt by Gov. Gray Davis to
water down a cornerstone of the landmark HMO reforms he signed into
law last year: the right for patients to sue their HMOs to recover
medical costs. By ROBERT SALLADAY.
</P>
<P>
   SAFEWAY-GENETICS (San Francisco) _ The fight over genetically
engineered foods spread to Safeway as shareholders defeated a
resolution that would have removed the products from the chain's
stores nationwide. With most of the votes counted, the stockholders
were heeding the corporation's arguments: Barring modified foods
was ``impracticable . . . and could put Safeway at a competitive
disadvantage.'' By JANE KAY.
</P>
<P>
   LOVE-BUG (Undated) _ By Friday afternoon, the so-called ``Love
Bug'' computer virus had been largely tamed _ downgraded from a
hurricane to a tropical depression, as it were _ but it left plenty
of fear and loathing in its destructive wake. And there remained
plenty of other storms on the virtual horizon. The havoc that
VBS.LoveLetter.A wreaked also created a strong reminder of how
widespread and virulent the shadowy world of computer viruses
remains. BY PAUL GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CAREER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Think about your career in terms
of baseball for a minute. You're on second base, and a teammate
singles to center field. As you run toward third, you look at the
coach for a sign: Should you stop at third or head for home? But
all he does is stare blankly at you. What should you do? By DAVE
MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   CISCO (San Francisco) _ The current Barron's cover story on
Cisco Systems rocked the markets Monday _ especially mighty Cisco.
At the same time, students of Cisco will want to be aware of an
equally important Cisco piece, the diametrically opposed cover
story in Fortune magazine featuring a very tight close-up on the
face of Cisco CEO John Chambers. By ADAM LASHINSKY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ADVENTURE-TOURS (San Francisco) _ I've always maintained that
commercial adventure-travel trips are an oxymoron: you pay the
outfitters a lot of money to make sure you don't have an adventure.
You spend the cash to guarantee, as much as possible, that you
don't wander down the wrong trail, that you sit down to a hearty
(and hygienic) hot-cooked supper each evening. By JOHN FLINN.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   RITALIN (Berne, N.Y.) _ Like thousands of children, 7-year-old
Kyle Carroll takes Ritalin for a diagnosis of attention
deficit/hyperactivity disorder, or ADHD. And like thousands of
parents, Michael and Jill Carroll worry about the drug's side
effects, including sleeplessness and loss of appetite. But they
keep their child on the medication, in part because they fear child
welfare workers will take him away if they don't. By RICK KARLIN.
</P>
<P>
   FITNESS-BALLS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Adult fitness centers are looking
a little like a children's gymboree, with knee-high white, red and
blue balls rolling around the room. Although you may be tempted to
toss a ball, or even bounce on it since it resembles the popular
pogo ball, they're meant to be used to improve fitness. By KRISTI
L. GUSTAFSON.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NINERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ In the spring of their
rebuilding, the San Francisco 49ers are a team badly in need of
resolution, but wherever they look all they see is an image just
out of focus. By JOHN CRUMPACKER
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PANCAKES (Undated) _ For a dish that has been around almost as
long as fire, pancakes can be mucked up pretty easily. They can
come out soggy in the middle or too brown on top. They can be too
thick or too thin. In fact, it seems that pancakes seldom turn out
just right. Goldilocks had better luck with porridge. By RUTH
FANTASIA.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 11:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1897 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-IRA-DISARM-2ND &LR;  &UR; TAKE-     05-11 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRA-DISARM-2ND </SLUG>
   TAKE-BOS  
 BELFAST, Northern Ireland: ... ``Costa Del Provo.''  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   But while some like Hughes say republicans have forgotten their
roots, Shane O'Doherty, who joined the IRA at 15 and served 15
years in prison for sending mail bombs that maimed people, thinks
it is time for the IRA to ``grow up'' and put behind them the
history that inspired them.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not just a problem for the IRA. A lot of armies have
had the same problem. Once at war, to reason is treason,'' said
O'Doherty, who renounced violence, got a degree from Trinity
College in Dublin, married an American, and is now a computer
consultant based in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   ``But times have changed. The IRA has to change with them,''
said O'Doherty. ``This talk of being mass-attacked and burned out
by loyalists is bull. The real issue is that a very small bunch of
totally unrepresentative people won't decommission their own sense
of self-importance. While people are whining about IRA pride and
IRA surrender and unionist stalling, real people somewhat removed
from the argument have died at the end of the bombs and guns.''
</P>
<P>
   The republicans have made a seismic shift in tactics. By
accepting the Good Friday Agreement of 1998, the movement, in the
name of Sinn Fein, has accepted the principle of consent, that
Northern Ireland will remain part of Britain until a majority
living here decide otherwise. They have, as IRA leader Michael
Collins did in 1922, accepted partition as a political reality that
they will have to reverse by the force of argument, not the
argument of force.
</P>
<P>
   Some say that Gerry Adams, the Sinn Fein leader, or Martin
McGuinness, the former IRA chief of staff who was the minister for
education in the short-lived power-sharing government, could become
the next Michael Collins, the last IRA leader to compromise with
the British. Collins was shot by IRA dissidents in 1922. There has
been graffitti in Belfast warning Adams to ``Remember Michael
Collins.''
</P>
<P>
   Over dinner at one of the posh restaurants that have sprung up
in Belfast since the 1994 cease-fire, a senior official of the
Royal Ulster Constabulary, admitted that, from a security
standpoint, the IRA's turning in some weapons, or sealing its
hidden arms dumps, is meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't get the IRA to decommission their engineering
capabilities,'' said the officer, speaking on the condition of
anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   That officer and others say that besides being able to rearm as
quickly as it disarms, even if the IRA turned in its Semtex
explosives, it could still make bombs out of fertilizer, which it
has used to devastating effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't decommission all the cow shite in Ireland,'' said
one senior officer of the Garda Siochana.
</P>
<P>
   But those who say that disarming means little for security also
acknowledge it is essential as a confidence building measure in a
political culture that remains a study in mistrust.
</P>
<P>
   While Sinn Fein can influence the IRA, it cannot get the IRA to
do anything it does not want to, said O'Doherty and other former
and current IRA members.
</P>
<P>
   Most seasoned observers here believe that, despite their public
protestations to the contrary, if it was within their power to make
a token gesture of turning in some guns, Adams and McGuinness would
do it, not because they have gone soft, but because they have
already compromised on much more fundamental republican principles:
recognizing the legitimacy of Northern Ireland by entering the
assembly and, after the Omagh bombing, condemning the use of
violence by republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans who say politics will produce a united Ireland
sooner than armed struggle have always been marginalized, derided
as sellouts who have gone soft. But the proponents of physical
force are undeniably in decline, and those who agree with Adams and
McGuinness are in the ascendancy.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of this is about human nature and insecurity, O'Doherty
says. The IRA is effectively being asked to put itself out of
business. Few organizations do that willingly. O'Doherty says
people who are willing to kill, die and go to prison for their
beliefs tend to be even less rational and pragmatic when asked to
compromise, let alone dissolve their organization.
</P>
<P>
   When Joe Doc, IRA legend, first broached the subject of a
cease-fire to let politics take precedence, the other IRA men on
his cellblock at Long Kesh prison hooted. Gradually, he and other
IRA leaders like Danny Morrison won them over. Now he, Morrison,
and others who believe the days of armed insurrection are
counterproductive are trying to hold the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear the (dissident) argument, but I say what is your
alternative? I don't like the process either,'' O'Doherty said. ``I
say we'll go back to war if you could tell me we'll move forward.
But I don't believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, in Ireland there is always someone who does.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
