<HEADLINE>
IRA FIGHTS INTERNAL RIFTS OVER WEAPONS 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Dermot Finucane is an unlikely peacekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, the IRA man was a prison escapee, one of the most
wanted men in Ireland. After a Dublin court refused to extradite
him to Northern Ireland, he allegedly became chief of the Irish
Republican Army's ``southern command'' in the Irish Republic, where
most of the organization's weapons are stashed.
</P>
<P>
   These days, police on both sides of the border say, Finucane is
traveling regularly to southwest Ireland, where much of the IRA's
estimated arsenal of 50 machine guns, 600 assault rifles, 500
handguns, and nearly three tons of Semtex explosives is hidden in
underground caches that meld seamlessly into the lush countryside.
Police grudgingly give Finucane credit for keeping the IRA's arms
out of the hands of dissident hotheads.
</P>
<P>
   Since the IRA offered on Saturday to allow international
inspectors to check its arms dumps, part of a process it said was
aimed at putting the weapons ``beyond use,'' most attention in
London, Dublin, Washington, and other capitals has focused on
whether unionists will accept the IRA proposal. But a more
important long-term question is whether the IRA can sell the idea
to a large enough segment of its own members to avoid a split that
could wreck the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with IRA members, supporters, and security officials
on both sides of the Irish border suggest that the IRA offer, which
falls short of Protestant unionist demands for a handover of
weapons, was carefully calibrated to prevent a major split while
nudging the peace process forward.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Finucane's vigilance against potential
dissidents is necessary. ``We don't know whether he threatened
them, cajoled them or both, but whatever he's done has worked,''
said a detective with the antiterrorist branch of the Garda
Siochana, Ireland's national police force.
</P>
<P>
   According to British and Irish security sources, at least two of
the seven-member ruling IRA Army Council are so opposed to turning
in weapons that they have warned a bloody split would follow any
attempt to meet Protestant demands of guns up front before they
will rejoin a government with Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute over weapons has led not only to the suspension of
the local power-sharing government that was supposed to steer
Northern Ireland into a new, peaceful era. It has also bitterly
divided the IRA and raised the specter of mass defections to the
burgeoning splinter groups that have set off several explosions
recently. One of those groups planted the bomb that killed 29
people in Omagh in 1998, the biggest loss of life in Ireland's 30
years of Troubles.
</P>
<P>
   Interviews with a dozen current and former members of the IRA
suggest that behind the preoccupation with weapons is a fundamental
power struggle between the IRA, traditionally the dominant force in
the republican movement that seeks to wrest Northern Ireland away
from Britain, and Sinn Fein, which has traditionally been
subservient to the IRA.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-four years after the Easter Rising that they claim as
their mandate, and six years after they said they were prepared to
let their political representatives in Sinn Fein seek a united
Ireland through democratic politics, the IRA is at a crossroads. As
democracy begins to take root in Northern Ireland, Sinn Fein is on
the cusp of replacing the IRA as leaders of the republican
movement. That transfer in the balance of power, however, is not
proving to be a smooth one, and it has been made that much harder
because of the IRA's refusal to disarm and the unionist insistence
that it happen.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the IRA believe the effort to disarm them is really an
attempt to humiliate them and prove that they were terrorists all
along, not the freedom fighters they consider themselves to be.
While most in the IRA are sticking to their cease-fire, reluctantly
accepting the leadership's pleas to be patient, a growing number of
IRA volunteers are sliding over to the dissidents who argue that
the peace process is a trap that will leave Northern Ireland firmly
and permanently entrenched as part of the United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   Many are frustrated by what they consider the slow pace of
change in reforming the Royal Ulster Constabulary, Northern
Ireland's mostly Protestant police force, and in withdrawing the
14,000 British troops remaining in Northern Ireland. Several IRA
operatives claimed the growing international chorus demanding that
they at least say their war is over, if not actually turn in
weapons, makes that prospect less, not more, likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you push the IRA, the IRA pushes back ten times harder,''
said one IRA volunteer from South Armagh, the area controlled by
former IRA chief of staff Tom ``Slab'' Murphy, who security sources
and even some republican sources say is the leading skeptic on the
IRA's Army Council.
</P>
<P>
   But Murphy's skepticism, sources say, has been offset by Brian
Keenan, the IRA's Belfast commander who is widely regarded as the
most influential member of the Army Council. Keenan remains a firm
backer of Sinn Fein's strategy, according to security and
republican sources. It is Keenan, they say, who has pushed hardest
for keeping the IRA's weapons locked up and under international
scrutiny rather than turning them in or destroying them, which most
IRA members would view as an act of surrender.
</P>
<P>
   Some IRA men cannot fathom life without the IRA. And if they
give up their guns, then there is no IRA. Some of them have accused
others of ``going soft,'' a volatile charge in a movement where
macho defiance is admired and the disloyal are beaten or summarily
executed.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Doherty is one who has felt the sting of that charge.
</P>
<P>
   If there were an IRA hall of fame, Joe Doherty would be in it.
Thirty years ago, after watching the overwhelmingly Protestant
local police stand by while his Catholic New Lodge neighborhood was
overrun and torched by pro-British loyalists, he joined the IRA at
the age of 15.
</P>
<P>
   He fired the shot that killed the most senior member of the
British Army's elite SAS commando unit to die in Northern Ireland,
and made a daring escape from custody the day before he was
sentenced to life for it. He was eventually arrested in New York,
where he was posing as a bartender, and his 9-year fight against
extradition made him a cause celebre. When he was finally
extradited in 1992, Doherty arrived home to a hero's welcome and a
prison cell. There are few IRA living legends bigger than Joe Doc,
as he is known in the republican enclaves of his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   But one of his childhood friends stopped him on the street the
other day and called him a traitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhh,'' Doherty said, wincing and sighing heavily in the
office where he and other ex-prisoners are training to become youth
workers. As one of the leading proponents of ending the ``armed
struggle'' to allow politics to take precedence, Doherty finds it
hard when some old comrades accuse him of selling out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard times. People are upset, scared, angry, turning on
each other. No one knows where this thing is going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing'' is the peace process, which has delivered a
remarkable degree of normalcy to Northern Ireland after 30 years of
virtual civil war.
</P>
<P>
   On the gritty streets that Joe Doc returned to upon his release
from prison 18 months ago, few say the IRA should go back to war,
but even fewer think they should give up their guns. Ordinary
people fear attacks like the ones of 1969 that inspired Doherty to
join the IRA in the first place, and remain unconvinced that the
police force that stood by 30 years ago and remains 90 percent
Protestant has fundamentally changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm constantly stopped on the street by older people who say
don't give up the guns. It's not about going back to war. It's
about protection,'' said Doherty.
</P>
<P>
   Some IRA fighters, called Provos because they belong to the
Provisional IRA, have become cynical. Brendan ``Darkie'' Hughes is,
like Doherty, an IRA legend, having shot, bombed, and escaped his
way into republican folklore. But unlike Doherty, he does not
support the peace process. He thinks some republicans have sold out
for the trappings of success, like new cars and vacation homes in
Donegal, where they can spend weekends pretending to live in a free
country. Cynics call Donegal ``Costa Del Provo.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
