<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1899 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-11 1659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOTHER'S DAY AND THE OTHER MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For many stepmothers, Mother's Day is something to dread, a day
full of disappointment and hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Niah Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   For most mothers whose children also have a stepmother, Mother's
Day is a time to forget about the other woman in your children's
lives and revel in their exclusive attention.
</P>
<P>
   Not for Vivian Smith-Benton.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia and Smith-Benton have two things in common: Jaheem
Smith-Garcia, who is 9, and Nyiema Smith-Garcia, 13. Smith-Benton
is their mother. Garcia became their stepmother three years ago
when she married their dad, Naheem Allah-Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   On Mother's Day, Jaheem and Nyiema will have a card and gift for
their mother that their stepmother helped them buy, and a card and
gift for their stepmother that their mother helped them buy.
</P>
<P>
   This generosity of spirit is not something the two women have
ever talked about; it's evolved because both were able to see past
their own needs and make the children their priority.
</P>
<P>
   There's no better time to do it than on Mother's Day. While this
may be a day intended to honor mothers, in families reconfigured
through divorce and remarriage children can get caught in
destructive fallout.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Child's perspective
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From a child's perspective, there's no reason to honor a
stepmother on Sunday. ``This is Mother's Day, not Stepmother's
Day,'' says Perdita Kirkness Norwood, a stepmother advocate and
author of ``The Enlightened Stepmother'' (Avon, 1999). ``You may be
a mother to them but you are not the mother. It's foolish to expect
to be remembered,'' she tells stepmothers.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a typical stepmother anticipates something. ``She
spends the day hoping for a card, waiting for a phone call, or
crying alone,'' says Norwood.
</P>
<P>
   When a stepmother isn't remembered, she tends to harbor a hurt
that indirectly affects her household. Perhaps she puts unusual
distance between herself and the kids the next time she sees them,
or she's short with them or critical. They have no idea why this is
happening and react negatively in return. Suddenly, relationships
that may have been tenuous at best are out of control.
</P>
<P>
   It's also neither uncommon nor unhealthy for a stepmother to
take her hurt to her husband, says psychologist and researcher
Patricia Papernow. Unfortunately, ``When we're unhappy, we tend not
to be very gracious,'' she says. ``Instead of, `I've been sad ever
since Mother's Day,' we say, `Your kids didn't remember me! How
could you let that happen to me?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The trouble is, ``no parent can hear that without getting
defensive,'' she says. Instead of a response that makes a
stepmother feel better _ ``I appreciate everything you do for my
kids'' _ she gets one that makes her feel more isolated: `They're
just kids; you're the grown-up. It's your problem, not theirs.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, a father and children whose stepmother criticized
them last year for ignoring her won't necessarily have learned the
lesson she expects, says Norwood. ``Instead of doing something for
her, they'll just think that whatever they plan for Mom needs to be
done furtively,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that stepchildren are cruel. ``They're in a loyalty
bind,'' says Papernow, who specializes in remarried families.
</P>
<P>
   She says children of all ages, especially at the beginning of a
father's remarriage but even years afterward, feel protective of
the relationship with their biological mother. ``They think, `If I
move toward my stepmother, I have betrayed my mother,' '' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they have a close and loving relationship with a
stepmother; even if they live primarily with their stepmother and
father; even if their biological mother is abusive, Mother's Day is
a huge symbolic line that's difficult to cross.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why Norwood urges stepmothers not to take it personally
if you're not remembered. ``This is not about you,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doing whatever helps
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps surprising, what helps stepmothers most is helping the
children. And what children need most is permission to deal with
the reality of their lives, says Margorie Engel, president of the
Stepfamily Association of America. In other words, she says, ``make
it easy for the kids.'' For instance:
</P>
<P>
   --Model for them. Talk about what you're doing for your mother
and ask what they have in mind for theirs.
</P>
<P>
   --Offer to be helpful: ``Do you need a ride to get a card?''
``Do you like to make gifts? I once made a great jewelry box for my
mother out of a cigar box. I could show you how.''
</P>
<P>
   --Offer to rearrange schedules. ``You're supposed to be at our
house that weekend, but I bet it'd be fun for your mom if you woke
up at her house Mother's Day morning . . .''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only does this help kids with their reality _ `I do need
something for Mom' _ but it eliminates conflict for them and gives
them permission to like you as a person. In addition, it helps you
feel less like a victim, '' says Engel. If you don't see immediate
benefits from doing this, you will in years to come. ``They will be
grateful you gave them space to love you both rather than try to
pretend about or deny their mother's role,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Children who need the most help on Mother's Day are those whose
mother has died. ``You know kids are thinking about their mom on
this day. Get it out in the open,'' says Engel.
</P>
<P>
   If it's the first year the stepfamily is together, she
recommends saying, ``I bet Mother's Day is tough for you. Is there
something you would like to do to remember your mom?'' Some
possibilities: visiting the grave, drawing pictures, telling
stories of Mother's Days when their mom was alive.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be hurt if they want to do something with their dad,
without you, says Norwood, who wishes she had had advice like this
when she first became a stepmother to three teenage girls and one
boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pretended Mother's Day wasn't happening. We ignored it,''
she says. ``That was a mistake. I wish we had talked about their
mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, helping children deal with their reality means mom
gives them permission to thank their stepmother, says Papernow. For
instance: ``You know, Stephanie does so many nice things for you
all year long. Mother's Day might be a nice time to let her know
you appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What dads can do
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fathers can do that too, but it's trickier. ``If you push too
hard, it can feel (like you are encouraging them to be) disloyal,''
says Papernow. Recommend a thank-you note, not a Mother's Day card,
suggest but don't insist. On the other hand, Papernow does urge
fathers to express their own gratitude on Mother's Day: ``I know
how much you do for my kids. Thank you.'' Papernow is the author of
``Becoming a Stepfamily'' (Analytic Press).
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Smith-Benton has managed not to be jealous of or angry
about the relationship her children have with their stepmother
partly because of her work as visitation project coordinator for
the Massachusetts Probate and Family Court. ``I've seen the damage
when parents aren't cooperative. That's not what I want for my
kids,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Does she ever feel things have gone too far, for instance when
Garcia makes it a threesome at parent-teacher conferences, or when
Jaheem calls Garcia ``Mami'' (Spanish for mommy)?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' she says, adding, ``I hope I'm as good a
stepmother to Tyrell,'' her husband's 13-year-old son from a
previous marriage.
</P>
<P>
   For Garcia, stepparenting comes almost naturally. ``I had two
brothers from my father's first marriage,'' she says. ``The word
`step' was never used. They were just my brothers.' '' She began
her relationship with Jaheem and Nyiema with the most positive
attitude possible: ``To me, they were the children in my life,
never a task to deal with. I'm blessed to have them.''
</P>
<P>
   She's also blessed now with a baby, 11-month-old Alenah. ``Just
before the baby was born, Jaheem asked if I would love her more
than him,'' she remembers. ``I told him, `Everyone you love, you
love in a little bit different way. You don't love your mommy the
same as you love me, do you? But you still love me, right? I'll
love her and I'm still going to love you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand why he voluntarily makes her a homemade
Mother's Day card every year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
SUGGESTIONS FOR STEPMOTHERS &QC; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Asking your stepchildren ``Did your mom have a nice Mother's
Day?'' helps them bring their two worlds together.
</P>
<P>
   --It's not unusual for one stepchild to remember you and another
not to. Don't make a big deal out of it.
</P>
<P>
   --Some children may resent it if you encourage remembering their
dead mother on Mother's Day. Say you are doing it for yourself:
``I'm going to light this candle on Mother's Day for your mother. I
want to remember her because she birthed you.''
</P>
<P>
   --If you've experienced sadness on previous Mother's Days, make
a plan for yourself or tell your husband, ``Mother's Day makes me
feel sad and lonely. Can we plan something?''
</P>
<P>
   --It's not appropriate to tell your stepchildren you were sad on
Mother's Day because they didn't remember you.
</P>
<P>
   --Even if you have been remembered by your stepchildren in the
past, don't assume it will automatically happen again. Children do
not feel the same sense of obligation to a stepmother, plus their
feelings toward you are more likely to be capricious and depend on
your last interaction.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AFTERTHOUGHT _ Three leading pediatrian/researchers will be
available to answer questions about children's brain development on
an Internet chat (www.JJPI.com) Monday from 9 a.m. to 10 p.m. The
Pediatric Town Forum is cosponsored by the American Academy of
Pediatrics and the Johnson &AMP; Johnson Pediatric Institute.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Barbara F. Meltz welcomes letters and comments and can be reached
via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
