<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 11:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1900 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-11 0612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING MOM? DON'T KID YOURSELF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``How To Manage Your Mother''?
</P>
<P>
   I gave up trying to manage my mother years ago when it finally
dawned on me that it's folly to think you can manage anyone else,
maybe especially your mother.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the title of this book was irresistible. Would it
reveal some arcane secret of mother management hitherto unknown to
the general public? It didn't, of course, but it's an intelligent,
accessible book about, as the subtitle states, ``Understanding the
Most Difficult, Complicated, and Fascinating Relationship in Your
Life.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as a dustjacket blurb from writer/actor Stephen Fry puts it,
``Does for mothers what Dian Fossey did for gorillas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The title is ironic,'' said the book's co-author, Alyce Faye
Cleese, from New York, where she was promoting the book.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret of managing your mother is learning to manage
yourself in your relationship with your mother.''
</P>
<P>
   To that end, it's crucial to reexamine the fundamental ways in
which you think about your mother. One example: try to think about
her as another adult, with a past that didn't always involve you,
instead of ``my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleese, a psychotherapist who is married to actor John Cleese,
interviewed celebrities and civilians about their relationships
with their mothers. She and co-author Brian Bates wove the stories
into the book's self-help format. Readers with demanding mothers
may take comfort in learning that Colin Powell had to make
Brigadier General before his mother would give him credit for
achieving anything. Those with ``martyr'' mothers might be
interested to know that Mike Nichols' famous funny line, ``Hello,
Michael. This is your mother. Remember me?'' was taken straight
from his not-so-funny relationship with his mother. Keeping a sense
of humor about your mother, or trying to, is one of the keys to
mother management, says Cleese. But you probably know that.
</P>
<P>
   She recommends talking with your mother about your shared past.
``Memory can be very tricky,'' she said. ``We lock in memories over
a lifetime and they shape our attitudes toward our mothers. But
memories are malleable. And when we reexamine them, deconstruct
them, talk about them, our feelings about our mothers may change.
And that can make an enormous difference in how we get along with
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Adult children need to remember that their mothers will not be
around forever. It's important to make the most of your time
together, Cleese said, by enjoying a good relationship with her or
trying to improve a bad one. ``Remember your mother's age,'' she
writes, ``Say the things you want to say while you have the
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   And if those things you want to say aren't positive? Cleese said
it's important to confront your mother about conflicts and try to
resolve them before she dies.
</P>
<P>
   Even after she's gone, it's possible to deepen your
understanding of your mother and improve the relationship, Cleese
said. ``In a sense, our mother never leaves us,'' she said. ``Our
mothers stay with us emotionally for the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleese was 16 when her mother died. She remembers her as a
loving woman, a memory that has made her feel secure. ``She was
lots of fun, she left me with such gifts,'' she said. Not long ago,
a friend of her mother's, a woman in her 90s, sent Cleese a long
letter about her mother. ``She wrote, `I want you to know that your
mother was really as wonderful as you remember her,'' Cleese said.
``It meant the world to me.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
