<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-WEB-MOVIE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S `QUANTUM PROJECT' HEADS FOR THE INTERNET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  By DAVID BLOOM  
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's being billed as the first-ever feature film
created specifically for the Internet, and it's debuting Thursday
night, worldwide, from Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Whether some obscure film-school project beat ``The Quantum
Project'' to the Net, it's safe to say this is the first feature
ever created specifically for the Net that can boast a blue-ribbon
cast and crew.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Dorff stars as a physicist preoccupied by his studies of
the quantum universe of subatomic particles. By a series of
coincidences, he reunites with his former girlfriend, played by Fay
Masterson, then reconnects with his father, played by John Cleese.
</P>
<P>
   The $3 million project is the first of a planned four
``chapters'' of Net-only stories based around ``The Quantum
Project,'' according to Barnet Bain and Stephen Simon, the film's
producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most interesting part was designing the film for the
emotional and visual language of the Internet,'' said Simon.
</P>
<P>
   The two are best known for producing ``What Dreams May Come,''
on which ``The Quantum Project's'' director, Eugenio Zanetti, also
worked.
</P>
<P>
   Zanetti, who won an Oscar for production design on
``Restoration,'' said because the film was created for computers,
he could play with such formerly untouchable limitations as the
picture's aspect ratio, jumping it ``from IMAX to Cinemascope in a
single shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Given Zanetti's artistic chops, the film looks fabulous, and
though compressed, the story is engaging and cryptic enough to bear
repeated viewing.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it'll pack them in at the PC is another question.
</P>
<P>
   But pioneering Web site SightSound.com, which helped finance the
film and has exclusive rights to it for the next year, doesn't have
to have a big first weekend for the film to make economic sense on
the Web, officials said. Because the Net has effectively endless
shelf space, the film can continue to be available, and repeatedly
sold, for as long as the company wants.
</P>
<P>
   But for right now, only PC owners with recent versions of the
Windows Media Player will be able to play the movie (Mac users must
wait for Microsoft to update their version of the player). It'll
cost you $3.95 to buy the 37-minute movie, but once you download it
(beginning at 9:01 p.m. PST), you can watch it as often as you
want.
</P>
<P>
   Be warned, though: at nearly 90 megabytes, the download will
take four hours on a 56K modem. Cable modem or DSL connections will
take only about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Bain said they are experimenting with the business
model behind the film, including offering alternative versions
later this summer. Perhaps sometime in the future, they will even
let fans put together their own version of the movie, using an
array of scenes and soundtrack material, much as some underground
dance music enthusiasts routinely issue remixed tracks of other
artists' work.
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Bain, whose TV movie about Linda McCartney will debut
in three weeks, said they will create another four-part drama and
two comedies in coming years for the Net as they continue to
experiment with its possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``This must be as near as I can imagine to the heyday of
Hollywood, where there was a process of discovery every moment of
the way,'' said Simon.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-04-00 0115EDT &QL;
</P>
