<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT MESS RUNS DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's vacation gave me leisure to contemplate the US
Justice Department's latest adventures in bloody-minded
belligerence _ the ``rescue'' of Elian Gonzales and the proposed
assassination of Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference? The doorkickers at Bill Gates's mansion
definitely have their fingers on the triggers.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some of my readers at MIT can explain to me how I'll be
better off with two Microsoft monopolies instead of one. That's the
plan cobbled together by the US Justice Department and the
attorneys general of 19 states. Well, 17, anyway. The attorney
general of my native state of Illinois, along with his counterpart
in Ohio, refused to go along with a breakup. But Midwestern common
sense didn't stand a chance. Indeed, common sense has taken a
beating throughout this sorry affair.
</P>
<P>
   There's the astonishing refusal of Microsoft to settle this case
a couple of years ago, when it could have done so at virtually no
cost. And there's the remorseless arrogance with which the firm has
conducted itself throughout.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, there's the government's determination to
attack a prominent billionaire at the behest of some slightly less
prominent billionaires.
</P>
<P>
   Even the government's own star economic witness in the case
admitted he saw no sign that Microsoft's business practices were
hurting the public. But they sure bedeviled a lot of lesser
software moguls. It's their rage and envy that's driving this case
_ that and a tendency to full-auto ferocity that's become a
trademark of the Clinton Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   No question the Branch Davidians in Texas were lawbreakers
deserving of arrest. No question Elian belongs with his father. And
no question that Microsoft has crossed the line into monopoly abuse
from time to time. But in Waco, Miami, and now in Washington,
Attorney General Janet Reno has rejected moderate solutions and
sent in the SWAT team.
</P>
<P>
   So we're to have two Microsofts rather than one. There'll be a
Windows operating system company and another company that might be
called Everything Else Inc. Notice this remedy has little to do
with the alleged outrage that spawned the original case:
Microsoft's decision to include an Internet browser as part of
Windows. The government attorneys seem hardly interested in
righting that mythical wrong. Instead, they want to hobble
Microsoft, thereby ensuring that it sins no more.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the great divorce say it'll spawn an explosion of
software creativity. Hordes of new products will flood the market,
unhindered by the wrath of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Really? There already are plenty of Windows-alternative
operating systems. Like Macintosh, Linux, Unix, OS/2 and Be. There
are alternative office suites _ Lotus SmartSuite, Corel
WordPerfect, Sun StarOffice. But consumers overwhelmingly prefer
Windows and Microsoft Office, and will go on preferring them even
after a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Another theory behind the breakup is that Microsoft will no
longer be able to use its hold over Windows to pressure customers
to buy other Microsoft products. But Everything Else Inc. would
still have an office suite software monopoly. Microsoft Office has
about 85 percent of the market. So the CEO of Everything Else Inc.
could offer discounts to Office users that buy other Microsoft
software, the sort of thing that got Microsoft in trouble in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   To prevent this would require limitations on the conduct of
Everything Else Inc., the very sort of remedy the government says
it wants to avoid. And yet, the government breakup proposal
includes a litany of such limitations to last until the company is
dismantled. If these restrictions can be made to work during the
years of courtroom appeals this case may spawn, why not longer? A
10-year requirement that Microsoft charge the same price to all its
customers and publish the secret codes that make Windows work ought
to level the playing field. Throw in a hefty fine to punish
Microsoft's hubris, and that's that.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not enough for the Justice Department. It would
rather spend tens of millions of taxpayer dollars on the
anti-Microsoft crusade, thereby slashing the company's stock value
and the personal wealth of millions of investors by tens of
billions of dollars. And for the grand finale, it wants to
eviscerate the company that probably did more than any other to put
personal computers in over half of all American homes.
</P>
<P>
   All for our own good, of course. Janet Reno has said so. She's
wrong, but as Lazaro Gonzales and Bill Gates have discovered, that
hardly matters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached at
bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-04-00 1723EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
