A1912 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a BC-REBEL-FLAG-COX     05-11 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REBEL-FLAG-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rebel flag fight moving to Georgia after S.C. vote
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The Confederate battle flag is on its way down
in South Carolina. That means a full-fledged fight in Georgia is
not far behind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's coming to Georgia sooner than later,'' said Republican
pollster Whit Ayres of Roswell, Ga..
</P>
<P>
   So far, Georgia Gov. Roy Barnes has played a passive role in the
brewing debate over the state flag, which incorporates the battle
emblem that's flown over the South Carolina Capitol dome since
1962.
</P>
<P>
   Barnes has encouraged dialogue but insists it's strictly a
matter for the Legislature _ the same stance South Carolina Gov.
Jim Hodges took until a tourism boycott by the NAACP triggered
persistent negative publicity.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday night, on the state's Confederate Memorial Day,
the South Carolina House voted to remove the controversial banner
from its copper-clad Capitol dome. Derided by late-night comics,
South Carolina is the only state that flies the Rebel flag on top
of its Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The vote by the South Carolina House will only heat up debate in
Georgia, where Democrats _ especially Barnes _ are trying to keep a
lid on the issue through the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how he can avoid it,'' Ayres said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Georgia's black legislative caucus _ including Rep.
Tyrone Brooks (D-Atlanta) and Donzella James (D-College Park) _
have stayed in touch with their counterparts in South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   For one, they've talked to South Carolina House Minority Leader
Gilda Cobb-Hunter (D-Orangeburg). She predicted South Carolina's
action is ``going to force action in those Southern states where
the Confederate flag is part of the official banner.''
</P>
<P>
   Cobb-Hunter said James visited South Carolina last week, ``and
we talked about this whole issue. She was sharing with me how
things are starting to percolate there in Georgia.''
</P>
<P>
   The South Carolina Senate still must sign off on the House plan.
House leaders said they were optimistic the Senate would give the
bill routine concurrence.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker David Wilkins (R-Greenville) took the well to
personally to encourage support for a compromise the Senate passed
last month. The House slightly modified the bill during two full
days of debate. The bill passed 63-56.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a defining moment for our state,'' Wilkins said. ``I
think it's a giant step forward. This is a very decisive and
dignified action on the part of the South Carolina House. There
will be those that criticize this action, this compromise, some
that say we went too far, some saying we didn't go far enough. The
bottom line is we got the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   The bill would remove the battle flag from the Capitol dome and
move it to a prominent soldiers' memorial on the grounds on July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Only three of 26 black House members voted for the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The plan's great failing, many black legislators said, is that
the battle flag would move to an even more prominent place on the
Capitol grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That, at best, sends a mixed message and, I think, even a bad
message,'' said House Speaker Pro Tem Terry Haskins (R-Greenville).
``If the black members didn't vote for a plan that takes the flag
off the dome, that's hard to explain.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a final vote, typically a formality, remains in the House
for passage.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which originated in the Senate, goes back there for
inspection. The plan includes flying a square battle flag at the
38-foot granite Confederate Soldiers Monument. The memorial sits on
the north mall of the Capitol, a highly visible intersection of
Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not heal. This does not come close to healing. It
only further divides,'' said Cobb-Hunter, who voted against the
bill.
</P>
<P>
   The House version would fly the battle flag on a higher flag
pole and provide illumination at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of sacrificing and giving all the time,'' Rep. Leon
Howard, a black Democrat from Columbia, said during a party caucus
meeting before the formal House debate. ``I'm not willing to
sacrifice anymore. We need to stop sacrificing principles.'' ``All
I can say is that not much there excites us,'' Dwight James, South
Carolina NAACP executive director, said outside the House chamber.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
