<HEADLINE>
FORMER CAMBRIDGE TECHNOLOGY CEO COUNTERSUES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The former chief executive of Cambridge Technology
Partners countersued the large consulting firm Thursday, escalating
a fight over his launch of a rival start-up.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Cambridge Technology sued founder and former chief,
James K. Sims, claiming that he actively recruited its employees
for his new firm, in violation of an nonsolicitation agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The suit also named Gen3 Partners Inc., Sims's Boston technology
consulting firm, and Arthur M. Toscanini, a former Cambridge
Technology chief financial officer who now works for Sims.
</P>
<P>
   In papers filed Thursday in Middlesex Superior Court, Gen3
Partners and the two executives said Cambridge Technology is
seeking a ``scapegoat'' for its ``own business shortcomings.''
</P>
<P>
   The suit provides a closer look at a once-powerful consulting
company that has begun to grapple with losses and a restless staff.
But the dispute also reflects the damage that start-ups in the
Boston area are beginning to inflict on older technology firms,
industry observers say.
</P>
<P>
   Similar battles have raged in Silicon Valley, where Oracle Corp.
and SAP have had little success in keeping workers from migrating
to younger Siebel Systems Inc., said Rob DeSisto, an analyst with
Gartner Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people want to leave and they're entrepreneurial, they're
going to take the risk and chance it,'' DeSisto said. ``I don't
think lawsuits would in any way scale back activity that would
happen anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   The exodus from Cambridge Technology has been particularly swift
and painful. A Lehman Brothers analyst recently estimated a 48
percent turnover rate _ the highest in the information technology
services sector.
</P>
<P>
   In their countersuit, Sims and Toscanini seek an unspecified
amount of money for losses they allegedly incurred due to Cambridge
Technology's actions.
</P>
<P>
   Toscanini claims the firm refused to pay his 1999 bonus and
misreported his wages to tax authorities. Sims alleges two
directors made promises they did not keep to try to prevent him
from immediately selling his 2.5 million shares.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a fairly simple dispute,'' said Tim Mead, a Cambridge
Technology senior vice president. ``At the end of the day, we're
just alleging there has been a broken promise to Cambridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Cambridge Technology also sued Semtor Inc., a Fort
Lauderdale technology company founded by Harold Gubnitsky, a former
Cambridge Technology vice president.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Thursday, Gubnitsky said he has worked hard to
build a corporate culture that would lure talented employees,
which, it so happens, include a few from Cambridge Technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is people go to the best places to work,'' he
said. ``In this economy, that's what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
