<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTER-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE INNOVATOR'S DILEMMA, AND MICROSOFT'S  
 AN E-HOLSTER TO CARRY GADGETS  
 MODEM INVENTOR WILL HEAD NEW E-BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bill Gates complains that everyone at Microsoft pitching a new
project seems to invoke the notion of the innovator's dilemma. The
term, Gates told Forbes magazine last year, is ``a required slide
in every funding presentation.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gates might do well to pay attention, says Clayton M.
Christensen, the Harvard Business School professor who coined the
phrase. His book, ``The Innovator's Dilemma: When New Technologies
Cause Great Firms to Fail,'' has been causing a stir at technology
companies since it was published in 1997. It describes how leading
companies are ambushed by new products.
</P>
<P>
   Technology industries, he says, go through life cycles. A large,
integrated company makes sense, in his view, when a technology is
young and it is a formidable task simply to make a product or
service that works. In the days when the national telephone network
was being built, Christensen said, ``a single company would have
dominated, even if AT&AMP;T were not created.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet as a technology matures, he noted, ``it causes the industry
to disintegrate.'' Then, speed of marketing and ease of
customization tend to matter more. That is when a technology leader
is most susceptible to a disruptive technology coming up from the
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Today's market for personal-computer software, Christensen
insists, has the characteristics of maturity. ``For Microsoft, the
mainstream product lines _ the Windows operating system and Office
suite _ are just huge software programs,'' he said. ``Most users
don't use more than 10 percent of their features.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Java,'' Christensen said, referring to the Sun
Microsystems language for Internet programming, ``is coming up.''
Like many insurgent technologies, he noted, Java was first
developed for another market _ consumer electronics _ but it found
its early use on the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   His prognosis for Microsoft? ``No matter what happens in the
antitrust case, Microsoft will go where IBM went in mainframes,''
said Christensen, whose book is being published in paperback by
HarperBusiness. ``Microsoft will still be dominant in PC operating
systems but, like mainframes, that will not be the mainstream of
computing anymore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft,'' he added, ``will still be around, but it will not
be the all-powerful entity it once was. This is the mechanism by
which markets destroy monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVE LOHR
</P>
<P>
   An E-Holster to Carry Gadgets
</P>
<P>
   As Tom Traeger's collection of portable electronic devices grew,
he saw the day approaching when he would own more gadgets than he
could comfortably carry. He imagined something that would let him
wear his cell phone, his organizer and even his pager at the same
time and give him easy, quick access to any of them. He imagined,
in fact, something like a shoulder holster.
</P>
<P>
   The result was the e-Holster, an accessory that closely
resembles a gun holster and can be worn completely concealed under
a jacket or sweater. The e-Holster was designed by Jerry Ahern of
Commerce, Ga., a firearms-concealment expert whom Traeger expected
to bring an intuitive feel to the problem. Designers of gun
holsters, he reasoned, know the ergonomics of easy access.
</P>
<P>
   Traeger's company, Personal Electronics Concealment of St.
Augustine, Fla., sells the e-Holster, along with his newest
product, the e-BeltPouch, from its Internet site
(www.eholster.com). The e-BeltPouch attaches to an ordinary belt
and holds a cell phone or an organizer in a sideways position,
permitting the wearer to sit down without fear of losing the
device.
</P>
<P>
   The basic e-Holster, in nylon, costs $99.95; a leather version
is $119.95. The e-BeltPouches range in price from $47.95 to $84.95.
</P>
<P>
   With a hand-held organizer on one side, a cell phone on the
other and a pager clipped to the harness, the e-Holster wearer can
look like a road warrior. ``There is a little macho thing to it,''
Traeger said.
</P>
<P>
   But that little macho thing might be a problem. ``I don't think
it's a very good idea,'' a San Francisco Police Department official
at the department's shooting range said. An officer frisking
someone, for instance, could think they're carrying a weapon. ``It
would certainly be a concern for any officer. They'd have to be on
the alert.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Modem Inventor Will Head New E-Business
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Hayes knows how to make money _ and how to lose it as
well.
</P>
<P>
   Credited with inventing the computer modem in 1978 as a
29-year-old engineer working out of his kitchen, Hayes built the
company that he had started to manufacture the devices, Hayes
Microcomputer Products, into an industry powerhouse in the 1980s.
But the company failed to adapt as lower-cost competitors eroded
its market share, and after years of struggle, it finally shut its
doors last year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after quietly serving as a consultant for Internet
companies and heading an Internet industry association, Hayes
recently re-emerged, this time as chief executive of a new
e-commerce unit of the online retailing company International
Brands.
</P>
<P>
   The company, called World Best Buy, has a Web site selling
discounted merchandise like clothing and electronics as well as
used items through an electronic garage-sale format that matches
buyers with sellers. It recently added an auction service and plans
additional services soon, though Hayes would not go into details.
</P>
<P>
   The site has $40 million in prepaid ads, Hayes said, and
interest among other advertisers, particularly in the automotive
business, is high. The site has a section dedicated to cars and car
parts.
</P>
<P>
   The story of Hayes Microcomputer, which introduced the
Hayes-compatible PC modem in 1981, remains a cautionary tale of the
computer industry. The company reached a peak of $250 million in
annual sales before seeking bankruptcy protection for the first
time in 1994, after failing to react quickly enough to competition
for its principal product and the rise of powerful new competitors
like 3Com and U.S. Robotics.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes successfully resisted takeover bids for several years, but
finally merged with Access Beyond in 1997, and ceded control.
</P>
<P>
   In the first half of 1998, the company lost $17.6 million and
filed for bankruptcy again in October. In January 1999, Hayes
Corp., as it was then known, shut down for good, ending a chapter
in PC history.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a disappointment,'' Hayes said, adding that he lost
$150 million in the bankruptcy. ``So I started doing what I know
best,'' he said, ``helping companies grow fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides consulting, Hayes has spent the last few years as
chairman of the U.S. Internet Industry Association, a trade group
that has focused, among other things, on promoting the Internet as
a tax-free zone.
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-07-00 2204EDT &QL;
</P>
