<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 11:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1921 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN     05-11 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-E-COMMERCE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE RETAILERS SET THEIR SIGHTS ON PRIVATE-LABEL MERCHANDISE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT1 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BOB TEDESCHI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Internet retailers spent the latter half of the 1990s trumpeting
the differences between their business models and those of
traditional retailers. Now that Wall Street is holding the
e-tailers accountable and demanding signs of future profitability,
Web merchants have shown a new respect for their bricks-and-mortar
brethren.
</P>
<P>
   A case in point: E-commerce companies have turned to an old
retailing standby, private-label manufacturing, to give them higher
profit margins and better control of inventory. Items like dog
food, cosmetics, diamonds, toys and golf clubs, to name a few, now
wear dot-com labels, and more are joining every week.
</P>
<P>
   Online retail executives say that by manufacturing their own
goods and selling them alongside well-known brands, they can hasten
the slow march toward profits.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts generally agree, but caution that several obstacles
could slow or even stall the private-label effort online. And in an
environment in which Web merchants have decreasing room for error,
they are moving as gingerly as they can _ while maintaining
Internet speed _ into this corner of the retailing realm.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latest companies to announce a private-label effort is
Ashford.com, an online seller of jewelry, apparel and other goods.
Late last month, the company rolled out the Ashford Collection, an
assortment of jewelry manufactured exclusively for Ashford, and it
will add similar lines of pens, scarves and leather goods in the
coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth E. Kurtzman, the company's chief executive, said several
factors were behind the move, but none more important than profit
margin.
</P>
<P>
   ``By purchasing directly from manufacturers, we can price 40 to
50 percent cheaper and still make 50 to 70 percent margins,'' he
said. ``If we can generate 20 percent of our sales from private
label, and have a 60 percent margin, while the other 80 percent of
sales generates a 35 percent margin, that's a definite contributor
to cash.''
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit of private-label manufacturing, Kurtzman said,
is that his company ``can react to customer trends more quickly
because the turnaround time is much shorter.'' For instance, he
said, if a certain type of earring generates buzz among consumers,
the company could have that earring in stock within six weeks,
``whereas with some of the brands, it'd take a year or more to see
changes in the product lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Such goods are also less likely to collect dust in the
warehouse, Kurtzman said. ``And with faster inventory turns, you
have less cash tied up in your inventory,'' he added. ``Again, that
helps you reach profitability more quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Van Kleeck, vice president of the National Retail
Federation, a trade group, said selling by private label ``has been
a very serious growth vehicle for many traditional
bricks-and-mortar retailers in the past seven or eight years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives retailers greater control of sales and marketing,''
he said, because brand manufacturers often dictate the terms of
pricing and advertising. ``And obviously, it's significantly more
profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   But Van Kleeck said dot-com companies faced a greater challenge
in introducing private labels because online shoppers generally
have a brand name in mind before they visit a specific Web site.
Consumers may be more wary of unbranded goods like private label
clothing that they have never seen, felt or tried on. ``The
consumers who've bought into e-commerce have done so because they
know the merchant or the product,'' Van Kleeck said.
</P>
<P>
   Getting consumers to try the product of a newly created company,
he said, could require considerably more marketing. ``But getting
people to turn away from traditional brands also takes time,'' Van
Kleeck said. ``And in Internet time, who knows what that means.''
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Chipshot.com, one of the earliest proponents of
online private-label retailing, the answer is two years. The
company, which sells golfing merchandise, began manufacturing irons
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The company's chief executive, Brian Sroub, said Chipshot
generated a substantial portion of its revenues by selling its own
brand. ``It's been the basis of our business,'' Sroub said. He
added that the private-label approach ``allows us to offer superior
quality at a lower price, and retain higher margins for
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, with Chipshot irons, Sroub said, the company buys
the grips, shafts and club heads from the same manufacturers that
supply the traditional brands, so the quality is the same. But
because Chipshot assembles the clubs when the orders are taken, it
can customize the clubs to the customer's specifications and
deliver them within a week _ a service that can take several weeks
at offline retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers of private-label merchandise must balance such
benefits against potentially sizable pitfalls. Among them is the
possibility that well-known manufacturers will refuse to sell them
their goods if they sense that the retailer is competing too
fiercely against them. Such so-called channel conflict can doom
e-tailers that use the big brands to draw customers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not all retail categories are so dependent on brands, and
those that are not have generated some of the more aggressive
private-label efforts on the Web.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly all of the sales of Furniture.com, for instance, are
attributable to private-label brands. Andrew Brooks, the company's
chief executive, said the site began carrying private-label goods
in its early days partly because the brand-name manufacturers did
not want to alienate their traditional retailer partners by selling
through a Web merchant.
</P>
<P>
   But the company quickly learned that ``furniture buyers don't
shop for brand,'' but for style, Brooks said. As a result, the Web
site groups furniture into collections of similar styles, he said,
an approach that yielded $20 million in sales during the last
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The paucity of well-known furniture brands is perhaps one reason
another high-profile e-tailer, eToys, is rolling out its
private-label effort with a collection of children's furnishings.
Jane Saltzman, vice president for merchandising at eToys, said the
company would begin selling 500 different products with the eToys
brand this fall, and branch out to other categories besides
furniture. ``We'll grow beyond that 500, but not to tens of
thousands,'' she said. ``I see this as a complement to our
assortment.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Kurtzman, of Ashford.com, said: ``It's important to
understand that this is about optimizing the balance between
branded and private-label goods. It's not a panacea for an Internet
retailer. It won't completely change the business model. But it's
certainly something we all need to do to generate cash and achieve
profitability more quickly. And the companies that don't do it will
have a harder time getting to where they need to be.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-07-00 1815EDT &QL;
</P>
