 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    PRESIDENTIAL POLITICS NOW FILTERED THROUGH INTERNET SCREEN
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The rise of the Internet and nonstop news cycles
has repaved the road to the White House, press secretaries for the
defunct presidential campaigns of Bill Bradley and Sen. John McCain
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the big changes brought on by online access to
campaigns, television still remains the best way to connect with
the voters, the bipartisan post-mortem by the two primary
contenders concluded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can talk all you want about the new media,'' said Eric
Hauser, former press secretary for Bradley's Democratic campaign.
``But the Internet is critically important because it is a way to
raise money. And you use that money to purchase television time.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Opinsky, press secretary for McCain's Republican
campaign, which the Arizona senator effectively ended in late
February, noted that ``because you can see everything on line, that
speeds up the whole pace of the echo chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result,'' Opinsky said, ``I can see now what's in the
Dayton Daily News at six o'clock in the morning. And that ensures
that practically every newspaper in America to some extent has as
much reach as the traditional national news outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   The workshop itself was an Internet event, available via a live
interactive video stream on CNN's allpolitics.com Web site. It was
sponsored by the Joan Shorenstein Center on the Press, Politics and
Public Policy of Harvard University's John F. Kennedy School of
Government, in collaboration with CNN.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, both staffers said, the two insurgent campaigns
differed in the way their candidates interacted with the press.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, Opinsky recalled, had spent many years building friendly
relations with Washington reporters _ an unusual tactic in the
post-Reagan era of presidential campaigns, where campaign
appearances and candidate accessibility is usually carefully
scripted and tightly controlled.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main job on the Straight Talk Express'' campaign bus, he
said, ``was to stay out of the way. ... It often proved hard to
talk to the senator about strategy because reporters were always
there.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's surprisingly good primary showing in New Hampshire on
Feb. 1 brought in $15 million on line in the next few days, ``which
was immediately put to good use buying more TV time,'' Opinsky
said. ``Before the Internet came of age, we could never have done
that,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Hauser's challenge was to overcome Bradley's image as an aloof
figure.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as both the former New Jersey senator and his top
press aide see it, candidates shouldn't have friendly relationships
with reporters, but rather maintain a certain professional
distance.
</P>
<P>
   Another panelist, Jake Tapper of Salon.com, one of a new breed
of online political journalists, said that because of the immediacy
of the Internet, Bradley's stiff attitude came across to potential
voters more quickly that it might have in previous years.
</P>
<P>
   Both campaign officials voiced concern over how far the four
major TV networks had scaled back their coverage of presidential
campaigns and the coming political conventions, often relegating
their coverage to their Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, they said, the current spate of cable-driven political
coverage appeals largely to ``junkies'' or political insiders
rather than educating the public about vital issues.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.allpolitics.com
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
