 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    A new place to park Pikachu
 &HT;    By Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   You've heard it said of Pokemon that fans ``gotta catch 'em
all.'' Moving with their runaway hit _ which is also the only thing
keeping Nintendo's sales numbers high and mighty above third-rate
game developer status _ the Pokemon craze culminates with Pokemon
Stadium ($60; www. nintendo.com; for the Nintendo 64) by offering a
new way to corral the hard-earned, dutifully nurtured bubble-gum
characters. Essentially useless without the GameBoy Color companion
piece, Stadium comes bundled with a ``Transfer Pak'' and allows for
traded and trained GBC Red, Blue and/or Yellow Poke-characters to
migrate and play together in multiplayer arena games and trading
modes. But without a GBC from which to migrate, Stadium is a
lightweight romp without reward and not conducive to the ``catch,
train and trade 'em all'' phenomenon _ while Nintendo takes your
money in a whole new way. Fans rejoice while everyone else rolls
their eyes and wonders when the craze will end _ or, better said,
if the craze will end: Pokemon Stadium has already sold well over a
million copies.
</P>
<P>
   A MOUSE-HAVE FOR KIDDOS
</P>
<P>
   Kutoka's Mia: The Search for Grandma's Remedy ($40;
www.kutoka.com; for PC and Mac with QuickTime) displays
conscientiousness toward childhood education while still retaining
playfulness. Designed for kids ages 5 and up, players guide a cute
little mouse named Mia through a resplendent 3-D cartoon
environment via simple mouse/cursor control. Mia's simple quest to
fetch a few ingredients is complicated by various puzzles and
simple games encountered along the way. It is always pleasant,
slow-paced and easy to understand. Mia side-scrolls through most of
the adventure, though she also has some freedom of movement through
the foreground and background as she chases the cursor wherever it
may be and interacts with other characters or objects as they are
clicked while talking to and encouraging the game player. The one
flaw might be the lack of distinction between scenery and
interactive icons on the screen, but it's a tiny issue. Yet another
wee scholarly endeavor that makes learning fun.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-05-08-00 1041EDT &QL;
</P>
