<SLUG> BC-CPT-GAMER0509-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    NHL Rock the Rink is action packedBy Staff Reports
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE CONSOLE
</P>
<P>
   Put a bunch of beer-league WWF drop-outs from the Marty McSorley
School of Hockey up against downsized NHL teams of goons and
power-players and you've got NHL Rock the Rink ($40; www.ea.com;
for the Sony PlayStation), a gloriously over-the-top,
three-on-three version of the coolest game on Earth, where there's
as much action after the whistle as there is during play. Monster
hits and checks, stick swinging and body slams punctuate impossible
play and super moves. Graphics are notably chunky and blotchy, as
we've come to expect on the outmoded Sony console, but the
intensity of gameplay more than makes up for the base presentation.
Riddled with overly enthusiastic color-commentary, Vancouver's
local sports personality, Don Taylor (along with a Don Cherry
sound-alike) keeps the laughs coming with improbable remarks such
as ``ludicrous save!'' or, after a particularly nasty hit, ``Oh!
The athletic protector comes through when it counts!'' Lots of
long-term aggression-letting and a definite ``party game'' for two
players at a time.
</P>
<P>
   In its last incarnation, ``Nemesis'' for the Sony Playstation,
the Resident Evil videogame series was starting to look like it was
on its last, decomposing zombie legs. Leave it to the Sega
Dreamcast and Capcom to pump some new blood into the series with
Resident Evil: Code Veronica ($50, www.capcom.com), a breathtaking
survival horror game that takes the best elements of the series and
adds the horsepower of the Dreamcast. Following heroine Claire
Redfield, you explore dynamically lit environments, gunning through
zombies, rabid dogs and exquisite cinematic scenes. Other
enhancements include the ability to carry more than one weapon for
that John Woo effect, an enhanced map system and, of course, much
better graphics. The best of the Resident Evil games, Code Veronica
has been keeping us up late, itching for more.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE DESKTOP
</P>
<P>
   Coming in at roughly $1.26 per game, Hasbro Interactive's Atari
Arcade Hits ($20; www.hasbrointeractive. com) offers retro gaming
at its finest. Twelve arcade ``classics'' (some bona fide
masterpieces, some instantly forgettable) in a desktop arcade are
included _ a quick trip down memory lane when games were
simplistic, pure and downright addictive. Blockbuster games like
Asteroids and the superior sequel, Asteroids Deluxe, are emulated
faithfully _ save for the fact that a keyboard cannot, by nature,
offer the same rapid fire of the original hair-trigger buttons.
Likewise, Centipede and its follow-up, Millipede, or the stalwart
Missile Command, were originally designed for a track-ball
interface, though a frightfully fast mouse such as the Razer
Boomslang 2000 does afford speed twitch effect otherwise
unrealized. Other ``hits'' such as the original, vector-beam
Battlezone and Gravitar not only stand the test of time but also
offset the otherwise dreary drudgery of Crystal Castles, Warlords
and the woefully plain Pong.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
