<SLUG> BC-CPT-CYBERSCENE0509-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    Numerous sites offering legal help
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You needn't have a ski mask and a sawed-off shotgun to
come into contact with the legal system.
</P>
<P>
   Most Americans have an occasional brush with the law _ whether
it comes from buying a new home, getting a divorce, settling a
small-claims court issue, making a will, incorporating a small
business or forming a business partnership.
</P>
<P>
   Most lawyers would _ understandably and logically enough _
recommend that each of these issues be handled by a legal
professional. But even if you plan to consult a lawyer, it's smart
to educate yourself beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   That's where the World Wide Web can offer an astonishing amount
of legal help.
</P>
<P>
   By far one of the best and most comphrehensive legal sites is
called Nolo.com (www.nolo.com).
</P>
<P>
   Especially worthwhile is a section called the Legal Encyclopedia
at www.nolo.com/encyclopedia/index.html. The name is a bit
misleading since, instead of essays and definitions, you'll find
well-reasoned self-help tips divided by categories, such as child
custody, purchasing a car, traffic court, small-claims court, debt
collections and bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the sort of advice you can expect, in this case about
deciding whether to file a lawsuit: ``You need to answer three
fundamental _ and fairly obvious _ questions as part of deciding
whether it's worthwhile to bring a lawsuit: 1. Do I have a good
case? 2. Can I achieve my goal in some other way _ for example, by
proposing a compromise settlement or mediation? 3. Assuming a
lawsuit is my best or only option, can I collect when I win?''
</P>
<P>
   This site takes good advantage of the interactivity possible on
the Web. For instance, if you decide to follow the compromise or
mediation route, you'll be able to read detailed information on
those options.
</P>
<P>
   Mediation is increasingly important these days as a way to
settle a legal issue outside the court system but with the aid of
impartial professionals. There is great information on that topic
at a site called Mediation Issues at adrr.com/adr1/. Among many
other topics on this page, you'll find links that will help you
learn about the ethics of mediation, its pitfalls, the sort of
credentials a mediator needs and mediation's place in family law.
</P>
<P>
   FindLaw.com at www.findlaw.com/ is an especially practical site.
There are links from there to sections that will help you find a
lawyer with the skills needed for your case, as well as sections on
constitutional, intellectual property and labor law. Lawyers can
use the site to learn more about professional development courses
and seminars and to take advantage of the case law and expert
witness sections.
</P>
<P>
   Another rich trove of legal information can be found at a site
called the 'Lectric Law Library Laypeople's Legal Lounge at
www.lectlaw.com/lay.html. While the name may be a little unwieldy,
the information is not.
</P>
<P>
   You'll find more links to topics than can be listed here, but
among them are areas on Civil Procedure Outline, Handling Your Own
Injury Claim, How to Fight Your Traffic Ticket, Lawyers' Billing
Abuses, Keeping Legal Fees Down During a Divorce and Finding a Free
or Reduced-Cost Lawyer. Finally, if you have more than a passing
interest in the law, you'll want to check out the site called
Current Events _ Law at law.about.com/newsissues/law/. You'll be
able to read news stories that examine the legal issues in the
news. For instance, last week there were stories about possibly
normalizing relations with Cuba and the legal issues surrounding
assisted suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
