<HEADLINE>
$ADV14 
 TONY BLAIR'S MODERNIZING WAYS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, May 14, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. A full-length version of
this article is available on request. 
 By WARREN HOGE 
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    It was just an ordinary day in the life of Britain's most
prominent working couple when Cherie Blair dropped in unannounced
on her husband, Tony, the British prime minister, as he went about
the nation's business in his Downing Street office. Nothing
surprising about that.
 &HT;    The official residence sports a laid-back appearance these days,
with aides in shirt sleeves and loosened ties keeping up a lively
banter in the corridors of British power and the wife of the prime
minister frequently breezing past the busts of William Pitt and
Benjamin Disraeli on her way down from the family quarters
upstairs, out the famous black front door with the white numeral 10
and off to her job as one of London's top downtown lawyers.
 &HT;    But where Blair's opponents had been trying with scant success
for three years to catch the sure-footed British leader off
balance, it took his wife that September day only a few minutes.
``I was here at the desk writing my party conference speech,''
Blair recalls as a spring rain rattles against the windows. He
looks over at the simple leather-top table in his den-size space,
which is entirely free of flags and portraits or any other signs
that a world leader occupies it. ``And she came to me and said,
'I've got some news for you, and it's going to be rather shocking
about the family.' Well, I immediately thought there was something
wrong, that there was something wrong with our kids. She said there
was nothing wrong with the kids that we had.''
 &HT;    He lays emphasis on the last word with a roll of his eyes.
 &HT;    ``'But Tony, I think we're going to have another.' It was not a
moment to forget, but I do a little because I was so shocked.
Delighted, of course, but really shocked. I think I said, 'You're
joking,' and she said, 'No, I'm not.' I asked, you know, all the
usual questions. And I think I did get around to saying, 'That's
wonderful, darling.' But that was after a few minutes.''
 &HT;    This month Blair, 47, and Cherie, 45, are expecting their fourth
child and their first in 12 years, and the newcomer is presenting
Blair with a test right in his own home of his frequently voiced
notions of a new, improved, up-to-date, socially advanced, even
cool Britain. He is faced with widespread public anticipation that
he will take some of the paternity leave that his reform-minded
government has just made part of British law, and his modern-man
reputation is on the line.
 &HT;    It was his wife, who specializes in employment law, who first
raised the issue, calling the attention of a London legal forum to
the decision by Finland's prime minister, Paavo Lipponen, 59, to
spend a week at home in March with his newborn daughter. ``I, for
one, am promoting the widespread adoption of his fine example,''
she said.
 &HT;    All eyes turned to Blair, who has made family stability a
centerpiece of his mission to shed his country of its trappings of
tradition and turn it into a more contemporary society. In a
typical challenge, the National Childbirth Trust said, ``What Tony
Blair does when his baby is born will be a very powerful signal to
other men about what real men do.''
 &HT;    Real men. When I bring up the phrase Blair winces and shifts in
his chair. ``I know what people want me to say, but the truth is,
if I went away and stopped taking any calls or having any
conversations, it just wouldn't be real,'' he says. ``I'll take
more time off. I'll try to cut down on official things. You've got
to have some common sense about it. I mean, you want to spend more
time with your baby, but you don't give up the job. If people want
their politicians to be honest, they have to know I cannot stop
being prime minister. And it's usually my job to take care of
things at night anyway. Cherie has many excellent qualities, but
once she goes to sleep, it takes a minor nuclear explosion to wake
her up.''
 &HT;    The announcement itself in November was a bomb, instantly
propelling Blair free of a series of parliamentary squabbles,
cabinet disputes and gathering complaints about breakdowns in
public services that had prompted his Conservative rivals to
predict that at last his extended political honeymoon was coming to
an end. The arrival of the first baby to be born to a sitting prime
minister in 150 years is likely to give Blair's political fortunes
a fresh bounce despite some disappointing results in local
elections this month, affording him another of the repeated escapes
from real damage that have prompted the right-wing Daily Telegraph
to call him Teflon Tony.
 &HT;    Exercising his power in a personal manner more akin to an
American president than a British prime minister, Blair has become
the most closely observed and _ despite some vocal irritation these
days at his unchallenged dominance of British public life _ the
most popular prime minister in history. He is lionized by the
foreign politicians who pass through Whitehall and held up as a
model by most of continental Europe's leaders, who have
traditionally gazed across the channel with little interest in
adopting the quaint customs of the people who live there. He has
become a player on the world stage in what is very likely the first
act of a long run.
 &HT;    Opinion polls continue to show the Labor Party 20 points ahead
of the Conservatives, and the only question about the outcome of
the next election, expected a year from now, is how much Blair can
preserve of the 179-seat majority in Parliament he arrived with in
1997. He has attracted international attention as a reliable go-to
guy with some unflinching acts at moments marked by hesitation in
other Western capitals.
 &HT;    He was the first allied leader to pledge solidarity with
President Clinton after the Monica Lewinsky scandal broke, he was
the most outspoken advocate of NATO's bombing in Kosovo and he has
become the allies' point man with the new Russian president,
Vladimir Putin. When Putin looked for an introduction to the West
this spring, he rang up London. The two men exchanged summit visits
in St. Petersburg in March and in London in April, and the British
leader bestowed upon the Russian what amounts to a Blairite
benediction, the title he reserves for himself and his true
believers: ``modernizer.''
 &HT;    The transaction validated Blair's wish that modern Britain be
thought of as the pivotal nation bridging Europe, a continent he
says he wants to help lead, with the United States, a country he
says he doesn't mind following.
 &HT;    ``This is our great strength,'' he says. ``There's no doubt in
my mind that Britain has an important role with Europe and a strong
relationship with the United States, and the two complement each
other. I will wage perpetual war against the view that Britain
should choose America rather than Europe or Europe rather than
America. It is completely and utterly counterproductive for this
country.''
 &HT;    Blair freely admits taking a lot of leads from President
Clinton's politics, but he has led a distinctly different personal
life. There seem to be no embarrassments lurking in Blair's past or
imminent eruptions of shoddy conduct in his present. For people who
liked Clinton's promise but felt betrayed by his performance, Tony
Blair might just be their man.
 &HT;    Blair likes to measure his modernizing project in terms of
upgrading the country's technological prowess, stocking its skills
bank and keeping it on the front lines of global competition. But
the coming of a baby to 10 Downing Street is casting things in more
human terms. The progress of the mission may no longer be computed
in just gigabytes, new job opportunities and trade figures but in
less tangible things like the hours he devotes to his family, the
dinners he has at home, the school meetings he attends, the
postnatal duties he shares and _ for the more tangible-minded _ the
pile of diapers changed on his nighttime vigil.
 &HT;    Blair runs none of the risk that many people in temptation-laden
public life do when they posture as defenders of family values and
supporters of marriage. He has a solid and whisper-free 20-year
union with a woman who has a remarkable career of her own and a
proven dedication to balancing an oppressively busy professional
life with real time at home.
 &HT;    On arriving at 10 Downing Street, he established a routine of
working habits designed to guarantee him time for his wife and
children, Euan, now 16, Nicky, 14, and Kathryn, 12. State dinners
were to be substituted by state lunches wherever possible. The
morning hour of 7:30 to 8:30 was inviolate while he took breakfast
with his family upstairs. At the other end of the day, 7:30 marked
his departure from work for family dinner. The red box of working
papers that accompany each British cabinet member home every day
was opened in the Blair household only after the family hour.
 &HT;    ``It seems to me he has a balance between his work and family
which just makes you think, Well, this is actually somebody who's
more like the rest of us and therefore he's more likely to make the
right call,'' says a Downing Street civil servant who is a holdover
from past Conservative governments. ``That's because he's doing it
against a more normal background than, say, a politician who's all
work and no play, like Thatcher coming down to work at 4 in the
morning.''
 &HT;    The Blair kids' friends come over in the afternoon, and the
scene is said by visitors to be the merry chaos you'd expect.
``We're very close as a family, but I think you'd be surprised to
know just how completely normal our family life is,'' Blair says.
``I mean, I do the same things, more or less, as any bloke does
with his kids.''
 &HT;    Weekends are often spent at Chequers, the official country
residence in Buckinghamshire where the Blairs kick a soccer ball
around the grounds in the day and in the evening frequently
entertain, mixing old friends from outside politics with the
occasional cabinet officer and celebrities from the worlds of
entertainment and sports.
 &HT;    The Blairs go about their churchgoing faithfully but privately,
with photographers encouraged to stay away. The Blairs are fiercely
protective of the privacy of their children. They appear as a
family in public only once each year, during their summer holidays
on the continent. Otherwise, the kids are off limits, and Blair
says, ``Having to be fair, in this regard, our press has behaved
pretty well.''
 &HT;    Let that behavior lapse, however, and the Blairs strike back
swiftly. When the tabloid Mail on Sunday planned to print an
utterly benign account of their family life by a former nanny,
Cherie Blair obtained a Saturday night injunction against
publication and then threatened to sue the young woman unless she
promised to honor the confidentiality clause of her employment
contract. They were willing to withstand accusations of gagging the
press and bullying a well-intentioned young woman to make the point
that any public mention, even favorable, of their private life was
out of bounds.
 &HT;    I asked Blair if he felt he had succeeded in immunizing his
children against the effects of growing up at Britain's most
important address. ``So far, touch wood, we've been lucky,'' he
says. ``It's very important because it isn't their fault that their
dad is prime minister. They've got to live the rest of their lives,
and there are two problems here. One is that their friends at
school become too impressed by it and the other is in a sense they
get used to it and not know that I will one day stop being prime
minister. A lot of people may not then be so keen on them and all
the rest of it. We teach them to choose their friends very
carefully, choose friends who are real friends, and just to realize
that this here, it's in some ways a magic moment for them.''
 &HT;    On an afternoon I spent at No. 10 talking to Blair's associates,
Blair went through the grueling prime minister's questions time at
the House of Commons, trading barked insults with the Conservative
leader William Hague, returned to No. 10 for a sensitive meeting
with David Trimble, the leader of the Ulster Unionist Party, and
then piled into a car with Cherie to attend a parents' gathering at
Kathryn's school. Anji Hunter, his special assistant and a friend
since they were teen-agers together in Scotland, says Blair has
always been that way.
 &HT;    ``Even as a backbencher, he was never someone who hung around
the tearoom or the bars,'' she says. ``At the end of the day, he
would vote and go home to his family.''
 &HT;    Tony Blair was born May 6, 1953, in Edinburgh and reared in the
northern English city of Durham, where his father was a university
law professor and rising figure in Conservative politics. Cherie
came from a working-class Labor family in Liverpool that fell apart
when she was 7. It was that year, 1961, that her mother was left by
her father, a television actor named Tony Booth, whose bent for
what the British tabloids call ``crumpeteering'' was to produce
five more children, three more marriages and a string of other
relationships. Cherie saw little of her errant father for much of
her youth, but the estrangement ended when he was severely burned
in a 1979 accident and gave up drinking. He and his fourth wife,
Stephanie, are now visitors to No. 10 and Chequers.
 &HT;    When Blair succeeded the wintry John Major as prime minister he
began promoting Britain very effectively as a place with flash. It
wasn't long before models, pop singers and movie stars began
flocking to a land they called Cool Britannia, with the shiny new
prime minister as its master of ceremonies. Charles Falconer,
another old friend and member of the House of Lords who shared
living quarters with Blair when the two were young lawyers in
London, says the image was misleading.
 &HT;    ``He vastly prefers a private life to the social life that comes
with being leader of the opposition or a head of government. His
home has always been London; his family has always been nearby. He
saw lots more of his family than many of his contemporaries did
during the '80s, and now he works in the same building where his
family lives. He's never been on great national campaigns like
yours, and he doesn't have to be away for any length of time from
his family.''
 &HT;    Blair claims his government will always take actions mindful of
their effects on family stability, and one of the five key planks
in the platform for the next electoral campaign is called helping
families. I ask Blair how something as public and unwieldy as
government could be effective in stabilizing something as private
and volatile as a family.
 &HT;    ``I've wrestled with this for 10 years really because I believe
passionately in family life,'' he says. ``It's an important part of
the stability of society. That's common sense and everyone would
agree. But on the other hand, if as politicians you end up kind of
preaching to people about their private lives, you get into trouble
very, very quickly.''
 &HT;    His list of vehicles for government attention include tax
policy, child-care support, schools, truancy, jobs for young
people, flexible working hours, parental leave, sex education and
opportunities for advancement for residents of inner-city
neighborhoods. ``You can't substitute government for parents,'' he
says, ``but you can where it is possible and sensible support
family life.''
 &HT;    Blair is more comfortable talking in family-values generalities
than he is about his own family, but the subject was hard to avoid
in the days following the announcement of Cherie's pregnancy.
Reporters busied themselves doing the math, and they computed that
the whole thing must have started sometime during the Blairs'
vacation travels last summer. When they asked if the child had been
conceived in England, France or Italy, Blair wasn't above noting
wolfishly that any of the three were possible. Later, he said he
thought England was the place. But he added, ``Not that Tuscany
wasn't romantic.''
 &HT;    With 13 highly competitive national newspapers selling a total
of more than 14 million copies a day, Britain subjects its
politicians to intense scrutiny. ``We don't have a great
constituency in the media these days,'' Blair says. ``There is a
tendency for the right to attack us because we are Labor and the
left to attack us because we are New Labor.''
 &HT;    The current general whine in Britain may be nothing more than a
necessary correction on the national tolerance-of-triumphalism
meter. ``Tony Blair has been so successful for sufficiently long,''
says Sion Simon, a political writer sympathetic to him, ``that
there is now a part of every Briton, including most of his closest
friends and allies, that would like to see him humiliated and
broken.''
 &HT;    The man I find in his study at 10 Downing Street appears in no
mood to accommodate them. ``Look, '' Blair says, ``it was
inevitable that this was going to happen. I mean, I used to think
sometimes in that first year, For goodness' sake, let's get back
into normal politics again.''
 &HT;    A lot of the incomings at the official residence are being
launched from the traditional forces in his party who believe that
New Labor ought to be more generous with state aid to the poor and
needy, that Blair is selling out the party's principles. Blair
doesn't duck.
 &HT;    ``If I went back to the old tunes of the left, I would
immediately get a whole lot of support from certain groups of
people,'' he says. ``I mean, it would be daft because it wouldn't
be what the country needed, but people could locate me. You know, I
think one of the problems is that I am totally grounded to what I
believe in, and I have complete confidence in it too. But it isn't
the same grounding as traditional right and left categories, and so
people go around saying I am not grounded.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Blair protests portrayals of him as a man feeling beaten down by
criticisms even as he moves toward the acclamation of almost
certain re-election a year from now. ``I am not dispirited, but you
do have to keep driving the argument forward,'' he says.
 &HT;    ``The fact that our opponents have to coalesce around this
notion of 'Well, they're arrogant' or 'Let's make the country
cynical about them' is because they don't have a big argument. If
they were saying, 'You're destroying the British economy' or 'Look,
you're running the country wrongly, you're taking it in the wrong
direction, and here are the reasons,' but they're not.''
 &HT;    Blair wants to be thought of as more than just a Labor leader
who has overcome the party's reputation for chaotic management or a
prime minister who used his power to become a competent custodian
of the country. He is fond of calling his government ``a project,''
implying not just a rearrangement of British politics but its
permanent restructuring.
 &HT;    ``I would say that we are winning the intellectual argument in
Britain,'' he says. ``I don't see any serious alternative. And I
think if you look around the world, most successful governments are
moving more or less in the same direction. It is that there is a
role for government and for community today, but it is an
empowering role, an equipping role. It's not old, big-style
government imposing top-down, heavy-handed intervention. And it's
making sure that it's not an exclusive but an inclusive type of
political society that you've created.''
 &HT;    The project envisions Blair himself and successors from Labor
running Britain for many years to come. I ask Blair if, three years
after starting it, he can keep the project on the rise even without
the public exuberance that helped send it aloft.
 &HT;    ``All governments in the end never satisfy everybody's
expectations,'' Blair says. ``But you've got to ask yourself: 'Are
we moving the country in the right direction? Are we modernizing
the country in the face of massive change and trying to do it so
that the benefits of change reach all the people? Are we basically
delivering on the things that we came into politics to deliver?' I
would say that I can answer those questions with a fairly
comfortable yes.''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Warren Hoge 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Warren Hoge is the London bureau chief of The New York Times.) &QL;
