<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKEL-BONUS-CENTERPIECE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'FREEDOM OF INFORMATION' IN NAME ONLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 14, or thereafter.)  
 By MAX FRANKEL  
 c.2000 The New York Times Magazine  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was on this date in 1965 that the FBI delivered to the White
House information about me from ``an extremely sensitive source''
suggesting that it might ``be of interest'' to President Lyndon
Johnson. Even 35 years later, however, my government refuses to
tell me, or historians, what this nugget might have been or whence
it came.
</P>
<P>
   The Rorschach blobs of censorial black on the documents
reproduced here are your taxes at work, obliterating our rights.
The fact of that White House transmittal is the only comprehensible
and legibly dated news I could glean from 41 heavily excised pages
sent to me in alleged compliance with the Freedom of Information
Act.
</P>
<P>
   It was seven years ago that I invoked that act to see my FBI
file, which had long been kept secret. I expected a full dossier
covering my years as a reporter in Moscow, Havana and Washington,
with particularly rich entries for the year 1965, when I annoyed
the authorities with articles about America's covert intervention
in the Dominican Republic and about escalation of the war in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   A part of my file _ apparently the portion that focused on
efforts to track down some of my 1965 sources _ was finally
censored into incoherence and ``declassified'' on Oct. 6, 1998.
Even then, it was not mailed until 18 months later, on March 30,
2000. And the mailing suggested that there were many ``additional
references'' in the files that ``may pertain'' to me. I was told I
could request them, whereupon they would presumably be similarly
blacked out and sent to me in the year 2007.
</P>
<P>
   I offer this amusing but sad evidence of government waste and
corruption because it is emblematic of how federal and most state
and local officials have sabotaged one of the hard-won freedoms
achieved by Americans and their media a generation ago: the right,
with only sensible exceptions, to find out what our government
does, knows and records.
</P>
<P>
   Federal agents and county sheriffs alike now routinely frustrate
the law by invoking phony ``security'' concerns to keep their files
secret even decades after any conceivable risk has disappeared.
When that dodge fails, they can refuse information to avoid
``unwarranted invasion of personal privacy,'' even if it is my
privacy that was obviously breached.
</P>
<P>
   And when no pretext can justify withholding information,
governments have learned to play the actuarial odds, stalling
inquiries for months and even years until all interest in, and
value of, their records have expired.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters once thought that they, as surrogates for the public,
would be the main beneficiaries of freedom-of-information laws.
With timely access to hearings and records, they hoped for more
effective monitoring of official behavior and investigations of
chronic injustice. But officialdom has learned to frustrate the
media with refusals that can be challenged with only costly
time-consuming litigation.
</P>
<P>
   It recently took a court hearing and three months for a Columbia
journalism student to gain admission to New York City's
administrative ``taxi court,'' and he had what most reporters lack:
time and legal training.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Police Department routinely deflects inquiries for
four months and dares the media to invest in full-scale litigation.
The New York Times had to go all the way to the Court of Appeals
last year to gain access to the performance records of doctors in
New York hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   As Adam Liptak, The Times' senior counsel, who handles the
paper's freedom-of-information actions, has observed, and as the
surveys of many newspapers around the country have confirmed, most
government agencies know how to work the system to frustrate
unwelcome inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   There is only one ``wonderland,'' Liptak reports, where
officials take the law seriously and usually respond positively in
24 hours: the state of Florida. The reason is that Florida law
guarantees an immediate, next-morning judicial review of rejections
and automatic payment of attorney fees if the state loses.
</P>
<P>
   Bureaucrats wanting to withhold a piece of information must seek
specific legislation, says Pat Gleason, general counsel to
Florida's attorney general. And as Congress and other states might
note, Florida has sunnily survived its nakedness.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, even the crudest censorship sometimes slips and
fails to conceal damaging evidence of official stupidity. Thus it
was that I learned from one clear line in a memo that the FBI had
to consult the Congressional Directory to discover that I worked
for The New York Times and that censored ``indices'' showed that I
often wrote about European affairs!
</P>
<P>
   And that ``sensitive'' letter to the White House concluded with
an oddly self-effacing explanation that ``all correspondents of The
New York Times are treated with circumspection by the bureau and
our relationship with The New York Times is strained.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads should roll for clearing that confession of respect.
</P>
<P>
   (Max Frankel is the former Washington Bureau chief, editorial
page editor and executive editor of The New York Times. He won a
Pulitzer Prize in 1973 and has been a correspondent in Eastern
Europe, Moscow and the Caribbean. Frankel now writes this ``Word &AMP;
Image'' column for The New York Times Magazine.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
