<HEADER>
A1968 &Cx1f; tab-z
u a BC-BATTLEFIELD-EARTH-CEN     05-11 2718
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTLEFIELD-EARTH-CENTERPIECE-ADV14-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV14 
 BATTLEFIELD HOLLYWOOD: THE SAMAHA FORMULA FOR FILM SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Sunday, May 14, or thereafter.) 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following article from The New York Times
Magazine is for use by clients of the ``Centerpiece'' package.
Nonsubscribers can use these articles only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. A full-length version of
this article is available on request. 
 By LYNN HIRSCHBERG 
 FROM: The New York Times Magazine 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Two years ago, Elie Samaha phoned John Travolta and told him he
was going to make his dream come true. Travolta had never heard of
him. ``I didn't know who Elie Samaha was,'' he recalls. ``And
neither did my manager.''
 &HT;    Samaha, who owns Franchise Pictures, a company that finances and
produces more than a dozen movies a year, wanted to meet with
Travolta to discuss ``Battlefield Earth,'' a script based on L. Ron
Hubbard's science-fiction novel. For more than 15 years, Travolta
had been trying to get this movie, his pet project, off the ground.
 &HT;    ``Battlefield Earth'' had bounced around three studios but had
been shelved again and again. So many years had passed that
Travolta switched from longing to play the youthful hero of the
movie to setting his sights on the nine-foot villain with the
cackling laugh _ and, yet, even after a string of $100 million
box-office hits to his credit, Travolta could not get Hollywood to
budge on ``Battlefield.''
 &HT;    ``I have a special affection for this book,'' says Travolta, who
is a follower of Scientology, the religion that Hubbard originated
when he was not turning out pulp fiction. ``Hubbard was a great
writer, and I had an idea of the movie's potential, a fantasy in my
mind that lasted for years.'' When Samaha called, Travolta agreed
to meet him for dinner at the Bel-Air Hotel.
 &HT;    Samaha was looking to up his game from the $5 million movies he
had been making at Franchise. He had read the script for
``Battlefield Earth'' and also saw potential: a big, controversial
movie with a big profile in the industry; a big star, who is also a
big star overseas; and a script that was ready to shoot. There was
only one sticking point. ``I said, 'If John wants to make this
movie, what does he want to get paid?''' Samaha recalls. ``Because
I do not pay anybody what they make. That is not my business
plan.''
 &HT;    If ``Battlefield Earth'' had not been Travolta's dream, he would
have demanded his usual $20 million. But dreams lead to compromise
in Hollywood, and Samaha knows that. It is a key part of his
business plan: scavenge and dig and find the script or project that
a star most wants to make; finance it overseas; then shoot it in
Canada to save money.
 &HT;    Travolta's pet project arrived in theaters on May 12. The actor
took a pay cut _ even investing $5 million of his own money when
the production fell short _ but he is thrilled with how things
turned out. ``Elie is primarily a financier,'' Travolta says. ``But
he understands vision.''
 &HT;    It is 10 minutes into the first quarter of the Lakers game, and
Samaha will not sit down. Franchise Pictures has six courtside
seats on the floor of the Staples Center, and on this April evening
Samaha has invited Sylvester Stallone, a producer named Mark Canton
and John Ptak, a top senior agent at Creative Artists Agency who
specializes in foreign financing, to join him at the game.
 &HT;    Samaha, who at 43 looks like a taller, lankier Stallone, is
dressed in black pants, black shirt, black tie and brown suede
shoes, and he runs from seat to seat, attending to his guests. He
gets them food, drinks, programs, tickets to the VIP bar, to the
skybox. In exchange, Samaha gets them. With the exception of
Stallone, who is a longtime friend, none of Samaha's other guests
would have recognized him five years ago.
 &HT;    Then, he was known, if he was known at all, as the slightly
shadowy guy who could get you into Roxbury, a club he owned on the
Sunset Strip that became notorious when the actress Shannen Doherty
got involved in a brawl there.
 &HT;    But the business in Hollywood has shifted. These days, Samaha's
skill at attracting foreign financing for movies with big stars has
become highly attractive to the increasingly risk-averse studios.
Whereas he used to seem vaguely sleazy, studios are now impressed
by the scale of Samaha's ambition, by his knack for fostering
favorite-orphan projects like ``Battlefield Earth'' and producing
them at a price.
 &HT;    So far, Franchise has undertaken, among others, ``The Big
Kahuna'' (for Kevin Spacey), ``The Pledge'' (for Jack Nicholson and
Sean Penn), ``Get Carter'' (for Stallone) and, most successfully,
``The Whole Nine Yards'' (for Bruce Willis). When everyone else
said no or maybe or we'll see, Samaha said yes. He served the
stars.
 &HT;    Like a latter-day Sam Goldwyn or Harry Warner, Samaha, who is
Lebanese and learned English from watching Clint Eastwood films,
views the movie business as the perfect job for an immigrant with
drive: there are no class restrictions; there is no need for a
formal education.
 &HT;    ``In Hollywood, you only need success to have more success,''
Samaha explains, fussing over Stallone. ``People laughed at me. I
didn't care. They didn't take me seriously. They didn't even return
my calls three years ago.'' He pauses, briefly considering
Shaquille O'Neal, who is passing the ball to Kobe Bryant. ``But I'm
in the business to make money, and why would I hold a grudge? I
mean, who the hell was Elie Samaha three years ago?''
 &HT;    Part of Samaha's credibility with the Hollywood community comes
from the box-office success of ``The Whole Nine Yards.'' Samaha
produced the project when Warner Brothers was not interested. It
was stuck in their library: studios commission and develop hundreds
of scripts a year and only a handful get made; the rest languish in
a movie purgatory known as ``turnaround.'' Samaha loves turnaround
_ he can buy scripts stuck there for almost nothing, and often the
scripts have been polished and tweaked (for better or for ill) at
someone else's expense.
 &HT;    ``The Whole Nine Yards'' was personally important to Bruce
Willis because it had been developed by his brother, David. To help
keep costs low, Willis and the other principals deferred their
usual salaries in lieu of a percentage of the final gross. So far,
the movie has made $60 million domestically.
 &HT;    Warner Brothers was amazed. Surprise success is a magic wand in
Hollywood. It can smooth out rough edges and inspire faith. ``The
Whole Nine Yards'' was just fluky enough to make people wonder if
Samaha knew something they didn't. This is not to say that Samaha
has arrived, exactly.
 &HT;    ``Elie's first real test will be 'Battlefield Earth,''' John
Ptak says. ``Elie listens and he's charming. But that stuff's all
Act 1. This is a three-act business. Act 1 is style and personality
and relationships. Act 2 is creating the avenues and highways to
put the cars on. And Act 3 is creating the actual cars, which are
the movies. You need all three acts to be successful. 'The Whole
Nine Yards' proved something. We'll see if 'Battlefield Earth' can
continue on that road.''
 &HT;    Samaha never had the same anxieties about ``Battlefield Earth''
that plagued the rest of Hollywood. Among executives, there was a
free-floating worry that ``Battlefield Earth'' would have the taint
of what many consider to be a cultlike religion. In fact, Hubbard
wrote fiction before he created Scientology, and ``Battlefield
Earth'' is a straightforward aliens-vs-humans kind of epic. The
book is not an allegory _ the script lacks even the mythological
overtones of ``Star Wars'' _ and is dismissed by hard-core
science-fiction writers.
 &HT;    ``Most people who know anything about science fiction think of
Hubbard as a complete fraud,'' says the novelist John Kessel.
``Hubbard writes a kind of science fiction that we call 'thud and
blunder,' stories for crackpots and juveniles.'' The movie will not
financially benefit Scientology, either. The rights to the book
were acquired in the mid-1990s from Author Services Inc., a Los
Angeles agency that handles Hubbard's fiction and is not affiliated
with the church. Yet however tenuous the Scientology connection,
Hollywood remained wary.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Travolta claims that no one ever mentioned Scientology to him.
``No executive ever brought it up,'' he maintains. ``I don't think
it would have been appropriate protocol.'' Yet there is no question
that Travolta's passion for the project stems from his belief in
Scientology. He is not a science-fiction fan (``I guess I liked
'Stranger in a Strange Land,''' is all he can muster), and this
movie has always been his homage to Hubbard.
 &HT;    During the '90s, ``Battlefield Earth'' was shuffled from one
studio to another, from MGM to Fox 2000 to Warner Brothers. The
project looked permanently stalled. But a few years ago, Travolta
saw a window on his calendar and told his manager, Jonathan Krane,
that he wanted to make his movie. Samaha was told of Travolta's
desire by Cassian Elwes, an agent at William Morris. Samaha had
badgered Elwes for access to his big projects, projects that the
studios had rejected. He saw a great opportunity to prove
something.
 &HT;    Samaha promptly secured a fluctuating credit line of up to $200
million from Imperial Bank in Los Angeles. With Travolta accepting
a pay cut, and after other concessions, like shooting in Canada,
the film's $90 million budget was slashed to $65 million. Over the
next six months, Samaha raised 70 percent of the budget for
``Battlefield Earth'' by selling off overseas rights to the film.
The international market for stars like Travolta, Willis and
Stallone is consistent and huge. Increasingly, this is how movies _
especially expensive action movies with big stars _ are financed.
 &HT;    Despite the qualms about the relationship between ``Battlefield
Earth'' and Scientology, Samaha managed to secure major financial
backing from Intertainment AG, a publicly held company in Germany,
where hostility to the religion is widespread. Samaha recalls: ``I
would yell at everyone, 'This is a science-fiction film starring
John Travolta!' again and again.'' As for Warner Brothers, which is
now distributing the movie for Franchise, its gamble is minimal _
Samaha has done all the major financing for them.
 &HT;    In fact, ``Battlefield Earth'' represents the consummation of
three distinct agendas: Samaha gains credibility by pulling off a
financing feat with a major star; Warner Brothers gets a big summer
movie with little financial investment; and Travolta gets to
realize his dream. No one, except Travolta and Krane, seems to care
whether or not the film has any artistic merit. As Samaha sees it,
creativity is up to the filmmakers.
 &HT;    Franchise's walls are lined with posters for movies that few
people have heard of: ``The White River Kid,'' ``Free Money,''
``Confession.'' These films are the foundation of the company.
Franchise has made dozens of low-budget movies. Some feature stars
_ Marlon Brando is in ``Free Money'' and phoned Samaha personally
to request Franchise's financial help. (At first, Samaha thought
the call was a prank.) The movie, like many in Franchise's library,
was never released in theaters, having gone straight to cable and
video. There is a lot of money in that secondary business _ you
shoot the film for five million and sell it for six _ but no
prestige.
 &HT;    There is a greater potential for financial failure with movies
like ``Battlefield Earth'' or ``Get Carter,'' but Samaha was not
happy staying on the fringes, however safe, of Hollywood. ``I
wanted to make bigger movies. I wanted to make movies with major
movie stars. There are only 30 stars in the world. If I have a
Stallone movie, I know I can do $42 million internationally. If
it's Meg Ryan, I can do $35. If it's Julia Roberts, I can do $45.
And besides, actors are like good wine. You put them on the shelf
and they're worth more. A movie with a star in it is good for my
library. A library is worth money. It's very easy. It's my
business.''
 &HT;    Samaha moved to Los Angeles 18 years ago. Born in Beirut, he was
4 when his father died; Elie and his brother and sister were reared
by their mother. He was athletic and joined the Lebanese Christian
Army when he was 14. Instead of attending high school, Samaha flew
off to London and Paris, where he managed the career of a
girlfriend who was a model. ``We don't like to talk about her,''
Samaha demurs. ``She is now dating one of the most powerful men in
the United States.''
 &HT;    After working for a year in New York as a bouncer at Studio 54,
Samaha migrated to Los Angeles in 1982. He read an article that
listed ``the five most successful businesses to be in'' and settled
on dry cleaning. ``I called my cleaner Celebrity Cleaners,'' Samaha
says.
 &HT;    In four years, Samaha and his brother, who remains his partner,
had 38 dry cleaners. They sold all except four businesses but kept
the real estate. He now owns property all over Los Angeles,
especially on Sunset Boulevard.
 &HT;    ``I made my first film, 'The Immortals,' in 1995 for $1.8
million,'' Samaha recalls. ``It was about the yakuza. I sold it to
October Films, to HBO and overseas. I made so much money on it, and
I thought, This is a great business.''
 &HT;    Samaha's first partners in the movie business were Amir Malin
and Avi Lerner at Millennium Films. They wanted to stay low end and
low budget. (Malin eventually left and was a founder of Artisan
Entertainment, which had enormous success with ``The Blair Witch
Project.'') Samaha wanted Millennium to shift gears from cheap
movies with B-list stars to large movies with top stars. His
partners disagreed.
 &HT;    ``They said, 'Quality doesn't pay.' I thought, Life's too short.
And I went on my own. They were laughing at me, of course.'' By
wooing agents and studio executives and talent like Stallone and
Willis, Samaha began forging powerful alliances. He sought out
projects _ like ``The Big Kahuna'' with Kevin Spacey and ``3,000
Miles to Graceland,'' a heist movie set in Las Vegas that Kevin
Costner wanted to make _ that had been languishing in one way or
another.
 &HT;    The stars Samaha has signed up impress everybody, from the
studios to Imperial Bank, which, with a consortium of other banks,
has upped Franchise's line of credit to $300 million. ``As long as
Samaha maintains his relationships with talent,'' says Jared
Underwood of Imperial Bank, ``we believe he can deliver.''
 &HT;    But what happens when one of his movies fails at the box office?
If ``Battlefield Earth'' is not a smash overseas, foreign investors
could blanch when asked to invest in future Franchise projects.
Similarly, Samaha's enthusiasm for the pet projects of big stars
may not prove to be all that wise in the long run.
 &HT;    Samaha does not seem worried, though. ``My projected numbers on
'Battlefield Earth' are really conservative,'' Samaha says. ``I'm
already covered internationally, and there's no way I'm going to
lose if the movie does $35 million domestically. And Travolta has
never had an action movie do under $35 million.''
 &HT;    Isn't he secretly hoping for a blockbuster? ``You can't be a
jerk in this business,'' Samaha says. ``I'm looking to do a $15
million weekend on 'Battlefield Earth.' Fifteen is huge for me. My
expectations are reasonable. And besides'' _ he smiles slightly _
``this is just so fun. If I was a betting man, and I am, I would
bet that this movie is going to change Franchise Pictures. On
'Battlefield Earth,' I can't lose.''
 &HT;    
 c.2000 Lynn Hirschberg 
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Lynn Hirschberg writes frequently for The New York Times
Magazine.) &QL;
