<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0102 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1982 &Cx1f; tab-z
w e BC-DOUGLAS-FAIRBANKS-JR-     05-11 1543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOUGLAS-FAIRBANKS-JR-OBITUARY-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOUGLAS FAIRBANKS JR.: SON OF ZORRO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Note: Last updated 18 Feb. 1999. Insert TK date and cause of death
in 2nd graf.) 
 Includes a 350-word sidebar 
 By GAYDEN WREN  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In an era when practically everyone in Hollywood seems to be the
child of a former star, a special distinction belongs to Douglas
Fairbanks Jr., the suave, sophisticated actor who was the first
second-generation movie star.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a lifetime of accomplishments onscreen and off,
Fairbanks never quite shook the ``Jr.'' from his name, always
remaining slightly in his father's shadow. But when he died
XXXDATEXXX from XXXCAUSEXXX, the entertainment world lost one of
its most popular and long-lived fixtures.
</P>
<P>
   Though there was a marked resemblance between the two, Fairbanks
never had the flamboyant exuberance which distinguished his
father's best films. Instead, he was debonair and casually
seductive, as likable onscreen as he was off, where he was one of
Hollywood's most famous raconteurs. He could carry off a
swashbuckling role in his father's style _ his most enduring film
was perhaps ``The Prisoner of Zenda'' (1937) _ but was equally
comfortable in screwball farces, romantic comedies or brawling
dramas.
</P>
<P>
   Though many later believed him to be the son of Hollywood's
first superstar couple, Douglas Fairbanks and Mary Pickford,
Fairbanks Jr.'s mother was actually the actor's first wife, Anna
Beth Fairbanks. Born in New York on Dec. 9, 1909, he was initially
a chubby child who bore little apparent resemblance to his dashing
father, from whom he was estranged for much of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In his teen years, however, he sprouted rapidly, growing into a
lanky, muscular body and clean-cut, chiseled good looks which
tagged him as a potential star. Making his screen debut at age 14
as the star of ``Stephen Steps Out'' (1923), he quickly grew into a
silent-film regular. In such films as ``Stella Dallas'' (1925),
``Broken Hearts of Hollywood'' (1926) and ``A Woman of Affairs''
(1928), he generally played reckless prodigal sons or shiftless
lovers _ usually seeing the error of his ways by the final reel.
</P>
<P>
   A particularly effective performance as a pushy reporter in
``The Power of the Press'' (1928), directed by the young Frank
Capra, earned Fairbanks the chance to star opposite Joan Crawford
in ``Our Modern Maidens'' (1929). Shortly afterward, the two stars
married in real life.
</P>
<P>
   The coming of sound posed no obstacle to Fairbanks, whose voice
was light but resonant, and he was soon appearing in Warner Bros.
talkies, including such classics as ``The Dawn Patrol'' (1930),
``Little Caesar'' (1930) and ``Union Depot'' (1932).
</P>
<P>
   Warner's trademark tough-guy action roles weren't the best fit
with Fairbanks' dapper presence, however, and he left the studio in
1934. He spent several years making British films _ including the
historical epic ``Catherine the Great'' (1934) _ before he returned
to Hollywood for ``The Prisoner of Zenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing opposite the even-more-dapper Ronald Colman, Fairbanks
suddenly clicked as Rupert of Hentzau, a rakish, amoral but
charming swordsman with a quip ever on his lips. Cheerfully
betraying everyone in sight _ and making good his escape at the
film's end _ Fairbanks' murderous Rupert was almost the evil twin
of Douglas Fairbanks Sr.'s rakish-but-heroic Zorro.
</P>
<P>
   Energized by his success in the role, Fairbanks spent the next
few years mingling romantic comedies such as ``The Joy of Living''
(1938, opposite Irene Dunne) and ``Having Wonderful Time'' (1938,
opposite Ginger Rogers) with adventure movies such as ``Gunga Din''
(1939, as a reckless British sergeant) and ``The Sun Never Sets''
(1939, with Basil Rathbone as his brother). In 1941 he returned to
the swashbuckling genre for ``The Corsican Brothers,'' this time
playing twins.
</P>
<P>
   A staunch Anglophile, Fairbanks was an early advocate of
American involvement in World War II, serving as national vice
chairman of the Committee to Defend America by Aiding the Allies in
1940 and 1941. After Pearl Harbor, Fairbanks joined the Navy,
serving as a lieutenant commander until the end of the war and
earning several decorations. He would remain active in diplomatic
and military activities into the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Returning to Hollywood after the war, Fairbanks renewed his
swashbuckling credentials with ``Sinbad the Sailor'' (1947), a
lavish, special-effects-studded epic in which his performance was
seen by some as a salute to his father, who had died in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly interested in off-camera work, the actor produced
and co-wrote his next two swashbucklers, ``The Exile'' (1948) and
``The Fighting O'Flynn'' (1949). He then returned to England to
make ``State Secret'' (1950).
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks moved to England in the early 1950s, and his film
output diminished. He experimented in television, hosting,
producing and often acting in an anthology series, ``Douglas
Fairbanks Presents.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he was largely absent from the movies thereafter _ his
final film was ``Ghost Story'' (1981), which teamed him with fellow
silver-screen veterans Fred Astaire, Melvyn Douglas and John
Houseman _ Fairbanks remained active in other fields. He appeared
in various stage plays, including playing Henry Higgins in a
British production of ``My Fair Lady,'' and lent his warmth and
sophisticated presence to orchestra narrations and
television-series hosting duties, including the American
presentations of ``The Compleat Gilbert &AMP; Sullivan'' in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, the actor also served on several corporate
boards, worked for various charitable organizations and, with his
seemingly bottomless supply of jokes and stories, was a welcome
figure in society on both sides of the Atlantic. He published three
autobiographical books, including ``The Fairbanks Album'' (1975),
``Salad Days'' (1988) and ``A Hell of a War'' (1993).
</P>
<P>
   He was married three times, most recently to Vera Shelton in
1991, three years after the death of Mary Lee Fairbanks, his wife
of 49 years. He leaves three daughters _ Daphne Fairbanks-Weston,
Victoria Van Gerbig and Melissa Morant.
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks never achieved the superstardom of his father, but he
lived a long and rewarding life, succeeding at nearly everything he
tried his hand in. If, as critics said, his best performances all
gave the sense that he was having a lot of fun, it was probably
because he was. &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE.) (OPTIONAL TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
 &UR; BC-DOUGLAS-FAIRBANKS-JR-OBIT-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: it was probably because he was.) &QL; 
 &UR; SIDEBAR: THE SON ALSO RISES &LR;  &QL;
<P>
   Most of Douglas Fairbanks Jr.'s best films can be found on video
cassette, and a few on laser disk or DVD. A greatest-hits sampling
might include the following six films:
</P>
<P>
   + `THE PRISONER OF ZENDA' (1937).
</P>
<P>
   Fairbanks' defining role, as Rupert of Hentzau, a
roguish-but-dashing swordsman maneuvering between villainous
Raymond Massey and heroic Ronald Colman, who plays the king of
Ruritania and his look-alike cousin. The performance works
precisely because Fairbanks never shows the slightest trace of
conscience. Watch the dialogue scenes between him and Colman, which
feature fencing as skillful as any of the sword fights.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE JOY OF LIVING' (1938).
</P>
<P>
   This neglected gem features Irene Dunne as a harried Broadway
star beset by fans, agents and a rapacious family, with Fairbanks
as the devil-may-care shipowner who captivates her in spite of
himself. As the parasitic family, Guy Kibbee, Alice Brady and a
young, surly Lucille Ball are hysterical.
</P>
<P>
   + `GUNGA DIN' (1940).
</P>
<P>
   One of the great action movies of all time, with director George
Stevens pitting Cary Grant, Fairbanks and Victor McLaglen against
vicious Indian cultists and their own propensity for getting into
trouble. A rousing epic, then and now, and only distantly related
to the Rudyard Kipling poem.
</P>
<P>
   + `THE CORSICAN BROTHERS' (1941).
</P>
<P>
   Double for your money, with Fairbanks as long-lost twin
brothers, psychically linked and caught up in bewildering
intrigues. The special effects that bring Fairbanks face to face
with himself are still first-rate.
</P>
<P>
   + `SINBAD THE SAILOR' (1947).
</P>
<P>
   A deliriously colorful Arabian Nights story, with Fairbanks as
the title character. A strong supporting cast includes Anthony
Quinn and Maureen O'Hara. Fairbanks borrows some of the flamboyant
mannerisms of his swashbuckling father's ``Thief of Baghdad'' in
this more-than-a-little-tongue-in-cheek epic.
</P>
<P>
   + `STATE SECRET' (1950).
</P>
<P>
   Many of Fairbanks' best films involved doubles, and so does this
meticulously plotted, surprisingly witty British thriller.
Fairbanks plays an American doctor who, visiting a small Middle
European country, discovers that its ruler has been assassinated
and replaced with a ringer. Itself a sort of ``Prisoner of Zenda''
evil twin, this is one of the actor's best and most intelligent
films.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Gayden Wren is the entertainment editor for The New York Times
Syndicate.) &LR; 
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
