<HEADER>
A1996 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-BEER-COLUMN-NY     05-11 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-BEER-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEER _ BETTER WHEN CONSUMED THAN WHEN STUDIED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, May 11, or thereafter)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER column.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Usually red wine is the star of studies and press releases.
</P>
<P>
   We're constantly bombarded with news stories about the effects
of red wine. A glass of red wine every day helps prevent heart
disease. Red wine in moderation is good for the blood. Too much red
wine will give you a headache. Red wine spilled on a white sofa can
end a relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently it never matters if the red wine is a merlot or a
cabernet or something of a Mad Dog 20/20 vintage. Just has to be
red.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, though, beer is getting a lot of play from media-hungry
researchers who apparently would rather concentrate on this sort of
material than, I don't know, A CURE FOR CANCER or something.
</P>
<P>
   I collect this stuff because I can. Consider these actual
beer-related findings, theories and studies from the last couple of
months:
</P>
<P>
   _ A Dutch researcher said that consuming a reasonable amount of
beer every day could be even better for your heart than the
proverbial glass or two of red wine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Some nimrods from the animals-rights activist group PETA
touted beer as a nutritionally preferable alternative to milk with
a campaign featuring the slogan, ``Got Beer?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Harvard Medical School found that in terms of raising one's
HDL, or ``good'' cholesterol, consuming moderate amounts of beer is
the same as consuming moderate amounts of wine or liquor.
</P>
<P>
   _ A study commissioned by Guinness found that mustachioed
consumers of the creamy-topped stout lose more than 160,000 pints a
year due to ``upper-lip absorption,'' gross. That figure would be
even higher if David Crosby and that Fluff dude who used to caddy
for Tiger Woods became regular Guinness drinkers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Another study theorized that when you've had five beers in one
sitting, you've officially reached a binge. So just have four and a
half and go home with a smile!
</P>
<P>
   _ New York University researchers found that higher beer prices
often reduce beer drinking _ and cigarette smoking. Um, sure, if a
six-pack is pricier, fewer purchases can be made and it leaves less
spare change for smokes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Meanwhile, the Public Health Institute in Berkeley, Calif.,
was finding that 10 percent of beer drinkers consume 43 percent of
beer. This means that people who drink a lot of beer drink a lot of
beer.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have a white lab coat or a research grant, but I have
done some field research of my own in this area, starting with my
first illegal beer (can of Hamm's Draft in a silver can designed to
resemble a miniature keg) and my first legal brew (Old Style in a
mason jar, from a tap at Nick's Sports Page in Dolton), both
quaffed many years ago.
</P>
<P>
   I've observed that consuming too many beers leads to:
</P>
<P>
   _ Excess midriff syndrome, aka ``a beer gut.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Long lines in the bathrooms at Comiskey Park and Soldier
Field, where guys tell the same jokes year after year while
belching loudly and randomly screaming things like ``Cubs Suck!''
and ``Da Bears!'' and the ever-popular, ``The water's cold!''
</P>
<P>
   _ A temporary cerebral condition known as ``stupidity.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most ridiculous and pointless beer study yet arrived
courtesy of the Center for Disease Control in Atlanta. They got
tremendous play in the media with their findings on teen-agers,
gonorrhea and cheap beer.
</P>
<P>
   As the Los Angeles Times put it, ``When the price of beer goes
up, teen-age gonorrhea goes down, federal health officials say.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, not quite. What the CDC said was this: A tax increase of
20 cents per six-pack could reduce gonorrhea rates among teen-agers
but 9 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   And even that was a shaky extrapolation of the actual four-page
study.
</P>
<P>
   The basic finding of the study was that when teens drink,
they're more likely to have sex without a condom, with multiple
partners and with high-risk partners.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it could be argued that the causal relationship is
the other way around _ that teens who have more sex are more likely
to drink beer.
</P>
<P>
   The study looked at gonorrhea rates among the young and beer-tax
increases from 1981 to 1995 and came up with the conclusion that
more expensive beer leads to a lower rate of this particular STD.
</P>
<P>
   But if you look at the study itself and not just the news
stories that parroted the findings, you'll see that even the CDC
admits the study does NOT prove an actual connection between the
price of beer and the rate of gonorrhea.
</P>
<P>
   So what's the point?
</P>
<P>
   To get media attention, of course. To see your findings appear
in hundreds of newspapers and on local newscasts across the
country. And to use those clippings the next time you have to prove
your worth as a researcher.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I'll continue with my field research. This just
in:
</P>
<P>
   Beer makes you belch. Video at 5, 6 and 10.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper &LR; suntimes.com) is a columnist for the
Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
