<P>
   PHILLIPS-AUCTION (New York) _ The Phillips Gallery will hold the
biggest sale in its 206-year history Thursday evening when 31
Impressionist and modern works that may bring $80 million are sold.
By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   HAMLET-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``It is curious; one never thinks
of attaching `Hamlet' to any special locale,'' the critic Kenneth
Tynan once wrote of Shakespeare's tragedy, and the director Michael
Almereyda has brilliantly seized upon that by rooting his
voluptuous and rewarding new adaptation of the play in today's
Manhattan. By Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-CLOISTERS (New York) _ The most beautiful European cloister
I've ever experienced lies along the Hudson River, just south of
the Bronx border. In every European city I've run straight to every
cloister mentioned in each footnote of my guidebook. Predictably,
my expectations were forever higher than any mere human cloister
could deliver. By Helen Schary Motro.
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-PALACE-PATIO (New York) _ A palace was not a palace without
a patio in the days of Don Pedro Fajardo y Chacon (circa
1478-1546), the Castilian nobleman who built the Castle of Velez
Blanco near the southeastern coast of Spain between 1506 and 1515.
By one of those happy sets of circumstances that often befall the
Metropolitan Museum, the Velez Blanco patio was installed in 1964.
The courtyard, closed for refurbishing in 1997, reopens Friday and
is closer than it has been in many years to its 16th-century self.
By Grace Glueck.
</P>
