<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESSURE-TREATED POSTS WON'T HARM DOGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER C. HOTTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I have to replace a long stockade fence to keep the dogs in
the yard. I would like to use cedar posts; the rest of the fence
can be any kind of wood, but my son says the posts must be pressure
treated. I am concerned that the dogs will rub up against the posts
and be poisoned by the copper arsenate in the pressure-treated
posts. Why can't I use cedar posts?
</P>
<P>
   C.D., Hanover, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Why not indeed. Yes, you can use cedar posts, which will last
about 15 years, when set in the ground, possibly longer if there is
good drainage under each post. However, there is no good reason
against using pressure-treated posts. The copper arsenate will not
rub off on the dogs. Such posts will outlast the fence. And to
avoid the controversy, consider installing an electric fence, an
invisible boundary that will keep the dogs in and other critters
out.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am redoing my asphalt driveway with a rumble strip and
cobblestone borders. I was quoted prices for mortaring in the
stones, and for not mortaring them. Should the stones be mortared
or not?
</P>
<P>
   PAULA DAULL, Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First of all, what the driveway man calls cobblestones are
really paving stones, granite pieces cut into squares and
rectangles. Cobblestones are natural, uncut stones, very round, and
if they are put in a driveway you don't need a rumble strip. Being
so uneven, they are rumble strips all by themselves, and,
incidentally, difficult to walk on.
</P>
<P>
   That done with, the paving stones do not have to be mortared; in
fact, they should not be mortared unless they are set on concrete.
Paving stones, like bricks and patio blocks, are best set in sand
or stone dust. And, dry-set stones should be less expensive than
mortared stones.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I live on a hill, and my neighbor's house is higher than
mine. The downspouts on his house are very long with extensions
that empty out about a foot from my property. The water flows down
my land and erodes it. How can I stop that flow and erosion? No
one, including the neighbor, seems to have a solution.
</P>
<P>
   J.S.T.P., Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. If you can get your neighbor to move the downspouts so they
discharge parallel to his house and harmlessly away, fine and good.
Or, he could build dry wells (holes in the ground) to accommodate
the water, if there is enough property to allow those wells to be
10 feet from the house.
</P>
<P>
   If these ideas cannot be taken to heart, then I suggest you dig
a dry well on the property line, or near it on your land, allowing
the discharge to go into the well instead of down your property. If
you cover the dry well with a wooden lid and cover that with turf,
no one will be the wiser, and you will win the good neighbor award.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I bought a house with no railings on either side of an open
stairway of 10 steps. I had new oak railings installed. It involved
taking out a wrought-iron rail on one side and installing railings
on each side, with 37 balusters and three posts of oak. There are
16 feet of railing altogether. The cost was $4,000. Is that high?
</P>
<P>
   J., Westwood, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. I think it is; materials might cost $500 to $700, leaving
$3,500 to $3,300 for installation. A price of $2,000 would have
been quite reasonable, even $3,000 is acceptable, but $4,000 is
exorbitant, in my oppinion. A dealer in the staircase industry,
with whom I checked, concurred.
</P>
<P>
   This would have been a good time to call for bids. Also, if the
purchase of the house was recent, you could have insisted that the
seller fix the unsafe condition of the stairway.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107, or e-mail him
at hotton(at)globe.com)
</P>
