<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2030 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS &LR;      05-11 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-REVIEW-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF THINGS HAD CHANGED, A NEW CAMRY WOULD BE ON ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The three-year itch arrived right on schedule, about 34 monthly
payments into the four-year coupon book on my 1997 Camry.
</P>
<P>
   The itch comes for no real reason outside of boredom.
</P>
<P>
   There is no sensible explanation for trading in the '97,
especially with only 30,000 miles on the odometer. It still looks
new and is practically indistinguishable from its successors unless
you're an expert on the nuances of Toyota's minor changes for 1998,
1999, and 2000.
</P>
<P>
   It never has had a major repair, just scheduled maintenance.
That means not so much as a flat tire or trip to the body shop.
Biggest fix-its: a new set of wiper blades and regulation gas cap
to replace the oversized wrong one we inherited from a
``full-serve'' fuel stop, and replacing a broken plastic clip that
holds the hood support rod.
</P>
<P>
   Financially, the '97 is worth at least twice what I owe on it.
</P>
<P>
   So why sell it?
</P>
<P>
   As best as I can figure, I've gotten so used to a lifetime of
used cars that three years was about the maximum length of my usual
relationship with a vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But it's going to be hard to part with this car. You know the
saying, ``Be careful what you wish for, because you might get it?''
That's one I'm wary of. But this was one time I went out to buy
something and discovered that I got everything I was hoping for . .
. and maybe a little more.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what I wanted:
</P>
<P>
   _ A four-door sedan so another couple could comfortably join us
for an evening out or a daytrip.
</P>
<P>
   _ Something totally reliable.
</P>
<P>
   _ A car that cost less than $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   _ A V-6 (or turbocharged 4-cylinder) with 5-speed manual
transmission.
</P>
<P>
   This Camry has met and continues to meet all four requirements.
</P>
<P>
   Still, when the itch is there, you have to scratch it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of salve, my pals from the New England Motor Press
Association conspired to send temptation my way _ a session with a
2000 Camry V-6 LE, followed by another with a 2000 Camry Solara,
the two-door coupe version of the Camry.
</P>
<P>
   The major differences between new and old, to me, were that the
new vehicles had an automatic transmission and were equipped with
sunroofs.
</P>
<P>
   And each was new. And tempting. Driving the 2000 Camry was like
sitting in a newer version of my car.
</P>
<P>
   A walk around the two Camrys parked side-by-side revealed only
the most minor of changes. The 2000 has a chrome trim ring round
the grille opening. The taillights, straight bars on my '97, now
dip down toward the center of the car. The hood is held up by
hydraulic cylinders instead of the prop rod on my 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' says Toytota's Wade Hoyt. ``If it ain't broke, you make
the taillights bigger.''
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't appear to have been kidding. The changes are that
minor.
</P>
<P>
   The driving experience is remarkably similar, too. Even though I
still prefer my manual transmission, the automatics on both 2000
models were quick and smooth and always seemed to be in the right
gear. On-ramp and merging acceleration was fine on both and each
behaved well on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   The dashboard displays haven't changed nor have the deep
cupholders in the center armrest with a couple of flimseys that pop
out for the rear-seat passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Handling was similar in all three cars. The surprise is that the
suspension and tires in my '97 still do a comparable job to the new
versions. I was thinking maybe things had softened up over time.
All three, being V-6s, have disc brakes and ABS. The Camry ABS in
my '97 has kicked in many times, and I now regard it as an old
friend coming along for a ride on wet and icy roads. The Solara
suspension was slightly tighter _ just enough to be noticeable. It
is, however, far short of being a true ports coupe. For that, you'd
have to go elsewhere in the Toyota family and try the Celica or the
coming MR2 Spyder roadster.
</P>
<P>
   The sound system in the 2000s, meanwhile, has a great optional
improvement over the AM/FM/Stereo/Cassette in my '97. Try a 6-CD,
in-dash unit. You feed the CDs in one at a time like quarters into
a parking meter. Having seen CD magazines squirreled away under
seats, in center consoles, in the glove compartment and in the
trunk, this was a slick system. Oh yes, the speakers were much
improved, too.
</P>
<P>
   An all-day Saturday outing to see our local team lose in the
championship game of the State Girls Basketball Championship game
proved the Solara is a perfectly acceptable car for four adults.
Our companions had no trouble hopping in and out of the back seat.
I tried it myself and agreed with their assessment that legroom was
fine even with the front seats all the way back.
</P>
<P>
   Reading the manuals for each of the 2000s revealed that Toyota
recommends premium fuel for optimum performance. Funny, I thought,
didn't the dealer tell me mine would run fine on regular? I know he
did, and I've been running it that way for three years with not so
much as a knock. It also regularly delivers 25-28 miles per gallon.
Still, a review of my manual reveals that Toyota recommends that I
should be running the '97 on premium, too. Now that it's drinking
the more expensive blend, I suspect performance might have crept up
a notch, but, then again, it might only be my imagination.
</P>
<P>
   Now about that itch.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the payment book is down to 10, I'm pretty sure I'm
going to keep my '97.
</P>
<P>
   About a month ago, a colleague tossed a brochure in my mailbox
that said TRD (Toyota Racing Development) would be coming out with
a supercharger this summer and that it would fit my V-6. I'm
thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   I'm also thinking of tightening up the suspension with some
Solara struts if they fit. And a sunroof would be a nice addition.
</P>
<P>
   All it takes is scratch, scratch, scratch . . . .
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe a can of that air freshener named ``new-car smell''
might be all that's needed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
