<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2031 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EBAY-SUSPENSION-HNS &LR;      05-11 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EBAY-SUSPENSION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     HIGH ART DEAL GOES AWRY ON THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ZACHARY COILE  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A Sacramento, Calif., lawyer was suspended from
trading on the auction house eBay after allegedly using an online
alias to drive up bids for a painting he was selling _ a piece some
believe could be a lost masterpiece by late artist Richard
Diebenkorn.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-day suspension by San Jose, Calif.-based eBay came as
questions mounted over the seller's credibility and whether the
orange and green abstract landscape is an original or a fake.
</P>
<P>
   But the suspension could wind up benefiting the seller,
32-year-old Ken Walton. The penalty cancels all his proposed sales
on eBay's site, including the deal Monday night to sell the
painting to a Dutch art collector for $135,805.
</P>
<P>
   If the piece is found to be a Diebenkorn, Walton could put it up
for bid again. Significant pieces by the painter have sold recently
at auction for $1 million and up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything is possible,'' Walton said Wednesday. ``Maybe (the
buyer) wants to back out. Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Walton, who offered the piece for sale under the user-name
``golfpoorly,'' was suspended by eBay for making a $4,500 bid on
the painting using a separate user-name, ``grecescu.''
</P>
<P>
   The practice is known to company officials as ``shilling,'' when
the seller artificially bids up the auction price to reap a bigger
profit from the final sale.
</P>
<P>
   Walton denied the violation of eBay rules was an effort to make
more money on the deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I placed this bid for an acquaintance of mine who, after
noticing the frenzy surrounding the auction, expressed an interest
in taking part in the action, but did not have an eBay account or
an active e-mail address,'' he said in a statement faxed to the
media. ``I placed a bid for him with one of my eBay accounts, not
realizing that this was against eBay policy.''
</P>
<P>
   He then praised the company for taking action against him,
saying, ``I applaud their efforts to maintain eBay as a safe
trading community.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the bid history, listed on eBay, the $4,500 bid
wasn't the major cause of the painting's inflated price. The
preceding bid came in at $4,201. The next bid was $4,811.
</P>
<P>
   But an eBay spokesman said any effort to inflate the price, even
by a small amount, is a major violation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shilling is one of the biggest concerns that our users have
because it gets to the very integrity of the bidding process,''
eBay spokesman Kevin Pursglove said. ``When we hear about it, we
move very fast.''
</P>
<P>
   Pursglove said eBay policy called for Walton to be suspended
from using the service for 30 days. A repeat offense could result
in a lifetime ban.
</P>
<P>
   The penalty comes after Walton was being criticized by
journalists and art collectors after he admitted Tuesday that he
had lied about aspects of the painting.
</P>
<P>
   In his online posting about the piece, Walton claimed the
painting has a inch-long hole caused by a child's Big Wheel. The
problem was, he has no children.
</P>
<P>
   He also claimed in the posting that his wife wouldn't let him
hang the picture in the house because she said it ``looks like it
was done by a nut case.'' The problem was, he has never been
married.
</P>
<P>
   Walton said Wednesday that he invented the tale as a funny story
to entertain bidders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought it was a cute little vignette to explain why I
was getting rid of a bunch of junk from the garage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His reputation was further tarnished by a report that he had run
into similar troubles last year, when he offered another painting
for sale on eBay.
</P>
<P>
   The piece had the signature, ``P. Gray,'' but Walton made no
claims as to the artist. Believing the piece was the work of early
20th century painter Henry Percy Gray, a Nebraska businessman
agreed to pay $7,600 for the work.
</P>
<P>
   When the businessman, Michael Luther, received the painting, he
found that the signature was a fraud, added years after the work
was completed. He threatened a lawsuit, but never filed one.
</P>
<P>
   Walton vehemently denied that he added a signature to any
painting.
</P>
<P>
   In a phone interview, Walton said he made a hobby of going to
garage sales and estate sales to find paintings. He said he had an
eye for rare finds and undervalued pieces. His profits would help
fund his fledgling law business, he said. He sold many of the
pieces on eBay under a third user-name, ``advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Walton argued that he had been mischaracterized in news stories
as devious and untrustworthy. But he admitted he brought much of
the negative coverage on himself.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm embarrassed by the whole thing. I hate the publicity,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   After the story broke this week, Walton pledged to have an
expert evaluate the painting. He said he wouldn't sell the work to
the buyer for $135,805 unless the piece was found to be a real
Diebenkorn.
</P>
<P>
   But Walton appeared to back off that pledge Wednesday. He said
it was too early to tell if he would sell the piece to the high
bidder or keep it himself.
</P>
<P>
   The high bidder, Robert Keereweer, a software executive from
Nieuwkoop, Netherlands, has said he wants to complete the sale, if
the painting is authentic.
</P>
<P>
   Keereweer said he believes the painting is a Diebenkorn after
seeing a photo online showing the signature, ``RD '52'' _ possibly
referring to the artist's initials and the year 1952. Once the hole
is fixed, the piece could be worth $500,000 to $1 million,
Keereweer said.
</P>
<P>
   Walton said he had no idea the piece could be a Diebenkorn
before he put it up for auction. He said he still doesn't know if
it's an original work.
</P>
<P>
   Diebenkorn, who died in 1993, was one of America's greatest 20th
century artists. He is associated with the rise of Abstract
Expressionism in the 1940s and 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Gretchen Grant, Diebenkorn's daughter said she doubts Walton's
painting is authentic, because there is no record of it in the
catalog of the painter's works.
</P>
<P>
   She said Walton had not contacted her about seeing the piece to
check if it matches her father's other works from the same period.
But Grant said she remains curious to find out if it's an
undiscovered piece.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's real ... I think that one always hopes for that,'' she
said. ``But there's another danger, that a work that isn't up to
the quality of the artist is being shown as the artist's work.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
