<SLUG> BC-GLF-GROWTH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLF'S GROWTH NUMBERS COULD BE MISLEADING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Includes 10-year growth text table.)  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the National Golf Foundation released a report late last
year, the one that in essence said the much-ballyhooed golf boom
perhaps isn't much of a boom at all, there were plenty of numbers
for industry leaders to crunch with their morning tee times.
</P>
<P>
   Approaching doom, said some, shaken out of their spikeless shoes
because the number of golfers in this country (26.4 million) and
the amount of rounds played (530 million) weren't significantly
higher than they were in 1988. Factor in the finding that said for
every golfer brought into the game, one quit, and critics felt they
had evidence of cracks in the sport's foundation. Just look at the
spiraling golf stocks, the growing cost of equipment and tee times,
the abundance of upscale courses that are impossible for beginners,
and the reality that barely more than 5 million of those who play
are termed ``avid golfers,'' they said.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the golf world, a universal chant percolated _ ``The
Three Toos, they called it, as in too expensive, too
time-consuming, too intimidating _ and it has grown loud enough so
that more and more industry people are challenging their colleagues
to open their eyes and ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Golf has burped,'' said Leigh Bader. ``For so long, people
have been so wrapped up in doing what they were doing, they forgot
why there were doing it. It's not that golf isn't healthy, it is.
OK, there are issues, but golf has always had issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only now the issues have changed and it's in our self-interest
as an industry to understand that the solution is simple.''
</P>
<P>
   From where he sits, which is in an office above a pro shop
jammed-packed with equipment at a nine-hole course he had the nerve
to think about buying 13 years ago, Bader has as meaningful a view
of the golf world as any industry CEO or blue-blazered USGA
official. Much of Bader's success is traced to a bold investment he
and partner Joe Ricci made for Pine Oaks GC in Easton, but this
innovative merchandiser said he is guided by a basic business
principal (``customer acquisition and retention'') as well as a
passionate commitment to pay off a priceless debt to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buried frozen orange juice cans in my backyard to play
miniature golf,'' said Bader. ``My father brought me my first set
of clubs and took me to the course so he could have company. We
shared a love of this game. We need to have respect for the
institution of golf, and people in the industry need to think about
the values of the game and the quality it brings to the table. Golf
builds friendships.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he warned, the sport is not doing as much as it should to
encourage new friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at private country clubs will tell you, `We have 300
people on our waiting list. I don't know what the problem is,' ''
said Bader, shaking his head. ``Hello, I tell them,'' and he makes
like he is holding out a phone, ``Wake up. Where do you think your
members are coming from?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His office may be in St. Augustine, Fla., but Joe Louis Barrow
shares a view similar to Bader's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf industry has a wonderful opportunity to grow the
game,'' said Barrow, recently named national director of The First
Tee, a collaborative of golf organizations to build courses and
driving ranges which attract new players. When the NGF report was
issued, Barrow did not dwell on stagnant figures for
player-participation, number of rounds, or equipment sales.
Instead, he saw that ``41 million people expressed an interest in
taking up the sport or in essence wanted to re-engage their
interest'' and concluded that the game needs to capture a healthy
percentage of those people.
</P>
<P>
   To do so, said Barrow, the industry needs to reshape its
thinking and spend more time ushering players into a game that
everyone agrees is extremely difficult to learn. ``We need
non-traditional golf facilities where kids are welcomed and other
beginners, too,'' said Barrow. ``In essence, shorter, friendlier
courses with not too many bunkers, geared to encourage people to
come and have fun, to learn the game before they graduate to more
conventional golf courses.''
</P>
<P>
   Though they come from diverse backgrounds and are separated by
more than a thousand miles, Bader and Barrow are united in their
passion for the game and they can hear one another clearly. Their
fathers introduced them to golf and each man considers children
crucial to the sport's future health.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a farm league for the sport,'' said Bader. ``We've
taught over 3,000 kids over the years how to play the game, about
the business, and they go from here. But not all clubs share that
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   From his national perspective _ overseeing an organization that
is just three years old, one whose stated mission is to make golf
more affordable and accessible with a strong emphasis on
introducing kids of all races and economic backgrounds to the sport
_ Barrow understands the numbers are daunting. Minorities make up
27.6 percent of the US population, but just 5 percent of the
nation's golfers. Children 12-17 account for 14.4 percent of the US
population, but just 2 percent of them are introduced to the game
each year.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the brilliant opportunity for golf,'' said Barrow.
``The norm has been for parents, a sibling, perhaps an uncle to
introduce kids to the game, but we will be able to do that now and
those kids will encourage their parents to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The First Tee, said Barrow, has achieved its first goal _ to
have 100 golf facilities opened or under development by the end of
the year _ but the true measure of the initiative will not be
measured for a few years. He judges by what he has seen, and Barrow
said more minorities are coming into the game and more people are
being exposed to the sport thanks to what are termed
``non-traditional facilities,'' from three- to six- to nine-hole
courses, to driving ranges like the one in Charleston, S.C.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just came back from the dedication,'' said Barrow. ``It's
right in the heart of an urban area. It doesn't take up that much
ground, and kids can walk to it.''
</P>
<P>
   But once they walk to it, will they stay? Numbers in the NGF
report indicate there's a 50-50 chance they won't, and no one in
the golf industry likes those odds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Retention is a huge issue,'' said Ruffin Beckwith, senior vice
president of the World Golf Foundation. ``Attracting new golfers,
recruiting them to the sport, has not been a problem. But if 3
million people take it up, 3 million people will leave it.''
</P>
<P>
   Too expensive. Too time-consuming. Too intimidating.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When he heard that the NGF report had concluded with ``The Three
Toos,'' Bader shrugged. ``I said they had a meaningful grasp of the
obvious,'' for he had witnessed this dilemma first-hand for many
years.
</P>
<P>
   Though he appreciates the purpose of the study and concedes that
it will serve ``as a calling card for the industry to wake up,''
Bader cautions his colleagues to keep things in perspective, to
remember that golf is dwarfed in size, for instance, by
recreational fishing, which, if it were a corporation would rank
13th on the Fortune 500 list of America's largest businesses with
$108 billion contributed to the economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golf equipment industry was less than just $5 billion
world-wide,'' said Bader. ``Nike is a $9 billion company. WalMart
had $160 billion in sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong. Golf is big. It's on the radar screen.
It's a pretty nice size, but I would say to those who think it's in
trouble: `How big should it be? There are 260 million people in
this country. What percentage of them should play?''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis, said Bader, shouldn't be on quantity to quench
thirsty egos, but quality to assure the game's future. ``If we
provide good golf experiences, we will cultivate committed
golfers,'' he said. ``And committed golfers should be our goal.''
</P>
<P>
   Bader hopefully will hear other industry leaders say the same
thing in November when he attends a summit meeting in Florida,
hosted by the World Golf Foundation. The purpose of the gathering
is to figure out how to tap into those 41 million people who want
to play golf, or play more than they do.
</P>
<P>
   When he's there, Bader just may draw a bunch of circles for his
colleagues. The circles represent the many different agendas people
in the industry have _ equipment-makers, private clubs, municipal
course owners, food and beverage vendors, travel agents, PGA Tour
officials, USGA executives, golf course superintendents . . . the
list goes on and as he rattles off the names, Bader assigns each a
circle.
</P>
<P>
   The groups have various interests, so the circles are all over
the paper, but ``they overlap in one area,'' said Bader as he
shaded it in.
</P>
<P>
   ``The golfer. We're all in business because of the golfer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PAR FOR THE COURSE
</P>
<P>
   (! used as column separator) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Golf participation has remained steady the past two years after a
jump in 1997 when Tiger Woods won the Masters. Participants are
defined as anyone 12 or older who played at least one round
(figures in millions): &QL; 
 &QL; 
