<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2034 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-AUTHOR-PHILLIPS-ART-B     05-11 1953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-PHILLIPS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 `MOTHERKIND' AUTHOR PHILLIPS HONORS MOTHER-DAUGHTER BOND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH P. KAHN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Toward the end of Jayne Anne Phillips's new
novel ``MotherKind,'' Kate Tateman, the book's protagonist,
momentarily slips away from the demands of caring for her newborn
baby and dying mother to think about an earlier, less encumbered
time in her life when she was footloose in India, a free spirit in
every sense of that '60s-spiked term.
</P>
<P>
   ``Success was so attainable as a Westerner tasting the exotic,''
Phillips has Kate musing, ``a temporary nun trying on spiritual
practice, a drifting, artistic traveler with no ties but aging
parents and happenstance alliances. Why not? They were all much
easier than parenthood, running a house others lived in, facing up
to the spiraling complications of intimacy with what felt to (Kate)
like a whole crowd, some of whom were blood-related to one another
but not to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``In finding her soft American life so demanding, she risked her
own contempt,'' writes Phillips, raising what some will inevitably
see as a window on the 47-year-old author's own passage into middle
age and motherhood.
</P>
<P>
   Now, drawing connections between fiction and autobiography is a
risky, often ill-informed business, as Phillips herself would be
the first to argue (and stridently so). Superficial resemblances
are sometimes that, nothing more _ and certainly not what turn
``real life'' into real art. Still, the parallels between
Phillips's own circumstances and Kate's are hard to ignore, maybe
impossible to resist.
</P>
<P>
   Like Phillips, Kate in ``MotherKind'' is a teacher and writer
who grew up in Appalachia and still locates her spiritual center
there, notwithstanding her worldy wanderings. Like Phillips, Kate,
too, has moved into a large house in the Boston area with her
future husband, a physician, and his two young sons by a previous
marriage. As with Phillips 15 years ago, the birth of Kate's first
child overlaps with the end stages of her mother's cancer, a
conjoining of intergenerational forces that throws the mundane
aspects of domesticity into cosmically sharp relief. Even Kate's
fictional neighborhood is the same one that lies just outside
Phillips's door, in the leafy hills above Brookline Village where
famous writers can pass for car-pooling moms and soccer practice
can take precedence over novel writing.
</P>
<P>
   Guarded as she usually is in answering questions about her own
family, Phillips acknowledges that her new novel closely tracks
aspects of her own not-so-long-ago life, even as she politely
discourages conversation about her children (now 15 and 11),
stepchildren, and husband, a cardiologist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say that all my work, no matter how fantastic it
seems, is autobiographical at the core,'' says Phillips, seated at
her dining room table on a sun-splashed May morning. ``I certainly
drew on a sense of being enclosed in that kind of domestic feel
when you're raising young kids. And it very much comes out of my
sense of losing my mother, 15 years ago. I feel as if I have lived
two lives since then, my self in a way very separate from that
person _ at the same time informing (Kate's) life with a lot of
details I remember or invented.''
</P>
<P>
   But, the author continues, ``The real heart of the book is the
cyclical nature of time itself and how we fit into it. The
mother-daughter bond and how it's connected to the wash of
generations. That part I would say is autobiographical, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Would it not have been just as easy, though, she is asked, to
make Kate's husband, say, a tax attorney? Or the father of two
teenage daughters? To send Kate on a pilgrimage to Machu Picchu
rather than Kathmandu, one of Phillips's former haunts?
</P>
<P>
   Phillips laughs. ``I probably should have made him a tax
attorney,'' she replies. ``And I thought about making it a family
of girls, but that would have betrayed the sense of these two
women'' _ Kate and her mother, Katherine _ ``isolated in a
mother-daughter relationship. It was important that they be
surrounded by boys because it accentuated the loss of the female
line, that matriarchal aspect of the past.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Phillips leans back in her chair. ``I remember thinking even two
to three years after my mother died that I hadn't really had time
to think about it,'' she says. ``I feel her death most keenly when
I go back home and see her friends, because they're the people who
remember her the way I remember her. So there's a funny kind of
distance about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure what I myself was trying to find in the book,''
she adds quietly. ``I'll probably think about that when the
publication is completely over with. But I was involved in editing
it, in decisions about the cover, all those things that sort of
drag on. I've been thinking about this book more as an object, you
know, than what's inside the book.''
</P>
<P>
   That will change soon, for ``MotherKind,'' to be published by
Knopf this week, once again casts Phillips as among the singular
literary voices of her generation, a writer keenly attuned to the
deep themes of her time if not to the whims of the commercial
marketplace. Since bursting upon the scene in 1979 with ``Black
Tickets,'' a widely-praised short story collection, the West
Virginia native has won plaudits for her haunting tales of
isolation and obsession, of unfashioned lives and unrealized
dreams, of small-town traditions pitted against contemporary
cultural forces. Twenty years go, Nadine Gordimer called Phillips
``the best short story writer since Eudora Welty,'' and ever since
the critical bar has been set high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Machine Dreams'' (1984), Phillips's first novel, followed the
lives of four generations of a West Virginia family from the Great
Depression to the Vietnam war. Michiko Kakutani of The New York
Times lauded it as a ``seamless, magical novel,'' and it earned a
National Book Critics Circle Award nomination. Nurtured along the
way by Seymour Lawrence, the late publishing legend, who died just
before ``Shelter'' came out, Phillips became linked to a new
generation of women writers whose ranks include Lorrie Moore,
Louise Erdrich, Mona Simpson, and Bobbie Ann Mason. It did not hurt
her public image, either, that Phillips was _ and is _ strikingly
attractive, with long brown hair, soft features, and vixenish eyes.
As one British writer put it when her last novel appeared (Phillips
has a large and loyal readership overseas), she ``looks like the
original Biba babe.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But marriage and motherhood have demanded their sacrifices of
Phillips, too. ``Fast Lanes,'' her second story collection, was
published in 1987, and ``Shelter,'' her second novel, appeared 6
years ago. In the interim, Phillips has taught fiction and
literature courses _ at Harvard, Boston University, and most
recently at Brandeis _ but she has admittedly found it hard to
juggle familial duties with classroom work and writing. Her
literary output has suffered accordingly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've tried to avoid teaching full time,'' she says, ``although
I did that for years, mostly while I was working, or rather not
working, on `Shelter.' I had a year's leave last year while I
finished this last novel.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips had intended to write ``MotherKind'' _ the title refers
to a nanny agency Kate employs, though it evokes a more univeral
concept of motherkind _ before she got to ``Shelter,'' she says,
``but I knew I wasn't ready to. And I still work very slowly. A lot
of the work is done in a very interior way, it's self-censored
before it reaches the page. Almost everything I write I end up
using, but I don't write quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   The subject of Phillips's own mother comes up. Again, the
parallels to the fictional Katherine are obvious ones. Both are, or
were, strong, well-educated women who divorced their husbands,
taught school in their respective communities, and never strayed
from the small towns where their children had been raised, or at
least until illness forced them to rethink the meaning of home and
family. Phillips's mother, like Katherine, lived with her daughter
during the last year or so of her life.
</P>
<P>
   ``My real mother?'' Phillips repeats with a breath of surprise.
``Well, she was very different from the character in the book.
There is a flavor of the way she spoke, I guess. A flavor of the
energy between her and me.'' She pauses. ``She was just a much
bigger character than the one in the book. Any time you try to base
a character on the essence of a real person, it's like the blind
man and the elephant. You only have a tiny piece.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like Katherine, Phillips goes on, her mother evinced a ``clarity
of inner strength'' during her three-year battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a very vital, very organized, very accomplished person
who could do everything,'' Phillips says. ``And everything had to
be perfectly done. She was also an incredible cook, an incredible
gardener, an incredible quilter. The first time my mother ever
sewed anything, she made herself a tailored suit. She also had a
huge group of women friends, which was typical of the place I grew
up. Families there went back for generations. They weren't living
the kind of life we would now think of. When I go back now I don't
even recognize the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what maternal qualities she shares with her mother,
Phillips hesitates. ``She didn't have to carve out time to do the
thing that she did, which is my situation'' with writing, Phillips
answers. ``I have an adjacent consciousness that works in a silent,
subconscious way while I'm dealing with getting dinner or teaching
class. Which is how artists get through the day. So in a sense her
example is a bad example for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips laughs. ``For her,'' she says, ``everything had to be
done and be done perfectly. And she was able to do that. My kids
see me as overinvolved and overprotective. My mother was big on
holidays like Christmas, and I have the same compulsion. I love old
toys, old photos, old ornaments. Something about them make me
incredibly happy. Seasonal rituals are really important to me,
because we don't have many of those now. We live in isolated
fashion, surrounded by people we're not necessarily connected to.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'd say my parenting is based on the example my mother set,
but I'm living in a completely different world,'' Phillips says.
``I'm a little bit, uh, not in synch.''
</P>
<P>
   Already embarked on her next book, Phillips says she wants to
concentrate on writing novels, not short stories, because ``all my
stories are inside my novels at this point. I want a different sort
of process now.''
</P>
<P>
   Showing a visitor her elegant backyard garden, Phillips remarks
that ``MotherKind'' is fundamentally about an idea threaded
throughout her fiction: the idea of what constitutes ``home.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As Kate's father states,'' says Phillips, ``home is not where
you live but where you come from. I'm interested in the sense of
home as a spiritual thing. Something that you carry with you from
your origins, and that there's nothing wrong with that. How you
separate from home in the same way you separate from your parents,
that paradox of presence and loss and of understanding the one
through the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Details of her home life _ what one might call ``the spiraling
complications of intimacy'' _ are less important, Phillips
suggests. ``I think it would be more interesting,'' she says with a
laugh, ``if you said I was married to a roofer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
