<HEADLINE>
GIVE YOUR GARDEN CONSTANT COLOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The yellow forsythia, the pink magnolias. So beautiful. So
brief. So finished for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Does beauty in the garden have to be so . . . temporary?
</P>
<P>
   Many yards look colorful in spring and then seem to take the
rest of the year off. If you install flowers that you like
willy-nilly, you'll probably get a May-June garden, because that's
when most plants bloom.
</P>
<P>
   It takes planning and know-how to get continuous garden color
July through September, the months when we actually spend a lot of
time outside, so we solicited tips from professional landscape
designers whose jobs involve keep clients happy year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Their tricks include: employing colored foliage; planting
annuals and tropicals; selecting plants that bloom later in the
season; pruning after the first flush of flowers to get plants to
bloom a second time; and using plants with multiple interest.
</P>
<P>
   So take heart. Thanks to the increasing availability of many new
kinds of annuals, tropical plants, and tender perennials, the
options for season-long color in the garden are radically
expanding.
</P>
<P>
   --Colored foliage: This is the favorite new tactic in the color
wars. After all, flowers don't last all season, but foliage does.
</P>
<P>
   Colored foliage was long considered in questionable taste.
Silver dusted stachys or gently variegated vinca was admissible,
but the eye-popping colored patterns on coleus leaves were regarded
as a surviving example of Victorian excess. But now coleus and
other hot-hued foliage are the rage. What changed?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, people got tired of pastels. And once they
experimented with bright colors, a wave of tropical plants too
intriguing to resist hit the market. Also, breeders introduced new
versions of old standbys, like coral bells with purple leaves. Now
there are perennials, annuals, bulbs, and shrubs with colored or
variegated leaves at every garden center.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to overdo this, however, so use such lively leaves for
accents. Most are either chartreuse or purple, compatible colors,
but they don't look great mixed with the green variegated foliage
with white margins, also popular now.
</P>
<P>
   Colored shrubs have the strongest impact and add structure to
flower gardens, but most quickly outgrow their allotted space.
Landscape designer Warren Leach of Tranquil Lake Nursery in
Rehoboth, Mass. solves this by cutting shrubs severely each year.
Since you're growing them for their foliage, you don't have to
worry about cutting off the flower buds. He recommends purple smoke
bush, and ninebark, which has chartreuse foliage all summer. His
new favorite is Ogon, a bridal wreath spirea with chartreuse
leaves, which also has white flowers in April.
</P>
<P>
   The new varieties of cannas with brilliantly striped foliage
have upstaged the green-leafed variety and beg to be planted where
they can be backlit to duplicate a summer sunset. Other popular
tender bulbs (dig them up in the fall and store them in the
basement) inlude purple-leaved dahlias such as Bishop of
Llanddaff. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Annual impact &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Annuals and tropicals: Planting annuals has been the
time-honored way to get color throughout the summer if your garden
has full sun. While perennials are the ants of the garden _
blooming briefly, then saving up energy to survive another year _
annuals are the grasshoppers, blooming all summer long with no
thought of winter. They're more work, though, because they require
replanting each May and June as well as frequent watering and
deadheading, which means removing the spent blossoms before the
plants go to seed.
</P>
<P>
   But annuals are definitely the way to go if you want a big
impact from a small garden, or want to brighten up the front rows
of larger borders. For a unified effect, avoid mixes and buy annual
flats in a single color.
</P>
<P>
   White cosmos is probably the best all-around annual. It's
graceful, goes with anything, and is good for cutting. Westwood,
Mass. landscape architect Joseph Hudak's favorites are the ones the
rabbits won't eat. So he's replaced petunias with snapdragons from
the Rocket series and cleome, which self-seeds in his garden.
</P>
<P>
   Leach also likes cheerful Lemon and Tangerine Gem Marigolds,
spreading integrifolia petunias, tall skinny Verbena bonariensis,
and heliotrope. Despite its reputation, I've never found heliotrope
from garden centers to be particularly fragrant, but Leach says
that to get a good scent, they have to be grown from cuttings, not
seed.
</P>
<P>
   Many annuals are really perennials growing too far north. More
people are using tropical perennials as annuals because they put
out blooms all season long. Salvia guaranitica is prized for its
colbalt blue flowers. Deborah Howard, who runs Howard Garden
Designs Inc. in Newton, Mass. with her architect daughter Karen,
likes Salvia splendens Van Houttei, which spreads 3 feet and is
covered with ``gorgeous blood red flowers.''
</P>
<P>
   You can also grow treasured tropicals like hibiscus or bananas
as houseplants and simply move the pot onto the patio each summer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Long-blooming perennials &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Summer bloomers: Most perennials bloom for only two to three
weeks. Long-blooming exceptions include blue Russian sage, golden
rudbeckia, and purple coneflower for summer, fall-bloom boltonia,
and various sedums, such as Autumn Joy. But it takes a giant border
to achieve all-season bloom with only perennials because you need
to include so many different kinds.
</P>
<P>
   So, many people add roses, which have the longest bloom period
of any shrub. Older types tend to be scant of bloom in high summer
unless you pick more heat-resistant varieties such as Betty Prior
and the Fairy, or the newer low-maintenance varieties such as
Carefree Beauty and Carefree Wonder. Designers also praised the
super-hardy Explorer series from Canada, particularly Henry Hudson
and Champlain and the musk single pink rose Ballerina.
</P>
<P>
   Hydrangeas are popular summer-blooming shrubs these days, but
unless you live in a warmer location like Cape Cod, pass up the
celebrated blue hortensia varieties in favor of super-hardy white
Annabell. It stays small and you can cut it down like a perennial
in the fall without sacrificing flowers.
</P>
<P>
   --Pruning: Some perennials will rebloom if they are cut back
after the first flowering. Howard cuts mauve catmint to the ground
after the stems fall open to get fresh new leaves and flowers. If
delphiniums are deadheaded, they will send up new shoots that will
flower in the fall if the old stems are cut down soon after the new
ones appear.
</P>
<P>
   Phlox is the backbone of the English summer garden, but many
people here have abandoned it because it requires a lot of water
and gets ugly mildew in our climate. However, designers are
enthusiastic about a new mildew-resistant white variety called
David. ``As with any phlox, you have to pinch back all but six
stems when it sprouts, and then pinch it as it grows to make it
bushy,'' says Howard. ``Then keep deadheading it to keep it
reblooming.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Double planting &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --Multiple interest: You need a big yard for this, since most
plants that have multiple interest are trees or shrubs like crab
apples or viburnums with spring flowers and fall berries or
foliage. A few perennials actually have brilliant fall foliage,
especially the perennial geraniums.
</P>
<P>
   You can also do double planting: Put daffodil and crocus bulbs
in the same hole with day lilies during fall planting, or combine a
summer-blooming Clematis viticella vine with a lilac.
</P>
<P>
   --A word about shade: It's a test of ingenuity to get
season-long color in shade, hence the huge popularity of impatiens.
Nicotianas are among the few other annuals that will bloom without
a lot of sunlight. Look for Nicky Hybrids' Lime Green, langsdorfii,
another classy green flower, and alata, a white species with great
evening fragrance, suggests Leach.
</P>
<P>
   Perennial red-flowering astilbes such as Federsee or Blut
(that's German for blood) have reddish leaves for extra interest.
Of course, the best foliage plants for shade are hostas, which are
available in innumerable combinations of green and chartreuse, as
well as blue-green. The new lysimachia nummularia Aurea is a ground
cover with lime-green foliage (no flowers) that provides contrast
to other greens. Emerald 'N Gold is one of several colorful
evergreen euonymus for shade.
</P>
<P>
   Hudak, whose new book is ``Design for Gardens'' (Timber Press),
finds flowering wax begonias ``very dependable.'' But he warns that
tuberous begonias ``are susceptible to meltdown. . . . Everyone
loves the flowers because it's a greenhouse-raised thing. Then they
put in it in their garden and it falls apart.''
</P>
<P>
   The more you learn, the more you'll see that the possible
combinations for season-long color are infinite.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
