<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2041 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-11 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OWNERS OF VINTAGE CARS THINK THEY CAN CLIMB THE HILL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (l and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRIFFITH  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, Vt. _ Hill climbs are a throwback to an era when
people first wanted to see if their cars could make it up the
mountain and then how fast they could make the climb.
</P>
<P>
   Thus we give you the Mount Equinox Hillclimb, an annual weekend
of vintage car racing under the auspices of the Vintage Sports Car
Club of America.
</P>
<P>
   It's an event that continues because, in the words of the club's
Karen Miller: ``Promises that were made by people who are now dead
to other people who also are now dead are being honored by their
heirs.''
</P>
<P>
   The original promises were made by the Davidson Family, who
owned the mountain, completed an unpaved road to the summit, and
built the Skyline Inn (now the Equinox Mountain Inn) in the late
1940s.
</P>
<P>
   The promises were made to the Sports Car Club of America, which
had asked permission to conduct a hill climb on the Davidsons'
road.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the event was held in various months and under
the auspices of various clubs until 1973 when it finally settled
into an early-summer event conducted by the VSCCA.
</P>
<P>
   As a vintage car event, only prewar race cars and a limited
number of rare and unusual postwar cars built before 1960 are
considered for entry. This is the other end of the hill-climbing
spectrum from the the Pikes Peak-type of all-out assaults on time
and height.
</P>
<P>
   The Davidsons bequeathed the mountain to the Carthusian Monks, a
cloistered order who have made the area their only Western
Hemisphere monastery. A business arm of the monastery, run by
mountain manager Jerry Madison, oversees the inn, toll road,
hydroelectric system (the monks have a series of seven man-made
ponds and a man-made lake), and radio tower rentals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our event continues to run at their (the monks') good
graces,'' said club editor and mountain historian Jim Donick. ``I'm
sure they have reservations about people risking their lives on
their mountain in this event, but they've been willing to continue
the tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   In general, the racers have little contact with the monks, but
there have been a few notable exceptions.
</P>
<P>
   One year, a young monk from France who had been a racer silently
watched the event with the permission of Father Prior Diamond.
</P>
<P>
   Another year, recalled Bob Girvin, event chairman for 15 years,
a young man arrived for a vocational retreat.
</P>
<P>
   The monastery was alerted and the prior came down to greet the
newcomer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their mountain and their road,'' said Girvin, and if they
wish to use the road, our event stops.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race was red-flagged while the prior came down and chatted
with the young man. Then they started back up the mountain. Our
radio spotters reported they passed the first checkpoint, then . .
. nothing. After a while, I started back up the hill and found them
stopped in the middle of the road in deep conversation absolutely
oblivious that the race was waiting on them,'' said Girvin.
</P>
<P>
   The outside world was recognized, the pair moved on, and the
race continued as it does today, the sporting equivalent of a
handshake deal.
</P>
<P>
   The event's only fatality occurred in 1956 when Paul Flickinger
pushed a little too hard in trying to break five minutes in a
prewar Maserati Grand Prix racer. The car spun into a post and his
pressurized fuel tank ruptured and spread a spray of methanol fire.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question there's an element of danger in the event
even today,'' said Donick. That applies to both the cars, which are
self-insured by the owners, and the drivers, who are covered by a
club medical policy in addition to their personal insurance.
</P>
<P>
   But, that being said, the logistics are impressive. Ambulances
and medical personnel are at various checkpoints on the 5.3-mile
climb and a radio-network of corner workers keeps virtually the
entire course under surveillance with ``chase cars'' ready to
respond if a car stops along the way.
</P>
<P>
   The entry list for last year's race read like a museum's
collection with names such as Lotus, Allard, Kurtis, Porsche,
MG-TD, Alfa-Romeo, Jaguar, Cooper, Fiat-Abarth.
</P>
<P>
   Notable among them was a 1915 Stutz Bearcat owned by Bob Reed.
It has a 450-cubic-inch, 4-cylinder, T-head engine, just like the
one that was raced successfully (11th place) at Indianapolis in
1911. Reed has driven it all over Europe and through the Alps.
</P>
<P>
   It looked sensational heading up Equinox, but it didn't make it
to the top.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too steep,'' said Reed. ``The incline was too much, even in
first gear, then it got hot and didn't want to run.''
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Carlisle's Dudley Cunningham won the King of the
Mountain title in his 1957 Lotus racer in 4:39.50, one of five
participants who broke the five-minute barrier.
</P>
<P>
   But, in this event, racers basically try to better their car's
previous fastest time to the summit because they're anything but an
evenly matched group.
</P>
<P>
   Girvin's car, for example, is a one-of-a-kind Allard coupe. The
factory made two, one Jaguar-powered that now resides in a British
museum, and his, originally owned by the duPont Family with a
393-cubic-inch Chrysler hemi engine.
</P>
<P>
   For a first-time spectator, the event was a bit of a
disappointment. Every six or seven minutes you'd hear the wonderful
sound of an engine straining up the mountain to your vantage point.
Then it would flash around a corner into view, accelerate past,
maybe slide a tad on the next corner and disappear away.
</P>
<P>
   The surprising treat?
</P>
<P>
   Watching the cars come down in groups of three and four at the
end of each run was as much a pleasure as the competitive aspect of
the climb.
</P>
<P>
   Which just goes to prove that what goes up, must come . . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
