<HEADLINE>
THE ODD MASTERMIND BEHIND WEB SATIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PATTI HARTIGAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the great things about the Internet is that it channels
the energy of some quirky folks who might otherwise spend their
time firing off letters to the editor, hunting down space aliens,
or walking down Main Street au naturel.
</P>
<P>
   Take HC, the solitary force behind www.c3f.com, a labyrinthine
site that includes ``the Net's only sorta daily satire column.''
For five years now, this esoteric individual has created twisted
commentaries that are either drop-dead funny or simply defy
explanation. The most recent offering is an animated image of Bill
Gates's head being split in two, revealing less-than cerebral
matter. On Tax Day, the site featured a California tax form with a
scrolling stock ticker tape and instructions that were, like,
totally la-la.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't your typical text-only satire, like The Onion. HC is
one of the only people out there using the technology of the
Internet to satirize news, pop culture, or whatever happens to be
bugging him. Click on the item slugged ``Earthquake Hallucinating
Rampant,'' and the screen shakes. Dig into the archives and watch
the ``1997 Year in Review Generator'' spew out wacko headlines
mixing references to Mother Theresa, Frank Gifford, and Dolly the
Sheep. The sensibility is best described as postmodern geek, like
Don DeLillo meets Max Headroom meets Mad magazine. Admittedly, it's
an acquired taste.
</P>
<P>
   So who is the mastermind of this maze? His real name is Howard
Cohen, a 39-year-old former programmer in Del Mar, Calif. He
started the site back in 1995 to sell his novel online. ``It's not
a standard novel,'' Cohen says. ``It doesn't have character and
stories and sex and violence and blah, blah, blah.'' It also
doesn't have a name that can be printed in a family newspaper; for
short, it's known as ``MFU.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first novels online, it hasn't exactly taken off,
although Cohen did get the thing published by an obscure small
press and has sold ``hundreds'' of copies. Most of the novel is
still posted on the massive site, tucked away in an elaborate
parody of the online magazine Slate.
</P>
<P>
   The satire section uses a name that is a takeoff on The
Washington Post. In the early days, Cohen called the parody The New
Times York _ until he heard from the lawyers. The cease and desist
letter from the Times is still posted on the site: It seems the
powers that be objected to the use of the slogan, ``All the news
that's fit to sell Toyotas.'' Cohen changed the name to The Street
Wall Journal, which didn't last long either. He has heard from the
Post's lawyers, but he took his chances; so far, they've let him
be. His next target would have been a local paper called The Austin
Lobe. That would have been fun.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Cohen has plenty of time on his hands. Years ago, he
made a bunch of money as a programmer, and he hasn't had to work
ever since. Instead, he spends all his time pushing the boundaries
of Web satire. ``I'm not addicted to the Web; I'm addicted to
writing and producing stuff,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   And there sure is a lot of it. The site is an endless series of
links, complete with the ``sorta daily'' stuff as well as parodies
of ancient Web sites, including the old Microsoft Network and
Time-Warner's defunct Pathfinder site. In its own bizarre way, this
self-contained universe chronicles a five-year history of pop
culture, politics, and the Internet itself.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen seems happily immersed in this world: He doesn't get out
much. In fact, he can go for weeks without leaving the house. ``I'm
a total recluse,'' he explains. ``I want to challenge J.D. Salinger
to a contest to see who is the better recluse. I think I have him
beat.'' Oh, and he also doesn't talk very much; there have been
weeks when the only word he said was ``plastic'' _ as in ``Paper or
plastic?''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, now he orders his groceries online. What about
clothes? ``I don't have to wear clothes,'' he says. ``In fact, as I
speak to you, I am utterly, absolutely naked. It's good when
Jehovah's witnesses answer the door.'' Is he kidding? Probably not.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Another Internet First!!! It's called ``Quantum Project,'' and
it's being billed as the ``first Internet feature film with an
established crew and cast.'' That may or may not be true; there are
thousands of films available online. Nevertheless, the 31-minute
film was made exclusively for distribution on the Internet and
produced by the folks who made ``What Dreams May Come.'' The film
stars Fay Masterston, Stephen Dorff, and John Cleese; Dorff plays a
physicist looking for love. For $5.95, users can download this
sci-fi romance from www.sightsound.com (which financed the $3
million film) and from www.quantumprojectthemovie.com. Download
time is expected to be 10 minutes on a broadband connection or four
hours on a low-speed modem. If the technology works and the film is
worth watching, this may be the beginning of a new era of film
distribution. (And Cohen will never have to leave the house to get
a video ever again.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1328EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
