<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0116 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2046 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      05-11 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT COMPUTER GAMES CAN'T TEACH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   E-mail from Eileen: ``I can understand why your granddaughter's
Waldorf school might de-emphasize TV, but not computer use. Don't
you want your grandchild to be prepared for the future?''
</P>
<P>
   Good question, Eileen. How can we prepare young children for the
future? I think about that every Nana Day _ my weekly time with my
grandchildren _ when Danny, 6, and I are exploding volcanoes and
Jess, 9, and I are constructing a dollhouse from a kit. We also
read, climb rocks, paint, sew, cook, and follow our curiosity. In
comparison, playing with my computer was easier and far less messy.
</P>
<P>
   Still, I gave up on educational computer games after Danny and I
built a birdhouse together. On the screen was a perfect image, but
I realized that all Danny had done to create it was click the
mouse. In every piece of software I'd purchased the images kept
changing, but the child's task remained the same _ simply more
clicking.
</P>
<P>
   The difference became all the more apparent when Danny and I
decided to build a birdhouse. The nails bent, the wood split, the
final product was a disaster by all standards but our own. Real
life demanded a higher level of competence, and it taught us what
we needed to know for our next project, a sailboat. This time we
measured more carefully. We thought twice and cut once. Danny
slammed the hammer straight down. I protected my fingers. We made
real progress.
</P>
<P>
   Television, you know, was also once considered the great
uplifter, a powerful tool for educating the masses, but we ended up
instead with a selling machine. We have a long history of
technological wonders _ I remember film strips _ which failed to
deliver the results they promised, and I'm convinced this one is no
different. There's no way a machine can teach young children what
they need to know about being human.
</P>
<P>
   I'm writing this on my old Power Mac, which is already obsolete.
It offers no clue to the state of the art 10 years from now. Young
children need to develop inner qualities that will prepare them for
what we have not yet imagined, and since computers do only what the
human mind dictates, it's crucial to develop in children qualities
needed to improve computers, not merely operate them, qualities
such as:
</P>
<P>
   --Flexibility of mind. The computer, a rigid taskmaster, allows
no room for alternative choices of effective action. The vast
majority of computer programs teach young children there is only
one right answer.
</P>
<P>
   --Trust in themselves. The computer acts as the ultimate
arbiter. In computer-based learning, the machine denies the self
any role in setting standards for satisfactory progress.
</P>
<P>
   --Creativity. Computer programs, for the most part, supply all
the ingredients. The child must select from a prepared menu and as
a result is forced to operate within the limits of the programmer's
imagination rather than discovering the dimensions of her own.
</P>
<P>
   --A range and depth of experience. Computers provide visual cues
and sounds. Children, however, are embodied creatures whose thought
processes are stimulated by all five senses. Experts agree that
learning through the manipulation of objects, physical activity,
and spontaneous play builds the complex neural circuitry needed for
later abstract thinking.
</P>
<P>
   --The motivation to learn, not merely perform. Computers are
operant-conditioning machines that use various rewards as
reinforcement. Young children learn to perform in order to see
dancing ducks or shoot trash from space, activities that diminish
the importance of the task itself. Such rewards can come to replace
personal motivation and the satisfaction of working hard to
accomplish a conscious goal.
</P>
<P>
   For a fuller examination of the computer as a learning tool, I
recommend Jane Healy's ``Failure to Connect: How Computers Affect
Our Children's Minds _ For Better and Worse'' (Touchstone).
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say that computers are not useful tools,
especially for older children with strong motivation, an ability to
focus and organize their thoughts, a capacity for sustained work,
an integrated emotional, social, and intellectual life, and a
guiding sense of values. They must bring these traits to the
computer. They cannot find them there.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who spends time with youngsters knows they are capable of
great flights of imagination and intuition, profound moral
judgments, surprising insights, powerful spiritual longings, and a
joyful receptivity to the world at large. Only other human beings
can inspire children to value and develop and rely upon these
strengths in themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Why would we ever entrust young children to a machine that lacks
them?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Linda Weltner's Web site is http://www.shore.net/weltner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
