<HEADER>
A2048 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-ORIOLES-BORDICK-A     05-11 1531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ORIOLES-BORDICK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 MIKE BORDICK IS THE MAINE MAN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WINTERPORT, Maine _ Truth be told, there aren't a lot of places
for someone to drop a dollar or two in this little town hugging the
Penobscot River a couple of Tiger Woods drives south of Bangor.
</P>
<P>
   You've got The Flower Patch, T. Tasket's Baskets, Bayside Video
Variety &AMP; Laundromat, Dean's Discount Tires, Varney Insurance
Agency, Kaler St. Music, The Drydock (``Winterport's Family
Restaurant''), and El-Hajj's Market, recently relocated to larger
quarters a few blocks south of its original location.
</P>
<P>
   And then, of course, you've got the Winterport House of Pizza,
which happens to be Ground Zero for discussion and analysis of
Winterport's official favorite sun and the only current Maine
product in the majors (and one of the few Downeasters ever). For
only at the Winterport House of Pizza is the specialty of the house
a thick Bordyburger.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, sure, proprietor Dave Wilson serves up the expected pizza,
calzones, and subs. But if you want a full Winterport experience,
you must order a Bordyburger, which, as the menu explains, ``is a
double cheesburger with savory onions, pickle slices, crisp
lettuce, and a TOP secret sauce, served with oven fries.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wilson is no front-runner. He was serving up Bordyburgers
even before Mike Bordick, his old high school running buddy,
started putting up A-Rod/Derek/Nomar numbers as the Baltimore
Orioles' starting shortstop. When a guy makes it out of Winterport,
Hampden Academy, the Bangor American Legion, and the University of
Maine to become a big league ballplayer, that's a major story in
and of itself. And never mind him becoming one of the game's great
defensive shortstops or establishing an Oriole record for April
runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   The people of Winterport have an unconditional love for their
man Mike that transcends the latest statistics. ``He is polite,
sweet and sincere,'' said Jo-Ann Barrows, a family friend who is an
administrative assistant to the school superintendent. ``He has
never stopped being friends with my kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor he has ever stopped being just plain Mike to Dave Wilson.
The two went to Hampden Academy (the regional high school serving
Hampden, Winterport, and Newburgh) and were in each other's
weddings. ``When he calls during the season,'' Wilson said, ``we
never talk about baseball. It's about families or fishing or
something like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Now if Bordick were the self-promoting sort, he'd be bragging
about the best start of a career that began with the Oakland A's in
1990. Heading into Wednesday night's game in Toronto, the
34-year-old shortstop was hitting .353 with seven homers and 32
runs batted in. To put it into perspective, his previous big league
triple crown stat highs were .300 (in 1992), 13 home runs (in '98),
and 77 (in '99).
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that the bat is a bonus. Bordick already has a
first-class reputation in every American League dugout for what he
does in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``Funny you should be asking me about Mike Bordick,'' Don Zimmer
said before Sunday's Yankees-Orioles game. ``Joe Torre and I were
sitting in the dugout the other night talking about him. He makes a
great play against us to start a double play, and I said, `They
talk about (Seattle's Alex) Rodriguez and the guy in Cleveland
(Omar Vizquel), and our guy (Derek Jeter) and your guy (Nomar
Garciaparra), and this guy plays that position as well as anybody.'
Day-in, day-out, he does a hell of a job. I don't know him at all,
but I really like him. I love watching him play. I call him
`Tough.' He is tough as nails.''
</P>
<P>
   Not an hour later, Jorge Posada hit a single up the middle,
except that Bordick made a superb play to his left and threw him
out. You could just see Zimmer giving Torre an ``I told you so''
elbow nudge in the ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Bordick is simply one of those professionals you never
have to worry about,'' said Baltimore manager Mike Hargrove. ``He
is thoroughly professional in the way he goes about his business.
He is the consummate professional. He never offers an excuse when
anything goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Who saw all this coming when Bordick was hitting .201 for the
legendary John Winkin as a freshman at the University of Maine? Who
could possibly have seen this coming when, following a great junior
year (.364), three of his teammates were drafted while his name was
never called? OK, there was somebody, but somebody with an
asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one person who always believed he would make it was his
father, Mike,'' said Barrows. ``His father was behind him the whole
way.''
</P>
<P>
   But his father couldn't get him into professional baseball. The
man who did that was Oakland scout J.P. Ricciardi, who spotted
Bordick playing for the Yarmouth/Dennis Red Sox in the Cape League,
and who took a chance on that rarest of all American species: a
position player from Maine. The state's last three noted exports to
the bigs had all been pitchers (Carlton Willey, Jim Beattie, and
fellow Black Bear Bill Swift), and whose most storied product, Old
Town's Louis Sockalexis, was born 128 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The young Bordick wasn't exactly overflowing with bravado.
``Just like any other kid, I dreamed of being in the big leagues,''
said Bordick. ``But it really didn't seem to be a realistic goal
until I had played a couple of years in the minors.''
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer isn't surprised to hear that. During his 52 years in
organized baseball he has been a frequent eyewitness as kids from
cold climes try to establish themselves in competition with the Sun
Belt set. ``I've seen these young kids from New England and they'd
be way behind the kids from California, Texas, and Florida who were
playing 40 or 50 high school games a year, as opposed to 17 or
18,'' Zimmer said. ``But sometimes all you need to do is come back
three months later to see a difference. You can't make quick
judgments on these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Maine was a high-powered program that went to
the College World Series twice while Bordick was there. But the
state of Maine is still the state of Maine and one of the great
Bordick stories concerns a four-error game against Vermont in what
could only be described as a snowstorm. A kid from Scottsdale,
Ariz., doesn't have this on his resume.
</P>
<P>
   But Bordick had great hands, for one thing, and great resolve,
for another. He soaked up knowledge from the likes of Double A
manager Tommy Reynolds and Oakland manager Tony La Russa, who
demonstrated his deep feelings for the kid shortstop in the
penultimate day of the 1992 season. Bordick had singled off Juan
Nieves and homered off James Austin to put his average at .2996,
and thus making him an official .300 hitter, but La Russa still
took him out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Recalled Bordick, ``He came up to me and said, `I had the
opportunity to hit .300 once in the minors in a similar situation,
and I didn't do it. I want you to be rewarded for a great season.'
I told him I wanted to play, but I'd do whatever he said.''
</P>
<P>
   The closest he's come to .300 since was .277 last year, but he
has rewarded La Russa's 1992 contention that there was ``hidden
pop'' in his bat with home run totals of 13 in '98 and 10 last
year. As for this year's numbers, Bordick's classic explanation is
that ``there have been a lot of guys on base for me.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, of course, The Man Who Made Cal Expendable, signing a
free agent contract in December 1996. Although he downplays the
idea of it being any big deal, his skipper begs to differ. ``There
definitely was pressure on the guy taking Cal's place at
shortstop,'' said Hargrove, who took over the Orioles this year
after nine seasons with the Indians. ``I can remember how tough it
was on Doug DeCinces when he replaced Brooks Robinson at third. We
were good friends and we talked about it all the time. Those things
aren't easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove considers himself blessed. He's got himself a
shortstop's shortstop, a guy who, as Hargrove says, ``Catches every
ball you're supposed to catch.'' As for the batting part, Hargrove
chuckles. ``Would I have expected these kind of numbers? No. But I
can tell you he was a real Indian-killer, so maybe I'm not all that
surprised,'' he said. ``What is obvious is that he's getting better
every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Full disclosure: Mike Bordick wasn't born in Maine. He lived in
Marquette, Mich., until his family moved to Winterport as he was
entering his sophomore year in high school. But he learned how to
play ball there and he feels like a Maine guy, which is all that
counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very proud of being able to represent Maine in the big
leagues,'' he said. ``I always remember something (Old Town's) Dick
McPherson used to tell me. He'd say, `People in Maine persevere.' I
think that's what I've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Just remember one thing: Out of 750 big league players (not
counting guys on the disabled list), only one comes from Maine.
That may say more about Mike Bordick than anything.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2051 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS     05-11 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARRON'S TOUCH KEEPS TECH INVESTORS IN CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cisco Systems got ``Barroned'' this week.
</P>
<P>
   Barron's, the financial newsweekly, ran a cover story on Cisco
last weekend, which argued that the stock of the high-tech giant
was way overvalued.
</P>
<P>
   The price of Cisco's stock fell Monday, and it fell again
Wednesday, even after the company reported spectacular earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Internet companies got the Barron's treatment. A cover
story that ran March 20 predicted that many dot-com companies would
run out of cash in the coming months. About a week later the
auditors for drkoop.com, an online health company cited in the
Barron's story, reported that the firm might not have enough cash
to continue as a going concern. The news triggered a tumble in
Internet stocks that has yet to end.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Barron's article appeared, the Goldman Sachs Internet
index has dropped 43 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Has Barron's singlehandedly toppled the Nasdaq? Hardly. No one
has that kind of clout. But in a series of well-timed stories the
paper has poured cold water on the hopes and dreams of technology
investors.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when a whole new class of publications has sprung up
to worship the new economy the way teen magazines worship Britney
Spears, Barron's old-fashioned, skeptical tone has had an impact.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is happy about that. On the Cisco message board on
Raging Bull, a financial Web site, disgruntled investors this week
have been taking shots at Barron's.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like the editor (of Barron's) wanted to buy some
Cisco at a bargain,'' wrote one angry investor. Added another, ``I
wouldn't get all worked up over Barron's. They are just a jealous
mag rag that missed the boat on the '90s by being bearish on the
markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron's editor Ed Finn doesn't mind the attention, but he
rejects the bear label.
</P>
<P>
   ``The word I would use to characterize our philosophy is
contrarian,'' said Finn, in a telephone interview. ``We actually
run three or four positive stories for every negative one we do.
The negative ones tend to get noticed.''
</P>
<P>
   Barron's takes a classic value approach to the stock market. It
looks at the numbers and demands to see that they add up. That kind
of thinking has been out of favor of late and, in fact, an investor
who subscribed to the value doctrine would have missed out on the
Wall Street party the past few years. Barron's lead columnist, Alan
Abelson, has probably predicted the end of the bull market at least
100 times in the last three years.
</P>
<P>
   But when it comes to technology stocks, the Barron's approach
has brought some much needed reality to a fantasy world. The
dot-com story said that at current rates of spending, many Internet
companies would burn through their money faster than most people
realized. It wasn't a brilliant observation, but the stark
presentation of the actual numbers got investors' attention.
</P>
<P>
   The Cisco piece was similarly straightforward. It pointed out
that the Cisco needs a sky-high stock price to afford all the
acquisitions it is making. It also noted that with a price/earnings
ratio of well over 100, Cisco will have to earn staggering profits
in future years to justify its stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Finn concedes that the timing of the recent pieces has been
fortuitous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is possible if we said some of these things earlier, no one
would have listened.'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barron's was somewhat premature in its criticism of Amazon.com.
Last May the publication ran a story called ``Amazon.bomb,'' which
highlighted the retailer's growing losses and its dim prospects for
ever making large profits. Amazon's stock price nearly doubled over
the next six months; it has since fallen precipitously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Amazon is trading lower today than it was when we
wrote the story,'' said Finn, with obvious pride. (He's right).
</P>
<P>
   Several money managers we spoke to were skeptical that Barron's
or any other publication really had much influence on stock prices.
``The fact is that tech stocks have been on a precarious perch for
the last six months,'' said Ned Riley, chief investment officer at
State Street Global Advisors. ``It wasn't going to take much of a
catalyst to make them change direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick Moore, a portfolio manager with Jurika &AMP; Voyles in Oakland,
Calif., says that you can usually make a lot of money betting
against what the press says, especially when it comes to technology
stocks.
</P>
<P>
   That may be so. But as journalists and Barron's fans, we'd like
to think that clear writing and clear thinking helps investors cut
through the fog.
</P>
<P>
   Finn agrees. ``No one wants to hear bad news, but sometimes
delivering it is part of our job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
