<HEADER>
A2054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-DOTCOM-REALITY-BOS &LR;      05-11 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOTCOM-REALITY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENTURE FIRMS LOOK FOR PROFITABILITY WHEN CHASING NET HOPEFULS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Did the dot-com dream really end? It sure seemed that way last
month, when once-hot Internet stocks plummeted and teary-eyed
executives begged for more cash.
</P>
<P>
   But if the recent turmoil has killed Internet aspirations, no
one told the Johansson cousins. The young founders of Inka.net
Inc., a Watertown, Mass. builder of online exchanges, are bustling
about, lining up deals _ but spending little time wooing investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still haven't had to make one investor call,'' crows
27-year-old Frans Johansson.
</P>
<P>
   Now that so many dot-com CEOs have been humbled, it's easy to
forget that cash-flush venture capital firms are still chasing
after fledgling technology firms, still looking for the next Akamai
Technologies Inc., Lycos Inc., or eBay Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Fueled by Internet investments, venture capital funding more
than tripled to $22.7 billion in the first quarter of 2000 from
just $6.2 billion in the year-earlier period, according to the
National Venture Capital Association in Arlington, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Today's financing tends to be more narrowly focused on
business-to-business Internet companies, including software and
service providers such as Inka.net. But even a few online retailers
_ considered Wednesday's news _ have received cash infusions.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Roxy.com, a Marlborough, Mass. online
retailer of consumer electronics, thumbed its nose at naysayers
when it announced it had raised $25 million. Amid market turmoil in
April, CornerHardware.com of San Francisco attracted $21 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of this money is still in the venture capital firms, and
it needs to be spent,'' said Michael Troiano, president of Primix
Solutions Inc., one of Inka.net's partners. ``The difference is
that it's not easy money. Now, they're looking for good ideas.''
</P>
<P>
   Venture capitalists say they're seeking companies that include
profitability in their business plans. They want at the helm
experienced managers whose visions include more than a
multibillion-dollar payout and a vacation house on Martha's
Vineyard.
</P>
<P>
   George McCabe, one of Inka.net's initial investors, says too
many start-ups seem to be struggling to come up with ideas to match
their money-drenched dreams. As they excitedly discuss plans to
create e-business companies in already crowded industries, McCabe
rolls his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to be an also-ran,'' said McCabe, a partner
with Pilot Ventures in New York. ``That's something that is so
pervasive today.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet hopefuls might learn a few lessons from Inka.net. The
company's owners, Frans and Christian Johansson, started two
medical companies in the 1990s before saving up enough money to
enroll in Harvard Business School in the fall of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While they were studying, their entrepreneurial instincts took
over. Soon, in the school's cafeteria, their cramped apartment, and
classrooms, they were discussing ideas for an Internet services
firm. In January, the two dropped out of school to concentrate on
Inka.net.
</P>
<P>
   The name ``Inka'' comes from the Swedish word for the Inca,
South American Indians who amassed an empire in the 15th and 16th
centuries, building a vast network of roads linking their conquered
lands.
</P>
<P>
   The Johansson cousins, whose mothers are African-American and
fathers are Swedish, spent most of their childhoods in Sweden
before moving back to the United States. Like the Inca, they hope
to connect organizations across the Web through their own ``road''
system.
</P>
<P>
   The Johanssons got a break _ and ruffled a few feathers _ when
they swiped Roland Adolfsson, a star employee with the technology
consulting firm Primix Solutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were obviously disturbed and upset,'' said Primix's
Troiano. ``But the more (Adolfsson) told us about it, the more
excited we got.''
</P>
<P>
   Primix placed Inka.net in its Internet ``hatchery,'' which gives
the Johanssons easy access to software systems integrators and
consulting services. Inka.net now shares Primix's offices in
Watertown but will leave the nest later this month for its own
offices in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Inka.net already has attracted $3 million in seed money from a
group of investors, including Pilot Ventures, Primix CEO Lennart
Mengwall, and Bill Hambrecht, chief executive of W.R. Hambrecht &AMP;
Co.
</P>
<P>
   The Johanssons say there is enough interest in their company
that they can afford to be choosy about which firms fund them in
their second round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a list of the venture capital firms,'' said
27-year-old Christian Johansson. ``We already know who we want to
talk with.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors seem to like the fact that the company builds online
trading platforms for other Web sites rather than try to compete in
the already crowded field of Internet exchanges. So its success
does not directly hinge on the success of an online business.
</P>
<P>
   Inka.net is now building an exchange that will allow members of
the Association for International Businesses to buy and sell
translation services. The pop-up exchange will be included on the
virtual organization's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The company's customers also include the New England Translators
Association.
</P>
<P>
   But even start-ups with a lot of buzz and funding face enormous
challenges. An unfriendly market for technology stocks makes it
difficult for Internet start-ups to go public. Dozens of companies
_ from Playboy.com to local Internet researcher Gomez Advisors _
have either delayed or refrained from scheduling initial public
offerings.
</P>
<P>
   The tumultuous financial markets also are making it harder for
fledgling technology companies to hire talented workers, many of
whom are heading to more established companies for regular salaries
rather than cash-equity deals.
</P>
<P>
   And when there's a good idea, there are dozens of me-too
upstarts waiting for a few million dollars in funding so they can
jump in the same marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that (Inka.net's) plan is exposed to the world, everyone
is going to duplicate what they've done,'' said Martin DeBono, an
analyst with Gomez Advisors. ``They need to get it out there
faster.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
