<HEADLINE>
WILL JUICED BALL STUDY YIELD FRUIT? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo and a graphic are being sent to NYTNS clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
888-346-9867 or 888-603-1036.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Baseballs are flying out of major league parks at a record clip
and the usual conspiracy theories are being raised.
</P>
<P>
   (itals)The ball is juiced. Mark McGwire and friends are hitting
something that looks and feels more like a Titleist HP Eclipse than
an old-time hardball.(unitals) Today's ball is wound tighter than
Tom Coughlin. It's not made by Rawlings, it's made by Wham-O
(itals)_ the company that brought us those cool Super Balls of the
1960s. It's Flubber. Or Son of Flubber.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to stifle complaints from every pitching coach and
meatball artist hurling middle relief, baseball commissioner Bud
Selig and his lieutenant, Sandy Alderson, have commissioned a
scientific study to determine if today's baseballs conform to size,
weight, and impact standards established by Major League Baseball.
The study is being conducted by Professor Jim Sherwood of the
University of Massachusetts at Lowell.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing about the ball everywhere I go,'' says Selig.
``When people say, `What about the ball?' I want every bit of
empirical data we can find as to how the baseball is produced. Is
it different or not different? I think we ought to study
everything, but I'll be surprised if it's any different.''
</P>
<P>
   Enter Dr. Sherwood, a professor of mechanical engineering.
Sherwood has a doctorate in aerospace engineering and was compiling
data on car-crash simulation before baseball commissioned him to do
some bat testing a few years ago. With Larry Fallon, a doctoral
candidate at UMass Lowell, Sherwood has been hired to dissect and
analyze the 2000 baseballs being manufactured at a Rawlings factory
in Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   Sherwood and Fallon work in a lab at the Baseball Research
Center at the university and operate one of the two bat-testing
machines in existence. Using calipers, scales, and tape measures,
they'll see if the baseballs conform to specifications.
</P>
<P>
   Don't bother sending them that foul ball you caught off the bat
of Denny Doyle in 1975. Sherwood says it's impossible to compare
today's baseballs with balls from prior seasons because performance
deteriorates as the balls age. Any ball made prior to 1999 is
probably useless for the sake of comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Sherwood says there is a specific range for the performance of a
baseball as spelled out in the rulebook. A major league ball
traveling at a speed of 100 miles per hour that hits a wall of
2-inch north white ashwood is supposed to bouce back at 57 miles
per hour. Presumably, a juiced ball will bounce back at a faster
speed.
</P>
<P>
   Big leaguers hit a record 931 home runs last month. They set
records for homers in a day (57) and a week (262). At the current
pace, major leaguers will hit 6,254 home runs this year, shattering
last year's record of 5,528. At the end of April, 22 players were
on pace to hit at least 48 homers. The record for most players with
48 or more homers in a season is five, achieved in 1996 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Conspiracy buffs note that fans love home runs and baseball
loves increased attendance and therefore, it is in the interest of
Major League Baseball to juice the ball and create more offensive
fireworks. This is the first year the ball has been stamped with a
facsimile of Selig's signature. Did the Comish order a livelier
baseball from the Costa Ricans?
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not that smart,'' says Selig. ``But fans aren't
objecting. We're 5.8 percent ahead of last year's attendance and
unless something's out of hand, fans are enjoying this. And let me
ask you, is Pedro Martinez pitching with a different baseball? It's
only been one month. Too early to get hysterical.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked with Ted Sizemore at Rawlings and he swears
there's nothing different. I think there are a lot of factors.
We've had two expansions in the '90s. Ballparks are smaller.
Hitters are clearly bigger and stronger. I'm a history buff and I
was recently watching old film of DiMaggio and Musial and I was
struck by how much bigger players are today.''
</P>
<P>
   When Selig talks about expansion he is saying what we all know:
There's too much bad pitching in the majors. Every roster has three
or four guys who are Triple A pitchers. Making matters worse is the
extinction of the high strike. If umpires would call strikes
between the belt and the letters (as the rule states), ERA's would
shrink and so would the hideous home run totals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the ball is the problem,'' says Alderson, a
Dartmouth grad (Harvard law school) who served as general manager
of the Oakland A's before joining the commissioner's office. ``The
ball is made exactly the way it was made 30 years ago, but people
seem to think these balls are made in Area 51.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today everything is oriented toward offense. Nine guys walk up
there looking for home runs. There's no anathema to striking out. I
watched Jose Canseco for a lot of years. I think he thinks of a
strikeout as sort of the flip side of a home run _ still
entertaining for fans.''
</P>
<P>
   In 30 ballparks across North America, the home runs will
continue to fly while two scientists search for the truth in their
baseball lab under a campus bookstore in Lowell, Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
