<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2056 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-HATFIELD-ART-BO     05-11 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-HATFIELD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 IF IT'S SUNDAY, THIS MUST BE WOBURN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOAN ANDERMAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWTON, Mass. _ Juliana Hatfield is dressed in black, electric
guitar slung low, performing for a rapt crowd. She's scratching out
pretty, messy chords and singing _ in the thin, sweet voice that
has become a signature of '90s indie-pop _ about love, drugs, and
hotels. It's a familiar image _ except for the neat rows of Doc
Martens on the wall behind her, and the boxed pairs of plastic pink
flamingos dangling over her head, and the sound system, which
consists of a speaker balanced on a giant, hand-shaped chair.
</P>
<P>
   While a typical musician's itinerary might include a 21-city
tour, Hatfield is on a 21-store tour. Beginning Wednesday, she hit
the road for a string of free concerts at every Newbury Comics
record store, playing three live performances a day over seven
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our 20-year history we have never attempted an undertaking
this outrageous and all-encompassing with any artist,'' said
Newbury Comics CEO Mike Dreese.
</P>
<P>
   The whirlwind New England tour leads up to Tuesday's release of
two new Juliana Hatfield CDs. ``Beautiful Creature'' is a low-key
collection of ballads and pop tunes and ``Total System Failure'' is
an aggressive rock album by Juliana's Pony, a collaboration with
drummer Zephan Courtney and Weezer bassist Mikey Welch. Her new
label, Zoe/Rounder, dreamed up ``Store Tour 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I must not have been thinking clearly, because I just said
yes,'' Hatfield confesses in the office of the Needham Street store
before the first mini-set of the day begins at 2.
</P>
<P>
   The simultaneous release of two wildly different albums is
unorthodox. Hatfield calls it self-indulgent. But it's also an
extraordinary artistic statement, a window thrown wide open on her
distinct musical voices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really just sort of happened. It wasn't planned,'' Hatfield
says. `` `Beautiful Creature' is really a bunch of demos that I'd
been working on for a period of nine months or so, with different
producers, different muscians. At the end of that, I just sort of
felt finished, and I thought that some of those songs might make a
cohesive album. And then I just had a lot of free time, so I came
up with this idea of doing a whole rock thing, really fast.''
</P>
<P>
   She says ``Total System Failure'' was motivated by the urge to
cut loose and have fun. But the result is brittle and disturbing.
``I'm only realizing this now,'' she says, ``but I think a lot of
it was inspired by Los Angeles,'' her home for seven months last
year. She wrote the songs soon after she returned to Boston, where
the Duxbury native began her career in the Blake Babies. ``This
attitude of disgust, and of being unforgiving, rubbed off on me in
that way. I mean, things don't really hit you until you're out of
them.''
</P>
<P>
   She shakes her head at the suggestion that it requires a good
bit of courage to put two versions of yourself up for public
consumption. ``It's not guts really. It's just freedom. There was
no one looking over my shoulder, critiquing me,'' she says,
referring to the fact that she wasn't signed to a label at the
time. ``So, they're just natural extensions of me.'' Zoe/Rounder
snapped up both projects after hearing them late last year.
</P>
<P>
   The 20-minute set in the shoe section draws mainly from
``Beautiful Creature,'' which for obvious reasons lends itself
better than the scathing rock songs to a solo performance. ``I'm
just gonna play a few, and you decide if you like them,'' Hatfield
says before laying into the delicate chords of ``Might Be in Love''
and ``Hotels,'' a langorous ode to her constant state of
restlessness. ``Slow Motion'' follows, a darkly quiet gem, and
``Choose Drugs,'' a deceptively titled song with a tragic refrain:
``I say it's me or drugs/You choose drugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, she receives fans behind the makeup counter for a
quick autograph-signing session. Many tell her in hushed tones that
she's awesome. Some are quite speechless, staring and smiling as
Hatfield scrawls her name on their posters and T-shirts. One young
woman asks if she can snap a photo of her in a pink tiara she's
brought along. ``Kristin Hersh wore it!'' she tells Hatfield, who
obliges.
</P>
<P>
   One show down, 20 to go.
</P>
</TEXT>
