<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2058 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-CANADA-MEDICINE-HNS &LR;      05-11 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-MEDICINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     NEW YORK SENIORS TRY TO GET AROUND THE HIGH COST OF
PRESCRIPTION DRUGS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JAMES M. ODATO   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Advocates for New York senior citizens plan to
begin organizing trips to Canada to help Medicare patients buy
cheaper medications.
</P>
<P>
   Two politically tinged trips bound for Montreal are planned for
early June by the New York Statewide Senior Action Council and
Democratic Rep. Louise Slaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Between June and the end of the year, when expansion of the
state's prescription drug subsidy program kicks in, Statewide
Senior Action is trying to arrange shorter trips to a small
Indian-run pharmacy on the Canadian side of the St. Regis Mohawk
reservation.
</P>
<P>
   The June trips, organizers say, are aimed at highlighting the
high cost of prescription drugs in the U.S. Drugs sold in Canada
can be 40 to 50 percent cheaper than those in New York, said
Michael Burgess, executive director of Statewide Senior Action.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen, which is helping to organize the June trips,
intends to invite Hillary Rodham Clinton, the Democrats' candidate
for a New York seat in the U.S. Senate, and the Republican
candidate, presumably New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani. Clinton
proposes to abolish laws that prevent cross-border purchases of
drugs by U.S. pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   The bus excursions are planned at a time when state and national
elected officials are proposing ways to end pricing inequities in
the U.S. Some citizens arrange purchases from many nations,
particularly Mexico and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led state senate this week scheduled a May 31
hearing in Albany on the drug cost issue. GOP State Sen. John
Marchi is pushing legislation that would prohibit drug companies
from selling prescription products in New York at prices above
those charged elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would create an interstate compact to deal with drug
costs and make it a felony to sell drugs at a higher price to
states in the compact.
</P>
<P>
   Burgess said he's contacted a Canadian pharmacy at the Mohawk
Reservation. But the seniors need a Canadian doctor's prescription
before buying at the Mohawk pharmacy, just like any other Canadian
pharmacy, said Gus Pike, pharmacist at the Mohawk store. He said he
needs to study whether he will take on the extra business.
</P>
<P>
   People on both sides of the border say the practice is not
widespread.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen too often,'' said Alain Vezina, a spokesman
for the Quebec health department, adding that Canadian doctors
discourage the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Vanessa Johnson, of the consumer watchdog group Public Citizen,
added that most U.S. citizens simply can't afford to go to Canada
regularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to change the law here to make it easier to get
prescriptions,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
