<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTER-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAREERPATH'S WRONG TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somewhere along the way, I've acquired a reputation as a soft
touch. The word has gone forth to a host of embattled Internet
companies: Let's get that guy in Boston to write nice things about
us. That'll do the trick.
</P>
<P>
   I suppose that's why I got a call Wednesday from CareerPath.com,
a California job-hunting Web site that's facing a likely lawsuit
from Monster.com. It's another of those intellectual property cases
that'll continue to roil the Internet until nobody owns his own
name any more.
</P>
<P>
   I've written about such cases from time to time, and I've tended
to favor the free flow of online data _ just the attitude that
CareerPath is hoping for. Besides, The New York Times Co., owner of
The Boston Globe, is an investor in CareerPath, and while such
grubby concerns aren't supposed to motivate an honest journalist,
one can always hope.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the deal. CareerPath offers a service called Resume Scout
that lets an employer check out multiple Internet resume listings
with a single search. Need to hire an expert in Visual Basic
programming to fend off the Love Bug virus? Type in ``visual
basic'' and you'll get lots of relevant resumes.
</P>
<P>
   CareerPath doesn't just search the various free resume services
on the Web. The service also works on commercial job-search sites
such as Monster.com. A company can pay $9,400 a year for access to
the Monster resume database. But if the Monster subscriber pays an
additional $200 a month to CareerPath, he can search the Monster
listings and dozens of others, all at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   Good for CareerPath and its customers, perhaps. But the people
at Monster are furious. They never gave permission for their
resumes to be listed by CareerPath, and they don't receive a dime
of compensation. Monster's lawyers have fired off a
cease-and-desist letter, demanding that CareerPath cut it out.
CareerPath vows to fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're actually helping Monster,'' says Rob Feinstein,
CareerPath's vice president of marketing. ``We're making it easier
for recruiters to utilize their multiple subscriptions.''
</P>
<P>
   Feinstein notes that his service will only provide Monster.com
resumes to users who've paid their Monster membership fee, so
they're not stealing any business. What right does Monster have to
complain?
</P>
<P>
   CareerPath compares its plight to that of Bidder's Edge. This
outfit is being sued by Internet auction house eBay, because
Bidder's Edge runs a Web site that lists auction information from
eBay, without eBay's permission. A federal judge has publicly
hinted that he's going to rule in favor of eBay, but he hasn't made
it official yet.
</P>
<P>
   He never should. I believe Bidder's Edge has every right to do
what it's doing, for two reasons. First, Bidder's Edge doesn't
charge a penny for its service, so it's not directly piggybacking
on eBay's hard work.
</P>
<P>
   Second and more important, Bidder's Edge is merely displaying
publicly available Internet data. eBay publishes its auction
listings right on the Web for all to see. Such openly published
Internet files are routinely indexed by all kinds of search
engines, which are vital to the smooth functioning of the Web. If
sites can demand payment from search services that list them, the
Web will become even more unmanageable than it is today.
</P>
<P>
   The CareerPath case is different. Monster.com's resume list is a
private database, stored on a password-protected server. The
company is surely entitled to set limits on its use, just as this
newspaper can decide who gets to reprint its articles.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, CareerPath charges $200 a month, or $2,400 a year.
Those CareerPath customers who also subscribe to Monster.com may
well have joined so they can use CareerPath's handy search feature.
Some part of the $2,400 fee is due to the availability of
Monster.com listings. These customers might want to pay less, or
might not subscribe at all, if they couldn't get access to the
Monster.com resumes. That means CareerPath is deriving some of its
revenue by tapping unbidden into someone else's database.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, guys. This won't do. CareerPath's Resume Scout is a great
idea, but it's one that piggybacks on somebody else's great idea.
And it doesn't suddenly become all right, just because it's
happening on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   CareerPath should either drop Monster from its service, or drag
out its checkbook and start paying royalties. No doubt this isn't
what the folks at CareerPath were hoping to read over their morning
corn flakes. But I can't have people thinking I've gone soft.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Hiawatha Bray is a member of the Globe staff. He can be reached by
e-mail at bray(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1340EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
