<HEADLINE>
BRINGING OUT THE WEIRD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: x stars 
By ROB LOWMAN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes it's hard to see past director Martin Scorsese's
``Raging Bull''/``Mean Streets'' image. But the New York City
filmmaker's more offbeat works, like ``After Hours'' and ``King of
Comedy,'' are interesting in ways his acknowledged masterpieces
like ``Goodfellas'' and ``Taxi Driver'' or his forays into the
religion realm _ ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' and ``Kundun'' _
aren't.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's because the few times Scorsese sheds his serious
visage, he demonstrates a sense of humor. The Farrelly brothers
(``Dumb and Dumber'') don't have to worry, though; Scorsese's idea
of humor plays off the extreme intensity of his characters. (Come
to think of it, Travis Bickle's ``You talkin' to me?'' rant in
``Taxi Driver'' is pretty funny _ in a perverse way.) The
difference, though, is that in ``After Hours'' and Scorsese's
latest, ``Bringing Out the Dead,'' the characters are not as likely
to pull out a gun and blow someone's head off. Nevertheless, what
you get are not belly laughs but uneasy chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dead,'' which hits video stores this week, is a hyperkinetic
story of ambulance driver/medic Frank Pierce (Nicolas Cage) who
works the night shift in New York City. Haunted by the ghost of a
young girl he was unable to save and trapped in his job (he can't
even get himself fired, though he repeatedly tries), he careens
through a surreal world of sirens, lights and the dead or dying,
unable to connect with anything around him, including a series of
eccentric partners played by Ving Rhames, John Goodman and Tom
Sizemore.
</P>
<P>
   Like the hapless computer programmer in ``After Hours,'' the
numbed- out Pierce's fate is randomly determined by a series of
bizarre events (or emergency calls) until he meets Mary Burke
(Patricia Arquette), whose father has suffered an apparent fatal
heart attack. Pierce suggests putting on a piece of his favored
music (Sinatra, as it turns out) to bring him back. It works, but
he's essentially a vegetable. Mary, a former junkie who's trying to
pull her life together, has trouble handling having her father in
this state, and Pierce, who's attracted to her, is conflicted over
what is the right thing to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   As dark as this all may sound, ``Dead's'' loopy gallows humor
keeps it afloat at times. Frank is affiliated with a hospital
called Our Lady of Perpetual Mercy, and inside there's a statue of
her with a neon halo. At one point, Marcus (Rhames) performs a
raising-of-the-dead ceremony on a drug-overdose victim while his
spaced-out friends gawk.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Dead'' may not be great Scorsese _ it goes down too many
dead-end avenues (pun intended) _ you can have fun along the way.
</P>
<P>
   !folo!A John Deere letter: Some people may find ``The Straight
Story'' hokey; others, heartwarming. Based on the story of
73-year-old Alvin Straight, who sets off to visit his ailing and
estranged brother, traveling more than 300 miles from Iowa to
Wisconsin aboard his lawn mower, the film is directed by _ of all
people _ David Lynch (``Blue Velvet'').
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Straight (beautifully played by Oscar nominee
Richard Farnsworth) dispenses simple gems of wisdom to folks he
encounters. To the cynical, it will seem banal. But my suggestion
is to suspend your cynicism; the trip is better than you might
think.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
``Bringing Out the Dead'' (Paramount) is priced for rental; sale
price on VHS is $106.99. The DVD is priced at $29.99 and includes a
making of documentary with interviews of the cast and crew. ``The
Straight Story'' (Disney) is priced for rental; sale price on VHS
is $103.99. There is no DVD version yet. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1355EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
