   The Hearst News Service will file the following for Friday and
Sunday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee or Eric
Rosenberg at 202-298-6920.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN POLL (Washington) _ Republican George W. Bush is making
dramatic inroads into traditional Democratic constituencies to lead
Democrat Al Gore 48 percent to 42 percent in the presidential race,
according to a bipartisan survey called The Voter.com-Battleground
2000 poll. Voters' deepening concern over values rather than
specific issues is helping Bush score gains among such usually
loyal Democratic groups as women, Catholics and union members. By
STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   SOCIAL-SECURITY (Washington) _ When George W. Bush gives his
Social Security speech Monday outlining support for private
investment accounts, one of the naysayers will be liberal economist
Dean Baker, who calls the Social Security issue a ``phony crisis.''
That's news also to mainstream Democrats, who want to use the
budget surplus to shore up the government's retirement system for
the elderly. But Baker, a Washington author and leader of a local
think tank, says that with a strong economy, the nation could
simply grow its way out projected Social Security insolvency. By
DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   Eds: Marianne Means is on vacation. Her MEANS-COLUMN will resume
next Monday, May 15, in the COMMENTARY (``k'') category.
</P>
