<SLUG> BC-JOHNSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS FROM SIERRA LEONE SCARS THE IMAGINATION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CECIL JOHNSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the atrocities committed by the butchers who rampage in
Sierra Leone under the rubric of the Revolutionary United Front,
none are more appalling than the amputations and mutilations.
</P>
<P>
   Not just arms and hands, but legs, ears and other body parts
brutally severed with axes and machetes.
</P>
<P>
   Such cruelty would violate the rules of war, even it were only
combatants who were being subjected to it. But in this case it is
civilians _ men, women and especially children who, during the nine
years of the internecine bloodletting that is the Sierra Leone
civil war, are bearing the brunt of the gruesome maiming.
</P>
<P>
   Picture a small girl with dazed, uncomprehending eyes and stumps
above her elbows. That's the poster child for the RUF.
</P>
<P>
   The maiming is believed to be a key part of the RUF's campaign
to terrorize the population and make the people eager for peace at
any price. It is the same practice that was used by the Belgians in
colonizing the Congo.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all the revulsion that the amputations elicit, they
are only the peak of the malevolence unleashed on hapless civilians
of that small part of the world where Cinque grew up, was sold into
slavery and returned to after a protracted legal battle in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   Cinque, you may remember, was the leader of the 1839 Amistad
mutiny. They made a movie about that a few years ago. He was a
member of the Mende tribe, and the Mendes constitute about 30
percent of the population of Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The Mendes are fighting on the government side of this madness,
which is not entirely to their credit, but it is far better than
killing, maiming, torturing and raping with the RUF.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the accounts of the RUF's mass killings, gang rapes of
women and prepubescent girls, abductions and torture contained in a
report on the situation in Sierra Leone issued by Human Rights
Watch defy belief.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most chilling revelations is that much of this
brutality is being meted out by children, boys as young as 10 or 12
who have been abducted, given military training, drugged and forced
to fight.
</P>
<P>
   Children killing and maiming other children. Children beating
and shooting people old enough to be their grandparents. Children
deprived of the opportunity to develop a sense of right and wrong
or any appreciation of the value of life. Children used as cannon
fodder for their brutal commanders.
</P>
<P>
   Some of those interviewed by Human Rights Watch described the
young boys among the rebels as some of the most vicious killers.
</P>
<P>
   Although the greater atrocities have been committed by the
rebels, the government forces have not been blameless. They, too,
have been guilty of on-the-spot executions of captured rebels and
collateral killings of civilians, who often have been used as human
shields. So have the Nigerian-led peacekeeping forces of the
Economic Community of West African States, a.k.a. ECOMOG.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the RUF, which attracted support in 1991 by promising
to rid the country of the corrupt and venal government in the
capital of Freetown, that has turned into the people's worst enemy.
</P>
<P>
   The autocratic government was corrupt, concerned more about
enriching itself off of Sierra Leone's minerals, primarily
diamonds, with little care for the people. But the RUF, led by
former army Cpl. Foday Sankoh and Gen. Sam Bockarie, has never
offered any real change for the people. They are backed and
supplied by the leaders of Liberia, Burkina Faso and Libya who are
paid in diamonds by the rebels and who covet Sierra Leone's diamond
mines.
</P>
<P>
   Mercenaries from those countries and even Ukraine are said to be
involved in the fighting on the rebel side.
</P>
<P>
   The whole nightmare in which so many have suffered, lost limbs
and died is just about greed. It is as simple as that. Sierra Leone
has the mineral resources to be a prosperous country. But because
of the greed of a few on both sides of the war, it is the world's
poorest.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the shaky cease-fire cobbled together last year has
come apart, another orgy of death, destruction and mayhem is
beginning. Only the insertion by the international community of
enough forces to overwhelm the RUF can stop the barbarity.
</P>
<P>
   But that appears unlikely because the Western powers no longer
see that they have any vital interests in places like Sierra Leone
now that the Cold War has ended. It would be next to impossible to
convince the American public that there is any reason to put the
lives of American troops at risk in such a place, although
humanitarian concern should be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a columnist and editorial writer for the Fort
Worth Star-Telegram. You can reach him at
cecil(at)star-telegram.com or (817) 390-7663. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
