<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HBO'S DRUG SERIES HITS HOME FOR FAMILY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A nasty 2-inch scar snakes down Kelly's right cheek, the work of
a woman wielding a butcher knife that would have taken an eye had
she not seen it coming. The woman was too high and too desperate
and too strong to stop, and, besides, Kelly (not her real name) was
merely trying to save them both.
</P>
<P>
   Four years after her mother attacked her in their living room,
knocking her over a couch and a table, through a door and a window,
specks of Kelly's blood are still in the carpet they can't afford
to replace, a daily reminder of what was and what can be.
</P>
<P>
   Two drug rehabs have made Kelly's mother a different woman, they
both acknowledge with bowed, nodding heads, and, who knows, perhaps
they believe it. Drug addiction is a disease that ravages the body
and the mind and the soul and leaves little to rehab anyhow.
</P>
<P>
   So the woman who bore the child now bears the burden of having
tried to sell her flesh and blood for the instant gratification of
the drug life that was really no life at all.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly and her mother are in the living room, in the dark, on the
couch, watching a tape of an HBO series about the drug life Kelly
knows firsthand. She'd called days earlier wondering about the
series, wondering if it was her life.
</P>
<P>
   About 45 minutes into the first hour of the show, she begins to
sob lightly, reminded in painful detail what drugs can do to a
family.
</P>
<P>
   HBO's ``The Corner,'' which ends its five-Sunday run May 21, was
said to be too real and too painful and too depressing for
audiences, and perhaps that's so. Praised by most who have seen it,
the series is unflinching in its depiction of drug users as
everyday folk who simply got caught up in the life and couldn't get
out. It has failed to capture the ``wow'' factor of another HBO
offering, the mob series ``The Sopranos,'' even though its nuance
is just as sharp, its characterizations just as unsettlingly real.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, for one, can't get enough of the series. She relates
heavily to the teen-age character in the series, a young man living
in a world of contradictions, a victim of his parents' misdirection
into the drug life.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, Kelly, her older sister, mother and father lived
in a comfortable three-bedroom home in east Fort Worth, taking
walks and bike rides to a park on Saturdays, attending church on
Sundays, making sure each evening dinner was one they ate together.
No phone, no company, no TV. All that changed when her sister
drowned while away at a summer camp. Mother and father, strained
and pained, fought constantly and drank incessantly. Dad left, Mom
headed back to work, and Kelly found herself growing up fast.
</P>
<P>
   Life was hard, and it took its toll. Kelly remembers hearing the
nervous voice of her mother discussing by phone which corners to
cut to make the mortgage. But there were never enough corners. They
ended up in this small two-bedroom apartment in a world where
Kelly, now 18, must look into the worried eyes of men and women
with no place to go, nothing to do, little to say. This is, Kelly
says, ``my corner.''
</P>
<P>
   When home from her retail job at a shopping mall, she spends
most of her time looking out her window, watching people crisscross
the streets, selling drugs, drinking liquor, getting into
never-ending arguments and fistfights. She hears the beeping of a
forklift moving pallets of donated food, the bouncing of a
basketball on the hard concrete, and, sometimes, the clatter of a
police helicopter overhead. All the while, she dreams.
</P>
<P>
   For Kelly's mother, who quit her job as a nurse's aide and is
now on welfare, alcohol numbed the pain, and drugs numbed her life.
She remembers coming home in the middle of the night tearing apart
the house in search of drug cash. Kelly's scar came that night as
she refused, this time, to get out of the way and let things be.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Kelly has been sharing her bedroom with 10-year-old
twin cousins whose mother is now in rehab, their father locked away
in prison. Kelly is proud that they talked the cousin into getting
help and that her sons will be safe.
</P>
<P>
   Hanging on the wall above her bed is a poster of the cast from
``Beverly Hills, 90210,'' which is surrounded by a sea of posters
and pictures of hip-hop stars and a small one of Malcolm X.
</P>
<P>
   She wants to know if ``The Corner'' has a poster, and she's told
it does. She looks at the ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' poster and
slowly removes it.
</P>
<P>
   Watching from the doorway is her mother, who nods, and smiles,
her eyes swelling like a dam about to burst.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be OK if I'm OK,'' she says. ``She'll be OK if I'm
OK.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at(817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1414EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2085 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-HAMLET-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-11 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAMLET-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NOT_SO_GREAT DANE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 1/2 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To like or not to like the new movie ``Hamlet''?
</P>
<P>
   The filmmakers don't let you answer that question easily. There
are a lot of clever ideas in this New York update of Shakespeare's
classic tragedy, but just as many of them are simply strained
attempts to play out the concept. The verse sounds good coming out
of uniformly contemporary, American mouths, yet few of the
performances crackle or connect. The thing is self-consciously
cinematic to such a degree that no one's going to accuse it of
being a filmed play; but then, Laurence Olivier's simpler, noirish
1948 production was every bit a movie, and without having to call
attention to the fact every two minutes.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes? No? Up? Down?
</P>
<P>
   I just can't make up my mind.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, Hamlet is a wild-haired, stubble-chinned,
film-student slacker played by _ who else? _ Ethan Hawke. His
uncle, Claudius (Kyle MacLachlan), and mother, Gertrude (Diane
Venora), now run his dead father's Denmark Corporation, a big
multinational something-or-other with vast media interests.
</P>
<P>
   It's doubtful, however, that Denmark's media interests surpass
those of adapter-director Michael Almereyda, who gets some kind of
extra-textual video footage or electronic gadget into just about
every scene.
</P>
<P>
   This is pretty good stuff, for a while.
</P>
<P>
   The Ghost (Sam Shepard, who quite chillingly emphasizes the
demanding father aspect over the supernatural take) first
materializes through a high-rise security camera. Hamlet, who
spends days going over wild tape footage while nursing his
indecision, splices together an accusatory short film in place of
the famous play-within-the-play. Polonius (Bill Murray, of all
people, giving the movie's best performance, a deft high-wire walk
between the buffoonish and concerned parent interpretations of the
role) wires Ophelia (Julia Stiles, pouty throughout) for the big
betrayal scene.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all, Hamlet recites the soliloquy while trudging up the
``Action'' aisle at a Blockbuster store. But whether or not this
monotonous kid decides to take up arms remains academic, since
Hawke's performance isn't exactly the soul of wit. He gives the
role an apt youthful inertia, but it's the kind of right artistic
strategy that really doesn't come off well in practice.
</P>
<P>
   You'll probably wish this 21st-century Hamlet will make his
moves sooner than most previous incarnations, if only to cut short
the droning. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Hamlet'' (R; violence). &QL; 
The stars: Ethan Hawke, Kyle MacLachlan, Sam Shepard, Diane Venora,
Bill Murray, Liev Schreiber, Julia Stiles. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Michael Almereyda, based
on William Shakespeare's play. Produced by Andrew Fierberg and Amy
Hobby. Released by Miramax Films. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 52 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2086 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BATTLEFIELD-EARTH-REV     05-11 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BATTLEFIELD-EARTH-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALACTICALLY BAD
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Battlefield Earth'' is a movie that's so bad on so many
different levels that ... dare we say ... it's almost entertaining.
This isn't just stupid-bad like ``Wild Wild West'' or ``Inspector
Gadget.'' This is ``Showgirls'' bad, the kind of unintentionally
camp movie that will play for years to come as an example of
Hollywood filmmaking at its most fatuous.
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. Buy a ticket for this mess, and you'll be
sorry. ``Battlefield Earth'' is a shrill, hollow and unintelligible
movie with no redeeming value whatsoever aside from watching John
Travolta ham it up as an evil alien who looks like a Rastafarian
Michelin Man with Klingon colorings. (Dig the KISS platform boots,
too, John.)
</P>
<P>
   Travolta's career will survive this catastrophe. The same can't
be said for director Roger Christian, a George Lucas collaborator,
who, judging from all the tilted camera angles, watched one too
many episodes of the old ``Batman'' television series before
undertaking this project. Not only that, but Christian botches
nearly every action sequence in the movie, rendering each set piece
dull, incoherent and pointless.
</P>
<P>
   ``Battlefield Earth,'' for the uninitiated, is based on L. Ron
Hubbard's mammoth science-fiction potboiler about a group of brave,
beleaguered human outcasts who dare to take on their towering alien
overlords, the dreadlocked Psychlos. The action takes place in A.D.
3000, centuries after the Psychlos conquered the planet (apparently
it took all of nine minutes) and, now they're just hanging around
to strip mine all the minerals. (Why such an advanced alien race
would place a high value on gold is one of a myriad of questions
best left unasked.)
</P>
<P>
   Most of the action takes place at the Psychlos' headquarters
where the head of security, Terl (Travolta), plots to exploit the
humans so he can acquire a stash of gold and beat a path back to
his home planet. Terl, however, doesn't count on the
resourcefulness of Jonnie Goodboy Tyler (Barry Pepper), who learns
of the Psychlo ways through a knowledge zapper (again, don't ask)
and begins to apply Euclidean geometry to the task of overthrowing
his tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's stupidity is on such a grand scale that there simply
isn't enough space to list all the asinine moments. But permit me
to name a few: Terl randomly handing Jonnie Goodboy a book in
Denver's public library (looking pretty good after 1,000 years of
neglect), challenging him to find something in it that will help
him win his freedom. Jonnie Goodboy blows the dust off the book and
it's ... the Declaration of Independence!
</P>
<P>
   There's also the time when the film's lone human female
(Travolta's wife, Kelly Preston, has a cameo as a Psychlo with an
immense tongue) tells Jonnie Goodboy: ``I really don't believe in
fate. But I always knew this was your destiny.'' And, yes, she was
quivering in her buckskin costume when she said this.
</P>
<P>
   Travolta shamelessly throws himself into Terl, and, actually, is
intentionally quite funny in several scenes, usually the ones
involving his conviction that humans love to eat rats. Typically,
however, his broad performance suggests a certain fondness for
``Austin Powers''' Dr. Evil, and the filmmakers clearly missed a
golden opportunity to create a Mini-Terl sidekick. (The thankless
henchman role, instead, went to Forest Whitaker, who should fire
his agent.)
</P>
<P>
   Coming as it does from Hubbard, some have suggested
``Battlefield Earth'' could be a subliminal recruiting tool for the
author's Scientology sect. But if the filmmakers couldn't get the
obvious storytelling bits right, they'd be sorely challenged to
deliver a convincing subtext. If a sequel, as rumored, is planned,
perhaps we can request some subliminal snack-bar messages.
Beleaguered humans deserve a break, too.
</P>
<P>
   Hold the rat, though.
</P>
<P>
   _____ &QL; 
The film: ``Battlefield Earth'' (PG-13; intense sci-fi action). &QL; 
!bbox!The stars: John Travolta, Barry Pepper, Forest Whitaker. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Roger Christian. Screenplay by Corey
Mandell, based on the novel by L. Ron Hubbard. Released by Warner
Bros. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 57 minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
