<HEADER>
A2088 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-BOSSA-NOVA-REVIEW-LAD     05-11 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSSA-NOVA-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOVING TO A DIFFERENT BEAT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 2 stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Bossa Nova'' is a soundtrack in search of a movie. Brazilian
director Bruno Barreto's wispy valentine to Rio de Janeiro
percolates to the sultry and subtle rhythms of Antonio Carlos
Jobim's bossa nova music, but apart from the songs and the scenery,
there just isn't much here to hold your interest.
</P>
<P>
   Barreto, working from a screenplay by Alexandre Machado and
Fernanda Young, aims to capture the same kind of beautiful
melancholia that was a hallmark of Jobim's music. (Think
``Getz/Gilberto,'' particularly ``Corcovado.'') And there are
moments when the movie captures a certain ethereal magic, only to
have it dissolve through the story's rather earthbound plot
machinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bossa Nova'' allows us glimpses of the wounded hearts of
several Rio residents. Chief among them are an expatriate American,
Mary Ann (Amy Irving, Barreto's wife), who hasn't recovered from
her husband's drowning death, and Pedro Paulo (Antonio Fagundes), a
suave attorney still hurting from his wife's infidelities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bossa Nova'' intertwines their cautious romance with other
storylines. Mary Ann, an English teacher, schools a Brazilian
soccer star (Alexandre Borges), although he's more interested in
learning the language of love. A beautiful intern in Pedro's
office, Sharon (Giovanna Antonelli), captivates Pedro's mopey
half-brother (Pedro Cardoso). Pedro's father (Alberto de Mendoza),
an expert tailor, frets about losing his lifelong business in a
nasty divorce. Mary Ann's friend, Nadine (Drica Morales), conducts
a romance over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   These stories intersect in a frenetic finale that's unconvincing
because the movie has never invested much time in explaining its
characters. Barreto blithely assumes that Jobim's music and Pascal
Rabaud's gorgeous cinematography of a postcard-perfect Rio will be
enough to make you overlook the story's deficiencies. But the mood
simply isn't that intoxicating, and, left sober, the viewer is
clear-headed enough to mull over the movie, warts and all.
</P>
<P>
   The soundtrack, however, is an excellent investment. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The film: ``Bossa Nova'' (R; for language and some sexual
content). &QL; 
The stars: Amy Irving, Antonio Fagundes. &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Directed by Bruno Barreto. Screenplay by
Alexandre Machado and Fernanda Young. Released by Sony Pictures
Classics. &QL; 
Running time: One hour, 35 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
