<P>
   REBEL-FLAG _COLUMBIA, S.C. _ The Confederate battle flag is on
its way down in South Carolina. That means a full-fledged fight in
Georgia is not far behind. The vote by the South Carolina House
will only heat up debate in Georgia, where Democrats are trying to
keep a lid on the issue through the November elections. (Manuel,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   METHODISTS _ CLEVELAND _ Daily coverage, as merits, of United
Methodist General Conference in Cleveland. Issues coming up this
week are same-sex blessing, a new TV ad campaign to rival the
Mormons, legislation apologizing for the denomination's past racism
and trying to raise a huge amount of money for historically black
Methodist colleges that include Clark Atlanta U., some
denominational reorganization, and possible resolutions on Elian
and gun control, to name a few. (GWhite, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (a) General News and (l) Lifestyle categories.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-HICOURT _ Texas Supreme Court issues a ruling in a lawsuit
that challenged the Waco school district's groundbreaking retention
policy, which holds back students who fail the state mandated TAAS
test. Court upheld lower court ruling favoring the school
district's policy but remanded to the lower court a portion of the
lawsuit that questioned if the district violated the Open Meetings
Act in deciding on the policy. By Martha Ashe. File mugs available.
(Waco Tribune-Herald),
</P>
<P>
   ATTN: Texas Editors.
