<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   GORE-LIKEABLE _ WASHINGTON _ Why does Al Gore trail George W.
Bush in most opinion polls, despite the advantages of peace,
prosperity and incumbency? Polling data show that one big reason is
that voters don't seem to like him as a person. (Shepard, Cox News
Service). 25.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
</P>
<P>
   HAMILTON-JORDAN _ Twenty years ago, Hamilton Jordan was the
gatekeeper who controlled access to the most powerful man in the
country, a brash newcomer to Washington who moonlighted as
Georgetown's most notorious pubcrawler. Today, former President
Carter's chief-of-staff has no power than any other Little League
assistant coach. Between one life and another, he went through a
divorce, has survived cancer three times, run for the U.S. Senate
and lost, and gone from a thirtyish Beltway climber to a sedate
middle-aged father of three young children. In his book ``No Such
Thing As a Bad Day,'' Jordan reflects on the bumps in the road and
what he's learned in a life out of the public eye. We profile
Jordan at 55, a political has-been who believes he's never been
more alive. (Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 45.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in (p) Politics and (l) Lifestyle cateories.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 6
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
