<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, May 12:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-AFRICA (United Nations) _ The Security Council on Thursday
will discuss the Ethiopia-Eritrea conflict and other possible
African wars as the council delegation returns after a weeklong
trip to Africa, where it had intended to deal with only one war, in
Congo. Council members are dismayed that new generation of African
leaders _ presidents of Uganda, Rwanda, Ethiopia and Eritrea _ seem
to be falling into old patterns. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-LEONE (Freetown) _ Developments in the crisis between
U.N. peacekeeping troops and rebels in Sierra Leone: six Kenyan
peacekeepers who escaped from the rebels were mistakenly injured by
Sierra Leone government soldiers Thursday. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUGS (Paris) _ Five major pharmaceutical companies agreed
Thursday to slash the cost of drugs for treating AIDS in Africa and
other developing countries, the United Nations announced. By Donald
G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MEDIA (Moscow) _ Armed men wearing black masks and
identifying themselves as tax inspectors on Thursday searched the
headquarters of Media-Most, a media group whose NTV television
station, Echo radio and Segodnya newspaper have often been critical
of the Kremlin. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Chechen rebels ambushed a Russian
convoy in Ingushetia Thursday, killing several soldiers. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-COURT (Jerusalem) _ The Israeli Supreme Court on Thursday
overturned a lower court decision that had granted early release to
an Israeli settler who killed a Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-UNREST (Dateline to come) _ Developing: U.S. peacekeeping
troops were attacked by Serbs in two incidents late Wednesday, and
on Thursday Albanians gathered near Prizren for the funeral of a
slain KLA leader. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-CHINA-ARMS (Washington) _ The U.S. reaction to China's
suggestion that it would increase its nuclear arms if the United
States builds a proposed antimissile defense shield. By Jane
Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GENERAL-SEX-CHARGES (Washington) _ Developments in the Pentagon
sexual harassment case. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-FOR-LAND (Washington) _ The House is to vote Thursday on a
huge environmental bill, one that would devote some oil-drilling
royalties to land purchases and other steps that protect sensitive
areas from future development. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-FORECAST (Washington) _ Government forecasters said
Thursday that they expect an above average hurricane season this
year because of La Nina. They are also saying that La Nina is
worsening the drought conditions in the Midwest and the South.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Atlanta) _ Aggressively questioning both sides, three
federal appeals judges asked today whether 6-year-old Elian
Gonzalez is too young to apply for asylum and whether being from
communist Cuba compromises his father's parental rights. Judge J.L.
Edmondson, a Reagan appointee expressed concern that the boy would
be sent back to a Communist country. But in an unusual move, he
appeared in court before the hearing began and cautioned the
audience not to read anything into his questions and statements
from the bench. Judge Charles Wilson, a Clinton appointee, asked
how Elian could apply for asylum if he was to young to even write
his own name. Judge Edmondson also said a ruling would probably
come in ``weeks.'' By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT2,3.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ Fire threatens the Los
Alamos lab and the adjacent town. By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-DECISION (Santa Fe, N.M.) _ The fire began as a
controlled burn to prevent a forest fire. There are reports that
the weather service told the parks service before the blaze was set
that high winds and hot dry conditions were in store. What goes
into the decision to set such a fire and what are the issues around
it. By George Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-DEFAMATION-SUIT (Denver) _ What began as a dispute over the
behavior of pet dogs has escalated into the biggest legal threat
ever to hit the Anti-Defamation League, a $10.5 million jury
verdict against the organization for comments that its Denver-area
director made defending a Jewish couple who claimed their Catholic
neighbors were anti-Semitic conspirators, plotting to harm them and
their children. The case, now on appeal, raises issues of privacy,
defamation and the purpose of the ADL. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   SC-FLAG (Columbia, S.C.) _ South Carolina now has a plan to
remove the Confederate battle flag from the statehouse dome, a
Martin Luther King holiday and the start of an African-American
memorial. All have been approved in the face of opposition from the
NAACP. So will the continued economic boycott have any effect in
the face of all these state actions? By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   MAINE-DRUGS (Boston) _ The Maine legislature is expected to pass
a compromise bill Thursday that waters down an earlier measure
imposing the country's first state-fixed price ceilings on drugs as
of 2001, but still threatens the pharmaceutical industry with such
price controls as of 2003. The bill effectively turns the state
into one giant pharmacy benefits manager for Maine's 325,000
residents without insurance. It has been endorsed by Maine Gov.
Angus King, who was expected to sign it as soon as it was passed By
Carey Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-PLANT-POLLUTION (Albany, N.Y.) _ The EPA is releasing for
the first time a detailed tally of all the toxic chemicals released
from power plants across the country. Significant because it adds
to the picture of what is leaving the country's dirtiest power
plants, in the South and Midwest, and wafting in the wind over New
York and other eastern states. By Winnie Hu.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NEW YORK &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI (New York) _ Folo on the furor involving Mayor Rudy
Giuliani's announcement that he is separating from his wife, and
her statements regarding the history of their marriage. And a look
at its political implications. By Elizabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   With photos, NYT5,6.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-REACT (New York) _ Reactions from all over to the
Giuliani developments. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   EGAN-ARCHBISHOP (New York) _ The Vatican has appointed the
bishop of Bridgeport, Conn., Edward Egan, as the new archbishop of
New York. He succeeds Cardinal John O'Connor, whose funeral was
held on Monday. By Diana Jean Schemo.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
