<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-FED (Washington) _ In 1994, when the conventional wisdom
held that inflation was all but inevitable if the economy grew more
than 2.25 percent a year or unemployment fell much below 6 percent,
Alan Greenspan posed a provocative question to his colleagues at
the Federal Reserve. ``Is it automatically the case,'' Greenspan
asked, ``that when the economy is tightening up that inflation
takes hold?'' He did not have an answer at the time. But such early
musings stimulated considerable debate within the Fed, and
ultimately led the central bank in effect to suspend the old rules
about the relationship between growth, unemployment and inflation.
Judging that rapid advances in technology were making businesses
and workers more productive in ways that tempered upward pressure
on prices, the Fed instead gave the economy more or less free rein
to find its own limits. It may now have found them. By Richard W.
Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-SUVS (Atlanta) _ In an extraordinary admission by a large
corporation, Ford Motor says it has concerns about the effect of
sports utility vehicles on the environment and on road safety. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   With photos from Cox, our partner.
</P>
<P>
   PENNEY-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ J.C. Penney, whose stock market value
has dropped by $15 billion in the last two years, is now the
subject of much takeover speculation. Last week, its chief
executive announced that he would resign amid slumping sales and
earnings. And Carl Icahn has disclosed that he is buying a stake in
the company. Penney's hopes are pinned for the most part on Vanessa
Castagna, its new merchandising chief, who came from Wal-Mart. Can
she deliver the Wal-Mart touch to a chain of department stores? By
Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Both Microsoft and the
government draw on lessons learned from the AT&AMP;T case to justify
their points of view. The record is at variance with both sides'
statements. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   ILOVEYOU-VIRUS (Manila) _ Onel de Guzman, a 23-year-old computer
scientist who has been identified by officials as the source of the
``I love you `` virus, tells reporters that it is possible that he
may unleashed the virus by accident. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ The weekly column. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Stocks were higher in early trading. In late
morning, the Dow Jones industrial average was up 1.37 percent, the
S&AMP;P 500 up 1.70 percent and the Nasdaq composite index up 2.95
percent. Treasury prices were lower. By Robert D. Hershey Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DELL-EARNINGS (Undated) _ Dell Computer reports first-quarter
earnings after the stock market closes. The forecast is for 16
cents a share and revenue of $7.1 billion. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
