<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2104 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-ART-(TRIMS)     05-11 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN GONZALEZ CASE PRESENTED TO ATLANTA COURT 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT2, NYT3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase individual rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By EDWARD WONG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a long-awaited legal showdown in the custody battle over
Elian Gonzalez, lawyers for the two sides of the boy's family, as
well as those for the U.S. government, argued their cases in an
Atlanta federal court Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers distilled five months of an international struggle
that has embroiled two governments, thousands of Cuban-Americans
and a family bitterly divided by politics to an hour-and-a-half of
legal arguments at the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   As more than 100 supporters chanted and waved banners outside
the courthouse, lawyers for Elian's Miami relatives tried to
persuade a three-judge panel to make the Immigration and
Naturalization Service grant the 6-year-old boy an asylum hearing.
But Elian's father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez, and the U.S. Justice
Department believe the boy should be returned promptly to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Several months ago, the immigration agency returned Elian's
asylum application to his Miami relatives without reading it,
saying that only the boy's father could speak for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bond between a parent and his child is not only recognized
in our constitutional order, but is recognized throughout the
world,'' James Castello, a lawyer for the government, said in a
news conference following the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   But in an earlier ruling, the judges in this case indicated that
immigration laws do not set a minimum age for an asylum applicant.
The relevant statute says that ``any alien'' may apply for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   In the courtroom, lawyers for the Miami relatives repeatedly
stressed that point. They also argued that the Cuban government
would persecute Elian because the boy's mother had fled the
country.
</P>
<P>
   But Gregory Craig, the lawyer for Juan Miguel Gonzalez, said the
ongoing custody battle has taken a heavy toll on Elian's family,
and that the boy's asylum application cannot be taken seriously
because a 6-year-old is too young to hold informed political
beliefs. Many child psychologists have agreed with that point.
</P>
<P>
   ``This family is in jeopardy of being destroyed if this case
goes on much longer,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The judges threw pointed questions at both sides. They asked
government lawyers what would have happened if Elian's mother had
survived, or if she had been a woman who died trying to cross from
East Berlin to West Berlin during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, the government lawyers said, the child should
still be reunited with his father.
</P>
<P>
   The judges also asked Craig whether the fact that Elian's father
is living under a communist government compromises his abilities to
be a parent.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been free to express openly his feelings and his
opinions throughout,'' Craig said.
</P>
<P>
   The judges grilled the lawyers for the Miami relatives about
whether Elian understood the contents and gravity of his asylum
application. The lawyers insisted that the boy knows he does not
want to return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Lazaro Gonzalez and Marisleysis Gonzalez, Elian's great-uncle
and cousin, arrived at the gray stone courthouse in downtown
Atlanta at 8 a.m., one hour before arguments were scheduled to
begin, according to The Associated Press. They were greeted by
cheering supporters waving both Cuban and U.S. flags and carrying
placards with slogans like ``Give Elian His Day in Court.'' Like
thousands of Cuban-Americans, the Miami relatives do not want to
see the boy returned to a communist nation headed by President
Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, the lawyer representing Elian's father, strode into the
courthouse to the jeers of Cuban-American protesters. His client,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   Elian is staying with his father, stepmother, 6-month-old
stepbrother, several former schoolmates and a teacher at a
farmhouse on the 1,100-acre Wye River conference center, which the
government had used for Middle East peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The father and son were re-united on April 22 after Attorney
General Janet Reno ordered a pre-dawn raid on the home of Elian's
Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The two were separated since last November, when Elian's mother,
Elizabet Brotons, took him on a smuggling boat in an ill-fated
attempt to reach the United States. When the vessel capsized,
Brotons and 10 other Cubans drowned. But Elian was discovered on
Nov. 25 clinging to an inner-tube off the Florida coast.
</P>
<P>
   The boy was given ``parole'' status by the Immigration and
Naturalization Service and placed in the custody of Lazaro Gonzalez
in Miami. Days before the raid, Lazaro Gonzalez defied government
orders to hand over the boy, hoping to stall federal officials
until the Atlanta court could decide on the asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The court's three-judge panel, made up of Judges J.L. Edmondson,
Joel A. Dubin and Charles R. Wilson, is to expedite their decision
and announce it within two or three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   If the Atlanta court sides with the boy's father, lawyers for
the Miami relatives have 45 days to ask all 12 judges of the
federal court to hear the case. If the court denies that request,
the lawyers have 90 days to appeal to the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Atlanta court does force the INS to look at the
boy's application, legal experts say there is little chance the
agency will grant asylum to Elian. Successful asylum seekers must
prove that they have been persecuted or that they have a
``well-found fear'' of persecution if they return to their
homeland. So far, experts say, there is no evidence that Elian
would meet those standards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
