<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-LOVE-BUG-HNS &LR;      05-11 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOVE-BUG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     THE LOVE BUG IS THE COST OF DOING BUSINESS ON THE NET 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The so-called ``Love Bug'' computer virus has been largely tamed
_ downgraded from a hurricane to a tropical depression _ but it has
left plenty of fear and loathing in its destructive wake. And there
remain other storms on the virtual horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The havoc that VBS.LoveLetter.A wreaked was a strong reminder of
how widespread and virulent the shadowy world of computer viruses
remains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really scary how much damage computer viruses can do, and
there are a lot of them out there,'' said Tom Gebauer, multi-media
developer at Media Logic, an advertising and design firm in
Colonie, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's 50 employees got an early warning and were able to
delete the virus before ``Love Bug'' overwrote and trashed their
vast number of graphics files, known as jpegs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a strong warning to be on the alert for other viruses
ready to create problems,'' said George Purdue, vice president of
management information systems at The HUM Group, a medical
malpractice insurer based in Latham, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Purdue and his team had the ``Love Bug'' virus cleaned up and
blocked from their Microsoft Outlook e-mail system. But Purdue
won't let his guard down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect we'll see a lot of copycats,'' Purdue said. ``It's a
simple Visual Basic Script file. It would be easy to re-name it and
send it out again. An eighth-grader could do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's attack by the ``Love Bug'' virus was merely the
latest among 47,205 identified and defused viruses, according to
the AntiVirus Research Center of Symantec Corp., based in
Cupertino, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Symantec Web site, with a downloadable antidote to the
``Love Bug'' virus, was flooded with hits last week and difficult
to access.
</P>
<P>
   After numerous tries, Fred Halley Jr., facilities manager at
IKON Office Solutions, a computer training company in Latham, was
able to download Symantec's new Norton Anti-Virus program.
</P>
<P>
   That followed anxious moments after the virus struck his office
disguised as an e-mail with the heading ``ILOVEYOU.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Love Bug'' virus was rated a No. 5 _ the highest risk
factor _ by Symantec. The company has listed four others lurking in
cyberspace with a No. 4 risk factor.
</P>
<P>
   Even at computer-savvy IKON, staffed by computer experts who
train computer technicians, about half of the 100 employees opened
the ``Love Bug'' virus in their Lotus Notes e-mail system and
spread the bug before IKON's corporate offices in Buffalo issued a
warning and later an antidote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fixed in an hour and didn't cause permanent damage,''
Halley said.
</P>
<P>
   IKON pays Symantec for anti-virus protection on a
per-workstation and per-server basis. It adds up to thousands of
dollars for the peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not foolproof.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough game to beat,'' Halley said. ``The computer
hackers are creating new viruses faster than anyone can devise
anti-virus protection.''
</P>
<P>
   Halley said the anti-viral protection and an expensive software
backup system
</P>
<P>
   The virtual world is no different from the real world, he
suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an otherwise good world, we have robbers, rapists and
murderers,'' Halley said. ``It's the same with computers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1440EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2108 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-$ADV1     05-11 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-$ADV13-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CHECHENS STEP UP ATTACKS, RUSSIA COOL ON TALKS
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., May 13 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ After a fresh string of successful attacks by Chechen
rebels against crack Russian squadrons and mixed messages from
Moscow about peace talks, the nine-month-old war on Russia's
southern border threatens to drag through the summer, analysts said
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of Russia's presidential elections in March the army
claimed a territorial victory over the separatists, who are
fighting for independence from Russia. Generals said the army
controlled all key areas in the Muslim-dominated republic the size
of Maryland, and was chasing down the remnants of what they called
wounded and demoralized groups of rebel fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Independent military observers doubted Kremlin claims that the
situation was under control, predicting instead that rebel
formations would evade the army, hideout in their mountain
headquarters and plan for a new spring offensive _ a parallel to
events in the first Chechen war that saw separatist rebels taking
back the whole republic from the Russian army in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   These predictions have held true, and over the last two months
the highly mobile formations of fighters have shown once again that
although they may be fewer, they are definitely not out of the
fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been like clock-work,'' said Sergei Karaganov, the
chairman of Moscow's Foreign and Defense Policy Council, a think
tank . ``Once the leaves blossom on the trees, (the rebels) started
fighting again. Moscow has no exit strategy out of this guerrilla
war. It doesn't want to talk peace. So, of course this is going to
drag on.''
</P>
<P>
   Since March, Russian forces have, on average, experienced 30
casualties per week, bringing the total reported dead to 2,250 and
wounded to 6,575, according to General Valery Manilov, the deputy
chief of the Russian general staff. Russian non-governmental
organizations claim the military under-reports losses, however, and
say the real figure is closer to 10,000 dead.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel causality figures are much harder to come by. Daily
reports are contradictory. If all the Kremlin claims were added up,
the army has killed more than 100,000 rebels. Rebel spokesmen offer
no numbers of their own.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the war in August, Russian officials
estimated the rebel fighting force to be about 20,000. The rebels
estimated their numbers at 15,000.
</P>
<P>
   Military analysts now estimate there are some 7,000 rebels still
fighting. In comparison, Russia currently has about 50,000 troops
in the region, down from the 100,000 stationed in the republic
during the fiercest fighting in December and January.
</P>
<P>
   If the war was only a numbers game, the rebels would have been
down and out long ago. But experience, training and tactics have
definitely played a more influential role in battle. Even Russia's
military brass has had to admit that their poor organization,
communications and planning have contributed to their losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebels are guerrilla fighters. This is their land, their
terrain. Russians aren't trained for these hit-and-run battles,''
said Karaganov.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after two months of relative quiet, the Chechens are
ratcheting up their attacks. In an interview with the French
newspaper Le Figaro last week, Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov
said he had given orders to the fighters to step up the guerrilla
war against the Russian army.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the rebels claimed that they had killed 30 Russian
soldiers in an ambush attack just 30 miles from the devastated
capital Grozny, a position that Russia has said was completely
cleansed of fighters as far back as February.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers were impossible to independently verify. If true,
it would mark the single-most deadly one-day attack since Chechens
ambushed a Russian patrol in March, killing 40 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a group of decommissioned Russian soldiers came
under attack in Ingushetia, the Russian region bordering Chechnya
and an area considered outside the war zone. No one took immediate
responsibility for the attack, but Gen. Manilov said he suspected
the rebels. A total of 18 Russians were killed, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Maskhadov, the highest-ranking popularly elected Chechen
official and a man Russian President Vladimir Putin has placed on
Russia's Most-Wanted List of criminals, also said in his interview
he would be willing to begin peace negotiations with the Kremlin
through a third-party intermediary.
</P>
<P>
   Putin has not made any public statement about Maskhadov's offer.
Other officials have uttered conflicting signals.
</P>
<P>
   The politician Putin named to head up a human rights commission
for Chechnya told reporters Thursday he was ready to meet with
Maskhadov. In a separate briefing on the same day, however, Manilov
refused to consider such talks. ``The talk about political
negotiations is nonsense. Aslan Maskhadov is wanted by the police.
We will not talk to him,'' Manilov said.
</P>
<P>
   Army officers deny that they are concerned about the spread of
fighting outside of the southern front, where the Russians have
concentrated their forces, and still insist they have the rebels
licked.
</P>
<P>
   Unnamed security officials told the Interfax news agency this
week that the rebels don't have the capability to launch
large-scale attacks and would continue separate but inconsequential
raids, sabotage and terrorist actions against military and civilian
targets in the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's general in charge of Chechnya appealed to the militants
to lay down their weapons and take advantage of the amnesty Moscow
has offered until May 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are tired of war, they want peace and a normal life,
therefore take advantage of the amnesty,'' Maj. Gen. Gennady
Troshev said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Take a sober look at the situation, consider your actions and
lay down your arms.''
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   www.kavkaz.com
</P>
<P>
   www.pravetelstvo.ru
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
