<HEADER>
A2109 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-TURNER-0512-CO     05-11 0441
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-TURNER-0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TURNER MEETS WITH PUTIN TO 'CATCH UP'
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (l) Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Atlanta's favorite son Ted Turner pulled off quite a
coup Thursday, snagging a private meeting in the Kremlin with
arguably one of the world's most private and controversial people,
Russian President Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting side-by-side with Putin in the Kremlin's Blue Room,
Turner said he requested the meeting in order to catch up with an
old friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did good work together in the mid-1990s when we organized
the Goodwill Games, a lot of time had passed and we have a lot to
catch up on,'' Russian television quoted Turner as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Turner dreamed up the Goodwill Games, an amateur sporting
competition similar to the Olympics, in the late 1980s as a way to
help strengthen U.S.-Russia ties with the end of the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The two men worked together to organize the 1994 games in St.
Petersburg, Putin's hometown, and where he was deputy mayor.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to Turner's other sports and media ventures, the
games were widely considered a failure.
</P>
<P>
   Turner _ founder of CNN and owner of the Atlanta Braves _ was
not available for comment after the Kremlin meeting, but his
spokeswoman Maura Donlan characterized the meeting as ``amiable.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men discussed reviving the Goodwill Games by 2005. They
also discussed peace and security issues.
</P>
<P>
   Turner organized the chat as part of a three-day trip to the
Russian capital to hobnob with other Russian luminaries during
Friday's scheduled grand opening of Former Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev's new library. The Turner Foundation donated an
undisclosed amount for the building.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, the former head of Russia's secret service, was elected
president on March 26. During his campaign he shunned press
interviews and kept meetings with private individuals to a minimum,
culling a reputation as an aloof and somewhat shady politician.
</P>
<P>
   Cracking this stereotype a bit, Donlan said the media mogul
clinched the meeting with Putin without any trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just went through the usual channels. It was very easy,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   When berated by a reporter for tips on how to gain access to
Putin, the advice given was matter-of-fact: Putin never forgets his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.gorbachevfoundation.neu.edu/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.bravosweb.com/turner/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
