<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0152 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2116 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k BC-ROEPER-GIULIANI-COLUM     05-11 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROEPER-GIULIANI-COLUMN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS RUDY'S LONG WINNING STREAK COMING TO AN END? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use Thursday, May 11, or thereafter. This replaces
ROEPER-BEER-COLUMN, which moved earlier today. The BEER column
should be used Tuesday, May 16.)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by clients of the ROEPER-COLUMN.
Nonsubscribers can use this article only by special arrangement.
For purchase information, see end of text. 
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.2000 The Chicago Sun-Times  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only a short time ago, New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was on a
roll, riding high as one of the most famous big-city mayors this
country has ever known.
</P>
<P>
   Whether he was wolfing down a hot dog at a Yankees game and
hanging with pals like Joe Torre, traveling to Arkansas to take
digs at the Clintons, schmoozing with Howard Stern's parents at a
live broadcast birthday party or getting into spirited battles with
artsy types over putatively religious paintings festooned with
elephant dung, Rudy G. was having the time of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Not since Oswald Copplepot considered a run for mayor of Gotham
City in ``Batman Returns'' have we seen such a gleefully mean guy
taking such a voracious bite out of the Big Apple.
</P>
<P>
   Rudy G. had it all. Great job, great health, great kids, great
wife, great girlfriend(s), I mean,
good-friends-who-just-happen-to-be-women.
</P>
<P>
   OK. So maybe he had too much going for him.
</P>
<P>
   Karma has a way of kicking you in the shins at times like this.
Over the last couple of weeks, fate has tattooed Giuliani on the
skull and soul with a devastating and quite public one-two-three
combination.
</P>
<P>
   In late April, Giuliani had a press conference to announce he'd
been diagnosed with prostate cancer. Treatable, but still.
</P>
<P>
   A week later, he told reporters he was ``very good friend(s)''
with Judith Nathan, a 45-year-old woman who'd been seen kanoodling
(as they say in the gossip press) with him at numerous events.
</P>
<P>
   And a week after that, Giuliani was again meeting with the
press, this time to acknowledge that he and his wife Donna Hanover
were discussing separation.
</P>
<P>
   (Is it even worth mentioning that Hanover is a sometimes-actress
who recently postponed her appearance in the play ``The Vagina
Monologues'' to deal with all this? Parenthetically, heck yes.)
</P>
<P>
   Hanover then squirted a stream of lighter fluid into the boiling
barbecue by calling a press conference of her own to confirm the
separation and to make a pointed reference to difficulties in her
marriage due to an alleged relationship in the past between
Giuliani and his former communications director, Cristyne
Lategano-Nicholas _ prompting Lategano-Nicholas to deliver her own
message to the press: ``I have no desire to speculate why Donna
Hanover decided to issue the statement that she did.
Understandably, this is a difficult time. I wish both the mayor and
Donna Hanover a successful resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   And then we have Hillary Clinton as a cold side dish to this big
heaping plate of steamy controversy. In response to the news about
Giuliani's cancer, Clinton actually had the astonishing gall to
begin her statement with, ``Like all New Yorkers...,'' thus
managing to act sympathetic and remind voters she's now a resident
of the state.
</P>
<P>
   Wow! And to think we're entertained just because our mayor gets
huffy and tells the media he's still thriving and they shouldn't
dig a plot for him in Holy Sepulchre Cemetery just yet. Chicago's
just a silly sitcom compared to the middle-aged version of
``Felicity'' they've got playing in New York.
</P>
<P>
   As Giuliani has stated, politics are not quite atop his ``To
Do'' list these days, not when he's got kids and cancer and
relationships to worry about. The once unthinkable _ that Rudy
might not run against Hillary for the U.S. Senate and that she will
go up against some less-than-colorful party regular _ now seems
quite probable.
</P>
<P>
   An undistracted Giuliani would have whupped Mrs. Clinton's ass
(to use the parlance of Jimmy Carter eyeing an antsy Teddy
Kennedy); but a beleaguered Rudy is extremely vulnerable. His best
move at this point would be to drop out.
</P>
<P>
   Then what? Unless the Republican Party can persuade one of the
battling Baldwin brothers to switch parties and throw his hair gel
into the ring, whoever emerges from the short list of GOP hopefuls
most likely won't be able to offset Mrs. Clinton's head start in
the campaign _ not to mention her money, power, fame and yes,
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Hillary Clinton. Get used to it. It's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Thus giving the political media and the legions of
Clinton-hating extremists a reason for being in the 21st century.
The prospect of the former first lady returning to Washington as a
junior senator relegated to a relatively crummy office and begging
for committee membership crumbs from some of the very blowhards who
tried to run her husband out of office is almost too delicious to
contemplate.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper (rroeper(at)suntimes.com) is a columnist for
the Chicago Sun-Times and the author, most recently, of ``Urban
Legends: The Truth Behind All Those Deliciously Entertaining Myths
That Are Absolutely, Positively, 100% Not True!'' Roeper is also a
commentator for Fox News in Chicago and has appeared on programs
such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News with Dan Rather,''
``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
