current program in Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   In setting his course, Bush is certainly not alone. The partial
privatization route has long been trod by moderate and conservative
economists and research groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prudent thing to do is put aside savings today so 40 years
from now young people will be able to pay for a good portion of
their own benefits,'' said John C. Goodman, president of the
Dallas-based National Center for Policy Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   William Beach, director of the Heritage Foundation's Center for
Data Analysis, said, ``We look at reforming Social Security as a
way of reforming the tax most lower- and moderate-income people
face.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor is the partial privatization route solely a Republican
course. Several prominent Democrats, including Sens. Bob Kerrey of
Nebraska, John Breaux of Louisiana, and Chuck Robb of Virginia,
have offered versions of a partial privatization bill.
</P>
<P>
   Economists differ over the wisdom of a partial privatization
plan, also known as a ``carve-out'' because it carves a portion of
the payroll tax out of the public system.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, a bitterly divided Advisory Council on Social
Security split three ways, with five of the 13 members supporting a
5 percentage point carve-out for personal accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Most economists who advocate a privatized approach argue that
real stock market returns have historically averaged about 7
percent a year, while Social Security offers a real rate of return
of about 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the partial privatization plan argue that in addition
to the obvious risks faced by individual investors, the approach
comes with hidden costs and implications.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron notes that since Bush's program would be aimed primarily
at younger workers, its impact would not begin to be felt for at
least a decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   Since the 75-year deficit in Social Security is equal to about
15 percent of the projected benefits, a 3 percentage point
carve-out would increase the deficit to about 33 percent, Aaron
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are talking about is humongous cuts in assured
benefit income for middle-income Americans,'' Aaron said. ``I can
understand why Mr. Gore and others are rubbing their hands waiting
for the details from Mr. Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gebhardtsbauer, (CQ) senior pension fellow for the American
Academy of Actuaries, notes that without huge benefit cuts, Bush's
plan would neither solve Social Security's long-range financial
problems nor reduce the federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   ``He not only has not fixed Social Security's problem, he may
have created more,'' Gebhardtsbauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Reischauer, president of the Urban Institute and
former director of the Congressional Budget Office, said a
2-percentage point carve-out would not produce enough income in
most cases to match what would be lost in guaranteed Social
Security benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The political economist in me says (Bush) is committing
suicide. The policy analyst in me says I should take my hat off and
congratulate him for raising an important policy issue for this
century,'' Reischauer said.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also criticize Gore's plan because it does not
address Social Security's long-term financial problems.
</P>
<P>
   They're also uneasy because Gore's plan would eventually change
the nature of Social Security by using general revenues to help
finance the program instead of relying solely on payroll taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Paying down and eventually eliminating the federal debt _ the
heart of Gore's plan _ simply means it will be easier for the
government to borrow again in about 20 years when the Social
Security surplus is depleted by the retiring Baby Boomers.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the trust fund would become a pledge that the
federal government would have to honor either by using general
revenue or reducing benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Gebhardtsbauer estimates Gore's plan would eventually require
more than $100 billion a year from general revenues to help finance
Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Using general revenue to pay Social Security benefits
``eliminates the discipline we've had since (President Franklin D.)
Roosevelt started it,'' Gebhardtsbauer said. ``That discipline is
that if you want to increase benefits, you have to increase
(payroll) taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Privatization supporters are even more critical of Gore's
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not doing anything is the real concern because we're on a path
that will require higher and higher taxes in the future,'' said
Goodman. ``Today's young people may not get all the benefits
promised because of resistance from future taxpayers who may not
even be born yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Beach, of the Heritage Foundation, is skeptical of Gore's
prediction that he can credit the debt reduction and interest
payment savings to Social Security and thereby keep the system
solvent until 2050. He suggests that the federal government will
find other ways to spend the money before it is needed for
retirement payments.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web:
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush: www.georgewbush.com/
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore: www.algore2000.com/
</P>
<P>
   Larry Lipman's e-mail address is larryl(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
