<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROSIDE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINGS GET INTERESTING, UGLY IN CROWDED HOUSE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
With BIGBRO 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's the good news that hit Spain's incarnation of the TV
sensation ``Big Brother,'' currently entering its third week on the
air: Within two weeks, two of the participants _ who had agreed to
spend 100 days locked in a house with eight other strangers under
the watchful eyes of a battery of cameras for the amusement of the
entire country _ had already begun a sizzling romance.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the bad news: The female half of that couple was voted
out by viewers in that second week.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, there's more good news: Her departure earned a
whopping 46 share, outdone only by its repeat on the weekly
highlights episode, which drew a staggering 75 percent of all
viewers watching TV. This was in no small part because her exit met
with a tearful farewell from her partner _ ``The man stood in the
doorway, crying, shouting, 'I want to marry you when I get out! I
love you so much!''' exults ``Big Brother'' executive producer Paul
Romer, who created the original series for Netherlands television.
</P>
<P>
   Here's how big a phenomenon ``Big Brother'' _ which will make
its American debut on CBS in July _ is in Spain: It beat out the
European soccer tournament in the ratings, something never before
achieved or even thought conceivable. It was a huge hit last year
in the Netherlands, and has been so far as well in Germany, where
the contestants are about two-thirds of the way through their run.
Given American audiences' fervor for reality programming, it could
well ace out ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire'' as the water-cooler
discussion topic of choice.
</P>
<P>
   America's ``Big Brother'' house is currently under construction
on the CBS Radford lot in Studio City. When it's up and running, 10
contestants selected from across the United States will enter the
house and commence being the subject of non-stop scrutiny for 100
days. Unlike ``MTV's The Real World,'' participants cannot leave
their premises to interact with the outside world. Every week or
so, one contestant (of two selected by a secret vote of the house's
inhabitants) will be voted out by viewers.
</P>
<P>
   It'll pay to be popular: The last surviving home dweller wins
$500,000; the runner-up $100,000. And, of course, individual
members can parlay as much fame and wealth from their participation
in the project as they can muster. When the Dutch series ended, the
winner went on to a part in a movie and numerous commercial
endorsements. The runner-up released his own CD; two women appeared
in Dutch Playboy magazine and another now co-hosts a weekly
entertainment program.
</P>
<P>
   When it premieres in July, ``Big Brother'' will be stripped
across the network's prime time schedule: A half-hour at 8 p.m.
every Monday, Tuesday and Friday; a live, hourlong broadcast in
which psychologists and participants' family members offer their
observations airs 8 p.m. Thursdays, along with an hourlong recap of
the week's events at 8 p.m. Saturdays. (CBS's other reality series,
``Survivor,'' will air on Wednesdays.) In addition, four different
Internet sites will stream non-stop material from the home 24 hours
a day. Though cameras will be set up in the house's bathroom,
that's simply for security reasons, Romer says (in case, say, a
participant has a heart attack); none of that material will air on
TV or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Creator Romer admits the producers require a super-human
contribution from the participants, and says they emphasize to the
contestants how difficult life may be for them in the weeks leading
up to the broadcast date.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not very easy,'' he says. ``We made sure we prepared our
house guests as well as we could, psychologically as well as
physically. We told them everything they could expect for those
three months, and everything they could expect after. They were
aware of what was waiting for them. We didn't want to hide that
from them, we didn't want to give them a surprise. They were aware
of what they'd be facing. It's like preparing astronauts for a trip
to the moon _ we told them everything.''
</P>
<P>
   As for romantic encounters, Romer says, ``We don't really
encourage that, but they will be there. This show is about human
behavior, and relationships are part of that. We told married
people and people with partners _ we made them aware that over 100
days, people would fall in love, and that could affect their
private life. But when we were selecting the contestants, we were
looking for people who were open to possibilities, and counting on
the fact that some relationships will appear.'' To date, Romer
says, no marriages have been broken up by ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   If it isn't already, ``Big Brother'' is on the verge of becoming
a global phenomenon: After the U.S. start-up in July, nearly a
dozen more countries will begin similar programs in September,
including Italy, Switzerland and South Africa.
</P>
<P>
   And those interested in applying for the American series can
still do so through May 12: Application forms and information are
available at CBS.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
