<SLUG> BC-PANCAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WITH PANCAKES, THERE'S A RIGHT WAY AND A WRONG WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RUTH FANTASIA  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a dish that has been around almost as long as fire, pancakes
can be mucked up pretty easily. They can come out soggy in the
middle or too brown on top. They can be too thick or too thin. In
fact, it seems that pancakes seldom turn out just right. Goldilocks
had better luck with porridge.
</P>
<P>
   In the interest of better breakfasts, here are several ways to
make pancakes more dependable fare from Karen Dewey of Dewey's
Diner in Albany and ``The Bread Bible,'' by Beth Hensperger
(Chronicle Books, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   _ Pancake batter works best when mixed and then allowed to rest
in the refrigerator for a few hours because it gives the dry
ingredients time to dissolve into the moisture.
</P>
<P>
   _ All-purpose flour is the standard, but an equal amount of cake
flour can be used to make lighter, more airy pancakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't get fussy when mixing. It's normal for there to be a few
lumps in the batter.
</P>
<P>
   _ There's no correct thickness to a pancake; it's whatever way
you like them. After all, crepes are just really thin pancakes with
extra eggs in them. The thinner the batter, the thinner the
pancake.
</P>
<P>
   _ Heat the skillet or griddle until a drop of water splashed on
the surface dances and sizzles. When the water has evaporated,
lightly grease the pan with oil or margarine.
</P>
<P>
   _ The first pancake always absorbs the excess grease in the pan,
so use it as a tester. Once it's cooked, decide if it's the correct
thickness. If it's too thin, add another spoonful of flour; too
thick, add a tablespoon or two of water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Depending on the recipe, pour no more than 1/3 cup of batter
onto the griddle for each pancake. Let cook until the top is all
bubbly and the edges of the pancake are dry. Cooking the first side
makes the pancake strong enough to flip easily and ensures the cake
is cooked through the center. Turning the pancakes too soon is one
of the most frequent mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   _ When the first side is cooked, turn the pancake to cook the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   _ If not serving the pancakes immediately, place them on a
paper-towel-lined baking pan, cover loosely with foil and hold in
an oven set at 200 degrees. Place more paper towels between layers
of pancakes to prevent them from becoming soggy.
</P>
<P>
   _ If serving immediately, slather them with butter right after
they come off the griddle.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pancakes can also be cooled to room temperature, frozen in a
single layer on a baking sheet and them stacked in freezer bags. To
reheat, microwave on high power for 15 seconds to 1 minute,
depending on how many you are heating, wrapped in a paper towel.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the best thing about making pancakes is that you can add
just about anything to them. Add chopped pecans, berries, chopped
apples or dried cranberries before cooking. If everyone wants
something different, simply make a plain batter and sprinkle on the
extras right after scooping the batter into the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Savory pancakes make good dinners. Add scallions, grated
zucchini, rosemary, chopped ham, grated cheese, chives, corn or
peppers. For dessert, make them sweet with chocolate chips or
rum-soaked raisins. Or top them with cream cheese and jam or orange
segments simmered in sugar and a bit of Grand Marnier.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a basic pancake recipe to get you started. If you prefer,
use a mix.
</P>
<P>
   _ Buttermilk Pancakes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   From ``The Bread Bible,'' by Beth Hensperger.
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   Pinch salt
</P>
<P>
   2 1/4 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons melted butter
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, combine the flour, baking soda and salt. In
another bowl, whisk the buttermilk, eggs and melted butter. Pour
the buttermilk mixture into the dry ingredients, stirring just
until moistened. Let rest for a few hours, refrigerated.
</P>
<P>
   Gently fold in any additional ingredients such as berries or
chocolate chips. Heat a griddle over medium heat until a drop of
water dances lightly across the surface and lightly grease it.
Using 1/4-cup measure for each pancake, pour the batter onto the
griddle. Cook until bubbles form on the surface, the edges are dry
and the bottoms are golden brown, 4 minutes. Turn once, cooking
again until the bottoms are golden, 2 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   _ Zucchini-currant Pancakes
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 pancakes
</P>
<P>
   From Bon Appetit, September, 1999
</P>
<P>
   2 cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon baking soda
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cinnamon
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground allspice
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   3 large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 medium zucchini, grated, squeezed to remove excess moisture
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup dried currants
</P>
<P>
   Additional vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Butter
</P>
<P>
   Maple syrup
</P>
<P>
   Heat oven to 200 degrees. Whisk flour, sugar, baking powder,
baking soda, cinnamon, allspice and salt large bowl. Whisk
buttermilk, 3/4 cup oil and eggs in medium bowl. Add to dry
ingredients and mix just until blended but still lumpy. Fold in
zucchini and currants.
</P>
<P>
   Heat griddle or heavy large skillet over medium heat. Brush
lightly with vegetable oil. Working in batches, pour batter by 1/3
cupfuls onto griddle, spacing apart. Cook until bottoms are golden,
about 2 minutes. Turn and cook until second sides are golden and
pancakes are cooked through, about 2 minutes. Transfer to baking
sheet; keep warm in oven. Serve hot with butter and syrup.
</P>
</TEXT>
