<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ENTERTAINMENT-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Weekend Section stories from The New York Times News Service for
Friday, May 12.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FEATURES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   N.Y.-PALACE-PATIO (New York) _ A palace was not a palace without
a patio in the days of Don Pedro Fajardo y Chacon (circa
1478-1546), the Castilian nobleman who built the Castle of Velez
Blanco near the southeastern coast of Spain between 1506 and 1515.
By one of those happy sets of circumstances that often befall the
Metropolitan Museum, the Velez Blanco patio was installed in 1964.
The courtyard, closed for refurbishing in 1997, reopens Friday and
is closer than it has been in many years to its 16th-century self.
By Grace Glueck.
</P>
<P>
   NY-HOUSTON-STREET (New York) _ An elfin, top-hatted statue
perched high on a venerable red-brick building at Houston and
Lafayette streets leans over the sidewalk, holding a mirror above
the passing crowds. The gold-leaf figure is Puck, the playful
sprite of Shakespeare's ``Midsummer Night's Dream,'' whose
mischievous spirit animates the building that takes his name and
the scene below on which he muses. For along Houston Street, Puck,
who proclaims ``What fools these mortals be!,'' has a rich array of
humanity to marvel at _ finger-snapping jazz-hounds, 4 a.m. pool
sharks, dancing fools, fools waiting behind a velvet rope to start
dancing, very pregnant folk singers, walkers, poseurs from SoHo
(south of Houston), shoppers from NoHo (north of Houston),
gardeners, noshers, moviegoers of every stripe _ and a handful of
sinks for the bar and bathroom, if not the kitchen. If this be
folly, play on. By night and by day, for a river-to-river slice of
city life as varied and colorful as the mondo-maki fare at Mr.
Sushi, Houston Street is unrivaled. By Tina Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   (Will move with a ``t'' travel code)
</P>
<P>
   PHILLIPS-AUCTION (New York) _ The Phillips Gallery will hold the
biggest sale in its 206-year history Thursday evening when 31
Impressionist and modern works that may bring $80 million are sold.
By Carol Vogel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVIES &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BATTLEFIELD-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Battlefield Earth'': Roger
Christian, director; with John Travolta, Barry Pepper, Forest
Whitaker, Kim Coates. Reviewed by Elvis Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   CENTER-FILM-REVIEW (Undated) _ ``Center Stage'' - Nicholas
Hytner, director; with Peter Gallaher, Donna Murphy, Debra Monk.
Reviewed by A.O. Scott.
</P>
