<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2139 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EXAMINER-PROBE-HNS &LR;      05-11 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-PROBE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EXAMINER INVESTIGATOR HAS LENGTHY RESUME &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients.) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By PETER HARTLAUB &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; .2000 San Francisco Examiner &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Charles B. Renfrew's resume is heavy reading. It
goes on for three pages, single-spaced, small type, documenting a
50-year professional career with highlights that include a federal
judgeship, an appointment as the U.S. deputy attorney general and
an executive post at Chevron.
</P>
<P>
   In his newest assignment in his hometown of San Francisco, the
former Army artilleryman will head an internal review of the
editorial policies of The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew's appointment by The Hearst Corporation on Wednesday
came nine days after Publisher Timothy O. White testified that he
offered Mayor Willie Brown favorable treatment in the Examiner's
editorial pages in exchange for Brown's support of Hearst's plan to
buy the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   White is on an indefinite paid leave of absence pending the
outcome of the review.
</P>
<P>
   Following a high-profile arbitration job last year involving the
legal fees for a multibillion-dollar settlement by tobacco
companies, Renfrew is not likely to be overwhelmed by the
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't think of a better person they could get for it,'' said
U.S. District Judge William H. Orrick Jr., who has known Renfrew
since the 1950s. ``He's a straight arrow. Not a chance he'd be
caught up in the political maelstrom.''
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew, 71, released a short statement saying the review will
begin immediately, but said it would be ``premature'' to discuss
specifics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to direct this important review process,''
Renfrew said. ``I am fully confident I have the cooperation of the
Hearst Corporation and the Examiner to conduct an open, independent
and unlimited review.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst spokeswoman Debra Shriver said a number of people were
interviewed for the job over a short period of time. Renfrew was
chosen by James Asher, Hearst's chief legal officer for
development. Renfrew has no deadline to complete the review.
</P>
<P>
   Shriver said Wednesday morning that Renfrew may retain a
journalism expert to assist him. Shriver said later that it's only
a ``possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Reached at home, White said he found out about the appointment
while reading The Examiner on Wednesday afternoon, and was pleased
to learn that the Hearst Corp. found a jurist with Renfrew's
stature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is gratifying to see this moving ahead quickly,'' White
said. ``I am confident of the outcome and that my Hearst and
Examiner colleagues and I will be fully cleared of any
wrongdoing.''
</P>
<P>
   Hearst Newspapers President George B. Irish , who declined to
comment on the Renfrew appointment Wednesday, will oversee
publishing duties at The Examiner until the investigation is
complete. He is expected to testify in the trial this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Renfrew has started investigating testimony that so
far has gotten more attention than any other portion of the
2-week-old trial of an antitrust lawsuit filed by Clint Reilly, who
is seeking to block the sale of the Chronicle to Hearst Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation will likely center around an Aug. 30, 1999,
lunch attended by White, Examiner Executive Editor Phil Bronstein
and Brown. White testified May 1, the first day of the trial, that
during the lunch, he offered more favorable treatment on The
Examiner's editorial pages in exchange for Brown's support.
</P>
<P>
   After the lunch, White sent an e-mail to Irish, stating: ``I
asked Willie how I was going to justify to my superiors in New York
wanting to support him and cooperate with him when he was seeming
to go out of his way to make our lives difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's lawyers later introduced part of a deposition
transcript that showed White giving similar testimony about the
Aug. 30 lunch to the U.S. Department of Justice last December, when
at least one Hearst lawyer was present.
</P>
<P>
   White has since said about his May 1 testimony that he was tired
and confused by the questioning, and that he did not offer Brown
favorable treatment in exchange for his support. Editorial page
editor James Finefrock wrote a letter to readers in Sunday's
Examiner, pledging that the editorial page ``is and has been
independent of any `horse trading' for favors from politicians or
anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's attorneys, who claim other Hearst executives must have
known about White's supposed deal with Brown, met the appointment
of Renfrew with skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they going to investigate?'' Alioto said. ``The guy
said it on the stand - I don't know what else you want.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-counsel Daniel Shulman said he and Alioto met 21 years ago
during a case in Renfrew's court, on opposite sides in an antitrust
dispute involving several rental car companies.
</P>
<P>
   Later Alioto and Shulman were on the same side in a lawsuit
filed against Chevron Corp., where Renfrew acted as general
counsel.
</P>
<P>
   Shriver said as far as she knew, Hearst Corp. had not hired
Renfrew before or had a case in his courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew, married with four children and five stepchildren, was
born in Detroit but has spent most of his life in San Francisco,
where colleagues say he has been active in his church.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew was in the U.S. Navy from 1946 to 1948 and the Army from
1952 to 1953, finding time to get an undergraduate degree from
Princeton University in between. He got his law degree in 1956 from
University of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew was a U.S. district judge from 1972 to 1980, appointed
by President Richard Nixon. From 1980 to 1981 he served as deputy
U.S. attorney general, appointed by President Jimmy Carter. In 1983
he became vice-president of Chevron Corp. in charge of legal
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   He has also worked as an arbitrator, a Boalt Hall School of Law
professor and has partnered in two San Francisco law firms _ most
recently from 1993 to 1997 at LeBoeuf, Lamb, Greene &AMP; MacRae.
</P>
<P>
   Friends and colleagues say Renfrew is among the most respected
lawyers in the city. Orrick said Renfrew has been on ``everyone's
short list'' for the U.S. Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Marilyn H. Patel said Renfrew is a humorous,
creative jurist whom she often recommends to mediate settlement
talks and other dispute resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you suggest his name, you don't get any objections,'' Patel
said.
</P>
<P>
   As Renfrew changed jobs often, he had at least one rough
transition.
</P>
<P>
   Critics tried to block his appointment as deputy attorney
general _ the No. 2 prosecutor spot in the nation _ claiming he
made statements in a law review article that discrimination against
Mexican and Asian Americans has not been as pervasive as bias
against other minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   Renfrew responded by pointing to his record promoting civil
rights, and later was confirmed for the appointment.
</P>
<P>
   He was also criticized after his appointment as a federal court
judge, when he called hearings at 7:30 a.m., hours before his
colleagues were getting started.
</P>
<P>
   Shulman declined to give his opinion of Renfrew, but said he
remembers the judge's rigorous schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he had some pretrial conferences on Saturday
morning,'' Shulman said.
</P>
<P>
   During his career, Renfrew has handled several high-profile
cases involving the media:
</P>
<P>
   _ As a federal judge in 1979, he fined newspaper Publisher John
McGoff $10,000 for not answering questions about the source of
funds for the purchase of the now-defunct Sacramento Union.
</P>
<P>
   _ As U.S. deputy attorney general in 1981, he settled the
investigation of leaks to reporters in the Abscam case by issuing
letters of reprimand. In the case, several officials were found to
have violated Department of Justice regulations by leaking to the
media details of a federal investigation into political corruption.
</P>
<P>
   _ As part of a three-member arbitration panel in 1988, he
ordered McClatchy newspapers to pay a casino owner $647,454 in
attorneys fees in an unsuccessful attempt to sue McClatchy
Newspapers for libel.
</P>
</TEXT>
