<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-GUN-CHECKS-$ADV14-COX     05-11 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUN-CHECKS-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    STATE GUN CHECKS MORE EFFECTIVE THAN FBI'S
 &HT;    For release Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many states have a higher rate of blocking
ineligible persons from buying guns than the FBI, according to
state and federal statistics.
</P>
<P>
   These states succeed because they use a broader base of records
to conduct background checks _ including state criminal histories,
lists of people wanted for crimes, and mental health files.
</P>
<P>
   For example, last year the Georgia Bureau of Investigation
denied gun purchases last year to more than 14,000 people, or 6
percent of applicants, while the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement denied gun purchases to more than 6,000 people, or 2.5
percent of applicants.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the FBI rejected roughly 90,000 of the 4.5
million applications it processed, a rate of 2 percent, according
to a March report by the Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 10 million instant background checks were conducted by
federal and state agencies last year. About half the checks were
conducted by the FBI, and the rest by states. Each check takes
about three minutes for an approval. Denials may take up to three
days.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, states do a better job ``because they often can
perform more thorough checks than the FBI,'' Attorney General Janet
Reno said in a March 14 letter to President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI does not have access to some state records when
conducting background checks, said Daniel Welos, acting operations
manager for the National Instant Criminal Background Check System.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to get all the states' information and put it in
a national database that the FBI and other states can check,''
Welos said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to their own records, states have access to federal
records, including files of people wanted by the FBI, Secret
Service files, immigration files and records of dishonorable
discharge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state checks are a better system,'' said Martha Wright,
chief of the User Services Bureau of the Florida Department of Law
Enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 15 states handle background checks on handguns and
``long guns'' such as rifles. Another 11 states conduct handgun
checks and leave long-gun approvals to the FBI. For states that
don't conduct checks _ including the District of Columbia and U.S.
territories _ the FBI has been handling them since November 1998
under the Brady Act.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their successes, the state background checks are in
jeopardy. That's because it costs states more money to do the
checks than they receive in fees. Florida charges gun dealers $8
for each check, while it costs the state $8 to $10 apiece to
research the application. Last year, Florida conducted more than
240,000 background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Florida and other states have appealed to Congress to help them
pay for the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without this funding, it is unlikely that state legislatures
will continue the state programs,'' Gov. Jeb Bush of Florida warned
last year in a letter to Senate Judiciary Committee leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI does not charge dealers a fee for checks. Instead, it
receives an annual appropriation from Congress to operate the
system. The FBI spent $40 million on checks last year.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice Department supports the states' effort to get more
money from Congress to run the background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., the ranking Democrat on the Senate
Judiciary Committee, added an amendment to the juvenile justice
bill last year to earmark $40 million to the states for checks. The
bill has been tied up in a conference with the House since last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   The instant background checks do not yet apply to guns sold at
gun shows or to dealers that are not registered with the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
