<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0164 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2159 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS &LR;      05-11 1513
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXAMINER-SALE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     S.F. NEWSPAPER EXECUTIVE TELL HOW HE USED INSIDER'S TIP 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By SETH ROSENFELD  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The head of the company that prints San
Francisco's daily newspapers has testified that he passed to Hearst
Corp. executives in New York a warning from some members of the
Chronicle board of directors that they better act quickly if they
wanted to buy the morning paper.
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Steven B. Falk, president of the San
Francisco Newspaper Agency, said he passed along the tip he
received from Alan H. Nichols Jr., who was then on the Chronicle
board.
</P>
<P>
   Falk said Nichols, then chief financial officer of the Chronicle
Publishing Co., indicated that Hearst should make a fast bid for
the Chronicle before some of its owners sold other properties and
decided to keep the paper.
</P>
<P>
   In a booming voice, attorney Joseph M. Alioto asked, ``Did Mr.
Nichols tell you in sum or substance that the Hearst Corporation
should act quickly because the Chronicle family members might find
themselves flush with cash and decide to keep the Chronicle?''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was that indication, yes,'' said Falk.
</P>
<P>
   The testimony came in former mayoral candidate Clint Reilly's
antitrust suit to block Hearst from buying the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Falk was a key witness for Hearst and the Chronicle as they
began their defense to Reilly's complaint.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto claimed outside of court that the information passed by
Nichols had been meant to thwart Chronicle shareholders who wanted
to keep the 135-year-old paper in family hands. Nan Tucker McEvoy,
a major shareholder and former board chair, had once declared the
Chronicle would be sold ``over my dead body.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichols, now president of Mountain View Internet firm Geocast,
could not be reached for comment Wednesday. Falk denied that there
was anything wrong in the communication between him, Nichols and
the Hearst Corp. So did Gregory Lindstrom, a Chronicle lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Falk runs the San Francisco Newspaper Agency, created in 1965 to
oversee a joint operating agreement between Hearst, which owns The
Examiner, and the local Chronicle Publishing Co.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, Falk's agency collects all revenue, and
handles all printing, circulation and marketing for both papers.
After paying for the joint operations, the agency splits the
remainder evenly between each paper, which pays the costs of its
independent editorial staff.
</P>
<P>
   Joint operating agreements are allowed under the 1970 Newspaper
Preservation Act, an exception to antitrust laws meant to keep
alive newspapers that otherwise might fail so communities could
benefit from multiple editorial voices.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco agreement was set to expire in 2005, but the
Chronicle's owners last year decided to sell to Hearst for $660
million.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's suit claims Hearst's plans to buy the Chronicle and
sell The Examiner to the Fang family, publishers of the
thrice-weekly San Francisco Independent, would create an illegal
newspaper monopoly that would reduce editorial and economic
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly contends Hearst's agreement to give the Fangs a subsidy
of up to $66 million over three years to offset costs of publishing
The Examiner is a sham, because it is not enough to make the paper
a viable competitor to the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst has denied the allegations and claims The Examiner could
not survive outside its profit-splitting agreement. Since it is a
failing enterprise, Hearst may legally shut or sell it and buy the
Chronicle, Hearst says.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Halling, a Hearst lawyer, put Falk on the stand in an
effort to prove The Examiner would fail outside the agreement and
that the surviving Chronicle would still face fierce competition
for some of the $1.3 billion in advertising in the 11 Bay Area
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Falk testified that the two San Francisco dailies are in the
middle of one of the nation's most competitive media markets, and
face competition for advertising and readers from a dozen suburban
papers as well as television, radio, cable and the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Key competition comes from Knight Ridder, the newspaper chain
that owns the San Jose Mercury News and the Contra Costa Times, and
which Falk called ``the evil empire.''
</P>
<P>
   Falk said The Examiner's and Chronicle's joint operating
agreement crippled the larger Chronicle, which in effect subsidizes
The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, though, Alioto forced Falk to concede that
the agency has no actual figures that separate the shared revenue
and costs of each paper.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no measurement specifically,'' said Falk.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto turned to a June 22, 1999, e-mail that he said showed
Falk had passed inside information from Chronicle director Nichols
to Hearst.
</P>
<P>
   In it, George Irish, head of Hearst's newspaper division, told
Hearst President Frank Bennack Jr.: ``Today, Steve Falk relayed a
conversation he had with Dick Rosenberg, who was in the Chronicle
board meeting about the discussion on the decision to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rosenberg told Steve that they . . . ended up with the
expectation that Hearst would make their best offer very quickly,
instead of waiting until all the other offers were in . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``Dick told Steve that there is still a great deal of
longstanding dislike of Hearst among some of the shareholders and a
strong offer up front could lead to their acceptance without the
longer process.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve told me that Rosenberg opined that if we waited until
the end of the process, they may find themselves flush with cash
and decide to keep the Chronicle,'' Irish wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Falk testified that he never spoke with Rosenberg, and that
Nichols had dropped by his office.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a somewhat casual hallway conversation,'' Falk said,
``though it was clear to me the message . . . was . . . Rosenberg
and other board members are hoping Hearst steps up to the plate in
an aggressive way quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Irish happened to phone Falk the next day, and Falk passed the
hint along without mentioning Nichols as the source, he testified.
</P>
<P>
   When Falk testified that he didn't recall the exact words of his
talk with Nichols because it was not a major event, Alioto was at
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You say not a major event! You have the chief financial
officer giving you inside information about what's going on in the
board of directors meeting of the Chronicle, the competitor of the
Hearsts, with regard to the sale of the Chronicle, you say that was
not something that was of great moment to you?''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's right,'' said Falk. ``I believed Nichols was doing his
job. I think Alan was being a very savvy CFO. His mission was, I
believe, to get the highest price he could for the Chronicle, for
his board and for his shareholders, and I think he thought if he
dropped a little bit of information in the right place, that word
may just get back to where it might do some good.''
</P>
<P>
   And, Alioto said, ``which means the executive offices in New
York of Hearst, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' said Falk.
</P>
<P>
   Alioto has contended that Hearst abused its position within the
joint operating agreement to get the Chronicle at lower than market
price.
</P>
<P>
   Hearst and the Chronicle have denied that.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's testimony began with Michael Weaver, a consultant to
Reilly and former chief financial officer of the Orange County
Register.
</P>
<P>
   After Hearst in March decided to sell The Examiner to the Fangs,
Weaver wrote Reilly: ``There is no doubt that the Fangs can and
will put out a paper for less than $25 million per year in net
costs to themselves during the three years of Hearst subsidy; cream
as much off the top for themselves and the Independent as they can;
and then either merge the papers or close their `money losing
venture.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Not a pretty picture for the competitive newspaper situation
in San Francisco,'' Weaver wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Under questioning by Christopher Hockett, a Fang lawyer, Weaver
admitted knowing nothing of the Fangs' plans for The Examiner.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Hearst retained former U.S. District Judge
Charles B. Renfrew to review ``editorial policies`` at The Examiner
and whether suspended Examiner Publisher Timothy O. White violated
journalistic ethics by offering Mayor Willie Brown favorable
treatment in The Examiner's opinion pages in exchange for Brown's
support of Hearst's plan to buy the Chronicle.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Chronicle and Hearst asked Walker on Wednesday
to dismiss Reilly's suit, saying he lacks legal standing to bring
it because he has shown no injury from Hearst's plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``First, Mr. Reilly apparently does not have enough of a stake
in his own case even to testify,'' said Halling. ``Number two, Mr.
Reilly, who purports to be trying to save The Examiner, is not even
a subscriber to The Examiner.''
</P>
<P>
   Alioto claims Reilly has standing to sue as a consumer of both
papers who would suffer higher subscription and advertising rates
if Hearst gets the alleged monopoly ownership of the Chronicle, and
as a private attorney general protecting the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
