<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2161 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-11 0986
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAREER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STEALING HOME TAKES SOME THOUGHT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAVE MURPHY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Think about your career in terms of baseball for
a minute. You're on second base, and a teammate singles to center
field. As you run toward third, you look at the coach for a sign:
Should you stop at third or head for home? But all he does is stare
blankly at you.
</P>
<P>
   What should you do? Answer the question now, based only on the
information you've been given.
</P>
<P>
   If you're still at third base, ask yourself a second question:
Are you stifling your own career? And if you're a boss, think about
whether your workers would answer the question the same way you
would.
</P>
<P>
   There is no absolutely right or wrong answer to the baseball
question, any more than there are absolutely right or wrong answers
in the workplace. But here are some things to consider:
</P>
<P>
   _ Know your default position.
</P>
<P>
   Ideally, you could have asked a bunch of other questions before
answering the baseball question. But no matter how many questions
you asked, a lot of what you did would depend on your instincts as
the situation unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   A good manager would never have left you in this quandary, of
course. Players would have been told that you keep running hard
unless a coach stops you, so you would have headed for home without
giving it a second thought.
</P>
<P>
   But not all managers in the workplace give explicit
instructions. You have to decide for yourself whether to wait
silently for directions, ask for advice or rely on your instincts.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a third-base coach will wait as long as possible
before giving a signal. Runners who appear tentative are a lot more
likely to get stopped than those who are blasting away at full
speed. The tentative ones have already lost a step or two, and
that's enough to sway the coach.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing happens in the workplace. Workers who exude
confidence are more likely to get waved ahead; those who have to
ask permission for everything are destined to spend an eternity at
third base, if they get that far.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't underestimate how much you know.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of baseball players can become so dependent on the coach
that they forget to keep track of obvious things, such as the score
of the game, how many outs there are, where the outfielders are
positioned and how well each of them can throw.
</P>
<P>
   You also should know your own reputation. If your nickname is
Rabbit and the coach doesn't put up the stop sign, you can feel
pretty safe about heading home. On the other hand, if your nickname
is The Piano Mover, you might want to stop at third. And get some
oxygen.
</P>
<P>
   One good side effect from all the layoffs in the last decade is
that fewer bosses are micromanagers. They simply don't have the
time to yammer at you about every step you should take to do your
job.
</P>
<P>
   That is not good news, however, for those workers who would
instinctively stop at third base. If you're passive about your
career path, waiting for that big assignment to come your way and
assuming that your boss knows how well you're doing, you'll
probably be disappointed. The good assignments go to those who know
how to take the extra base.
</P>
<P>
   Think of the things you do know. Many people are most effective
at particular times of day. Does your job let you take maximum
advantage of those times? Could you change your hours so that it
did?
</P>
<P>
   Would you be better off leaving the office at 1 p.m. each day,
taking a two-hour nap, then finishing your work at home? Would you
be more focused if you ignored all phone calls between 10 a.m. and
noon so you could work uninterrupted? Would trading certain job
duties with a colleague make both of you more effective?
</P>
<P>
   You'll know the answers to those questions better than your boss
will. If you seem to be hitting your stride as you're rounding
third base, a lot of bosses won't stop you.
</P>
<P>
   _ Expect to make a few outs.
</P>
<P>
   Even if you have a wonderful and alert third-base coach,
sometimes you're going to get thrown out. If you made it safely
every time, you and the coach would be playing it too cautiously.
</P>
<P>
   Your boss is going to disagree with you from time to time, and
you might even wind up in serious trouble once in a while. But if
you usually make smart choices and your intentions were good, no
boss with half a brain will be too disappointed in you. As a boss,
you want workers whose biggest fault is being a little too
ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sometimes the smartest play is playing dumb.
</P>
<P>
   This ought to come with a ``Kids: Don't try this at home''
label, but here goes: If you're a good worker and you want to try
something your boss probably won't like, sometimes it's best to
just try it without asking permission. When you get caught, make it
sound as if all you did was follow the obvious path.
</P>
<P>
   If you ask permission, get turned down and try it anyway, that's
insubordination and could get you in serious trouble. But if you
just try it and then the boss finds out, the trouble won't be as
severe. And if a few weeks passed and your strategy seemed to work,
you just might get away with it.
</P>
<P>
   Remember: This advice applies only if you're already a
well-respected worker, and you have to have a logical business
reason for doing what you did. ``Gee, I thought you wanted me to
take that $2 million and go to Tahiti'' probably won't cut it. On
the other hand, ``After I was done with the client, it just made
more sense for me to finish the work at home instead of driving all
the way back to the office'' just might.
</P>
<P>
   A good manager won't be all that bothered by a well-intentioned
mistake, even if you get caught trying to steal home.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; -- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dave Murphy is the careers editor of the San Francisco
Examiner, P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. His electronic
mail address is murphy(at)examiner.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
