<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2173 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-EGAN-ARCHBISHOP-ART-6     05-11 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGAN-ARCHBISHOP-ART-620&AMP;ADD-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN APPOINTS NEW YORK'S 9TH ARCHBISHOP  
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DANIEL J. WAKIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Turning to an able administrator who long served in
the Vatican, Pope John Paul II reached into the relatively small
diocese of Bridgeport, Conn., and named Bishop Edward M. Egan as
New York's ninth archbishop Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Egan succeeds Cardinal John O'Connor, a man who apparently did
not favor him much for the job, and will take over as the nation's
most visible and powerful Catholic leader. O'Connor died on May 3
at the age of 80.
</P>
<P>
   Egan will undoubtedly receive the red hat of a cardinal,
traditional for the New York archbishop.
</P>
<P>
   The clergyman, 68, is widely viewed as an interim leader, given
that bishops are required to submit their resignations to the pope
at age 75. The pope had asked O'Connor to stay on after he
submitted his resignation.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday held near the Midtown Manhattan
headquarters of the archdiocese, Egan said, ``My first reaction
was, `Edward, get down on your knees and thank the Lord to give you
a hand, and don't get up too quickly.'''
</P>
<P>
   Egan is known for turning around a troubled diocese, his talent
for bolstering the priesthood and his expertise in canon law, but
he has little experience as a parish priest. He is a theological
conservative in the image of the pope, who has filled the ranks of
bishops around the world with like-minded men.
</P>
<P>
   After eight days of speculation that Egan would be chosen _
thanks in part to comments by family members that he had the job _
the announcement came as it normally does: a dry statement and
short biography included in the Vatican's daily press bulletin. His
installation is scheduled for June 19.
</P>
<P>
   The New York archbishop presides over 2.4 million Catholics in
the country's second-largest archdiocese after Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Egan, who said he had known about his
appointment for two weeks, revealed little of his plans for the
archdiocese, saying he had much to learn.
</P>
<P>
   But he disclosed his leanings on some issues.
</P>
<P>
   For example, he left open the possibility of closing parochial
schools if necessary. ``There are times when you have no choice,
and can't pay the bills,'' he said. And he said parents should have
the choice of schools for their children without having to pay
``double,'' an apparent reference to support for school vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about his stand on any potential anti-discrimination
law in New York regarding sexual orientation, he said: ``Stay
tuned, sir. You will find out in a couple of months.''
</P>
<P>
   There were no real surprises on questions of doctrine or church
teaching, and he reiterated his opposition to contraception and
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Egan immediately sought to convey a sense of humility regarding
his new assignment, while reaching out to his future flock.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you I know no place in the world that is quicker to
accept someone who wants to be a New Yorker,'' he said. ``And I
want to be a New Yorker.'' The bishop also showed a certain
political acuity: ``Perhaps Mrs. Clinton could give me some advice
about being a New Yorker,'' he said, a barbed reference to Hillary
Rodham Clinton's recent move to New York in order to run for a
Senate seat.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop also expressed sympathy for Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
who on Wednesday announced he was separating from his wife and last
week announced that he has prostate cancer. ``He has my prayers,''
the bishop said.
</P>
<P>
   He also sought to cast a good light on his relationship with
O'Connor, saying several times they had no differences regarding
Catholic education. But he did not make a general statement about
their relationship until the end of his answer, when he said: ``We
had a wonderful relationship. He was very supportive.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The tall, deep-voiced bishop strove to maintain a jovial
attitude with scores of reporters, often chiding them for speaking
too softly or too quickly, and he spoke a few words of Italian to a
journalist for an Italian church newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   But Egan hinted that he is not all humility. ``I don't feel like
a boss, but give me a little time and I will,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He will certainly need more than humility as archbishop of New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a position of deep influence and power in the American
church, whoever sits in that seat,''said Chester Gillis, an
associate professor of theology at Georgetown University in
Washington, D.C., who focuses on the U.S. church and its relations
with Rome. ``It means that other leaders in the church certainly
would have to consult with the archbishop of New York. He would
yield significant power in the National Council of Bishops.''
</P>
<P>
   And nothing matches New York's combination of fast pace, media
attention and economic and political influence _ all of which call
for a man with force of personality, with which O'Connor was richly
endowed.
</P>
<P>
   Egan is no stranger to that world, though the media spotlight
has been relatively faint in Bridgeport, a diocese of 360,000
people where he served as bishop for 12 years. O'Connor, too, came
from an obscure posting _ Scranton, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's age and background as a teacher and expert in canon law _
a traditional route to the top of the Catholic hierarchy _ would
likely lead to a less high-profile way of directing the
archdiocese, said the Rev. John Langan, a professor in the
Georgetown philosophy department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an affirmation of conservative continuity, but in a lower
key and with a much less public style,'' Langan said. ``One of the
interesting questions is what his energy level will be like. This
is the kind of job that can devour several 40-year-old men.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan served as an auxiliary bishop in New York from 1985 to 1988
in the post of vicar of education. When he was named auxiliary,
O'Connor made clear in a letter to diocesan priests that the man
was not his choice.
</P>
<P>
   Nor did Egan's name figure on a list of three recommendations
given to the pope, according to a church official familiar with the
process. O'Connor likely would have had some influence on those
proposals.
</P>
<P>
   As vicar for education in New York, Egan did not limit himself
to Catholic schools. He also spoke out about public schools,
appearing at a 1987 City Council hearing to criticize a proposal to
distribute contraceptives in high school health clinics. ``Try
decency. Try chastity. Try Western civilization,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of the marks he made in Bridgeport, local Catholics say, was
on education.
</P>
<P>
   When he took over in 1988, the diocese was deeply in debt, and
schools as well as churches in poorer neighborhoods were struggling
as immigrant Catholic populations of Lithuanians, Slovaks, Poles
and Italians dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Egan imposed shared financing of the schools, requiring that
wealthier sections of the diocese like Greenwich, Danbury and
Westport help to fund impoverished areas. He also closed several
dilapidated or poorly attended schools.
</P>
<P>
   And overall finances improved. Under Egan, a fund-raising
campaign begun in 1995 has so far brought in $28 million, with $15
million more in pledges.
</P>
<P>
   With much of the world, and particularly the United States,
suffering a shortage of priests, Egan won attention for producing
an unusually large number of priests in his diocese.
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference Thursday, the bishop cited the increase
in priests as one of his main accomplishments in Bridgeport, and
held up one of his business cards, which have the address of a
residence for young men contemplating the priesthood on the back.
He said he passes them out liberally.
</P>
<P>
   Egan was born in Oak Park, Ill., in 1932, and was ordained as a
priest at 25. He worked only briefly in a parish. He has a
bachelor's degree in philosophy from St. Mary of the Lake Seminary
in Mundelein, Ill., and completed seminary studies at the
Pontifical North American College in Rome. He received a doctorate
in canon law from the Pontifical Gregorian University, also in
Rome.
</P>
<P>
   He later spent 14 years as a judge on the Sacred Roman Rota, the
Vatican's highest tribunal, which hears appeals on matters of
church law, especially annulments of marriages. He also taught
judicial practice at the Gregorian. Egan was one of six canon law
experts chosen to review the updated Code of Canon Law, issued in
1983, for Pope John Paul II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
