<HEADER>
A2189 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-PROVIDENCE-2TAKES     05-11 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-PROVIDENCE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A VICIOUS FIGHT CASTS ITS SHADOW 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. _ Dozens of students picked up caps and gowns
at Providence College on a sun-drenched afternoon last week, while
others flipped a Frisbee across a lawn. But as students scurried to
classes and prepared for final exams, an ugly incident hovered over
this small Catholic school, tarnishing the otherwise idyllic
end-of-semester scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Eight basketball players were involved in a brutal fight with
three other Providence students one evening last month that left
two students lying bloodied on the ground and in need of
reconstructive facial surgery, according to the police.
</P>
<P>
   The incident has angered many of the 3,700 Providence students
and disappointed administrators, and it also threatens to decimate
a once-proud basketball program that twice has been to the Final
Four. The Providence Friars have been a primary source of pride,
inspiration and entertainment for people in this area for half a
century, but they are scrambling right now just to find enough
players to fill next season's roster.
</P>
<P>
   As many as six players, at least three of whom were projected to
be starters, could be lost from next season's team as a result of
the fight. Much will depend on the outcome of criminal cases and
college disciplinary proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the basketball players have been charged with assault
for their roles in the fight. Those players, along with the four
others, have already been punished by a college discipline
committee; each of the eight players was expelled, suspended or
placed on disciplinary probation. School officials declined to
discuss details of the punishment.
</P>
<P>
   The eight players have appealed the discipline committee's
findings, and they remain on campus to take final exams this week
and await the completion of their appeals, which is expected soon.
</P>
<P>
   If the penalties are upheld, none of the players would be
eligible to play here next season. Six of the eight had intended to
return, but even students on probation are not permitted to play on
a Providence College team.
</P>
<P>
   And since Providence has a recent history of enforcing strict
penalties against other students found to have violated college
rules, two people familiar with the appeals process said it
appeared unlikely that the penalties would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
   If they are not, the basketball coach, Tim Welsh, might have
only four scholarship players returning from a listless 11-19 team.
But Welsh is trying to be optimistic in the midst of the
embarrassing ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Providence College basketball has been around for many, many
years,'' Welsh said. ``This was an unfortunate incident. We all
have to learn from it and move forward. But the program is not
going to go under because of something that happened in 10
minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight took place on a chilly Monday evening, April 10, after
the players had gone to the apartment of Thomas Cook, a senior, at
47 Eaton St., just a few hundred feet off campus. Cook works as a
bouncer at Prime Time Cafe, a brick-faced bar about a mile off
campus, where lines of students wait to get in on many nights.
</P>
<P>
   Cook had helped remove David Murray, a 6-foot-9-inch center from
New York City, from Prime Time three days earlier, because Murray,
22, did not have valid identification, said Maj. Martin Hames,
chief of detectives for the city police. Some shoving occurred as
Murray was forced to leave the bar, Hames said.
</P>
<P>
   Several players spent the weekend trying to find Cook, Hames
said, to confront him about what they considered a lack of respect.
The players arrived at the tan-and-white three-story house where
Cook lives at about 10:30 p.m. The police said that Murray and two
other basketball players _ Donta Wade and Llewellyn Cole _ punched
and kicked Cook. He was found in the driveway disoriented, and he
needed surgery to repair a fractured jaw and a broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   Wade was also charged with hitting Mark Hogan, another
Providence student. He needed surgery to repair injuries to his
cheekbone and his eye socket and a metal plate had to be inserted
in his face, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth player, Jamaal Camah, was charged with punching another
college student who lives at the house, Ryan Kerwin.
</P>
<P>
   Although the players are all African-American and the injured
students are white, many students and others with ties to the
college insisted that the incident was not racially motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Murray, Wade and Cole have been charged with multiple counts of
felony assault, assault with a deadly weapon and conspiracy to
commit felony assault. The deadly weapons were the shoes apparently
used to kick the injured students. The fourth player, Camah, was
charged with one count of assault. They all pleaded not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Cole, a 6-foot-7-inch forward from New York City, was the only
senior on the team and will obviously not be back. But the other
three are juniors who had been expected to start for the Friars
next season: Wade, a 6-2 guard who had a 38-point game against
Notre Dame last season; Murray, the 6-9 center, and Camah, a 6-4
guard.
</P>
<P>
   John C. Revens Jr., who is Cole's lawyer, and Daniel McKinnon,
Murray's lawyer, disputed the police's version of the events,
although each declined to offer specifics.
</P>
<P>
   A friend of the players said they had gone to Cook's house to
retrieve a gold necklace that Murray had lost in the jostling with
Cook at Prime Time on April 7. Murray had not been allowed into the
bar, the friend said, because he did not have an ID, but he had
somehow slipped inside. Cook helped to eject him and, in the
pushing that took place outside the bar, Murray apparently lost a
necklace, the friend said.
</P>
<P>
   When Murray and seven teammates went to Cook's house three days
later to retrieve the necklace, the players were told that Cook was
not home, the friend said. They were walking the short distance
back to the campus when Cook and several other students confronted
them. Both sides started arguing, the friend said, and Wade and
Cook wound up squaring off, beginning the skirmish that left Cook
and Hogan seriously injured and the basketball program in shambles.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a fight,'' Revens, Cole's lawyer, said. ``There's no
dispute about that. As to where the fight occurred and how it
occurred, there will be a dispute about that.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon, Murray's lawyer, said the fight was ``substantially
more complicated'' than has been reported by the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who might appear, at first blush, to be the
aggressors might prove to be the people who started to retreat,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Providence College has not released the names of the
players involved in the fight because of federal privacy laws,
Wade, Cole, Murray and Camah were arraigned in District Court on
April 14. A Big East Conference official confirmed that the other
four students who accompanied them to Eaton Street are also
basketball players.
</P>
<P>
   College officials declined requests for interviews, and some
students involved in the incident did not respond to interview
requests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been extremely careful about not saying anything until
the appeal process is completed,'' said Edward Caron, the vice
president for college relations and planning.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh, a former Iona coach who just finished the second year of
a seven-year contract, might be left with only the remnants of a
team that was one of the worst in the Big East last season.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh said he would meet with students, alumni and fans for ``20
hours a day,'' if necessary, to restore faith in the program, but
the 39-year-old coach and the team are obviously in a dire
situation.
</P>
<P>
   The Friars appeared in the Final Four in 1973, when Ernie
DiGregorio was making fancy passes to Marvin Barnes, and in 1987,
when Rick Pitino was climbing to coaching prominence with a future
coach on the court named Billy Donovan. The school boasts of former
players like Lenny Wilkens and John Thompson and former coaches
like Joe Mullaney and Dave Gavitt.
</P>
<P>
   While many Providence students were reluctant to discuss the
fight and the basketball players, some were outspoken. ``It's a
ridiculous situation,'' said David Tanski, a freshman. ``They
should be kicked out of school and put in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Welsh said, ``If certain people need to be penalized, they
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Burke, another freshman, said: ``The glory days of
Providence basketball are behind us. That's why I think they should
just get rid of these kids and start fresh. Maybe they can make it
back. They've done it before. You can do it easier these days. You
only need a couple of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Welsh might need more than that just to hold a
scrimmage. Since Providence could have as few as four returning
players to go along with four high school recruits, Welsh is
pursuing several junior college players and preparing for the
worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more determined than ever,'' he said. ``We're faced with
this and now we have to figure a way out. It's not something I'm
just saying to you, I truly believe it. It's not like we're coming
off a Final Four year. I like the kids coming back. I'm not saying
it's going to be a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some students speculated that because the players were used to
receiving preferential treatment, from having full scholarships to
getting early choices in classes and dormitories, they responded
aggressively when something went against them.
</P>
<P>
   But another student noted that the players are taught teamwork
throughout their careers and perhaps followed that approach while
trying to help a teammate. ``It's good to be a good teammate and
take care of each other,'' said Joe Valenzano, the former sports
editor of The Cowl, the student newspaper. ``It's not good to go
out and hunt people down.''
</P>
<P>
   One senior who spoke on the condition of anonymity said he loved
Providence, but that the school must remind everyone that violence
will not be tolerated. He was holding a graduation cap that had
``Done With College'' etched across it. Those words, usually
associated with celebrating a significant achievement, could have a
different meaning for some basketball players at Providence this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
