A2193 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-MIRACLE-REVIEW-LADN &LR;      05-11 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIRACLE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE OBSTACLES, `MIRACLE' FINISHES FIRST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `tonight' refers to Sat., May 13) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the face of it, ``Miracle in Lane 2'' doesn't sound terribly
promising. It's programmatic, feel-good material based on a true
story concerning a spunky kid suffering from spina bifida and his
dream to compete in the Soap Box Derby (the depiction herein seems
to take place in an alternative universe in which the Soap Box
Derby is treated like the Super Bowl).
</P>
<P>
   It has a lot of artificial obstacles (creating a brake for the
boy's car not requiring his feet, confronting the Derby tribunal
over its draconian policies regarding the disabled) that are easily
surmounted. It features such melodramatic pronouncements as ``I
hate you! I wish you were dead!'' and ``Racing is the best thing
that ever happened to me! I was so close!''
</P>
<P>
   But darned if ``Miracle in Lane 2'' doesn't triumph over its
narrative problems the same way its heroes emerge victorious over
their creaky plot complications. And the fact that the film stars
``Malcolm in the Middle's'' Frankie Muniz as Justin Yoder, the
young boy in question, not only makes it a must-see for young
viewers but also a richly entertaining one for all ages.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz is aided and abetted by an often funny script by Joel
Kauffmann and Donald C. Yost, which transforms Justin into a
self-deprecating wise-cracker (``My legs are linguini, and I have
more stitches in my head than a baseball'') prone to imaginative
flights of fantasy. He imagines his own funeral, where the preacher
extols the virtues of Justin's wheelchair more than Justin himself,
and some very funny visits with God (Tuc Watkins), who appears to
Justin as his favorite race-car driver, wearing a T-shirt that
reads ``I don't make mistakes'' while working on his hot rod and
taking a blowtorch to some marshmallows.
</P>
<P>
   The film also probes the difficult emotional terrain of Justin's
family _ to pay for his medical procedures, his dad (Rick
Rossovich) is forced to work two jobs and mom (Molly Hagan) also
works long hours. His perfect-seeming jock brother Seth (Patrick
Levis) is seeing a shrink due to his conflicted emotions toward
Justin; in turn, Dad has a complex disconnect when it comes to
Seth's successes. Through all this, the film is even able to
depict, credibly and humorously, Justin's parents' romantic life.
</P>
<P>
   Justin, who has spent his life living in the shadow of his
brother's numerous sports trophies, decides he wants to try out
Soap Box racing when he befriends the grumpy neighbor Vic (Roger
Aaron Brown), who likewise has deeper emotional reasons for his
surliness. Vic, who has previous experience working with Derby
cars, proves to be an invaluable asset, helping Justin reach the
finals.
</P>
<P>
   Muniz, as usual, is adorable and funny. It could also be
important for some children to see someone they respect so much
playing a handicapped character: They might feel a greater
sympatico for the disabled and understand there are fewer
differences between them than there might appear. &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Miracle in Lane 2.'' &QL; 
What: Biopic about a child born with spina bifida who becomes a
Soap Box Derby champion. &QL; 
The stars: Frankie Muniz, Rick Rossovich, Molly Hagan, Patrick
Levis, Roger Aaron Brown. &QL; 
Where: Disney Channel. &QL; 
When: 7:30 and 9:10 tonight; also Monday, Wednesday, Friday and May
23 and 25. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
