<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RATED-X-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X-RATED, Y BOTHER?
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 1 star 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once you get past the rather inspired casting of Emilio Estevez
and Charlie Sheen as porn-king brothers, there's virtually nothing
to recommend ``Rated X,'' a docudrama about San Francisco's
Mitchell brothers, Artie (Sheen) and Jim (Emilio), who discovered
porn star Marilyn Chambers and ended their relationship in a
particularly violent manner.
</P>
<P>
   The episodic script, credited to Norman Snider, Anne Meredith
and David Hollander, wouldn't pass muster at a Robert McKee
introductory screenwriting seminar. If Artie meets a woman who's
not a porn actress and spends more than 15 seconds in her presence,
he'll be marrying her within two scenes. There's no explanation as
to how the guys got from running an indifferently attended porn
theater to hosting sold-out galas.
</P>
<P>
   There's not even really any character development _ what did
these guys think of what they were doing? Were they cynical
geniuses or complete chuckleheads? Did they have any redeeming
qualities before they got all coke-addled? You'll never know from
watching this.
</P>
<P>
   Estevez directs, employing all manner of stylistic flourishes _
shock cuts, varying the film speeds, overexposing the film stock _
so that ``Rated X'' looks more like a commercial or music video
than a film. All the pyrotechnics can't disguise, alas, how thin
this gruel is. There have to be better ways to see naked women than
``Rated X.''
</P>
<P>
   ____ &QL; 
The show: ``Rated X'' &QL; 
What: Docudrama about brothers in the porn business. &QL; 
The stars: Charlie Sheen, Emilio Estevez, Rafer Weigel, Tracy
Hutson, Megan Ward, Terry O'Quinn. &QL; 
Where: Showtime &QL; 
When: 9 Saturday (13th); also May 18, 29. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1545EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
