<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0175 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2196 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-RABBI-MURDER-2TAKES-N     05-11 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-MURDER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TANGLED WEB IN THE MURDER OF A RABBI'S WIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ANDREW JACOBS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHERRY HILL, N.J. _ For nearly four years, as the innuendo and
accusations mounted about Rabbi Fred Neulander's role in the
slaying of his wife, a burly, talkative man would buttonhole
reporters, strenuously proclaim the rabbi's innocence and offer his
own theories about who might have beaten Carol Neulander to death
in the living room of her suburban Philadelphia home.
</P>
<P>
   Calling himself the rabbi's private investigator, a congregant
and a close friend, Leonard Jenoff would alternately tell reporters
that the 1994 murder was the work either of a bumbling burglar or
an ill-trained terrorist. ``Russians or Israelis,'' he once
whispered to a reporter for a local newspaper, The Jewish Exponent.
``That's all I can say.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he is saying a good deal more.
</P>
<P>
   According to the long-winded confession he made to prosecutors
last week, Jenoff was the man Neulander recruited to kill his wife.
In September 1998, the rabbi was charged with planning his wife's
murder.
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff told prosecutors that after confronting Ms. Neulander in
the driveway of her home one evening, he choked on his fear, asked
to use the bathroom and then slinked away. Instead, he told them,
he paid his roommate, Paul Michael Daniels, to help carry out the
killing a week later.
</P>
<P>
   On May 1, shortly after Jenoff made his confession, he and
Daniels were arrested and charged with murder and conspiracy.
Daniels, who is unemployed and who says he is mentally ill and a
longtime drug addict, has told the authorities that he was paid for
his role in the crime.
</P>
<P>
   The Camden County prosecutor has said he may seek the death
penalty for all three defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander, who is free on bail, calls Jenoff's tale a
fabrication. In an interview Wednesday, he emphatically proclaimed
his innocence. ``His story is entirely baseless,'' he said, sitting
in the same room where the murder took place. ``I had nothing to do
with the death of my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   To those who live in the amorphous subdivisions that sprawl east
of the Delaware River, last week's revelations added yet another
layer of intrigue to a sensational crime. Neulander's murder has
fascinated residents and traumatized those who know the 58-year-old
rabbi, a charismatic figure who guided South Jersey's largest
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just keeps getting more and more surreal,'' said Pam
Rosenblum, a mother of two young daughters who lives across the
street from the Neulander home. ``We just wish this whole thing
would come to an end already.''
</P>
<P>
   As detailed by prosecutors, the killing of Carol Neulander, 52,
is a convoluted tale of deception that seems to defy common sense.
Neulander, they say, wanted his wife of 29 years dead so he could
continue his affair with another woman, the host of a radio talk
show in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say he feared divorce proceedings would bring out
his infidelity and threaten his position as the leader of M'kor
Shalom, the synagogue he and his wife had started two decades
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Although Jenoff says he wielded the first of four blows that
killed Ms. Neulander, he claims he, too, is a victim, saying the
rabbi took advantage of his weaknesses. The lawyer for Daniels says
the same thing about Jenoff: that he exploited someone he knew had
limited mental capabilities.
</P>
<P>
   The conspiracy, as laid out by investigators, brings together
three men seemingly with little in common: Neulander, a community
leader who was cherished by his congregation; Jenoff, 54, a
recovering alcoholic bruised by a string of personal and
professional losses; and Daniels, 26, a troubled soul who has spent
his adult life addicted to cocaine and heroin.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander's trial was originally scheduled for next month,
although it has now been postponed until the fall. It was the
impending trial, Jenoff said, that prompted his confession. With an
absence of hard evidence, Jenoff said, he feared that the rabbi
might be acquitted.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just wanted to do the right thing,'' said his lawyer,
Francis Hartman. ``The truth was just eating away at him.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Friday, he summoned a Philadelphia Inquirer reporter, the
Camden County prosecutor and a detective to a local diner to hear
his story. Over coffee and a cup of fruit salad, he said the rabbi
had lured him into the scheme with promises of $30,000 and help in
getting a job with the Mossad, Israel's secret service.
</P>
<P>
   Although details of his account have changed twice in the last
week, he now says he was initially lured into thinking his target
was an enemy of Israel. Only later, after he had agreed to carry
out the killing, did the rabbi reveal that the proposed victim was
his wife, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neulander and his lawyers say Jenoff's story is pure fantasy.
One lawyer, Dennis Wixted, described Jenoff as ``an oddball and
eccentric,'' so desperate for attention he would make up a tall
tale for 15 minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   He said Jenoff thought he could have his notoriety and escape
prosecution through an immunity deal. So far he has not been
offered a reward for his cooperation, although the prosecutor has
not ruled out leniency.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the confessions of Jenoff and Daniels, Wixted said there
was nothing to link the rabbi to his wife's death, ``no weapon, no
fingerprints, no evidence,'' he said. As he had in the past, he
described Ms. Neulander, the owner of two bakeries, as the victim
of a robbery gone awry.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know Leonard Jenoff said his buoyant personality and
relentless self-promotion masked a battered ego. In recent years,
they said, he endured a stormy divorce, the collapse of his
business, the loss of his home and alcoholism. In a town where most
people own spacious colonials surrounded by well-fed lawns, Jenoff
lived in a succession of modest rented apartments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, when Jenoff's life was at its most chaotic, a social
service agency referred him to Neulander, who provided financial
assistance and spiritual guidance, lawyers for both men said.
</P>
<P>
   When Jenoff complained about having to attend Alcoholics
Anonymous meetings at a church, Neulander established a 12-step
program at the synagogue. Both men were smokers who would stand
outside the synagogue for cigarette breaks.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, when Jenoff was married a second time, the rabbi
offered his house for the ceremony. ``The rabbi did great things
for my client, but on the other hand it seems as if he was grooming
him for this terrible crime,'' Hartman said.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi and his lawyers play down the relationship, saying it
never rose to the level of friendship. ``The guy's life was broken
down, a mess,'' Wixted said. ``He came in for spiritual advice.
That's how it started, and that's how it remained.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the affections were not mutual, Jenoff became the
rabbi's most vocal defender soon after Ms. Neulander's death. When
the rabbi was mobbed by reporters after his arrest in 1998, Jenoff
bravely escorted him through the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may be guilty as sin of adultery,'' he announced to
reporters at the time, ``but there's no evidence he hired anybody
to kill his wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Neulander has said he thought Jenoff's detective services were
free, and either way, he never requested them in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Wixted has suggested that Jenoff's decision to go to the
authorities may be retribution for not receiving more money for his
work. Wixted described his investigative efforts as farcical.
</P>
<P>
   ``He once went to a psychic and came back with a sketch of what
he said was the killer,'' Wixted said. ``I gave him a check for
$750 and showed him the door.''
</P>
<P>
   The main thing Jenoff and Daniels shared, it seems, were their
battles with addiction. They met at a substance abuse clinic and
later attended 12-step meetings together. In 1995 and 1996, they
shared an apartment at the Landmark, a collection of white-brick
high-rises in Cherry Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels is a paranoid schizophrenic who has struggled with
cocaine and heroin addiction since he was 16, said his lawyer,
Craig Mitnick.
</P>
<P>
   He said Daniels had few friends and many demons. ``He lives the
existence of very simple things,'' he said. ``He's very vulnerable
and easily manipulated.''
</P>
<P>
   Jenoff has said he paid his roommate $7,500 for his
participation in the crime, a sum Mitnick said he could not
confirm.
</P>
<P>
   According to lawyers for both men, Jenoff posed as a deliveryman
on the night of the killing, Nov. 1, 1994. Once inside the home,
they said, Jenoff knocked Ms. Neulander unconscious with a lead
pipe. He then called in Daniels, who hit her twice more. Before the
pair fled in his car, Jenoff delivered a final blow, lawyers for
both men said.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Neulander came home from the synagogue to
find his wife dead in a pool of blood. When detectives arrived,
they noted that there was no blood on him, something they found
unusual. The lack of blood suggested that he had not touched the
body to check for a pulse or determine a condition, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions grew when the woman who was pressuring Neulander to
leave his wife told investigators about an exchange they had before
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trust me, something will happen by the end of the year,'' she
told prosecutors. She also told them that after the murder the
rabbi said, ``See, I told you to trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the five and a half years since Ms. Neulander's death,
Neulander said he has struggled to lead a normal life. Although he
was forced to resign his position at M'kor Shalom, he still
presides over the occasional funeral and wedding. Most days he
works as an educational consultant or spends his time on a book
about his experiences in the rabbinate.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in his living room Wednesday afternoon, wearing shorts
and loafers, Neulander appeared relaxed as he spoke about several
topics, from his immigrant parents and the difficulties of
maintaining a front lawn to bouts of loneliness, fear and
humiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered around the room were religious books, photographs of
his three grown children and a harmonica he recently began learning
to play.
</P>
<P>
   Many friends and former congregants have abandoned him, he said,
but others have rallied to his side, including his children. ``They
have been terrifically supportive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He described the last few years as ``devastating and
isolating,'' and said he was eager to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it will be vile and embarrassing, but when it's all
over, I'm sure the truth of my innocence will emerge,'' he said.
``Then the healing can begin.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
