<HEADLINE>
THE CONTEMPORARY `JESUS'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below; `today' refers to Sun. May 14) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By DAVID KRONKE 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As played by Jeremy Sisto, ``Jesus,'' in the words of those
philosophers the Doobie Brothers, is just all right. He boogies
with the best of them, he gets in playful water fights with his
disciples, he has a hearty laugh reminiscent of Jeff Bridges,'
which he employs copiously and with good-natured encouragement when
his followers unwittingly say idiotic things. As CBS's mini-series
``Jesus'' posits him, he's kind of the first leader of a
self-empowerment getaway weekend seminar.
</P>
<P>
   Portraying Jesus is kind of a thankless task, at least until the
betrayal and crucifixion parts of the story kick in: Even though
the whole point of Christ was that He was a human, the actor isn't
really expected to depict Him as such. Movie Jesus has to be all
beatific and bland, white-bread and just a smidge dreamy (in both
senses of the word). Sisto boasts all the usual traits of our
Western concept of Jesus, but because he's trying to exercise some
subtlety, he doesn't quite have the charisma one might expect from
the leader of a world religion.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, ``Jesus'' is a handsomely mounted version of the
gospels. It boasts the requisite international cast (Armin
Mueller-Stahl as a German Joseph lamenting the plight of the Jews,
Jacqueline Bisset as the Virgin Mary with a French-British accent).
Of course, there's an American Christ and Satan (Jeroen Krabbe) and
Pontius Pilate (Gary Oldman, not as loud as usual but still loud)
have British accents. It hits all of the high points of Christ's
life we all grew up with in Sunday School (the Transfiguration,
water into wine, resurrecting Lazarus, overturning the tables at
the temple, etc.). A fictional character named Livio is laced
throughout the proceedings; he's essentially the Forrest Gump of
Ancient Jerusalem: He's on hand for all the tumultuous occasions.
He also explains the political situation leading up to Christ's
crucifixion to such an extent his name should be Expositio.
</P>
<P>
   It's all done well, with reverence and an occasionally sense of
humor, but it's also something most of us have seen reenacted so
many times (including last month, with ABC's ClayMation ``The
Miracle Maker,'' which told the same story in half the time) that
the question seems to be, why do we need another version?
</P>
<P>
   The mini-series' most interesting conceit also turns out to be
its most problematic: Its depiction of Satan. When Jesus spends his
40 days in the wilderness, preparing for His mission, ``Jesus''
missteps grievously by having Satan (Jeroen Krabbe) show up in a
contemporary black suit (with black T-shirt) and use special
effects in order to tempt Christ: It's the Devil as Hollywood
Executive.
</P>
<P>
   Satan's second appearance, while Jesus awaits his unenviable
fate at Gethsemane, is more compelling. He argues that all Jesus
will achieve by sacrificing Himself is becoming a figurehead for
oppression: ``Killing for Christ will be a big business in the
coming centuries,'' Satan hisses, cynically but accurately. Jesus
must find a commanding reason to repudiate Satan and !ital!not!off1
save His own skin.
</P>
<P>
   What's interesting about this is that Martin Scorsese did
essentially the same thing 13 years ago in ``The Last Temptation of
Christ'' (both films even open with Jesus having a nightmare).
Instead of showing Jesus in turmoil over how His name would be
wrongly used over the centuries, Scorsese showed Jesus in turmoil
in consideration of the simple joys of humanity He, as a man, was
sacrificing in order to save all of mankind.
</P>
<P>
   Both films eloquently describe thoughts that reasonably could be
expected to have run through His mind under those final
extraordinarily difficult circumstances of a man's life, but
Scorsese was roundly pilloried for his efforts while today,
religious groups are extolling this  &QL; 
_____ &QL; 
The show: ``Jesus'' &QL; 
What: Mini-series about Christianity's savior. &QL; 
The stars: Jeremy Sisto, Jacqueline Bisset, Debra Messing, Gary
Oldman, Jeroen Krabbe, Armin Mueller-Stahl. &QL; 
Where: CBS (Channel 2) &QL; 
When: 9 today and Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
