<HEADER>
A2199 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-THEATER-ROW-NYT &LR;      05-11 1235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-THEATER-ROW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRANSFORMING THEATER ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   By RALPH BLUMENTHAL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Some of the prostitutes had Actors' Equity cards.
That, at least, was a point of connection for the theater people
and other dreamers who 25 years ago thought they could reclaim
perhaps the seediest sex strip on wild West 42nd Street.
</P>
<P>
   There was another link to culture. The International Body Rub
Institute, the French Palace and other massage parlors that lined
the block between 9th and 10th Avenues were decorated with murals:
nudes, many painted by a quixotic Israeli artist who waited on
tables down the block at the Hello Deli.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like the Bloomsbury Group goes porn,'' recalled Andre
Bishop, artistic director of the Lincoln Center Theater and one of
the founders of Playwrights Horizons, a pioneer in the ultimately
successful effort to turn the block into the flourishing Theater
Row, which prefigured the far larger revival of 42nd Street and
Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   Now the eastern half of the enclave, between Ninth and Dyer
Avenues, is poised for its own transformation. With the stroke of a
pen _ lots of strokes of lots of pens, actually _ the biggest Off
Broadway theater redevelopment project in New York City history has
taken final form.
</P>
<P>
   Contracts for a new 499-seat Shubert theater, five new or
rebuilt smaller theaters and a 40-story apartment tower overlooking
the Dyer Avenue exit from the Lincoln Tunnel were signed on April
14, supercharging a renewal that until now has been makeshift.
</P>
<P>
   There was no self-congratulatory announcement but relief that
the complex series of closings had survived. Participants looked
back at what some called an unlikely urban drama, largely
unscripted, with (so far anyway) a happy ending. In all, from
pornographic past to high-rise future, the resurgence became, quite
literally, a groundbreaking story of urban renewal through the
arts.
</P>
<P>
   It even drew praise from an unlikely quarter: Martin Hodas,
known in his heyday in the 1970s as ``the peep show king'' and the
entrepreneur behind many X-rated storefronts that have since been
driven from the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a wonderful thing they did,'' said Hodas from his
home in Queens. ``I never liked the idea of massage parlors.''
</P>
<P>
   The strip, a theater locale in decades past, entered the 1970s
so tawdry that some visitors preferred to come and go walking down
the yellow line in the middle of West 42nd Street, far from the
soliciting women and the string of menacing sex boutiques and
grungy groceries.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Live Burlesque'' house, where women strolled around
talking off their clothes and pointing absently to parts of their
anatomy, ignored its electrical bills, so Con Edison finally ripped
up the street and disconnected the power cable to the building.
</P>
<P>
   The cellar of another club was home to a reclusive old woman
with an enormous wardrobe who emerged intermittently in full makeup
and laden with jewelry to roam the block shrieking at passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   Into this mix in 1975 stepped Playwrights Horizons, a
four-year-old company that had just lost its home in the West Side
YMCA. Its artistic director, Bob Moss, took one look around and
decided, ``Sometimes you have to do things that don't make any
sense, and this is one of them.'' He took quarters in an abandoned
pornographic movie house at 422 W. 42nd St. for $1,200 a month and
rechristened it the Judith Anderson Theater, then soon expanded
Playwrights' stake on the block by moving down the street to the
former burlesque house at No. 416, at twice the rent.
</P>
<P>
   The company appealed for help from Broadway luminaries, among
them Richard Rodgers. Instead of cash he sent a contribution more
to the point: $500 worth of paint, Lysol and cleaning equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Even the streetwalkers pitched in, Bishop recalled, with those
holding union cards asking for parts. ``There was an odd
camaraderie on the block,'' he said, ``particularly when the fleet
was in.''
</P>
<P>
   The company soon put itself on the map with hits like
``Vanities.''
</P>
<P>
   A second brave troupe, the Lion Co., arrived, and others,
including the South Street Theater, Intar and the Acting Co. soon
followed. Moss, who left Playwrights to become artistic director at
Syracuse Stage, a leading outpost of regional theater, dated the
turnabout from the day in 1975 when he looked out of his window and
saw strangers, including one out-of-place interloper in a business
suit, surveying the strip for who knew what.
</P>
<P>
   They included Fred Papert (the suit), who had founded the
nonprofit 42nd Street Development Corp. during the successful
effort to save Grand Central Terminal on East 42nd Street from the
wrecker's ball. (His compatriot in the effort, Jacqueline Kennedy
Onassis, later wielded a shovel in the Theater Row groundbreaking.)
</P>
<P>
   Papert's group had bought the block of West 42nd Street between
9th and 10th Avenues from desperate landlords who had been losing
money and faced mounting tax bills while playing reluctant host to
sex establishments. By holding a mortgage on the properties of the
nonprofit group, they at least had a chance for some financial
recovery if the renewal took, which is in fact what happened.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the unsightly buildings, Papert wondered what it
would it would take, short of demolition, to turn the neighborhood
around.
</P>
<P>
   Moss told him: ``I have a better idea. This can all be turned
into theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   By picking tenants who changed the ``urban vibrations,'' as
Papert put it, his group turned the trickle of new theaters into a
boomlet, which he hoped to advance with his relentless promotion of
a 42nd Street trolley line.
</P>
<P>
   The failure of the new Manhattan Plaza housing towers across
West 42nd Street to draw sufficient tenants to the wasteland
produced another opportunity: 80 percent of the units were
earmarked for low-paid people in the performing arts. That idea
proved a bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first lights going on in the apartments,''
Bishop said. ``It was an outstanding moment. Suddenly we didn't
feel as desolate.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the last links with the gritty past are about to be severed.
Demolition for the new apartment tower and theaters began last week
by the builders, Daniel Brodsky, Robert Quinlan and Michael Field.
They said the $75 million job, which includes 260 rental
apartments, 20 percent of them for low- and moderate-income
tenants, could be completed in 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Shubert organization is spending $6 million or more on its
new theater, its 17th wholly owned establishment in the city and
the city's first commercial stage built specifically as a transfer
house for productions that start modestly off or off Off Broadway
and then, on the strength of reviews, seek to make the leap to
theaters large enough to earn money or even, if lightening strikes,
to Broadway. The new theater will be run by Ben Sprecher, who owns
the Variety Arts and Promenade Theaters and manages the Lucille
Lortel.
</P>
<P>
   The project also includes two theaters with 99 seats and one
with 199 seats on a 41st Street parcel acquired from the Port
Authority of New York and New Jersey. They will replace three
99-seat theaters that now occupy the Shubert site. Two other
theaters of 83 and 99 seats, the Harold Clurman and the Samuel
Beckett, will be rebuilt in place, and support space, including new
rehearsal studios, will be provided.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
