<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2211 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-BRITAIN-ZIMBABWE-$ADV     05-11 1255
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-ZIMBABWE-$ADV14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITAIN, ZIMBABWE RIFT DEEPENS AS FORMER COLONY'S LAND WAR
CONTINUES
 &HT;    (950&AMP;ADD)
 &HT;    With primer box on Zimbabwe attached at end of story.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., May 14 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Britain and its former colony Zimbabwe are embroiled in
a rancorous conflict that some diplomats fear may make an already
dangerous crisis even worse.
</P>
<P>
   So deep is the rift between Britain and President Robert
Mugabe's government that the United Nations is expected to appoint
a mediator to attempt a reconciliation. U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan is expected to name a go-between within a few days, diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
   South Africa's President Thabo Mbeki raised the possibility of
U.N. mediation last week after talks between the British and
Zimbabwean governments failed to produce a resolution to the bloody
confrontation.
</P>
<P>
   The situation in Zimbabwe, the former Rhodesia, has been
deteriorating rapidly since February, when men who identified
themselves as veterans of the country's war of independence began
invading white-owned farms to take back land they believe belongs
to black Zimbabweans. Nineteen people have been killed in the
violence _ 16 of whom were black _ all of whom were opponents of
the Mugabe regime.
</P>
<P>
   Most white farmers, who own about a third of Zimbabwe's
productive land, are of British descent, and many hold United
Kingdom passports. About 70,000 of the country's 12.5 million
residents are white.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Mugabe, Zimbabwe's 76-year-old president, has vigorously
supported the farm raids and has stepped up his campaign of blaming
whites and Britain for the country's deepening economic crisis.
Mugabe, who led Zimbabwe's war in the 1970s against white rule,
suspended parliament in April and is required by the constitution
to hold a general election by August. The president, who fared
poorly in a constitutional referendum in February, has not yet set
a date.
</P>
<P>
   British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook has been unsparing in his
condemnation of Mugabe for the violence and chaos. Cook, Britain's
point man on last year's NATO attacks on Yugoslavia, has demanded
that Mugabe stop the violence and submit to free and open
elections.
</P>
<P>
   When Mugabe ignored his demands, Cook placed an embargo on arms
and military equipment to the former colony and suspended US$57
million in payments for land reform. Britain also orchestrated a
harsh condemnation of Mugabe's government by the Commonwealth of
States, the association of the United Kingdom and former British
colonies.
</P>
<P>
   After securing the rebuke, Cook took the opportunity to scold
Mugabe. ``That statement from the Commonwealth will have a
considerable impact around Africa, but perhaps particularly in
Zimbabwe, where President Mugabe had tried to pretend that the
problem is only Britain,'' Cook said. ``What President Mugabe is
crying out for is for us to treat him as a martyr so he can then
try to present himself, in elections, to his own people as somebody
who is standing up on their behalf against the old colonial
master.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, a furious Mugabe accused Britain of conspiring with
the white farmers to topple his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down with British imperialism and neo-colonialism,'' Mugabe
shouted to an aroused assembly of his party members earlier this
month. ``Let us realize that the world is inimical, that there is a
campaign, a very vicious campaign against Zimbabwe.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe said he found it ironic that the country's former
colonial masters would lecture Zimbabwe on human rights. ``What can
the British teach us ever? What lessons can we learn from them,
what justice, what morality? None.''
</P>
<P>
   The fiery president said he was unconcerned about Britain's
threat to end financial support. ``They can keep their money,'' he
told the jubilant party members. ``We want our land. And from our
land we will get money.''
</P>
<P>
   Whites are welcome to leave, he said. ``We can also assist in
showing them the various ways they can leave the territory,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   ``We want good relations with Britain, but the Britain of today
is hostile, and we would rather be on our own than have a hostile
friend,'' Mugabe said. ``A hostile friend is an enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hostility over the Zimbabwe crisis is common in England, where
sympathy with the white farmers is nearly universal. For weeks,
Britons have been inundated with images of bloodied and beaten
whites. The press here has been relentless in its attacks on Mugabe
and his regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't deny that it makes me really angry to hear Mugabe
saying whites this and whites that,'' said Simon Barnard as he
sipped a pint of bitters at the Red Lion pub in central London. ``A
few thousand Royal Marines would set things right for my money.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspapers have carried stories that Britain and its allies have
made plans for a military rescue of 20,000 European Union citizens.
The government has denied that it had devised any such plans, but
spokesmen have suggested that the government was planning for every
contingency.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki and other African leaders worry the dispute could get out
of hand and perhaps inspire other maverick African politicians to
take up Mugabe's hard-line tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki is expected to raise his reservations about the aggressive
British approach to Zimbabwe at a summit in London next week with
Cook and British Prime Minister Tony Blair. The South African
president is expected to castigate the British for responding with
harsh statements and actions to every new twist in Zimbabwe while
telling leaders that an African solution was needed.
</P>
<P>
   Mbeki's stance is backed by other African leaders and the
Commonwealth, the only organization now believed to have a chance
of defusing the situation in Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Former South African President Nelson Mandela, who was in London
last weekend, also called for a quieter approach to dealing with
Mugabe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is no use standing on hilltops and shouting about such a
highly sensitive matter,'' Mandela said. ``An approach through
diplomatic channels without much publicity is more likely to bring
about a positive result.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
