<HEADER>
A2216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-COMING-FILM-REVIEW-NY     05-11 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMING-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`COMING SOON': IT'S GOOD TO HAVE GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Production notes at end of review) 
 By A.O. SCOTT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Coming Soon'' explores two phenomena that have inspired
countless magazine articles and how-to guides, as well as
widespread anxiety and fascination: the female orgasm and the Ivy
League admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   Colette Burson's amiable new comedy follows three seniors at the
prestigious (and barely fictitious) Halton School in Manhattan as
they struggle to find academic advancement and sexual fulfillment.
The story focuses on a smart, winsome strawberry blonde named
Stream (Bonnie Root), and what plot there is turns on her search.
</P>
<P>
   Since this is a romantic comedy _ imagine a collaboration
between John Hughes and Whit Stillman in close consultation with
the editors of ``Our Bodies, Our Selves'' _ the happy outcome is
never in doubt, and the audience's pleasure along the way depends
on the heroine's momentary frustration.
</P>
<P>
   The ironclad conventions of the genre demand that she transfer
her affections from the bad rich boy (archetypally impersonated by
James Spader in ``Pretty in Pink'' many years ago and here played
by James Roday) to the social misfit whose true sensitivity is
camouflaged in sullenness and sarcasm. Within the rarefied social
world of Burson's script (written with Kate Robin), this role is
filled by young Henry Rockefeller (Ryan Reynolds), who declares his
rebellion by changing his last name to Lipschitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``How Emilio Estevez,'' exclaims Stream's friend Jenny (Gaby
Hoffmann), and it's not always clear whether the movie means to
endorse her mockery or refute it. Henry, who sports a wispy hipster
beard that vanishes and reappears from scene to scene, starts out
as an annoying poseur but by the end he's a rock 'n' roll
dreamboat.
</P>
<P>
   Jenny herself is subjected to similarly whimsical treatment.
Sometimes she's a self-absorbed, spoiled ninny, sometimes a fount
of hard-headed feminine wisdom, sometimes a sad, lonely girl decked
out in fishnet stockings and heels. But as portrayed by Hoffmann,
who may be the Madeline Kahn of the Clearasil set, she's also the
source of some of the film's best scenes, and the mouthpiece for
its funniest lines. ``My father bought me a learning disorder'' is
Jenny's blase explanation of why her low SAT scores won't keep her
out of Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Even Hoffmann's estimable comic energies are overshadowed by Mia
Farrow, her orange curls like a circus fright wig, who plays
Stream's mother, Judy, as a batty bundle of New Age nostrums and
neurotic rage. ``I feel 100 percent judgmental,'' this dogmatically
nonjudgmental purveyor of countercultural toothpaste shrills when
she discovers that her daughter is, as the saying goes, sexually
active.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie's most exacting satiric judgment is reserved for
Judy and her generation, which includes Spalding Gray, as a
pompous, self-promoting college admissions adviser, and, briefly,
Ryan O'Neal as Stream's father, predictably remarried to a
predictably bubble-headed younger woman.
</P>
<P>
   Judy, meanwhile, is dating a tiresome ceramicist played by Peter
Bogdanovich, who once directed O'Neal in a frothy romantic comedy
called ``What's Up, Doc,'' which also starred Barbra Streisand,
whose name is dropped in passing, as well as Madeline Kahn, whom we
may one day regard as the Gaby Hoffmann of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   While ``Coming Soon'' takes up the cause of a later generation,
it recalls the salutary candor of the '70s about sexuality,
especially female sexuality. Its frank good humor stands in sharp
contrast with the strange combination of timidity and
exploitiveness of more widely distributed recent teen-age comedies
like ``Down to You,'' ``Whatever It Takes'' and ``Committed,''
which can't decide whether young women's sexual desires should be
punished or ridiculed _ if they are even allowed to exist.
</P>
<P>
   Burson's pluck and honesty may indeed be the reasons that her
film _ like Sarah Kernochan's ``All I Wanna Do,'' another unusually
intelligent, unapologetically feminist vehicle for Hoffmann's
talents _ has been pushed to the margins of the entertainment
world. ``Coming Soon'' was passed over by several major studios and
twice threatened with the dreaded NC-17 rating by the Motion
Picture Association of America. It has now been released in an
R-rated version by Unapix Films.
</P>
<P>
   There is nothing gratuitous or graphic on the screen _ no
nudity, no skimpy starlet get-ups, nothing but respect, in fact,
for the young women who make up its cast and its intended audience.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, ``Coming Soon'' has its share of loose ends and its
longueurs. Given her subject matter, Burson might have been a bit
more attentive to narrative rhythms. No, the earth doesn't move,
but at least you don't feel used afterward.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `COMING SOON'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Colette Burson; written by Burson and Kate Robin;
director of photography, Joaquin Baca-Asay; edited by Norman
Buckley; production designer, Anne Stuhler; produced by Bandeira
Entertainment, Beau Flynn, Stefan Simchowitz and Keven Duffy;
released by Unapix Films/A-Pix Entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Cast: Tricia Vessey (Nell Kellner), Gaby Hoffmann (Jenny Simon),
Bonnie Root (Stream Hodsell), James Roday (Chad), Ryan Reynolds
(Henry Rockefeller/Lipschitz), Mia Farrow (Judy Hodsell), Spalding
Gray ( Jennings), Leslie Lyles (Vivien Simon), Ryan O'Neal (Dick)
and Peter Bogdanovich (Bartholomew). &QL; 
 &UR;  &LR; Running time: 91 minutes. &UR;  &LR; ``Coming Soon'' is rated R (under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes
several brief sexual scenes, some drug use and many lengthy
discussions of sexual matters. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
