<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2218 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOTHERKIND-BOOK-REVIE     05-11 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOTHERKIND-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MOTHERKIND': CARETAKER FOR BOTH SON AND MOTHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By MICHIKO KAKUTANI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In fierce, magical works like ``Black Tickets'' (1979) and
``Machine Dreams'' (1984) Jayne Anne Phillips depicted characters
torn between the dream of home _ ``a two-lane road densely overhung
with the deciduous trees of a more familiar world'' _ and the dream
of escape. Restless survivors of the '60s, these people found
themselves on the road, on the move, on the lam, and yet their very
rootlessness and dislocation left them haunted by the families and
vanished small-town worlds they had tried to leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   Though Kate, the heroine of Phillips' disappointing new novel,
shares an emotional resume with her earlier creations _ a girlhood
in Appalachia, years of aimless wandering, a sense of fragmentation
and loss _ she has now settled down to a life of quiet domesticity
in the outskirts of Boston. She has become what her husband, Matt,
calls ``the Queen of Safety'': she has ``circled the wagons''
around her family, and wants ``everything absolutely tacked down,''
as she struggles to take care of her newborn son and her ailing
mother, Katherine.
</P>
<P>
   In the hands of writers like John Updike, Anne Tyler and Alice
Munro, this sort of bourgeois existence has provided the makings of
a compelling fictional world. But in Phillips' case, the mundane
routines of daily life do not fully engage her imagination. As a
result, her decision to take a sort of `` Dalloway'' approach to
Kate's story, minutely recounting her every move and mood, feels
claustrophobic and static: a litany of a stressed-out woman's
struggles with diapers, baby prams, spoiled stepchildren, her
mother's pain medication and her own vagrant feelings.
</P>
<P>
   ``MotherKind'' has none of the hypnotic gothicism that gave
``Black Tickets'' and ``Shelter'' a subversive undertow, and the
bulk of its scenes, which take place in or near Boston, lack the
sure sense of place that lent books like ``Machine Dreams'' a
specific gravity and weight. In fact Phillips, who grew up in a
small West Virginia town much like the ones featured in her earlier
work, demonstrates little feel for New England in this volume: it's
a generic, yuppified world, defined vaguely by changing seasons and
elaborately celebrated holidays.
</P>
<P>
   For some reason Phillips has chosen not to use her superb gifts
as a ventriloquist in ``MotherKind'': Her characters do not talk to
us in the first person, as they have in so many of her previous
books, but are viewed through the distancing scrim of an omniscient
narrative that lends their thinking a strangely portentous,
second-hand feel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kate sometimes imagined herself a flat meadow ravaged by
wildfire, an unsuspecting meadow,'' Phillips writes. ``For years,
she'd avoided babies, which was easy, because most women she knew
didn't have them. Most women thought they were looking for men, not
babies. Kate thought now that they were wrong: they were all
looking for babies, even those who said they didn't want children,
or didn't like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Kate finds herself becoming a new mother and her own mother's
caretaker at the same time. As a girl she had been her mother's
confidante _ privy to the secrets of her parents' failing marriage
_ and now, she vows, she will be her mother's partner ``in this
long dance, this last boat trip.'' As Katherine grows weaker and
weaker, the roles of mother and daughter are reversed. It is Kate
who must monitor her mother's medication schedule and encourage her
to eat; it is Kate who tends life in the house, trying to balance
the demands of her mother, her son, her husband and his two
children. Her own work as a poet recedes, as that ``alternate
world'' of words, of association and image, takes a back seat to
her familial duties.
</P>
<P>
   In much the same way that she used her sensual imagination to
evoke the humid atmosphere of adolescence in ``Shelter,'' so
Phillips evokes the mysteries of pregnancy, birth and motherhood in
these pages: the hormonal haze, the heightening of memory and
expectation. Yet when she turns to the actual facts of Kate's life
_ going to the mall, preparing for an Easter party, taking the
children to the beach _ her poetic gifts falter, giving way to
flat-footed even perfunctory recitations of tasks performed and
noted.
</P>
<P>
   To make matters worse, her looping narrative, which continually
moves back and forth in time in small, jerky flashbacks, impedes
the forward momentum of the novel without adding much in the way of
felt emotion. The short scenes set back home in Appalachia, while
finely written, simply point up the pallor of the scenes set in
Boston.
</P>
<P>
   It is only in the last quarter of the book, as the illness of
Kate's mother accelerates, and Phillips focuses on the intricacy of
the mother-daughter bond, that the reader's sympathy is truly
engaged. These final pages have an immediacy lacking in the
remainder of the book, an unflinching willingness to look at the
complex machinery of familial relations and the obdurate fact of
mortality, and they remind the reader of the author's enormous
gifts as a writer, gifts that are sadly hidden in the remainder of
this volume.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `MOTHERKIND'
</P>
<P>
   By Jayne Anne Phillips
</P>
<P>
   295 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $24.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
