<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2226 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-NY-PALACE-PATIO-ART-2     05-11 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PALACE-PATIO-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PALATIAL PATIO'S FRESH AIR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Spain, Peru)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 9, 10 are being sent to
NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by
calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A palace was not a palace without a patio in the days
of Don Pedro Fajardo y Chacon, the Castilian nobleman who built the
Castle of Velez Blanco near the southeastern coast of Spain between
1506 and 1515. The crowning glory of his Gothic abode was its
patio, an ensemble that mated local Gothic and Spanish-Moorish
structural elements with architectural and decorative components
from the Italian Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Now fast-forward from the 16th to the 20th century and to the
Metropolitan Museum of Art, where, by one of those happy sets of
circumstances that often befall the Met, the Velez Blanco patio was
installed in 1964. A treasure in its own right, it also serves as a
grand entrance to the Thomas J. Watson Library and as a showcase
for the museum's collection of Italian Renaissance statuary,
including Tullio Lombardo's ``Adam'' (circa 1490-1495), an early
Renaissance example of a heroic nude.
</P>
<P>
   The courtyard, closed for refurbishing in 1997, reopens Friday,
and is closer than it has been in many years to its 16th-century
self. Its delicate carvings, modeled on monuments of Roman
antiquity, have been meticulously cleaned; more sophisticated
lighting has been installed; and greater authenticity has been
achieved by a new floor of white Macael marble, styled like the
patio's original paving and taken from the same quarry. The big
Fajardo coat of arms, formerly under the arcade, has been
reinstalled in a more visible position, high on the patio's west
wall.
</P>
<P>
   On the east wall is a richly colored Flemish tapestry of early
Renaissance vintage, ``The Triumph of Fame,'' thought to have once
been owned by Queen Isabella of Spain and recently acquired by the
Met. The museum has seized the occasion to mount two temporary
shows, ``Sculpture and Decorative Arts of the Spanish Renaissance''
and ``The Forgotten Friezes From the Castle of Velez Blanco.''
</P>
<P>
   The patio was originally built, at Don Pedro's behest, by an
itinerant group of Northern Italian sculptors and artisans who
carved its 2,000-odd marble parts and worked them into a graceful
ensemble of arcaded galleries, capitals, windows and door frames
that is considered one of the treasures of early Renaissance Spain.
By the early 19th century, after decades of political unrest, the
castle was abandoned, and at the turn of the 20th its owners sold
the intact patio to a Parisian dealer.
</P>
<P>
   In search of a centerpiece for his own castle going up at Park
Avenue and 67th Street, the investment banker and art collector
George Blumenthal bought the patio in 1913. Later, from 1934 to
1941, he served as president of the Met and bequeathed it his
treasure. In 1945, four years after his death, his house was razed,
and the patio was dismantled and shipped in blocks to the Met.
</P>
<P>
   It lay in storage until 1963, when, after a five-year research
project by Olga Raggio, now chairman of the Met's department of
European sculpture and decorative arts, it was reassembled at its
present site. Two extra arches and some modernities added during
the Blumenthal restoration were tossed out, and voila! In the words
of Raggio, who has also supervised the latest restoration, a
monument was returned to life.
</P>
<P>
   The show on the patio's balcony, ``The Forgotten Friezes From
the Castle of Velez Blanco,'' adds another twist to the monument's
lengthy saga. In 1992 the removal of an old heating system at the
Museum of Decorative Arts in Paris uncovered crates containing 10
large horizontal reliefs, unopened since their arrival, by bequest,
in 1905. Each relief is about 20 feet long and robustly carved in
Scotch pine. Their subjects are the triumphs of Julius Caesar and
the labors of Hercules, heroic ideals to which men of the
Renaissance aspired.
</P>
<P>
   Research by Monique Blanc, curator of the department of medieval
and Renaissance art at the Paris museum, established that the
friezes _ most with pieces missing _ were made for the reception
halls of the very same Velez Blanco castle from which the patio was
stripped. Six of the panels _ three devoted to Caesar, three to
Hercules _ are on view in the show.
</P>
<P>
   They are an impressive group, each panel squeezing a dense
medley of images into its limited space. The fact that they lacked
a religious theme, a rare circumstance in Roman Catholic Spain for
works displayed so prominently, is seen as evidence of Don Pedro's
preference for the classical tradition in which he was educated.
</P>
<P>
   The three friezes concerning Caesar depict his triumphal
procession through Rome. In the most salient, a fierce-looking
Caesar, waving a victory palm, rides on his chariot preceded by
officials carrying the fasces of authority, musicians, a dancing
jester and soldiers bearing booty. Behind him comes his horse,
really a unicorn with human feet, and the beginning of a long
procession of cavalry soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest of the Herculean friezes illustrates the
super-baby in his cradle strangling serpents sent by the goddess
Hera to destroy him, slaying the redoubtable Nemean lion that had
been ravaging the countryside and dispatching a three-headed
monster named Cacus who stole cattle that Hercules had liberated
from a three-bodied giant named Geryon.
</P>
<P>
   The two sets of friezes are stylistically different: the
Herculean figures are more naturalistic than the Caesarean and
closer to late Gothic in their landscape, composition and narrative
structure than to the Renaissance mode of the Caesar reliefs. Their
compositional density does not make for easy reading, but the
challenge is worthwhile.
</P>
<P>
   The other show, of 65 Spanish Renaissance sculptures and
decorative objects installed in a small gallery right off the
patio's main floor, includes many items from the Met's collections
that have not been publicly displayed before. Polychrome figures
and reliefs, glass and lusterware, church silver, metalwork, tiles
and a rare pair of tapestries from a set of 10 illustrating events
during the Catholic reconquest of Spain by Ferdinand and Isabella
give an idea of the cross-cultural influences on Spanish art by
Muslims and Western Europeans.
</P>
<P>
   Standout sculptures include a Spanish Pieta from the first half
of the 16th century, delicately carved in alabaster with traces of
polychromy, notable for the mingled expression of horror and pity
on the Virgin's face. ``The Holy Family With Saints Anne and
Joachim'' (1567-68), a relief in wood by Diego de Pesquera,
beautifully exemplifies the Spanish technique of estofado, in which
gilt and polychromy play off each other in complex patterning. A
later, startlingly realistic life-size statue of St. John the
Baptist (early 17th century) by Juan Martinez Montanes departs
innovatively from the estofado technique by the use of a more
natural polychrome finish.
</P>
<P>
   In the small selection of silver liturgical articles, an
elaborate mid-17th-century monstrance _ designed to protect and
display the consecrated wafer at Mass _ immediately strikes the
eye. Of silver gilt with applied enamels, it is attributed to Diego
de Atienza, a Spaniard active in Peru, who made it for a friar in
Lima. Its lower half is more in the austere early 17th-century
style of Philip II in Spain, but the elaborately rayed nimbus, or
sol, containing a glass compartment for the wafer, is much more
extravagant, anticipating later Peruvian developments.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   One of the most characteristically Spanish arts is wrought iron,
of which there are a few good examples here, though not enough. A
fine 17th-century grille of wrought iron and bronze by Francisco
Gonzales repeats elegantly proportioned skinny spindles for
decorative effect; a 17th-century drop-front desk of carved and
gilded bone and wrought iron with intricate geometrical patterning
shows the lingering influence of Islamic design.
</P>
<P>
   Plates, bowls, vases and other examples of lusterware, a type of
tin-glazed earthenware imitating Chinese porcelains, range from
refined to folksy. On the more restrained side is a double-handled
water bottle from Valencia (first half of the 16th century) whose
allover floral pattern is bordered by Moorish geo-metrics. But
there is naive exuberance in the treatment given a dish whose
crudely drawn image of the Christ child displays symbols of the
Passion on a band down the front of his robe.
</P>
<P>
   Glassmaking, an Andalusian specialty in Renaissance Spain later
refined by the immigration of Venetians to Catalonia, is
represented by a number of ebullient pieces, notable for their
florid design with lots of swirls and loopy handles. Among the
flasks, bowls, decanters and vases is a plain cow from the 17th
century, of pale pinkish glass tinged with purple, probably
inspired by the Muslim dromedary flasks then popular in Spain.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, a very good day for Spanish culture.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
