<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-CLEM-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METHODIST'S GRIEF TURNS TO HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Ohio, N.C., Va.)   By CARY McMULLEN   
 The Ledger, Lakeland, Fla.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ When the Rev. Kelly Ann Clem showed up last week at
the Cleveland Convention Center for the United Methodist Church's
General Conference, a woman checking for her name tag stopped and
smiled at her.
</P>
<P>
   ``She said, `I know who you are. I want you to know we prayed
for you.' That happens all the time. I feel powerfully connected to
my brothers and sisters, especially in the Methodist Church,'' Clem
said during a lunch break at the conference Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Clem is not one of the superstars of Methodism; not a bishop or
the pastor of a huge church. She is the pastor of Southside United
Methodist Church, in a rural community near Gadsden, Ala. But six
years ago, she was thrust into the national spotlight when Goshen
United Methodist Church, where she was serving then, was struck by
a tornado during a Palm Sunday worship service. Twenty people in
the church died, including Hannah Clem, the 4-year-old daughter of
Kelly and Dale Clem.
</P>
<P>
   Now 40, the mother of 8-year-old Sarah and 3-year-old Laurel
Hope, Clem and her husband, who is also an ordained Methodist
minister, are poised for a new venture of faith. They are set to
become missionary pastors in Lithuania. With her frosted hair cut
short and dangling earrings, Clem looks more like a suburban soccer
mom than a buttoned-down missionary.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back at the tragedy, she said, ``I remember everything
about that day. How can it be that all that happened in one hour in
church? It's still hard to believe it even happened to us.''
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of the chaos that ensued, with national television
cameras looking on, she spoke of faith and assurance. A long string
of funerals followed, including Hannah's, but the next Sunday, Clem
led Easter Sunday services for her congregation in an improvised
church.
</P>
<P>
   She was interviewed by Katie Couric and The New York Times.
Everyone marveled at how serene she appeared. But inside, she was
dealing with crushing grief. The day the tornado hit, she had told
her superiors that she couldn't go back to her church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a natural reaction,'' said Bishop Robert Fannin of the
North Alabama Conference. ``She was thinking, `How can I bear to be
reminded of my suffering?' But her tremendous understanding of
ministry called her to realize she had to work through the
suffering with her congregation.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of her parishioners, Clem said, ``They'd come to me and
throw their arms around me. They were being my pastor. I realized
we needed each other.''
</P>
<P>
   She cried every day for nearly two years, she said, yet she
stayed at Goshen until July 1996, long enough to see a new church
building constructed, in large part with funds that poured in from
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   A lifelong Methodist who spent her high school years in
Annandale, Va., Clem studied psychology at Furman University, then
went to Duke Divinity School in hopes of being a church-based
counselor, not a pastor. But at Duke, she said, ``I found out who I
was. I was in the company of people who thought like I did. It was
like all of me fit in. I realized God had led me to this point.''
</P>
<P>
   She met and married Dale Clem there and after graduating from
seminary in 1985, they returned to Dale's native Alabama as a
clergy couple. Eventually, Dale was appointed campus minister at
Jacksonville State University in Alabama while Kelly stayed with
parish work.
</P>
<P>
   Next month, they will be off to Lithuania, part of a new
initiative by Methodists in Eastern Europe. The Clems became
interested in the region through sponsorship of a child from
Belarus who was exposed to radiation from the Chernobyl disaster.
</P>
<P>
   Then in March, Dale Clem accompanied a medical missionary trip
to Lithuania. There are eight new Methodist congregations there,
and they were looking for clergy couples. Within two weeks of
submitting an application, the General Board of Global Mission told
them they had been approved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to keep them in North Alabama, but without question
Kelly and Dale can serve the church well anywhere they are. I can't
say enough about them,'' Fannin said.
</P>
<P>
   Clem said she still thinks about Hannah every day, but takes
comfort from her daughter, Laurel Hope, who was born with a
V-shaped birthmark on her forehead identical to one Hannah had.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we had to name this child Hope. I had hoped it
wouldn't be a girl; I thought it would be too hard. But she's so
funny, she's brought us laughter. We haven't stopped smiling since
she was born.''
</P>
<P>
   As for her poise at a moment when many would have been incapable
of speech, she said, ``We needed to tell our story. It may have
helped deal with the grief. It kept us from bottling it up. Most
people aren't as blessed as we were. It let us tell our story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll grieve for the rest of my life, but I think back
with such awe at how the congregation, strangers, even the media
became vehicles through which we could tell the story of our faith
in Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   (The Ledger of Lakeland, Fla., is a member of The New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
