<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 16:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2240 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT     05-11 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-PAGE1-CONSIDER-NYT 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Friday, May 12. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUGS (Paris) _ In a move that could change the face of
AIDS treatment in Africa and Asia, five major pharmaceutical
companies offered Thursday to negotiate deep cuts in the prices of
their drugs for poor nations plagued by the disease. The
announcement was made by the World Health Organization in Geneva,
and the companies were careful not to appear together to discuss
the offers. All were afraid of running afoul of American antitrust
laws, which prevent corporations not only from colluding to raise
prices, but from colluding to lower them. But even if the prices
drop steeply _ and cuts of 80 percent or more are being talked of _
no one expects an easy end to AIDS in the Third World. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-AFRICA (United Nations) _ Nine days ago, seven members of
the Security Council, led by Richard C. Holbrooke of the United
States, took off for Congo to gauge what small hopes for peace
might be salvaged from a conflict reaching across half a continent.
A lot was at stake, they thought: the political and economic
stability of at least six countries embroiled in the Congo; the
fabulous wealth of the country, one of Africa's largest and
richest, and the future of U.N. peacekeeping. By the time the team
returned to New York on Thursday, seven countries and several new
crises later, Congo had all but receded into the background of
broader concerns about Africa and its evolving political
leadership. And U.N. peacekeeping was on the ropes before a single
soldier was even sent to Congo. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-MEDIA (Moscow) _ Armed tax police on Thursday searched
the headquarters of a major Russian media group often critical of
the Kremlin, and company officials and politicians called on
President Vladimir Putin to explain the raid. The head of the
Media-MOST group said the search was a political action aimed at
limiting his company's freedom of speech. The police insisted it
was a criminal probe. (Summary from wires) By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA-TRADE (Washington) _ The Senate on Thursday decisively
approved legislation to promote commerce with Africa and the
Caribbean, ending more than five years of trade-bill defeats for
the Clinton administration. The 77-19 vote underscored the unusual
bipartisan support for a compromise measure hammered out by Senate
and House negotiators that would lower tariffs and quotas on
products from sub-Saharan Africa, the Caribbean and Central
America. With Senate approval and overwhelming backing from the
House, which approved the measure last week, the legislation now
goes to President Clinton, who strongly supports the bill and is
expected to sign it quickly. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   OIL-FOR-LAND (Washington) _ By a broad majority, the House on
Thursday approved a sweeping environmental measure that would
redirect money the government collects in oil-drilling royalties
for use in trying to protect sensitive areas from development. The
measure was backed by large numbers of Republicans as well as by
Democrats, reflecting the election-year lure of a bill that would
channel huge sums of money back to home districts while giving
lawmakers a chance to cast what many portrayed as a vote on behalf
of the environment. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL GENERAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CUBAN-BOY (Atlanta) _ Aggressively questioning both sides, three
federal appeals judges asked Thursday whether Elian Gonzalez is too
young to apply for asylum and whether his father's parental rights
are compromised because he's from Communist Cuba. The judges said
they would expedite a ruling but indicated it would be weeks before
they decide. (Summary from wires) By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ A firestorm swept through
the abandoned streets of Los Alamos on Thursday, burning as many as
400 homes, some down to their foundations, while frustrated
firefighters braced for wind gusts up to 60 mph. All 11,000 people
in Los Alamos were evacuated, and on Thursday morning another 7,000
fled suburban White Rock, where many evacuees had once sought
safety. At the storied Los Alamos nuclear laboratory, for the first
time shut down by fire, flames singed a research building but it
did not ignite. Explosives and radioactive material were protected
in fireproof facilities, lab officials said. (Summary from wires)
By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   FORD-SUVS (Atlanta) _ In an extraordinary statement for a large
corporation, Ford Motor Co., which started the sport utility boom
in 1990 and is now one of the world's two biggest producers of
sport utility vehicles, said that it faced a ``dilemma'' in
continuing to sell the highly profitable vehicles despite what the
company acknowledged were serious safety and environmental
problems. In a ``corporate citizenship report'' issued at the
company's annual shareholders' meeting here, Ford Motor
acknowledged that sport utilities contribute more than cars to
global warming, are permitted higher tailpipe emissions, and pose
safety and visibility dangers for other motorists. Ford said that
it was making progress toward solutions and was even looking for
alternatives to the off-road vehicles, although continuing to
produce them. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   ILOVEYOU-VIRUS (Manila, Philippines) _ Appearing nervous behind
a pair of dark glasses, a young computer student told reporters on
Thursday that ``it is possible'' that he released a destructive
program that crippled computer systems around the world. The
student, Onel de Guzman, 23, did not quite admit creating the ``I
love you'' program that spread rapidly last week through e-mail
systems in at least 20 countries. But when asked whether he might
have accidentally released the orogram, he replied, ``It is
possible.'' By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI (New York) _ Joking that ``rumors of my demise are
greatly exaggerated,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday that he
had not yet made a decision about whether he would stay in the race
for U.S. Senate. But he brushed aside repeated questions about
whether he had had an affair with his former communications
director, Cristyne F. Lategano, as the mayor's estranged wife said
this week. By Elizabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   EGAN-ARCHBISHOP (Undated) _ Making official an appointment
eclipsed by the death of Cardinal John O'Connor last week, the
Vatican on Thursday announced that Bishop Edward Egan of
Bridgeport, Conn., a canon lawyer and classical pianist with many
years in Rome, would become the next archbishop of New York.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   EGAN-PROFILE (Bridgeport, Conn.) _ A profile of Bishop Edward
Egan, chosen by Pope Paul II as the next archbishop of New York. By
Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
</TEXT>
