<SLUG> BC-SHADOW-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SHADOW BOXERS': IT'S NOT ABOUT MUSCLES
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Production notes appear at end of review.)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As much as some people would like to regard boxing as
nothing more than a brute contest of physical endurance, the sport
also has its spiritual side. The importance of attitude _ of
psyching yourself up and psyching out your opponent, of maintaining
a feeling of emotional and physical self-mastery under extreme
stress _ is almost as crucial to winning as physical strength and
agility. That point is brought home again and again in ``Shadow
Boxers,'' Katya Bankowsky's upbeat documentary portrait of women's
boxing, a sport that has only recently begun to be taken seriously
by promoters.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the movie, which opens today in New York, focuses on
Lucia Rijker, the Dutch prizefighter who is the closest thing to a
superstar in women's boxing. In and out of the ring, Rijker exudes
a take-charge charisma and calm self-containment that recall the
imperturbable solidity of a star like Queen Latifah. Determined and
relentless in the ring, Rijker, a Buddhist chanter, is a wonder to
watch as she maneuvers with a ferocity that seems unaffected by any
mood swings.
</P>
<P>
   Rijker, who was born in Amsterdam of mixed racial parentage, was
a teen-age kickboxing champion before she took up regular boxing.
In 1994 she moved to Los Angeles to go professional and was pursued
by several promoters, including Don King and Bob Arum. (She ended
up signing with Arum as his first female fighter.) Since 1997 she
has held the title of women's super lightweight boxing champion of
the world.
</P>
<P>
   Discussing the joys and stresses of boxing, Rijker is more
articulate than most fighters. The training process, she says, is
an intensely isolating experience because of the concentration on
self. That may explain why the movie offers no glimpses into her
personal life, although she does mention that she would one day
like to have a family. We also see her fitting in comfortably at an
otherwise all-male training camp. Here, she doesn't strain to be
one of the boys or insist on attending their raucous all-night
parties, at which she describes her fellow trainees as behaving
like ``eight animals.''
</P>
<P>
   For Rijker, isolation breeds self-knowledge. Boxing. she says,
forces her to go to scary psychological places she would normally
never visit and to confront her deepest fears. She is also aware of
how short-lived a profession it can be: She keeps a picture of
herself as a baby beside a portrait of a fighter who died in the
ring to remind herself of the risk of remaining in the sport for
too many years.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's portrait of Rijker is wound around a cursory survey
of women's boxing, which the Golden Gloves did not recognize until
1995. Rijker's professional career is contrasted with that of Jill
Matthews, a Golden Gloves flyweight, who jokes that she prepared
for her championship bout with ``a manicure and a pedicure.''
</P>
<P>
   Matthews' vision of the personal rewards of boxing closely
parallels Rijker's. For both women, it is a profoundly
self-empowering sport in which winning can be so heady that they
recognize its addictive potential. But for women, winning isn't
really a triumph of muscle power as it is of self-discipline or as
Matthews tersely phrases it, ``of mind over matter.''
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SHADOW BOXERS'
</P>
<P>
   Written, directed, produced, edited and released by Katya
Bankowsky; directors of photography, Anthony Hardwick and Tony
Wolberg; music by Zoel. Produced by Swerve Films.
</P>
<P>
   With: Lucia Rijker.
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 72 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
