<HEADER>
A2247 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-CHARM-FILM-REVIEW-NYT     05-11 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHARM-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DISCREET CHARM OF THE BOURGEOISIE': BUNUEL'S OLD AGE AND SECOND
CHILDHOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   By A.O. SCOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Luis Bunuel's career began with one of the most famous images in
cinema _the sliced eyeball of ``Un Chien Andalou,'' his 1928
collaboration with Salvador Dali _ and ended in the 1970s with a
loose trilogy of high-style surrealist extravaganzas for the French
producer Serge Silberman. The first of these _ ``The Discreet Charm
of the Bourgeoisie,'' which won the Academy Award for best foreign
film in 1973 _ has now been rereleased by Rialto Pictures, to
celebrate the centennial of the director's birth. More such
releases are promised, but `'The Discreet Charm'' is an excellent
place to renew acquaintance with Bunuel (who died in 1983), or to
meet him for the first time. In half a century of moviemaking that
took him from his native Spain to Mexico, Italy and France, Bunuel
experimented in a wide range of styles, from the Italianate
neo-realism of ``Los Olvidados'' (1950), to the tragic eroticism of
``Viridiana'' (1961) to the fashion-magazine sadomasochism of
``Belle de Jour.'' ``The Discreet Charm'' belongs both to his old
age and to his second childhood: It combines a masterful command of
the medium with a mischievous, anarchic sense of imaginative
freedom.
</P>
<P>
   The plot is a kind of metaphysical shaggy-dog story, involving
six highly cultivated people attempting to sit down to a civilized
meal together. Their efforts are obstructed first by a simple
misunderstanding _ guests arrive to find their unprepared hostess
in her satin dressing-gown _ and then by progressively weirder
occurrences involving international drug-smuggling, surprise
military exercises, and a succession of dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Before long the film forsakes linear narration altogether and
becomes a marushka doll of alternating realities, dreams within
dreams, flashbacks inside of tangents, periodically intercut with
shots of the six principals strolling along a desolate country road
on their way either to a grand picnic or a Technicolor remake of
``The Seventh Seal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But what is the meaning of this?'' asks Madame Thevenot (the
resplendent Delphine Seyrig, she of the satin dressing gown) when
the doings become especially peculiar. You may ask yourself the
same question, at once missing the point and getting the joke. The
fun of the film is that the characters play every scene with
unflappable propriety and absurd dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Rey _ decked out in gray plaid suits and leather gloves
and, at one point, an exquisite silk paisley robe _ is a debonair
Latin American ambassador who may be at the center of an
international drug smuggling operation, may have killed one of his
hosts in cold blood and may be having an affair with his best
friend's wife, played by the icily elegant Stephane Audran. When
the friend (Jean-Pierre Cassel) discovers the two in almost
flagrante delicto, they have a drink and make dinner arrangements
as though nothing untoward had taken place.
</P>
<P>
   Time may have rendered the object of Bunuel's satire a bit
obscure. The haute bourgeoisie whose fastidiousness he so lovingly
lampoons _ the recipe for a dry martini punctiliously offered by
Jean-Pierre Cassel is the director's own _ has faded into
obsolescence. The correctness of their manners may inspire more
nostalgia these days than derision, but if you look around, you
might notice the stealthy traces of Bunuel's influence in some
surprising places.
</P>
<P>
   His affectionate mockery, his reverence for feminine elegance
and the humanity at the heart of his ostentatious perversity make
him a sort of eccentric uncle to Pedro Almodovar. His Dada spirit
surfaces in ``Being John Malkovitch,'' just as his sense of
branching, overlapping realities resonates with the pop
inventiveness of ``Run Lola Run.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a spooky, primal dimension to the movie, an evocation
of childhood's deepest nightmares and richest sorrows, that may
remind you of ``The Sixth Sense.'' But the charm, at once elegant
and wildly indiscreet, is Bunuel's alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
