<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2249 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-AFRICA-TRADE-340&AMP;ADD-     05-11 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AFRICA-TRADE-340&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE APPROVES TRADE DEAL FOR AFRICA AND THE CARIBBEAN  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, W.Va., Mass., N.C.)  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT with DAVID STOUT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate voted overwhelmingly Thursday to grant
broad new trading privileges to dozens of countries in Africa and
the Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   The senators approved the measure in a 77-19 vote. The House
passed the bill a week ago by a 309-110 vote. The legislation,
which President Clinton is expected to sign shortly, will expand
duty-free access to U.S. markets for more than 70 nations.
</P>
<P>
   While Thursday's outcome was practically preordained, it was
nonetheless an occasion for celebration at the White House. Clinton
had made passage of the bill a high priority. And while the trade
measure ratified Thursday is totally separate from one to grant
normal trade relations to China, Clinton and other supporters of
the China bill hoped that the Africa-Caribbean accord would create
momentum for the China trade bill and show that Congress can act in
a collegial, bipartisan way on a major issue.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen Democrats joined six Republicans Thursday to oppose the
measure, with much of the opposition coming from lawmakers in
textile-producing states.
</P>
<P>
   Opposing lawmakers have argued that domestic-apparel companies
could suffer huge job losses because of relatively low-cost
imports. ``As cheap imports continue to flood the domestic market,
job losses will not only continue but increase,'' said Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., who opposed the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Maine's two Republican senators, Olympia Snowe and Susan
Collins, both considered less conservative than Helms, opposed the
bill. Democrats who voted no included Sens. Richard W. Byrd of West
Virginia and Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the bill, in the administration and on Capitol
Hill, have argued that it will boost the economies and living
standards in poor countries of sub-Saharan Africa and the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker J. Dennis Hastert argued before the House vote that
passage would be practical as well as humanitarian. ``By promoting
expanded trade, the United States will be minimizing the need for
foreign aid and disaster relief,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Behind the overwhelming votes in both chambers lay more than a
little horse-trading. For instance, in a concession to U.S. textile
makers, the amount of duty-free textile imports will grow gradually
over several years. Other favors seemed to have little to do with
the Caribbean or Africa, like a provision on men's suits made from
Canadian wool.
</P>
<P>
   And U.S. drug-makers succeeded in having deleted from the bill a
section that would make anti-AIDS drugs available more cheaply in
sub-Saharan Africa, which has been devastated by the disease.
Clinton issued an executive order on Wednesday to do what the
deleted provision would have done.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1705EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0200 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT12-COX     05-11 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    INDUSTRY DIVIDED OVER DIVIDING MICROSOFT
 &HT;    470&AMP;add. Moving in the (w) Washington and (f) financial
categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With Microsoft's legal fate unlikely to be settled
any time soon, the high-tech world found itself divided Thursday
over what impact the antitrust case will have on its own future.
</P>
<P>
   Some have joined the Microsoft camp. They argue that by branding
the software giant as a lawless monopolist, U.S. District Judge
Thomas Penfield Jackson has shaken up one of the most dynamic
sectors of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   In so doing, they say, the court ruling has curbed investor
confidence and contributed to the sharp recent slide in high-tech
market values.
</P>
<P>
   Others applaud the government plan to cleave Microsoft in two,
which Jackson must now weigh, as precisely what's need to energize
high-tech competition and spur fresh cycles of innovative growth.
</P>
<P>
   And there's also a faction that regards the most watched
antitrust battle in decades as beside the point when weighed
against other concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, many of us are so involved now in trying to
create Internet technologies, the whole Microsoft scenario isn't
considered that important,'' said David Peterschmidt, president of
Inktomi, an Internet infrastructure firm.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Lewis, a veteran computer consultant and columnist, has
little sympathy for Microsoft's past behavior or for the quality of
Windows, the world's most widely used desktop operating system.
</P>
<P>
   But, he adds, ``Technology is moving so fast that by the time
this legal mess is resolved, consumers may not even notice or care
whether Microsoft is one company, two, or 57. The Internet, not the
desktop computer, is becoming the center of power.''
</P>
<P>
   As Lewis sees it, ``the operating system is just the dial tone
that you need to make a call to the Internet. Just as any phone
company can provide the dial tone for a telephone these days, any
company _ not just Microsoft _ can provide the operating system for
an Internet-connected device.''
</P>
<P>
   Those views are shared by the top brass at Microsoft even as
they revile the government's breakup proposal and ask the judge to
summarily dismiss it as a viable remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, on Wednesday, when Microsoft offered up its own limited
remedial plan, co-founder and chairman Bill Gates was in Las Vegas
telling a trade show audience that cyberspace has become king of
the hill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet will change more in the next five years than it
has in its entire history,'' Gates said. ``We're at the verge of
moving beyond the transaction phase into a phase where we think of
the Internet as (an applications) platform.''
</P>
<P>
   In Gates's mind, to be sure, that platform revolves around
Windows 2000. He showed the convention audience how the company's
new heavy-duty operating system, plus a cluster of related
products, address each of the areas that Microsoft sees as crucial
to the Internet's growth.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts who see merit in breaking up Microsoft nonetheless
see problems down the road. In the rapidly growing market for
Internet appliances, hand-held devices and wireless services, many
software engineers find it hard to divine where the operating
system ends and applications begin.
</P>
<P>
   While some insiders view Microsoft's conduct-based plan as more
realistic than the government's formula, they also fear that the
software giant wouldn't keep its side of the legal bargain.
</P>
<P>
   As Jesse Berst, a top online editor for Ziff-Davis, puts it:
``Fixing the Microsoft problem is a delicate operation. The
government proposes to use a meat ax. Microsoft's counterproposal
is better suited to the crime. But the company's conduct has proven
that we can't take halfway measures. Only cutting the company in
two will prevent it from committing more crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   But Todd Spangler, another Ziff-Davis analyst, holds that ``in
the unlikely event the proposed breakup of Microsoft holds up on
appeal many months from now, it would only prevent a singular
Microsoft from competing in the next generation of Internet-based
computing.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, said Jim Kobielus, an analyst at the Burton Group Corp.
in Midvale, Utah. ``Plenty of companies have built their businesses
on Windows-specific applications and have done very well with it,
so why should the Microsoft applications (company) be any
different? Just because the judge (might say) mommy and daddy can't
live together any more doesn't mean the children won't still play
with each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
