<HEADER>
A2253 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-ART-REVIEW-MARKETPLAC     05-11 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-REVIEW-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SHOWCASE FOR EMERGING TALENT NURTURED WITHIN THE SAME
ENVIRONMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By HOLLAND COTTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Good business is the best art,'' said Andy Warhol,
who might have been an accountant if he hadn't been an artist. His
once-provocative words would probably sound common-sensical to an
MFA candidate today. At present they are serving as the title for
an exhibition at the Bronx Museum of the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The show, organized by Marysol Nieves and Lydia Yee, celebrates
the 20th anniversary of the museum's Artist in the Marketplace
program (AIM, for short), intended to coach emerging artists in the
byzantine process of establishing a career.
</P>
<P>
   The program's drill is as follows. Every year, three dozen
artists are chosen to participate in a 12-week seminar led by the
museum's curatorial staff and an assortment of art world guests,
who advise on everything from landing a gallery to writing grants
to dealing with irksome realities like taxes and critics. As a
parting gesture, the museum gives the artists a group show, a
symbolic launching pad.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes the future happens fast. Several recent program alumni
can be spotted in high-profile shows around town just now, from the
Whitney Biennial (Rina Banerjee, 1996), to ``Greater New York'' at
P.S. 1 (Mark Dean Veca, 1997; Nicole Awai and Nadine Robinson, both
1998), to ``Making Choices'' at the Museum of Modern Art (Katharina
Bosse, 1998, and Glenn Ligon, 1984).
</P>
<P>
   Three of Ligon's text-based paintings about racial identity open
the Bronx survey. Dating from 1990, they have acquired
near-canonical status in the art of that period, as has the work of
other AIM veterans seen here. Byron Kim's skin-colored abstract
paintings and evocations of Asian-American immigrant life by Tomie
Arai and Lynne Yamamoto are history book material.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard to see such icons with fresh eyes in the context
of the Bronx Museum's episodic sampler. But it is intriguing to
learn that all of these artists were shaped by the same
institutional environment, and to find as one moves through the
rest of the show that their basic concerns continue to be explored,
if in more oblique terms, by their successors.
</P>
<P>
   Banerjee's ``Postcolonial-Spider-Broom Woman,'' for example, a
fantastic web of gauze, beads and industrial tubing, has many
things to say about the dangers and seductions of exoticism, but
says them indirectly. An installation by Ernesto Pujol titled
``Peter Pan's Table'' approaches the anxieties of a homosexual
childhood with sly, theatrical wit: sculptures of male genitals are
lined up like pastries on a little wooden desk, with a punishing
pair of scissors lying nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Lane Twitchell, who is in his early 30s, draws on his Mormon
background in imaginative ways. A substantial selection of his
output has been brought together here, from a straightforward
portrait painting he contributed to the 1997 AIM group show to some
of the elaborate, image-packed cut-paper pieces he has done since.
</P>
<P>
   The formal intricacy of Twitchell's recent work, with its
painstaking use of repetition and detail, finds echoes elsewhere:
in Seong Chun's sculptures crocheted from text-covered strips of
paper, in Valeska Soares's bundles of thorny branches swathed in
cotton batting and in Sarah Sosnowy's mural-size,
circles-within-circles mandala formed from dozens of smaller
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Painting has itself always held an important place in AIM
exhibitions, and it does so here. An anarchic, attention-grabbing
concoction by Fabian Marcaccio (silicone gel, printed fabric and
plaster are among the ingredients) stumbles off the canvas and
tears across the wall. By contrast, a sexy wall piece by Paul Henry
Ramirez is executed with the pin-point precision of an Islamic
miniature.
</P>
<P>
   Photography is the odd-medium-out here, though there are
first-rate entries by Laura Larson, and Bosse, who was born in
Finland, comes across as a particularly versatile artist. She is
represented by two very different architectural series made five
years apart, and neither resembles the striking figurative images
she showed at the Bronx Museum in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   These artists are just the tip of the AIM iceberg. Work by
dozens of their colleagues is also included in the roundup, in
slide format or displayed in flat files. The slides, set out on
light boxes, are a little difficult to see, but give a sense of the
sheer variety of sensibilities that have passed through the museum
over a couple of decades. The material in the flat files naturally
has a more immediate presence and is well worth spending time with.
</P>
<P>
   Several artists seen in the main exhibition are represented
here. But so are AIM graduates equally worthy of mainstage
attention, among them Brian Mukerjee, Nicole Carstens, Brian
Guidry, Skowmon Hastanan, Matthew Deleget, Max-Carlos Martinez,
Valerie Atkisson and Tamara Mewis. Some have gone on to bigger
things. They all look good here. And they are all part of an
important history.
</P>
<P>
   On July 13, the 20th annual Artist in the Market show will open
in the museum's lower galleries, and will run concurrently with the
anniversary gathering through the summer. They make sense together.
One speaks of solid accomplishment; the other promises surprises.
That's a business-as-usual combination for art in the Bronx.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
