<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN12-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   EDS: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Standing tall in a roomful of first graders
</P>
<P>
   By Gary Borders
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ The first-graders at Cushing Elementary
were quietly working in their seats when I showed up. The teacher
was across the hall, so all eyes were on me as I walked in, feeling
self-conscious, holding a box filled with bags of Gummy Bears, a
stack of Sunday comics and a couple of children's books I would
read as a backup if I ran out of other tricks with which to
entertain a gaggle of 6-year-olds.
</P>
<P>
   I stood there, feeling rather tall, a rare feeling for me. ``So,
are you our guest?'' one kid chirped up. I allowed as how I was.
</P>
<P>
   I was unaccountably nervous. My job involves a fair amount of
public speaking, at ribbon cuttings, civic clubs and for nine years
in a college classroom teaching journalism part-time. I've spoken
in front of several hundred people and not been particularly
nervous. Maybe I wasn't especially erudite or entertaining, but I
didn't waste a lot of time agonizing over it. Now here I was about
to speak to a couple dozen rug rats, and my palms were sweaty, my
heart racing.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher came back and introduced herself. I've adopted her
classroom for the next year, which means I have agreed to show up
on occasion to help out, maybe take the kids on a field trip or
two. When we talked on the phone, she was pleased but nonplussed as
to what I would be doing. That made two of us.
</P>
<P>
   I am my father's son. He couldn't wait until we kids became
adults so we could carry on intelligent conversations with him.
Same with me. As much as I loved my girls when they were little, I
identify with them a lot more now that they're allegedly adults,
albeit adults still on my payroll. Now I had a roomful of
bright-eyed and absolutely adorable children wondering what bag of
tricks I had brought on this rainy morning. I had visions of
children dropping off to sleep as I droned on about newspapers to
children who have just barely learned to read. At least I had the
Gummy Bears.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher introduced me and instructed her charges to sit in
their chairs, zip their mouths and open their ears in a cadence
well familiar to the children. The kids obeyed immediately.
First-grade teachers are doing God's work is all I can say.
</P>
<P>
   We started talking about the newspaper. The kids knew a
surprising amount about what's in a newspaper and began to
enthusiastically volunteer information. One little girl proudly
announced that she had once had her picture in the paper. Another
said his dad reads the stories to everyone each night around the
dinner table. The subject of recycling came up. I assured these
miniature environmentalists that we recycled our newspapers and
encouraged everyone to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   I loosened up. This crowd wasn't as tough as I thought it was
going to be. Probably what helped is that I could comfortably sit
in a little kid's chair and be at eye level with them. There are
advantages to being short.
</P>
<P>
   Now came time to delve into the bag of tricks. Using a cheat
sheet, and with a few false starts, I made a hat out of the
four-page Sunday comics section _ what's called a pressman's hat.
Press operators used to wear these to keep ink out of their hair,
though in truth I haven't seen somebody wear one in at least 20
years. Even though I had practiced several times, I still nearly
messed up. Pressure. Finally, I managed to get a hat made and
quickly crammed it on the head of a freckled-face boy wearing a
Dallas Cowboys jersey before it fell apart. He gave me a big,
gap-toothed grin in return. I left the instructions and some extra
newspapers for the teacher. No way was I going to try to make two
dozen hats while being watched by that many eyes.
</P>
<P>
   The teacher had found a ``Curious George'' book that involved
the main character delivering newspapers by bicycle, so we all
gathered around while I read the story, punctuated with a steady
stream of comments from the kids. They are so innocent and
guileless at that age, taking joy in a simple story about a monkey
whose curiosity gets him in trouble time and again.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I was out of tricks and concluded by handing out the bags
of Gummy Bears, each of which came with a couple of balloons with
the newspaper's logo on them. The teacher kindly allowed the kids
to dig into the candy, which made both her and me extremely
popular. At her urging, the kids all clapped and then gave me a
``round of applause,'' which is a circular version of The Wave. I
promised to come back in the fall, though there will be a fresh set
of first-graders to meet.
</P>
<P>
   I'm looking forward to my next visit. Maybe I can learn how to
make a pressman's hat without looking at the directions by then.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of the Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. E-mail: gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
