<TEXT>
<P>
   EDS: EMBARGOED FOR SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   Remembering a simpler time
</P>
<P>
   By Ernest Murray
</P>
<P>
   Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ It must be hard for Judy Niewald Vasquez of
Gallup, N.M. to write a mean letter _ not that she would ever have
to. Her handwriting is so precise, so elegant and so proper that I
have no doubt that people go out of their way to be just as
courteous as she must be.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Vasquez writes, ``I grew up in southern Indiana in a town
of 700 people, but I think my childhood was not different from most
kids in small towns.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, read for yourself her list of ``remember when...''
</P>
<P>
   _ Everyone's mother and grandmother darned socks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Driving a pickup truck meant you were a farmer or rancher.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your mom kept a grease can, saving fried-out grease to use in
making lye soap.
</P>
<P>
   _ A family didn't buy anything they could make or grow.
</P>
<P>
   _ Listening on the party line was a common activity for farm
wives.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your dad worked six days a week and your mother cooked seven
days a week.
</P>
<P>
   _ You carried a coal-oil jug to the store to be filled so your
mom would have fuel for the stove to cook supper.
</P>
<P>
   _ You didn't drive anywhere you could walk to.
</P>
<P>
   _ Many elderly peoples' nightmare was that they would outlive
the money they had saved during their lifetime and no relatives
would take them in and they would end up at the county poor farm.
</P>
<P>
   _ You washed your clothes and your hair in cistern water to make
them softer.
</P>
<P>
   _ Velvetta cheese came in a wooden box.
</P>
<P>
   _ You heated your bathwater on the stove in a tea kettle.
</P>
<P>
   _ You make aftershave lotion by mixing some store-bought hand
lotion and rubbing alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   _ Your mom sent you for a bucket of water from the well just
before lunch so everyone would have cool water on a hot summer day.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com.Website:
www.coxnews.com/newsservice.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
