<HEADER>
A2258 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HELDUP-FILM-REVIEW-NY     05-11 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELDUP-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HELD UP': A FILM AND AUDIENCE HELD HOSTAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
By A.O. SCOTT    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Jamie Foxx is a witty actor and an intuitive comedian
who can sometimes manage to make the lamest material _ the WB
sitcom that bears his name, for instance _ amusing.
</P>
<P>
   As if to test his powers, ``Held Up,'' which might have worked
better as an episode of ``The Jamie Foxx Show,'' strands its star
in the middle of the Arizona desert (actually the outskirts of
Regina, Saskatchewan) with nothing to do but hold a gun to his own
head and negotiate with the North Butte sheriff's department on
behalf of the inept stickup man (Eduardo Yanez) who has taken him
hostage.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, causally directed by Steve Rash from what is a
moderately jokey script by Jeff Eastin, squanders some promising
possibilities and commits the inexplicable crime of separating Foxx
from his co-star, Nia Long, almost the whole time. In the opening
scenes, the two of them, playing Mike and Rae, a Chicago couple
vacationing in their newly purchased vintage Studebaker, show a
rare comic chemistry that turns explosive once Rae discovers that
he has squandered their nest egg on his cherished ride.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of fighting it out in the tumbleweeds, Rae hops onto a
pickup truck full of cowboys and spends the rest of the movie
drinking tequila in the Las Vegas airport, leaving Mike at the
mercy of a pubescent car thief, a passive-aggressive convenience
store owner, a gang of bumbling robbers and eventually a SWAT team.
</P>
<P>
   He's probably better off. Long, whose hauteur is an aspect of
her beauty, is nobody you would want to mess with, but she's a
perfect foil for Foxx's quicksilver riffing. He can shift, as if in
midair, from a strut to a grovel, and his funniest lines tend to be
the ones he mutters under his breath, taking back whatever foolish
boast that just popped out of his mouth. Behind his narrow eyes you
can see a darting, improvisational intelligence. If only he used
more of it in selecting his projects.
</P>
<P>
   The fun of ``Held Up'' is all in the setup, which plays off the
barely suppressed panic a black man might feel finding himself
stranded in a remote spot populated by strange white people who
assume he must be either a criminal or a celebrity. A young
videogame player decides Mike must be Puff Daddy, and soon the
local news is reporting that Mike Tyson is involved in a hostage
situation out in North Butte. But the movie's farcical momentum is
taken prisoner along with Mike and his fellow shoppers, who include
a mystical biker type (Michael Shamus Wiles) and a sweet blond
woman with a purse full of condoms (Sarah Paulson).
</P>
<P>
   The actors, to their credit, work hard to help Foxx squeeze what
sparks he can from a static situation that consists of two groups
of people staring each other down through plate glass windows (soon
shot away for the convenience of the cameras) and waiting for the
next thing to happen. There is an exploding hot dog, a dead body in
a crate, a skunk and a flesh wound caused by a piece of Cool Ranch
Dorito shrapnel, but the steady accumulation of absurdity that is
necessary for real farce is missing.
</P>
<P>
   The audience is made to sit around, like the townspeople who
have gathered outside the store, hoping to hear a good joke or two.
And there are one or two, which I won't ruin for you. But by the
end, even the irrepressible Foxx seems tired and defeated, and we
can only hope he perks up in time for his next movie.
</P>
<P>
   Fans of ``Northern Exposure,'' meanwhile, may enjoy seeing Barry
Corbin and John Cullum, who played the astronaut and saloon keeper
of Cecily, Alaska, reunited on the big screen, playing, of all
things, a sheriff and a shopkeeper. If only someone had thought to
bring along that moose.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HELD UP'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Steve Rash; written by Jeff Eastin, based on a story
by Eastin and Erik Fleming; director of photography, David A.
Makin; edited by Jonathan Chibnall; music by Robert Folk;
production designer, Rick Roberts; produced by Neal H. Moritz,
Jonathon Komack Martin and Stokely Chaffin; released by Trimark
Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   With: Jamie Foxx (Mike), Nia Long (Rae), Barry Corbin (Pembry),
Jake Busey (Beaumont), John Cullum (Jack), Micheal Shamus Wiles
(Biker), Sarah Paulson (Mary) and Eduardo Yanez (Rodrigo). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 91 minutes. ``Held Up'' is rated PG-13 (parents
strongly cautioned). It has some mild profanity and a fair amount
of wildly off-target gunfire.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1712EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
