<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TRAFFIC-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HUMAN TRAFFIC' TAKES A TRIP INTO THE HIGH LIFE WITHOUT THE
COMEDOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Justin Kerrigan knows his rave scene. The Brit native makes his
feature debut writing and directing ``Human Traffic,'' a portrait
of the chemical generation in Cardiff, Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Five funky twentysomethings leave soul-killing customer service
jobs behind every Friday night for a weekend of, in the words of
film spokesman Jip (John Simm), ``clubs, pubs, drugs and party!''
</P>
<P>
   Jip, who works at a Gap clone by day, guides us through his
weekend Odyssey like a hopped-up Homer. He's a master of
ceremonies, introducing us to his crew, interpreting local custom
and explaining the fine points of club culture in narrative asides
and comic skits.
</P>
<P>
   While some of these gags are inspired, Kerrigan's approach is
literal minded and hampered by colorless scripting and a
frustrating tendency to milk every joke dry.
</P>
<P>
   Jip's mates includes best bud Koop (Shaun Parkes), a would-be DJ
rapper who pushes overpriced American vinyl on local kids like a
hip-hop P.T. Barnum; Koop's fast-food drone girlfriend Nina (Nicola
Reynolds), who despises her robotic job; live-at-home layabout Moff
(Danny Dyer), who wears his unemployment like a self-deluding badge
of moral courage; and LuLu (Lorraine Pilkington), Jip's gal-pal,
whose mantra that she's just fine being single, thank you, doesn't
fool anyone.
</P>
<P>
   They all drop Ecstasy, chase it with pints of ale, head for the
hottest club in town and top it off with a night of great sex. Not
exactly a cautionary tale, and the closest Kerrigan comes to even
moderating his portrait is odd-man-out Moff's throbbing hangover
and the completely contrived observation: ``We'll all outgrow this
soon, when the comedown is worse than the high.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a certain honesty in his celebration of restless youth,
if not exactly a thoughtfulness, and his embrace of sensory
pleasures and irresponsible fun should connect with his target
audience. He embraces his characters, and there's no doubt that he
lives and loves the milieu. What he misses is the spark, the
sensibility and creative charm of the other, better films that
inspired him.
</P>
<P>
   For all his flash and fantasy, Kerrigan lacks the profane poetry
and dangerous edge of ``Trainspotting'' and the sheer sense of
surprise of ``Go.'' What's left is a bubbly, high-spirited paean to
the joys of pharmaceutical phun that grooves to a throbbing beat
but constantly trips over flat, prosaic dialogue and literal,
lifeless sight gags.
</P>
<P>
   Human Traffic. Directed and written by Justin Kerrigan. Cast:
John Simm, Lorraine Pilkington, Shaun Parkes, Nicola Reynolds,
Danny Dyer. Miramax. 100 minutes. Rated R for language, sexual
themes, brief nudity and drug use.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1715EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0208 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-BATTLEFIELD-SPI &LR;      05-11 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-BATTLEFIELD-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOGIC IS LOSER AS HUMANS FIGHT FOR FREEDOM IN `BATTLEFIELD EARTH' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: C  
 By SEAN AXMAKER  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Man is an endangered species,'' alerts the introductory card
to ``Battlefield Earth,'' the adaptation of L. Ron Hubbard's ``Star
Wars''-inspired, epic sci-fi novel. It should have warned us that
logic was also hitting hard times.
</P>
<P>
   It is the year 3000. After a millennium of brutal subjugation by
the Psychlos (seemingly an unholy mating of the Klingon and Ferengi
races from ``Star Trek''), humans live like cavemen in the
irradiated wilds, foraging through a dying Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Rebellious young Jonnie Goodboy Tyler (Barry Pepper, in flowing
locks and an unchanging expression of determined sincerity)
searches for a better land and discovers a race of intergalactic
corporate pirates, 8-foot alien slavers sucking the planet dry of
resources in the name of profit.
</P>
<P>
   Terl (John Travolta) is an especially devious Psychlo, with a
plot to make a fortune mining a cache of gold discovered in the
wilds. Psychlos can't breathe the air so they live under a dome
pumped full of their homeworld gases and the radiation reacts with
their chemistry, so greed and arrogance get the better of common
sense.
</P>
<P>
   Terl teaches scrappy Jonnie the whole of Psychlo knowledge,
gives him a spaceship, and sends him out with a pack of humans to
secretly mine the vein virtually unsupervised. Cocky is one thing,
but this egocentric complacency stretches credulity even for these
swaggering space pirates.
</P>
<P>
   Jonnie uses the time to search for American military bases
(amazing how those planes and armaments survive the centuries
intact and juiced up), turn savages into expert jet pilots on the
seven-day training plan, and plot the freedom of humankind from the
vicious slavers. Can't you just see Mel Gibson in the role
screaming ``Freedom!!!'' to a bunch of primitive guerrillas
wielding machine guns and lobbing missiles?
</P>
<P>
   Travolta has the time of his life as the blackmailing Terl,
tossing his head back to cackle every time he achieves the perfect
double-cross. Forest Whitaker, is his dim assistant, fumbling and
groveling as a junior-league con-artist constantly outmaneuvered by
Terl. This toxic Abbot and Costello team provide much-needed comic
relief in an otherwise humorless paean to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Director Roger Christian, a former production designer and set
decorator, creates a world of crumbling dead cities and empty malls
turned into human hunting grounds but constantly trades logic for
effect. After a thousand years of occupation, we're supposed to
believe this technologically advanced, supremely crafty and
ruthlessly efficient race is still holing up in the decaying
remains of human civilization? These guys can't even fit through a
doorway!
</P>
<P>
   They're also not very bright. They can't be _ the plot depends
on the most ludicrous decisions and senseless actions ever made by
a thinking race. How else can a plucky tribe of hunters and
gatherers defeat the most powerful race in the galaxy? Heart, soul
and courage will get you only so far _ what you really need is an
enemy so stupid they invite their own demise. And a few Harrier
jets don't hurt either.
</P>
<P>
   Battlefield Earth. Directed by Roger Christian. Screenplay by
Corey Mandell and JD Shapiro, from the novel by L. Ron Hubbard.
Cast: John Travolta, Barry Pepper, Forest Whitaker, Kim Coates,
Richard Tyson. Warner Bros. 117 minutes. PG-13 for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
