<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2262 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-FILM-KAHUNA-SPI &LR;      05-11 0529
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KAHUNA-SPI </SLUG>
  
 spacey sly, delightful in small-scale `big kahuna'  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 Our Grade: B  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With his ``American Beauty'' success, Kevin Spacey has finally
achieved something like superstar status, but he's smart enough to
realize that his true appeal _ and long-term future _ lies in
playing quirky characters in commercially risky, heavily dramatic
situations.
</P>
<P>
   So, instead of cashing in his Oscar for a $20 million salary and
a string of bloated Hollywood comedies and action vehicles, he's
appearing this year in two _ possibly three _ small-scale,
low-budget art films made by his own production company, Trigger
Street Productions.
</P>
<P>
   The first of these, and the first film for which he's taken a
solo producer credit, is ``The Big Kahuna,'' a low-low budget,
three-character drama that was shot in a single New York City
studio set last February on a Roger Corman schedule: a mere 16
days.
</P>
<P>
   Adapted by chemical engineer-turned playwright Roger Rueff from
his own play, the film takes place in a hotel hospitality suite
rented by a industrial lubricant company at a convention in
Wichita, Kan., where three marketing reps are out to snare a vital
new account: the big kahuna of the title.
</P>
<P>
   Spacey plays Larry, a brash, successful, 40ish hustler who seems
to genuinely enjoy the thrill of the chase, never asks himself too
many probing questions about life, and is prone to outbursts of
irony delivered in that irresistibly cynical Kevin Spacey style.
</P>
<P>
   His partner and long-time pal is Phil (Danny DeVito), a recently
separated veteran in his early 50s who has gradually tried of the
hypocrisy and indignity of the sales game, and finds himself
increasingly pondering the futility of his existence in
introspective asides.
</P>
<P>
   And the catalyst for the drama is Bob (Peter Facinelli), a pious
young fundamentalist Baptist at his first convention, who finds
himself in instant conflict with the values of the older salesmen
and refuses to compromise his principles to snare the kahuna.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 90 minutes, Larry tears into Bob, Bob retaliates in
his own inadequate way, and the increasingly melancholy Phil tries
to moderate. In the process, all three characters regularly reveal
new levels of their inner selves, and ultimately learn a valuable
lesson about life.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly a great play, and its enigmatic, open-ended
conclusion is a bit of a letdown. Visually, first-time director
John Swanbeck has not even tried to cinematically open the
proceedings up, and the result never lets us forget its theatrical
origin.
</P>
<P>
   But the dialogue is delightfully acerbic and often profound,
Spacey is a delight to behold in this kind of slyly aggressive
role, and he's generous enough as a producer to allow DeVito to
quietly steal the movie with the most totally appealing and
seemingly heartfelt performance of his career.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Kahuna. Directed by John Swanbeck. Screenplay by Roger
Rueff, from his play. Cast: Kevin Spacey, Danny DeVito, Peter
Facinelli. Lions Gate. 90 minutes. Rated R for language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
