<SLUG> BC-MOMS-MARCH12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'WALL OF GUN DEATHS' UNVEILED TO HIGHLIGHT GOALS OF MARCH
 &HT;    Eds: The notation (underscore) in the Web address at the end
stands for that symbol.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adding a dramatic backdrop to their push for gun
control, organizers of the Million Mom March joined some of the
nations' mayors Thursday at a memorial wall bearing the names of
4,001 victims of gun violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are the forgotten casualties of a silent war,'' said
Mayor Anthony Williams of Washington, comparing the ``Wall of Gun
Deaths'' to the memorials for Vietnam and Korean war veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``These victims unfortunately died for no great cause. They
didn't die in some far-away conflict. They died on our streets.
They died in our neighborhoods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The names on the wall came from a report by the U.S. Conference
of Mayors that sought to quantify gun deaths in the first 11 months
since the April 1999 massacre at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The black wall _ 12.5 feet high and 54 feet long _ is standing
in two pieces on a large stage on the National Mall, the
centerpiece of Sunday's rally for ``sensible'' gun control.
</P>
<P>
   The Mother's Day event is expected to attract 150,000 marchers
to the nation's capital as well as hundreds of thousands to similar
rallies in 67 other cities, including Atlanta and Austin.
Organizers believe this march will be the largest rally ever for
gun control.
</P>
<P>
   Among the names on the wall, written in chronological order of
death, is that of Blake King, who died last year at 17.
</P>
<P>
   His uncle, Mayor Scott King of Gary, Ind., told the story of his
nephew's death. What started as a fist fight between two teenagers,
he said, ended up with one of them running next door, grabbing his
father's unlocked gun and shooting Blake in the head.
</P>
<P>
   Visibly emotional, King recalled the young man's funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different ball game when you sit in a church,'' he
said, ``and you hear sobbing behind you and it's your own children
sobbing for the loss of their cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   King thanked the ``mothers of America'' for their grass-roots
campaign to stop gun violence. He noted it was also mothers who
``stepped up and stood up and spoke up'' years ago to begin what
has become a successful campaign to reduce drunk driving.
</P>
<P>
   The mayors' report is based on the responses of 100 cities to
requests for information. Several large cities, such as New York
and Los Angeles, were not included in the survey, which means the
total number of gun deaths since Columbine is likely much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Among the cities surveyed, Chicago reported the most deaths at
415, followed by Detroit with 364 and Baltimore with 245.
</P>
<P>
   Some cities reported only homicides, while others included
suicides and accidental shootings. Of the 4,001 reported, 658 were
suicides and 25 were accidents.
</P>
<P>
   About one-fifth of the names on the wall belong to people under
21, including 791 people 11 to 20 years old and 25 children under
11.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.millionmommarch.com,
www.usmayors.org/uscm/gun(underscore)safety/2000report.htm
</P>
<P>
   Eunice Moscoso's e-mail address is eunicem(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
