A2266 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0512-CO     05-11 0770
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tax plan may work against Bush
 &HT;    By Dave McNeely
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ George W. Bush's proposal for a huge tax cut may
turn out to be an albatross to his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Bush gave the first hint he was positioning himself for a
presidential campaign tax cut suggestion on Nov. 13, 1996, by
signaling he wanted to cut taxes in Texas. The governor surprised
Texas House and Senate leaders with whom he previously had worked
closely with a press release calling for a $1 billion Texas tax cut
in the legislative session beginning in January.
</P>
<P>
   It came just eight days after Republican presidential nominee
Bob Dole and tax-cutting evangelist Jack Kemp had lost to Bill
Clinton and Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Dole had been softened up in the 1996 Republican primaries by
multimillionaire Steve Forbes, who spent a lot of money promoting
his flat-tax idea. The Bush-for-president team could predict that
in 2000, Bush would need an antidote to a tax-cut proposal. What
better than its own?
</P>
<P>
   And so the trajectory for the GOP Iowa caucuses and New
Hampshire primary in 2000 was set.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's 1997 tax cut ran into trouble. Democrats insisted that
education spending be part of the bargain. Bush pleased educators
by going along. It passed the House. But the Republicans in the
Texas Senate killed it. Still, Bush wound up with the $1 billion,
two-year tax cut he'd asked for.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, Bush tried again. He got legislators to hold teachers
to half the $6,000 raise they wanted to bring them up to the
national average and spend the rest of the budget surplus on a $2
billion two-year tax cut.
</P>
<P>
   It knocked only 60 bucks off the average Texas homeowner's
property taxes. But $2 billion looks huge in small states such as
Iowa and New Hampshire. Bush took his tax-cutter merit badge, plus
a proposal to cut federal taxes $483 billion over five years, to
those states early this year.
</P>
<P>
   But even in usually tax-shy New Hampshire, Arizona Sen. John
McCain had success with his argument that putting all of the
projected surplus from the hot economy into tax cuts ``is not a
conservative effort.'' McCain said at least some should be used to
shore up national security and pay down the national debt.
</P>
<P>
   Since Bush won the nomination, his tax cut proposal is up to
$1.3 trillion over 10 years. Democratic opponent Al Gore maintains
Bush's ``tax scheme'' actually would cost $2.1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Gore charges the proposal ``has two problems _ it
has the wrong priorities and it's wrong for our economy.'' It would
cause interest rates to soar, the deficit to balloon and programs
such as Social Security, Medicare and education to suffer, Gore
argues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush tax plan could shatter confidence in our economy _
sending a message to the world that under George W. Bush, the era
of fiscal responsibility is over,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, Bush's team has sought to buy some slack, using White
House predictions that the hot economy will produce an even bigger
surplus than had been projected earlier as evidence Bush's tax cut
can work.
</P>
<P>
   Still, a House Republican leadership proposal last year for a
smaller tax cut than Bush's ``fell flat on its face,'' pointed out
U.S. Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Waco, who sits on the House
Appropriations Committee. ``The American people had enough sense to
understand that you can't have a free lunch.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal had assumed no emergency spending for 10
years and less money for defense than President Clinton proposed,
Edwards said. ``And of course the Congress is adding to, not
subtracting from the Clinton defense budget. And Bush is promising
more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't see where Governor Bush can make his
trillion-dollar tax cut work in the real world,'' Edwards said.
``It approaches the `voodoo economics' that his dad talked about''
_ a reference to the elder Bush's 1980 campaign criticism of Ronald
Reagan's claim that he could spend more for defense, cut taxes and
still balance the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the elder Bush changed his tune after becoming
Reagan's vice president, ``what President Bush said about voodoo
economics was true: The country tripled the national debt in the
1980s,'' Edwards said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that most average persons want us to protect the
important programs, and reduce the national debt,'' Edwards said.
``And ironically, it's put the Democrats into being more fiscally
conservative than the Republicans. And that could be Bush's
Achilles' heel.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
