<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2268 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-ADVENTURE-TOURS-HNS &LR;      05-11 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ADVENTURE-TOURS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LOST IN THE JUNGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN FLINN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Darkness was falling, I was alone and, I was
pretty sure, lost. The bamboo forest I was walking through was said
to be chock-full of Bengal tigers. I could feel the hair standing
up on my arms. I sensed there were hungry eyes out there in the
forest, watching me.
</P>
<P>
   I've always maintained that commercial adventure-travel trips
are an oxymoron: you pay the outfitters a lot of money to make sure
you don't have an adventure. You spend the cash to guarantee, as
much as possible, that you don't wander down the wrong trail, that
you sit down to a hearty (and hygienic) hot-cooked supper each
evening and that you're back in the office, safe and sound, right
on schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Adventure is what happens when things go wrong, when the outcome
is in doubt, when you're forced to rely on your own wits and skill
to extricate yourself from a dicey situation. I'm a big fan of
so-called adventure travel trips, but I don't confuse them with
true adventure.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as I was discovering as I felt my way down the dark
forest path, sometimes on these trips things really do go wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Geographic Expeditions, a San Francisco adventure travel
company, had secured a permit to visit a previously off-limits
corner of Bhutan, a Buddhist kingdom in the Himalayas between India
and China, and had invited me along on a scouting trip. Ostensibly
our goal was to locate the world's highest unclimbed mountain,
which had somehow gone missing, but the real joy was walking
through breathtaking country no Western eyes had ever seen before.
</P>
<P>
   As we were leaving Thimpu, Bhutan's somnolent capital, we met
with World Wildlife Fund officials who told us a just-completed
census had found that the cloud-draped bamboo forest we'd be
walking through harbored Asia's third-largest population of Bengal
tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Big cats were much on my mind one afternoon as I ambled down a
muddy yak-herders' trail along the frothing river known as the
Chamkhar Chuu. Lost in a little wild-things reverie, I was idly
scanning the mud and the gravelly riverbank for paw prints.
Suddenly I heard a crashing in the bamboo. Out of the corner of my
eye I saw something springing toward me; there was a blood-curdling
roar.
</P>
<P>
   Gotcha! It was Jim Sano, one of our trip leaders. With my heart
about to explode out of my chest, I clubbed him with my bamboo
walking stick as he had a good laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Later, at dusk, it occurred to me that I hadn't seen anyone for
hours. I had been walking without a halt since lunch, and it seemed
like I should have long ago reached our agreed-upon camp, a meadow
called Petso. Had I overshot it?
</P>
<P>
   I continued down the trail, inching my way along in the fading
light, when I stumbled into a half-drunken Bhutanese man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Petso?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   He looked confused and then gestured back the way I had come.
Then, looking a little unnerved to be out on the trail at that
hour, he disappeared into the forest.
</P>
<P>
   Dusk was feeding time for tigers. I stood and listened, willing
myself to make out the sounds of my group's camp. Instead, all I
could hear was something crunching through the bamboo, fortunately
far off. I couldn't possibly have walked past the camp without
seeing, I decided. I kept walking. Soon it was pitch black.
</P>
<P>
   It looked like I was going to have to spend the night out alone
in tiger country.
</P>
<P>
   I began to take inventory: I was carrying plenty of warm
clothing and rain gear, so hypothermia wouldn't be a problem. I had
almost a liter of water and a PowerBar for sustenance. I had a
headlamp with fresh batteries, and a lighter and toilet for
starting a fire.
</P>
<P>
   I flipped on my headlamp and continued down the forest path,
keeping an eye out for one of the shallow caves the local
yak-herders use for shelter. These, I'd noticed, often had a small
pile of firewood stacked nearby. I could get a roaring blaze going
to ward off the tigers.
</P>
<P>
   This sounds strange, but I was rather enjoying myself. The thing
about true adventure, the reason people get addicted to adrenaline,
is that it focuses your mind and sharpens your senses in a most
marvelous way.
</P>
<P>
   The forest, I noticed for the first time, was full of exotic
scents; I could hear every crunch and crackle in the bamboo, every
tiny change in the pitch of the river. I'd walked over 20 miles
since breakfast, but I felt a surge of new energy, an extra spring
in my stride.
</P>
<P>
   And then I rounded a corner and almost knocked over Tashi and
Karma, two of our Bhutanese camp-helpers who had been sent out to
look for me. Camp was half a mile farther, they explained. Petso
had been full of leeches, so the guides had decided to keep going.
</P>
<P>
   Soon I was sitting down to a hot, three-course dinner at a
folding table inside our spacious dining tent. Tashi and Karma were
setting up my tent for me and unrolling my cushy sleeping pad and
goose-down sleeping bag.
</P>
<P>
   Things were under control; my little adventure was over before
it had begun. I felt relieved and a little sad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1725EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
