<HEADER>
A2269 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-NY-HOUSTON-STREET-ART     05-11 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOUSTON-STREET-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S HOUSTON STREET: DOWNTOWN LIFE, RIVER TO RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT11, 12 and 13 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.)  
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An elfin, top-hatted statue perched high on a
venerable red-brick building at Houston and Lafayette Streets leans
over the sidewalk, holding a mirror above the passing crowds. The
gold-leaf figure is Puck, the playful sprite of Shakespeare's
``Midsummer Night's Dream,'' whose mischievous spirit animates the
building that takes his name and the scene below on which he muses.
</P>
<P>
   For along Houston Street, Puck, who proclaims ``What fools these
mortals be!'' has a rich array of humanity to marvel at _
finger-snapping jazz-hounds, 4 a.m. pool sharks, dancing fools,
fools waiting behind a velvet rope to start dancing, very pregnant
folk singers, walkers, poseurs from Soho (south of Houston),
shoppers from Noho (north of Houston), gardeners, noshers,
moviegoers of every stripe _ and a handful of sinks for the bar and
bathroom, if not the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   If this be folly, play on.
</P>
<P>
   By night and by day, for a river-to-river slice of city life as
varied and colorful as the mondo-maki fare at Sushi, Houston Street
is unrivaled. By night, where else could one find what in many
cities would be impossible _ a $9.95 lobster dinner a few doors
down from hearty Tibetan cuisine, just a stroll away from
headlining rap and folk artists and films both conventional and
controversial?
</P>
<P>
   By day, one can find arguably the world's best knish, urban
garden and barroom bar. Not to mention more playgrounds than you
could shake a stickball at. Plus water views, the arch of bridges
spanning the East River in the shadow of the Lillian Wald and
Bernard Baruch housing projects and the majestic expanse of the
Hudson as it widens into the Narrows.
</P>
<P>
   The street is kind to filmgoers, offering two fine houses. At 18
W. Houston is the Angelika Film Center, where one can take in
anything from the latest foreign movie to more mainstream fare. It
has the feel of a bohemian multiplex, with its beret tipped to more
eclectic tastes in both film and food, selling vegan baked goods
upstairs and decent popcorn downstairs. Do obey the signs and
refrain from wearing Rollerblades here!
</P>
<P>
   Across town, the Film Forum (209 W. Houston) feels much homier,
and its offerings tilt a bit more to the avant-garde and the
socially conscious. The latte-sipping crowd at the Angelika is a
mix of college students and middle-aged adventurers. At the Film
Forum, you could expect a younger Woody Allen waiting in line for
``The Sorrow and the Pity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was here that, along with my fiance, Pete Newman, who
accompanied me on my trans-Houston journey, I caught ``The
Specialist,'' Eyal Sivan's chilling documentary on the Eichmann
trial.
</P>
<P>
   For music, our favorite was the Mercury Lounge (217 E. Houston),
tucked in the back of what was once the servants' quarters to the
Astor Mansion, then later a tombstone store. One monument remains
embedded in part of the bar's countertop. The night we visited the
music room, which felt as if it were lighted by exit signs, we
found comfortable seating, famously good acoustics and Sara
Hickman, the Texas singer-songwriter who sat with her guitar right
up against her very round belly, making us wonder how her lively,
pleasing music sounded to the child growing inside.
</P>
<P>
   Xena Night and Hip-Hop
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks east, we poked into Meow Mix (269 E. Houston),
which features Xena Night every second Tuesday, for watching the
warrior princess. Most nights it's a lesbian bar, but not
exclusively so, especially on evenings with bands that attract a
broad audience.
</P>
<P>
   And for an active dance scene with a DJ, crystal chandeliers and
music ranging from hip-hop to techno to contemporary, there's the
nightclub Chaos in the old Provident Loan Society Building, which
once housed Jasper Johns' studio (225 E. Houston). The club has
just introduced a new modern-style lounge downstairs, in contrast
with the Oriental-rug, red-velvet Old World of upstairs.
</P>
<P>
   On the west side, the Zinc Bar (90 W. Houston) has a wide
variety of live music. For a good Cuban singer, there's Xiomara, on
Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   At S.O.B.'s, at Houston and Varick Streets, I'm afraid we looked
too suburban as we stepped up for admission to Large Professor Plus
Mad Skilz.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, this is hip-hop,'' one bouncer warned us. ``Rap
music,'' the other added, in case we didn't get it. The first one
frisked Pete, but the second one waved his colleague off, as if we
were obviously too green to be packing heat. Inside, the music was
pounding with urban energy as the professor talked his lyrics at a
virtuosic pace. The only thing that shocked us, frankly, was the
cost of two run-of-the-mill drinks _ $15. When we left later, we
noticed the windows on Houston rattling with the bass.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
