<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2271 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-NY-HOUSTON-STREET-ART     05-11 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOUSTON-STREET-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the bass.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For night owls in search of a landing spot, there's Soho
Billiards at Houston and Mulberry Streets. Though pool aficionados
complain that it looks more like a car dealership than a cozy,
traditional tucked-away pool hall, it has an ample supply of tables
and is open until 4 a.m. on weekends. We were not charmed by the
funky, terribly dusty, stucco ceiling and the odor of a soggy
rec-room; we'd hoped to see more characters and fewer
regular-looking people. But once we found two cue sticks that were
acceptably symmetrical, we had a couple of enjoyable midnight
games, for only $10 an hour for two.
</P>
<P>
   `So Come In Already'
</P>
<P>
   Daytime brought a different look to Houston Street. Pete and I
made a five-and-a-half-mile round-trip trek across the
thoroughfare, from the artistically renovated Broadway-Lafayette
subway station along the south side, east to the East River, and
then back along the north side and west to the Hudson. Finally, we
returned east to our starting point at the subway stop.
</P>
<P>
   Our journey, along the border between the named streets south of
Houston and the numbered streets to the north, took us through an
urban kaleidoscope that had served as way station and home to waves
of immigrants from Jews and Hispanics on the East Side to Italians
on the West, to the hip and arty in recent decades. We marveled at
random, captivating images: a lady carrying an armful of
pussywillows, a dog being hand-fed a hot dog, the shaggy calf and
foot of a man receiving a streetside pedicure, a cormorant floating
peacefully on the East River, a pondful of turtles at a community
garden, a shredded prom corsage in the gutter under a tunnel-like
building near the West Side Highway and colorful seven-story murals
on the sides of buildings.
</P>
<P>
   One recent Sunday we headed east from Broadway _ which divides
east from west on Houston Street _ because it was early in the
afternoon and because Pete loves knishes. Ages ago, he had heard
about Yonah Schimmel's (137 E. Houston) and the fresh knishes that
rise from the basement on the dumbwaiter: sweet potato knishes,
``buy them for the party'' chocolate knishes, kasha knishes to go
or blueberry knishes at the tables. The descendants of people who
couldn't wait to leave the Lower East Side flock back to this knish
emporium between Eldridge and Forsyth Streets for the authentic
taste of Yiddish eats. ``So come in already,'' the store's Web site
admonishes.
</P>
<P>
   We proceeded east to Russ and Daughters (179 E. Houston), an
85-year-old family food tradition, which was likewise packed with
people ordering whitefish, garlic paste, goat cheese and caviar.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandfather was one of those Eastern Europeans who had a
hard work ethic but not much patience,'' said Mark Russ Federman,
55, who gave up his law practice to go into the business.
``Customers would come in like they still do and say: `I don't want
this! Trim the fat off that!,' and he'd reply, `Did I invite you?'
and throw them out. The business wasn't doing so well until he
brought in his three daughters. They'd stand behind the counter
smiling, and it was quite unusual at the time to see pretty young
women reaching into herring barrels.''
</P>
<P>
   Federman's mother, Anne, is the youngest of the three daughters,
who have all retired to Florida, ``in the same shtetl,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Farther east, three cats graced the merchandise at NY Bars and
Backbars (49 E. Houston), where one could buy an official, original
Automat machine, complete with the labels from the days when it
sold Manhattan cheesecake for three nickels. Across the street we
enjoyed poking through Manhattan Castles and Props (74 E. Houston),
offering bathtubs, subway signs, sinks and antiques al fresco, in a
caged-off slice of the sidewalk that gives it the air of being
slightly forbidden.
</P>
<P>
   A Community Garden
</P>
<P>
   My favorite block coincided with a bit of a thunderstorm. Just
east of the Bowery, we had arrived at the Liz Christy
Bowery-Houston Garden, named for the founder of the Green
Guerrillas who died in 1985 at age 40. As we strolled among the
community garden's apricot tulips, trilliums and nasturtium
seedlings in cold frames, we noticed a young man standing on one of
the rough-hewn, wooden public seats struggling to thread his
umbrella handle through the latticework above it. Satisfied, he sat
in the corner, and his beloved nestled her head beneath his
shoulder, under the open umbrella, protected from the rain.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place defies the city,'' Pete said, after we had counted
about a dozen turtles surfacing around the rim of the garden's fish
pond. The place is open to the public when there are gardeners
present, and from noon to 4 p.m. on Saturdays, and 6 p.m. until
dusk during the growing seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Street was named after William Houstoun, a delegate from
Georgia to the Continental Congress of 1784 and _ more important
for naming purposes _ the son-in-law of Nicholas Bayard III, who
owned property on which the street was built. The spelling was
shortened in the 1800s, confusing tourists who mispronounce it with
a ``you'' sound, like the Texas city, as opposed to an ``ow''
sound.
</P>
<P>
   Early in that century, it was considered a rural and residential
enclave of ``uptown'' Manhattan, which later gave way to factories
and became a center for the printing trades. It was in this milieu
that the erstwhile humor magazine Puck thrived inside the 1885
Romanesque Revival structure at Lafayette Street built to house it.
The building was once also home to Spy magazine; it is now the
frequent host of upscale weddings and home to Pratt Institute's
Manhattan outpost.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0217 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2272 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t BC-NY-HOUSTON-STREET-ART     05-11 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-HOUSTON-STREET-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Manhattan outpost.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The thoroughfare is unusually wide, especially by New York
standards, and, with a few more trees, could pass as a boulevard.
When Houston Street was widened, many buildings flanking the street
were sliced off, exposing the blank walls of their next-door
neighbors. On the south side, at the corner of Thompson Street, the
Japan Artists Society has sponsored a building-high mural of two
cats, with a city in the background, containing the following
announcement: ``A pondering feline is melting into the Socratic
skyline.''
</P>
<P>
   Architectural Jewels
</P>
<P>
   We strolled by McKim, Mead &AMP; White's 1894 Cable building at
Broadway, a jewel in the crown of the neighborhood's fabled
cast-iron district. The building, foot-stompingly beautiful and
believed to be designed by Stanford White, was once the powerhouse
for cable cars moving from the Battery as far north as 36th Street.
(Wheels 26 feet in diameter pulled the cables under Broadway.)
</P>
<P>
   After a short amble past I.M. Pei's New York University housing,
we came upon the anomalous Time Landscape at Houston and LaGuardia
Place _ a 25-by-40-foot fenced-in area depicting what Manhattan
looked like in more pastoral times. The pristine woodland was
created, then sealed off, by the artist Alan Sonfist, and
encourages reflection on what Houston Street might have been in an
earlier era.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of contemplation, two blocks west at Sullivan
Street, is the Church of St. Anthony of Padua, a reminder of the
neighborhood's Italian pedigree, which honors its patron saint with
a lively street festival in June.
</P>
<P>
   While playgrounds appear every few blocks, especially on the
east side with Hamilton Fish Park at Pitt Street and Sara D.
Roosevelt Park at Chrystie Street, I particularly enjoyed one for
dogs: the Mercer-Houston Dog Run Association, complete with hose
and a small dog pool, open by membership. This little park at
Mercer Street attracts quite a crowd of spectators when it fills up
in the late afternoons for a canine happy hour.
</P>
<P>
   Posters and River Views
</P>
<P>
   On our westward journey, once we crossed the Avenue of the
Americas, the feel of the street changed, becoming more like any
Greenwich Village lane than an arterial. On this western swing we
found a few pleasant surprises.
</P>
<P>
   We explored Alphaville (226 W. Houston), which specializes in
vintage toys and movie posters. I was particularly drawn to the
full sheets of Wacky Packs sporting stickers with such spoofs of
name-brand products as Gadzooka Bubble Gum and Botch Tape that I
had adored in grade school. The owners, Steve Karchin and Gary
Kraut, had traveled far and wide in their quest for ``childhood
artifacts,'' particularly from the 1940s, '50s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   In true Manhattan fashion, public toilets and access to the
scenic riverfronts are as hard to find around here as a person
wearing fewer than three black garments. And be warned that gaining
access to river vistas at either end of Houston Street can be
daunting. Trying to get to the East River, we had to risk crossing
a traffic circle with inadequate crosswalks, as cars left the FDR
Drive. On the West Side, we walked confidently to the farthest
reaches of the Pier 40 parking garage, pretending we had left a car
there, so we could lean over the top-floor railing for a gorgeous,
albeit challenging, view of the Hudson.
</P>
<P>
   From Sushi to Cichetti
</P>
<P>
   For dining, by day or by night, Houston Street offers a wide
variety of choices, heavily weighted toward the West Side. We had
to keep heading back to the blocks between Macdougal Street and La
Guardia Place for the temptations of cheap lobster (El Paso, 134 W.
Houston), very affordable sushi ( Sushi, 142 W. Houston, with ample
avocado in the California rolls _ the mark of a good sushi bar) and
the lure of Tibet on Houston (136 W. Houston), offering an
appetizing cuisine we had never sampled. Check out the daikon
radish dishes.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks east, Arturo's Restaurant-Pizzeria (106 W. Houston)
offers live music most nights, outdoor seats and tasty pasta
dishes. For a nightcap there's Madame X (94 W. Houston), a moody
downstairs bar dressed all in red, which offers live music weekday
nights.
</P>
<P>
   And if you're around in the daytime, you might want to pick up
some gnocchi at Raffetto's (144 W. Houston), one of New York's
oldest pasta makers.
</P>
<P>
   On the East Side we couldn't resist the 1940s appeal of Sunday
brunch at Katz's Deli (205 E. Houston), still conjuring up its
wartime slogan: ``Send a salami to your boy in the Army.'' We
could, however, send back the foul, poorly diluted orange juice
from concentrate. The perfectly browned blintzes and authentic
knishes made up for that, as did all those letters from recent
presidents, blown up to five feet in height, thanking the owners
for all the salamis.
</P>
<P>
   On my way to a party farther east on the Lower East Side, I was
hard-pressed to find inspiring dinner choices, and ended up at the
Clinton Restaurant (293 E. Houston), where the shrimp salad was
good and plentiful, the avocados were unavailable and the
wallpaper, of faded pheasants and mountain scenes, was probably
older than everyone in there. It was here, south of the border of
Alphabet City, that I got a pungent taste of the street's Hispanic
flavor. Marc Anthony and Luis Vargas played on the jukebox, and the
menu was presented in both Spanish and English, with more Spanish
spoken.
</P>
<P>
   We followed the crowds to Cafe Colonial (73 E. Houston), which
features Brazilian cuisine, though that's not obvious from the
decor, which favors old advertising signs in English. The Brazilian
beer was dark and copious, the hearts-of-palm salad with Roquefort
cheese attracted the forks of everyone around the table, and the
steaks were very well received.
</P>
<P>
   For gracious atmosphere, Ballato Restaurant (55 E. Houston) and
Bar Cichetti (220 W. Houston) ranked high. We liked the way the
maitre d' at Ballato welcomed some of his patrons by name, ushering
them in to the warm dining room, with its distressed plaster and
Old-World feel.
</P>
<P>
   At Bar Cichetti, the yellow walls, done half in bead board,
formed the perfect backdrop for the two bottles of Veuve Clicquot
our friends bought to toast our engagement.
</P>
<P>
   (STORY ENDS HERE. OPTIONAL SIDEBAR FOLLWS IN 4th TAKE)
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
