<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HAWKE-FEATURE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO ACT, PERCHANCE TO WRITE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest movie ``Hamlet'' is set in contemporary New York,
where the troubled scion is heir to a media conglomerate called the
Denmark Corp. and an aspiring filmmaker himself.
</P>
<P>
   More striking than all of the up-to-the-minute electronics and
sleek Manhattan locations, however, is the palpable youth of this
production's melancholy Dane. Ethan Hawke, not yet 30, is the
youngest actor to play Shakespeare's best-known character in a
major motion picture. And it takes nothing away from Laurence
Olivier's, Mel Gibson's or Kenneth Branagh's interpretations to
note that something about this feels incredibly right.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the reason why a lot of people have a caricature of
Hamlet in their minds as a self-involved, infantile kind of guy is
because, oftentimes, you're watching somebody much too old for the
part play it,'' says Hawke, who has essentially embodied the
literate soul of his generation in such zeitgeist movies as ``Dead
Poets Society,'' ``Reality Bites'' and ``Before Sunrise.'' ``If
you're watching a young man do it, his obsession with trying to
define his relationship with his mother and father, his trying to
figure out who he is in relationship to the world ... It's just a
young man's dilemma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael always said that he saw Hamlet, set in this modern
way, more as a Holden Caulfield or Kurt Cobain than as a Laurence
Olivier at 40,'' Hawke continues. ``I happened to have loved
Olivier's Hamlet, but there's a great line in `Catcher in the Rye'
where he talks about Olivier playing it more like a general than
the screwed-up kid he thought he was. I kind of took solace in that
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael is Michael Almereyda, the New York experimental
filmmaker who adapted and directed the new ``Hamlet.'' He
collaborated with Hawke on the movie's script, location choices
(whoever had the idea to set the soliloquy in the ``action'' aisle
of a Blockbuster video store should take a bow) and thematic
emphases.
</P>
<P>
   All that and whatever other ideas the theater-trained (though
Shakespeare inexperienced) Hawke brought to the party were welcome.
But it was the callow sensitivity he projects so well that made
Hawke perfect for the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the tradition of casting the play has warped the idea
of who can play it in the movie, because to sustain all of that
language for 4 1/2 hours every night might require an older and
more experienced actor,'' Almereyda observes. ``But there are all
kinds of ways for younger people to be fresh for Shakespeare in
movies because the discipline is different. What's really required
_ and what I went for with Ethan _ is a level of intimacy, so the
lines weren't spluttered and declaimed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ethan brought that intimate quality, as well as a young man's
vulnerability, to the piece, and that felt new to me. The hope, for
both of us, was always to present a complete person that you'd feel
sympathy for, that it wasn't just someone filling the part.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, youthfulness isn't the only quality that makes
Hawke's movie Hamlet distinctive. The actor has his own, unique _
some would say heterodox _ take on many aspects of the play and
character. Most crucially, on Hamlet's legendary indecisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has this extraordinary dilemma of being told to kill
somebody by his father, and I don't think Hamlet is wrong not to
want to do it,'' Hawke reckons.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Ghost comes to tell Hamlet to kill Claudius, we
usually assume that he should kill Claudius. My whole idea was,
y'know, being a vigilante is not necessarily the best idea,
especially for a basically peaceful man. Even in the original text,
they're all talking about how he's not an amazing warrior like his
father, that all Hamlet wants to do is read.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who's to say that he should just go blast Claudius? I think
putting it in a modern setting helps you to feel the reality of
that more. When it's set in the olden days, you just think
everybody killed each other, and he should just go stab the guy.
But when it's like, OK, here's a gun, go shoot him, it makes you
understand a little more viscerally why Hamlet's having an
existential dilemma.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawke's co-stars include Kyle MacLachlan as the murderous,
usurping uncle Claudius; Diane Venora as Hamlet's mother, Gertrude;
Sam Shepard as his father's Ghost; a surprisingly effective Bill
Murray as Polonius; Julia Stiles as Ophelia; and Liev Schreiber as
Laertes.
</P>
<P>
   As you may have noticed, it's an all-American cast, which Hawke
feels complements the movie's modern vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all kind of excited about that, because people in this
country can be such Anglophiles when it comes to Shakespeare,'' he
says. ``We think only the British know how to do it right, and
everybody gets really intimidated by that. So it was fun to have
this kind of renegade group of American actors running around New
York doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general, I feel like, whatever you can do to make it
personal and heartfelt is good,'' he adds. ``If it's too scholarly,
if it's too put in a box, then I think people go to sleep. You
know, Shakespeare wasn't meant to be high art. A lot of people
would enjoy it more than they (think) they would if it wasn't
treated so preciously.''
</P>
<P>
   Filming ``Hamlet'' in New York solved a few of Hawke's own
dilemmas. Since the birth of his daughter, Maya, almost two years
ago, the actor has made only one other movie, ``Snow Falling on
Cedars,'' and essentially abandoned Malaparte, the theatrical group
he helped found. The movie allowed him to work his theatrical
muscles without the all-consuming demands of a stage production
while staying close to the downtown loft that Hawke and his wife,
actress Uma Thurman, call home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A theater company is kind of like a family, and it's really
fun, but once you actually have a family, there isn't that much
time to do that,'' he explains. ``I used to do whatever I wanted,
and what pleased me the most was work. So I'd work 52 weeks a year
if I could; everything else was kind of boring. But now, I have to
do things that I find really challenging if it's going to take me
away from my family. So many things shoot in, like, Istanbul, and
that might have been fun when I was single. But now I have to be
more creatively discerning.''
</P>
<P>
   While Thurman recently filmed some movies in Europe, Hawke
contentedly tagged along and kept busy with parenting duties and
work on his new novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have one little, secret blessing, which is that I love to
write,'' he says, ``and I can, pretty much, do that wherever we
go.''
</P>
<P>
   Hawke's first book, ``The Hottest State,'' was published to
mixed reviews and much complaint about its author being a popular
young actor. Hawke has been dodging the pseudo-intellectual label
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   And he's not the least bit bothered by it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to allow people to think that,'' he says. ``It's
constructive criticism in a certain way. You know, it was so much
easier for me to get a book published than it is for anyone else
that I should take that heat and take it gladly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that time will tell whether or not I'm serious,'' he
adds. ``But I also think, in general, that we live in a period when
people are just so cynical and mistrustful of your intentions. I
really don't consider myself an intellectual. I do love to read,
and if that makes me an intellectual, then I guess I am. But
there's also some idea that you're an intellectual because you
don't love the living of life. That's not the case with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us to our concluding question: What does Ethan
Hawke want his future to be or not to be?
</P>
<P>
   ``I started when I was so young that I feel like the challenge
for me is to not burn out and to stay fresh,'' says Hawke, who made
his first major movie, ``Explorers,'' while still in junior high in
Princeton, N.J.. ``In the past couple of years, I've tried to
recultivate in myself the attitude of an amateur. For any person
involved at all with the arts, I think it can be really damaging if
you turn yourself into too much of a businessman.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounding like something out of the luxe, Manhattan ``Hamlet,''
Hawke continues: ``We live in a culture where the only barometer
for success that anybody really respects is money. But I think that
can't be the only criterion by which you judge yourself, or you'll
just be a miserable rat ... and you really won't be an artist.
</P>
<P>
   ``My idea, really, is just to try to live the most interesting
life that I can and accept whatever comes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
