<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CLOISTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHERE UNICORNS AND TAPESTRIES WAIT IN TIMELESS REPOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;    Helen Schary Motro, who grew up in Manhattan and divides her
time between Israel and New York, is a columnist for The Jerusalem
Post.
 By HELEN SCHARY MOTRO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most beautiful European cloister I've ever
experienced lies along the Hudson River, just south of the Bronx
border. The Cloisters and I were introduced in early May of my 11th
year, a season when the transplanted monastery gardens in Fort
Tryon Park explode with color.
</P>
<P>
   Our sixth-grade class had studied the social, political and
economic structure of medieval Europe with a thoroughness that
years later could carry us cold through college examinations. We
had spent the interminable dark winter immersed in the Middle Ages,
hardly raising our heads to see if the 15th century ever arrived.
</P>
<P>
   We passed our weekends assembling bulky scrapbooks, scavenging
our parents' bookshelves, buying up secondhand magazines on 42nd
Street. In gold and peacock watercolors, we painstakingly adorned
with gothic lettering the individual compendiums of our year's
work. Our ``medieval books'' were displayed for admiring parents in
the school library with a seriousness and pomp matching that of the
rare-book room at the British Museum.
</P>
<P>
   In May our class set out in a yellow school bus with bad shocks
on a bumpy crusade up the Henry Hudson Parkway. The Cloisters wing
of the Metropolitan Museum of Art is more than a reproduction of a
medieval microcosm that any come-lately millionaire could hope to
construct in Arizona. Chapels and cloisters were transplanted stone
by stone from monasteries scattered throughout Europe. On a site
overlooking the New Jersey Palisades, they were rebuilt on the
biggest hill in New York near the highest-numbered streets in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect haven of beauty abloom with fragrant blossoms, the
bubbling stone fountain in the center, the spring air limpid and
the sunshine sending warm rays upon our shiny childhood hair _ it
was my first aesthetic jolt.
</P>
<P>
   I've kept trying to recapture that platonic essence of cloister
ever since.
</P>
<P>
   In every European city I've run straight to every cloister
mentioned in each footnote of my guidebook. Predictably, my
expectations were forever higher than any mere human cloister could
deliver.
</P>
<P>
   In high school I dragged hapless friends on the endless trip
through upper Manhattan on the No. 4 bus. Finally it made a
majestic sweep into the circular driveway of the Cloisters; we
disembarked and forded the mental moat back to the Middle Ages. But
my friends always remained bewildered; reality did not match my
magical description. We hurtled noisily back downtown on the A
train.
</P>
<P>
   I introduced my two little girls to the Cloisters in exactly the
right spring season.
</P>
<P>
   Driving them in from the suburbs in my station wagon, I told
them over my shoulder of my mystical class trip and the wondrous
surprise that was awaiting them. But my little girls had never
heard of troubadours or Eleanor of Aquitaine, of stained glass
windows or illuminated manuscripts.
</P>
<P>
   They trailed blankly after me through the courtyards until their
patience wore out and they started to beg for Good Humors and tug
my arm toward the gift shop.
</P>
<P>
   Years later, I took my first daughter to the Cloisters on the
last sunny weekend before she left for college. I suspect I wanted
to take my parting from her by coming together to the womblike
gardens nestling hidden and comforting inside fluted arches. She
recognized the white unicorn, an old friend from the reproduction
of the tapestry tacked up on our kitchen cupboard, and said with
sparkling eyes that she would certainly come back in the spring to
see the rose trees flower.
</P>
<P>
   But for her the spring was years still in the future.
</P>
<P>
   It is suddenly spring again, a spring when I feel leaden and
pedestrian _ ages older than the springs of my Middle Ages. Among
the mail filled with offers of things I do not want I find the
bulletin of events from the Metropolitan Museum. One page near the
back lists hours, activities and location of the Cloisters. Tucked
at the bottom is an unobtrusive photograph of a flowering cloister
garden, almost begging to be overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   I feel myself again walking in the orderly line of sixth
graders, holding hands, two by two, with the teacher at the head
and a chaperoning mother at the rear, wearing a starched cotton
dress tied at the waist, filing out from the cool vaulted halls
into the brilliant sunshine of the Cuxa cloister.
</P>
<P>
   What need have I to be moved by the fairyland beauty of foreign
castles along a foreign Rhine or to trudge with tourists through
congested Florence, when right next to the prosaic Hudson looms our
majestic medieval fortress controlling all of Manhattan Island?
Along with Manhattan, holding my old heart within its walls, a more
than willing captive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
