<SLUG> BC-IVOR-WOODY-ALLEN-IN-SMALL-TIME-CROOKS-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FORGET THE $20 MILLION _ GET ME WOODY'S $5,000' 
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
entertainment column.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly entertainment column with color and black-and-white art.)
 Includes black-and-white photos and color slides of Woody Allen
with Tracey Ullman in scenes from ``Small Time Crooks.'' 
 By IVOR DAVIS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    Julia Roberts gets $20 million a movie, and Leonardo DiCaprio
joins her in the financial stratosphere. Sean Penn, Michael Caine,
Hugh Grant, Drew Barrymore, Tracey Ullman and Kenneth Branagh all
get handsome paychecks for simply stepping in front of a camera.
 &HT;    But when Woody Allen comes courting, these Rolls Royces of
Hollywood turn into Volkswagens. Allen pays even the biggest stars
a miserly $5,000 a week _ and they line up to be in his films.
 &HT;    Everybody wants to do a Woody Allen movie, even though the parts
are often small, the perks are few and far between, there's
virtually no individual artistic input and, most of the time, he
won't even let them see a complete script.
 &HT;    In fact, he seldom even tells his actors what the film is about
_ which, he claims, most of them prefer.
 &HT;    ``Actors don't really want to read a full script,'' he says.
``All they want to know is what they're doing.''
 &HT;    But the prestige keeps them coming _ being in a Woody Allen
picture means you've arrived. Michael Caine took a huge salary cut
for ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' (1986), and it brought him an Oscar
as Best Supporting Actor. Last year Sean Penn got a Best Actor
nomination for ``Sweet and Lowdown.''
 &HT;    But Allen insists that he can't really get any actor he has a
mind to.
 &HT;    ``It's a 50/50 breakdown of actors who work in my movies and
those who can't or don't,'' says Allen, whose latest, ``Small Time
Crooks,'' will open May l9.
 &HT;    ``Actors want to be in my films,'' he admits, ``but they have to
be between jobs, because we don't pay them anything. Some of them
get 10 or 20 million dollars a picture. We give them $50,000 for 10
weeks' work. Everybody gets the same _ they don't get any
percentage of the picture, that's it. It's low-paying, and they've
got to want to do it.''
 &HT;    Hugh Grant, coming off the hit ``Notting Hill'' (l999), wanted
to do it as soon as he got a fax from Allen that said, ``I've
written a comedy that has a character who is a charming, well-bred
Englishman on the outside, but turns out to be a real bastard on
the inside. I thought you'd be perfect for it.''
 &HT;    ``I didn't know whether to take that as a compliment or an
insult,'' Grant says with a laugh during a separate interview.
 &HT;    Since he made his directorial debut with ``Take the Money and
Run'' (1969) _ like ``Small Time Crooks,'' a comic crime story _
Allen has become a legend in the business, making 30-plus films,
among them such classics as ``Annie Hall'' (l977), ``Manhattan''
(1979), ``Zelig'' (l983), ``Hannah and Her Sisters'' (l986),
``Crimes and Misdemeanors'' (l990) and ``Bullets Over Broadway''
(l994).
 &HT;    Nonetheless, the writer/director/actor has had to struggle to
keep his career afloat.
 &HT;    ``In many films I've gone over budget and have had to give my
entire salary back to the film company,'' he says. ``So I worked a
whole year on a film, writing, directing, editing it, for no money
at all. I've done it a dozen times.
 &HT;    ``So I've not gotten rich,'' he concludes, ``and neither has
anyone who has worked with me.''
 &HT;    The secret to his survival, he says, is his low budgets _
``Small Time Crooks'' cost a penny-ante $15 million.
 &HT;    ``The reason I get so much freedom, I can cast anyone I want to,
nobody reads the script and nobody says anything is because I'm
working at a financial level that they can't get hurt,'' he says.
``They could lose a little money, but not a lot.''
 &HT;    His latest film is one of the wildest comedies he's made in
years _ but Allen insists that he's never been the overly serious
Bergman wannabe that his detractors suggest.
 &HT;    ``I'm a comedian who makes comic films,'' he says. ``Some are
more serious, some are more frivolous. It's really just the roll of
the dice. My next film could be a comedy about death and famine,
for all I know. Some of my more serious movies are what I would
call a full-meal deal, as opposed to this one, which is a
souffle.''
 &HT;    The cast for ``Small Time Crooks'' includes Allen as an
ex-convict turned dishwasher, Tracey Ullman as his manicurist wife,
Elaine May as their cousin and Hugh Grant as a smooth-talking con
man. Allen and Ullman open a cookie shop as a front for a tunnel
into the bank next door, only to have the cookies make more money
than they could get from the bank.
 &HT;    Allen, who is nursing a cold _ ``I'm not a hypochondriac,'' he
insists, ``I'm an alarmist'' _ says that the idea for the movie
came to him when he read a story about a gang of thieves trying to
break into a bank from a next-door building.
 &HT;    ``I thought, what would happen if the little business they'd set
up took off like a rocket ship,'' he says, ``and they no longer
needed to rob that bank?''
 &HT;    Getting ideas is the easy part, Allen says. He learned to
generate ideas quickly as a staff writer on Sid Caesar's ``Your
Show of Shows'' in the 1950s.
 &HT;    ``Years ago, when I first started, you'd come in on the Sid
Caesar TV show on Monday morning,'' he recalls. ``You had to write
it by Wednesday, so they could rehearse Thursday and Friday,
because it went out on Saturday night. You couldn't sit around
waiting for miraculous inspiration.
 &HT;    ``My ideas come to me when I'm walking or shaving or at a
restaurant,'' he adds. ``I write them down, and then I go through
all my matchbook covers and napkins and say, `Which of these ideas
are going to be my next movie?'
 &HT;    ``So many of my films have happened that way,'' he says. ``If I
was a great writer it wouldn't be easy _ but on the level I write,
it's not hard for me.''
 &HT;    Allen has always insisted that his movies are not
autobiographical, although ``Husbands and Wives'' (l992), which
came out in the midst of his acrimonious breakup with Mia Farrow,
came uncomfortably close to his own personal domestic scenario.
``Deconstructing Harry'' (1997) seemed almost an autopsy of the
Allen psyche, and Kenneth Branagh did an out-and-out Allen
impersonation in ``Celebrity'' (1998).
 &HT;    Even Allen admits that his personal preoccupation with death
often creeps into his work, especially in films such as ``Crimes
and Misdemeanors'' and ``Hannah and Her Sisters.''
 &HT;    ``I've always been aware of the rapid passage of time _ the
finiteness of life, the inevitable conclusion of life for you and
your loved ones,'' he says. ``The imminence of illness _ those
things were always on my mind, ever since I was a little kid. I was
unusually preoccupied with it.
 &HT;    ``When I turned 50,'' the filmmaker continues, ``it was a magic
number _ and when I turned 60, I couldn't believe it.
 &HT;    ``You would think I shouldn't worry about it,'' Allen adds,
``because my father is 100 years old and my mother is in her late
90s. So I suppose it's all in the genes.''
 c.2000 Ivor Davis  
<TEXT>
