<HEADER>
A2293 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-CENTERSTAGE-TEX     05-11 0373
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CENTERSTAGE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BALLET AS CONCEIVED FOR A BRITNEY SPEARS VIDEO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ballet lovers are drawn to the art form for several reasons: the
extraordinary music; the physical beauty and athletic grace of the
dancers; and, most of all, the dance itself, with all its
imagination, challenge, drama and humor.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about the ballet in ``Center Stage,'' however, is
that it silences the two-left-feet dialogue and interrupts the
hoary story lines. It can't keep us away, however, from the
central-casting characters, who are such stereotypes it's like they
were created before dance itself.
</P>
<P>
   The movie _ like ``Fame'' in concept but certainly not in
execution _ details a year at a preparatory academy for the
American Ballet Theatre. The familiar characters include a clumsy
ingenue (Amanda Schull) who'll get her chance to shine
(coincidentally, also a recent plot on ``The Simpsons''); the
earnest newcomer (Sascha Radetsky) and creepily seductive teacher
(real-life ABT star Ethan Stiefel) who vie for her affections; the
prima donna (Susan May Pratt) who suffers from bulimia and having
an ambitious stage mother; and the streetwise toughie (Zoe Saldana)
who'll be great if she can just get over such bad-attitude offenses
as chewing gum in class. Peter Gallagher, who must be thanking his
lucky stars for ``American Beauty,'' looks embarrassed as a hotshot
instructor.
</P>
<P>
   Even the dancing, which provides the movie's best moments (a
relative term), often has a watered-down feel to it _ ballet as
conceived for a Britney Spears video. But anyone with enough taste
and intelligence to enjoy the best of the dancing is going to
recognize the rest of ``Center Stage'' for the hokum that it is.
However, it's just entertainingly bad enough that you might enjoy
it if you can get enough friends together to make fun of it. One
campy midnight movie, comin' up!
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Center Stage''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 1 1/2 on a 1-5 scale
</P>
<P>
   Length: 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: PG-13
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2294 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-CITYOFANGELS-1000(     05-11 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-CITYOFANGELS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEING EVERYTHING TO EVERYBODY MAY BE TOO MUCH FOR `ANGELS' TO
SURVIVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paris Barclay knew that getting the ratings his ``City of
Angels'' needed to survive would be difficult, and with the season
winding down and time running out, his highly touted medical drama
is living out its worst possible scenario: It's on life support,
with its fate in the hands of others.
</P>
<P>
   After airing a dozen or so episodes and generating
less-than-inspiring ratings, the year's most widely dissected
midseason series is facing cancellation. CBS unveils its fall
2000-2001 lineup to advertisers next week, and odds that ``City of
Angels'' will be on it hinge on CBS President Leslie Moonves
sticking with a promise he made in November that if the series
staggers out of the ratings gate, ``we'll stick with it.''
</P>
<P>
   The melodrama, which aired Wednesdays and stars Blair Underwood
as a passionate surgeon struggling to keep a financially strapped
hospital from crumbling, drew extraordinary attention at the outset
_ and not just because Steven Bochco was one of the executive
producers or because a bulk of the episodes were being directed by
Barclay, a multiple Emmy-winner for his splendid work on ``NYPD
Blue.''
</P>
<P>
   The attention was based as much on politics as on the creative
reputations of those involved. With the NAACP circling the networks
because of an absence of African-American and Latino characters on
series television, anticipation swirled around ``Angels'' as
observers wondered whether such a high-profile drama featuring a
predominantly black cast could stay true to the authenticity of the
setting while not alienating white viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Because white households make up 79 percent of the television
audience and black ones only 12 percent, convincing a sizable chunk
of white viewers to become regular viewers is vital to any show's
survival.
</P>
<P>
   The networks, with the exception of the smaller and more
niche-heavy UPN and the WB, are reluctant to gamble on a series
that might attract far more black than white viewers because
advertisers have traditionally been lukewarm toward series with a
largely black viewership. (According to Nielsen Media Research,
about 20 percent of ``Angels''' 8 million viewers are not black. By
comparison, the audience for another midseason entry, ``Malcolm in
the Middle,'' is double that and 90 percent white.)
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, Barclay and Bochco tried to sell the idea
early that ``Angels,'' while set in a Los Angeles hospital with
mostly black doctors treating black and Latino patients, wasn't a
black drama but ``a drama that happens to have black people in
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Such an assertion, many black producers say, merely illustrates
the challenges facing series populated by non-whites _ how, for
instance, black- and Latino-oriented programs must worry about
being too racially and culturally exclusive.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Farquhar, who created ``Moesha'' and is now co-executive
producer of ``The Parkers,'' both on UPN, calls such attempts to
shed ``the black show label'' a producer's way of getting around
the so-called black tax, a kind of inevitable bounty levied against
shows whose viewer base is almost exclusively black, and therefore
``far less valued'' by advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parkers,'' a broad comedy based on a mother and daughter
attending the same college, has in its first season become the
most-watched series in black households, attracting close to 4
million viewers a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gets good ratings by UPN standards but doesn't attract the
demographic advertisers, so therefore doesn't get the respect it
deserves,'' says Farquhar. ``When I read about the shows doing a
lot for their networks, it's `West Wing' for NBC and `Judging Amy'
for CBS. We're practically invisible. Why is that?''
</P>
<P>
   ``City of Angels'' has been far from invisible, but that hasn't
helped it with advertisers or viewers. As to why white viewers have
for the most part stayed away, Barclay says there's often a
perception that shows about blacks will deal with race and
constantly blame white people for black people's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong: I'm not saying that's what happened
here,'' Barclay says. ``But no one is going to return to any place
where they are constantly being blamed. But it's frustrating for us
because that's not what we're about.''
</P>
<P>
   The overarching vision of ``Angels'' was not to do a show that
focused directly on issues relating to being black in America, but
to deliver a mainstream medical drama that would deal organically
with race through the experiences of the characters.
</P>
<P>
   This decision came less from a creative decision than from
Bochco's fear that a series, no matter the quality, would never
work if it was unwilling to follow the crossover rules.
``Mainstream audiences have never been particularly comfortable
with (race),'' says Bochco. ``Comedies work because they're
nonthreatening. They're not designed to delve deep. They don't
offend.''
</P>
<P>
   MORE
nn
</P>
<P>
   Recent TV history backs up Bochco's fears. In 1979, Bochco
created ``Paris,'' with James Earl Jones as a police captain and
criminology professor. The series, on CBS, was gone in four months.
Carl Weathers as a San Francisco police officer in ABC's ``Fortune
Dane'' lasted one season in 1986, and in 1995, Jones co-starred
with Joe Morton in the generally praised ``Under One Roof.'' The
series focused on a middle-class Seattle family, but CBS yanked it
after four episodes.
</P>
<P>
   With this in mind, ``Angels'' was written carefully _ and
therefore passively _ as it tried to balance the scales (a white
doctor feeling the kind of institutional racism blacks have always
complained about; a less-talented black resident crying racism when
a white counterpart gets better assignments) while offering a
traditional mix of romantic fallout, life-threatening medical drama
and bureaucratic nightmares.
</P>
<P>
   The series premiered with 13 million viewers in the Sunday time
slot of the popular ``Touched by an Angel,'' but it immediately
began to lose viewers with subsequent airings, including
African-Americans who thought the series was trying so hard not to
offend its white audience that it was sacrificing its cultural
pulse.
</P>
<P>
   ```City of Angels' is under tremendous pressure,'' says Yvette
Lee Bowser, who, as one of the few black female producers, created
``Living Single'' and ``For Your Love,'' and is expected to add the
comedy ``The Thing About Family'' to NBC's fall lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the torchbearer, so it's also the target everyone will
shoot arrows at. It has to be everything to everyone. But if you
try to do that, you end up being nothing to no one.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Thing is,'' adds Blair Underwood, who was a regular on
Bochco's ``LA Law,'' ``what it will take is a greater number of
dramas about blacks and Asians and Hispanics so that we no longer
look to one or two programs to be the end-all and be-all. Are you
shooting yourself in the foot to say you're a black drama? I don't
want to sound like the whining victim here, but, yeah, you are. It
should be about the quality of the work. That's it.''
</P>
<P>
   And what about the quality of ``Angels?'' It may be that the
pervasiveness of medical dramas such as ``ER'' and ``Chicago Hope''
has made it difficult to mount a fresh medical drama, but
``Angels'' story lines have suffered from a sense of staleness. A
senior staffer commits suicide after learning that his services are
no longer needed; a patient refuses surgery that would save his
life. Love triangles between the lead characters. Its chief
distinction turned out to be simply the race of its characters.
(Bochco also blames the early 7 p.m. start time for story-line
``softness.'')
</P>
<P>
   Before finishing the filming for its season, ``Angels'''
producers sensed trouble. They shifted the tone of the series and
dropped the dark, drab backdrops, the darkly lit settings, and the
gospel music that filled the breaks. If the series returns for a
second season, Vivica A. Fox, who starred with Underwood as a
hospital administrator and love interest, won't return with it. The
two never clicked.
</P>
<P>
   An ``Angels'' return could also hinge on other minority-oriented
shows CBS places on the fall schedule. Gregory Nava's series about
a Hispanic family is said to be a lock. And with more black, Latino
or Asian leads set for the fall, CBS would feel less pressure
politically in the dispensing of ``Angels.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the experience ``Angels'' has had is a largely bitter
one, it might have served a purpose. It's high profile and
difficulties, among many other factors, have helped propel
development of new minority series, and Barclay and Underwood could
eventually get their wish of having all dramas being just dramas.
</P>
<P>
   ``(We've) got to get away from having test cases every few
years, this whole black-drama-is-a-gamble notion,'' says Barclay.
``I firmly believe that if you put enough quality programming out
there, people will watch and say, `That's a good show.' Not a good
black show.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpperkins(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1739EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-FILM-KERRIGAN-TEX     05-11 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-KERRIGAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KERRIGAN'S FILM CHRONICLES ONE OF HIS NUMEROUS INTRIGUING
EXPERIENCES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ When Justin Kerrigan walks into Breadwinners, the airy
and eclectic Dallas breakfast joint, he looks like he could be any
other McKinney Avenue denizen: close-cropped blond hair,
saucer-sized youthful blue eyes, T-shirt, khakis. The only thing
giving the 25-year-old director of ``Human Traffic'' away is his
Welsh accent, which graces the words that fly from his mouth at a
breakneck clip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human Traffic'' moves at the same pace. Kerrigan's film
follows five young proles through a dance-, drink- and drug-fueled
weekend on the rave scene in the clubs of Cardiff, Wales. The
good-natured movie is about ``release,'' a term that Kerrigan uses
often as he settles in for Breadwinners' version of eggs Benedict.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surprising thing about the film is that people of older
generations and people who've never been part of the culture seem
to be able to identify with it,'' Kerrigan says. ``So many people
begin with, `Oh, that's my friend. That was me and my mate.' So I'm
thinking, `Well, how? This is just a personal film about me and my
friends in Cardiff.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think every generation fundamentally goes through the
same things, the same sexual insecurities, the social paranoias. I
think everyone can relate to a lost weekend, to going out with
their friends and forgetting their 9-to-5 jobs, their family
stresses or whatever problems they got.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet at 25, Kerrigan has had experiences nobody else is likely to
share. Although he grew up in Wales, he attended school in Florida
when he was 9, returning to Wales to get involved with the club
culture when he was 15. He studied art and became interested in
film. By the time he was 18, he was raising money to buy a
secondhand camera to make short films, which helped him get into
the International Film School of Wales. He made six short films
before he received his degree; five of them made it to television.
</P>
<P>
   Kerrigan says all his films are at least semiautobiographical,
which is only fitting for a guy who is a natural storyteller. His
tales are so amusing, you have a hard time believing that they're
true, one in particular when he attended an arts event at Windsor
Castle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are celebrities everywhere, all British celebrities, and
I'm the only unfamous person there,'' Kerrigan says. ``And Jeeves
is walkin' around with the free martinis, and I'm gettin'
(hammered) ... I go down to the end of the Great Hall to get an
ashtray, and I turn around, and there's the queen right there. And
there's no security, and everybody's, like, mingling. So I'm
thinking, `This is a bit surreal,' and I'm the next in line, and
she's approaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I'm trying not to laugh; she goes, `Oh, hello, who are
you?' And I say, `Oh, I'm Justin Kerrigan.' And I put my hand out,
and everyone just freezes. I realize then, you're not supposed to
shake the queen's hand. So I'm looking at her, she's looking at me,
and I'm thinking, `You're not gonna leave me hanging here,' y'know?
And she shakes my hand after, and sticks around for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   But Kerrigan isn't just all about parties and amusing anecdotes.
Although ``Human Traffic'' is a breezy jolt of adrenalin, he plans
something more serious with his next film. It's about his
relationship with his father, who recently died at 50.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just made me realize how short life is,'' Kerrigan says.
``If you've got time off, you'd better use it. It's so easy to just
get wrapped up in your job. It's those times where you actually
release and go out with your friends and look back and say, `Yeah,
I had a good time.' ''
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7872, or e-mail:
robp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
