<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush at the arms bazaar
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ When a top National Rifle Association official was
taped in mid-cackle saying that a George W. Bush White House would
mean a presidency ``where we work out of their office,'' Bush was
quick with a rebuke.
</P>
<P>
   No surprise there. The candidate is leaving yellow lines and
flat armadillos in his wake as he veers from the right shoulder to
the middle these days.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA's lip-prints are not what a candidate wants on his
collar when courting the women voters Bush must have.
</P>
<P>
   Polls show that gun slaughter, particularly of children, rates
high among women's concerns. This is reflected by the Million Mom
March, a grassroots nationwide gun-control movement. Its showcase
event is this Mother's Day at the Washington Mall.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is Clintonesque in his ability to project empathy without
spending any. Undoubtedly right now he's figuring out a way to tell
these mothers, some of whom have lost children to gunfire, he feels
their pain.
</P>
<P>
   Gun carnage will always be a hard issue on which Bush can offer
any bold solutions. For one thing, he comes from a gun-happy state
in a gun-happy country. For another, he owes too many favors to the
gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Bush ought to know that more than anything else a gun
issue is what he most owes for his national profile and his current
office.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was concealed firearms permits. While one can
overstate any single appeal to voters, it is clear that
``conceal-carry'' was the single most distinctive issue separating
Bush and relatively popular predecessor Ann Richards in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-gun forces did a good job of getting out the
conceal-carry vote for Bush amid an otherwise lukewarm turnout.
Bush won by 7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not to do time-travel games, but if Ann Richards had made a
devil-deal and said she was all for six-shooters on hips in Texas,
George Bush might still be just the eldest son of an
</P>
</TEXT>
