<HEADER>
A2299 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-MUSTER12-COX     05-11 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSTER12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MILITARY RETIREES HOLD THEIR CAPITOL MUSTER, VOW TO RETURN
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ About 250 retired members of the armed forces held
a brief ``muster'' at the Capitol on Thursday to press their demand
for the lifetime health care they claim they were promised but
didn't get.
</P>
<P>
   After indignant speeches about Congress's failure to fund the
care they say recruiters promised them, the middle-aged and elderly
veterans made a strategic withdrawal to the weapon they are using
to stir up support for their cause: the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   They vowed to return in September with a larger group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm here on borrowed money today,'' said retired Air Force
Major Billy J. Young of Fort Gratiot, Mich., ``because it's time we
let these people up here understand that we have been relegated to
second-class employees of the federal government ... and we're
tired of it.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar Senate bill, introduced by Sens. Paul Coverdell,
R-Ga., and John McCain, R-Ariz., has been signed by only 27
senators.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon officials, including Defense Secretary William Cohen,
have acknowledged that recruiters and military retention officials
routinely promised lifetime medical care to members of the Army,
Navy, Air Force and Marines who began careers prior to June 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Although military lawyers have acknowledged in court that the
promise was made, the Pentagon argues that it does not constitute a
binding contract by the government, and so far courts have agreed.
</P>
<P>
   Military base closings, which eliminated many military
hospitals, and federal budget cuts have left an estimated 1.8
million retired personnel and their dependents without the promised
care.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they are placed on the rolls of the department's
Tricare program, which requires them to pay a portion of their
care. When they reach age 65, they are placed on Medicare and told
that they must pay for their own prescription drugs and, if they
want outpatient care, pay $49.50 a month for the plan's Part B.
</P>
<P>
   Young has filed a lawsuit accusing the federal government of
unlawfully discriminating against retirees by failing to keep the
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Only one member of Congress, Rep. Ronnie Shows, D-Miss.,
attended the rally. Shows and Rep. Charlie Norwood, R-Ga., have
introduced a bill to fund the promised care. It has been signed by
more than 270 members of the House, more than enough to pass it.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Rear Adm. Jeremy ``Bear'' Taylor, 66, who came to the
rally from Ogden, Utah, said he continues to work as manager of the
Ogden airport because without his civilian health insurance, he
could not afford to pay up to $1,000 a month for medication for
this wife's rheumatoid arthritis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This a great cause and we're working hard at it,'' Taylor
said, ``because people are dying as second-class citizens, even
though they paid their dues.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Priestley of Panama City, Fla., a retired Navy lieutenant
commander who organized the rally with a three-month e-mail
campaign, called on the group to go home, send out more e-mails and
return with their comrades for a bigger rally in September.
</P>
<P>
   Retired Army Sgt. Maj. Dempsey Henson, who received three Bronze
Stars and nine service-connected disabilities during his service in
Vietnam, came to the rally from Broomfield, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing fatigues, he carried a sign that declared Congress was
``ripping off'' the retirees' health care.
</P>
<P>
   After 1956, the law was passed to give military retirees who
enlisted after that time Tricare coverage rather than fully paid
health care.
</P>
<P>
   The bills in Congress would allow those who began careers after
the law was changed to enroll in the Federal Employee Health
Benefits Plan if they pay premiums equal to those paid by retired
civil service employees of the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.classact-lawsuit.com/scripts/classnews.asp
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nesmith's e.mail address is jeffn(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
