<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2316 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-NEWORLEANS-1000(2Take     05-11 0924
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWORLEANS-1000(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORLEANS-CUISINE) 
CHANGES IN NEW ORLEANS HAVEN'T TAKEN QUAINTNESS OUT OF THE FRENCH
QUARTER
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by NEW ORLEANS-IF YOU GO and NEW(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PATRICIA RODRIGUEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ It is barely after 9 a.m. as the shuttle-van
driver inches his way down Chartres Street in the French Quarter,
past shuttered boutiques and restaurants where workers are just
starting to sweep out the debris from last night's dinner rush, and
drops me off in front of the 2-month-old W hotel.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much of a sign, just a big red W suspended over the
street, but I know immediately I've arrived at the newest outlet of
the boutique hotel chain.
</P>
<P>
   The sound system is blasting techno music by Moby. In the lobby
_ a tiny, darkened room with velour-covered walls, stark leather
chairs, a stiff gold velour couch, and perpetually drawn
floor-length drapes _ a man wearing black greets me in an accent I
later decide is German. Upstairs, in my room, decorated with
flawless tastefulness in neutral tones and sleek modern lines, the
bedside CD player has been thoughtfully turned on; from the W's
house CD, Grace Jones is growling the retro-chic ``Slave to the
Rhythm.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this New Orleans _ or New York?
</P>
<P>
   One of the things I've always loved about New Orleans is that
you know where you are, from the minute you step off your flight;
the city's distinctive architecture, music and food have given it a
sense of place that seems immutable.
</P>
<P>
   Every time I visit, I know I am going to eat bread pudding
souffle at Commander's Palace and a muffuletta dripping with olive
salad at Central Grocery and a Lucky Dog from one of the ubiquitous
streetside pushcart vendors. I will stay at a creaky,
antique-filled hotel in the French Quarter and wander endlessly
through the district's narrow streets, eyeing feathered Mardi Gras
masks and colorful folk paintings. I will listen to live blues at
Tipitina's and ride the St. Charles Avenue streetcar through the
magnolia-lined Garden District, stopping to admire the stately
Southern Gothic mansions and the eerie raised tombs in the old
cemeteries.
</P>
<P>
   But as I planned this late-April trip, everyone wanted to talk
not about old familiar favorites, but new attractions.
</P>
<P>
   There was, most prestigiously, the National D-Day Museum, the
pet project of historian Stephen Ambrose, which has grown to a $23
million, multimedia installation due to open June 6. Within a year,
it will be joined by another new museum, the Ogden Museum of
Southern Art, forming the nucleus of an arts district within
walking distance of the French Quarter. There was the new, vast
Harrah's casino and a soon-to-open theme park called Jazzland, both
trading on sanitized versions of the area's music and food. Plus a
bevy of new hotels, including two Ws and several other stylish
boutique operations, not counting the Ritz-Carlton set to open this
year.
</P>
<P>
   The new hot nightspot? Whiskey Blue, a sleek LA-style lounge
owned by Cindy Crawford's husband. And of the city's 2,000
restaurants, the ones that kept getting mentioned were two new
spots, located outside the tourist-friendly French Quarter, serving
Spanish/Mediterranean and Asian cuisines, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Honestly, I was a little bit worried. Would we still be able to
tell we were in New Orleans?
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Part of New Orleans' appeal is that it has a history like no
other city in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   It was settled in 1718 by French colonists on a piece of high
ground overlooking a bend of the Mississippi River; as the city
grew in an arced shape contained by the river, it earned the first
of its many nicknames, the Crescent City. Ruled by the French and
then the Spanish before becoming part of the United States in 1812,
the city developed as a blur of European, African and Southern
influences. It became famous for its spicy creole/Cajun cuisine,
its jazz, its huge collection of pre-1800 buildings and homes, its
voodoo practitioners, and its exuberant Mardi Gras celebrations,
not necessarily in that order.
</P>
<P>
   This rich culture, plus liberal alcohol laws _ the bars never
close, and it is perfectly legal (and somewhat expected) to walk
down Bourbon Street drinking a beer _ have made it a tourist
magnet. More than 11 million people visited in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism has for years been one of the city's largest industries,
and it has expanded rapidly in the past decade. Since 1996, though
6,000 new hotel rooms have been built, bringing the city's total to
about 30,000, occupancy rates have hovered steadily at a healthy 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though New Orleans has long been a city of small
homegrown restaurants, hotels and clubs, or at least of chains
owned by families like the Brennans of Commander's Palace and
Brennan's fame, large national corporations have started to creep
in.
</P>
<P>
   Within the past few years, a House of Blues, a Virgin Records
Megastore, a Bubba Gump Shrimp Co. and a Jimmy Buffett's
Margaritaville have all opened prominent locations in the French
Quarter. Hotel chains like the Marriott and the W have taken over
and renovated many older buildings. The Harrah's casino, open since
October '99, took up an entire city block at the end of Canal
Street, with its immense gaming halls containing 3,000 slot
machines and 120 tables for games like poker and roulette; it is
estimated that each man, woman and child landing at the airport
must spend more than $60 at the casino for it to break even.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1800EDT &QL; 
