<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Clinton lights into possible successor
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton, in his most pointed attack yet against the
Republican who could follow him in the White House, said that
George W. Bush, if elected, would let polluters control the
nation's environmental policy and appoint Supreme Court justices
who would outlaw abortion. Clinton leveled his criticism in an
interview with Diane Rehm on WAMU-FM in Washington. Moreover,
Clinton said, Bush would press for big tax cuts and higher Pentagon
spending that would bring back budget deficits and higher interest
rates. ``It will mean that we won't have much money left over to
invest in education or the environment or health care,'' he said.
Clinton noted that Bush opposed the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban
Treaty _ defeated by the Senate last year _ and said Bush ``wants
to build a much bigger missile defense system than the evidence
warrants.'' He suggested Bush's positions could affect efforts to
reduce nuclear stockpiles around the world. ``So I think that gives
me some pause,'' he said. ``I think that's troublesome.''
</P>
<P>
   A FINE STATE OF AFFAIRS
</P>
<P>
   With Rudy Giuliani and his wife discussing separation, his
health in jeopardy and an extra-marital relationship exposed, even
he himself seems uncertain as to whether he will continue his
Senate bid against Hillary Clinton. ``I'm not thinking about
politics right now,'' he said at a news conference. ``I'm thinking
about my family, the people that I love. ... Politics comes at
least second, maybe third, maybe fourth, somewhere else at least.''
He added: ``It will all work itself out some way politically.''
Giuliani had just announced that he and Donna Hanover, after years
of speculation about the state of their marriage, were splitting
up. The Associated Press quoted an unnamed Republican official who
is a strong Giuliani supporter as saying the mayor was leaning
toward getting out of the race: ``His heart, his soul, his body are
not in this thing.'' But the official cautioned that Giuliani
hadn't made a final decision.
</P>
<P>
   KEY SWING VOTERS LEANING BUSH'S WAY . . .
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush is tied with Al Gore among women and leads among
conservative Democrats who supported Ronald Reagan, says a new
Voter.com-Battleground poll released today. It suggests that voters
are growing increasingly pessimistic about the state of the nation_
a bad sign for Democrats. ``All the indications are that Bush has
an edge in the race and that Gore is the underdog, which is
unbelievable given the strong economy and what Bush went through in
the primaries,'' said political analyst Stuart Rothenberg.
Nationally, Bush led Gore 48-42 percent in the bipartisan survey by
Democratic pollster Celinda Lake and Republican pollster Ed Goeas.
It had a 3 percentage point error margin. A national survey
released a day earlier by the Los Angeles Times showed Bush leading
51-43 percent among registered voters.
</P>
<P>
   . . . AND GORE GETS SOME FEMALE ADVICE
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore has been put on notice by two dozen women's
organizations that he needs to work harder to win women's political
allegiance. In an hourlong session at the Old Executive Office
Building next to the White House with about 40 leaders of the
women's groups, Gore was told he needed a better media strategy to
convey his positions on issues like Social Security, paycheck
fairness, domestic violence and abortion. ``The message isn't
getting out to women,'' Kim Gandy, executive V.P. of the National
Organization for Women, said after the meeting. Nancy Zirkin of the
American Association of University Women said the meeting was
requested four months ago, on a nonpartisan basis, so the women
could hold a general discussion with Gore about their concerns.
</P>
<P>
   MARCHING TO THE VETERANS' BEAT
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore courted veterans with $1.2 billion in new education
money for them, their families and their survivors. ``Those who
fight for our security should never have to fight for the education
they need to succeed,'' he told about 150 veterans at a VFW post in
Jacksonville, Fla. If Congress agrees, monthly federal payments to
veterans and their families would be increased by 25 percent, from
$536 to $670 next year. Benefits also would be indexed to
inflation, and veterans could use the money for other types of
learning, such as high-tech training, during school breaks. Gore
said no new money would be needed to pay for the increased benefits
since they will be covered by money available from the Department
of Veterans Affairs. George W. Bush's campaign criticized the
proposal as ``a day late'' and ``millions of dollars short.''
</P>
<P>
   TALK LIKE THE HARVARD GUYS?
</P>
<P>
   Linguists rejoice. There's hope yet for George W. Bush, who when
at a loss for a word to describe Israel once labeled the important
U.S. ally a ``buddy.'' Bush joked this week that he had ordered a
batch of ``Verbal Advantage'' vocabulary tapes, which promise users
``a Harvard graduate's vocabulary in just 15 minutes a day.'' Bush
has joked that he has no chance in November because Al Gore
graduated from Harvard. While Bush got his graduate business degree
from Harvard; his undergraduate degree is from Yale.
</P>
<P>
   BOSNIAK _ THAT MUST BE HARVARD-SPEAK
</P>
<P>
   Although aides to George W. Bush dismiss as unimportant the
several times he has mangled the proper terms for people of various
nationalities, they were elated by a report that Al Gore had
committed a similar error. Karen Hughes, Bush's communications
director, gleefully broadcast the bulletin that Gore had referred
to Bosnians as Bosniaks. ``It can happen to the best of us,''
Hughes said, ``as I hope the vice president will concede.'' Yes,
but The New York Times pointed out that Bosniak apparently is an
acceptable alternative, listed in some dictionaries.
</P>
<P>
   CORZINE'S STOCK RISES FAST
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street millionaire Jon Corzine, making his first bid for
public office with a run for the Senate in New Jersey, has eclipsed
ex-Gov. Jim Florio in their race for the Democratic nomination. A
new Quinnipiac College poll shows Corzine leading 48-33 percent
with less than a month until the primary. The margin of error was
5.3 percentage points. In March, Florio led Corzine by nearly a 2-1
margin. Six months ago, Corzine, who stepped down as co-chairman of
the Goldman Sachs investment firm last year, had only single-digit
support. A debate in Trenton tonight will be the first in a series
between the two, who're seeking the seat of retiring Democrat Frank
Lautenberg.
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
