<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-HNS &LR;      05-11 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-POLL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     POLL SHOWS BUSH GAINING IN DEMOCRATIC VOTING BLOCS  
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (EDS: Filed in ``w'' and ``p'' categories)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)   
 &HT;     By STEWART M. POWELL   
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican George W. Bush is making dramatic
inroads into traditional Democratic constituencies to lead Democrat
Al Gore 48 percent to 42 percent in the presidential race,
according to a bipartisan survey released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Voter.com-Battleground 2000 survey conducted by Democratic
pollster Celinda Lake and Republican pollster Ed Goeas showed that
voter anxiety over moral values and the direction of the nation _
rather than proposed solutions for specific problems _ is helping
Bush garner support among once-loyal Democratic voting blocs.
</P>
<P>
   Anniversaries of the shootings at Columbine High School and the
Oklahoma City bombing, coupled with fresh episodes of mass killings
and tremors in the stock markets have stirred voters' concerns
about the future of their nation, Lake and Goeas reported.
</P>
<P>
   The scandals that afflicted President Clinton during his
presidency continue to shape attitudes as well, with 62 percent of
those surveyed expressing disapproval of Clinton ``as a person'' at
the same time that 57 percent express approval of his handling of
his job as president.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has stormed back from a 4 percentage-point deficit among
women voters in March to seize a 3 percentage-point edge over Gore
among women _ thanks to a whopping 12 percentage point edge among
white women. Bush now leads Gore among all; women, 47 percent to 44
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush even enjoys a 14 percentage-point advantage over Gore among
conservative Democrats who voted for Ronald Reagan in the 1980s but
returned to the Democratic fold to help elect President Clinton to
two terms. Bush now leads among the key swing bloc, 55 percent to
41 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also has gained against Gore among union households,
slashing Gore's 11 percentage point edge in March to just 2
percentage points in the latest survey.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also is scoring gains in the Midwest where both Lake and
Goeas predict the 2000 presidential campaign will be decided. Bush
leads Gore 45 percent to 40 percent in Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has scored the gains thanks to his adoption of an
``umbrella theme'' that emphasizes ``compassionate conservatism,''
steps to overhaul the education system and plans to end partisan
rancor, said Goeas, president of the Tarrance Group, a polling firm
that is polling for five Republican governors, 16 Republican
senators and more than 40 GOP House members.
</P>
<P>
   The joint Republican-Democratic survey was conducted nationwide
by telephone from May 1 to May 3 _ six months before the election _
to reach 1,000 likely voters. The margin of error is 3.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The survey assessed voter sentiment nationwide. The U.S.
Constitution calls for presidential elections to be decided by
candidates' accumulation of electoral votes in state-by-state
contests rather than a single nationwide popularity contest.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big story is that the gender gap has been neutralized by
George W. Bush without losing the intensity with men,'' Goeas said.
</P>
<P>
   Lake said Bush's post-primary campaign is boosting his support
among women by neutralizing the long-standing advantage that
Democratic candidates enjoy from proposals to solve specific
``kitchen table'' issues such as health-care reform, protecting the
solvency of Social Security and expanding the reach of Medicare for
elderly Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key dynamic to this election is whether Democrats can
break through the values' barrier and talk about issues in a
values-oriented way to maximize their advantage on the issues,''
said Lake, a pollster for the 1992 Clinton campaign who now serves
as president of Lake Snell Perry &AMP; Associates, Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats ``have to be worried about'' Republican success
hijacking the venerable Democratic issue of education reform, Lake
said, noting that Democrats' 20 percentage-point advantage on the
issue in 1998 has been cut to a 7 percentage-point edge now.
</P>
<P>
   Lake declared: ``Democrats clearly need a big fight on education
to clarify where the Republicans are on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has suffered other setbacks, including diminution of
support among African American women since voters were energized by
the Democratic presidential primaries. The survey found that 53
percent of African-American women said they believed the country
was on the ``wrong track'' _ sentiment that could reduce turnout
for Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Voters' ambivalence and increasingly pessimistic outlook could
spell trouble for Democrats as November grows closer,'' Lake
warned. ``Democrats need to mobilize their constituencies.''
</P>
<P>
   Support for Gore among working women in general and retired
women in particular has ebbed since March, Lake said. Bush has
reaped an 18 percentage-point gain since March among white senior
women, aged over 65, to hold a 9-percentage point advantage over
Gore, the survey found.
</P>
<P>
   Lake and Goeas said that Gore could face additional challenges
carrying Democratic-leaning states such as California, Oregon,
Washington and New Mexico due to third-party challenges from the
Reform Party's Pat Buchanan and the Green Party's Ralph Nader.
Those two candidates each drew 3 percent of the vote in the latest
survey, but if that swells to 5 percent or more, their candidacies
could hurt Gore in key Democratic states, Lake and Goeas said.
</P>
<P>
   In a hypothetical four-way race nationwide, Bush leads Gore 45
percent to 39 percent, with Buchanan and Nader drawing 3 percent
each. Buchanan and Nader have not yet completed arrangements to
appear on the November ballot in all 50 states.
</P>
<P>
   The single biggest boost Gore gets from the survey is evidence
that he is rebounding among Hispanic voters, a traditionally
Democratic voting bloc with the exception of GOP-leaning
Cuban-Americans in Florida. Gore has recovered from Bush's initial
9 percentage-point edge among Hispanics to lead Bush by 12
personage-points in the latest survey.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
