<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-COURT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI HIGH COURT BARS PAROLE FOR SETTLER CONVICTED OF KILLING
ARAB 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOEL GREENBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ The Supreme Court on Thursday overturned a decision
to parole a Jewish settler who had initially been sentenced to life
imprisonment for the execution-style killing of a Palestinian.
</P>
<P>
   The settler, Yoram Skolnik, 31, was granted parole in March on
the ground that he did not pose a danger to the public. His
sentence had been twice commuted, first to 15 years by President
Ezer Weizman, then to 11 years by a former justice minister, Tzahi
Hanegbi.
</P>
<P>
   Skolnik was to have been freed last month, but his release was
held up by a petition to the Supreme Court by Zehava Galon, a
legislator from the leftist Meretz Party.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling on the petition Thursday, a seven-judge panel headed by
the chief justice, Aharon Barak, said the parole board had acted
unreasonably by failing to give appropriate weight to the danger
posed by Skolnik, who the judges said had acted out of ``profound
hatred'' stemming from a dangerous ``nationalistic ideology.''
</P>
<P>
   The judges ruled that Skolnik should serve out the remaining
four years of his term.
</P>
<P>
   On March 23, 1993, Sknolnik killed Musah Abu Sabha, a
Palestinian who had been caught near Susia, a settlement south of
Hebron in the West Bank, carrying a knife and grenade. Abu Sabha
was subdued after trying to stab a settler, and as he lay face down
with his hands bound behind him, Sknolnik shot him nine times with
an Uzi submachine gun.
</P>
<P>
   Galon, the petitioner, said after Thursday's ruling that the
decision to parole Skolnik had been ``morally tainted.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Supreme Court is essentially saying that a murderer cannot
go free after seven years,'' she said. ``The price for murdering an
Arab is not seven years,'' she added; such a short term ``is
unacceptable in Israeli society.''
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians sentenced to life terms for killing Israelis have
not had their sentences commuted, nor have they been eligible for
parole. But as part of interim accords with the Palestinians,
Israel has released scores of prisoners convicted of killing fellow
Arabs whom they suspected of being informers for the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Alluding to those releases, Fred Skolnik, Skolnik's father, said
after Thursday's ruling, ``There are murderers who have served
less: terrorists.''
</P>
<P>
   Benny Elon, a legislator from the extreme rightist Moledet
Party, accused the judges of favoring Galon's views. ``When she
petitions the Supreme Court, she's coming home,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a similar case, the district court in Tel Aviv sentenced a
settler, Gur Hamel, 28, to life imprisonment for killing an elderly
Palestinian in an olive grove near the West Bank settlement of
Itamar in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hamel attacked the Palestinian, Ahmed Hatatbeh, 68, as he was
harvesting olives near Beit Furik, a Palestinian village,
strangling him and then crushing his head with a rock. Hamel
originally claimed that he had acted in self-defense. The judge
rejected arguments by Hamel's lawyer that he was emotionally
disturbed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
