<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-ART-610&AMP;ADD-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHECHEN REBELS ATTACK RUSSIAN TROOPS IN NEIGHBORING REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Secessionist rebels mounted a major attack outside
Chechnya's borders for the first time in nearly nine months
Thursday, all but wiping out a convoy of 22 Russian soldiers as it
moved down a mountain road in Ingushetia, a Russian region
bordering Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The mid-morning ambush of two troop trucks and an armored
vehicle in the foothills of the Caucasus Mountains killed 18
Russian Interior Ministry troops and wounded three others. One
soldier was reported missing.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials said the servicemen had finished a tour of
duty in Ingushetia and were preparing to head home when the attack
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were attacked treacherously with grenade launchers by
bandits who hd in the roadside bush,'' the first deputy chief of
the Russian general staff, Col. Gen. Valery Manilov, said. ``We
hope that we will track them down and punish them for their
crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Russian planes later bombed forests near the ambush site, north
of the village of Khalashki and just a few miles from the major
government-run camps for Chechen war refugees. It was not known
whether the attackers were hit.
</P>
<P>
   With Thursday's deaths, Manilov said, 2,251 Russian servicemen
have died in the Chechen conflict, a figure some outside experts
contend is well below the true number.
</P>
<P>
   The ambush was a departure for the battered rebels, who had not
attacked Russian troops outside Chechnya's borders since the early
stages of the Chechen war in September. The war began last summer
after rebels invaded the neighboring province of Dagestan, touching
off a struggle with Russian troops along the border of the two
provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel leaders threatened on Tuesday to carry their war for
Chechen independence into nearby provinces unless Russian troops
withdraw from Chechnya by the end of May.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels' website, www.kavkaz.org, quoted the guerrilla
commander Shamil Basayev as saying that the rebels would ``declare
jihad across the whole of the Caucasus, everywhere the Russian
aggressors are.''
</P>
<P>
   The main Russian spokesman on the conflict, Sergei
Yastrzhembsky, dismissed the threat as ``mere bravado not backed by
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear if the rebels, backed into southern Chechnya's
mountains by the Russians, could widen the conflict beyond periodic
ambushes like the one Thursday. The Russian military says many
guerrillas have melted into the civilian populations of Chechnya
and Ingushetia.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ambushes like Thursday's make it clear that
Russian forces have not restored order to the area, as spokesmen
are now claiming. The rebels have staged damaging attacks on
Russian convoys on the average of every two weeks since general
fighting ended in March, killing as many as 32 soldiers in a single
ambush.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian military says it has killed about 100 rebels this
month alone.
</P>
<P>
   Manilov argued Thursday that ``despite all the difficulties and
complexities, life is returning to normal'' in Chechnya. He said
296 of the 353 schools had reopened; 37 of 60 hospitals were in
operation; and some 2,500 rebels had taken up an amnesty offer,
extended to May 15, and laid down their arms.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The subsiding of open war appears to have won over the Council
of Europe, a 41-member group that threatened to suspend Russia's
membership over human-rights violations in the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The group dropped the threat Thursday at a meeting in
Strasbourg, France, after Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov argued that
Russia has established its own agency to investigate allegations of
crimes and human-rights abuses by its troops.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The council repeated its demand that Russia open talks with
Chechen representatives on a political settlement, but Manlilov and
Yastrzhembsky re-stated Thursday that that is not an option.
</P>
<P>
   The prospects for a political dialogue briefly brightened this
week after it was disclosed that the head of an independent Russian
commission looking into wartime abuses, the Russian legislator
Pavel Krasheninnikov, had met in Ingushetia with a top
representative of Chechnya's president, Aslan Maskhadov.
</P>
<P>
   Krasheninnikov apparently traveled to the meeting under the
protection of Russian troops, lending the air of an official
endorsement to the session.
</P>
<P>
   But Manilov on Thursday repeated the official line on talks,
saying that the notion of negotiations with Maskhadov is
``nonsense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0248 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2336 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      05-11 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FIRST-RELEASE DIRECTOR MEETS A BIG BOY 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK LYMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Tom Dey thought the preview screening of ``Shanghai
Noon,'' his first effort as a feature film director, was going
pretty well, but he was unprepared for the phone call from Disney
distribution executives. ``They said they were so excited about it
that they wanted to make it their big Memorial Day release,'' Dey
said. ``Never did I imagine anything like that. We were just a
relatively small production shooting in Calgary. We were never
considered a summer heavyweight. It was a dream come true.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Dey and his comical western, starring Jackie Chan and
Owen Wilson, is up against Tom Cruise and ``Mission: Impossible
2,'' the only two national releases on the summer's premier movie
weekend. Cruise opens on May 24, Chan two days later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to work this angle: We're the underdogs, feel sorry
for us,'' Dey said.
</P>
<P>
   The summer movie season is already here. ``Gladiator'' opened to
$34 million last weekend. John Travolta's ``Battlefield Earth''
opens on Friday, Disney's computer-animated ``Dinosaur'' on May 19.
Then comes Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   The films considered likeliest to be box-office champions _
which include ``The Patriot'' with Mel Gibson, ``The Perfect
Storm'' with George Clooney and ``Nutty Professor 2: The Klumps''
with Eddie Murphy _ will roll out with weekly predictability
through Labor Day weekend. But which films, if any, will emerge as
the summer's sleepers? Some think ``Shanghai Noon'' is a contender.
</P>
<P>
   The film is a gentle-hearted western about a Chinese Imperial
Guard ( Chan) who comes to America in the 1880s to rescue a
kidnapped princess (Lucy Liu) and hooks up with a hapless train
robber ( Wilson).
</P>
<P>
   Dey, working his way through a slice of gooseberry pie at the
Farmer's Market this week, said he had not really wanted to make
the film when he walked into a meeting with executives at Spyglass
Entertainment, which produced the film (as it did last summer's
``Sixth Sense'') with Disney. ``But there I was, in the room with
them, and I suddenly started pitching and talking about how I'd
make the film, and they said they really liked what they heard,''
Dey recalled. ``I thought, `Oh, what have I done?'''
</P>
<P>
   He flew to Hong Kong to meet with Chan, star of the 1998 sleeper
hit ``Rush Hour,'' and then to Beijing, where some of the opening
scenes were eventually shot in the Forbidden City, after much
difficulty.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1994, after studying at the American Film Institute, Dey
had been making television commercials at Ridley Scott Associates.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Shanghai Noon'' opens, though, he plans to take some
time off before tackling another project. ``I don't know if I have
a directorial style,'' he said. ``I mean, this is just my first
movie. But I think that, basically, I'd rather be felt than
heard.''
</P>
<P>
   That is to say, he would rather go for the emotion in a scene
than go for the funny line. He learned something else, too, he
said. Not until ``Shanghai Noon'' was well into shooting did he
realize what it was really about: the friendship between Chan's and
Wilson's characters. ``It's not about an Imperial Guard coming to
America to rescue a princess,'' he said. ``It's about friendship.
It's about a very simple thing. That's maybe the most important
thing this movie taught me. I learned how to look into a script and
find that simple thing.''
</P>
<P>
   TRACEY LOVES WOODY
</P>
<P>
   Tracey Ullman's office, from which she plots her career and runs
her critically acclaimed HBO comedy series, is on a residential
side street in central Santa Monica, within exhaust reach of the
freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call from Woody Allen saying he had a new script and
wanted me to play a part in it,'' Ullman said. ``I asked if I could
see the script, and they had someone bring it over. The man sat out
there on the sofa while I sat in here and read it. It was a
wonderful part. Could I keep the script? I called up and asked. And
they said yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen has been known to refuse to allow his actors to see, much
less keep, an entire script, so Ullman was happily surprised. It
was necessary, though, because of the size of her part. In ``Small
Time Crooks,'' the first film Allen will release through
DreamWorks, Allen plays a hapless hoodlum who has a loving but
bombastic relationship with his long-suffering wife, played by
Ullman. Opening on May 19, it co-stars Hugh Grant, Michael Rapaport
and Elaine May.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you see Woody in the movie?'' she asked. ``I thought he
looked so cute in his stone-washed denim shorts. It was great
seeing him play somebody again who wasn't rich and sophisticated.''
</P>
<P>
   Ullman said that Allen always knew what he wanted in a scene but
that he was also willing to let some of the actors try lines or
movements or wardrobe of their own. Grant, who plays an
uncharacteristically unsympathetic role, was able to ad-lib a
revealingly acid twist on his exit line in one scene, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all,'' she said. ``I would be happy if I were to do
nothing for the rest of my life but my television series and Woody
Allen movies.''
</P>
<P>
   A MODERN CLAUDIUS
</P>
<P>
   Claudius is normally played by an actor appreciably older than
the one playing Hamlet. ``I thought that they had the name of the
part wrong when they called to ask me to play the role,'' said Kyle
MacLachlan, who appears opposite Ethan Hawke's Danish prince in
Michael Almereyda's modern-day translation of the Shakespeare
tragedy, opening on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It had been many years since MacLachlan had played Shakespeare.
Before landing his career-starting role in the lead of David
Lynch's ``Dune,'' he had studied and performed Shakespeare in
regional theater, playing Romeo twice, the boy in ``Henry V'' and
Octavius in ``Julius Caesar.'' Between ``Dune'' and now, no
Shakespeare.
</P>
<P>
   MacLachlan said he was particularly taken with Almereyda's
decision to pitch the tragedy in a very naturalistic, American
style of acting and speaking. ``I've always maintained that the
best way to speak Shakespeare is to make it as accessible as
possible,'' he said. ``If that means you ruin the structure of the
poetry, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   He can also be seen in Mike Figgis' experimental ``Time Code,''
and will be spending the next few months in New York filming a role
_ as the first substantial romantic interest for Charlotte (Kristin
Davis) _ in ``Sex and the City'' on HBO. At the same time, he said,
he hopes to renew his contacts with the New York theater world and
possibly land a stage role. ``I'd love for it to be Shakespeare,''
he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
