<HEADER>
A2337 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l BC-FITNESS-BALLS-HNS &LR;      05-11 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FITNESS-BALLS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MEDICINE BALLS MAKE A COMEBACK IN GYMS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By KRISTI L. GUSTAFSON   
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Walk into your local gym and you're guaranteed to
see many frightening (and often unidentifiable) pieces of workout
equipment. But now adult fitness centers are looking a little like
a children's gymboree, with knee-high white, red and blue balls
rolling around the room. Although you may be tempted to toss a
ball, or even bounce on it since it resembles the popular pogo
ball, they're meant to be used to improve fitness.
</P>
<P>
   Kate Ryan, group fitness director at an area Gold's Gym has been
incorporating the rubbery fitness balls into her strength-training
classes for four years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball helps to both strengthen and tone because you're
working a whole new group of muscles just by trying to maintain
your balance,'' Ryan said. ``It can become a full-body workout.''
</P>
<P>
   What is now the latest fitness craze originated in Europe as a
physical therapy tool nearly 50 years ago and was introduced to the
United States in the 1960s. Columbia Physical Therapy in East
Greenbush, N.Y., has used the balls for the past four years to help
treat neurological disorders, orthopedic problems and back pain,
according to therapist Denise Conklin.
</P>
<P>
   She has found them particularly useful with older adults,
particularly in helping them regain balance. They start by
maintaining their balance sitting on the ball, as if it were a
chair and move on to leg and arm lifts (while sitting) as balance
improves.
</P>
<P>
   The ball as a fitness tool is nothing new. They were originally
called medicine balls or Swiss balls (because of their European
origin). Now you'll find a wide variety manufactured by fitness
companies, such as FitBall and Resist-A-Ball, and sold online and
in sports stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw them at all the fitness conferences and decided to try
them with our clients,'' said Randy Jurus, a fitness manager at an
area gym. ``They were popular almost immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   As a personal trainer, Jurus uses the fitness balls with the
majority of her clients.
</P>
<P>
   Jurus often has clients stretch their upper body by lying over
the ball and using it as a guide to reach out farther than they
normally would.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball acts as a guide and usually helps people to me more
effective with their stretches,'' Jurus said. ``They'll stretch
further and push themselves more.''
</P>
<P>
   When incorporated into a fitness class or training session the
ball can act as a replacement for a workout bench, the wall or even
the floor, adding variety and difficulty to the exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're perfect for the beginner to the professional athlete,
especially skiers and golfers,'' Ryan said. ``And age is not a
factor. We have children, teens, adults and seniors all using the
ball for different workouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Skiers often loosen up and practice the twisting motion and
movements they use on the slopes with the help of the fitness
balls. Skiers are able to strengthen the hip and leg muscles used
on the slopes by doing squats with the ball between their backs and
the wall. Twisting with the 3.14-pound ball in hand strengthens
oblique muscles which are important for core strength, a
fundamental concern of skiers, according to Kathleen Lessman,
former editor of Freeze magazine, a skiing publication, in order to
ease muscle strain.
</P>
<P>
   Strength training often involves using the ball for support
while maintaining your balance throughout various exercises.
</P>
<P>
   ``People often have a difficult time keeping their balance while
lifting a leg or their arms, which is often done when strength
training with the ball,'' Ryan said. ``It takes time to develop the
coordination and balance necessary for the fitness ball to truly be
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Ryan will use the fitness balls for part of a class.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ball helps to vary the routine and it keeps it
interesting,'' said Dr. Lisa Silverberg, 48, who takes Ryan's
classes throughout the week. ``It keeps it challenging and exciting
and I'm motivated to keep up with Kate (Ryan).''
</P>
<P>
   The American Council on Exercise tests each fitness fad to hit
the gym floors and strongly recommends fitness balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of the few new exercise tools that is not gimmicky,''
said Mark Anders of the council. ``People show significant
improvement in both strength and muscle mass once they begin using
the ball on a regular basis.''
</P>
<P>
   The inflatable balls are made of thick, durable PVC foam and are
among the less expensive pieces of equipment used to tighten and
tone. For about $20 to $50 each, it is a much cheaper alternative
to the large and costly exercise machines that often become dust
gatherers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
