<SLUG> BC-OVERWHELMED-COURTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     JUDGES ALONG THE U.S.-MEXICO BORDER PLEAD FOR MORE MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MARK HELM  
 &HT;     c. 2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Six years after the government began boosting law
enforcement along the U.S.-Mexico border, soaring arrest rates are
stretching court caseloads to the breaking point from South Texas
to California, a group of federal judges said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you think it's legitimate to fight crime and illegal
immigration, then you also need to give us the resources to finish
the job after the arrests are made,'' said Chief Judge Marilyn L.
Huff of the U.S. District Court for the Southern District of
California.
</P>
<P>
   Huff made the blunt comment to lawmakers at a Capitol Hill
meeting. She and six other federal judges from the Southwest called
on Congress and President Clinton to approve an 8.5 percent hike in
judiciary spending, from $4.3 billion this year to $4.6 billion in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The federal police presence along the border has jumped sharply
since 1994. The number of immigration agents has grown by 93
percent; drug agents are up 155 percent, and the U.S. Border Patrol
alone has doubled _ to 5,000 agents.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, arrests are up 125 percent in the region. The
Administrative Office of the U.S. Courts projects that in two years
courts in the five southwest border districts will be handling
almost a third of all federal criminal cases filed in the United
States, up from a quarter of the cases now. In the border town of
Del Rio, Texas, more people were indicted on federal charges in
1998 than in Houston, the nation's fourth-largest city.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the dramatic rise, the five districts along the
border have seen only a 30 percent increase in court staff since
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Dineen King, chief judge of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals in New Orleans, said at the meeting, ``I think when our
senators and congressmen look at the numbers, they will support our
efforts.''King said evidence that the legal system in the Southwest
is in distress can be seen ``everywhere.''U.S. marshals,
responsible for guarding thousands of additional prisoners without
added resources, are dangerously outnumbered, she said. On some
occasions, two marshals are assigned to escort as many as 80
prisoners to or from court, she said.
</P>
<P>
   As federal prisons have filled, King said, marshals have been
forced to haul prisoners to jails hundreds of miles from the
border. The officers worry that they will face an escape attempt or
a riot, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Huff said that prisoners from her court in San Diego are being
housed in jails as far away as Oklahoma and Seattle. ``Every time
these prisoners need to appear in court, we have to bus them
hundreds of miles to my court, and then put them on the bus and
send them back,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Inside federal courthouses, security is a constant concern, King
said. A prosecutor in Tucson, Ariz., was ordered to abandon her
post when she found herself alone in a courtroom with 45 unmanacled
prisoners and only two unarmed marshals.Huff said that prosecutors
_ overwhelmed by caseloads that have doubled or tripled _ are
forced to cut deals that allow criminals to serve shorter
sentences. ``When you have 4,000 cases before eight judges, there's
no other way,'' she said.Huff said the only way her district can
handle the tidal wave of cases is to press into service six judges
who have retired, including one who is 86.U.S. District Judge
Edward C. Prado said the 10 federal judges in the western district
of Texas handle an average of 703 cases a year, just under 10 times
the national average.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about judges who are afraid to work long hours,''
he said. ``It's about a system that is being overwhelmed.''
</P>
<P>
   King said she and the other judges felt they had to come to
Washington because few lawmakers have addressed the problem in the
region.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist also has urged Congress to
add judges to the federal courts in the Southwest. Rehnquist said
earlier this year that those courts face an ``unmanageable'' trial
schedule because of illegal immigration and drug crimes in the
region. At the meeting Thursday, several lawmakers whose districts
lie along or near the border promised to push Congress to raise
spending on district courts in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of us who live on the border understand the problem and
want to help,'' said Rep. Solomon P. Ortiz, D-Texas, whose district
includes the border city of Brownsville.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Silvestre Reyes, D-Texas, who worked 26 years as a Border
Patrol agent and sector chief, said Congress should ``act to
relieve the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
