A2348 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-BUCHMAN-QA14-COX     05-11 0480
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUCHMAN-QA14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP;A with Dana Buchman
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Memphis native Dana Buchman tends to portray herself as a
designer with a businesswoman's mindset. The runway shows that most
other New York-based designers stage bi-annually are, in Buchman's
opinion, too superfluous and cost-ineffective. And the celebrities
that most designers covet as clients are, in her view, so many
alien beings who really can't do much to advance her 14-year-old
signature brands or her three-decades-old career.
</P>
<P>
   Buchman, 47, made a recent personal appearance at Phipps Plaza's
Saks Fifth Avenue in Atlanta. After a runway showing of her spring
and fall collections (proceeds from which benefit the State of
Israel Bonds foundation), she sat down for a chat with fashion
editor A. Scott Walton.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What direction are you taking your clothes in response to the
casualization of the workplace?
</P>
<P>
   A: I'm not into casualization. You need casual, soccer mom
clothes for the weekend, of course. And many companies are going
casual. But I notice that the women I dress _ who are not the cute
young things, but the women with more status in their organizations
_ they want to look put together.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where do your design ideas originate?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's an evolution. I always start with the color, and then
pick the fabric and make sure it works with the color. And then you
make adjustments. And silhouettes come next.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How hard do you work to stay in keeping with prevailing
trends?
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't think my customer wants to be way ahead. But she
doesn't want to be behind either. The pace has picked up over the
last 10 years. Things happen all at once. So you want to look `on
trend.' But the customer I dress doesn't want what she bought to
look funny in a year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Does being a native Southerner affect your work in any way?
</P>
<P>
   A: The colors I use come from the South. The South has this
great light. Have you been to New York in the winter? It's so
different. The light here makes you want to dress differently. The
other thing is I tend to do seasonless fabrics.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has your design approach changed much?
</P>
<P>
   A: I haven't changed the fundamental aesthetics, which have
always been color, fabric, femininity, fit and detail. But I have
made the line younger in the last year or two. And it's been very
well received.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why aren't you selling on the Internet yet?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think e-commerce will work for us. We're not that huge of a
company, so we thought we'd let other, bigger companies work out
the kinks first. Some of the specialty department stores we sell to
are launching sites, and we're very involved with that.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
