<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIM-TRUNKS14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Swimsuits for men just got smaller
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    By Ginger McFarland
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Women would be well-advised to put extra ice in those poolside
drinks this summer, because men's swimwear has the potential to
raise the heat index.
</P>
<P>
   This season's trendiest look in trunks is a cross between a
competition-style brief and a boxer brief. Retailers call them
``box-cut'' or ``square-cut.'' We call them tight and tiny.
</P>
<P>
   Prada's got a pair with little side ventilation zippers _ as if
these short shorts need ventilation. And Gucci, ever the
envelope-pusher, offers the same style in a red and white tropical
print as well as an even more daring bikini style that ties on one
side.
</P>
<P>
   This new breed of trunks is great for getting the optimum in
rays and stares from all those who wish they could look as good as
you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only the most confident of men are buying this style,'' said
Donnie Sukarome, manager of the Polo Sport store at Lenox Square.
``I only ordered a few, but we sold out as soon as they came in.''
</P>
<P>
   P.S. If you don't have the confidence to pull off the box cut or
Speedo, go with the Hawaiian print broad short _ they're great for
everybody.
</P>
<P>
   Ginger McFarland writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
