<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWIMSUITS-ONEPIECE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Designers put imagination and innovation into their one-piece
styles
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One-piece swimsuits aren't just for coverage-conscious women
anymore. For this season, designers poured as much imagination and
innovation into their one-piece styles as they devoted to bikini
and tankini looks in the past.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the newest one-pieces burst with an array of
bright colors. Any neutral suits have the added appeal of shiny,
sleek-looking fabrication. Embellishment _ embroidered necklines,
piped trim in contrasting colors and cut-outs _ heighten the suits'
style quotient. And designers have done interesting things with
straps to draw more attention to the soft curves of women's
shoulders and reveal more of their backs.
</P>
<P>
   There are lots of reasons why one-piece suits work: more
coverage; underwire support systems that are more comfortable and
less conspicuous; and they transition more fluidly between
swimming, sunbathing, beachcombing and pool parties than bikinis
do.
</P>
<P>
   And don't forget _ there's less risk of the top or bottom half
getting lost in the wash.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B :
</P>
<P>
   For more information about this topic:
</P>
<P>
   www.jantzen.com
</P>
<P>
   www.bramasole.com
</P>
<P>
   www.maliamills.com
</P>
<P>
   A. Scott Walton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
