<HEADER>
A2351 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-BOOKS-SKUBE14-COX     05-11 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-SKUBE14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A son relives mother's death years afterward
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed For Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``At the end, a nurse stripped the neck brace, pressed her
fingers against the carotid artery, and felt for the faintest sign
of a pulse. The Velcro made a sound like stitches ripping.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodger Kamenetz's remembrance of his mother in ``Terra Infirma:
A Memoir of My Mother's Life in Mine'' (Schocken Books, $11
paperback) is both tender and bittersweet, with none of the false
sentimentality of a Mother's Day card. In both its lyricism and its
emotional subtlety, it recalls Russell Baker's opening sentence in
``Growing Up'': ``At the age of 80 my mother had her last bad fall,
and after that her mind wandered free through time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sons more often than daughters seem to hear a parent's
admonitory voice from beyond the grave, and seek redemption through
words that went unspoken when there was still time. But settling
accounts can be painful. Oscar
</P>
<P>
   Wilde's unsparing observation is true in more instances than we
like to acknowledge:
</P>
<P>
   ``Children begin by loving their parents. After a time they
judge them. Rarely, if ever, do they forgive them.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of us are luckier than others, and it would be nice to
report that Kamenetz _ who teaches literature at Louisiana State
University _ found in his mother's agonizing death a measure of
forgiveness. It would be nice to report that his mother's last
words released him from the guilt of unfulfilled promise. But
redemption comes unbidden, like grace. ``Her dying words,'' he
writes, ``were a triumph. They hold me still in their grip.''
</P>
<P>
   Becoming `somebody'
</P>
<P>
   Kamenetz's mother _ like Baker's _ wanted him to ``be
somebody,'' but his mother's idea of being somebody had the spur of
social inferiority and the goad of envy. Miriam Kieff grew up the
abandoned child of a mother and father she tried to obliterate from
memory. Brought up by her grandfather, she dropped out of high
school at 16 and went to work at a Woolworth's store in Baltimore,
selling costume jewelry. One summer she and her sister lit out for
Atlantic City, and there she met Irvin Kamenetz, just out of the
military and with no aspirations of his own.
</P>
<P>
   His mother was always ashamed, Kamenetz writes, that she never
finished high school. Yet from that scarred childhood grew a fierce
drive to make something of herself. ``Even though both her mother
and her father abandoned her, she did not abandon herself. With her
children grown, she returned to school and graduated from college.
But she never found whatever it was she needed, and her failed
hopes would be her children's to fulfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until I graduated from Yale,'' Kamenetz writes, ``I was my
mother's main chance.'' Alas, he graduated _ in the spring of 1970
_ from experimenting with LSD and participating in antiwar
demonstrations to pounding the pavement and sweeping floors. No one
was hiring poets that year. ``She was disappointed I didn't become
`somebody great, like Henry Kissinger.' After all, I'd gone to
Yale. She didn't realize that all I'd opened in New Haven were the
doors to perception. ... One day my brother told me, `She's given
up on you.' At last I had succeeded in failing.''
</P>
<P>
   As that passage should suggest, Kamenetz's is a portrayal both
of his mother and of himself. It is one of filial love but also
self-flagellation. And even the love that Kamenetz quite obviously
feels for his mother is streaked with bitterness. If Kamenetz is
not every mother's son, neither was Miriam Kieff the
undifferentiated figure whose motives were selfless and maternal.
</P>
<P>
   Tangled emotions
</P>
<P>
   Most of us know little of our parents' childhood. Intimately
familiar with our own childhood, we resist thinking that our
mothers and fathers once had theirs, with the same uncertainties
and insecurities. Our parents were forever adults. Then there comes
a time, usually in midlife, when we try to re-create the child who
would become our mother or our father and we draw a blank.
</P>
<P>
   In their particularities, Miriam Kieff and the infant she bore
50 years ago embodied the tangled emotions that bind families
together and, sometimes, keep them apart. The Kamenetzes were a
family that came together only at the mother's deathbed.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mother died in the Church Home Hospice in Baltimore,''
Kamenetz writes, ``at the age of 54. Her last words were `I Love
You.' The radio was playing `Raindrops Keep Falling on My Head.'''
</P>
<P>
   That he should be in the grip of her words all these years later
tells us something of the biological bond between mother and child.
Kamenetz wanted, despite himself, to succeed for the sake of the
woman who was not herself lovable but who nonetheless gave him
life. The death of the father, Freud somewhere writes, is the
emancipation of the son. It is the death of the mother that is
relived in the quiet moments long after.
</P>
<P>
   THE READING ROOM, the AJC's guide for book clubs that appears
the fourth Sunday of every month on these pages, is available
online at www.accessatlanta.com/partners
</P>
<P>
   /ajc/xsite/readroom/
</P>
<P>
   Questions or suggestions? E-mail readingroom(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
