<HEADER>
A2352 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-CENTERSTAGE12-     05-11 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-CENTERSTAGE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dance rules saga of love, sweat, tears
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Center Stage'' is aimed at those adolescent girls who have toe
shoes dangling from their bedposts and posters of Mikhail
Baryshnikov stuck on their walls. Or of the newer dance
hearttthrob, Ethan Stiefel.
</P>
<P>
   An old-fashioned show biz fantasy with leotards and plies,
``Center Stage'' is a kind of movie that gets retooled every 10
years or so. Its antecedents include ``Fame,'' ``Dirty Dancing,''
``The Turning Point'' and even ``Flashdance.'' It's the female
version of a sports movie: Sweat and inspiration lead to love and
brief heartache, but ultimately, growth, self-worth and even
stardom result. (Instead of the Big Game, the flick climaxes with
the Big Show.)
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Schull has the Jennifer Grey/Jennifer Beals role, playing
wholesome Jody Sawyer, who lands one of the coveted spots at the
American Ballet Academy in Manhattan. Artistic director Jonathan
Reeves (Peter Gallagher) and top teacher Juliette (Donna Murphy)
make it clear from the start: At semester's end, only six of the
students (at most) will be asked to join the dance company
affiliated with the school.
</P>
<P>
   Cue the cat fights! In its early minutes, ``Center Stage''
promises to be a hopeless soap opera, tossing together young
characters designed to clash. Nice Jody winds up rooming with
tough, arrogant Eva (Zoe Saldana), who slouches in late to class
and defies the school's uniform rules. Their third roomie is
Maureen (Susan May Pratt), an uptight princess with a steely stage
mother (Debra Monk) and (no big surprise here) a streak of bulimia.
</P>
<P>
   On the Y-chromosome side of school, there's nice-guy Charlie
(Sascha Radetsky), who has his eye on Jody. But she's smitten with
choreographer Cooper (Stiefel, ABT's real-life dance star), who not
only moves like a god but rides a Harley.
</P>
<P>
   Stage-turned-screen director Nicholas Hytner (``The Madness of
King George'') knows ballet, and he relishes the demanding work it
requires. The movie underscores the cruel physical imperatives of
the discipline, from Maureen's eating disorders to the widespread
mockery of a student who's packing a few pounds more than the
rail-thin ideal.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Center Stage'' is not exactly a backstage expose. Its main
purpose is to entertain, and even the rivalries among the
characters melt away. The movie goes exactly where you expect:
Jody's eyes are opened to the man who really loves her; Eva stops
throwing attitude and gets serious about her dancing; Maureen
stands up to mom and dares to eat pizza.
</P>
<P>
   There's something sweet about the movie's familiar formula, its
generosity toward its characters. More demanding adults should
remember that this is geared for teenagers (though it doesn't shy
away from some discreet sexual situations). The actors were chosen
mostly because they can dance; it's a kick to see them leap and
spin without stunt doubles. On the downside, these kids can
sometimes underwhelm in the acting department, but never painfully.
</P>
<P>
   Prized stage choreographer Susan Stroman (``Contact,''
``Chicago'') choreographed the numbers, which include classical
ballet moves, a high-energy Broadway dance class, some salsa
dancing and the big, climactic show performed by the students.
</P>
<P>
   In this last big sequence, Hytner gleefully goes over the top,
daring us to complain when he tosses reality to the wind. (For
example, Schull, dancing the lead role, goes through several
costumes and hairstyles without leaving the stage.) Young dance
lovers won't care. Neither will adults with gently lowered
expectations. ``Center Stage'' may be softheaded and hokey, but
it's bighearted. And it knows how to move.
</P>
<P>
   ``Center Stage''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ethan Stiefel, Amanda Schull and Zoe Saldana. Rated
PG-13 for language and sensuality. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   53 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A simplistic but sweet-natured film designed to
make young dance lovers swoon.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For recommended ballet videos:
www.balletdance.about.com/entertainment/balletdance/msubvid.htm
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
