A2353 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-HUMAN12-COX     05-11 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-HUMAN12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    This `Traffic' takes all the wrong turns
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A rave film from Wales _ now there's a phrase I never thought
I'd use _ this frenetic exercise in uselessness covers one lost
weekend in Cardiff, as some dead-end twentysomethings drink, drug,
club-hop, have sex, don't have sex and deliver some of the most
drearily self-conscious dialogue this side of a ``Real World''
reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Our main narrator is Jip (John Simm), a clothing store clerk,
who knows his Scorsese and knows his Ecstasy (as in the designer
drug) but isn't sure he'll ever find true love. Or even someone
who'll sleep with him. Conveniently, his best mate is Lulu
(Lorraine Pilkington), a comely, funny, available blonde with whom
he has a supposedly platonic relationship _ that is, they keep each
other company from club to club.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's Koop (Shaun Parkes), a connoisseur of vintage
vinyl. The only thing he loves more than his LPs is his girlfriend,
Nina (Nicola Reynolds), of whom he is inordinately _ and wrongly _
jealous. Finally, there's Moff (Danny Dyer), who's around mostly to
mouth off at his clueless conservative parents and spew a stoned
``Star Wars'' deconstruction that's pretty much a rip-off of a
similar incoherent movie-geek riff in Kevin Smith's ``Clerks.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Jip, director Justin Kerrigan knows his drugs and his movie
references _ from ``Taxi Driver'' to ``Trainspotting.'' What he
doesn't know is anything about characters or storytelling or any of
those niceties that would make this picture something more than a
pretentious generational whine.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens with footage of a real rave, and you can feel the
brutal energy bursting off the screen. So a rave movie from Wales
may not be such a bad idea after all. But once Jip and crew move
front and center _ and stoned _ ``Human Traffic'' becomes as
frustrating as being stuck in traffic. The motorized kind. And, as
all of us who live in Atlanta know, you don't need to go to a movie
for that.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : Film trailer, other articles:
www.mymovies.net/moviest/metrodome/humantraffic/link.htm
</P>
<P>
   www.villagevoice.com/issues/0018
</P>
<P>
   /taubin.shtml
</P>
<P>
   ``Human Traffic''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Simm. Rated R for sex, profanity, nudity and lots
of drugs and alcohol. 1 hour, 24 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: You've seen ``Monkees'' reruns edgier than this.
It's movie garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
