<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS12-     05-11 2047
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mini reviews of current movies
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie, Steve Murray and Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Grades range from A to F.
</P>
<P>
   ``28 Days'' PG-13 (profanity, substance
</P>
<P>
   abuse and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sandra Bullock
</P>
<P>
   and Viggo Mortensen.
</P>
<P>
   The cinema's chipper girl next door (Sandra Bullock) goes clean
and sober in an addiction and rehab movie that, thankfully, isn't
an appalling clinical ``comedy'' like ``Patch Adams.'' It's a
professional, appealing comedy-drama, but in trying to be all
things to all viewers (to beer-loving Bullock fans as well as
devoted 12-steppers), it never really comes into focus. (SM)1 hour,
43 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Across the Sea of Time'' G
</P>
<P>
   3-D Imax film
</P>
<P>
   about New York City.
</P>
<P>
   History comes alive visually in this 3-D Imax movie focusing on
New York City. It's full of big, gloriously detailed ``stereoview''
photographs depicting immigrant life at the turn of the century.
(Bob Longino)51 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Center Stage'' PG-13 (sexuality and language)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ethan Stiefel,
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Schull and Zoe Saldana.
</P>
<P>
   An old-fashioned show biz fantasy for teenagers with leotards
and plies, ``Center Stage'' is a kind of movie that gets retooled
every 10 years or so. Its antecedents include ``Fame,'' ``Dirty
Dancing,'' ``The Turning Point'' and even ``Flashdance.'' It's the
female version of a sports movie: Sweat and inspiration lead to
love and brief heartache, but ultimately growth, self-worth and
even stardom result. (SM)1 hour, 53 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``East Is East'' R (profanity
</P>
<P>
   and domestic violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Om Puri
</P>
<P>
   and Linda Bassett.
</P>
<P>
   Set in working-class Britain in 1971, this uneven but energetic
film focuses on a boisterous Anglo-Pakistani family. The father is
a tyrannical type, while the mother is a grounded fish-and-chips
Englishwoman. And the kids are totally caught up in the exploding
England Swings pop-culture surrounding them. The very good cast,
headed by Om Puri and Linda Bassett, is a huge asset. (ERG) 1 hour,
36 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Erin Brockovich'' R (profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Julia Roberts
</P>
<P>
   and Albert Finney.
</P>
<P>
   Julia Roberts delivers in a funny, down-to-earth film about an
everyday mom with business spunk who, without a law degree but with
a lot of pluck, helps crash a big-time company responsible for
devastating health problems in a small, dirt-poor town. Call it
``Working-Class Girl.'' (Bob Longino) 2 hours, 11 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Frequency'' PG-13 (violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Dennis Quaid
</P>
<P>
   and Jim Caviezel.
</P>
<P>
   John Sullivan (Jim Caviezel) hears dead people. Specifically, he
hooks up to his dad's old ham radio set in 1999 and finds himself
talking to his dad (Dennis Quaid) in 1969. More crucially, John
knows his dad, a fireman, will be killed in a failed heroic rescue
the next day. Although over-plotted, the sentimental film has that
``what if?'' fascination. It's also a mind-bender and especially
savvy about emotional button-pushing. (ERG) 2 hours. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Gladiator'' R (extreme violence,
</P>
<P>
   perverse sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Russell Crowe.
</P>
<P>
   Two thousand _ or, if you want to add computer effects, 200,000
_ thumbs up for Ridley Scott's spectacle starring Russell Crowe as
a Roman general, who returns to the Colosseum to take revenge on
the odious Emperor Commodus (Joaquin Phoenix). The battles staged
before the mob of mindless ancient Romans are the film's
centerpieces, but its brave heart (so to speak) is Crowe. (ERG) 2
hours, 33 minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``High Fidelity'' R (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Cusack,
</P>
<P>
   Iben Hjejle and Jack Black.
</P>
<P>
   Freshly dumped by his longtime girlfriend, record-store owner
Rob (John Cusack) rhetorically asks himself, ``What came first _
music or the misery?'' In other words, does he listen to songs
about heartbreak because he's miserable, or is he miserable because
he's listening to these songs? ``High Fidelity'' is as smart as it
is enjoyable. It's a great date movie about dating. (SM)1 hour, 54
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Human Traffic'' R (sex, profanity, nudity
</P>
<P>
   and strong drug content)
</P>
<P>
   Starring John Simm.
</P>
<P>
   Movie garbage. In this rave flick from Wales, five
twenty-somethings spend their usual lost weekend drinking, doing
drugs, club-hopping, having sex, not having sex and delivering some
of the most drearily self-conscious dialogue this side of a ``Real
World'' reunion. You've seen ``Monkees'' reruns edgier than this.
(ERG)1 hour, 24 minutes. D-
</P>
<P>
   ``I Dreamed of Africa'' PG-13 (nudity, sensuality
</P>
<P>
   and some violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kim Basinger
</P>
<P>
   and Vincent Perez.
</P>
<P>
   Cardboard figures have adventures in Africa. Oscar winner Kim
Basinger stars as real-life woman Kuki Gallmann, who up and moves
her family from Italy to the Dark Continent because, as she tells
her son, ``I've stopped growing.'' Directed by one-hit wonder Hugh
Hudson (``Chariots of Fire''), the movie never slows down long
enough to get inside the heads of its characters. (SM) 1 hour, 54
minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``Keeping the Faith'' PG-13 (profanity, sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ben Stiller,
</P>
<P>
   Edward Norton and Jenna Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, it's a sweet-natured hymn to love and longtime
friendship. Edward Norton (as a priest) and Ben Stiller (as a
rabbi) are pals whose childhood friend (Jenna Elfman) returns to
catch both their eyes in more than a friendly way. The first 90
minutes have charm, a sophisticated sexiness and some nice, offbeat
bits. Then things start to crash. (SM)
</P>
<P>
   2 hours, 9 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Love and Basketball'' PG-13 (profanity and sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Omar Epps
</P>
<P>
   and Sanaa Lathan.
</P>
<P>
   All's not fair in love or basketball is one of several themes in
this flawed but appealing romance. Q (Omar Epps) and Monica (Sanaa
Lathan) meet as kids and rival basketball players. They realize
throughout the film that they love each other as much as the game.
Director Gina Price-Bythewood (her producer is Spike Lee) may not
have scored a slam dunk, but she comes close thanks to her engaging
stars. (ERG)1 hour, 58 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jordan to the Max'' Unrated
</P>
<P>
   Imax documentary
</P>
<P>
   about Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   It shoots, it scores. Like Mount Everest, Michael Jordan has his
own 2-D Imax film. It's the biggest format for the biggest sports
story ever told. Part bio, part well-deserved pat on the back, it's
a loving look at the Chicago Bulls superstar and hones in on the
1998 NBA playoffs when a determined Jordan led his team to a sixth
championship before retirement. (Bob Longino) 45 minutes. B
</P>
<P>
   ``My Dog Skip'' PG (violent content and mild profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Frankie Muniz,
</P>
<P>
   Diane Lane and Kevin Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the late Willie Morris' memoir about growing up in
small-town 1940s Mississippi, this family film is a remembrance of
how things can pass from our lives but never really leave us.
Nine-year-old Willie (``Malcolm in the Middle's'' Frankie Muniz) is
a shy only child whose life changes when his mom (Diane Lane) gives
him a Jack Russell terrier puppy, despite dad's (Kevin Bacon)
objection. (ERG)1 hour, 35 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Old Man and the Sea'' Unrated.
</P>
<P>
   A live-action animated short.
</P>
<P>
   Oscar: best animated short. This 'toon, based on Ernest
Hemingway's novel, is, like the author's word choice, deceptively
simple and strikingly beautiful. It's everything a moviegoer would
expect, but didn't get, from ``Fantasia/2000.'' (Bob Longino) 22
minutes. A-
</P>
<P>
   ``Return to Me'' PG (mild violence and sexual situations)
</P>
<P>
   Starring David Duchovny
</P>
<P>
   and Minnie Driver.
</P>
<P>
   In what may be Hollywood's first organ-transplant romance,
bereaved widower David Duchovny falls for shy heart-transplant
recipient Minnie Driver, unaware that his beloved first wife's
ticker is beating inside her chest. Duchovny is actually rather
wonderful here, with a sweet pensive romanticism. But Driver
herself just doesn't seem worthy of Duchovny. (ERG) 1 hour, 56
minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``The Road to El Dorado'' PG (mild thematic material
</P>
<P>
   and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Animated film featuring the voices
</P>
<P>
   of Kevin Kline and Kenneth Branagh.
</P>
<P>
   Not cute enough for kids, not clever enough for adults,
DreamWorks' latest animated feature is gorgeous but curiously dull.
Kenneth Branagh and Kevin Kline are the voices of a couple of
16th-century scam artists looking for the Lost City of Gold in the
New World. The movie fuses visual splendor with unsteady
storytelling and tone. The waterfalls are beautiful, but the movie
is a washout. (SM) 1 hour, 23 minutes. C
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of Engagement'' R (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tommy Lee Jones
</P>
<P>
   and Samuel L. Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rules of Engagement'' is another military flick that climaxes
in a courtroom, where soldiers shout out conflicting reports of
what really happened in the heat of battle. ``Rules'' is laughable,
but it's watchable thanks to the leads. Tommy Lee Jones is the
flick's anchor. And Samuel L. Jackson delivers an on-the-stand
blow-up like Jack Nicholson's ``You-can't-handle-the-truth''
bluster from ``A Few Good Men.'' (SM) 2 hours, 7 minutes. C-
</P>
<P>
   ``The Skulls'' PG-13 (violence and brief sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Joshua Jackson
</P>
<P>
   and Paul Walker.
</P>
<P>
   In this conspiracy thriller for the Clearasil set, the WB's
Joshua Jackson plays an average Joe sucked into an elite, monied
club. It comes with a price, though. Like he can't ever get out.
(SM) 1 hour, 47 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``Time Code'' R (drug use, sexuality, l
</P>
<P>
   anguage and some violence)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stellan Skarsgard,
</P>
<P>
   Salma Hayek and Jeanne Tripplehorn.
</P>
<P>
   The medium is the message in Mike Figgis' sometimes terrific,
sometimes tedious experiment in digital filmmaking. Here's the
gimmick: the screen is divided into four parts showing simultaneous
action in real time involving a large cast of characters. The
film's technique and technology are fresh. The story isn't. The
plot devices are moldy: A jealous lover. An estranged wife. A lying
sexpot. A loaded gun. (SM)1 hour, 37 minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``U-571'' PG-13 (violence and profanity)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Matthew McConaughey,
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Keitel, Bill Paxton
</P>
<P>
   and Jon Bon Jovi.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew McConaughey leads a reconnaissance mission to take over
a damaged German sub and capture the secret Nazi coding device
that's confounding U.S. efforts to win the war. Despite a
predictable script, blatant cliches and a penchant for
chest-beating fanfare music, ``U-571'' has plenty of furious
action, occasional suspense and lots of super-loud booms. It's no
``Das Boot,'' but it can suck you in. (Bob Longino) 1 hour, 56
minutes. B-
</P>
<P>
   ``Up at the Villa'' PG-13 (language, violence
</P>
<P>
   and implied sexuality)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sean Penn
</P>
<P>
   and Kristin Scott Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Some aristo-Brits overstay their welcome in 1930s Italy. Among
them are a young but penniless widow (Kristin Scott Thomas), a
dashing ne'er-do-well (Sean Penn) with more than a dash of Bogey in
him and a gossipy princess (Anne Bancroft) in love with her own
poisonous bons mots. Despite having a familiar theme and
shallowness, the movie profits from the leads' chemistry and from
Penn's performance. (ERG) 1 hour, 55 minutes. C+
</P>
<P>
   ``The Virgin Suicides'' R (strong thematic
</P>
<P>
   elements involving teenagers)
</P>
<P>
   Starring Kirsten Dunst
</P>
<P>
   and Josh Hartnett.
</P>
<P>
   This shimmery, darkly comic adaptation of Jeffrey Eumenides
novel about five teen girls and the boys who obsess over them marks
the assured, often inspired feature debut from writer-director
Sofia Coppola. (Yes, that Sofia, who was unwisely cast by dad
Francis in his ``Godfather III.'') She takes a dreamy,
cinematically difficult book and creates a visually hypnotic movie.
(SM) 1 hour, 36 minutes. B+
</P>
<P>
   ``Where the Heart Is'' PG-13
</P>
<P>
   Starring Natalie Portman
</P>
<P>
   and Ashley Judd.
</P>
<P>
   A cornpone comedy-drama about a single mom, made with enough
polish to be a guilty pleasure. Natalie Portman plays the pregnant
teen who heads for California and winds up becoming the Wal-Mart
Mom in Oklahoma. She gets good support from Stockard Channing,
Ashley Judd and Sally Field. (SM) 2 hours. C+
</P>
