<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2356 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-MOVIES-TIMECODE12-COX     05-11 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TIMECODE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Experimental `Time Code' a wild ride that registers as addictive
cerebral thrill
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The medium is the message in Mike Figgis' ``Time Code,'' a
sometimes terrific, sometimes tedious experiment in digital
filmmaking. As a demonstration of new technology and actors'
chutzpah, it's remarkable. As entertainment, it's often flat and
hackneyed.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the gimmick: Intrigued by the possibilities of digital
cameras _ they're cheap and can shoot up to 93 minutes without a
break _ Figgis (``Leaving Las Vegas'') came up with a basic story
line. Then he hired and rehearsed more than 20 actors to play
interconnected characters in the plot, largely improvising their
roles over a 90-minute framework. Finally, he loosed four cameramen
(including himself) to shoot their performances in simultaneous,
synchronized takes.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, what you get in ``Time Code'' is a single story
told in four parts, shown simultaneously on a screen divided into
quadrants. If that sounds confusing, think of it this way: If one
character walking on a sidewalk suddenly ducks into an office
building, the camera may follow him inside. Or it may stay put,
letting the actor disappear from one screen and reappear on another
as he wanders into range of the next camera. (Most of the action
takes place within a few square blocks, letting characters interact
in amusing ways.) Meanwhile, the audio track constantly shifts from
one of the four frames to the next. Throughout the movie, Figgis
chooses which audio channel we listen to; at first you may be
frustrated by not being able to choose for yourself which
conversation to follow.
</P>
<P>
   The film's technique and technology are fresh. The story isn't.
Though it's set in the sharky contemporary world of Hollywood
filmmaking, the plot devices are moldy: A jealous lover. An
estranged wife. A lying sexpot. A loaded gun.
</P>
<P>
   The film's main setting is a film company's offices, where
executives _ played by Steven Weber, Xander Berkeley and Holly
Hunter among others _ anxiously await Alex (Stellan Skarsgard),
their founding producer. Separated from his wife (Saffron Burrows),
he's been drinking too much, and his colleagues worry if he's
prepared for that day's meeting with international star Ana (Mia
Maestro). Simultaneously, wealthy Lauren (Jeanne Tripplehorn) rides
in a limousine toward the production office, along with her lover
Rose (Salma Hayek), a would-be actress whom Lauren suspects is
having an affair. Other notable characters include another actress
(Leslie Mann), a masseuse (Julian Sands) who rubs down his clients
even as they conduct staff meetings, and Ana's rock star boyfriend
(Alessandro Nivola).
</P>
<P>
   When Ana pitches a movie idea to Alex, describing an experiment
exactly like the one we're watching, he replies, ``It's the most
pretentious crap I ever heard.'' This kind of self- referential
mockery is one of the movie's pluses, balancing out its unfocused
and melodramatic moments. There's also frisky chat about fake
Hollywood projects, including a movie from the ``South Park''
creators called ``Time Toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   At its best, ``Time Code'' is like a dance or musical
composition _ for example, when all four screens zoom in on a
closeup of separate actors, or the moment when two actresses, in
different zones and for different reasons, start crying. Wherever
they happen to be, the actors have to pretend to be knocked around
by three fake earthquake tremors, in synch. It's Figgis' way of
showing off, reminding us that their improvisations are harnessed
to a rigidly timed framework. Also testing the limits of nonstop
filming, two of the actors have to simulate a full-bore (if fully
clothed) sex act, without the usual safety net of cuts or the
editing room. And several times, two cameramen converge on the same
room or street corner to cover the same scene, heightening the
suspense: Will they accidentally film each other?
</P>
<P>
   Moments like these are enthralling for any film buff. But your
strongest response to ``Time Code'' will probably be cerebral, not
emotional. As usual, Figgis resorts to some overemphatic music
choices for the soundtrack, including his own jazz compositions.
Cast standouts include Skarsgard as a sympathetic emotional wreck,
and Tripplehorn, who is stuck for most of the running time with a
camera inches from her face, recording every tiny reaction as she
eavesdrops on other characters. Even though it's dramatically
undernourished, you'll know ``Time Code'' has cast a spell on you
when you don't want to leave your seat before the very last of the
four frames has faded from the screen, for fear of missing
something.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B :
</P>
<P>
   For background, movie stills and actor info:
www.movieweb.com/movie/timecode/``Time Code''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Stellan Skarsgard, Salma Hayek, Jeanne Tripplehorn and
Saffron Burrows. Rated R for drug use, sexuality, language and
violence. At Tara. 1 hour, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An ambitious experiment in synchronous digital
filmmaking, but more likely to appeal to your head than your gut.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
