<HEADER>
A2357 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-SUMMER-MOVIES14-COX     05-11 2834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUMMER-MOVIES14-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A multiplex of happenings
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   From this Friday's ``Dinosaur'' to August's filmed-in-Savannah
``The Legend of Bagger Vance,'' it's going to be a long, hot,
crowded summer at the multiplex. Here's a selected listing of
coming movies (as always, dates are subject to change):
</P>
<P>
   MAY
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinosaur'' _ Disney's done everything traditional about this
movie _ the story, the catch phrase jokes, the mostly sugarcoated
fantasy _ except the visuals.
</P>
<P>
   It's a $200 million eye-popping 71 minutes of computer animation
and live action often mesmerizing in its detail. We dare you not to
get sucked in as a meteor shower pummels the earth, sending shock
waves, earthly debris, fire and brimstone across the screen.
</P>
<P>
   The dinos are often remarkable _ until some of them open their
mouths and speak like they're in ``Dumbo'' (the voices include D.B.
Sweeney, Alfre Woodard, Julianna Margulies, Joan Plowright and
Della Reese). It's a weird, jolting mix of prehistoric chaos and
modern schmaltz. (Friday)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mission: Impossible 2'' _ Chinese director John Woo has pumped
American movies before. Remember ``Face/Off''? Now Woo's got his
trigger finger on the sequel to Tom Cruise's 1996 version of TV's
popular spy series. The film's trailer hints at a wild motorcycle
chase, high-climbing cliff antics, a way, way up stealth drop and
some fancy footwork by Cruise to kick a nemesis in the kisser. Oh,
yeah. And there's a plot. Maybe something about a deadly virus.
(May 24)
</P>
<P>
   Also in May
</P>
<P>
   ``East-West'' _ Catherine Deneuve heads Regis Wargnier's (whose
``Indochine'' won the 1992 best foreign language film Oscar) film
about Russian emigrants who returned from France to the motherland
under Josef Stalin only to discover deception and loss of freedom.
(Friday)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Big Kahuna'' _ Fresh off his best actor Oscar for
``American Beauty,'' Kevin Spacey blazes onscreen in this
independent film about salesmen and salesmanship. The script is no
``Glengarry Glen Ross,'' but Spacey and co-stars Danny DeVito and
Peter Facinelli deliver credible performances. (Friday)
</P>
<P>
   ``Small Time Crooks'' _ Some say Woody Allen's latest comedy is
a kind of throwback to his earliest films such as ``Take the Money
and Run.'' We wouldn't go that far. But it does contain a sizable
helping of weightless hilarity while poking fun at America's need
for greed. The physical comedy scores as well as the one-liners as
Allen, as an ex-con dishwasher, and Tracey Ullman, as his
manicurist wife, plot a New York bank robbery. The robbery never
works, but they do stumble their way into a whole lot of cash.
(Friday)
</P>
<P>
   ``Road Trip'' _ Was college really like this? Yeah, in many ways
it probably was. A quartet of guys heads out to try and retrieve a
sex video one of them has accidentally sent to his girlfriend. The
film, produced by Ivan Reitman (``Animal House,'' ``Ghostbusters'')
and filmed in Georgia last year, is full of sex jokes, gross-outs
(including one that should make you queasier than ``American
Pie''), insults and stereotypes. Tom Green's the name star, but he
appears mostly at the beginning and end. (Friday)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bossa Nova'' _ It's a romantic comedy with Amy Irving
involving several couples in Rio de Janeiro juiced with the beat of
Antonio Carlos ``Tom'' Jobim's music. (May 26)
</P>
<P>
   ``Shanghai Noon'' _ Jackie Chan's latest martial arts chop sends
him to the Old West, where he tries to rescue a kidnapped Chinese
princess (Lucy Liu). (May 26)
</P>
<P>
   ``Passion of Mind'' _ Demi Moore looks forlorn as a woman with
two lives _ as a mother in France and a slut in New York. One is
only a dream, but she doesn't know which. (May 26)
</P>
<P>
   JUNE
</P>
<P>
   ``The Perfect Storm'' _ A fish story with bite. Based on
Sebastian Junger's gripping book, George Clooney, Mark Wahlberg,
Diane Lane and John C. Reilly man the fishing ships as nature
convenes three storm systems, creating the most wretched storm in
modern history. A perfect sign that the action should be good: The
director is Wolfgang Petersen, who helmed ``Das Boot'' to six Oscar
nominations. The ships-at-sea scenes were shot in a huge indoor set
with ship models, a massive water tank and large blue screen. One
new gimmick involves suspended platforms so that cameras could be
moved more fluidly through a swaying
</P>
<P>
   ship. (June 30)
</P>
<P>
   Also in June
</P>
<P>
   ``Running Free'' _ A horse tale. Young Chase Moore plays a
stable boy in Namibia who befriends a colt dubbed Lucky. (June 2)
</P>
<P>
   ``Hamlet'' _ Ethan Hawke, Julia Stiles, Bill Murray and Sam
Shepard take the Bard to modern-day New York for murder, a hostile
corporate takeover and emotional lamenting. Michael Almereyda
adapted the screenplay and directed. (June 2)
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Momma's House'' _ Martin Lawrence plays an FBI guy who has
to impersonate a large granny to remain undercover in Georgia to
help protect a single mom and her son from an escaped con. It's
``Witness'' meets ``Mrs. Doubtfire.'' (June 2)
</P>
<P>
   ``Gone in 60 Seconds'' _ It's the hearing that goes first. You
may not have any after producer Jerry Bruckheimer (``Top Gun,''
``The Rock,'' ``Armageddon'') turns up the volume in this loud
homage to car thievery. Nicolas Cage is the cagey wheeler-dealer,
but he's only doing it to save his brother. The cast also includes
Oscar winner Angelina Jolie, Giovanni Ribisi, Delroy Lindo, Will
Patton and Robert Duvall. (June 9)
</P>
<P>
   ``Titan A.E.'' _ The A.E. stands for ``After Earth.'' And it's
the animated story of a teen out to save what's left of the human
race by finding a legendary spacecraft. Stars' voices include Matt
Damon, Bill Pullman, Drew Barrymore and Nathan Lane. It's ``2001:
</P>
<P>
   A Space Odyssey'' meets ``The
</P>
<P>
   Lion King.'' (June 16)
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaft'' _ This time Samuel L. Jackson is the coolly bad (shut
your mouth). He plays the nephew of John Shaft (Richard Roundtree
in a cameo) who's out to protect a murder witness (Oscar nominee
Toni Collette). Director John Singleton says he's ditched the
bell-bottoms of the 1971 original, but Isaac Hayes' Oscar-winning
theme song is reportedly intact. Co-stars include Christian Bale,
Jennifer Esposito, Dan Hedaya, Busta Rhymes and Vanessa L.
Williams. (June 16)
</P>
<P>
   ``Fantasia/2000'' _ It's already played on Imax's big, big
screen, but now Disney's heavily computer-animated version of the
original 'toons to classical tunes heads into regular-size
theaters. (June 16)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Butterfly'' _ Fernando Fernan Gomez (``The Grandfather'')
stars in this Spanish tale of a teacher who instructs a shy young
boy about the ways of the world as civil war erupts. (June 16)
</P>
<P>
   ``Boys and Girls'' _ So where did ``The Blair Witch Project's''
Heather go? She got sucked into a twentysomething relationship
film. Heather Donahue is among the supporting cast as Freddie
Prinze Jr. and Claire Forlani play childhood opposites who wind up
dangerously close in college. Also lending support: Atlanta-based
singer Monica. (June 16)
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, Myself &AMP; Irene'' _ Oscar doesn't like him. But the
Farrelly brothers are giving Jim Carrey a try. Here he plays a
Rhode Island cop with a split personality. And both fall for Renee
Zellwegger. Apparently, it takes two to complete her. (June 23)
</P>
<P>
   ``Chicken Run'' _ Sort of a ``Babe'' in the henhouse, it's ``The
Great Escape'' all over again with clay animation and fowl voices
provided by Mel Gibson, Julia Sawalha, Miranda Richardson and Jane
Horrocks. (June 23)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Patriot'' _ Partially filmed in South Carolina, Mel Gibson
goes revolutionary as a reluctant hero in early America's break
with the Brits. It sounds a lot like James Stewart's
``Shenandoah,'' though that was a different war and century.
Directed by Roland Emmerich (``Independence Day,'' ``Godzilla'').
(June 30)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Adventures of Rocky and Bullwinkle'' _ Watch them try to
pull a movie out of their hat. The 'toon villains _ Boris Badenov
(Jason Alexander), Natasha (Rene Russo) and Fearless Leader (Robert
De Niro) _ jump into the real world while heroes Rocky and
Bullwinkle are strictly animated. Think ``Who Framed Roger
Rabbit.'' Among the cameos: Billy Crystal and John Goodman. (June
30)
</P>
<P>
   ``Groove'' _ Basically, it's ``Go'' without the energy and humor
and with endless rave music. During one long night, ravers take
drugs, dance, kiss the wrong people, hug, talk, party and prove
that relationships haven't changed in hundreds of years. But the
music sure has. (June 30)
</P>
<P>
   ``Kikujiro'' _ Writer/director Takeshi Kitano is known for
police-gang wars, blazing guns and pools of blood. Not this time.
It's a comedy. And we'll tell you this: The characters include Fat
Biker and Bald Biker. (June 30)
</P>
<P>
   JULY
</P>
<P>
   ``What Lies Beneath'' _ It's got name talent all the way around.
Harrison Ford and Michelle Pfeiffer star. Robert Zemeckis directs.
It's a $65 million supernatural thriller shot in Vermont from a
story by Steven Spielberg. Can you see dead people? It appears
Pfeiffer's character might. (July 21)
</P>
<P>
   ``Loser'' _ ``American Beauty's'' Mena Suvari portrays a
downtrodden New York University student who falls for a nerdy guy
(Jason Biggs of ``American Pie''). The writer/director is Amy
Heckerling (``Clueless,'' ``Fast Times at Ridgemont High''). (July
21)
</P>
<P>
   Also in July
</P>
<P>
   ``Scary Movie'' _ Keenen Ivory Wayans does his comedy thing on
the ``Scream'' series. Among the stars: Carmen Electra and, of
course, Marlon and Shawn Wayans. (July 7)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Kid'' _ Hey, it's Bruce Willis and a little boy. But this
one is different. Willis plays an image consultant who comes face
to face with himself as an 8-year-old kid. (July 7)
</P>
<P>
   ``Jesus' Son'' _ Billy Crudup plays a drugged-up wanderer who
gets into weird situations. (July 7)
</P>
<P>
   ``X-Men'' _ The comic book phenom heads for the big screen with
a weird cast. Ian McKellen, Halle Berry (in blond wig), Anna
Paquin, Bruce Davison and Patrick Stewart. The reason to see it:
Ray Park (aka Darth Maul and ``Sleepy Hollow's'' headless
horseman). (July 14)
</P>
<P>
   ``Pokemon 2'' _ Don't say we didn't warn you. Last year's
mind-blowingly bad animated cash cow is back promising to introduce
six new characters. Can in-store toys be far behind? Betcha your
kid won't want to buy just one. (July 21)
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad About Mambo'' _ ``Felicity's'' Keri Russell plays a
Belfast girl who sort of flashdances the samba, rumba and, yes, the
mambo. (July 21)
</P>
<P>
   ``Thomas and the Magic Railroad'' _ Part live action, part
animation, it's the big screen version of the TV series ``Thomas
the Tank Engine and Friends.'' The movie involves a little girl on
her way to see her grandpa when she gets on the wrong train, meets
a magical conductor and winds up in a toy world. And we're serious
when we say it features Peter Fonda and Alec Baldwin. (July 26)
</P>
<P>
   ``Wonderland'' _ A drama of a family's three generations
spending time in London over a weekend. (July 28)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Broken Hearts League'' _ It's a friends film where all the
guy pals are gay. The cast includes Zack Braff, Dean Cain, Andrew
Keegan, Nia Long, Mary McCormack and Timothy Olyphant. It's written
and directed by Greg Berlanti. (July)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Wisdom of Crocodiles'' _ This one's been on the shelf for
a while, and now that Jude Law got a supporting Oscar nomination
for ``The Talented Mr. Ripley,'' maybe you'll get to see it. Law
plays a serial killer who ices the femmes who love him. (July)
</P>
<P>
   ``Blood Simple'' _ Those ``Fargo'' guys _ Joel and Ethan Coen _
got their start in 1985 with this offbeat tale of jealousy, a cheap
saloon and planned murder. Frances McDormand, M. Emmet Walsh and
Dan Hedaya star. For the film's 15th anniversary, it's been
restored and re-edited. (July)
</P>
<P>
   ``Things You Can Tell Just by Looking at Her'' _ Glenn Close,
Calista Flockhart, Cameron Diaz and Holly Hunter lead a group of
actresses playing Californians in interconnected tales of romantic
yearnings, disease, lost dreams and newfound loves. (July)
</P>
<P>
   AUGUST
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nutty Professor II: The Klumps'' _ It'll be all Eddie
Murphy all the time as he reprises his dual role as an overweight
professor who after taking a magic potion turns into Buddy Love.
Again, Murphy will layer on the prosthetics to play the outlandish
Klump clan: mama, papa, brother Ernie and granny. (Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Legend of Bagger Vance'' _ Filmed in Savannah and
Charleston, S.C., last year for $70 million, it's Robert Redford's
homage to golf with Matt Damon, Will Smith and Charlize Theron in a
tale about a mysterious caddie with a perfect swing. Locations
include the Jekyll Island Club, Colleton River Plantation and
Kiawah Island's Ocean Course. (Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla 2000'' _ Maybe he's finally back where he belongs.
The 180-foot-high creature returns to the Land of the Rising Sun in
this Japanese-made action/adventure. It's Godzilla vs. an alien
monster. The director is Takao Okawara. (Aug. 11)
</P>
<P>
   Also in August
</P>
<P>
   ``Coyote Ugly'' _ Now Bruckheimer's turning up the steam. This
is the producer's film about young, scantily clad women living life
to the fullest as barmaids at the crazy Coyote Ugly, New York's
hottest nightspot. (Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hollow Man'' _ Kevin Bacon becomes an invisible fellow in
this thriller about secret formulas and danger. Co-starring as
scientists are Elisabeth Shue and Josh Brolin. Watch out, the
director is Paul Verhoeven (``Robocop,'' ``Basic Instinct,''
``Showgirls''). (Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   ``Space Cowboys'' _ Here's proof that baby boomers are older
than they think they are. Astronauts from the '60s are summoned by
NASA to save the planet from a satellite crisis _ if they can pass
rigorous physical tests. Among the geezer stars: Clint Eastwood,
Tommy Lee Jones, James Garner, Donald Sutherland and William
Devane. (Aug. 4)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bait'' _ Jamie Foxx stars in this prison comedy about a
released con who could lead authorities to a major criminal and the
whereabouts of gold from a heist. (Aug. 8)
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer Catch'' _ Freddie Prinze Jr. is the poor boy who falls
for a rich girl. (Aug. 11)
</P>
<P>
   ``Imposter'' _ A futuristic thriller with Gary Sinise as a
well-respected scientist who wakes up one day to discover he's the
world's most-wanted bad guy. (Aug. 11)
</P>
<P>
   ``Shower'' _ It's a Chinese film about traditions being overrun
by modern culture. It stars Zhu Xu (``King of Masks'') and is from
co-writer/director Zhang Yang, a pioneer in the nation's
underground music video scene. (Aug. 11)
</P>
<P>
   ``Cecil B. DeMented'' _ What you need to know is that it's
written and directed by John Waters, and it's a kind of
``Bowfinger'' on hallucinogens. Stephen Dorff leads a team of
cinema terrorists who kidnap a Hollywood star (Melanie Griffith)
and force her to film an underground renegade movie. Naturally,
Patricia Hearst co-stars. (Aug. 11)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bedazzled'' _ Elizabeth Hurley plays the devil (we believe she
can do it) who turns a nerdy, low-level techie (Brendan Fraser)
into a rich, powerful and sexy guy. Co-written and directed by
Harold Ramis. (Aug. 11)
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Carter'' _ Sylvester Stallone just won't give up. Here he
is again in an action/adventure based on the '70s British film
about a brother's strange murder. Co-starring are Miranda
Richardson, Rachel Leigh Cook and Michael Caine (who was in the
original). Didn't Billy Crystal tell us Caine will appear in
anything? (Aug. 13)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring It On'' _ That ``Virgin Suicides'' vixen Kirsten Dunst
as the captain of a cheerleading squad trying to repeat as national
champions. Uh, it's a comedy. (Aug. 18)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Way of the Gun'' _ It's about cold-blooded criminals
suddenly wrestling with their consciences. Ryan Phillipe and
Benicio Del Toro play the baddies who kidnap a pregnant Juliette
Lewis. It's all firearms and sentimental impulses from there. (Aug.
25)
</P>
<P>
   ``Blow Dry'' _ The screenwriter for ``The Full Monty'' takes on
a full head of hair. In this comedy, a sleepy (even boring)
working-class town finds itself host of the prestigious National
Hair Championships and all the glam hams that come with it. The
cast includes Alan Rickman, Natasha Richardson and Rachel
Griffiths. (Aug. 25)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Crew'' _ Just what you want to see. A band of geezers
fighting to save their ratty senior citizen residence hotel from an
invasion of yuppies. The cast includes Richard Dreyfuss, Burt
Reynolds, Dan Hedaya and Seymour Cassel. (Aug. 25)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Replacements'' _ Not to be confused with Oliver Stone's
``Any Given Sunday,'' Keanu Reeves plays a scab quarterback in this
pigskin tale. The movie co-stars Gene Hackman. (Aug. 25)
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Rangers'' _ TV stars (Dylan McDermott and James Van Der
Beek) and singers (Usher Raymond and Randy Travis) saddle up in
1875 Texas to take on a band of renegades. (Aug. 25)
</P>
<P>
   ``Whipped'' _ Amanda Peet stars in this comedy about New York
dating. (August)
</P>
<P>
   Bob Longino writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
