<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0267 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2358 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-GORE-LIKEABLE12-COX     05-11 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-LIKEABLE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    VOTERS NOT WARMING UP TO GORE, POLLS FIND
 &HT;    630&AMP;add. With GORE-DATA. Moving in (w) Washington and (p)
politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite the advantages of peace, prosperity and
incumbency, Al Gore trails George W. Bush in most public opinion
polls, partly because a sizeable number of Americans don't seem to
like the vice president as a person.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly rubs some people the wrong way,'' said Ed Goeas, a
Republican pollster and co-publisher of the Voter.com-Battleground
2000 Poll, which was released Thursday and showed Gore trailing
Bush by 6 percentage points in a national survey of 1,000 likely
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters rarely measure the degree to which presidential
campaigns are a personality contest. But such contests ``always
involve personality,'' said former GOP strategist Jack Pitney, now
a political science professor at Claremont McKenna College in
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Cold War, the voters applied an exacting
personality test: Can we trust this person with the Bomb?'' said
Pitney. ``Now the test is different: Can we stand this person on TV
every day for the next four years? In other words, do we reach for
the clicker when his face pops on the screen? So far, Gore is
flunking the clicker test.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gallup poll released this week showed that 44 percent of
respondents viewed Gore unfavorably, the highest reading since he
became a candidate for president. Bush's unfavorable rating was 32
percent, about where it has been since his rocky primary showings
in February.
</P>
<P>
   In Gallup's polling since February 1999, Gore's unfavorable
ratings have been consistently near 40 percent, a level once
regarded as death to a campaign. His unfavorable ratings
consistently exceed the job disapproval ratings of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The peak in Gore's unfavorable ratings come at the same time
Bush is widening his advantage in national preference surveys.
</P>
<P>
   A Los Angeles Times poll this week showing the Texas governor
leading Gore 51 percent to 43 percent among registered voters
nationwide. In the Battleground 2000 poll, Bush leads Gore 48
percent to 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   These findings came even though the vice president is promoting
the best national economy since World War II, has 23 years of
political experience and is waging a relentless assault on Bush
proposals, repeatedly describing them as ``risky' or ``reckless''
or ``arrogant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Any poll is just a snapshot, and none of them mean very much
with the election still six months away,'' Doug Hattaway, Gore's
campaign spokesman in Nashville, said in response to the Gallup
poll.
</P>
<P>
   Another source of comfort for the Gore campaign is that most of
the people who dislike Gore are the same people who disapprove of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's highest unfavorable rating, 49 percent, in the
Battleground 2000 poll comes from white Southerners, a core
Republican constituency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the kind of thing that can cause panic in a campaign, but
it shouldn't,'' said Craig Smith, who was Gore's campaign manager
before the shake-up that moved the campaign to Nashville last year.
``We're at a stage now where voters aren't paying much attention.
But when they were, back during the early primaries, Gore and Bush
were tied in the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in the Gallup poll in February, the favorable and
unfavorable ratings of Gore and Bush were virtually the same.
</P>
<P>
   But among undecided voters, Gore is viewed more favorably than
Bush, according to the Battleground 2000 poll _ ``a very big
surprise and a very important factor for Democratic fortunes,''
said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake, who conducts the
Battleground 2000 poll with Goeas.
</P>
<P>
   That poll shows 44 percent of those voters have a favorable
opinion of the vice president, while 34 percent are unfavorable.
Bush was viewed favorably by 36 percent, while 39 percent had an
unfavorable opinion.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   It is clear, however, from a variety of polls that Gore is not
making what Pew Research Center Director Andrew Kohut describes as
``a chemical connection'' with voters.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Kohut allows poll respondents to give their own
one-word description of candidates. Last September and again in
March, the most frequent word to describe Gore was ``boring.''
Bush, on the other hand, was most often described as ``good'' or
``okay.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in Pew's March poll, the quality voters least liked
about Gore was his personality.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has a reputation as a natural back-slapping
politician, his personality also was the quality voters least liked
about him in the Pew polls. And that dislike has grown: last
October, 19 percent listed his personality as his least likeable
characteristic, but in March poll, 33 percent did.
</P>
<P>
   In the Los Angeles Times poll, Gore's personality was the third
most important characteristic cited by his supporters. Most cited
was experience, 28 percent, and political philosophy, 16 percent,
with 15 percent citing personality. Bush's personality placed third
among his supporters, too. It was cited by 16 percent, trailing
trustworthiness, 29 percent, and political philosophy, 21 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On the Web: www.voter.com, www.gallup.com
</P>
<P>
   Scott Shepard's e-mail address is scotts(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
