<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2365 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t BC-NEWORLEANS-2ndTake-TE     05-11 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWORLEANS-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
NEW ORLEANS: to break in. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And yes, some of the development worries New Orleans purists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of people here periodically wonder if New
Orleans is in danger of becoming kind of a clone of Houston, but I
rather doubt that will happen for a couple of reasons, the main one
being that the extent of well-preserved 19th-century and older
architecture really mitigates against the endless horizontal sprawl
of other big cities, '' says New Orleans writer Jason Berry, who
with photographer Philip Gould has written ``Louisiana Faces:
Images From a Renaissance.'' The book, celebrating the state's
music, art and culture, will be published by LSU Press this fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is culturally one of the richest cities in the world ...
and I think on the whole, New Orleans is a place that has a grasp
on its past. It really markets its history commercially.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Stroll along the French Quarter streets, and you can overhear
snippets of the guides' spiels as they lead groups on walking tours
or drive by in horse-drawn carriages, weaving a seamless blend of
history and modern-day lore, the factual and the mythic.
</P>
<P>
   ``On your left, the restaurant of the famous Cajun chef, Paul
Prudhomme ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Later on, we'll tell you where you can see one of the homes of
Anne Rice, whose vampire books were set in New Orleans ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are coming up on Jackson Square, where there is always a
party ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``Marie Laveau may have been known as a famous voodoo priestess,
but her real occupation was a hairdresser ...''
</P>
<P>
   New Orleans is like that _ history is embedded throughout its
core, the new unable to fully separate itself from the old. Even
the newest buildings and businesses pay homage to the city's past.
</P>
<P>
   At the International House, a stylish boutique hotel opened in
1998 on the edge of the French Quarter, the bellhops may wear
Italian-style suits, the rooms may be decorated in minimalist beige
and the in-house restaurant may be a sleek Asian operation called
Lemon Grass. But the hotel also has hung portraits of New Orleans
jazz greats, stocked its in-room CD players with albums by favorite
sons like Wynton Marsalis and Dr. John, and arranged for a local
voodoo priestess to conduct love-spell ceremonies for guests upon
request.
</P>
<P>
   The anticipated Ogden Museum of Southern Art and the National
D-Day Museum both chose to restore existing historic buildings in
the city's warehouse district. The Ritz Carlton Hotel is doing a
multimillion-dollar renovation on the site of the long-gone but
still beloved Maison-Blanche department store on Canal Street.
</P>
<P>
   Even Jazzland, the 140-acre theme park set to open May 20 on a
site 20 minutes from downtown, has taken its thematic cues from the
city. Sections of the park are called Mardi Gras, Cajun Country and
Pontchartrain Beach. There will be daily Mardi Gras parades and
live zydeco and jazz performances. At the dining pavilions, guests
will chow down on jambalaya, oyster po-boys and beignets.
</P>
<P>
   And new building aside, there are many pockets of New Orleans in
which it's impossible to tell if anything has changed for 10 years
_ or 100.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a reason you can come back to this city, and it never
seems to change,'' says my tour guide on the otherwise eminently
skippable New Orleans vampire tour, explaining the stringent zoning
and preservation laws in the Quarter that require buildings to be
maintained in a historically accurate fashion.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``If something was originally a yellow building
when it was built, it's always going to be yellow.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   So, even though I spend the weekend trying to hit as many new
spots as possible, I find myself feeling on familiar ground _
partly because the Quarter never changes that much, partly because
there are old favorites I just couldn't resist.
</P>
<P>
   I don't ride the streetcar to the Garden District, but I sit for
an hour in Jackson Square, listening to a skilled pickup band of
street musicians rip through ``Sweet Georgia Brown'' and a string
of Dixieland tunes, then eavesdropping on the psychics and palm
readers earnestly talking to shorts-wearing tourists.
</P>
<P>
   I don't visit the Audubon Park Zoo, but I spend a late morning
at the Aquarium of the Americas, as fascinated by old exhibits (the
penguins, the sharks) as the new attractions (tiny sea horses,
cheerful California sea otters.)
</P>
<P>
   I don't eat brunch at Commander's Palace or beignets at Cafe du
Monde (partly because the line even at 10 a.m. spilled dangerously
into Decatur Street), but I can't resist a quick dinner at Paul
Prudhomme's K-Paul's, where the fried oyster Caesar salad and the
praline creme brulee are worth sitting at the bar and being served
by a harried bartender.
</P>
<P>
   Then, during my last few hours in town, a stranger seems to read
my mind. After hours of shopping and walking, and searching
unsuccessfully for a casual restaurant open for lunch on Easter
Sunday, I lobby for a hot dog, telling my companion plaintively,
``You can't go home without eating a Lucky Dog.''
</P>
<P>
   I didn't think the vendor heard me, but he smiled when he handed
over my hot dog, dripping with chili, onions and mustard.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, you can't,'' he said, giving me a couple of extra napkins
for good measure. ``That's right. There's some things you just
gotta do in New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   (Patricia Rodriguez is travel editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call her at (817) 390-7571, or e-mail:
prodriguez(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
