<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SLAYING-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FATHER OF INTERNET SLAYING SUSPECT SAYS SON HAD `TERRIBLE RAGE' 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TIMBERON, N.M. _ The man accused of killing a Texas A&AMP;M
University student last month after &UR;  &LR; posing as a woman on the
Internet has ``a terrible rage problem,'' chronic medical ailments
and sexuality issues, his father said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lockwood said his 31-year-old son, Kenny Wayne Lockwood,
probably succumbed to anger when he fatally shot Kerry Jason
Kujawa, 20, of Richmond, Texas. The elder Lockwood believes the
shooting took place in the living room of the family home in San
Antonio, where the suspect lived with his mother.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-hour interview, Lockwood, 65, described his son as a
sickly boy with a violent temper, growing up in the shadow of two
``overachieving'' older brothers. Once, Kenny attempted suicide,
his father said. Although he has a nursing degree, his battles with
pancreatitis and related illnesses have prevented him from working
for the past five years.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he occupied himself on the Internet, sometimes
pretending to be a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here he was posing as a blond pre-law (female) student and
this guy, a student, showed up at the house and something
happened,'' the father said. ``Whatever happened _ whoever said
what to whom, or whatever _ who knows?
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's done is a horrible, horrible thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that on the day of the killing in early April, his
estranged wife, Dina, was out of town. Police believe Kujawa went
to the Lockwood home looking for the mysterious young woman he knew
as ``Kelly'' from Internet conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators theorize that Kujawa may have been killed because
he discovered Kenny Lockwood was posing as ``Kelly'' _ the name of
Kenny's only romantic interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny has a terrible rage problem,'' his father said. ``We've
seen it through the years.'' &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Lockwood said he and his son have an ``aloof'' relationship,
and that has been especially true of the last five years while the
father has been living alone in the Sacramento Mountains of
southern New Mexico. He said they haven't spoken for at least six
months. Lockwood returned to San Antonio for a couple of days last
week and said he wanted to visit his son in jail in San Marcos. But
he missed the jail's visiting day.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lockwood, an Army retiree and former commander of the
defunct Bexar County Volunteer Militia, an anti-government
survivalist group, spoke dispassionately about his son during an
interview Monday in his Spartan, one-room cabin. Lockwood said he's
inclined to believe his son committed the crime _ not because he
gave what police called a ``full confession,'' but because of
physical evidence and computer records linking him to the fatal
rendezvous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was right in the living room. They took out a hunk of
carpet as evidence,'' Lockwood said. He said that after the arrest,
his two older sons used family phone records to verify that their
younger brother had talked to the victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boys sat down with telephone records and a calendar and
put it together themselves. He left a trail a mile wide. If the
kids could get it, you know what Big Brother's got,'' the father
said.
</P>
<P>
   And with a tinge of disbelief and disappointment in his voice,
Lockwood noted, ``he dumped the body on a friend's ranch'' near
Dripping Springs, Texas. The longtime friend was a former neighbor
in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Because the body was found in Hays County, the murder charge was
filed there and the investigation is being led by Sheriff Don
Montague. His investigators have not disclosed where they believe
the slaying occurred and have divulged few other details.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest warrant issued for Lockwood said Kujawa, an
engineering student, left his dorm at A&AMP;M for San Antonio on April
7 to finally meet ``Kelly,'' the screen name for the person he had
met in an Aggie chat room on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Lockwood was seen in Kujawa's dorm room
operating his computer. Lockwood's image was captured by a security
camera at the College Station, Texas, airport, where Kujawa's
bloodstained car was parked.
</P>
<P>
   Between Kujawa's disappearance April 7 and the discovery of his
body on April 19, police said Kujawa's parents in Richmond received
reassuring messages saying he was still with ``Kelly.'' Meanwhile,
others who knew ``Kelly'' from the chat room said those messages
continued as late as April 21. The final messages claimed Kelly and
Kujawa were engaged and headed to Richmond on Easter weekend to
meet his family.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood said his son's use of that identity was intriguing
because that was the name of his only significant romantic
interest, when he was a student at John Marshall High School in San
Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   After his son's arrest, Lockwood said, investigators called him
to discuss the case and a gun possibly used in the slaying. Police
said they believed a .22-caliber handgun was used, but the father
said such a gun had been stolen. He believes a .22-caliber rifle, a
12th birthday present to his son, may have been involved.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood said his two older sons, one of whom is an A&AMP;M
graduate, told him that the intense Internet relationship with
Kujawa wasn't Kenny Lockwood's first such entanglement. They were
referring to the claim of another A&AMP;M student, Scott Schneider, who
said he met Lockwood at A&AMP;M six months earlier, when he posed as
``Isaac,'' the younger brother of Kelly. The ruse was unsuccessful,
however, because Schneider didn't believe the mature visitor was
the teen-age sibling who Kelly said would be coming in her stead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
