<HEADER>
A2368 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e BC-TREK-BEN-BROWDER-IN-F     05-11 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TREK-BEN-BROWDER-IN-FARSCAPE-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BEN BROWDER, THE BEST BY `FARSCAPE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 (Includes a color slide and a black-and-white photo of Ben Browder
in a scene from ``Farscape.'') 
 By IAN SPELLING  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.)  
 &HT;    Ben Browder may as well be in a black hole.
 &HT;    The actor stars as Captain John Crichton on the Sci-Fi Channel's
inventive, visually stunning and increasingly popular series
``Farscape.'' But the show films in Australia, far, far away from
its devoted fan base, the newspaper and magazine raves, and the
cable network's steadily increasing advertising revenues.
 &HT;    ``The show hasn't even premiered here in Australia,'' Browder
says by cellular telephone while in a car on his way to the
``Farscape'' set. ``So my contact with reaction to it is via the
Internet. The response there is astounding.
 &HT;    ``It's just gratifying and a little overwhelming to know that
people have taken to the show the way they have,'' he says. ``Am I
surprised by it? Yeah, part of me is very surprised, but you go
into anything hoping people will like what you do.
 &HT;    ``I'm pleased that people see as much in `Farscape' as we try to
put into it.''
 &HT;    Actually, Browder says, being so far from the hype benefits the
show. It keeps the cast and crew focused on the task at hand, and
also provides a sense of freedom.
 &HT;    ``We're just doing the show, trying to tell good stories, and we
haven't had to deal with a lot of the extraneous stuff that can
possibly come into play,'' the Memphis-born, Charlotte-raised actor
says. ``Nobody's approached me on the street and said, `John, I
can't believe you did that to Aeryn!'
 &HT;    ``I haven't had anyone reprimanding me to my face for the things
that John has done,'' he says cheerfully. ``So that has been pretty
good, actually.''
 &HT;    Crichton, for those not in the loop, is a modern-day astronaut
who finds himself tossed across countless galaxies, smack-dab into
the middle of a raging war. To survive, he joins up with a batch of
renegades that includes a blue priestess (Virginia Hey), an
imposing warrior (Anthony Simcoe), a quirky trollop (Gigi Edgley),
a disenfranchised royal _ a convincing animatronic puppet from Jim
Henson's Creature Shop _ and the aforementioned Aeryn Sun (Claudia
Black), a potential Crichton love interest. They spend most of
their time aboard a sentient ship called Moya.
 &HT;    As the first season ended, the villainous, black-clad Scorpius
(Wayne Pygram) was gleefully torturing Crichton in an ``Alien Meets
Brazil''-style electric chair. Now, early in the second season,
Crichton and company are together again and back on the run.
 &HT;    ``I think it was an interesting journey that was mapped out for
season one,'' Browder says. ``He started off being unable to open a
door, and then reached a level of confidence and competence that
felt right to me. Then he seemed to get stuck, until we saw him in
Scorpius' chair. That seemed to turn him around, and made him into
something else.
 &HT;    ``A lot of season two for Crichton has been his dealing with the
problems of going native,'' he adds. ``It's not an easy journey for
him, and I don't think it should be. He still has a lot of
difficulties. Despite th fact that he's more comfortable in his
surroundings and with the people on Moya, it's still a very
dangerous and turbulent universe for him.''
 &HT;    Life for Browder isn't nearly as tumultuous. He's keen on
Australia, and remarks that his kids even speak with Aussie accents
these days. And, as further proof that his show has fully captured
the imaginations of sci-fi fans, a line of ``Farscape'' action
figures is in the offing.
 &HT;    ``It's something we can all look forward to,'' Browder says,
tongue firmly in cheek. ``It's got to be one of the scariest things
going, especially when you consider what you did to your own action
figures.
 &HT;    ``All I can think of is Rover chewing off John Crichton's legs
and people burning him in effigy and kids putting him through
fights he'll undoubtedly lose again and again,'' he says, laughing.
``It's kind of a scary proposition.'' 
 c.2000 Ian Spelling  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; (Ian Spelling is a New York-based free-lance writer.) &LR; 
 &UR; EDITOR: For further information on ``Farscape,'' consult the
official Web site at www.farscape.com. And don't forget to visit
The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on Inside Trek and
Sci-Fi and other features. &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or by fax at 732-390-4697.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to Inside Trek, a
weekly science-fiction column with color and black-and-white art.)
 &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2369 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-INTERNET-SLAYING-2NDT     05-11 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SLAYING-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
TIMBERON, N.M.: in her stead.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``On the Internet, you can be anyone you want to be. He was
impersonating two different people,'' Lockwood said. Yet, chat-room
participants said Lockwood had a third cyber identity, sometimes
claiming to be ``Kate,'' the little sister of Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood said his son picked up some of his computer savvy from
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very good, and I've always had a computer there since the
early days,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lockwood said that after he retired from the Army, he
worked for a San Antonio computer company; wrote a book on computer
viruses; lectured about computers for the Air Force and helped
start a business called Computers Made Simple. In New Mexico,
Lockwood writes for a local newspaper and publishes a map of the
tiny unincorporated resort community where he lives.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood said his son had a normal boyhood until he reached his
teen years, when medical woes disrupted schooling and turned the
sickly and homebound son emotionally inward. Kenny had friends,
Lockwood said, but he spent much of his time alone _ reading,
studying aviation and assembling model airplanes. About 60 models
decorated his room when police searched it, Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny was a wonderful kid. We used to go camping together
almost every weekend. In those days, the Lockwood family was a real
fun family because we were doing all these outdoor things
together,'' Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the son's health precluded such outings, the father
said, recalling that Kenny was subject to nausea, swelling and
eventually diabetes. In one five-year period, he was hospitalized
for three years, he said. Over time, the son amassed ``millions and
millions'' of dollars in medical expenses, paid for either by the
military or Social Security, Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd spent a long time in a body cast. When he went into the
hospital all &UR;  &LR; bloated up, &UR;  &LR; they checked him for AIDS and drugs,
hepatitis. But he had pancreatitis,'' Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got very bad, and they removed part of his pancreas and his
spleen,'' he said. Later, his gallbladder and part of his stomach
were removed, the father said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had nothing left. He had all those huge scars,'' Lockwood
continued. ``Between that and these anger attacks, he was a pretty
mixed-up kid.''
</P>
<P>
   After graduating in 1986 from high school, where the yearbook
shows he was in ROTC and the oceanography club, Kenny Lockwood
flipped burgers at a fast-food restaurant before getting a late
start on college courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``To Kenny's credit, while he was going through all this hell,
he went on and got a nursing degree. And when he got his diploma,
the dean walked out and presented his diploma and all those people
(in the audience) went crazy,'' Lockwood recalled.
</P>
<P>
   By now in his mid-20s, Kenny Lockwood didn't pursue a nursing
career, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``He couldn't work. No intestines left. Very weak all the time.
He couldn't last more than a couple of hours. He just kept having
problems,'' said his father.
</P>
<P>
   For the past four or five years, while the father lived alone in
New Mexico, the son was passing time at home, supported by a Social
Security disability check of about $600 a month. Lockwood said he
and his wife of 35 years, who are informally separated, cannot
afford to hire an attorney for their son, who is being held in lieu
of $500,000 bond; he assumes his son will have one appointed by the
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's what I used to pay those big taxes for,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood speculated that the six-hour interview his son had with
police before his arrest on April 27 &UR;  &LR; may be challenged because
Lockwood was hospitalized and heavily medicated when the ``full
confession'' was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they found the body, shortly thereafter, he went into one
of these convulsions and they had to take him to the hospital. If
they doped him up ... they didn't get a confession from him,''
Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would not hesitate to speak up in court on his son's
behalf. ``Would I get up and talk to the judge? Certainly. He's a
good kid, but something snapped in him. If you snap for a couple of
seconds, do you die for it? Well, maybe yes, maybe no.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that his son has no criminal record could work in his
favor. However, Lockwood recalled that about 10 years ago, his son
was arrested in San Antonio for ``trying to cash a check on our
account.'' The mother and police decided ``this kid's got problems
enough without going to jail,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Equally troubling was an incident several years earlier that
didn't involve police, Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was living under the shadow of two very overachieving
brothers,'' said Lockwood, referring to his son John, by a previous
marriage, and Mike Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``John was at the time the most decorated cadet that high school
had ever had, and Kenny stole his saber from him. He hid it in his
room. That doesn't sound like much, but that's a horrible thing.
That's like stealing an Aggie's boots,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenny Lockwood often worried his family by reacting angrily when
things didn't go his way, the father said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could never tell what would set him off. When he was in
grade school, he came home one day and tossed a toy truck through
the window. He'd always afterward be so apologetic. He'd mean it.
It would just pass. Like a switch, off and on,'' Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers claimed they once prevented Kenny Lockwood from
committing suicide, the father said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was so mad at me that he stuck a shotgun into his mouth,
and they had to talk him out of it,'' Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   The angry streak also surfaced when the parents questioned their
then-teen-age son about his friend ``Kelly,'' and years later, when
the mother asked him if he were homosexual.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some suspicion in our family, but I've never
pushed it. I remember one time Mama did ask him, and he flew into
one of these rages that you wouldn't believe,'' Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny and Mike Jr. and I have talked, `Is he gay or isn't
he?''' the father said, adding that the suspicions were based on
comments Kenny Lockwood made and videotapes he owned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the videotapes I found were kind of raunchy and most
of them had sort of gay themes, but he had normal ones in there,
too,'' Lockwood said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood said his son wasn't analyzed for psychological
problems, but he discounted any suggestion his son might have
multiple personalities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny would sometimes get wrapped up in his own little lies,
and they would grow and grow. Remember, on the Internet, you can be
anyone you want to be, and I think he got a little carried away
with being people that he wishes he was. That's the way I look at
it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Mike Lockwood, one of the biggest concerns is whether his
son will get adequate medical care behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a worry. He's going in there with all these pieces
missing,'' Lockwood said. ``I'm afraid that he's not going to
last.''
</P>
<P>
   Enduring his son's prosecution, and perhaps facing Kujawa's
parents, is another worry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have thought about writing to his parents,'' Lockwood said,
``but Lord knows, I don't know what to say. I don't know how to
start it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
