<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2373 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-ILOVEYOU-VIRUS-1STLD-     05-11 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ILOVEYOU-VIRUS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-670(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDENT SAYS HE MAY HAVE ACCIDENTALLY RELEASED COMPUTER VIRUS
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to add new reporting and background; adds new 6th graf on
reaction in Philippines; adds new 12th graf noting that de Guzman
was not detained; adds 1 line of background to original penultimate
graf; deletes original last graf and adds 750 wds on computing in
the Philippines and reaction there to investigation.) 
By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ Appearing nervous behind a pair of dark
glasses, a young computer student told reporters Thursday that ``it
is possible'' that he released a destructive virus that has
crippled computer programs around the world.
</P>
<P>
   The student, Onel de Guzman, 23, did not quite admit that he
created the ``I love you'' virus that recently spread rapidly
through e-mail systems in at least 20 countries.
</P>
<P>
   But when he was asked whether he might have accidentally
released the virus, he replied, ``It is possible.''
</P>
<P>
   De Guzman, who lives in an apartment that has been identified by
officials as the source of the virus, was being sought by
authorities, although they have not officially named him as a
suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion focused on him when it was learned that he had
submitted a thesis proposal to his computer college in February
that contained information similar to that used to create the
virus.
</P>
<P>
   The growing indications that the program was launched in this
low-tech country, possibly with skills acquired at the college, has
made its author not only a potential criminal but also, on the
campus and in the press, a bit of a local hero.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Thursday how he felt about the damage caused by the virus,
de Guzman said, ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he was not an Internet fanatic and that he and his
friends had only been trying to create what he called ``a gimmick''
_ a term used among young people here for an event that is exciting
and fun.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside him, his lawyer, Rolando Quimbo, said, ``He is
not really aware that the act imputed to him was done by him.''
</P>
<P>
   These comments reinforced a growing sense here that one of the
most virulent computer viruses ever known was not a premeditated
act of sabotage but could have been a prank that later raced out of
control.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at AMA Computer College, where de Guzman is a student,
said Wednesday that they believed that he might have intended to
steal passwords and Internet access rather than cause tens of
millions of dollars of damage to computer systems around the world.
</P>
<P>
   After de Guzman surfaced late Thursday afternoon, the
authorities made no immediate move to take him into custody.
</P>
<P>
   The lead investigator at the National Bureau of Investigation,
the top law enforcement agency in the Philippines, Nelson
Bartolome, said Thursday that the creators of the virus ``did not
know it was criminal. Perhaps it was just a prank.''
</P>
<P>
   If this is so, one analyst here said, the episode illustrates
the vulnerability of computer systems not only to sophisticated
vandals but to relatively crude and even unintended acts of
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you need very, very sophisticated programming
language to create viruses, in the same way that you don't need
very, very sophisticated weapons to wreak havoc on a society,''
said Randy David, a Filipino sociologist who has studied the
problem.
</P>
<P>
   De Guzman's thesis proposal, which was rejected by his college
because of its criminal implications, described a plan to ``steal
and retrieve Internet accounts of the victim's computer'' in order
to gain free access to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   That is one of the things the virus did, while also moving
through e-mail systems like a poisoned chain letter, paralyzing the
accounts of recipients who opened an attachment titled ``I love
you.'' It was a hybrid of computer programs known as viruses and
worms.
</P>
<P>
   The program's apparent Philippine authorship has aroused a burst
of perverse pride in a country where computers are still a
futuristic technology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the Filipino can!'' cheered an editorial in The Manila
Standard Thursday under the headline, ``The country's first
world-class hacker.''
</P>
<P>
   This is a country of nearly 80 million people where only 200,000
computers were sold last year. It is a country with one of the
world's highest literacy rates, where only 5 percent of public
school students have access to computers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   At the National Bureau of Investigation, the nation's top law
enforcement body, which is charged with prosecuting the creator of
the virus, criminal files are still kept in big metal cabinets
rather than on computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were clueless,'' said Chin Wong, editor of Computer
World, a twice-monthly magazine here, speaking of the
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its low level of computerization, the Philippines
itself was not among the nations badly affected by the virus. Until
now, it has never seen the need to write any laws against computer
crime. It will take some legal creativity to prove that the creator
of the virus committed a crime.
</P>
<P>
   So Art A. Borjal, a columnist in The Philippine Star, may have
felt justified in sounding jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, here is a Filipino genius who has put the Philippines on
the world map,'' he wrote Thursday, ``and who has proven that the
Filipino has the creativity and ingenuity to turn, for better or
for worse, the world upside down.''
</P>
<P>
   He blamed developed nations for creating a vulnerable computer
technology and said the home-grown virus is something that will
``make foreigners look at Filipinos with hidden envy.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the mood Thursday on de Guzman's campus, one of many
small, drab branches of the 10,000-student college that is known
for mass producing computer journeymen rather than sophisticated
programmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine, they were able to penetrate the Pentagon?''
said a computer engineering student who declined to give his name.
``Even though the Philippines is a Third World country, even though
we're behind in technology, they were able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking of de Guzman and a second student, Michael Buen,
who school officials said Wednesday may have collaborated with de
Guzman in creating the virus.
</P>
<P>
   De Guzman denied to reporters Thursday that Buen was involved.
But de Guzman's lawyer, Quimbo, said that ``knowledge of the
contents'' of the thesis proposal ``was not limited to Onel.''
</P>
<P>
   After a computer in de Guzman's apartment was identified _ with
the help of the U.S. FBI _ as the source of the virus, Philippine
authorities obtained a warrant for the arrest of two of the
residents.
</P>
<P>
   They arrested one man, Reomel Ramones, a bank employee, on
Monday and held him overnight. They also issued a subpoena for his
friend, Irene de Guzman, who also works in a bank and who is Onel
de Guzman's older sister. She appeared with him at the news
conference Thursday, also wearing a pair of dark glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the country's low technological level, computer colleges
have proliferated in recent years, in large part to serve foreign
companies that are based either here or abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Computer technicians are the latest wave in a long-standing
national industry _ the export of labor _ that has traditionally
involved construction workers, seamen, entertainers, nurses and
domestic help.
</P>
<P>
   ``Computer training is really a ticket for a lot of
lower-middle-class families to have their children work abroad,''
said David Celdran, a local journalist who reports on computers and
information technology.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign workers in all fields send home as much as $6 billion a
year, the nation's leading source of foreign exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skills they acquire at schools like AMA are really the
basic skills _ computer literacy, basic programming, electronics,
putting together motherboards, hardware, computer repair _ rather
than sophisticated computer engineering or programming skills,''
Celdran said.
</P>
<P>
   All the more reason for quiet pride on de Guzman's campus
Thursday, where faculty members insisted that they did not condone
computer crime although the students seemed fascinated.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he did was wrong, but amazing,'' said one of them. ``This
is technology that began in the United States, and yet we were able
to manipulate it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
