<HEADER>
A2376 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      05-11 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Calif.)  
 A SURPRISED `WILD PARTY'; ANOTHER LIFE FOR `CATS'; `I'M A WHAT?';
ALONG THE WAY By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The unexpectedly strong showing of the Public
Theater's production of ``The Wild Party'' in the Tony Award
nominations _ the show landed seven _ has apparently lifted the
fortunes of that struggling musical enough to persuade its
producers to run at least through the Tonys.
</P>
<P>
   The show, which opened to mixed reviews at the Virginia Theater
on April 13, received nominations for best musical, score, book and
lighting, as well as for the acting of its three leads: Mandy
Patinkin, Toni Collette and Eartha Kitt.
</P>
<P>
   And while the nominations provided a much-needed morale lift,
they did not provide a huge lift in sales; the show did about
$40,000 in business on Tuesday and Wednesday. Still, it has shown
stronger sales since its early days _ perhaps because of heavy
advertising _ and the producers believe it may be building
momentum.
</P>
<P>
   So now, the producers have decided to stick with the show
through the awards on June 4. They hope the national television
exposure and some winners generate sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are looking up,'' said Kenneth Lerer, chairman of the
Public Theater's board. ``We are moving forward.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to keep ``Wild Party'' alive probably means
``Macbeth,'' starring Kelsey Grammer and due on Broadway on June 8,
will end up at a Shubert theater. Recent advertisements for that
show have been cagey about its eventual home, saying it would play
at ``a Jujamcyn theater,'' but it is an open secret that the
production has been eyeing the Virginia. But with ``The Wild
Party'' staying open, Jujamcyn doesn't appear to have a theater
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Macbeth'' producers aren't commenting on their plans, but
because of advertising deadlines and technical questions, they will
soon need to know where they're playing. The closing of ``Amadeus''
on Sunday means the Music Box, owned by the Shubert Organization,
would be available. The production has been designed for the
Virginia but could fit in the smaller Music Box. The production
could be lucrative for the Shuberts; it has sold well in its
pre-Broadway run in Boston, and Grammer is expected to be a major
draw in New York, too.
</P>
<P>
   Rocco Landesman, the president of Jujamcyn, and Wolfe have a
long working relationship, which has included Wolfe's productions
of ``Angels in America'' and ``Jelly's Last Jam.''
</P>
<P>
   Box-office figures for ``The Wild Party'' have been at about 50
percent of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the small financial bump, the number of nominations is
seen by members of the production team as a vindication for a show
that has had its share of detractors. Oddly enough, the other
``Wild Party,'' produced by the Manhattan Theater Club, also found
a degree of redemption in the 13 nominations it received for Drama
Desk awards.
</P>
<P>
   Another Life for `Cats'
</P>
<P>
   You knew it was going happen.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``Cats,'' scheduled to close on June 25,
announced Thursday that the show would extend 11 more weeks in
response to extraordinary demand for tickets.
</P>
<P>
   Sales for ``Cats,'' the longest-running musical in Broadway
history, have been hot since word came in February that the show,
which has played at the Winter Garden Theater since 1982, would
finally meow for the last time. The announcement made front pages
coast to coast, and the race for tickets was on. Last week ``Cats''
had the sixth highest grosses on Broadway, with sales of $635,639.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm a What?'
</P>
<P>
   It was 6:30 a.m., Pacific Daylight Time, on Monday when Daniel
Davis' phone rang. He awoke, and some woman started screaming at
him manically, telling him that he had just won a Tony, or was a
Tony, or could buy a Tony, or something.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even realize what was happening,'' Davis said. ``I
thought, `Who is this insane woman?'''
</P>
<P>
   The woman, it turned out, was a press agent from
Boneau/Bryan-Brown, the agency that had handled ``Wrong Mountain,''
the short-lived David Hirson play in which Davis had played a
grandiose theater director. (The play, which was not loved by
critics, closed on Feb. 5 after 28 performances.) The press agent
was screaming about Davis' unlikely, but wildly applauded, Tony
nomination for best featured performance in a play. It is his first
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   How did Davis, who is currently between jobs, react to the news?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just stunned beyond belief,'' he said. ``I ran up about
a $2,000 phone bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, says Davis, who played Niles the butler on the
sitcom ``The Nanny'' for six years, he has had several calls from
directors wondering about his availability. He also said the
nomination was something of a vindication for a play he felt was
unfairly dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a joy because this feels like it comes from other
actors and people who do the work,'' he said. ``It just feels so
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Along the Way
</P>
<P>
   _ The critically acclaimed revival of ``Jitney,'' by August
Wilson, has been extended until July 16 at Second Stage, and there
is talk of a further extension. This week, the play won the New
York Drama Critics award for best play. Other winners included the
musical ``James Joyce's `The Dead,''' which opens in Los Angeles in
July, and ``Copenhagen,'' named best foreign play.
</P>
<P>
   _ The creators of ``How to Be a Red Hot Shakespearean Lover,'' a
lighthearted look at classic romancing techniques, must be on to
something. Recently the male half of the two-person cast, Greg
Steinbruner, proposed to the female half, Eve Hartmann. The show
finishes a run this weekend at the St. Marks Theater; a wedding is
planned for next year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bronson Pinchot, Keith David and Randy Danson head the cast of
Shakespeare's ``Winter's Tale,'' beginning at the Delacorte Theater
in Central Park on June 21.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Enter the Guardsman,'' now in previews at the Vineyard
Theater, has pushed its opening from May 18 to May 21. The reason?
``The Laramie Project,'' Moises Kaufman's docudrama, is scheduled
to open on May 18 at the Union Square Theater, around the corner
from the Vineyard.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
