<HEADLINE>
&HT;     49ERS CLOUDED WITH UNCERTAINTY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ In the spring of their rebuilding, the San
Francisco 49ers are a team badly in need of resolution, but
wherever they look all they see is an image just out of focus.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Garrison Hearst returned from Seattle on Tuesday
after surgery there to increase blood flow in his troublesome left
ankle. He might be able to play by October.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Steve Young popped in for a visit with coach Steve
Mariucci before flying to Phoenix to be with his bride, Barbara. He
is still deciding whether he wants to play again.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Jerry Rice met with general manager Bill Walsh on
Monday about his possible return to the 49ers, contingent upon a
salary cap-friendly contract being worked out.
</P>
<P>
   While Hearst's most recent surgery puts his return in doubt, the
49ers should know where they stand with Young and Rice by early
June. The financial effect of roster moves made after June 1 is
deferred until 2001, which is why transactions occur at this time.
</P>
<P>
   If the 49ers decide to part ways with either Young or Rice, they
would not take a hit to their salary cap for this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``June 1 is a big date for us,'' Walsh said. ``It's important we
be able to make firm plans soon. If Steve returns, signing another
quarterback is not a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   That would impact Rick Mirer, whom the 49ers are considering
signing in June if Young decides not to return. A decision can't
come soon enough for Mariucci, who fiddles while Young turns the
issue over and over in his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's being tugged in different directions,'' Mariucci said.
``One tug is he has a real desire to play. Then another tug is if
going in a different direction makes sense. Another tug is maybe
play one more year with Jerry. He really hasn't settled on one
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Young may be swayed by how good he feels after not playing for
nearly 10 months, Mariucci said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does feel good,'' the coach said. ``It's come down to Steve
making a decision to play or not. He feels the risks are minimal.
He just has to decide if he wants to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice, meanwhile, has made his desire to return to the 49ers
abundantly clear. His agent, Jim Steiner, is trying to work out a
one- or two-year contract at considerably less than the $5.49
million salary cap figure Rice is scheduled to carry into this
season. Of that amount, $3.95 million is in salary; the rest is
accounted for by his prorated signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh is hopeful an agreement can be reached, but cautioned,
``Until it's signed, it's not signed.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Hearst, his second surgery on the ankle will further
extend his already 16-month rehabilitation from the original injury
he sustained on Jan. 9, 1999. In the procedure Saturday in Seattle,
Dr. Pierce Scranton removed dead bone from Hearst's ankle and
inserted grafts taken from his knee to try to stimulate blood flow
and halt the onset of necrosis.
</P>
<P>
   According to the 49ers, no NFL player has had this type of
condition and returned to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels better, feels more hopeful,'' Walsh said.
``Obviously, it pushes us way back into the season. It's really up
in the air. We just don't know what the odds are (of his
returning).''
</P>
<P>
   For a team trying to rebuild, the 49ers need a clear vision of
where they are heading. Instead, the looking glass is clouded with
uncertainty.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
