<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2386 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-SIERRA-LEONE-355&AMP;ADD-     05-11 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-355&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REBEL ADVANCE ON SIERRA LEONE'S CAPITAL IS REPULSED 
</HEADLINE>
   By NORIMITSU ONISHI   
 C.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone _ Forces loyal to the government appeared
to push back a rebel advance onto this capital city Thursday, but
fighting intensified and spread to other areas in the country.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition made up of United Nations peacekeepers, Sierra
Leonean soldiers and a militia known as Kamajors secured the road
leading to the town of Waterloo, about 18 miles southeast of the
capital. But heavy fighting took place about 10 miles east of
Waterloo, said David Wimhurst, the spokesman of the U.N. force.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, fighting around Waterloo drove thousands of
civilians to gather at Jui Junction, 10 miles from Freetown, as
they fled toward the capital. Thursday, many people were returning
to their homes.
</P>
<P>
   In the capital, pro-government forces tightened security on the
streets, mindful that infiltrators played a critical role last year
in the near-fall of Freetown. British paratroopers limited access
to the western part of the city, the site of the U.N. headquarters,
even setting up barbed-wire along the beach.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers operated checkpoints, alongside Sierra Leonean
soldiers, militiamen, and rifle-toting men of unknown affiliation;
they were dressed in T-shirts and flip-flops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every minute that goes by strengthens our resolve to bring
lasting peace in this country,'' said Prince Nicol, the spokesman
for Lt. Col. Johnny Paul Koroma. In the rapidly shifting alliances
since last week, Koroma, is now supporting the government against
his former ally, Foday Sankoh, the leader of the Revolutionary
United Front. Koroma previously headed a short-lived junta that
toppled President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah in 1997; Kabbah now is
president again.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's fighting took place as the United Nations continued
to try to obtain the release of 500 hostages. The whereabouts of
Sankoh, who vanished after a deadly confrontation outside his house
Monday, were still unclear, Wimhurst said. But negotiations with
the Revolutionary United Front were being held through
intermediaries, including Liberia's president, Charles Taylor, a
former guerrilla who has long supported Sankoh.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Securing Freetown against an assault by the Revolutionary United
Front has become the priority of the U.N. force. But thousands of
U.N. peacekeepers remain deployed in large towns across the
country, some in rebel-held territory.
</P>
<P>
   In the northern town of Makeni, hundreds of Kenyan peacekeepers
who had been surrounded by rebels broke through to the north and
south. Most made it to friendly territory. But six were wounded,
three seriously, when they came under friendly fire by Sierra
Leonean soldiers who mistook them for rebels disguised in U.N.
uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   Some rebels have apparently begun wearing uniforms that they
stripped from the 500 U.N. members who are being held hostage.
Others have been using the hostages' equipment, including 13
armored cars belonging to Zambian troops.
</P>
<P>
   In a town about 65 miles by highway from here called Port Loko,
the site of two abandoned disarmament camps, U.N. peacekeepers were
attacked overnight by rebels using armored cars, Wimhurst said. No
casualties were reported.
</P>
<P>
   But the heaviest battles occurred on the road east of Waterloo,
according to the United Nations. Jordanian and Nigerian
peacekeepers formed a heavy presence in the area, and three
Landrovers filled with elite SAS British troops were seen heading
east of Waterloo. The 850 British troops in Sierra Leone, who are
officially here to evacuate European nationals, have been under
intense pressure to play a more active role in peacekeeping.
</P>
<P>
   Nigerians, Indians, Kenyans, Jordanians, Zambians, Guineans and
Ghanaians make up the 8,700-member force in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   The Sierra Leonean army, which is said to number 5,000, was far
larger before the junta took power in 1997. At the time most
soldiers reportedly sided with Koroma against the government. In
the anarchy of Sierra Leone, many who were soldiers during the day
became rebels at night _ and came to be known as ``sobels.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Sierra Leone's peace agreement, rebellious soldiers
fit to be rehabilitated were to be reintegrated into a new Sierra
Leonean army. But in the desperation that gripped the government in
recent days, the government effectively permitted Koroma to rally
his men against Sankoh's group.
</P>
<P>
   ``The government has not stopped them from doing what they are
doing,'' Septimus Kaikai, Kabbah's spokesman, said in an interview
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolutionary United Front and the Kamajor militia, which is
made up of traditional hunters who often provide security services
in West Africa, are each thought to total more than 15,000 members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
