u v BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT &LR;      05-11 0919
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EARLY-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Friday, May 12 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   AIDS-DRUGS (Paris) _ In a move that could change the face of
AIDS treatment in Africa and Asia, five major pharmaceutical
companies offered Thursday to negotiate deep cuts in the prices of
their drugs for poor nations plagued by the disease. The
announcement was made by the World Health Organization in Geneva,
and the companies were careful not to appear together to discuss
the offers. All were afraid of running afoul of American antitrust
laws, which prevent corporations not only from colluding to raise
prices, but from colluding to lower them. But even if the prices
drop steeply _ and cuts of 80 percent or more are being talked of _
no one expects an easy end to AIDS in the Third World. By Donald G.
McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
   LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE (Los Alamos, N.M.) _ A firestorm swept through
the abandoned streets of Los Alamos on Thursday, burning as many as
400 homes, some down to their foundations, while frustrated
firefighters braced for wind gusts up to 60 mph. All 11,000 people
in Los Alamos were evacuated, and on Thursday morning another 7,000
fled suburban White Rock, where many evacuees had once sought
safety. At the storied Los Alamos nuclear laboratory, for the first
time shut down by fire, flames singed a research building but it
did not ignite. Explosives and radioactive material were protected
in fireproof facilities, lab officials said. (Summary from wires)
By James Sterngold.
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-HARASS (Washington) _ Out of the blue, when they were
cooling down after their regular morning jog, a colonel was groped
by her male running partner, another colonel who forcefully tried
to embrace her; ``I pushed him back and said `no' and that was
it,'' she said. The woman, now one of the military's senior
officers and insists that her name not be revealed, did not report
this incident when it took place a few years ago. She said she
feared that both her reputation and her career could have been
ruined if she filed an official complaint. And even after the
vindication of a formal sexual harassment complaint filed against
filed by Lt. Gen. Claudia Kennedy against another general, the
senior officer who was accosted while jogging still believes she
did the right thing. But the Kennedy case has revived the question
of how pervasive sexual harassment remains in the military and how
such cases should be handled. By Elizabeth Becker.
</P>
<P>
   NY-GIULIANI-REACT (New York) _ Over sandwiches and keyboards
Thursday, around soda machines and bus stops, it seemed as if New
Yorkers were barely bothering with the news: the marital problems
of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani and his wife, Donna Hanover. ``Come on,
we knew a long time ago this wasn't much of a marriage,'' said
Sidney Levitan, 89, a retired high school administrator. Instead _
in a world where divorce is common, where a presidential scandal
has inured people to accounts of infidelity and where talk shows
obliterate lines between public and private every morning _ the
questions seemed to be less about the breakup of a marriage and
more about how the the husband and the wife are conducting
themselves during that breakup. By Randy Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   EGAN-PROFILE (Bridgeport, Conn.) _ As a seminary student in
Chicago, he was the only member of his class chosen to go to Rome
to finish his theology studies. As a young priest, he spent a mere
year in a parish before he was plucked to serve as an assistant to
the cardinal of Chicago. And later in the Vatican, he was one of
six experts in church law selected to spend mornings with Pope John
Paul II over breakfast, helping him review each word of the
proposed new Code of Canon Law. On Thursday, after a week of
unusually explicit leaks, the Vatican formally announced that
Bishop Edward Michael Egan of Bridgeport, Conn., had been chosen
the ninth archbishop of New York, to succeed Cardinal John
O'Connor, who died last week at the age of 80. By Laurie Goodstein.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT14.
</P>
<P>
   FORD-SUVS (Atlanta) _ In an extraordinary statement for a large
corporation, Ford Motor Co., which started the sport utility boom
in 1990 and is now one of the world's two biggest producers of
sport utility vehicles, said that it faced a ``dilemma'' in
continuing to sell the highly profitable vehicles despite what the
company acknowledged were serious safety and environmental
problems. In a ``corporate citizenship report'' issued at the
company's annual shareholders' meeting here, Ford Motor
acknowledged that sport utilities contribute more than cars to
global warming, are permitted higher tailpipe emissions, and pose
safety and visibility dangers for other motorists. Ford said that
it was making progress toward solutions and was even looking for
alternatives to the off-road vehicles, although continuing to
produce them. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT17.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANCIENT-SKULL (Undated) _ Scientists find the earliest
fossil evidence of migration out of Africa by human ancestors _ a
homo erectus skull 1.7 million years old in the republic of
Georgia. Surprisingly, these emigrants were using tools developed
700,000 years before, confounding the prevailing theory that it was
an advance in tool making that fueled the migration out of Africa.
By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1835EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
