<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0288 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2391 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-TAUB-PIANO-MUSIC-ART-     05-11 1348
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAUB-PIANO-MUSIC-ART-$ADV14-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINDING THE TRUTH IN THE COMPOSER'S HAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., May 14)  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT24 was sent May 10 to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATTHEW GUREWITSCH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his sparsely furnished apartment perched high
above West End Avenue and dominated by a Steinway grand, the
pianist Robert Taub was poring over musical manuscripts one recent
afternoon, as he often does.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I learn a piece,'' Taub says, ``I ask myself, `Why am I
learning it?' And the answer is that I feel a lot about it and
think there's something about it that I can communicate. But then I
ask: `Why did the composer write it? What did it mean to him?' And
the best answers are in the sketches and the autograph scores,
where you can see what choices were made and why.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not impossible to interpret a piece of music from the
printed score alone, and often an artist has no choice. Still, the
printed score is the diagram of a result, whereas a manuscript
captures the shape of inspiration on the wing. That, ideally, is
what Taub wants to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``No editor will print a double negative,'' Taub declares by way
of illustration. The point arises apropos of Beethoven's Sonata No.
30 in E, which Taub will perform on May 19 in a rare piano recital
in the Coolidge Auditorium at the Library of Congress in
Washington. The library, not incidentally, owns the manuscript of
the sonata, as it does those of Haydn's Sonata in E flat (Hob.
XVI:52) and Milton Babbitt's ``Canonical Form,'' also on the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The double negative occurs in the finale of the Beethoven
sonata, which starts out as a conventional theme and variations but
after four clearly designated variations takes on a freer, more
adventurous character. The last bar of the theme appears in
published editions without either a ritardando or a pedal marking _
quite rightly, since Beethoven, having written them in ink, later
scratched them out in pencil, his customary implement for
registering second thoughts. He brought out the pencil again at the
end of the sonata, where the theme recurs in its original form.
Here, he decided on reflection, the ritardando and the pedaling
mark were in order, along with a new low E, for resonance.
</P>
<P>
   The reverse adjustments at the beginning and the end of the
movement point to the same conclusion: that the theme and the
opening variations are not modular segments. On the contrary, the
movement unfolds as a single trajectory, no pauses for breath along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Like other pianists, Taub first learned the Beethoven from
printed scores; to the best of his knowledge (and he has not failed
to look), no facsimile of the manuscript exists. His path first led
him to the Library of Congress as he was preparing his 10-CD series
of the complete Beethoven piano sonatas for Vox Classics, a survey
as remarkable for the intellectual grasp of the material as for its
technical assurance and aura of poetic spontaneity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when I really began to realize what treasures
autograph scores are,'' he says. ``The immersion in the spiritual
world of the composer became so much more intense. Every printed
edition is sterile compared to an autograph score. The calligraphy
is imbued with the composer's emotion while rehearing the music in
the process of writing it down. Some of the Beethoven sonatas look
very neat. Others show evidence of greater struggle to find just
the right artistic statement. Some are very messy, but they give
you the sweep of the music.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus, to an artist of Taub's turn of mind, the spacious
arrangement of an arpeggio of grace notes in the manuscript of the
E major Sonata gives a graphic image of the generous elasticity
with tempo Beethoven had in mind. The same little notes squashed
into minimum space in the printed score give priority to mere
thrift, sending a subliminal and potentially misleading message.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that a tempo marking that readers of the printed score
simply know as ``prestissimo'' (a rare term in Beethoven) is
expanded in pencil from the original ink ``presto'' likewise
strikes Taub as powerfully suggestive.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations of an autograph take many forms. The Haydn
sonata on Taub's program, the composer's last, written for the
sophisticated taste of audiences in London, combines the masterly
plan of a formal French garden with an English garden's lush,
casual exuberance.
</P>
<P>
   The printed editions do not obscure Haydn's unfettered,
apparently improvisatory panache, but the manuscript magnifies
those impressions by orders of magnitude. Like the famously
immaculate manuscripts of Mozart, it is pristine, fluent, devoid of
decorative flourish, essentially elegant rather than
demonstratively so.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the sheer beauty of Haydn's hand, however, the autograph
also holds a few hidden surprises. Taub, a practiced and eloquent
guide to the music he plays, goes briefly off the record to
fulminate against the reputable publishers who presume, in
supposedly authentic editions, to correct `` Haydn'' silently
rather than face up to his occasional waywardness.
</P>
<P>
   He points to the evidence of bars 40 and 48 of the second
movement, where the composer's clusters of 32nd-notes add up,
respectively, to an extra half beat and full beat per measure. On
no authority whatsoever, editors solve the equation by cutting
32nds in two, creating hasty flurries of 64th-notes that regularize
the meter but disrupt the eddy and flow of the music. No, the
pianist admits with a broad grin, the arithmetic doesn't up, ``and
Haydn just didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   The reputation of an intellectual is a dubious asset for a
performer. Among contemporary pianists, perhaps only Alfred Brendel
and Maurizio Pollini have reconciled it with stardom.
</P>
<P>
   Taub, 43, could join them. For the last six years, he has been
artist in residence _ no courtesy title in this case _ at the
Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, N.J., an ivory tower
once peopled by the likes of Albert Einstein, J. Robert Oppenheimer
and John von Neumann. In truth, the institute is devoted to just
four disciplines: historical studies, mathematics, natural sciences
and social science. But maverick appointments may be made at the
director's discretion, which accounts for the presence of Taub.
</P>
<P>
   Taub lives mostly in Princeton. The average IQ at his sold-out
cycle of the Beethoven sonatas over the last three seasons at
Wolfensohn Hall there _ each concert repeated three times, with
introductory talks by the artist _ was assuredly far off to the
right on the bell curve. (Cycles on the Princeton model are now
under way at Merkin Concert Hall in New York and in other cities.)
</P>
<P>
   Yet for all the scholarship of Taub's preparation, there is
nothing cerebral or chilly about his approach or his playing. A
comment on the way his mind responds to such documents prompts a
gently insistent demurrer. ``I immerse myself in the music, and the
music immerses itself in me,'' he says. ``It's not just a question
of what happens in the brain. It's very moving to me to hear an
autograph score.''
</P>
<P>
   On the experience of performance, Taub quotes T.S. Eliot, the
only artist previously appointed to the Institute for Advanced
Study: ``You are the music while the music lasts.'' (The passage is
from ``The Dry Salvages,'' one of the ``Four Quartets.'') But of
course, the music is to a superior degree the composer, and with
living specimens, it is possible to move beyond talismanic
communion to actual dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Persichetti, before his death, couched advice to Taub
about his Piano Concerto in suggestive language rather than in
musicians' shoptalk: ``gruff,'' for instance, or ``far off'' (and
not ``pianissimo''). Leon Kirchner, having let Taub play his
Sonata, said, ``Well, Bob, it's OK, but really it goes like this,''
and ran through it as if conjuring up the whole thing on the spot.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The living composer with whom Taub is now most closely
associated is Milton Babbitt, his composition professor for several
years at the Juilliard School and at Princeton. His intention in
these studies, Taub hastens to explain, was never to become a
composer but to develop an insider's understanding of musical
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   Looking over his shoulder as he tears into ``Canonical Form,''
which Babbitt composed for him, is an especially enlightening
experience. Under Taub's fingers, music widely considered dense and
cerebral sings and dances. A brisk rhythmic fanfare in the left
hand _ set down on the page like Neptune's trident _ jabs out a
theme that instantly begins generating new transformations, while
little splashes high on the keyboard tickle the ear like memories
of half-remembered show tunes.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt, as many music lovers know, taught Stephen Sondheim.
Babbitt, we are often reminded, comes out of Tin Pan Alley. Taub's
execution of Babbitt's gestures makes the imaginative connections
crystal clear. This is a rendition in the face of which prejudice
simply dissolves.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt's calligraphy strikes my eye as square, functional,
decisive: the writing of an engineer rather than, say, a physician.
Taub would prefer not to hear it described as ``technical,'' a term
that perhaps reinforces unfortunate prejudices. But Babbitt, like
many other composers, releases only fair copies. Taub himself has
never gained access to Babbitt's drafts or sketches. ``Milton keeps
them to himself,'' the pianist says. ``Brahms burned his.'' I N a
strange twist, Taub's Library of Congress recital complements the
Smithsonian Institution's current exhibit ``Piano 300.'' An
inventory of musical instruments in the possession of the Medici in
1700, which mentions ``un arpicembalo che fa il piano e il forte,''
``di nuova invenzione di Bartolomeo Cristofori'' (``a keyboard
instrument that plays both soft and loud, newly invented by
Bartolomeo Cristofori'') supplies the point of origin for the
three-century time line, and one of only three extant Cristoforis
(this one dated 1722) has been imported for the occasion from the
National Museum of Musical Instruments in Rome. The occasion would
seem made to order for a recital of works played on instruments of
their own periods.
</P>
<P>
   Pianists of the historical persuasion who might relish such an
exercise are legion. But the chosen instrument for Taub's art is
the modern Steinway: in particular, a Steinway engineered for
maximum control.
</P>
<P>
   A chapter of his book, ``Playing the Beethoven Piano Sonatas,''
in production with Amadeus Press, is titled ``The Myth of the
Authentic Pianoforte.'' Not that Taub scorns the lessons to be
learned from antiques.
</P>
<P>
   ``I make it my business to play for my own experience
pianofortes of periods appropriate to specific pieces of music,''
he says. ``I've tried the early Beethoven sonatas on pianofortes of
the late 1790s, the `Waldstein' Sonata on a pianoforte of 1804 or
1805 and the later sonatas on pianofortes of the 1810s and early
1820s. What's interesting to me is the way Beethoven's compositions
transcend the instruments of their time, forcing the piano builders
to develop ever greater sonority and technological refinement. The
`Waldstein' was written in 1804. You can barely play it on a piano
of that time. You can't play it at all on a piano of 1797. The
range, the sonorous capacity, the sensitivity of pedal mechanisms _
none of these would be sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to think in terms of overall perception. Not only have
pianos changed, but our sphere of hearing has become enlarged. In
Beethoven's time, there were no screaming fire engines, no
airplanes. A thunderstorm was a major aural event. The day I play a
concert on a fortepiano will be the day when the whole audience
arrives by horse-drawn carriages and the hall is lit with candles
and everyone has become totally immersed in the aural world of the
early 19th century. And that will never be.''(BOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
