<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, May 12, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Large contrasts in temperature will be the salient weather
feature in the Northeast as humid air surges across the Middle
Atlantic states against cool, almost autumnal air holding its
ground over New England. Broken clusters of showers and
thunderstorms will move in a line along the sharp boundary between
these vastly disparate air masses.
</P>
<P>
   The mercury will soar toward 100 degrees across parts of the
South Carolina piedmont, and isolated thunderstorms forming along a
sea breeze front will dot Florida.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to the South Carolina heat, a chilly rain, perhaps
mixed with snowflakes, will fall near the central Canadian border,
where an unseasonably cold air mass knifes into the Plains. Farther
east, thunderstorms will erupt along and ahead of a cool front
spanning from the southern Great Lakes to the central Mississippi
Valley.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: WAR ON WILDFIRE
</P>
<P>
   Winds several thousand feet above New Mexico ordained the
outcome of Thursday's futile war against wildfires. Once the sun
rose, currents of air rising from the warming ground led to kindred
currents of sinking air that transferred momentum from fast winds
aloft toward the surface. Ground-level winds of 25 to 50 mph
resulted from the downward transfer, fanning flames. Moreover, the
air aloft was very dry. Thus, the downward transfer also lowered
surface humidity, another factor that encouraged the spread of the
wildfire.
</P>
</TEXT>
