<SLUG> BC-NEWORLEANS-CUISINE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRESCENT CITY CUISINE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies NEW ORLEANS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   New Orleans is famous for its dining, yet many places survive
largely on reputation or proximity to tourists. Ask around; nearly
everyone in town has strong opinions on restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   Among new places, our favorite was Cuvee (322 Magazine St.;
(504) 587-9001.) An airy, dark-wood dining room with a high,
gold-leaf ceiling, it features excellent service and
Spanish/French-tinged New Orleans cuisine with such superb dishes
as sugar-cane smoked duck breast served with Roquefort-pecan
risotto and foie gras, and a smoked lamb and goat cheese
quesadilla, served with traditional mole sauce. Desserts, such as a
chocolate and banana ``tres leches'' torte, and the extensive wine
list were equally sublime.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Grass (221 Camp St., in the International House hotel;
(504) 553-9550) is run by chef Minh Bui, who was named chef of the
year in '99 by New Orleans magazine. The serene setting offers such
nontraditional New Orleans fare as shrimp dumplings, wok-smoked
salmon steak and roasted five-spice duck breast with sweet rice and
baby bok choy.
</P>
<P>
   Getting attention for its contemporary creole dishes is Gamay
Bistro (320 Decatur St., in the Bienville House Hotel; (504)
299-8800); it was named one of the city's best new restaurants of
'99 by several critics. And we wanted to eat at Dick and Jenny's,
(4501 Tchoupitoulas St; (504) 894-9880). This small, casual cafe,
which opened last year, has become a local favorite for its creole
fare by chef Richard Benz, but the two-hour wait on a Friday night
dissuaded us, even though the folks in line on the leafy patio
seemed happy enough.
</P>
<P>
   Established spots that seem to be holding up include Nola, (534
St. Louis; (504) 522-6652) another of celeb chef Emeril Lagasse's
operations. The 2-story space, with an exhibition kitchen, is
bright and relaxed, yet offers good service for such specialties as
rich crawfish pie and shrimp pasta with warm remoulade.
</P>
<P>
   K-Paul's Louisiana Kitchen (416 Chartres; (504) 524-7394) and
its expansive chef, Paul Prudhomme, put Cajun cooking on the map;
an airy redesign a few years ago also added a slightly more formal
second dining room. The food, especially simple things like the
fried oysters, is still fresh and decadently rich; the attitude can
still be a bit we-don't-need-you.
</P>
<P>
   We also still like the po' boys and jambalaya at the
standing-room-only Acme Oyster House (724 Iberville; (504)
522-5973); the grilled muffulettas at the equally crowded Johnny's
Po-Boys (511 St. Louis; (504) 524-8129) and brunch at Commander's
Palace (1403 Washington Ave.; (504) 899-8221). Order a Bloody Mary
and the shrimp remoulade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
