<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-MALCOLM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE WHOLE TRUTH ON MALCOLM X 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the least, there is something of historical value in Louis
Farrakhan's qualified expression of regret for his role in the
assassination of Malcolm X.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I may have been complicit in words that I spoke leading up
to'' the murder of Malcolm X, Farrakhan told Malcolm's daughter,
Atallah Shabazz, in a ``60 Minutes'' interview taped last month,
``I acknowledge that and regret that any word that I have said
caused the loss of life of a human being.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan, ill with cancer, may have wished to seek forgiveness
from the people who suffered most directly from Malcolm's loss. The
Nation of Islam leader also sought reconciliation recently with
Wallace Deen Mohammad, the son of the Nation of Islam's founder,
Elijah Mohammad, and a person who remained close to Malcolm after
Malcolm criticized Elijah Mohammad and left the Nation of Islam to
found his own organization.
</P>
<P>
   As the memory of Malcolm becomes encrusted with political myths,
it is more important than ever that coming generations can see
clearly the differences between him and the men who had him
assassinated. Farrakhan called Malcolm a traitor for breaking with
Elijah Mohammad and wrote in the Nation of Islam's paper two months
before Malcolm was gunned down that ``such a man is worthy of
death.''
</P>
<P>
   Farrakhan's saying to Malcolm's daughter that he ``begs God's
mercy and forgiveness'' for those words leaves the impression that
his sole transgression was to write words that may have
inadvertently contributed to the assassin's decision to murder
Malcolm.
</P>
<P>
   But one of the three convicted killers, Thomas Hagan, in an
affadavit filed 13 years after the killing to attest that his two
co-defendants were innocent and that he acted with four other Black
Muslims, said the assassination was ordered as a religious duty. In
a 1979 article in the Globe, Hagan said: ``There was like a chain
of command in the Nation, and I thought that somebody higher up had
spoken to somebody in our group. . .''
</P>
<P>
   For the sake of history, if not for his own inner peace,
Farrakhan ought to say all he knows about the decision to have
Malcolm killed 35 years ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1842EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0294 </DOCNO>
