<HEADER>
A2400 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-EVERGLADES12-COX     05-11 0540
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EVERGLADES12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. SHOULD PAY MORE FOR EVERGLADES RESTORATION, FLORIDA SAYS
 &HT;    BY SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Florida Gov. Jeb Bush urged federal lawmakers
Thursday to pay an equal share in a plan to restore the Everglades,
the largest public works project since the Panama Canal.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, joined by Florida's two senators, Bob Graham, D, and
Connie Mack, R, also asked the Senate Environment and Public Works
Committee to reject the administration's proposal to give the
federal government more of a role in the allocation of water
resources in South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers estimates that the restoration
of the Everglades, whose natural flow of fresh water has been
disrupted by agricultural diversion and public works projects, will
take about 25 years and cost a total of $7.8 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Corps submitted a restoration plan last July that the
administration included in its Water Resource Development Act
introduced in Congress last month.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal would give the Army Corps of Engineers, the
Interior Department, and several other federal and state agencies
the right to evaluate and approve all restoration projects within
the Everglades. It also recommends the state pay 60 percent of the
overall costs and the federal government 40 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida believes that it should be on equal footing with the
federal government not only in terms of financing, but in managing,
governing and operating this project,'' Bush told the Senate panel.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Florida legislature approved a bill allocating $2
billion in state funds for the restoration over the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the Seminole and the Miccosukee Indian tribes
living within the Everglades echoed Bush's concerns that the
federal government would be too involved in the water management of
the Everglades.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attempting to federalize the water allocation decisions
blatantly disregards the existing body of Florida water law. With
Florida's water law thrown into disarray by this approach, the
Tribe's Water Compact is jeopardized,'' said Patricia Power, a
spokeswoman for the Seminole tribe.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of federal officials from the Army Corps of Engineers,
the Environmental Protection Agency and the Interior Department
asked the lawmakers to approve the administration's proposal and
not delay the Everglades restoration any longer.
</P>
<P>
   One panel member, Sen. Max Baucus, D-Mont., expressed doubts
about the overall costs of the restoration plan and its long-term
feasibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one has provided a compelling case that this plan is going
to work,'' said Baucus.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Bob Smith, R-N.H., chairman of the committee, said he would
consider offering the Everglades restoration as a separate bill and
not include it as part of the water resource legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will follow whichever path that gives an Everglades bill the
best chance of becoming law this year,'' said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he expected the full Senate to vote on Everglades
legislation before its July 4 recess.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Schultz's e-mail address is sues(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
