<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWORLEANS-IFYOUGO-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF YOU GO: NEW ORLEANS
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies NEW ORLEANS) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Getting around:
</P>
<P>
   Flights arrive at New Orleans International Airport, about 20
miles (or a 30-minute drive) from downtown. One-way cab fare to
downtown is $21 for one or two people; shuttle vans cost $10 per
person, one-way; the city bus costs $1.50 one way from the airport.
If you plan to stay mostly in the French Quarter, don't bother with
a rental car; parking is scarce and expensive, and you can walk or
take a cab to most tourist attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Staying there:
</P>
<P>
   The city has more than 30,000 hotel rooms, plus a growing number
of bed-and-breakfast inns. Expect to pay at least $100 a night for
a room in the French Quarter or in the neighboring Central Business
District or Garden District, though you may find specials or a
budget room for as low as $60, particularly during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   The newest options include:
</P>
<P>
   International House Hotel (221 Camp St.; (504) 553-9550;
www.ihhotel.com) has won plaudits from travel writers and design
editors since opening in late '98, and rightfully so. It blends New
Orleans style (a renovated 1906 Beaux Arts building that was the
city's first international trade center) with contemporary
furnishings. Large guest rooms are outfitted with down comforters
and high-thread-count sheets in cool shades of taupe and cream;
there are CD players, showers with dual shower heads and stocked
honor bars. The understated, candlelit Loa bar draws an attractive
crowd, mostly twentysomething to fortysomething. Doubles from $189.
</P>
<P>
   W French Quarter (316 Rue Chartres; (504) 581-1200;
www.whotels.com) took over the former Hotel de la Poste and its
quiet-but-central location on a good shopping street in the French
Quarter. Like all Ws, its rooms feature electronic goodies like CD
players, high-speed data ports and TVs hooked to high-speed
Internet access via an infrared keyboard. Homier comforts include
cotton bathrobes, Aveda toiletries and goose-down comforters on the
feather-mattress beds. Its house restaurant is Bacco, an Italian
eatery from the famous Brennan restaurant family. Doubles from
$179.
</P>
<P>
   Its sister hotel, the W New Orleans, (333 Poydras St.; (504)
525-9444; www.whotels.com) is a renovated Sheraton and also has all
the W goodies; it's close to the new Harrah's casino and a couple
of blocks from the French Quarter. Its house bar is Whiskey Blue, a
streamlined, dimly lit lounge filled with beautiful people, mostly
under 30, and owned by nightclub entrepreneur Rande Gerber, also
known as Cindy Crawford's husband. Doubles from $149.
</P>
<P>
   St. James Hotel (330 Magazine St.; (504) 539-9000) is a new
luxury boutique hotel in a restored building with a more
traditional New Orleans feel; there are rooftop terraces and rooms
featuring four-poster beds and marble baths, along with such modern
touches as data ports, two phone lines and mini-bars. Doubles from
$179.
</P>
<P>
   The Ritz-Carlton New Orleans (901 Canal St.; (504) 524-1331) is
slated to open July 31 in the former Maison Blanche department
store and the historic Kress Building. After $200 million in
renovations, the hotel will preserve the art nouveau style and
introduce a French-tinged decor in purple, gold and green. There
will also be a day spa and a creole/Continental restaurant,
Victor's, named for a restaurant that operated on the site in the
1830s. Special introductory rates through August, $175 double.
</P>
<P>
   What's new:
</P>
<P>
   Jazzland, a theme park with 30 rides, daily Mardi Gras parades
and Cajun and creole food, opens Saturday at the intersection of
Interstates 10 and 510. A special feature is the skycoaster, a kind
of simulated freefall in which riders are hoisted 170 feet into the
air, then pull a rip cord that swings them out over a lake. The
ride is an extra $25. General admission is $28.44, adults; $23.86,
children under 48 inches tall; free, children age 2 and under;
$14.22, guests over age 60. ( (504) 253-8000; www.jazzland2000.com)
</P>
<P>
   Harrah's opened its giant casino in October at 512 Canal St.,
within walking distance of the convention center and the French
Quarter. Decorated in an ornate New Orleans style, with fountains,
wrought-iron accents, Mardi Gras floats and plenty of twinkling
lights, the gambling halls contain 3,000 slot machines, costing
from a nickel to $500 a pull, and 120 table games. The casino
doesn't include a hotel, but there is a buffet and a small food
court serving Popeye's Chicken, po' boys and other regional dishes.
( (800) HARRAHS; www.harrahsneworleans.com)
</P>
<P>
   Storyville District (125 Bourbon St., (504) 410-1000) is a
year-old nightclub/restaurant complex that offers several stages
for live jazz and blues along with upscale cuisine; it's a joint
project of Jazz Fest founder George Wein and restaurateur Ralph
Brennan, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The National D-Day Museum opens June 6 in a renovated brewery at
945 Magazine St.; (877) 730-3329. (See accompanying article.)
</P>
<P>
   General information: New Orleans Metropolitan Convention and
Visitors Bureau, (800) 672-6124 or www.neworleanscvb.com.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patricia Rodriguez
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
