<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 18:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2407 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-$ADV1     05-11 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SECURITY-$ADV14-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BUSH PLAN ADDRESSES A `PHONY CRISIS,' ECONOMIST SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, May 14)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By DAN FREEDMAN  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ George W. Bush outlines his Social Security plan on
Monday against a backdrop of doomsday predictions that include a
survey showing more young people believe in UFOs than think the
government benefits will last until their retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Not so fast, says liberal economist Dean Baker, co-founder of
the Washington-based Center for Economic and Policy Research, and
co-author of a book called ``Social Security: The Phony Crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Social Security is not collapsing, he insists. And to the extent
that it may need propping up, growth levels even below those of
today's vibrant U.S. economy would be sufficient to keep it healthy
beyond 2050, he adds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The magnitude of the problem is very different from what 99
percent of the public understands it to be,'' Baker said in an
interview. If the public knew the system was sound for at least 37
years and that even in the worst-case scenario Social Security
could still pay 75 percent of benefits thereafter, ``I don't think
there would be serious debate'' on a major overhaul, Baker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush and many Democrats are taking no chances. The Texas
governor, in one of the biggest dice-tossing acts of his bid to
become president, will talk Monday about how he intends to deal
with the Social Security trust fund running out of money. Beyond
refusing to loan the system's revenues to other government
programs, Bush is calling for private investment accounts that put
a portion of payroll taxes into the stock and bond markets.
</P>
<P>
   Even before he details his plan, his Democratic opponent, Vice
President Al Gore, has lost no time in condemning it as ``risky''
and ``irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore would use the surplus in the Social Security trust fund _
about $2.2 trillion over 10 years _ to pay down the national debt.
Gore has said the billions of dollars in interest that would have
gone to service the debt would instead flow into the Social
Security trust fund, guaranteeing the system's financial health
through 2050.
</P>
<P>
   In Baker's view, they're both wrong. He says Bush's modified
privatization plan _ in which the government would guarantee
retirement income against precipitous dips in the market _ would be
``an elaborate way of having government invest in the stock
market.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore also is on the wrong track, Baker says, because his plan
would tie up trillions of dollars in a scheme to fix a system that
isn't broken. ``If we say you can't touch that money, we're
neglecting those needs we have now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The future of Social Security looks bleak because of some basic
demographic facts. The 65-year-old federal pay-as-you-go system
provides $32.5 billion in monthly benefits to 44.5 million retirees
and persons with disabilities. Money comes into the system from the
12.4 percent payroll tax paid by current employees.
</P>
<P>
   Although more money currently is flowing into Social Security
than is going out, that will change as the 77-million strong
baby-boomer born between 1946 and 1964 begin retiring _ some of
them early _ in 2008.
</P>
<P>
   With that many retirees supported by the 44-million ``Generation
X,'' born between 1965 and 1977, the trust fund will begin to drain
in 2023 and go empty on 2037.
</P>
<P>
   However, the system's annual trustees' report has moved the
drop-dead date forward in time for three years in a row, thanks to
a nearly full-employment economy with more workers paying Social
Security taxes. The date went from 2032 in 1998 to 2037 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Baker says, ``If we kept (the current annual economic growth
level of) about 4 percent out into the future, Social Security
would be fine forever.'' But neither Baker nor most economists
expect that.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, even with a modest growth rate of 2.5 percent annually,
Social Security would be in good shape through 2050, Baker says.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the drop-dead date might be, Social Security still
would have its payroll tax income and could pay 75 percent of
benefits. ``So even if we do absolutely nothing, there will always
will be a very large sum of money there.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker has many detractors.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Baker's) hypothesis that we might grow our way out of the
problem reminds me of what conservatives said about the deficit in
the 1980s,'' said Richard Thau, a privatization supporter who heads
Third Millennium, the organization that produced the 1994 survey
about UFOs and Social Security. ``It seems preposterous.''
</P>
<P>
   Thau notes that Social Security payments average $804 a month, a
subsistence retirement for the many low-income workers who depend
on it primarily. Setting up private accounts is an effort to ``grow
wealth'' for people who have none, Thau insists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of reason for personal accounts (is to tell
subsistence-level retirees), `You don't need to live on cat food.
We can elevate you to tuna fish,''' Thau said.
</P>
<P>
   Even economists who oppose privatization are not fully sold on
Baker's ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Aaron, senior economist at the Washington-based Brookings
Institution, agrees that ``there is no crisis'' in Social
Seckurity. But he says political leaders would be shirking their
duty if they ignored the projections of the system's looming
insolvency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ought to move ahead carefully and gradually,'' Aaron said.
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Freedman can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address dan(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
