u s BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT     05-11 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: RETIRED MAJOR LEAGUERS BEING CONSIDERED FOR OLYMPIC
TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   They may call themselves retired, but baseball players like to
think they could roll out of bed on Christmas Day and whack a
curveball, or throw one.
</P>
<P>
   Now a few retired players are being cajoled by seductive
whisperings of Olympic gold medals and one more road trip to beat
all road trips. The voice belongs to Bob Watson, who was general
manager of the Yankees when they won the so-called World Series in
1996. Watson has now moved on to truly global events, serving as
co-chairman of the selection committee for the U.S. baseball team
at the Summer Games in Sydney, Australia, in September.
</P>
<P>
   He tosses out a few names like Tim Raines, Chili Davis, Jimmy
Key, Terry Steinbach, Pat Kelly, Orestes Destrade, all currently
retired.
</P>
<P>
   He needs a talent pool because the Olympics, which opened for
the Jordans and Everts and Gretzkys in the past decade, are now
open to baseball professionals.
</P>
<P>
   The South Koreans are closing down their pro league in September
to send their very best, the Japanese leagues are sending a
legitimate all-star team, and the Cubans are sending their
state-supported amateurs who dominate world tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our college guys cannot compete with them,'' Watson said,
correctly.
</P>
<P>
   There is a major league cast to the manager, a chap named
Lasorda, but Major League Baseball is not about to do what the NHL
did in 1998 and will do again in 2002: shut down for a few weeks
and let its players represent their countries.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with this hard line, Dave Nilsson, the Australian catcher,
left the Milwaukee Brewers to play in Japan this season, in order
to represent his own country this September.
</P>
<P>
   Major League Baseball may grant a furlough to a few
professionals buried down deep on some 40-man roster, but Watson is
forced to seek talent that may currently be changing diapers,
playing golf and clipping coupons. ``The big question is, you shut
down mentally when you stop playing,'' said Watson, who retired in
1984, after 19 years. ``You go, `Wheeeew.' You don't worry about
doing it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Watson understands the skill and confidence that reside
in retired players. He guaranteed that Manny Mota, the Dodgers'
62-year-old coach, could still hit, although he does not plan to
recruit Mota, who is of Dominican ancestry, at any rate.
</P>
<P>
   Watson is going after more recent players, including Pat Kelly,
once a Yankees second baseman, who retired this spring after his
shoulder did not recover from surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly was already enthused about the Summer Games because his
wife is from Adelaide, and they plan to raise their family in
Australia. He recently did commentary for a television channel in
Australia, covering the Intercontinental Cup, baseball's major
amateur tournament, and while in Sydney, he sneaked into the
Olympic Stadium to look around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable stadium,'' he said. ``The games are going to be
so great.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he can dream about marching in the opening parade, and
representing his own country in his wife's homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd help out in any capacity _ coach, scout, hit fly balls,''
he said. ``But if I can play, that would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson is urging players to start looking for a semipro team in
their area, so he can send around a scout to see if their legs and
waistlines and arms are still acceptable. He will assemble a large
squad by early July, and then announce a team of 24 regulars and
six alternates by Aug. 23.
</P>
<P>
   He understands he is tinkering with the pride of major leaguers,
but said: ``I can talk to them a whole lot easier than a college
coach can. I coached in the World Series, I was general manager in
the World Series. I can call somebody up and say, `Hey, Rock.'''
</P>
<P>
   He would love to use Raines, the highly popular 40-year-old who
is coping with lupus and could not quite make it back with the
Yankees this spring although he was in good physical shape.
</P>
<P>
   Watson also heard from Orestes Destrade, a Cuban-born slugger
who had nine admirable seasons in Japan and finished up with
Florida in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Chili Davis, a mature presence with the Yankees his final two
years, has been enjoying not having people tell him what to do
after 20 years of following orders. Of all people, Davis has the
imagination to be intrigued, the way Watson is.
</P>
<P>
   As a player, Watson never imagined himself walking in the
opening ceremonies but now he says: ``All I want is on Sept. 27 to
hear the national anthem playing for the gold-medal ceremony.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson sells the image of the parade to his major league
colleagues. He counts on their inner voice, the one that says they
can still play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
