<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2410 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MESSAGE-BOTTLE-BOS &LR;      05-11 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MESSAGE-BOTTLE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IRISHMAN'S FIND ENDS 21-YEAR ODDYSEY OF BOTTLE WITH MESSAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANNA WEISS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a storybook idea, culled from books and beachcombing days
and idyllic Nantucket summers. In early September of 1979, Amy
Turano and Valerie Wozniak _ 13-year-old friends who had read about
messages in bottles _ decided they wanted to send one of their own.
</P>
<P>
   They threw a bottle in the surf, but it kept rolling back
ashore. So Amy's father suggested they drop it, instead, from the
ferry to Hyannis, Mass., deep into Nantucket Sound.
</P>
<P>
   This one came back, too. Twenty-one years later.
</P>
<P>
   The green wine bottle, which the girls had filled with notes and
sealed with wax, rolled onto the beach of Derrymore, Ireland, this
March, tossed by currents that could have carried it from Britain
to the Equator and back. It was sitting on the high-tide mark,
covered with kelp and shells. When Michael Wall first saw it, he
walked right by.
</P>
<P>
   Wall, 48, an avid fisherman with four children and four dogs,
works in a cattle feed mill nearby. The beach is his regular haunt,
and bottles are commonplace. But when he walked by this one again,
with his golden retriever, he noticed paper inside. He picked it up
and took it home.
</P>
<P>
   By the time his wife and daughter came in, he had broken the
bottle _ the only way he could get it open. He found a letter
inside, with a date and time: 1 p.m., September 2, 1979. And a
request: please fill out an accompanying note and mail it to one of
the girls. There were two addresses listed, both in Colchester,
Conn.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do not send the note back,'' the message went on,
``just put these papers back in the bottle and throw it in the
ocean. Thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Wall was 27, living in the same town, working at the
same mill. Valerie Wozniak and Amy Turano were Connecticut girls on
the brink of adolescence. Those days, the Turanos rented a cottage
on Nantucket Island for couple of weeks each summer, and allowed
their son and daughter to invite friends along.
</P>
<P>
   That year, the kids had read a story about a boy who sent a
message in a bottle and made a new friend, said Amy Turano _ now
Amy Thurber. They were inspired to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Andrew Turano, a pediatrician with a logical mind,
didn't have much hope for the plan. ``Children have imaginations
and they read stories,'' he said. ``You know how skeptical parents
are.''
</P>
<P>
   So he told them their odds of success were low, but he helped
them, anyway, sealing the bottle and selecting the drop-off point,
midway between Nantucket and Hyannis. Based on his knowledge of
currents, he said, ``I figured if it ever landed anywhere, it would
land on the British Isles.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, the girls leaned over the ferry railing on a
cloudy day and watched the bottle disappear. They talked about it
for a year or two, Thurber said, but ``it definitely was out of my
mind for a very long time.'' In the intervening years, the girls
graduated from high school together and slowly drifted apart.
</P>
<P>
   Thurber went to the Rhode Island School of Design, married,
divorced, and married again. She is now 34, a graphic designer and
illustrator, living in South Dartmouth, Mass. with her husband and
three-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   The girls _ now women _ haven't spoken in years, though their
parents still live in the same neighborhood in Colchester, half a
mile apart.
</P>
<P>
   It was to those parents' homes that Wall sent his response,
along with a copy of his local newspaper, which had written a story
about his remarkable find.
</P>
<P>
   Another local man recently found a message in a bottle some ten
miles off, Wall said in a telephone interview from his home
Thursday, but it had only been in the water for a year or two. This
one was special _ ``a long journey, you know,'' he said.
``Everybody's been asking me since.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, his newfound friends across the Atlantic hope he'll come to
the United States someday; Thurber would like to invite him
fishing. She also wants to take her son, Benjamin, to Nantucket,
where she hopes he'll pass the days as she did: catching firefiles,
feeding birds, walking the beach, making summer wishes.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, she said, her family isn't finished with its ocean
dreams. Her brother Paul, now 31, dropped a bottle of his own on
the same September day, 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He's still waiting to hear where it lands.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1903EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
