<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0306 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2412 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-CARDINAL-EGAN-BOS &LR;      05-11 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARDINAL-EGAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VATICAN LOYALIST TO SUCCEED N.Y. CARDINAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Egan is becoming an archbishop, not a cardinal.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bishop Edward M. Egan, a staunch Vatican loyalist credited with
bettering the schools, finances, and recruitment of priests in
Bridgeport, Conn., was tapped Thursday by Pope John Paul II to
replace the late Cardinal John O'Connor in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, 68, will be installed as the ninth archbishop of New York
on June 19, moving from a relatively obscure diocese with 360,000
Catholics in 88 parishes to the nation's most visible Catholic see,
with 2.4 million Catholics in 413 parishes.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's appointment was one of the worst-kept secrets in recent
Vatican history _ within hours of O'Connor's death May 3 priests in
Boston were hearing from their New York colleagues that Egan was
the pope's choice. The pope made the announcement less than 60
hours after O'Connor's burial Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference at Cathedral High School on Manhattan's
East Side, Egan appeared jovial, bantering with reporters. He
referred to a New York Times religion reporter as ``young lady,''
twice told Hispanic reporters ``I love your music,'' and joked
about the high salary of NBC employees.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black cassock and a pectoral cross, Egan answered
questions in English and Italian, made comments in Spanish, smiled
as he fielded potentially prickly questions about Hillary Rodham
Clinton and Rudolph Giuliani, enthusiastically affirmed his
opposition to abortion and birth-control for teenagers, and ducked
a question about gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you I know no place in the world that is quicker to
accept someone who wants to be a New Yorker,'' he said. ``And I
want to be a New Yorker.'' He said his first goal would be to get
to know priests of New York, saying that success is achieved in
parishes.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, Egan prayed and greeted worshipers at St.
Patrick's Cathedral, the seat of the archdiocese of New York.
</P>
<P>
   Egan seems to have the perfect resume for New York. He became
close to Pope John Paul II during 22 years as a canon lawyer and
judge at the Vatican, he got to know New York as an auxiliary
bishop there in the 1980s, and he has run a diocese since 1988.
</P>
<P>
   In Bridgeport, Egan is credited with saving a struggling
Catholic school system by replacing the parish-based system with
regional schools.
</P>
<P>
   Catholics in Bridgeport say Egan is charismatic in person and
dynamic at the pulpit. He is also a talented pianist.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's perfect for that job because he knows how to reach out
and talk to people and put them at ease,'' said Ed Byrne, 17, who
worked with Egan as an altar boy. ``He also has a really good sense
of humor. He's going to be missed (in Bridgeport), but I think they
really need someone like him in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony J. Cernera, president of Sacred Heart University in
Fairfield, Conn., said Egan is a passionate intellectual,
comfortable discussing quantum physics as well as theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very bright man,'' Cernera said. ``The issues in New
York are tough issues, but he's a tough guy. He'll work hard to
understand the issues and put together a game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Even before last week's speculation, Egan was seen as an
up-and-comer in the church hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this would come sooner or later, because he's really
overqualifed for here,'' said the Rev. Matthew Bernelli of St.
Mary's in Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's sharpest critics are lawyers representing 21 people who
claim they were victims of sexual abuse by priests employed by the
diocese of Bridgeport. All but one of the instances of alleged
abuse took place before Egan arrived in Bridgeport _ some of the
allegations are 30 years old _ but the allegations have been
litigated on his watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have offered his support, his apology, an
investigation, and counseling to the victims, and he has not done
any of that,'' said Jason E. Tremont, a lawyer representing the
alleged victims. ``Instead, the tactic has been to delay the
proceedings, to prevent any information from becoming public, and
we believe there's been a coverup _ that he had knowledge of sexual
abusers and let them continue on as active priests, including
having contact with other children.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan's spokesman, Tom Drohan, rejected the complaint.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you are dealing with here are the representations of
plaintiffs' counsel that is distorted, unfair to the facts, and
transparent in that...they are just trying to try their cases in
the paper,'' Drohan said. ``Now the facts: The bishop has condemned
this kind of behavior, or alleged behavior, on a number of
occasions, and these lawyers know it and so does the Connecticut
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Drohan said priests accused of sexual abuse have been
transferred to other parishes only after psychiatric evaluation and
``doctors told us it would be appropriate to put them back in an
area where they can practice their ministry.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Catholics hoping for changes in church policies on
the ordination of women, homosexuality, and other controversial
issues saw little reason for encouragement in Egan's selection.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is seen as a papal loyalist, and our general sense has been
that his position and statements on homosexuality have emphasized
the immorality of genital activity,'' said Marianne T. Duddy,
executive director of Dignity/USA, an organization of gay
Catholics. ``We had begun a dialogue with Cardinal O'Connor in the
last couple years and found it productive, and we would hope that
Bishop Egan would be open to the same kind of dialogue.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Bernard F. Law of Boston declined to be interviewed,
but issued a statement congratulating Egan, saying he ``has been a
good shepherd and gentle father of the flock in Bridgeport. I know
that he will bring those same fine priestly and episcopal qualities
to the archdiocese of New York.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Globe staff writer Fred Kaplan contributed from New York;
correspondent Richard Weizel contributed from Bridgeport.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
