u i BC-RUSSIA-PRESS-BOS &LR;      05-11 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIAN PRESS FREEDOM WEAKENS AMID GOVERNMENT PRESSURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV AND BRIAN WHITMORE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In what looked to many like a crackdown on freedom of
the press, heavily armed and masked security forces Thursday raided
the offices of a prominent Russian media company that has been
critical of Russia's newly sworn-in president, Vladimir V. Putin.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of investigators and tax police backed by S.W.A.T. units
broke down doors and forced their way into the three central Moscow
offices of Media-most, which owns a national television network as
well as a radio station, a newspaper, and two magazines. The agents
detained and interrogated company employees and spent 12 hours
searching the premises as taciturn masked men wearing flak jackets
and brandishing submachine guns guarded the entrances outside.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of Media-most charged the raid was designed to stop
criticism of the government and discourage journalists from probing
alleged Kremlin corruption. Russian politicians across the spectrum
from Communists to liberals joined Media-most executives in
condemning the raids as an ominous sign for press freedoms, coming
as it did just four days after Putin was inaugurated.
</P>
<P>
   The security agents and investigators who took part in the raids
refused to identify themselves or talk to journalists. Phones
inside the building were cut off and mobile phones confiscated.
Later in the day, the employees were allowed to go home, and late
Thursday evening, masked men carried boxes, apparently containing
confiscated materials, out of the building and putting them in a
truck.
</P>
<P>
   While the actual motivation for the raids remained the subject
of speculation, they reinforced the notion that due process in
Russia is subject to whims of political power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is insulting that a few days after a new president of
Russia took office, a president with whom many people in Russia
link a rebirth of the country, it seems as if everything is going
backwards,'' Media-most Chairman Vladimir Gusinsky told his
flagship television station, NTV.
</P>
<P>
   Putin, who was meeting CNN founder Ted Turner in the Kremlin as
the raids took place Thursday morning, did not comment on the
events at Media-most. Some analysts suggested that the true motive
for the raids was a vicious behind-the-scenes battle for influence
among Kremlin insiders, including a powerful coterie associated
with financier and media baron Boris Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   One Putin administration official suggested that the president
himself had been taken by suprise, which appeared to have been
sanctioned by Russia's acting prosecutor, Vladimir Ustinov, and the
Kremlin's chief of administration, Alexander Voloshin, both of whom
are considered Berezovsky allies.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday evening, a limousine bearing the presidential standard
and accompanied by a heavy security detail entered the grounds of
the Kremlin hospital where Putin's predecessor, Boris N. Yeltsin,
spent much of his second term. But there was no indication from the
Kremlin whether Putin had been hospitalized.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Putin's promises to uphold democratic freedoms, the
raids were likely to fuel concerns that the former career KGB
officer could reverse the country's newly won rights. A document
leaked to the press last week outlined plans to crack down on
political opponents using the Federal Security Service, the
domestic successor of the former Soviet secret police, which is
known in Russia as the FSB.
</P>
<P>
   Chief FSB spokesman Alexander Zdanovich denied any political
motivation for the raids, saying they were the result of a criminal
investigation into whether employees with Media-most's security
department had disclosed bank secrets and violated privacy laws.
</P>
<P>
   Zdanovich said the company's security agents had illegally
listened in on phone calls and conversations, including those of
Media-most's journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Human rights observers' hair would stand on end if they found
out someone else was doing this,'' Zdanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, had a different interpretation. He said Berezovsky had
long wanted to settle old scores with his rival Gusinsky, and at
the same time wanted to put pressure on Putin to name Berezovsky's
allies to his new government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putin was set up,'' he said. ``If he says he didn't know this
was going to happen, then what kind of president does that make
him? But if he goes along with it, everyone will know he is a
puppet. . . . And Putin himself has long wanted to get rid of
Media-most. So how can he go against this?''
</P>
<P>
   Newscasters at NTV speculated on air that the search may have
been triggered by a recent article in the company's newspaper,
Segodnya, that alleged wrongdoing by a high-ranking official in the
FSB. Segodnya editor Mikhail Berger said in an interview on the
station that the official, deputy FSB director Yury Zaovstrovtsev,
had taken part in the raids.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motivation, the raids managed to unite Russia's
usually divisive political factions. Communist leader Gennady
Zyuganov and prominent liberal Sergei Kiriyenko both denounced the
use of force, while former Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev
criticized what he called a ``provocation against the independent
media.''
</P>
<P>
   In reality, freedom of the press in Russia is still on shaky
ground. Media-most's journalists have never been free to report
whatever they want; Gusinsky, like the heads of most Russian media
companies, influences coverage in accordance with his own political
agenda. In 1996, he united with Berezovsky to publicly back
Yeltsin's reelection bid, and some of his media outlets responded
with unabashedly pro-Kremlin coverage of the election.
</P>
<P>
   But of late, Gusinsky has fallen out with the Kremlin.
</P>
<P>
   In December's parliamentary elections, NTV television supported
a political party that was openly hostile to the Kremlin. And in
contrast to Russia's state-controlled television channels, NTV
reported critically on Putin's presidential campaign, while giving
positive coverage to opposition candidates like liberal economist
Grigory Yavlinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Media-most publications have also been critical of the war in
Chechnya. Some media observers here say the Kremlin has waged a
campaign to discredit coverage that emphasizes the negative aspects
of Russia's efforts to take control of Chechnya, including
arresting journalists and harassing publications that veer from the
official line.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin earlier attempted to pressure Media-most by calling
in loans the company had taken from politically-connected banks and
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gusinsky tried to sell a bank he founded, called
most-Bank, in order to pay off a $211.6 million to Russia's natural
gas monopoly Gazprom. Media-most officials said that the deal, to
sell most-Bank to the state-owned Vneshtorgbank, was called off
after Voloshin intervened.
</P>
<P>
   About the only politician who applauded the raids was flamboyant
ultranationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky, who welcomed it as a sign
that the secret services are taking charge.
</P>
<P>
   ``The KGB has come to power, and Russia needs it,'' Zhirinovsky
said. ``Searches and arrests will happen almost on a daily basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 1928EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
