<HEADER>
A2433 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-ART-NYT     05-11 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UNREST-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO CITY MOURNS SLAIN GUERRILLA LEADER
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT22, 23 have been sent to NYT photo clients.
Graphic has been sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can
make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LANDOVICA, Kosovo _ Tens of thousands of people stopped work on
Thursday to mourn a former commander of the Kosovo Liberation Army
who was killed at his home on Tuesday. His family and fellow
commanders denounced the slaying as an attack on Kosovo's stability
and its very future.
</P>
<P>
   The former commander, Ekrem Rexha, who was known as Commander
Drini, received a military funeral on Thursday, with uniformed
soldiers laying wreaths and offering a gun salute at his grave. In
his hometown of Prizren, businesses closed as thousands of people
filed past his coffin in the biggest display of public solidarity
seen since the end of Kosovo's war.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a pain for all of the city of Prizren, a pain that all
of Kosovo feels,'' Gen. Agim Ceku, former commander of the Kosovo
Liberation Army and and now chief of its civilian successor, the
Kosovo Protection Corps, said in a speech at the graveside. ``To
kill a legendary commander on his doorstep, is not only a crime
against a hero, but against all the people who have already
sacrificed so much.''
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand people gathered on a hillside in Landovica,
several miles outside Prizren to bury Drini among other soldiers of
the Kosovo Liberation Army. Red flags of Albania, bearing the black
eagle, flew at half staff as former soldiers and villagers stood on
top of trucks to catch a glimpse of the proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who did this, did it against the KLA, against
freedom and against the future of Kosovo,'' Ceku said. Also present
was a former commander turned politician, Ramush Haradinaj, who was
a friend of Drini and had reportedly approached him to join his
newly formed coalition of political parties. Clearly upset,
Haradinaj declined to comment on the slaying, and drove away, alone
but for his bodyguards.
</P>
<P>
   Drini's death brings to 23 the number of Kosovo Liberation Army
members killed since the end of the war in June. The deaths have
come as a result of internal score-settling, business disagreements
or, increasingly, political rivalry. The grass-roots guerrilla
movement always had a varied following, but the shootouts between
former comrades-in-arms has shocked many people in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of its concern, the U.N. mission in Kosovo ordered
some 30 police officers to investigate. But Drini's family doubts
that the killer or killers will be found.
</P>
<P>
   Without naming anyone in particular, Ceku said opponents of a
liberal, stable and prosperous Kosovo were behind the killing, and
he implied that those who were against Kosovo Albanians' bid for
independence were involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a vision of what should be done after the war,'' he
said. ``In Kosovo there are still forces that are working against
Kosovo's freedom. They could not stop the freedom for which Drini
fought, now they are trying to stop the development.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of Kosovo cannot be built on murders and an absence
of security. Nobody is going to allow this, because it is against
the aspirations of our war, the ideal and the efforts Drini made.''
</P>
<P>
   Drini's family was more direct. They had received threats
recently, his brother, Nazim Rexha, said. He said he was sure that
the killing was not personal or business-related, but a political
attack on the moderate values of the former commander.
</P>
<P>
   Just back from seven years working in England, Rexha spoke more
freely than his relatives. ``They were intimidated lately,'' he
said of his family. ``I do not know by whom, but probably by people
who do not want to see a democratic state being formed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Drini was only guilty of one thing, of being clever,'' he
said. ``In Kosovo apparently we are only taught to be led and not
to lead. It seems somebody minds someone who can lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Drini's potential as a political leader may have been his
downfall. At 38, he was a professional soldier and former officer
of the Communist-era Yugoslav Army, and he taught at a military
college in Sarajevo until 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He joined the Kosovo Liberation Army soon after the conflict
began in 1998 and was rapidly made commander of the Pashtrik
region, one of seven regional zones of the guerrilla group's war
against the Serbian military and police forces. He was promoted to
its general staff during the intense fighting of the three months
of the NATO bombing campaign, and was known for his leadership and
organizational ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He and Ceku and a few others helped professionalize the
general staff during a critical time,'' a Western diplomat who knew
Drini said. ``They brought a lot of stability to the general staff
when the KLA was close to falling apart in the first weeks when
they were really being pounded. I think he provided some real
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   He spoke seven languages and was widely liked and respected by
military and U.N. officials. After the end of the war in June, he
left the guerrilla group and joined the local administration in
Prizren as an environment and safety officer.
</P>
<P>
   He was killed at 8:15 a.m. on Tuesday as he left for work. As he
bent to change a flat tire, a gunman shot him eight times in the
body and once, at close range, in the head. As he fell to the
street, dropping his keys, his wife, who is the mother of his
10-month-old baby, and seven-months pregnant with their second
child, rushed from the house to his side, according to a witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have killed my husband,'' she screamed to her neighbor,
who recounted the moments to a reporter. ``She kept screaming `Wake
up, wake up, we have a son and another on the way.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Since the shooting, violence has flared in the area. An American
peacekeeping soldier was wounded and required stitches after Serbs
attacked military policemen investigating an explosion in the
village of Vrbovac in southern Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
