r e BC-BOOK-NOTES11-COX     05-11 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES11-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sex-shifted viewpoint pays off
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Walter Sorrells' gender change has really paid off. After years
of attempting to sell his male-oriented mysteries, Sorrells created
a female sleuth _ Sunny Childs _ and began writing under the
pseudonym Ruth Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   The series became a hit, and last week the Atlanta writer was
honored by his colleagues with the Edgar Award for Best Paperback
Original for ``Fulton County Blues'' (Berkley, $5.99). In addition,
he has been nominated for a Shamus Award, given by the Private Eye
Writers of America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning the Edgar for best paperback is kind of like being
named Most Valuable Player in the minor leagues,'' he said. ``It
means you have a good chance at making it in the big leagues.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in Atlanta, ``Fulton County Blues'' follows Sunny on an
investigation into the death of her late father's friend, a Vietnam
War veteran. Along the way she uncovers clues that indicate her
father may not have been the hero she thought he was.
</P>
<P>
   Writing from the perspective of a woman has been fun, Sorrells
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I've found is that the worst thing I can do as a writer
is to write about a 38-year-old white guy from Atlanta. I think I'm
a simple person, and simple people are not interesting to write
about.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sorrells' next book, due out in September, Sunny Childs will
return to investigate the murder of a Shania Twain-type country
music singer in Floyd County.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrells is trying to sell another novel written under his own
name, but he plans to keep writing the Sunny Childs series and to
learn as much as he can about being a woman.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use my wife to check things sometimes, but not that much.
She did catch a big bra-size gaffe that I made. I didn't know my
bra sizes and I had someone wearing a 33B. Apparently they only
have even numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Good reviews: Not only has British author Nick Hornby gotten
good reviews for his novel ``High Fidelity,'' but he's also landed
a job with The New Yorker as a pop music critic.
</P>
<P>
   New Yorker editor David Remnick hired Hornby after seeing his
review of Steely Dan's ``Two Against Nature'' album. Hornby's first
regular review _ of Aimee Mann's ``Bachelor No. 2'' _ will appear
next Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The New Yorker had been without a pop music critic since
Elizabeth Wurtzel left to write her memoir, ``Prozac Nation.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rewarding Toni: You would think that Oprah Winfrey would
spread some of her literary influence around to writers who could
use a break. But her latest choice for her TV book club selection
is ``The Bluest Eye'' by Toni Morrison. This is the third time the
Nobel Prize winner's books have been spotlighted. The first two
were ``Paradise'' and ``Song of Solomon.'' Knopf has already gone
to press with 175,000 additional hardback copies, and Plume is
printing another 575,000 paperbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
