<HEADER>
A2437 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CD-PRICE12-COX     05-11 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CD-PRICE12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Feds say illegal deal has boosted prices, especially for hot
discs
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The feds say compact disc prices may drop ``significantly'' by
the end of the year as the result of an anti-trust settlement with
major record distributors.
</P>
<P>
   But major retailers were in no-comment mode Thursday. So it was
unclear just how much money CD buyers stand to save.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Trade Commission said music companies had forced
retailers into an illegal arrangement that cost CD buyers an
estimated $480 million between 1997 and 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Under the arrangement, retailers who participated in
co-operative advertising with distributors had to keep their prices
above certain specified levels. They were penalized by music
distributors if they sold their discs too cheaply.
</P>
<P>
   Distributors initiated the arrangement to help music retailers
who were being undercut by discount stores and electronics chains,
such as Target, Circuit City and Best Buy.
</P>
<P>
   Later, with discounters reined in, distributors themselves were
able to raise their wholesale prices, the FTC charged.
</P>
<P>
   From 1997 to '99, the average price for advertised CDs rose $3,
according to FTC spokesman Eric London.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't say that price increase was all related to the
illegal marketing program,'' said London, ``or how much it will
lower prices, or when. But we hope there will be some kind of
significant drop.''
</P>
<P>
   By one measure, the settlement's effect seems slight. The $480
million overcharge amounts to just 19 cents per CD, for all the
discs shipped over the past three years. But the FTC's action
mostly affects highly advertised new releases, which could fall by
much more than 19 cents.
</P>
<P>
   In the music retail business, prices are as unpredictable as the
next hot CD. Prices range widely from artist to artist, CD to CD,
store to store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our prices range from $14.98 to $18.98,'' said Richard
Kuykendall, manager of Wuxtry, an independent music store in
Decatur, ``but you never know.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Kuykendall said after Santana's album
``Supernatural'' became a hit last year, Arista raised its
suggested retail price.
</P>
<P>
   The FTC agreement is with the five largest music companies,
which distribute 85 percent of the CDs in the United States: Time
Warner, Sony, Universal, EMI and Bertelsmann.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FTC, the agreement will not affect on-line CD
sellers such as Amazon.com and cdnow.com, because they do not take
part in co-op advertising. But an executive with Amazon.com told
the The Wall Street Journal that the illegal arrangement had in
fact forced the on-line retailer to raise some prices.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement's demise, said Amazon's Jennifer Cast, ``gives
us additional freedom to price what we think is appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffry Scott writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
