<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Southern happenings
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Dalton, Ga. _ Prater's Mill Country Fair showcases the
cultural history of southern Appalachia on Saturday and Sunday.
Mountain music, Southern foods, living history exhibits and
handmade arts and crafts by 185 regional artists. Also, canoeing on
Coahulla Creek and visits to the 1850s gristmill. 706-694-6455;
pratersmill.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Brunswick, Ga. _ Harborfest on Saturday and Sunday features
powerboat and personal water craft racing, arts and crafts, food,
entertainment and 62nd Blessing of the Fleet. 912-262-6934.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Asheville, N.C. _ Fiber Day is Saturday at the Folk Art
Center, where fiber artists from the Southern Highland Craft Guild
and other area guilds provide demonstrations of carding, spinning,
weaving, dyeing, basketry and papermaking. Also, sheep-shearing
demonstrations and a fashion show of handmade wearables.
828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Owensboro, Ky. _ The International Bar-B-Que Festival on
Friday and Saturday features cooking teams that produce 10 tons of
mutton, 5,000 chickens and 1,500 gallons of burgoo. 1-800-489-1131.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Carrollton, Ky. _ Kentucky Scottish Weekend, Friday through
Sunday, features performers from Scotland, piping, drumming,
athletic events, ``Wee Scots Day'' and cultural and historical
seminars. 513-574-2969.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Memphis _ Memphis in May International Festival is under way
with a salute to India and a monthlong agenda of activities that
continue with International Week (through Sunday), World
Championship Barbecue Cooking Contest (May 18-20) and the Great
Southern Food Festival featuring the Sunset Symphony (May 27-28).
901-525-4611, www.memphisinmay.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Natchez, Miss. _ Natchez Opera Festival through May 27
features professional opera stars appearing in seven productions,
including the ``Barber of Seville,'' ``Man of La Mancha,'' ``La
Traviata'' and the Broadway comedy ``I Do, I Do.'' 1-800-647-6724.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lake Charles, La. _ Contraband Days through Sunday revives the
legend of French pirate Jean Lafitte burying his treasure along the
lake's shores. Features a pirate invasion, parades, crawfish eating
contests and music. 337-436-5508, www.contraband.usunwired.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta _ ``Experience Aloha! Hawaii on Tour,'' a free
multimedia presentation from the Hawaii Visitors and Convention
Bureau, will be at Perimeter Mall on May 19-21. Live island
entertainment, cultural and cooking demonstrations and interactive
displays are ongoing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tidewater, Va. _ The fourth annual Virginia Waterfront
International Arts Festival runs through May 21 at venues from
Williamsburg to Virginia Beach. 757-664-6490,
www.virginiaartsfest.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pensacola, Fla. _ Florida Springfest on May 19-21 features
Foreigner, John Hiatt, Loverboy, Martha Reeves and the Vandellas,
Fliter, Blue Oyster Cult, Lonestar, Chuck Berry, the Roger McGuinn
Band and Chubby Carrier and the Bayou Swamp Band. 850-469-1069,
www.springfest.net.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gadsden, Ala. _ The Gadsden Area Riverfest Festival on May
19-20 features the Beach Boys and the Gap Band on Friday, and John
Michael Montgomery and Trisha Yearwood on Saturday. 1-800-320-1692.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Rome, Ga. _ Mayfest on the Rivers on May 20 celebrates the
city's three rivers with free riverboat rides on a 48-passenger
excursion boat, the Corrugated Mad River run, and a concert
featuring Percy Sledge and Three Dog Night. 706-295-5576,
www.romegeorgia.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wilmington, N.C. _ The Wilmington Greek Festival on May 19-21
features Greek cuisine and pastries, cooking demonstrations, church
tours. 910-392-4444.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Thomasville, Ga. _ The Georgia Watercolor Society XXI National
Exhibition features more than 100 paintings by top U.S.
watercolorists through May 21. 912-226-0588.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Augusta, Ga. _ Morris Museum of Art presents ``Art and Nature:
The Hudson River School'' through June 4. The paintings are from
the Albany Institute of History and Art in Albany, N.Y.
706-724-7501, www.themorris.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Columbus, Ga. _ The Columbus Museum presents ``Janet Fish:
Recent Paintings,'' on view through June 18. 706-649-0713.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Orlando _ The Orlando Museum of Art presents
``Twentieth-Century Still-Life Paintings From the Phillips
Collection,'' through May 21. 407-896-4231 or www.omart.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Petersburg , Fla. _ ``John F. Kennedy: The Exhibition''
features the largest private collection of Kennedy artifacts in the
world. 1-877-535-7469, www.floridamuseum.org.
</P>
<P>
   _Paula Crouch Thrasher
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
