<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0326 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2439 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t BC-GETAWAY10-COX     05-11 1377
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GETAWAY10-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida park expands its musical direction
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIVE OAK, Fla. _ In the beginning, there was bluegrass.
</P>
<P>
   When Bill and Jean Cornett of Kentucky first opened Spirit of
the Suwannee Music Park here in 1985, they had plenty of pickin'
and grinnin' in mind. Longtime bluegrass fans and founders of the
27-year-old Festival of the Bluegrass in Lexington, the Cornetts
wanted a year-round, pastoral home for their musical passions.
</P>
<P>
   They found it on this oak-shaded parcel of land on the banks of
the Suwannee River. The Cornetts discovered the 600-acre park, then
an abandoned campground, in the early 1980s on one of their yearly
trips south during the cold-weather months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like everybody else north of Atlanta _ we have to go to
Florida in the winter,'' Jean quips.
</P>
<P>
   One look at the grassy central meadow (perfect for staging
concerts), the towering, moss-draped live oaks and the
slow-as-molasses flow of the Suwannee, and they were hooked. ``I
believe Mother Nature is a powerful force, and I could feel it all
around me,'' Jean, 71, remembers. She coined the park's motto,
``Music lives here,'' on that visit.
</P>
<P>
   That music, and much more, will certainly live over Memorial
Day, when the park hosts a family-oriented blowout with s'more
roasting, storytelling, sing-alongs and face-painting. Many
visitors will divide their time between park activities and the
Florida Folk Festival in nearby White Springs.
</P>
<P>
   Others will head straight for the pickin' sheds.
</P>
<P>
   In these rustic pavilions, dozens, sometimes hundreds, of
amateur players gather for impromptu jams. Fueled by hot bluegrass
licks, down-home camaraderie and, occasionally, beer, these jams
are a vital part of the music culture that has taken root here.
</P>
<P>
   In the early days, the Cornetts lured Lexington festivalgoers
with two nights of free camping. Word spread among bluegrass fans,
and soon kindred spirits were pouring in from all over the United
States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Today, legions of the bluegrass faithful gather for festivals _
the Suwannee Springfest in March and the smaller Spring Bluegrass
Festival in April drew 15,000 and 3,000. And plenty of them bring
their own instruments along.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is get people in here, and there'll be
pickin','' says the Cornetts' 38-year-old son, James, who took over
park operations three years ago. He estimates that, on festival
weekends, as many as 50 percent of the park's guests are musicians.
</P>
<P>
   And you don't have to pick a banjo or bow a fiddle, either. ``It
doesn't matter if you play the tuba, go ahead and bring it,'' says
Charley Chase, a bluegrass fan from Michigan. Chase, 68, owns one
of the park's 12 permanent cabins _ his is the one embossed on the
front with a fiddle and mandolin. Chase is one of the few regulars
who doesn't play an instrument, but he does sell CDs by Bill
Monroe, Flatt &AMP; Scruggs, the Carter Family and others at festivals.
</P>
<P>
   Lately, however, the rural rhythms heard here have been
accompanied by a chorus of new sounds.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade, the park has blossomed into a multiuse
campground that hosts events of all stripes, from blues concerts
(B.B. King played last fall) to hot-air balloon races, a
Renaissance festival, auto shows and hippie-rock weekends.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with Memorial Day weekend, this summer promises to be
the park's busiest yet. There's a gospel jubilee in June, a huge
garage sale in August, fireworks celebrations on July Fourth and
Labor Day and another bluegrass festival in late September. And
James Cornett says he's hoping to bring the jam-rock showcase
Furthur Festival here in early September.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the everyday attractions. A 30-mile web of sandy
horse trails snakes through the dense forest that lines the
Suwannee; bring your own steed or rent one at the park's stable,
which also offers riding lessons. A miniature golf course set back
in the trees draws putters of all ages, and there's a canoe rental
outpost for folks who want to get out on the river.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of campsites are scattered throughout, from
roughing-it plots to full-service RV sites with water, sewer,
electricity and cable TV hookups.
</P>
<P>
   There are also rental cabins and _ the park's swankiest digs _ a
375-square-foot ``treehouse'' that sits 12 feet off the ground in a
copse of oaks and palms. It's equipped with kitchen, bathroom and
loft.
</P>
<P>
   The something-for-everyone strategy appears to be working: The
park drew more than 300,000 visitors last year.
</P>
<P>
   A few loyalists at the Spring Bluegrass Festival expressed
concerns about the new diversity. ``They've let bluegrass slide,''
lamented Harry Bowen of Macclenny, Fla. The guitarist was showing
his purist pride _ jamming with three fellow musicians in ``the
Loop,'' a camping cul-de-sac popular with the pickers, on the train
anthem ``Steel Rails'' and other fave tunes.
</P>
<P>
   A North Florida Bluegrass Association member who has been coming
to the park since 1985, Bowen claims there are ``not near as many
(bluegrass events) as there used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But, says Jean Cornett, ``It takes all kinds of music and all
kinds of people to make the world go 'round.'' And, she adds, to
make the park profitable.
</P>
<P>
   As long as they continue to lure new bluegrass fans such as Dell
and Bill Fowler, the music will still live here. The Crestview,
Fla., couple visited the park during the Spring Bluegrass Festival,
eager to see crowd pleasers White Sands and Blackwater. They
attended their first bluegrass festival last May in Elba, Ala., and
quickly climbed aboard the bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Bill, 71, thought the park was ``one of the nicest places we've
been,'' and Dell, 60, was charmed by the hospitality of her fellow
campers. ``You meet these people, and it's like you've known them
your entire life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Many regulars pitch in with park maintenance. ``We have one
fellow from West Virginia who showed up with a chain saw one day
and did most of the trail clearing,'' Jean Cornett says. Others
help out by building picnic tables, making signs and doing
electrical work.
</P>
<P>
   Together, the campers have created not only an inviting
temporary home, but a lasting bond. ``A lot of us are older, and
we've lost a few regulars,'' Chase says sadly. ``It hurts to lose
these people. We're like a family. A big, bluegrass family.''
</P>
<P>
   IF YOU GO
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Spirit of the Suwannee Music Park is about 250
miles from downtown Atlanta. Take I-75 south into Florida, exit
south on U.S. 129 toward Live Oak. The park is 4 miles on the
right.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Events for 2000: Memorial Day Weekend Getaway, May 26-29.
Suwannee River Gospel Jubilee, June 14-17. Independence Day
Celebration, July 1-2. Summer Sizzlin' Garage Sale, Aug. 5. Labor
Day Fireworks Blast, Sept. 2. Fall Bluegrass Festival, Sept.
28-Oct. 1. Suwannee River Gospel Jubilee, Oct. 4-7. Country Jam,
Oct. 13-14. Magnolia Fest, Oct. 20-22. National Trail Ride Annual
Gathering, Nov. 3-8. Old Tyme Farm Days, Nov. 21-25.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Camping rates: On nonevent days, rates range from $12 for a
primitive site to $25 for full hookup site. (The loosely enforced
rule here is that campers are only allowed to stay for two weeks,
then they have to leave for a week.) During special events, rates
are $15-$65 per person per weekend. Cabins are $65 a night;
treehouse is $99 a night Sunday-Thursday, $129 Friday and Saturday.
A few single-wide trailers and campers rent for $25-$45 a night.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Nearby eats and accommodations: Live Oak offers a wide
assortment of chain restaurants. For more distinctive dining, try
the Southern fried chicken, burgers and seafood platters at the
Dixie Grill (904-364-2810) or take in the townie atmosphere (and
scarf up the fresh seafood) at the Brown Lantern (904-362-1133).
</P>
<P>
   Hotels in Live Oak include Econo Lodge (904-362-7459) and
Suwannee River Inn Best Western
</P>
<P>
   (904-362-6000).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Spirit of the
</P>
<P>
   Suwannee Music Park, 904-364-1683, www.musicliveshere.com.
Suwannee County Chamber of Commerce, 904-362-3071,
www.suwanneechamber.com.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
