<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2440 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-HEMPHILL-COX     05-11 1025
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEMPHILL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Paul Hemphill feels the sting of the South
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, May 14.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the most precious memories from Paul Hemphill's
youth is a battered old Rawlings baseball glove from his brief
career in the minor leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta writer bought it for $15 in 1954 on his way to
spring training in Panama City, Fla. Before he could try it out,
coach Eddie Miller took a razor blade and sliced away the top layer
of the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said I needed to feel the ball,'' Hemphill said one recent
afternoon at his suburban Atlanta home as he slipped the battered
glove onto his hand. ``He said I needed to feel the sting.''
</P>
<P>
   Putting the glove back in its place of honor in his writing
office _ just above his stash of Camels and just below a stunning
earth-tone oil portrait of his late father _ Hemphill shakes his
head at the reminder of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a good fielder, but I couldn't hit,'' Hemphill says.
Tall and lean, with a face as weathered as the glove, the
64-year-old Birmingham native speaks in a deep Southern voice as
deliberate as a slow-moving Alabama river.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I went to Auburn and flunked every engineering
course I took. Then a kindly professor told me I had a way with
words, so I ended up in journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   As he moved from sportswriter to news columnist for The Atlanta
Journal to author of 12 books, Hemphill played the game like a kid
with only a thin layer of leather protecting his nerve endings.
</P>
<P>
   In his newspaper columns he wrote poignantly about young men
returning from Vietnam in a pine box. In his novel ``Long Gone,''
he wrote about old baseball players at the end of their careers and
young players at the beginning of theirs. In ``The Nashville
Sound'' he wrote about country musicians who made it and those who
didn't. And in ``King of the Road'' he wrote about his racist,
truck-driving father.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Hemphill celebrated his 60th birthday by running around
the infield of the Daytona International Speedway to research
``Wheels,'' a book on stock car racing. A few years earlier, he
blew out his knee attempting to hike the Appalachian Trail with his
19-year-old son for a book titled ``Me and the Boy.''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of years ago, Hemphill left his home in Atlanta and
moved into a dank fishing cabin in the Alabama swamps to research
``The Ballad of Little River'' (Viking, $25).
</P>
<P>
   Located near the setting for ``To Kill a Mockingbird,'' Little
River is a community of about 200 people. The violence that erupted
there in 1997 fascinated Hemphill, who was interested in exploring
the state of race relations as well as getting a glimpse into the
lifestyles of the poor and infamous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd get up about daybreak at 6 and fix myself something to eat
and go down to Peanut Ferguson's store and pick up the Mobile
Register and then make my rounds,'' Hemphill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything went fine until the morning in August when I
awakened to find that two tires on my trusty old Blazer had been
punctured with an ice pick overnight,'' said Hemphill, who
suspected one of the men from a backwoods family that resented his
intrusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's going to be happy when the book comes out. Maybe some
of them will. But then, it's an unhappy book. Nobody can be happy
when a church burns down. It's still not rebuilt and probably never
will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Hemphill's unhappy conclusion is that while some things have
changed in Alabama and the South, other things have not.
</P>
<P>
   Still, says his friend and Auburn classmate Anne Rivers Siddons,
Hemphill has never stopped loving the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never seems to get calluses on his mind or his heart,''
said Siddons, who lives in Charleston. ``There's not a sentimental
bone in his body, but he never stopped feeling anger or surprise or
joy. He loves the South but he sees it pretty clearly. His was a
tough South. He grew up in Birmingham when there was very little to
rejoice about.''
</P>
<P>
   In his 1993 memoir, ``Leaving Birmingham,'' he recalled the
violence that tore apart his hometown in 1963, when police
commissioner Bull Conner ordered fire hoses and police dogs turned
loose on civil rights marchers.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, racial tensions still simmer in poor urban
neighborhoods and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the 1940s down there,'' Hemphill said. ``You leave
the interstate, it ain't changed. Forget, hell. They're out there
farming their land like their granddaddy did. They've got satellite
dishes, but they're not watching the right stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``Race relations have improved somewhat, but what's happened is
that the poor _ both black and white _ have been shut off
economically. That's where the trouble is.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain, Hemphill added:
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be signing copies of my book at Peanut Ferguson's
store or the Dixie Landing Cafe in Little River, and I'll be hiring
the retired black deputy sheriff Murray January as a bodyguard when
I go to Mobile.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HEMPHILL FILE
</P>
<P>
   Born: 1936 in Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   Education: B.A., Auburn University; Nieman Fellowship to
Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   Family: Married to Susan Percy; one daughter. Three children
from first marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Career: Sportswriter for several Alabama newspapers and The
Augusta Chronicle; columnist for The Atlanta Journal, 1965-69;
columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, 1976;
writer-in-residence, Brenau College, 1984-92.
</P>
<P>
   Books: Three novels: ``Long Gone'' (1979); ``The Sixkiller
Chronicles'' (1985); and ``King of the Road'' (1989). Nine
nonfiction books: ``The Nashville Sound: Bright Lights and Country
Music'' (1970); ``Mayor: Notes on the Sixties,'' with Ivan Allen
Jr. (1971); ``The Good Old Boys'' (1974); ``Too Old to Cry''
(1981); ``Me and the Boy'' (1986); ``Leaving Birmingham: Notes of a
Native Son'' (1993); ``The Heart of the Game'' (1996); ``Wheels: A
Season on the Winston Cup Circuit'' (1998); and ``The Ballad of
Little River'' (2000).
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
