<HEADER>
A2441 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-WEEKENDGUIDE-COX     05-11 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKENDGUIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weekend tv viewing guide By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceFriday
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Moonlighting'' (8 p.m. on Bravo) _ Tonight's rerun, ``Atomic
Shakespeare,'' is the best ``Moonlighting'' episode ever, a fantasy
in which Cybill Shepherd and Bruce Willis do their own wiggy
version of ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' much of it in iambic
pentameter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Gloria Estefan, Caribbean Soul: The Atlantis Concert''
</P>
<P>
   (8 p.m. on CBS) _ 'N Sync and Marc Anthony are musical guests,
but the spotlight is on Estefan, who sings her hits ``Conga,''
``Turn the Beat Around,'' ``Music of My Heart'' and ``My
Impassioned Speech Outside the Lazaro Gonzalez House Even Though I
Have No Real Connection to the Elian Case.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Miss Universe Contest''
</P>
<P>
   (9 p.m. on CBS) _ All the girls, none of that annoying
it's-all-about-the-scholarships prattle.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Miracle in Lane Two'' (7:30 p.m. on The Disney Channel) _ On
``Malcolm in the Middle,'' Frankie Muniz plays a boy whose best
friend is in a wheelchair. In this inspirational new movie, it's
Muniz who's in a chair, and who becomes a Soapbox Derby champ.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Who's Afraid of ... Cats?''
</P>
<P>
   (8 p.m. on Discovery Channel) _ Slow mice? Sofa legs?
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Saturday Night Live'' (11:30 p.m. on NBC) _ Pop-tart Britney
Spears is guest host and musical guest. If she lets the show's
writers take some jabs at her image, we might be laughing with her.
If not, we might be laughing at her.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``King of the Hill'' (7:30 p.m. on Fox) _ Eeeeew! Alert:
Pictures of Peggy's size 16 1/2 feet find their way onto the
Internet, where they become icons for foot fetishists.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Saturday Night Live: The 25th Anniversary'' (8 p.m. on NBC)
_ A repeat of the extraordinarily well-done retrospective, with
tributes to dead cast members John Belushi, Gilda Radner, Chris
Farley and Phil Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   Mother's Day
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Mommie Dearest'' (8 p.m. Saturday on Bravo) _ The only
possible reason for scheduling the Faye Dunaway ``No Wire
Hangers!'' camp classic this weekend is to make you appreciate your
own dear mommy.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Absolutely Fabulous Marathon'' (1-8 p.m. Sunday on Comedy
Central) _ Edina may have been the world's worst mum, and Patsy
wasn't even a mum at all, but that won't stop Comedy Central from
re-re-re-packaging their misadventures for Mother's Day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``I Remember Mama''
</P>
<P>
   (8 p.m. Sunday on Turner Classic Movies) _ Irene Dunne stars in
this 1948 classic about Norwegian immigrants at the turn of the
century.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Simpsons''
</P>
<P>
   (8 p.m. Sunday on Fox) _ Marge (left) in danger of being
out-mothered by an interloper? Not likely, but then nothing on
``The Simpsons'' ever is.
</P>
<P>
   Movies
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``In the Army Now'' (7:25 p.m. Friday on The Movie Channel) _
Pauly Shore and Andy Dick co-starred in this 1994 comedy, after
which Congress passed a law that they could never appear together
again.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Truman Show'' (9 p.m. Friday on The Movie Channel) _ For
Jim Carrey, life is just one big TV show.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Ocean's Eleven'' (10 p.m. Saturday on Turner Classic Movies)
_ The coolest of the Rat Pack movies, as Frank Sinatra and the boys
rob a Las Vegas casino, only to have their plan go up in smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Best Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Jesus'' (9 p.m. Sunday on CBS, concluding 9 p.m. Wednesday)
</P>
<P>
   The third big TV take on Jesus this season (after NBC's ``Mary,
Mother of Jesus'' and ABC's ``The Miracle Maker'') is the best: a
rich, imaginative view with one of the most joyful Jesuses ever
filmed. Jeremy Sisto stars, with a strong supporting cast that
includes Gary Oldman as Pontius Pilate and Jacqueline Bisset as
Mary.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Worst Bet
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Rated X'' (9 p.m. Saturday on Showtime)
</P>
<P>
   This otherwise forgettable piece of flimsy sleaze has attracted
some attention because brothers Charlie Sheen and Emilio Estevez
play brothers Artie and Jim Mitchell (respectively), the San
Francisco porn kings of the 1970s whose claim to fame is having
made ``Behind the Green Door.'' And also because Sheen, who's newly
sober, had to pretend to snort a lot of cocaine and smoke a lot of
pot.
</P>
<P>
   If that's enough enticement for you, wade on in. ``Rated X'' has
plenty of sex, drugs and profanity, as you might expect. It also
has close to zero insight into the Mitchells and nothing
interesting to say about the milieu they helped create. Sheen and
Estevez, heads shaved and eyes blazing, are mildly interesting to
watch, but the writing isn't much better than the Mitchell
brothers' movies themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: D
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
