<TEXT>
<P>
   FOR FRIDAY AMs
</P>
<P>
   Business Day Front Page (coded ``f'' unless otherwise noted): &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Top lede)
</P>
<P>
   CARNEGIE-NORRIS-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``If it don't go up, don't
buy it,'' said Will Rogers, on investing in stocks. Never has
anyone put that tongue-in-cheek advice to use more brazenly than
Carnegie Investment Management, which obtained millions of shares
in Mattel Inc. by promising to pay more than the market price. It
got the shares, but it didn't pay for them. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved.)
</P>
<P>
   (Center display)
</P>
<P>
   PENNEY-OUTLOOK (Undated) _ Vanessa Castagna, J.C. Penney's new
executive vice president and chief operating officer, has generated
plenty of positive buzz since she jumped ship from Wal-Mart Stores
nine months ago. Fresh off the triumph of revamping Wal-Mart's
once-dowdy apparel section into one of its most successful
departments, Castagna is viewed as the kind of results-oriented
executive who can finally shake Penney's out of its longstanding
ennui. By Leslie Kaufman with Richard A. Oppel Jr.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.)
</P>
<P>
