<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 19:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2444 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-GUNS-MOMS-BOS &LR;      05-11 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUNS-MOMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARCH BY MOMS COULD BOOST GUN CONTROL AS CAMPAIGN ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Sunday's Million Mom March on the Mall has the
potential to be something much larger than either its one-day
numbers, emotional appeal, or hype suggest. If it succeeds in
pushing gun control high on the national agenda, it could help Al
Gore's bid for president and endanger congressional Republicans in
swing districts.
</P>
<P>
   Gun control has emerged as a big concern of women in this
election year, so potent an issue that some predict the march could
generate a new women's political movement around the issue and put
political candidates who don't support a host of gun-safety
measures on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The gun-control issue is something that will really cut across
party lines,'' said GOP pollster Linda DiVall, noting that as a
single issue, gun control now is about twice as likely as abortion
to move women voters. And, she noted, Republicans have ``a lot more
conflict'' over the issue than Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   GOP presidential candidate George W. Bush has been trying to woo
women because they have provided the margin of victory for the
Democrats in the last two presidential races. So far, he has had
success, polls show, but gun-control could be a problem for him,
particularly if it gains altitude as an issue. While Bush supports
mandatory trigger locks and raising the age of handgun possession
from 18 to 21, the Texas governor signed a measure last year that
makes it legal in the state to carry concealed handguns.
</P>
<P>
   His position is anathama to the gun-control lobby, and Handgun
Control Inc., an advocacy group, recently began running a 30-second
ad in seven cities that highlights Bush's record. The ad also
quotes an official of the National Rifle Association saying, ``If
we win, we'll have a president ... where we work out of their
office.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who favors a host of new gun regulations and has proposed
stiffer penalties for gun-related crimes, lately has been hammering
Bush on his ties to the NRA and the concealed-gun law. ``Will he
fight for the gun industry, or for America's families?'' the vice
president asked in a recent newspaper interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think gun control could become a campaign issue, for the
mere reason that there is a big gender gap, and if Al Gore has
learned anything from Bill Clinton, it's that he needs to do
something to appeal to women voters,'' said Dianne Bystrom,
director of the Carrie Chapman Catt Center for Women and Politics
at Iowa State University. ``This could be the issue, and it's one
where he can really draw distinctions with George Bush.''
</P>
<P>
   Bystrom said that in the mid-1990s, pollsters started detecting
a split in how the sexes saw the crime issue. Men wanted harsher
punishment for perpetrators. Women, scared that they or their
families would be crime victims, sought more protection. Since the
massacre at Columbine High School and other incidences of school
violence, the fear factor has thrust gun safety to the top of the
women's agenda, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters say they have been stunned by the huge and widening
gender gap on gun control. A survey released Thursday by the Pew
Research Center found that 67 percent of the women and 46 percent
of men said gun control was more important than gun-owner's rights,
while 49 percent of men and 28 percent of women favored owner's
rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Women are angry, and they want action,'' said Democratic
pollster Celinda Lake, an expert on women's voting behavior.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of people tell pollsters they aren't sure more gun laws
will really make much difference, and they question how effectively
laws on the books are enforced. But that doesn't take into account
the very emotional nature of the gun debate, particularly for
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can be a very dangerous issue, especially for suburban
Republicans, because it's very symbolic in defining a candidate,''
said Tony Fabrizio, a Republican political consultant. ``You might
be for trigger locks, or smart-gun technology, but if you won't say
you'll take guns away from people, then you get painted as an
extremist and pushed out of the mainstream.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens here on Mother's Day, at a march billed as
mainstream event, is important.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful images of a crowd as large as 150,000 _ mostly women,
some pushing baby strollers, many from the inner city, a few
victims of violence, a lot of them stereotyped soccer moms _ aim to
vex Capitol Hill's GOP leaders, who for a year have bottled up a
fairly modest bill to provide background checks on buyers at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   But the ambition of march founder Donna Dees-Thomases, a Short
Hills, N.J., mother and professional publicist, is much larger than
pending legislation. She wants Sunday's rhetoric and show of
solidarity to stir up grass-roots activism when the women go home
and to influence voting in presidential, congressional, and even
local contests in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure the march will move the bill (in Congress) next
week, but the Martin Luther King march didn't move the civil rights
bill the next week either,'' said David Rosenbloom, director of
Join Together, a team at the Boston University School of Public
Health that works on preventing gun violence and substance abuse.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are estimating a crowd of 150,000, which will feature
women victims of gun violence, celebrites such as Rosie O'Donnell
and Susan Sarandon, and politicians, including First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton and Maryland Lieutenant Governor Kathleen Townsend
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Near the Lincoln Memorial, a group called the Second Amendment
Sisters is expecting as many as 10,000 women to march Sunday on
behalf of the rights of Americans to bear arms. Debra Collins of
Aurora, Colo., a march coordinator, says she shares the same
concern as the Million Mom Marchers _ protecting herself and her
loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   The NRA, the gun-rights lobby, this week launched a ``Safe
Kids'' advertising campaign and committed $1 million to put a
gun-safety program in every American classroom.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Center for Responsive Politics, the NRA has
donated $577,129 to congressional candidates and made $664,650 in
soft-money contributions to the Republican Party so far this
election cycle. The figures are higher than two years ago, and
reflect, some analysts say, the group's attempts to strengthen an
eroding position.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
