<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEM THAR STARS 'N' BARS WILL BE OURS  
 (FOR USE BY N.Y. TIMES NEWS SERVICE CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Ain't no doubt about it _ that dang Confederate flag
got no bidness flying up on top the Statehouse dome in South
Carolina. No bidness 'tall.
</P>
<P>
   Word is, they's civilized folks in South Carolina. What was they
thinking? By now they should of figgered out that no symbol of the
Confederacy belongs in a place where folks is all how-dee-do and
soft in the head from book learnin'.
</P>
<P>
   No sir.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate flag is meant fer the ignernt. It needs to be
flying in a place where the men is slow, the women is ornery, and
the gubmint's dumber than a sack full a hammers.
</P>
<P>
   N'other words _ HERE.
</P>
<P>
   The Confederate flag has flown over the capital in South
Carolina since 1962 and wudda flown till hell froze over if a bunch
of agitators hadn't made folks over there nervous as a cow with a
buck-toothed calf.
</P>
<P>
   Fine, I suggest they mosey on out to Arizona. It's high time we
seen the Stars and Bars waving over the copper dome at the end of
Jefferson Street. Which we will be certain to rename Jefferson
Davis Street.
</P>
<P>
   It's perfect for us.
</P>
<P>
   Near as I can tell, Arizona's the onlyiest one of all the
U-nited States to have a legislator (goes by the name a Karen
Johnson) who tried to have a law passed this year saying we's
prepared to secede from the Union.
</P>
<P>
   If that ain't Confederate enough for you, we got just about the
highest dropout rate in the Union, and at the same time got just
about the highest number of schoolgirls who's currently in the
family way.
</P>
<P>
   About a year back, we was ranked by the squishy-headed liberals
at the Children's Rights Council as the third worst state in which
to raise a child. We took it as a compliment. Sort of like recently
being listed 45th among states in public school spending per
student.
</P>
<P>
   We got another legislator (goes by the name a Barbara Blewster)
who compared homosexuality to ``bestiality, human sacrifice and
cannibalism.''
</P>
<P>
   And that ain't all. A politician in town said Blewster told her
once that Native Americans ``were not smart enough to do what they
need to do to get ahead, and that even African-Americans are more
advanced than Native Americans, (and) smarter.''
</P>
<P>
   If that ain't a Dixie-singing patriot, what is?
</P>
<P>
   She also believes teachers and administrators should carry
weapons to school. And she ain't alone. We got politicians who was
hoping to allow pistol-packing patrons into any ole public
building, playground or park, and dern near got a law passed.
</P>
<P>
   If that don't jar your preserves, you should know that while our
politicians paid no mind to health care and education and such,
they made dawggone sure to pass a law likely to help the Arizona
Cardinals git a new stadium. As you know, they's nothin' more
important than football.
</P>
<P>
   And I wonder if South Carolina has heard tell that folks in
parts of Arizona don't take kindly to furiners. Down near the
border, they's likely to point the business end of a shotgun at 'em
lest they high-tail it outta there.
</P>
<P>
   It'd be right nice to be waving our very own Confederate flag at
special occasions like that, hollerin' our new state motto:
</P>
<P>
   Y'all don't come back now, hear? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
