<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MY-MONEY-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LEGACY IN THE FILE CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
 MARILYN KENNEDY MELIA    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Money is one of the boundaries of intimacy. A tangle of unspoken
social conventions makes it perfectly acceptable to complain about
the cost of something but taboo to compare that price with your
weekly salary. Similarly, we can pass along a winning stock tip but
must keep quiet about the value of our brokerage account. That is
why we blush if a friend breaks with custom and trusts us with a
financial confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Between parents and children, even when the relationship is
close, the sharing of private, money-related issues can be a rare
event. Parents might admonish us to save more and spend less, or
ask us what our job pays, but they typically are close-mouthed
about their own balance sheets. Most adults I know don't have any
familiarity with their parents' finances while their parents are
alive. It is not until after their deaths that we, as their
children, are left to explore this aspect of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   When my father died three years ago, it was my job to decipher
what his holdings were and how my mother should budget for herself
in her new status as a widow. Never interested in money (except for
being a careful comparison shopper), my mother asked me to sort out
these baffling questions for her.
</P>
<P>
   For many of us time-pressed boomers, adding parent-related
duties to our already burdened schedules is enough to break the
fragile balancing act; that is why so many people hand over such
work to the professionals. Though I could have asked my mother to
hire an accountant or financial planner, I'm glad I didn't. The job
turned out not to be burdensome at all, but a true labor of love.
Stepping into Dad's den was like opening a window on his world.
</P>
<P>
   During the last couple of years of his life, my father stopped
working as a consultant and spent a sizable portion of his time
tending to his investments. He was an industrial engineer in his
professional life, so I wasn't surprised by the meticulous charts
he kept, showing the movements of his stock holdings. He had neatly
labeled files for his bank and brokerage statements and a few notes
on his stock selections.
</P>
<P>
   He did not leave behind any other personal writings, like a
diary, so these seemingly dull notes became precious to me. Others
have told me that even stumbling upon a grocery list or a voice on
an answering machine that belonged to a loved one who has suddenly
been lost can bring a rush of joy and excitement.
</P>
<P>
   Sorting out his financial affairs brought me those feelings, and
more. Learning how much he earned the year he retired, or how he
had contributed so diligently to his company's savings plan for
years, brought me newfound respect for his role as our family's
provider. I knew, too, when I found a sheet that inventoried his
assets, that he probably meant that as a message to me of where to
look, what to find.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting at his desk, I tried to imitate his patience and abandon
my usual hurry-up, get-it-done style. In one file, I stumbled
across a series of letters he wrote to his employer's benefits
department and his brokerage firm. It appears that his entire
savings account became temporarily lost somewhere in cyberspace
when it was electronically transferred. Anyone else would have been
screaming into the phone. He had to be screaming inwardly, but his
letters politely demanded a resolution.
</P>
<P>
   His financial acumen was equally inspiring. Looking through his
records was tangible proof that stock investing pays off over the
long term. I enjoy helping my mother monitor the portfolio he
assembled, not only because I have been able to learn a few things
but also because watching his selections provides me with a
continuing link to him. When I hear the business reports, I
silently say, ``Dad, I can't believe you had the foresight to buy
AOL when you did.'' Or: ``I wish you could advise me. Is the market
overvalued?''
</P>
<P>
   Now, when my husband and I drop our bank statements into the
family files, I think how one day, our sons will probably be
tidying up financial loose ends that we leave behind. For the first
time, they will have an up-close, objective look at our
extravagances, our thrift and, I hope, our savvy. More than the
dollars we leave them to inherit, a more meaningful legacy lies in
those basement files.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
