<HEADER>
A2463 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-ROBERDS0512-COX     05-11 0432
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROBERDS0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roberds' close-out sale to start next Friday
 &HT;    By Renee DeGross
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Roberds' liquidation sale at eight Georgia stores is
slated to start next Friday as part of the failed chain's
going-out-of-business plan, but customer orders are still in limbo.
</P>
<P>
   A bankruptcy court in Ohio will decide Monday which liquidation
firm will handle the close-out sale and how long it will last.
</P>
<P>
   The West Carrollton, Ohio, home furnishings and electronics
chain covered up its store windows with paper and shut down all
stores May 2, when it became evident its Chapter 11 reorganization
plan had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Roberds was unable to reach credit terms with major vendors. The
28-year-old chain closed distribution centers and stores in Ohio
and Georgia, cutting more than 1,300 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Customers with unfilled orders placed after Jan. 19 _ the day
Roberds filed for Chapter 11 protection _ will either get their
merchandise or a refund under a timetable to be determined by the
bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under bankruptcy code, the company is required to account for
all customers,'' said John Grigsby, chief financial officer and a
vice president of Roberds. ``We intend to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's in stock,'' Grigsby said, ``it will be sent for top
priority claims.''
</P>
<P>
   Top priority claims are any orders placed after the company
filed for bankruptcy protection. Orders placed before Jan. 19
``will take longer,'' Grigsby said.
</P>
<P>
   Customers getting merchandise repaired by Roberds or its vendors
will get their goods back, fixed or not, Grigsby said. The status
of extended service contracts will be dealt with in bankruptcy
court.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cloud, spokesman for the Governor's Office of Consumer
Affairs in Atlanta, said he has fielded about a dozen calls from
Roberds customers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are concerned about how they're going to get their
merchandise. Best thing you can do is refer them to bankruptcy
court,'' Cloud said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roberds has been around for decades,'' he added. ``This is not
a group that would defraud the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberds entered Atlanta in 1979 and slowly built up its presence
to eight locations in Georgia, a distribution center and service
center.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Atlanta was Roberds' biggest market, and the retailer had
planned to add at least three stores here this year. But Roberds
buckled under in the face of competition from Best Buy, Circuit
City and Atlanta-based Havertys, and the expansion of Rooms-to-Go.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
