<HEADER>
A2464 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-JESUS-REVIEW-SFCHR     05-11 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JESUS-REVIEW-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS' THOROUGHLY MODERN MESSIAH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.2000, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jesus comes to TV in all forms. The less said about what ``South
Park'' did a year or two ago, the better. I wouldn't care to dwell
on the Claymation Jesus that ABC presented on Easter, either. And
NBC was a bit unclear on the concept with ``Mary, Mother of Jesus''
in November.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's CBS' turn, and that network's two-parter, ``Jesus,''
amounts to an Extremely New Revised Standard Version. In a delicate
balancing act, ``Jesus'' modernizes the Christian Messiah while
simultaneously placing him in historical context and honoring his
divinity.
</P>
<P>
   That is a risky exercise, but ``Jesus'' pulls it off splendidly.
Jeremy Sisto (``Without Limits,'' ``White Squall'') isn't the most
charismatic actor around, but he brings a physicality and human
emotional side to Jesus that's new, eye-opening and finally
stirring.
</P>
<P>
   Jesus is anything but ethereal in this story of his adult life
and ministry. He's seen reeling in fishing nets, dancing at a
wedding feast, joking with his disciples, displaying a short fuse
at times, mixing among and jesting with his congregants during the
Sermon on the Mount.
</P>
<P>
   In his days as a young carpenter, he's even on the verge of
pursuing a girlfriend, Mary of Bethany (Stefania Rocca). She's the
sister of Lazarus (Peter Gevisser), and she clearly aspires to be
Jesus' wife. Jesus kindly explains to her, at last, that he has
other plans.
</P>
<P>
   The producers readily admit that the implication of romance,
however unrealized, is a leap; Scripture grants a friendship and no
more. There's a leap, too, when Satan (Jeroen Krabbe, clad as a
sort of man about town in a black, modern suit) makes a second
attempt, after tempting Jesus in the wilderness, to subvert the
soon-to-be-crucified Jesus at Gethsemane.
</P>
<P>
   The scene is an invention, but the biblical scholars who
ratified the script went along with it. Showing Jesus a vision of
mankind's warlike future _ ``Killing for Christ will be a big
business in the future'' _ Satan tells Jesus that his impending
suffering will be in vain. Jesus holds firm. The scene owes more to
Dostoyevsky than to Scripture, but it's a fit, at least
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   The other narrative innovation concerns Pontius Pilate (slyly
played by Gary Oldman, the surest-handed actor in the production).
In the tricky business of assigning responsibility for Jesus'
execution, Pilate is squarely blamed.
</P>
<P>
   Suzette Couture's script has Pilate manipulating Herod Antipas
(Luca Barbarschi) and the Jewish high priest Caiaphas (Christian
Kohlund) into asking Rome to solve their Jesus problem.
</P>
<P>
   But here, Jesus is just as surely Rome's problem. In the brutal
yet mercifully brief crucifixion scene, when Jesus asks God to
``forgive them, for they know not what they do,'' a mumbled
rejoinder comes from a Roman witness, the invented character Livio
(G.W. Bailey).
</P>
<P>
   ``We know exactly what we're doing, Messiah,'' Livio says to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed mostly in Morocco, ``Jesus'' features a wildly eclectic
cast from Italy, the United States, Britain, the Netherlands and
Germany. It's an Italian-American co-production, and it has already
shown its mettle in Italy, where it drew huge ratings in December.
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline Bisset, who played Joan of Arc's mother a year ago on
CBS, is Jesus' beatific mother, Mary. Armin Mueller-Stahl
(``Shine'') is Joseph, whose death triggers Jesus' ministry. Debra
Messing, far afield from ``Will &AMP; Grace,'' neither adds to nor
detracts from the show as the reformed prostitute Mary Magdalene.
</P>
<P>
   Sisto seems remarkably at ease in an understandably daunting
role. It helps him, no doubt, that the miniseries depicts a worldly
Jesus and that the script is in unadorned American English.
</P>
<P>
   There probably can never be a perfect actor as Jesus. Sisto's
handicaps include a less-than-commanding speaking voice. But he
uses his physical vitality to help compensate. His Jesus is a man
who takes a solid punch to each cheek, not merely an open-handed
smack; it's the manliest passivity you'll ever see.
</P>
<P>
   Director Roger Young allows some cheesy excesses. The electrical
charge that courses around Jesus at his baptism, for example, is
pure chintz. Also, some of the interior sets and backlighting are
too obvious. Hey, it's TV, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Jesus'' is nevertheless a powerful experience and, as it
picks up steam, an energetic departure from most dried-out Biblical
epics.
</P>
<P>
   Its insistence on rooting Jesus in his humanity serves to
heighten the sense of dread over the crucifixion to come. And the
miraculousness of the resurrection.
</P>
<P>
   For the Christian audience, anyway, it's one network miniseries
whose sequel can be awaited with intense interest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2008EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
