<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0345 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 20:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2466 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-PENNY-OUTLOOK-ART-990     05-11 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENNY-OUTLOOK-ART-990(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PENNEY'S PUSH TO SHED THE DOWDINESS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Ark.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By LESLIE KAUFMAN with RICHARD A. OPPEL JR.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Vanessa Castagna, J.C. Penney's new executive vice president and
chief operating officer, is making demands again. At a summit
conference for suppliers Thursday at Penney's headquarters in
Plano, Texas, the imposing Castagna, who stands nearly 6 feet tall
in heels, strides backs and forth as she hammers away on what it
will take to turn around the ailing department store chain she now
runs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have got to be more timely, more current, and ship modern
merchandise that is trend-right,'' she tells them, demanding that
clothing suppliers provide more fashionable goods already priced on
hangers so that they can go right to the selling floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking more of them, requiring more of them,'' Castagna
explained in an interview after the meeting, ``and they love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Love, perhaps, is a tad strong, but certainly Castagna has
generated plenty of positive buzz since she jumped ship from
Wal-Mart Stores nine months ago. Fresh off the triumph of revamping
Wal-Mart's once-dowdy apparel section into one of its most
successful departments, Castagna is viewed as the kind of
results-oriented executive who can finally shake Penney's out of
its longstanding ennui.
</P>
<P>
   ``She focused on changes internally as well as externally,''
said Kim Roy, a group president at Liz Clairborne, who attended an
earlier conference for apparel makers. ``It really bodes well for
Penney's.''
</P>
<P>
   Already Castagna has demanded a slew of changes: everything from
giving her suppliers score cards to asking her store managers to
work on Saturdays. But no one underestimates the task before her.
</P>
<P>
   With a decentralized business culture that has left an unusual
amount of buying power in the hands of individual store managers,
Penney's has been slow to reach customers with up-to-date styles.
Its aging stores are overstocked with slow-selling, oddball
merchandise that makes them seem cluttered. And a tradition of
promoting only from within, left them bereft of top talent.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, while direct competitors like Kohl's and Target
have been growing at close to double-digit rates in recent years,
Penney's completely missed the late 1990s consumer spending spree.
On a year-over-year basis, the company's sales per store have
actually declined in all but 9 months of the last 28. Penney's
stock has lost more than two-thirds of its value in the last two
years, leaving investors fuming for change and making the company a
prime takeover target. Last week, in a filing with federal
regulators, Carl Icahn, the corporate raider, indicated that he was
purchasing Penney's stock and might take up to a 15 percent stake
in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Icahn could simply be looking for a passive investment in a
company he thinks is undervalued or he might be considering a
takeover that would allow him to realize big profits by splitting
Penney's into its component parts.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Castagna has had to play a larger role as an
agent of change as other high-level executives have defected. And
the ultimate test could come soon. Just last week, James E.
Oesterreicher, Penney's chief executive and chairman, said that he
would step down and that a search for a replacement was under way.
Penney's said it would look both inside and outside the company to
fill the position, but Castagna is clearly one of the
front-runners.
</P>
<P>
   A 28-year veteran of the retail industry, Castagna is short on
financial and operations background but long on merchandising
talent. She had senior merchandising responsibilities at Lazarus, a
division of Federated Department Stores; at Target, the stylish
discounter; and at Marshall's. But Castagna is best known for her
work at Wal-Mart, where she became senior vice president and
general merchandising manager for women's apparel in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At that time Wal-Mart's clothing assortment was of low quality
and poorly presented. Customers may have been happy to pick up a
bargain, like a decal T-shirt for $4.99, but they were skipping
over the higher-priced and more profitable sweater sets and jean
jackets.
</P>
<P>
   Castagna is widely credited with helping Wal-Mart clearly
identify a strong image for each of its clothing brands. She had a
keen eye for the one or two fashion items to promote. But just as
important was the structure she built for decision making.
</P>
<P>
   ``She created a process of planning,'' said Tom Burns, who
worked as a consultant to Wal-Mart when he was with the Doneger
Group. ``She created different teams for each brand. And she
created her own product development team that worked on identifying
trends.''
</P>
<P>
   Wal-Mart does not break out apparel sales in its financial
statements, but analysts say it is clear she helped both sales and
profitability. ``When Vanessa was there, food sales began to
increase at a rate of 30 to 40 percent a year due to Wal-Mart Super
Center expansion,'' said Jeffrey Feiner, a retail analyst with
Lehman Brothers. ``Yet at that time, apparel, as a percent of the
total, remained the same, which confirms the point that apparel
sales did well during her reign.''
</P>
<P>
   Even more critically, Castagna managed to adapt and thrive at
Wal-Mart, which, with its headquarters in the small town of
Bentonville, Ark., and a dearth of woman executives, is known for
its good ol' boy atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   She succeeded, colleagues say, because she is tough _ but in a
nice way. Known to work 100-hour weeks herself, Castagna demands a
lot of her staff but she also entrusts them with a high level of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``She works through people very well,'' said Paul R. Charron,
chairman and chief executive of Liz Claiborne, which does business
with both Penney's and Wal-Mart. ``You won't see her taking over
meetings and usurping the prerogatives of a subordinate.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren D. Feldberg, who served as Castagna's boss at both Target
and Marshall's, echoes that view. ``She is a cheerleader,'' he
said. ``She describes it as putting on her pompoms.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Castagna is no shrinking violet. ``If you call her to see
how business is going,'' said Richard Baker, the chief executive of
sporting goods manufacturer Ocean Pacific and a long time business
friend, first ``she'll tell you how your business is going.''
</P>
<P>
   All her leadership skills will certainly be tested at Penney's,
which is famously insular and unresponsive. ``When the report card
comes in on Vanessa, she will have earned her `A' grade more for
what she was able to elicit from the J.C. Penney community than
what she did for suppliers,'' predicts Charron.
</P>
<P>
   Castagna has already started pushing internally just as hard as
she has been seeking external changes. Under her direction the
retailer has instituted a new compensation policy, making bonuses
more contingent on total company performance and less tied to the
gains of one division or store.
</P>
<P>
   At an April meeting with store managers, she zeroed in on the
contrast between Wal-Mart managers who take Tuesday and Wednesday
off and store managers at Penney's, who are often off on the busy
weekend shopping days. ``We have to have the best people being
there when the customers need them,'' she said firmly.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, she is doing away with many of Penney's
traditional business practices. For example, Penney's had long
prided itself on a decentralized ordering system that allowed
individual store managers to make the bulk of the purchasing
decisions. Not long ago, the company moved to limit the autonomy of
store managers but Castagna wasn't satisfied. She recently demanded
that all ordering be centralized at headquarters to create a more
consistent image.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, Castagna has moved to improve Penney's dealings with
its suppliers. ``It has been our history that we did not share
information with suppliers,'' she explained. ``It was a contractual
relationship. We would say, `This is what Penney's wants.' ''
Castagna has tried to make that a more reciprocal relationship. As
of November, suppliers could monitor sales of any of their own
items at any store through a Web site Penney's established.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of her carrot-and-stick methods, Castagna announced that
Penney's would give suppliers score cards rating them on sales,
profits, swiftness of product turnover and other things. They will
also be able to see other suppliers' ratings, so they can gain
insight on the competition.
</P>
<P>
   In return for all this information, Castagna wants suppliers to
give Penney first crack at offering new products, to shorten
delivery times and to ship merchandise ``floor ready'' with hangers
and price tags in place. She also insists that the suppliers stop
giving Penney's their second-tier staff. ``We want people who can
analyze the business, not just salesmen,'' she explains.
</P>
<P>
   It is probably too early to see much improvement in sales, but
Penney's says inventory and related costs are already down
substantially. Castagna believes the seeds she has planted won't
bear real fruit until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about remodeling a store, or changing a buying or
shipping mode,'' she says. ``We are changing the business model.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
