<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPED-MORRIS-NY-EGAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARCHBISHOP EGAN HAS A TOUGH ACT TO FOLLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (New York Times OpEd for use in papers of Friday, May 12)  
 ATTENTION EDITORS: The following material from The New York Times
Syndicate is for use by OPED clients. Nonsubscribers can use this
article only by special arrangement. For purchase information, see
end of text. 
 By CHARLES R. MORRIS    
 c.2000 New York Times    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The appointment of Edward M. Egan as the ninth Roman Catholic
archbishop of New York represents more than just the filling of an
ecclesiastical position; for the future of the city, it could be
the political event of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past century and a half, Egan's predecessors have
wielded enormous influence in local and national politics, far more
so than the holders of any other religious post. New York's
archbishops have often had more clout than senators or cabinet
members.
</P>
<P>
   Egan, 68, has spent 12 years as bishop of Bridgeport, Conn.,
where he led in fostering Catholic-Jewish relations and also
handled the delicate job of closing and merging several parishes;
in New York, he may be glad for the political skills those
experiences helped him develop.
</P>
<P>
   Egan's predecessor in New York, Cardinal John O'Connor, was a
master of the political give and take, and the turnout at his
funeral Monday rivaled that for a head of state. O'Connor was the
most recent in a long line of bishop-politicians that traces its
lineage to John Hughes, the combative working-class Irishman who
presided over the archdiocese from 1839 to 1864.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes led the New York church during a time when Catholics,
especially Irish Catholics, were regarded as an alien presence in
America. When Democrats ignored his requests in 1842 to curb the
blatantly anti-Catholic religious curriculum being taught in the
city schools, Hughes organized his own slate of candidates for the
state Legislature, took to the stump himself and swept the
election. Hughes was also a one-man anti-discrimination league,
standing up for Irish rights in public accommodations and hiring,
especially in the building trades.
</P>
<P>
   As Hughes consolidated his spiritual and temporal power in New
York, his national profile also rose. Presidents Franklin Pierce,
James Buchanan and Abraham Lincoln consulted with Hughes on the
issues of the day and occasionally called on him for diplomatic
missions. Lincoln even lobbied the Vatican, unsuccessfully, to make
Hughes a cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes' successors also wielded significant influence on
politics. Archbishop Michael Corrigan kept close ties to Tammany
Hall and in 1886 helped to mobilize Catholics against the mayoral
candidacy of the reformer Henry George. And Cardinal Patrick Hayes
used his Tammany connections to line up Democratic support in
Congress for legislation protecting church-run schools in the
Philippines in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinal Francis Spellman, who ran the diocese from 1939 to
1967, was considered the church's greatest politician and was
portrayed as close to Franklin D. Roosevelt, John Foster Dulles, J.
Edgar Hoover and important union leaders. Many Americans thought
Spellman had a real shot at becoming pope. The cardinal wasn't the
force he appeared to be in Cold War politics, and policy makers
considered him more of an irritant than an insider. He was ``always
pushing and pushing,'' according to Paul Nitze, an architect of
postwar foreign policy. Spellman was a supporter of Sen. Joseph
McCarthy, and he used his connections aggressively on behalf of
Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   O'Connor succeeded best in updating Hughes' methods for the
media age. He was a master of turning adversaries into allies. Had
he not been a priest, it would have been easy to imagine O'Connor
as a senator or a governor.
</P>
<P>
   The real test for the new archbishop of New York is how well he
maintains the position's power. It has been decades since Catholics
voted as an identifiable bloc, and an archbishop's influence now
depends as much on charisma as on the inherent power of his office.
There are few bully pulpits to compare to the see of New York. Egan
has a very tough act to follow.
</P>
<P>
   (Charles R. Morris is the author of ``American Catholic: The
Saints and Sinners Who Built America's Most Powerful Church.'')
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ------------------------------------------------- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on the OPED
package and other features. &QL;
