<HEADER>
A2470 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-11 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLINS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: A WOMAN SCORNS 
</HEADLINE>
   By GAIL COLLINS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   If we accept Clinton-era conventional wisdom and assume that a
male politician's ability to survive a sex scandal depends on the
wife's willingness to impersonate a good sport, Rudy Giuliani has a
problem.
</P>
<P>
   After Giuliani told reporters this week that he and his wife,
Donna Hanover, were separating, Hanover held a press conference of
her own. A professional TV journalist, she didn't bury the lead:
``For several years it was difficult to participate in Rudy's
public life because of his relationship with one staff member.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Cristyne Lategano, the mayor's former
communications director. Lategano and Giuliani always vigorously
denied having a romantic relationship, and after multitudinous
attempts to track down evidence to the contrary, the exhausted City
Hall press corps pretty much let the matter drop.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover, however, picked it back up again. She added that when
Lategano departed from City Hall last year, ``I made a major effort
to bring us back together,'' but that her husband ``chose another
path.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Judith Nathan, a nurse whom Giuliani describes as
a ``very good friend.'' For a press conference that lasted only a
couple of minutes, Hanover managed to squeeze in quite a bit of
information.
</P>
<P>
   The ``good friend'' situation may be a private matter, but the
city really does have an interest in what Hanover said about the
mayor's ex-communications director. Lategano came to City Hall with
no strong qualifications except intense loyalty, and helped turn
the administration into a flock of low-profile yes-men and -women,
who encouraged the mayor's tendency to view the world as a war
between the forces of good (himself) and evil (anybody who gets in
the way). When she left, she used Giuliani's intense support to
snag a $150,000 job with the New York Convention and Visitors
Bureau. If this was all done in the name of love, inquiring minds
want to know.
</P>
<P>
   New York City is a pretty sophisticated place, but we have never
before heard a mayoral wife accuse her husband of fooling around.
Back in the 20's, Mayor Jimmy Walker carried on a very public
affair with a young British showgirl, but his missus didn't
complain and the press never mentioned it. A New York Telegraph
reporter once explained that he and his colleagues ``did not wish
to penalize the man for his lack of hypocrisy'' when tons of other
public men pretended to be faithful husbands while cavorting in
secret.
</P>
<P>
   That would be an example of the win-win school of political
philandering.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, right after the mayor announced that he was being
treated for prostate cancer, Hanover appeared ready to be
supportive. She even gave up a part in the Off Broadway show ``The
Vagina Monologues'' _ the sort of sacrifice only a New York City
Republican's wife would be capable of concocting.
</P>
<P>
   But it's pretty hard to stand by a man who appears intent on
bolting out the door. Hanover didn't really have much chance to
follow in the line of Hillary Clinton or Sen. Charles Robb's wife,
Lynda, who managed to pretend that she found that nude-massage
story believable. What Giuliani wants might be more of a friendly
ex-spouse _ somebody like John McCain's first wife, Carol, who took
the curse off his shabby behavior by issuing warm statements in
support of his presidential candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, through two teary press conferences, Hanover has given
no indication she plans to let her husband off the hook. She used
to be a very public political wife, appearing in warm and fuzzy
campaign ads and confiding to a reporter that she felt her husband
was ``the most virile man ... so strong and wonderful.'' Then the
cone of silence descended, and the couple behaved like tenants in
an apartment building nodding vaguely to each other in the lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past few days the two of them have been confiding in us
quite a lot, really. It sometimes feels as if they're communicating
better with the press corps than with each other. Giuliani looked
ashen and shaky when he announced the separation, surprising not
only his constituents but apparently his wife as well. Thursday,
though, he appeared to be his old cranky self; you could tell he
was feeling better when he told one reporter to ``get lost.'' The
era of sharing, it seems, is over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
