<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-EUROPE0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ford chair defends SUV safety, environment steps
 &HT;    By Russell Grantham
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ford Motor Co. admitted at the company's annual
meeting in Atlanta on Thursday that its big, gasoline-thirsty but
popular sport-utility vehicles also have unleashed environmental
and safety problems.
</P>
<P>
   But company Chairman William Clay Ford Jr. also said the
Dearborn, Mich.-based automaker will keep making and selling SUVs
because it has done more to reduce their emissions and their threat
to other drivers than its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't do it, somebody else would, and they wouldn't do
it as responsibly,'' he told reporters Thursday after the company's
annual meeting. SUVs, pickups and vans account for about half of
Ford's North American vehicle sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not encouraging wanton destruction of the environment
using our SUVs,'' said Ford. But he added that he's aware vehicles
like Ford's 19-foot-long, nine-passenger Excursion open it to
criticism by environmental and auto safety groups that claim such
vehicles release more smog-causing emissions, can cause damage to
the environment when used off-road and can overrun smaller cars in
collisions.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. highlighted those and other issues in a
``corporate citizenship report'' that was passed out to
shareholders Thursday along with annual financial reports.
</P>
<P>
   Ford told about 300 shareholders that he wants the company to be
open about its problems and achievements.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to become a more transparent company and to have
everything that we do, good or bad, out there,'' he said. ``We take
our social responsibility very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the company has voluntarily certified its SUVs, pickups
and vans to meet tougher federal emissions standards years before
the standards take effect.
</P>
<P>
   Ford alternates its annual meetings between Detroit and areas
where it has a significant presence.
</P>
<P>
   The company builds the Ford Taurus and Mercury Sable at its
Hapeville, Ga., plant, which has been the subject of speculation
about expansion. Ford President and Chief Executive Officer Jacques
Nasser told shareholders it was too early to detail Ford's plans
for the plant, which he said is among the company's best. But, he
added, ``The future of the Atlanta plant is very assured.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Nasser said the company would announce
changes today, Friday in its European operations as part of a
restructuring plan there. Nasser said the company would take an
unspecified charge against earnings.
</P>
<P>
   In speaking to shareholders, Nasser said Ford's North American
products are driving the automaker's solid financial performance.
``All of these new products have given us one problem: How to build
enough of them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford shares closed up 68 3/4 cents at $52.93 3/4 on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
