<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2479 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT &LR;      05-11 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY LIFE, NOT A CUP OF TEA 
SLOWLY MOVING INTO DVD 
THE END OF THE AFFAIR 
NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES CRITICS 
OTHER RELEASES 
 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 BY PETER M. NICHOLS    
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAMILY LIFE, NOT A CUP OF TEA: Alan Ball was talking about his
idea for a movie the other day. ``Can you imagine pitching this?''
he asked. ``Two families, really screwed up. You think you know
what's going on, but it's really something different because
actually the movie is about the elusive nature of reality, and
there's a whole metaphysical bit with this plastic bag.''
</P>
<P>
   The film, ``American Beauty,'' was Ball's first movie script. It
didn't seem to be Hollywood's cup of tea. ``I thought, `If it ever
gets made, it will be for $12,' '' he said. But Steven Spielberg
liked what he read, and his studio, DreamWorks, bought it. Five
Academy Awards later, one of them for Ball as best screenwriter,
the film has been released on videocassette.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it is on tape, what is there new to notice? ``I've seen
it 20 times,'' Ball said. ``I see little continuity glitches, but I
also see things in the performances I didn't see the first 19
times.'' He mentioned the subtlety of Thora Birch's performance as
the mutinous teen-age daughter of Lester and Carolyn Burnham (Kevin
Spacey and Annette Bening) and the many layers Chris Cooper gave
Colonel Fitts, the Burnhams' spectacularly troubled neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   On video, one is again struck by the film's clean structure and
bright look, which sets off the darkness of the material. Ball and
Sam Mendes, the director, made a commentary for the DVD, which
hasn't been released or scheduled. ``Sam explains how at the
beginning of the film everything is a little darker, and as Lester
opens up and starts having a new life, there's more light,'' Ball
said.
</P>
<P>
   At first he did not like the idea that DreamWorks would be
making his film. ``I said no because they'd turn it into something
big and bloated and weird,'' he said. ``But then they convinced me
that they wouldn't. And they didn't.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SLOWLY MOVING INTO DVD: Like ``American Beauty,'' other films
with Spielberg connections are taking their time coming to DVD. The
next arrival will be ``Jaws,'' to be issued on disc by Universal on
July 11 and now No. 4 on Video Business magazine's list of the
biggest movies still missing on DVD.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of them are Spielberg's; it only seems that way. At the
top are the ``Star Wars'' films, which now include ``Episode I: The
Phantom Menace,'' from Fox. No reason is given for their absence,
but release decisions lie with their creator, George Lucas. Next
come the ``Godfather'' films. No blaming Spielberg here, either.
Distributors say the delay is caused by their director, Francis
Ford Coppola.
</P>
<P>
   Spielberg's approval is needed for the Indiana Jones films, No.
3 as a group, as it is for ``Jurassic Park,'' No. 5 after ``Jaws.''
He directed them all. From there the list fans out: ``Dr.
Zhivago,'' ``The Sound of Music,'' the three ``Back to the Future''
films (also controlled by Spielberg), ``Ben-Hur,'' the four
``Superman'' movies starring Christopher Reeve, ``Lawrence of
Arabia,'' ``Saturday Night Live,'' ``Grease'' and ``Touch of
Evil.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW RELEASES OF VIDEO CASSETTES: REVIEWS BY NEW YORK TIMES
CRITICS
</P>
<P>
   THE END OF THE AFFAIR: 1999. Columbia Tri-Star. $107.37; DVD,
$27.95. 105 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release date: May 16. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Were you two lovers?'' Henry (Stephen Rea) asks Maurice (Ralph
Fiennes). In fact, Maurice and Henry's wife, Sarah (Julianne
Moore), had a wartime affair, but now Maurice is about to join
Henry in an investigation of Sarah's latest affair. In his
adaptation of Graham Greene's 1951 novel, the director Neil Jordan
brilliantly turns to the real concern: an agonizing struggle
between religious faith and carnal love. Taking artful liberties,
``he creates a seamlessly engrossing film that does full justice to
its depth of thought and feeling,'' Janet Maslin wrote in The New
York Times. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CRADLE WILL ROCK: 1999. Touchstone. $104.16; DVD, $29.99. 132
minutes. Closed captioned. Release date: May 16. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Like a crowded Diego Rivera sociopolitical lobby mural, Tim
Robbins' sprawling cinematic pastiche tries to crystallize
Depression art, government and economics into a single and grand
theatrical gesture: ``The Cradle Will Rock,'' as staged by Orson
Welles and John Houseman. A WPA Federal Theater Project, ``Cradle''
is a Brechtian agitprop work by Marc Blitzstein (Hank Azaria), who
dreams up a musical under the auspices of an imaginary Brecht.
Robbins mounts a parallel ``Ragtime''-like tableau in a ``big,
brave, sometimes maddeningly reductive film that rises through
sheer talent and enthusiasm over its own limitations'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FELICIA'S JOURNEY: 1999. Artisan. $112.18; DVD, $24.98. 116
minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. Release date: May 16. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Searching the bleak English industrial landscape for the man who
impregnated her, young Felicia (Elaine Cassidy) encounters
Hilditch, a stout, beady-eyed chef who goes home to cook elaborate
meals under the videotaped supervision of his dead mother and baste
thoughts of dark deeds revealed only gradually in flashbacks of his
encounters with women in his little green car. But don't expect a
predictable cat-and-mouse game from the director Atom Egoyan, who
``brilliantly bends this Gothic-flavored fable to express his own
tricky cinematic vision'' (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   GALAXY QUEST: 1999. Dreamworks. $22.99; DVD, $26.99. 102
minutes. Closed captioned. PG. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the stars of ``Galaxy Quest,'' an old television series along
the lines of ``Star Trek,'' tour the fan club circuit, they are
approached by real aliens, called Thermians, who mistake them for
bona fide space heroes and ask their help against enemies chasing
them around the universe. That appeals to the ``Galaxy Quest''
captain (Tim Allen), who galvanizes his crew and blasts off with
the visitors on a mission that ``offers a few genuine laughs, moves
swiftly, if not at warp speed, and is led by a talented cast''
(Lawrence Van Gelder). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   OTHER RELEASES
</P>
<P>
   A variety of other films, some of which may have had a theater
release, appeared on television or been on videocassette in earlier
editions.
</P>
<P>
   POSSESSION. In Andrzej Zulawski's striking but perplexing horror
film, a tormented woman (Isabelle Adjani) has been cheating on her
husband (Sam Neill) with a human lover and another partner who
starts out with a handsome set of tentacles. ``It's a movie that
contains a certain amount of unseemly gore and makes no sense
whatsoever,'' Vincent Canby wrote in The New York Times. That may
have been because he was watching a theatrical version stripped
down to around 80 minutes. Here, 45 minutes have been restored,
making matters complete, if not that much clearer. 1981. Anchor
Bay. $14.98; DVD, $29.98. 123 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   WALKING WITH DINOSAURS. The BBC's six-part series, shown on the
Discovery Channel, takes the big creatures from the late Jurassic
period, 220 million years ago, when land reptiles battled to
establish themselves, to the late Cretaceous, 65 million years ago,
when a giant meteor or other causes spelled the end. 1999. BBC
Video. $24.98, two cassettes; DVD, $34.98. Episodes run 30 minutes
each.
</P>
<P>
   ANNE FRANK: THE MISSING CHAPTER. Based on Melissa Muller's
biography, which reveals that several pages were removed from the
original diary, Bernard Hammelburg's documentary stirs some new
ingredients into the famous story: Anne's reflections on her
parents' unhappy marriage, descriptions of how the family lived in
Germany before the war, and the identity and motivation of the
person who betrayed them to the Nazis. 1998. Home Vision. $29.95.
43 minutes. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
