<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELL'S EARNINGS EXCEED EXPECTATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dell Computer Corp. posted better-than-expected
first-quarter earnings on Thursday, benefiting from a richer mix of
products, with particular strength in sales of servers and storage
devices for Internet use.
</P>
<P>
   For the quarter ended April 28, Dell's profit rose 21 percent,
to $525 million, or 19 cents a diluted share, compared with $434
million, or 16 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. Revenue
rose 31 percent, to $7.28 billion from $5.54 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had expected Dell to earn 16 cents a share, according
to First Call/Thomson Financial, which tracks company earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Dell reported its results, its shares closed down 25
cents, to $44.6875. In after-hours trading, Dell rose as high as
$47.625.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's relative strength could help reassure technology
investors coming after a quarter when the Microsoft Corp. reported
slower-than-expected revenue. Many analysts have suggested that
companies are embracing Windows 2000 more slowly. Dell itself said
in February that its historic growth rates were unsustainable and
projected revenue growth in the low 30 percent range.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Kunstler, an analyst with J.P. Morgan, said that Dell's
revenue only modestly exceeded his estimate but that in the current
climate, that was a positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that everyone is really nervous about PC sales, it's
good that they beat it even by a little,'' Kunstler said. ``Dell
had guided down expectations ahead of Microsoft, so it's not like
one company's results are in conflict with the other.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell said the portion of its business coming from more
profitable products continued to increase, with revenue from
servers, storage products, work stations and notebook PCs at 48
percent of sales, up from 39 percent in the quarter a year earlier.
At the same time, the cost of components declined, particularly for
memory chips, which had been in short supply until recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some better-than-expected component pricing, and a
better-than-expected product mix,'' said Kevin Rollins, Dell's vice
chairman. ``That contributed to about 2 cents of the uptick,
relative to First Call. The other penny came from tapping into our
investments.''
</P>
<P>
   Rollins said Dell remained comfortable with revenue growth
forecasts in the low 30 percent range for the rest of the year.
``There may be some challenges in the second half of the year
concerning components,'' he said, ``but that will be offset by this
continuing infrastructure build for the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Dell announced a strategy to sell products and
services to Web-based businesses. Dell said sales to the largest
dot-com companies and Internet-service providers had grown nearly
260 percent over the last two quarters. Over the last two months,
the Dell Host Web-hosting service has gained more than 2,000
customers, 40 percent of them new to Dell and half of which
switched from other host suppliers, the company said.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
