</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SCHOOL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICE PRESIDENT VISITS INNOVATIVE CALIFORNIA SCHOOL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUDAHY, Calif. _ More accustomed to dealing with conflicts
between senators or nations, Democratic presidential contender Al
Gore began Thursday by listening to fourth- and fifth-graders
explain how they cope with hostile relations at their school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do some kids get into more trouble than others?'' the vice
president asked, triggering nods from a group of students selected
to solve peer conflicts at the Elizabeth Learning Center.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spent the day meeting with students and teachers at this
innovative kindergarten through 12th grade school, which draws from
this poor and predominately Hispanic East Los Angeles enclave.
</P>
<P>
   Seated at a picnic table in the school courtyard, Gore explained
to designated student ``conflict managers'' that some children may
be more belligerent because they have ``been victims of violence''
at home.
</P>
<P>
   He praised the mediators-in-training for helping their
classmates get along without resorting to name-calling or physical
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your parents must be very proud of you,'' said Gore before he
headed off to meet with parent volunteers and then to help teach a
first-grade class.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign visit was the fifth in a weekly series of what the
Gore campaign has dubbed his ``school days,'' where the candidate
devotes an entire day at a public school, usually located in an
important electoral state.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign views the school events as a way to underscore
the candidate's commitment to what voters tell pollsters is their
top priority: education. His Republican rival, George W. Bush, has
stressed education and frequently stops by schools. Last week on a
California swing, the Texas governor visited a San Diego elementary
school.
</P>
<P>
   For Gore the school events also help to soften the vice
president's stiff image by generating photographs of a smiling
candidate interacting with students and teachers.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president, who arrived in California late Wednesday,
spent the night at the home of the principal, Emilio Vasquez, and
showed up at the school at 7 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of students, dressed in their mandatory uniforms of
white shirts and blue pants and skirts, rushed up to him as he
roamed the concrete walks linking several buildings and temporary
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Later he plopped cross-legged on the floor with the
first-graders, who engaged him in a contraction word game. As they
repeatedly outfoxed him at the game Gore mockingly moaned ``oh
nooo, you're beating me '' and clasped his hand to his head as he
burst into laughter.
</P>
<P>
   At lunchtime he queued up with the students to receive his
chicken taquitos and beans and then sat down with members of the
student council, who gave him the pros and cons of attending the
school. While many praised the learning environment, they also
complained of crowded facilities, lack of a high school library and
not enough computers.
</P>
<P>
   At an afternoon question-and-answer session with students and
teachers, Gore said he opposed legalizing marijuana for medicinal
purposes and told an illegal immigrant who asked about college aid
to speak to one of his top advisers, Donna Brazile. Last December,
Gore was more equivocal on the marijuana issue, telling an audience
in New Hampshire that doctors ought to have the option to use the
drug. However, he later backed away from that stand.
</P>
<P>
   The trip to the Elizabeth Learning Center also gave Gore the
opportunity to see how an experimental urban school deals with the
problems of poverty, violence and language barriers.
</P>
<P>
   The 3,000-student school is located in an industrial area where
the per capita income is slightly more than $5,000 and 28 percent
of families fall below the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Virtually all of the student body, which is 98 percent Hispanic,
qualifies for federally subsidized student lunches and many do not
speak English as a first language.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the Los Angeles Unified School district, the second
largest district in the country, the school has been designated an
``urban learning center,'' which means the educators have tried to
foster closer relations with the community by providing adult
education and health facilities that parents as well as students
can use.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
