<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EGAN-PROFILE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAN WHO TAKES CHARGE: ARCHBISHOP-ELECT EDWARD MICHAEL EGAN
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Conn.)   (Eds: A shorter version of this story, EGAN-PROFILE-ABRIDGED, will
also move.) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT14 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After a week of unusually explicit leaks, the Vatican
formally announced Thursday that Bishop Edward Michael Egan of
Bridgeport, Conn., had been chosen the ninth archbishop of New
York, to succeed Cardinal John O'Connor, who died last week at the
age of 80. Egan is to be installed as archbishop on June 19 in a
ceremony at St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to say we wouldn't be surprised,'' said the Rev. Roger
Caplis, a seminary classmate of Egan's in Chicago, ``that if
anything happened in New York, Ed would be considered. They know
him in Rome. That makes a big difference.''
</P>
<P>
   As a seminary student in Chicago, Egan was the only member of
his class chosen to go to Rome to finish his theology studies.
</P>
<P>
   As a young priest, he spent a mere year in a parish before he
was plucked to serve as an assistant to the cardinal of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   And later in the Vatican, he was one of six experts in church
law selected to spend mornings with Pope John Paul II over
breakfast, helping him review each word of the proposed new Code of
Canon Law.
</P>
<P>
   Hours after the Vatican's announcement, Egan appeared before the
news media, saying that when he first learned of the appointment
several weeks ago, ``My first reaction was, Edward, get down on
your knees and beg the Lord to give you a hand, and don't get up
too quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Tall and burly with a voice to match, Egan told a television
reporter who reminded him that he is now the boss, ``I don't feel
like the boss, but give me a little time and I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Those who have tracked Bishop Egan's 43-year career in the
church say that he is a man who likes to take charge. In
Bridgeport, he had his hands in everything from the pension plan to
celebrating the confirmation Masses for nearly every child
confirmed in the diocese. His supporters praise him as a hands-on
administrator, a successful fund-raiser, a lively intellectual and
a talented homilist.
</P>
<P>
   But some who know him worry that he has spent so much of his
career in Rome that he is not adequately in touch with the church
in America, where laypeople have assumed an increasingly important
role. His parish experience was so brief that he has been pegged as
an ``office priest'' rather than a ``street priest.''
</P>
<P>
   In Bridgeport, his critics say he responded more as a legal
adversary than a pastor to parishioners who claimed they had been
sexually abused by priests in his diocese.
</P>
<P>
   People who have known both Egan and O'Connor say that the two
men are temperamental opposites, with very different styles and
skills.
</P>
<P>
   Where O'Connor was spontaneous and blunt, Egan is cautious and
measured. While O'Connor was earthy, the son of a union man, Egan
is courtly, the son of a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   Where O'Connor was more interested in ministering than in
managing the business affairs of the enormous corporation that is
the New York archdiocese, Egan involved himself in everything from
architectural plans for churches to building the endowment of the
Bridgeport diocese.
</P>
<P>
   And while O'Connor was loath to close even underused schools and
churches, Egan has made some tough and unpopular decisions in
Bridgeport to consolidate and, in some cases, shut facilities in
his diocese.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's shown tremendous strength and decisiveness,'' said
Richard F. Futie, pastor at St. Mary's Church in Stamford. ``He's
been efficient, wise, prudent and thrifty, and put us on a solvent
course.''
</P>
<P>
   Egan is, by all accounts, extremely erudite. He is fluent in
Latin, Italian and French, and learned to speak Spanish while in
Bridgeport, which is home to many Hispanic Catholics. He plays
classical piano. He reads up on quantum physics and cosmology.
</P>
<P>
   He has scant experience in the political spotlight, however,
receiving a few national headlines for speaking out against
abortion and in favor of taxpayer-financed vouchers for private and
secular schools. In a little-known move, he was one of only two
Catholic bishops to endorse a group affiliated with the Christian
Coalition, the conservative political lobby founded by Pat
Robertson and Ralph Reed.
</P>
<P>
   The Catholic Alliance had been set up to attract Catholics to
the work of the Christian Coalition, which was perceived to be
dominated by Protestants. But it quickly ran into fierce opposition
from bishops who did not welcome the idea of a politically
conservative, Republican-leaning group presuming to speak for
Catholics in America.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Egan issued a letter in 1996 congratulating the
Catholic Alliance's leadership and offering ``my prayers and
cooperation.'' Egan now serves as one of five bishop advisers for
the Catholic Alliance, which is now independent from the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Egan is not a newcomer to the New York archdiocese. But last
time, he received a less than warm welcome.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Egan was appointed an auxiliary bishop in the
archdiocese after spending 14 years in Rome. O'Connor made it no
secret that Egan had been foisted on him by the Vatican. Priests in
New York still remember the letter that O'Connor sent to his clergy
members explaining that Egan was not his choice, and that any one
of them would have been just as qualified.
</P>
<P>
   When it came time toast his new auxiliary bishop at a dinner in
Rome in Egan's honor, O'Connor raised his glass and proclaimed him
``Chicago's revenge on New York.''
</P>
<P>
   When Egan left for Bridgeport three years later, many priests
said that O'Connor was not sorry to see him go.
</P>
<P>
   ``His relationship with O'Connor was very professional, but I
don't think it was warm,'' said the Rev. Richard J. Ehrens, an old
friend of Egan who is a priest in Harwood Heights, Ill. ``I think
they just had a mutual tolerance agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Edward Michael Egan grew up in a large, comfortable home in Oak
Park, Ill., the son of Thomas J. and Genevieve Costello Egan. He
had two brothers and a sister. But at 68, he has already suffered
the deaths of his three siblings and his parents.
</P>
<P>
   He decided early on a priestly vocation, attending a junior
seminary before receiving a bachelor's degree in philosophy from
St. Mary of the Lake Seminary, in Mundelein, Ill., and finishing
his studies in Rome at the Pontifical North American College.
</P>
<P>
   He received a theology degree from the Pontifical Gregorian
University, considered one of the best in Rome. On Dec. 15, 1957,
he was ordained there, and returned to Chicago the next year. The
church where he worked so briefly was not just a local parish, but
Holy Name Cathedral in Chicago. But in no time, he was sent to the
chancery offices to assist Cardinal Albert Meyer.
</P>
<P>
   He spent from 1960 to 1964 back in Rome, earning a doctorate in
canon law from Pontifical Gregorian and taking the job of
repetitor, which meant that he would repeat the Latin lectures to
seminarians in English.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The current rector of Pontifical North American, Msgr. Timothy
Dolan, said he was revered by students, and described him as
``lovable and charming, a strong and decisive Irishman _ the kind
who could really touch the heart at a policeman's funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   He spent the next seven years in Chicago, working for Cardinal
John Cody as secretary and co-chancellor, and on commissions on
interfaith relations and social concerns. At one point, Cody named
him to replace an experienced liberal priest as head of a
commission on urban affairs, which meant culling contacts in
minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like putting a square peg in a round hole,'' said the
Rev. Thomas Ventura, a priest in Winnetka, Ill. ``If you can
distinguish between a street priest and an office priest, Ed Egan
was an office priest. But in fairness to him, he really worked
hard. It was not his natural milieu, but I think he's a good
soldier and did the best he could.''
</P>
<P>
   From Chicago, Egan was sent again to Rome to be a judge on the
Sacred Roman Rota, a 21-member tribunal of judges who work in
panels of three hearing appeals in many matters of church law,
especially marriage annulments. He also taught canon law at the
Pontifical Gregorian.
</P>
<P>
   During these years he was so immersed in Roman life that once,
as a guest on a television program during a visit back to Chicago,
he had to search for words in English to express himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had never seen him at a loss for words, so I said to him,
`Ed, what's going on?''' said his friend, Caplis, the host of the
television show. ``He said: `You know what's happening? I think in
Latin.'''
</P>
<P>
   (At his New York news conference Thursday, Egan answered a
question in English but used an English transliteration of the
Italian word for condoms, ``preservatives,'' to the confusion of
some reporters.)
</P>
<P>
   It was during his years in Rome that Egan once confided his
career strategy to his friend, Ehrens, with whom he vacationed in
Turkey, Greece, Egypt and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always said, `I found it's better not to ask for something
specific, because if you do, you might be sorry that you asked,'''
Ehrens said.
</P>
<P>
   After 14 years in the Vatican, Egan was consecrated a bishop and
sent to New York to serve as an auxiliary to O'Connor, where he was
given the post of vicar for education. He won respect for his focus
on administering Catholic schools.
</P>
<P>
   But he did not hesitate to speak out on public schools,
appearing in 1987 at a contentious City Council hearing about a
proposal to distribute contraceptives in high school health
clinics. He criticized the city's sex education program and
advocated teaching abstinence, telling the council members: ``Try
decency. Try chastity. Try Western civilization,'' instead of
waiting for AIDS ``to put an end to us all.''
</P>
<P>
   As vicar of education, Egan waded into turbulent waters when he
tried to replace the long-serving Catholic chaplains at both
Columbia and New York Universities and replace them with more
conservative clergymen.
</P>
<P>
   Paul E. Dinter, who had served 15 years as chaplain at Columbia,
said that Egan told him to take a sabbatical and that perhaps
afterward the diocese would find him another job. Dinter said the
bishop's approach was ``patronizing, paternalistic,'' and though he
was offended, he decided not to fight it.
</P>
<P>
   Egan also tried to remove the Rev. Raymond Rafferty from the
chaplaincy at New York University. But after the conflict became
public, Egan was overruled by O'Connor, who allowed Rafferty to
stay on for another year and a half, to the cheers of his student
congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't mind being the bad guy,'' said Dinter, who has left
the priesthood and now runs an education program at the women's
prison in Bedford Hills. ``In a cause he considers right, he will
be a bad guy.''
</P>
<P>
   But Egan spent only a short time in New York, which church
officials say was always the Vatican's intention. After three years
and seven months, he was named bishop of the Diocese of Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   The Diocese of Bridgeport is small, home to 360,000 Catholics in
88 parishes, a far more manageable operation than its giant
neighbor to the south, the Archdiocese of New York. The Bridgeport
diocese includes 33 Catholic elementary schools and five high
schools, three nursing facilities, eight homes for the elderly, and
many charitable programs. Although the seat of the diocese is in
struggling Bridgeport, the diocese's borders are also the borders
of Fairfield County, which encompasses wealthy enclaves like
Greenwich, Danbury and Westport.
</P>
<P>
   Egan has spent the last 12 years trying to turn around his
diocese. Friends say that when Egan was installed in Bridgeport in
December 1988, he was shocked to learn just how deeply the diocese
was in debt. Bridgeport was struggling to maintain churches and
schools that depended on dwindling populations of immigrant
Lithuanians, Slovaks, Poles and Italians, who had once been the
mainstays of life in many parishes.
</P>
<P>
   Egan reorganized the school system so that the financing of
schools was shared in common by the entire diocese, and poorer
parishes no longer had to bear the cost of their neighborhood
schools. By pooling the resources, and closing several schools that
were dilapidated or poorly attended, Egan strengthened the
diocese's 38 remaining Catholic schools, say several local Catholic
leaders who have observed the process.
</P>
<P>
   The bishop initiated a fund-raising campaign, beginning in 1995,
that raised $43 million in pledges, of which about $28 million has
been received, said Dr. Joseph McAleer, the diocese's director of
communications. The money has been used to finance seminary
education, open a home for retired clergy, finance Catholic
schools, and to build a substantial endowment. In the past two
years, the diocese has opened two new schools, including the first
Catholic special education school in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept the schools open, and now they're jammed,'' said Msgr.
Stephen DiGiovanni, pastor of St. John the Evangelist Church in
Stamford. ``He set the diocese on a solid financial footing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Egan has also gained attention for his ability to produce
home-grown Catholic priests in the midst of a severe shortage of
clergymen. He opened the diocese's first seminary residence for
young men considering the priesthood six months after he arrived in
Bridgeport.
</P>
<P>
   The diocese has ordained 52 new priests since the residence
opened, and 30 men are now studying for the priesthood _ a record
that far surpasses the new priests being produced, per capita, in
archdioceses like New York or Boston.
</P>
<P>
   As in many Catholic dioceses, Bridgeport too has been shaken by
lawsuits alleging that priests sexually abused children in churches
and schools. But the small diocese has had up to 30 alleged victims
who have accused eight priests of sexual abuse. The plaintiffs
accuse both Egan and his predecessor, Bishop Walter W. Curtis, of
shuffling clergy pedophiles from one parish to another instead of
confronting the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Most _ but not all _ of the alleged abuse took place before Egan
took office there. But in one case, the plaintiff claims that a
priest who abused him in 1983 was moved by Egan to another parish
in the diocese, when, in 1993, he abused another child. The
lawsuits have dragged on for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   In April this year, the diocese announced that it had settled
one lawsuit for an undisclosed amount. Frank Martinelli had charged
that when he was an altar boy at St. Cecilia Church in Stamford, he
was sexually abused by a priest, the Rev. Lawrence Brett, between
1962 and 1964, and that the diocese covered up the abuse.
Martinelli won a $1 million verdict against the diocese, the
verdict was reversed by an appeals court in 1999, and then the
diocese settled. The diocese asked the court to seal all the
records in this and the other cases.
</P>
<P>
   Egan removed Brett from the priesthood when the lawsuit was
first filed in 1993, and in 1997, after the verdict, publicly
condemned clergy sexual abuse in a letter read during Masses in the
diocese's parishes. But his defense, the same that he used in his
legal deposition, was that priests are independent contractors, and
therefore his diocese was not liable.
</P>
<P>
   Cindy L. Robinson, a partner in the law firm of Tremont &AMP;
Sheldon, which represents 21 people claiming they were abused by
Bridgeport priests, said, ``Neither the bishop nor anyone else in
the diocese has ever offered any counseling or any apology to these
victims, and that we find quite shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked to respond, Tom Drohan, a diocesan spokesman, said, ``We
are not going to comment on what we consider less than responsible
comments by plaintiffs' attorneys.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the tests facing Egan in New York is how much latitude he
will give to lay Catholics active in their parishes, and to
Catholic institutions controlled not by the clergy but by
laypeople.
</P>
<P>
   When Egan went to Bridgeport he was surprised to learn that
Sacred Heart University, a Catholic school in Fairfield, was
independent _ a separate corporation run not by the diocese but by
a board of lay people. As bishop, he was chairman of the board, but
his vote counted no more than any of the other 25 board members.
</P>
<P>
   He tried to have that changed. He proposed rewriting the bylaws
so that Sacred Heart University would be owned by the diocese of
Bridgeport. But the university's board voted overwhelmingly against
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was accustomed to being in charge,'' said Dr.
Anthony J. Cernera, president of Sacred Heart, when asked about the
incident. ``An independent university is a standard American model,
but Bishop Egan was coming out of a long experience in Rome where
that's not how it works. But to his credit, he accepted that that's
the reality, and he has worked as very well as a member of the
board in context.''
</P>
</TEXT>
