<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2496 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV14-NY     05-11 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV14-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL COMMENTARY: IN THE `FISCAL JEOPARDY' GAME, VOTERS DECIDE
WHO WINS 
</HEADLINE>
  (For release Sunday, May 14) 
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's time for ``Fiscal Jeopardy.''
</P>
<P>
   The first answer is: About $3.5 trillion, and falling rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The correct question is: What is the national debt?
</P>
<P>
   The next answer: About $5.6 trillion and rising rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   The question: What is the national debt?
</P>
<P>
   Confused?
</P>
<P>
   Well, there are going to be many confusing claims and
counterclaims emanating from the presidential campaign trail in the
next few months about who will do more to put the federal
government's finances in order. They start with very different
definitions of the debt.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore puts his emphasis on the national debt
held by the public, the $3.5 trillion that the government has
borrowed by selling Treasury securities to individual investors,
banks, pension funds and foreign governments.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas is taking the view that the
government's obligations include not just the public debt, but also
the special bonds it is issuing to the Social Security system in
ever-growing amounts, representing promises to pay retirement
benefits in decades ahead. By that accounting, the current $5.6
trillion in total debt will grow inexorably for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   The differences are coming into play as the candidates hurtle
into a high-intensity debate about how to shore up Social Security
in time for the aging of the baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has made paying off the entire public debt by 2013 the
centerpiece of his economic agenda. He wants to use excess Social
Security revenue _ more than $2 trillion over the next decade _ to
do it.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would then channel the interest savings from debt reduction
to Social Security, in effect committing trillions of dollars of
general tax revenue to keep the system afloat. In that way, he
would extend the system's solvency from 2037 to around 2050 without
cutting benefits, raising payroll taxes or altering the way Social
Security works.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping deal with Social Security in a relatively
painless way, Gore's plan would free up trillions of dollars for
other kinds of investment, helping to put downward pressure on
interest rates and create new economic opportunities for companies
and individuals.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's approach is different. This week he plans to set out a
goal of adding private investment accounts to Social Security, a
major change that would require hundreds of billions, if not
trillions, of dollars over the next decade. The only place to find
that money is the Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   To the extent that the surplus is used to finance private
accounts, it would not be available to reduce the public debt, a
goal in which Gore sees both economic logic and considerable
political appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's team argues that reducing the public debt is not the
only way to improve the government's financial condition. Because
the private investment accounts would replace part of the
government's obligation to pay Social Security benefits in the long
run, his approach would in effect reduce the debt, broadly defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd be improving the government's balance sheet in an even
more efficient way,'' said Lawrence Lindsey, the former Federal
Reserve governor who is Bush's chief economic adviser.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of any reduction in total debt under Bush's approach
would depend on the amount of money committed to the private
accounts, a decision that Bush says should be made through
bipartisan negotiations after he is elected.
</P>
<P>
   Under Gore's approach, the public debt would sink steadily, but
all the while the Treasury's obligation to the Social Security
trust fund would be rising even faster, from $855 billion today to
$4.2 trillion in 2013. So even if the public debt is retired on
Gore's schedule, the total debt would rise, from $5.6 trillion
today to $6.8 trillion in 2013.
</P>
<P>
   The two plans are pretty much a wash when it comes to improving
national savings. ``Whether you're taking $100 billion and buying
down debt or adding it to a pool of private funds available for
investment doesn't make a great deal of difference,'' said Robert
Reischauer, president of the Urban Institute and a former director
of the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's approach is conservative in the sense that it is based on
debt reduction, but it affirms Democratic orthodoxy by retaining
Social Security as a guaranteed benefit, even if tax revenue must
pay for it.
</P>
<P>
   Bush bucks mainstream economic thinking to a degree when he
plays down the importance of wiping out the public debt. But at
heart, his plan is about transferring some control of retirement
finances from the government to individuals _ a most basic
conservative value.
</P>
<P>
   We'll be back with the final round of ``Fiscal Jeopardy'' in
November, when the voters will decide. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
