<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elian frenzy
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _TV's rush to report what happened inside the
camera-free courtroom on Thursday was apparent when WXIA's Jon
Shirek appeared outside as soon as the Gonzalez hearing ended, but
was too breathless to give a full report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me catch my breath,'' he huffed to streetside colleague
Ken Watts. He then moved off camera to do just that.
</P>
<P>
   Shirek returned moments later, still looking over notes as he
described what he'd seen from his seat inside.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's three other local stations followed WXIA, breaking
into their regular programming for varying lengths of time.
</P>
<P>
   With few compelling images and the media dominating the scene,
there were times when one station's cameras showed another station
doing its report.
</P>
<P>
   WXIA's high, overview lens looked down on narrow Forsyth Street,
on a small circle where a reporter stood talking directly into a
camera. A quick surf to WSB, and there was the reporter: Richard
Belcher, giving his level-headed analysis of what went on inside.
</P>
<P>
   The most breathless local coverage belonged to WGNX.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a wild day!'' exclaimed anchor Helen Neill,
hours before the hearing began. Meteorologist Laura Huckabee
worried about the effect of forecasted hot and sticky weather on
demonstrators. ``Makes you cranky,'' she noted. And while other
stations reported that the early crowd was subdued and made up
mostly of other media, anchor Steve Johns let viewers know from his
studio seat, ``You can really hear activity picking up out there.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN's Martin Savidge, shortly after the hearing began at 9 a.m.,
caught himself before falling into the same kind of hype.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a large crowd _ actually, it was a relatively large
crowd,'' Savidge corrected himself.
</P>
<P>
   While the Gonzalez case has been the national media's ground
zero for months, it became just another story on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The network newscasts largely played it behind the wildfires in
New Mexico and New York Mayor Rudy Giuliani's separation from his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   Fox News anchor Brit Hume sounded tired of the whole thing when
he introduced the political asylum story: ``More on little Elian's
excellent adventure. . .''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
