<HEADER>
A2509 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w BC-COURTS-HELP-HNS &LR;      05-11 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURTS-HELP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERWHELMED SOUTHWEST JUDGES ASK FOR HELP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal courts in Texas and other Southwestern
border states have become overburdened by a dramatic increase in
illegal-immigration and drug-related prosecutions in recent years,
judges from the region told Congress on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The seven jurists, in a rare personal lobbying effort by sitting
judges, urged federal lawmakers to add judgeships and increase
funding for the courts to lighten the workload.
</P>
<P>
   The judicial docket is especially large in South and West Texas,
where too few judges are being called upon to handle too many
criminal cases, said Carolyn Dineen King, chief judge of the New
Orleans-based 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get some help,'' said King, who led the delegation
of judges from five courts in Texas, New Mexico, Arizona and
California. ``Someone has to speak. Someone has to say this isn't
working.''
</P>
<P>
   King said judges and court employees have been working longer
hours to handle the explosion in prosecutions. Civil attorneys and
their clients, meanwhile, have had to wait much longer than usual
to have their lawsuits heard by judges who are constitutionally
bound to ensure that criminal defendants receive a speedy trial,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   King, who oversees the administration of federal courts in
Texas, Louisiana and Mississippi, said she has had to shuffle
judges in the three states to ensure that criminal defendants have
not languished in jail due to the massive backlog or have been set
free too early.
</P>
<P>
   She said she too often has had to send jurists with a relatively
light workload to South and West Texas to help judges there handle
cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're managing to tough it out,'' she said. But this temporary
fix will soon fail unless Congress increases the number of judges
and provides more funding for courts, King told lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Charles Gonzalez, D-Texas, expressed strong support for the
judges' call for congressional help but said his colleagues from
states not on the Southwestern border might be less willing to
confront the regional problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing fair about the process up here,'' Gonzalez
said. ``The interest (in border issues) diminishes as you start
going north.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gonzalez said the judges certainly have the backing of
lawmakers from Texas, New Mexico, Arizona and California.
</P>
<P>
   The additional burden on the courts affects not only judges but
court staff, including law clerks, U.S., marshals and federal
public defenders, who must often toil longer hours to handle the
workload, King said. In addition, federal detention centers often
fill to capacity, requiring defendants to be held in state-run
facilities hundreds of miles from the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   King and her fellow judges pinned much of the blame for their
increased workload on a Congress intent on stopping illegal
immigration and drug smuggling but unwilling to ensure that U.S.
courts can handle the resulting rise in prosecutions.
</P>
<P>
   While funding a 99 percent increase in Border Patrol agents
since 1994, lawmakers have been reluctant to raise the number of
federal judges or increase court funding along the border, the
judges said.
</P>
<P>
   George Kazen, chief judge of the U.S. District Court for
Southern Texas, called on lawmakers to pay as much attention to
prosecuting as they do to catching criminals at the border.
</P>
<P>
   The judge said the costs will only increase in his court as U.S.
attorneys, with Texas Attorney General John Cornyn's approval,
press ahead with plans to prosecute in federal court defendants who
allegedly commit crimes with a gun. The plan, dubbed ``Texas
Exile'' and inaugurated in January, takes advantage of a strict
federal law that demands that gun-toting criminals face at least
five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.S. District Court for Southern Texas, which covers
Houston and points south, the number of criminal cases filed rose
145 percent, to 3,387, between 1995 and 1999 while the number of
judges remained steady at 18.
</P>
<P>
   The five U.S. district courts in South and West Texas, New
Mexico, Arizona and Southern California handled 26 percent of the
59,923 federal court criminal filings last year. The rest of the
cases were divided among the 89 other district courts nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   King has a strong ally. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist, in a Jan. 1 statement on
the judiciary, urged Congress to assign the five district courts
more judges, citing their ``unmanageable number of immigration and
drug-related cases.'' He specifically said the court in South Texas
needs two more judges.
</P>
<P>
   As for court funding, the federal judiciary is urging lawmakers
to increase its $4.3 billion budget by $363 million, or 8.5
percent, next year. But legislation pending in the House would
provide no increase.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
