<HEADLINE>
RANGERS SHOW MAJOR DOSES OF TOUGHNESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hockey players are tough, or so we are told.
</P>
<P>
   They whack each other with sticks, pound each other into the
boards and usually walk away from the game with only a handful of
teeth. Never mind they play two or three times a week and there's
usually a line shift every two or three minutes. Hockey players are
tough.
</P>
<P>
   Football players are tough, or so we are told. They block and
tackle and maim the quarterback and usually undergo a half-dozen
knee surgeries during the course of their career. Never mind they
play once a week and are covered with pads and helmets, some
players using Novocain and cortizone shots to dull pain.
</P>
<P>
   Football players are tough.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball players aren't tough, or so we are told. They have a
great union and multimillion dollar contracts, and knowledgeable
writers such as George Will and Doris Kearns Goodwin wax poetic
about emerald grass and blue skies. Never mind they play 162 games
and a 95-mph fastball in the back hurts like ...
</P>
<P>
   Baseball players aren't tough.
</P>
<P>
   Yet there was David Segui standing at first base Sunday, playing
in obvious pain because of a strained hip flexor. Of course
football players don't get strained hip flexors; they get broken
jaws and fractured ribs. But anyone who saw Segui limping around
the clubhouse could tell that he should have either taken the day
off or been used at designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The same probably could have been said for Luis Alicea, who was
still recovering from a strained calf muscle. But the DH spot was
occupied by Rafael Palmeiro, who has a strained left hamstring
muscle, which keeps him running full speed but doesn't keep him
from hitting home runs or driving in runs. Why should it? He almost
won the Most Valuable Player Award in 1999 despite undergoing two
knee operations within two months at the start of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's bat is so valuable that manager Johnny Oates won't
let him play first base until he's as close to 100 percent as
possible. So that left Segui to hobble out to first base all this
week, showing some of the physical toughness that baseball players
aren't noted for.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a gamer,'' hitting coach Rudy Jaramillo said. ``I love
his intensity and his fire. Raffy is the same way. The hamstring is
bothering him just as much as the knee was last year but he refuses
to come out. He's in there every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his injury, Segui said, ``I don't want to talk about
it. Does it really matter?''
</P>
<P>
   Anybody who has watched the Rangers closely knows it matters a
great deal. His two-run game-winning home run on Wednesday was
spectacular; but even before that, Segui's steady stream of two-run
singles and doubles into the gap had become an indispensable part
of the Rangers' offense. If he doesn't make it out to first base
this week, the Rangers are in deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of toughness, anybody who has seen Rick Helling's
swollen right hand would also marvel at how he held the Seattle
Mariners scoreless for four innings this week after getting hit by
Tom Lampkin's line drive. Yet if he comes out of that ballgame
early Monday, the Rangers' overworked bullpen is handed an even
greater burden.
</P>
<P>
   This is an extraordinary time for the Rangers. They have more
than a half-dozen key players either on the disabled list or
playing with injuries; their bullpen is sagging from overwork and
Oates doesn't know from game to game if he needs another infielder,
outfielder or pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing he really knows for sure is catcher Ivan
Rodriguez is willing to put the gear on game after game, endure the
physical abuse of one of the most demanding positions in all of
sports and still put up extraordinary offensive numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet somehow during this difficult period, the Rangers have won
seven of 10 going into last night's game against the Anaheim
Angels.
</P>
<P>
   They might not be hockey players or football stars beating each
other senseless but anybody paying attention ought to understand
that the one thing the Rangers have going for themselves right now
is sheer physical toughness.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
