<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-YOUTH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS HOPING YOUTH WILL SERVE ANOTHER TITLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARLINGTON _ Former Rangers manager Kevin Kennedy had a favorite
postgame phrase whenever one of his players made an especially
egregious mistake, particularly when it cost his team a chance to
win.
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't player development,'' Kennedy would say, implying
that the offending player would find himself on the bench or
perhaps back in the minors if they didn't improve.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing that Kennedy isn't in charge of this year's
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   The lineup, when everyone is healthy, includes two rookies _
center fielder Ruben Mateo and third baseman Mike Lamb _ a
second-year player, right fielder Gabe Kapler and a rookie utility
player, Scott Sheldon. There's two more rookies on the pitching
staff _ starter Doug Davis and reliever Francisco Cordero _ and two
more second-year players _ Jeff Zimmerman and Mike Venafro _ in the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   They are players who won't hear any Kennedy-esque pronouncements
from manager Johnny Oates when they err. Instead they are getting
the opportunity to play through mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point, you have to develop some players,'' Oates said.
``That's what's going on. You're trying to develop people, and
you're trying to win games at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   That, of course, is the tricky part.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers want to win the American League West for the fourth
time in five seasons. But they're also committed to the youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the minor leagues,'' Oates said. ``We can win and
develop at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a theory that Oates is determined to test, even through
mistakes like Mateo failing to slide into second base on a force
play on Wednesday, like missed signs, like throwing to the wrong
base, like hanging sliders and grooved fastballs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really worried about the next 140 ballgames,'' Oates
said. ``I want to win every ballgame I play, but there's certain
areas we need to look at. Ruben Mateo is going to play center
field. When Gabe Kapler is well he's going to play right field.
Lamb is going to play third base, with \RTom\S Evans getting some
playing time. Doug Davis we've identified as the No. 1 guy in our
minor-league system.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan has the blessing of general manager Doug Melvin.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Rangers entered last night's game at Anaheim in
last place in the West with a 15-18 record, three games behind the
division-leading Seattle Mariners, and even though they have been
hit hard by injuries, Melvin wants to see if the young players can
do the job rather than try to improve or plug holes with trades,
</P>
<P>
   It's a change in philosophy from the past few years, when young
players and prospects such as Ryan Dempster and Fernando Tatis were
traded for veterans like John Burkett, Todd Stottlemyre and Todd
Zeile, and high-priced free agents such as John Wetteland and
Rafael Palmeiro were signed, all with the goal of winning now.
</P>
<P>
   The results were the three division titles, but also a
burgeoning payroll and three first-round playoff exits.
</P>
<P>
   With the blessing of owner Tom Hicks, Melvin and Oates went with
a new philosophy this season and despite the early setbacks are
determined to stick with it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't be successful year in and year out getting everybody
retail,'' Oates said. ``You can't afford everybody retail. What
we're trying to do is get some players wholesale for a couple of
years. We got Ruben Mateo wholesale, until he becomes eligible for
arbitration. We got Mike Lamb and Doug Davis, some pretty good
players, wholesale.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers paid retail for free-agent pitchers Kenny Rogers and
Darren Oliver, indicating the desire to win still exists. But they
also traded two-time MVP Juan Gonzalez to the Detroit Tigers last
November in a nine-player deal that landed Kapler and Cordero, as
well as 25-year-old second baseman Frank Catalanotto, 27-year-old
starting pitcher Justin Thompson and minor-league pitcher Alan
Webb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't trade a player we were going to have for one year
for five players that we're going to have for one year,'' Melvin
said. ``We traded for players that we're going to have for a few
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates not only is playing the youngsters, at times he's
emphasizing future development over immediate success.
</P>
<P>
   Davis had a shaky first start, but remains in the rotation
rather than being banished to the bullpen. Lamb, a left-handed
batter, hit against Mariners lefty reliever Arthur Rhodes in the
eighth inning with the score tied on Wednesday, even though three
right-handed hitters were on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a reason; there's a plan,'' Oates said. ``Why do we
let Lamb hit against left-handers? There's a plan there. We're not
talking about a year; we're talking about a career. He's our future
third baseman. Why is Doug Davis in the starting rotation? This is
his career. This is the year we're trying to look ahead.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
