<SLUG> BC-RAC-PEGASUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER RECENT NEAR MISSES, PEGASUS A TRIPLE CROWN THREAT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ A Triple Crown winner is already being
talked about _ in some minds already awarded _ and we're still more
than a week away from the Preakness. But there appears to be reason
to pardon the giddiness.
</P>
<P>
   The Triple Crown is on the tips of tongues because it has almost
been awarded three consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're as close as you're going to get to a Triple
Crown winner at this point,'' trainer Jenine Sahadi said. ``There
are other horses that I didn't think were Triple Crown horses that
got close.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be Silver Charm, the 1997 Derby and Preakness winner
who was considered a lazy horse who only ran when challenged. And
Real Quiet, the 1998 Derby and Preakness winner who had a litany of
shortcomings _ a skinny build that earned him an unflattering
nickname (The Fish), surgery to straighten his crooked legs when he
was a year old, and a racing record with blemishes (the horse
couldn't win two races in New Mexico). Speaking of a blemished
racing record, Charismatic was a claimer before he won the Kentucky
Derby last year.
</P>
<P>
   Those horses didn't fit the picture of a Triple Crown winner,
but Fusaichi Pegasus offers none of that.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, let no one tell you he's a ``freak.'' Some people
in horse racing like to refer to animals who race as easily as
Fusaichi Pegasus as ``freaks.'' No-pedigree, $17,500-yearling
purchase Seattle Slew was a ``freak.''
</P>
<P>
   Fusaichi Pegasus has a bountiful pedigree. He's out of a dam who
is a full sister to 1992 Preakness Stakes winner Pine Bluff. In
human terms, Pine Bluff is Fusaichi Pegasus' uncle. Like 1982
Belmont winner Conquistador Cielo, his father is the late stallion
Mr. Prospector. This colt brought $4 million as a yearling.
</P>
<P>
   He was bred to run like this, look like this and strike our
imaginations like this. He's no freak.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Silver Charm, Real Quiet and Charismatic, the only way
this colt perplexes us going into the rest of the Triple Crown is
the pronunciation of his name (it's not FOO-see-AH-chee).
</P>
<P>
   You can overcome that. And FOO-sah-EE-chee has overcome so many
things by winning the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   It's mostly history he has overcome. He's the first Derby
favorite to win in 21 years. He's the first horse that was winless
at age 2 to win the Derby in 33 years. He's the first horse that
won the Derby while wearing protective front wraps on his ankles in
41 years.
</P>
<P>
   But it's one thing to overcome history. It appears Fusaichi
Pegasus overcame himself to win this year's Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Most everyone saw, or heard about, Fusaichi Pegasus bucking
during his morning exercise. Most everyone knows it got so bad that
he reared, tossed his rider and landed on his back one morning.
</P>
<P>
   The colt matured, and he did it in a short period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he came around a lot,'' trainer D. Wayne Lukas said,
observing the horse he'll try to beat in the Preakness with High
Yield. ``I was impressed with him. Obviously, all the fears we had
about \Rproblems\S in the post parade have been put to rest.''
</P>
<P>
   The only time he showed emotion during the pre-race activities
came when trainer Neil Drysdale's efforts to place a fly net over
him in the walkover to the paddock were answered by two heels
flying through the air. The colt bucked; otherwise, he kept the
composure he showed during the paddock schooling session Drysdale
sent him through two days before the Derby. It was marvelous _ the
colt didn't turn a hair.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the track, some wonder if Fusaichi Pegasus turned in a
fast final quarter-mile of the race. He did _ with little prompting
from jockey Kent Desormeaux _ but it wouldn't have been the fastest
of the '90s. It's estimated that Fusaichi Pegasus covered the final
quarter in 25 seconds, quite possibly a few hundredths faster. In
'93, Sea Hero came home in an estimated 24 3/5 seconds, and
Unbridled's estimated clocking in '90 was 24 2/5.
</P>
<P>
   Others: Spectacular Bid in 24 4/5, Affirmed in 25 2/5, Seattle
Slew in 26 1/5 and Secretariat (will they ever catch him?) in 23
1/5.
</P>
<P>
   At Pimlico for the Preakness, Fusaichi Pegasus will face maybe
seven other horses. But don't expect him to be as far back as he
was in the Derby. Drysdale accurately refers to him as ``handy,''
meaning he has ability to be close to the lead under slight urging.
</P>
<P>
   And though he's a big colt, the tight turns at Pimlico shouldn't
be a problem. Big horses tend to get in the way of themselves while
running turns. But Fusaichi Pegasus is the most athletic big horse
one can find. His turn move in the San Felipe prep race at Santa
Anita was particularly astounding.
</P>
<P>
   The Triple Crown hasn't been awarded yet, even if
hard-to-pronounce, easy-running Fusaichi Pegasus makes it easy to
think that way.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
