<SLUG> BC-SC-FLAG-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTH CAROLINA ACTS ON FLAG, BUT NAACP REMAINS MIFFED 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: S.C., Ga., Miss.)   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ In the space of a remarkable month, South
Carolina has made three momentous strides in its race relations,
voting to remove one symbol profoundly offensive to black residents
and creating two new ones to honor the achievements of black
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But without exception, those actions have been opposed by the
state chapter of the NAACP, which objected to the method necessary
to achieve them.
</P>
<P>
   It was the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People that first engendered national criticism of the Confederate
battle flag that flies atop the state Capitol, which the General
Assembly has now agreed to remove. But the NAACP's refusal to
accept the compromise has brought criticism from the black and
white moderates who have always been the core of the organization's
national support, and raises questions about the continuing
effectiveness of its economic boycott of South Carolina, which was
originally intended to get the flag off the dome.
</P>
<P>
   Just after 10 p.m. Wednesday, the House joined the Senate in
voting to remove the flag from the dome and the legislative
chambers, a goal that black leaders have sought for decades. But to
remove the flag, lawmakers had to agree to the demands of white
supporters of the flag that a smaller Confederate battle flag fly
on a 30-foot pole in front of the Statehouse, near a monument to
soldiers of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, after years of refusal, the state enacted an
official holiday to observe the birthday of the Rev. Dr. Martin
Luther King Jr., becoming the last state to do so. But to get the
votes of reluctant white legislators, the General Assembly at the
same time created a state holiday on Confederate Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   And Thursday morning, a large group of state leaders broke
ground for a monument celebrating African-American history on a
Capitol greensward strewn with memorials to Confederate heroes, a
few feet from a Statehouse built of granite quarried by slaves. But
no officials of the NAACP were present for the event, and several
black legislators, annoyed by the group's absence, said it was
because a staunch flag supporter, State Senator Glenn F. McConnell,
R-Charleston, had been a leader in getting the monument approved.
</P>
<P>
   The group's leaders later said that was not the reason for their
absence, but they did not explain why they were not there.
</P>
<P>
   Although the flag is now scheduled to come down on July 1 _
assuming the Senate and the House iron out minor differences in
their bills _ James Gallman, president of the state NAACP
conference, said Thursday that the economic sanctions against the
state would continue. The group's executive board will meet soon to
discuss the extent of the sanctions, Gallman said, but he predicted
that some form of boycott would remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some satisfaction that the flag will be coming off the
dome, and, of course, we do take credit for that partial victory
that we have won,'' he said in an interview. ``But there is still a
missing piece, because the flag will still be in a position of
sovereignty on the grounds. It's going to be so prominent that I've
even had some people tell me it would have been better to leave it
up.''
</P>
<P>
   The group's absolutist position _ joined by 23 of 26 black House
members who voted against the flag compromise on Wednesday night _
has exasperated white moderates and many other black officials,
particularly the six black senators who helped broker the
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   With national attention now likely to shift to efforts to remove
Confederate symbols from the state flags of Georgia and
Mississippi, several officials said that the NAACP would eventually
have to lift the boycott, or risk having it be ignored by a public
happy to see the flag removed from the dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be happy,'' said Sen. Robert Ford, D-Charleston, a
life member of the NAACP. ``They should be counting their blessings
that their boycott helped us achieve this victory. Instead, they're
pouting because they didn't get everything they wanted. It's
childish, and it's not realistic. But after a while, I think
they'll get over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Edgar, director of the Institute for Southern Studies at
the University of South Carolina, who was at the groundbreaking,
suggested that the boycott might begin to lose steam once the flag
came down and it was no longer featured on newscasts showing the
Capitol dome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, it will still be on a flagpole, but taking it off the
dome is what's significant,'' Edgar said. ``Once the flag is down,
I think the criticism will have less impact.''
</P>
<P>
   That clearly is the hope of Gov. Jim Hodges and the state's
business leaders, who are now hoping to convince tourists and
conventions that have canceled their bookings in the state that it
is now acceptable to return. Opponents of the flag compromise have
known that this moment was coming, of course, but they say the risk
of now being marginalized is less important than the principle of
standing up for what is right.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't believe in finding the easiest way out of a problem,
the quickest compromise,'' said Lonnie Randolph, president of the
Columbia branch of the NAACP. ``There's always an attempt to do
that when dealing with black-and-white issues, but that's not what
the NAACP is about. We are going to stand on principle, even if
that makes things more difficult.''
</P>
</TEXT>
