u i BC-CZECH-GYPSIES-ART-2TA     05-11 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CZECH-GYPSIES-ART-2TAKES-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CZECH GYPSIES KNOCK HARDER ON THE CLOSED DOORS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRAGUE, Czech Republic _ Monika Horakova, a sparky psychologist
of 26, is a member of the Czech Republic's Parliament _ the only
one who is a Roma, or Gypsy. But she is still seeking criminal
prosecution against the club in her hometown, Brno, that barred her
because of her race.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's happened many times to me,'' she said. ``But the problem
is the process. When you want to get your rights and fight, it's
very difficult. It's hard to prove discrimination, and it's up to
the state prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Once, in 1998, the club owner simply said the place was full
and, after she complained to the police, a bouncer told them that
she had been ``drunk and arrogant,'' she said, laughing. The police
did not bother to investigate her charges further. Last autumn, she
said, she was told explicitly: ``You can't go in because you're a
Gypsy.''
</P>
<P>
   She paused. ``You know, it's really unbelievable in the 21st
century. But the biggest problem in this country remains racism.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, with the Czech Republic's move toward the European Union,
Horakova decided to sue in a civil court, for violation of her
civil rights. Recently, she said, still delighted, the civil court
agreed with her and awarded her damages from the club owner.
</P>
<P>
   If the money is finally paid, she said, she will give it to
children's homes and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a precedent for the Czech Republic,'' she said. ``I
was _ God! _ I was very happy about it. It gave me a bit of hope
that my children will live in a free country, in a country where
you can get your rights.'' She stopped, quickly answering the
imminent question: ``And I hope it's not just because I'm a member
of Parliament.''
</P>
<P>
   Ondrej Gina, the 49-year-old Gypsy advocate who runs the Roma
Cultural Union from a trailer in his hometown, Rokycany, is not so
sure. He has brought many cases of discrimination against
restaurant and bar owners but never won.
</P>
<P>
   The Czech Republic has a big problem in its treatment of its
200,000 or so Gypsies, he said, and while policies are slowly
improving in the capital, huge problems persist in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was born here, but the town doesn't like me,'' he said
wryly. His relations with town hall are so bad that the mayor
refuses to see him.
</P>
<P>
   Gina started his protest activity in 1988, under the Communists,
when he went on hunger strike for eight days. The next year, with
the Velvet Revolution, he started a branch of the pro-democracy
Civic Forum in Rokycany, a town near Pilsen with 13,500 people,
about 800 Gypsies among them _ 90 percent of whom are unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Open discrimination in public places and restaurants is common
here, he said. ``It's illegal, but the town silently tolerates it,
or says it's a problem for the restaurant owners.''
</P>
<P>
   For five years, he has been engaged in a court case against one
local restaurant. Local courts throw out his case. When he appeals,
higher courts send the case back down for another round. His goal,
he says, is to get the state prosecutor to enforce the article in
the criminal code that forbids such discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the precedent,'' he said. Asked about Horakova's case
in civil court, he said: ``In civil court, we bring the case as
individuals. I want the state to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   He has even had an American-style sit-in, with the press
invited. ``But nobody would serve us,'' he said. ``The staff just
walked around.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of his problem with the mayor stems from a 1997 meeting on
housing, when city officials would not talk to the Gypsies as a
group, but only as individuals. The Gypsies lay on the floor and
would not leave. The police came and filmed the protest, Gina said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they showed it on television, to show the whole nation
what a mess the Roma can make when they are allowed to meet with
public officials,'' he said. ``Now the mayor says he'll never
negotiate with Gina again.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But Gina has another reason to be proud. His son, Ondrej Gina
Jr., 29, is the first Roma news announcer on the nightly prime
time, Czech state television news.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of going to college, ``I was trained to be a cook and a
waiter, but I never worked in this field,'' he said, smiling. ``It
didn't interest me.''
</P>
<P>
   What has shaped his life is having his father as a model, he
said: ``Everything I have in me I have thanks to him.'' But the
younger Gina also took advantage of communism's fall, working for a
non-governmental foundation and then leaving, in 1992, for Germany,
where he worked for a Gypsy group run by one of the few radical
Gypsy advocates, Rudko Kawczynski.
</P>
<P>
   Gina was a press officer for three years, became interested in
journalism and then was chosen to study at the Council of Europe
and the Central European University in Budapest, funded by George
Soros. Hired by Czech Radio in 1998, Gina did so well that a
television producer asked him to try television, and he quickly
became an anchor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viewers reacted very positively to seeing a Romany on the
screen,'' he said. ``I was pleasantly surprised. Of course, I
received some negative letters as well, but everyone has the right
to an opinion, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Going abroad was better than to a university, he said: ``I
learned to fight for my rights. I learned it was possible to
challenge authority. I try to educate myself all the time. But had
I not had this experience abroad, in another culture, I would not
be what I am now.''
</P>
<P>
   To his proud father, the television job has helped all the
Gypsies. ``Of course it's made a difference, it's made us more
visible,'' Gina said. ``They can see a Romany on television every
day. And I think it surprised a lot of people. The idea still
prevails that Roma can only work with their hands and a shovel.''
And Gypsies themselves started watching the news.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gina has seen the sharp change from communism, when life for
most Gypsies was better here, if only because they had jobs and
income. The goal of the communist state was assimilation, ``to turn
us into working socialist citizens of Gypsy origin,'' he said. That
meant the repression of language, songs and culture, as well as a
controversial birth-control program involving paid sterilization.
</P>
<P>
   But it also meant a certain legal equality, guaranteed jobs,
however poor, and the repression of overt racism. Skinheads and
neo-fascists are post-communist phenomena, Gina said, ``and
unfortunately, we were the first to be targeted.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The government was slow to take these phenomena seriously, he
said, and then worried about the country's image. Political parties
``sensed the negative sentiment toward Roma and were afraid they
would lose voters if they pressed Roma issues, so they played it
both ways, doing enough to have something to say abroad, but not to
do so much as to lose votes.''
</P>
<P>
   But with a recent wave of criticism from the U.S. Congress, the
State Department and the European Union about Roma policies here _
beginning with negative human-rights reports in 1997 _ the Czech
government began to deal more seriously with a worsening situation.
</P>
<P>
   Some Gypsies had been killed by skinheads, unemployment among
Gypsies was skyrocketing, the percentage of Gypsy children put into
special schools for the retarded _ after taking tests tilted toward
Czech language and culture _ had increased.
</P>
<P>
   ``They could no longer ignore it or talk around it,'' Gina said.
``Now they admit that racism and discrimination are big problems in
the Czech Republic, and they are beginning to do something about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he said, the Gypsies have learned to organize
themselves and to publicize their grievances, not just here but
abroad. There are more indigenous Czech foundations involved with
helping Gypsies, not just foreign organizations like Soros' Open
Society Institute, which helps Gina's organization.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also too much paternalism, Horakova said, with too
many Czechs who speak no Romany making a living by helping a people
they don't understand, while Gypsies themselves go jobless. ``It's
hard to be polite,'' she said. ``I call it the Roma industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, under pressure, the government is moving to create fairer
tests for children that do not depend so much on Czech-language
skills and culture. Because of a change Horakova initiated in the
law, entrance into secondary school is now by examination, open to
anyone, even those assigned to the special schools.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The younger Gina thinks that life is slowly improving here, that
the new openness must eventually filter down from the capital to
the countryside, where local administrators still rule with open
bias.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are still many xenophobes,'' he said. ``But many people
realize there is a problem that needs to be solved. I consider the
Czech Republic my homeland. I couldn't live anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   For Horakova, there is still the sense of a double life, in the
outer world and in the Gypsy one, but she enjoys the tension.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a great example of integration here, but I didn't know how
to describe it,'' she said. ``Then a friend told me, `You have a
permanent oscillation between Czech and Roma culture.' It's true.
Sometimes in an hour, I can switch between thinking in Romany and
thinking in Czech. It gives me a richer life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud I'm Roma, and we're a part of this nation,'' she
said. ``It's not about chauvinism. But you must never bow your
head.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
