<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-LEONE-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO SEND JESSE JACKSON ON MISSION TO SIERRA LEONE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also SIERRA-LEONE, U.N.-AFRICA) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton said Thursday that the United
States would try to help the United Nations reinforce its
peacekeeping troops in Sierra Leone and that he was sending the
Rev. Jesse Jackson to the region to see if he could help negotiate
a halt to the recent violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have asked Reverend Jesse Jackson, my special envoy for
democracy in Africa, to return to the region to work with leaders
there for a peaceful resolution of this crisis,'' Clinton said in a
statement. ``Reverend Jackson has been actively involved in our
diplomatic effort to help the people of Sierra Leone realize their
peaceful aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. peacekeepers have taken up positions to defend the capital,
Freetown, from rebel attack and apparently made some progress
Thursday, but fighting remains widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton conferred Thursday morning by telephone with Kofi Annan,
the U.N. secretary-general, about American support for military
efforts in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president continued to pledge that we would do whatever we
could to support reinforcement of the mission in Sierra Leone,''
said P.J. Crowley, a White House spokesman on national security
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said the United States would remain engaged in the
conflict politically, ``and we are willing to help militarily to
help end this conflict.''
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, Clinton said, ``I have instructed our military
to provide needed assistance to accelerate the deployment of
troops'' to the region. Freetown has been girding for an assault by
the Revolutionary United Front.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeeping troops number about 8,000, but they are lightly
armed and did not expect to engage in combat. The troops went to
Sierra Leone to help carry out a peace agreement signed last July
between the government and the rebels.
</P>
<P>
   The immediate task, administration officials said, is to get
reinforcements to Freetown who are properly equipped. The
peacekeeping operation is essentially in West African hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to support the commitment West African nations have
made to send additional troops to Sierra Leone to restore peace,''
Clinton said. ``A U.S. military team is now in Nigeria to determine
what assistance might be needed from the international community to
outfit and transport these forces as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said they still knew little or nothing about the
whereabouts and condition of about 500 peacekeepers who were taken
hostage by rebels early last week. The taking of the peacekeepers,
most from Zambia, set off the latest crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said he welcomed the statement Tuesday by West African
leaders in Abuja, Nigeria, calling for the release of all hostages
and pledging to protect democratic institutions in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said the United States would help in getting some
Jordanian troops into Sierra Leone in the next few days. He said
other contingents, including Indians and Bangladeshis, would be
arriving in the region within a couple of weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Crowley said the international commitment ``should send a clear
signal to the RUF that this mission is going to be reinforced.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. is serious about stabilizing the situation and
bringing additional capabilities into Sierra Leone, to try to get
Sierra Leone back towards the peace process,'' he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
