<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2519 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-SPAIN-OLIVE-OIL-500&AMP;A     05-11 1034
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPAIN-OLIVE-OIL-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPAIN FINDS PROMISING FUEL SOURCE IN RESIDUE FROM OLIVE OIL
PRODUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BENAMEJI, Spain _ Travel this corner of Spain, with its endless
hills of olive groves, and you begin to realize why the country
thinks of itself as a kind of Saudi Arabia of olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   It is not just the vast scope of Spain's annual olive oil
production, amounting to roughly one-third of the world's total.
Spanish olives, long processed for cooking, are now being
transmuted into a fuel.
</P>
<P>
   Olive oil production leaves behind a residue of roughly 5.5
million tons of crushed olive pulp and skin. For the last three
years, the farmers around this olive-growing hamlet, population
4,600, have delivered the residue to a specially designed power
station where it is burned to produce electricity and hence reduce
Spain's reliance on the oil that the Saudis produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farmers used to dry it and burn it in ovens to heat their
homes,'' said Francisco de la Torre, who manages the olive growers
cooperative of Nuestra Senora de la Gracia, which unites 550 local
growers. In the 1970s, when cheap natural gas arrived from North
Africa, the growers began storing the foul-smelling, blackish
sludge in cesspool-like pits that reeked, attracted insects and
often polluted the groundwater.
</P>
<P>
   The power plant in Benameji, nestled between Cordoba and the
sea, produces 12 megawatts of electricity, roughly enough for four
villages this size. It has been so successful that the leading
Spanish utility, Endesa, which built it together with the Abengoa
engineering group, is about to build two more, each costing $19
million, including one near Jaen, east of Cordoba, whose groves
alone account for more than 20 percent of the world's olive oil
production. Endesa has said there is potential in Spain for about
eight more such plants, each producing 16 megawatts.
</P>
<P>
   That is hardly enough to reduce Spain's electricity needs, but
the project is a small sign of Europe's resolve to develop
renewable sources of electricity like solar power, wind energy and
biomass, that do not deplete natural resources, while helping solve
the problem of industrial waste.
</P>
<P>
   The Spanish food processing industry produces biomass that must
be disposed of at considerable cost. De La Torre's cooperative, for
instance, after pressing 2,600 tons of virgin olive oil a year, is
left with almost 10,000 tons of crushed olive skin and pulp.
</P>
<P>
   So last month, Loyola de Palacio, the European Union official
responsible for energy, who is Spanish, announced that the
15-nation union would seek to double the share of electricity
produced with renewable fuels in the next 10 years, to 12 percent
of the total from 5.8 percent. In a country where tilting at
windmills has a certain tradition, the number of giant
power-generating windmills has doubled each year since 1995, to
1,400, and is expected to reach 9,000 by 2010; after selling sun to
tourists for decades, Spain now uses it to produce about 9
megawatts of electricity with solar cells, about half the European
total.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the United States, efforts to use natural fuels like biomass
have been stymied in part by relatively low prices for oil and
natural gas. Biomass now accounts for about 3 percent of national
energy use, but that also includes wood burning to heat homes.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the Clinton administration announced in August a
long-term effort to triple the amount of energy produced from crop
wastes and farm products by 2010. The idea, administration
officials said, is to reduce reliance on imported oil, create
additional farm income and generate technologies that American
companies can sell abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Carmen Becerril, director of the Institute for Energy
Diversification and Saving in Madrid, which is financed by the
Ministry of Industry, said ``the whole secret is price.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996 Spain, lacking domestic oil and gas resources, joined
several other European countries, including Germany and Denmark, in
providing state funds to offset the difference for consumers
between the cost of providing electricity from renewable sources
and the market price. Given the relatively low cost of the required
technology, she said, government price supports for power generated
from agricultural wastes like olive skins are a fraction of those
for electricity generated by solar power or wind energy.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Luis Marin, who is responsible for diversification at
Endesa, said the power generated at Benameji is fed into the
national grid. Given its relatively small share of the company's
total electricity production, he said, only about 2 percent of what
consumers spend for power is covered by the government subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   But even with government help, the path to alternative energies
can be a slippery one. Raimon Argemi Puigdomenech, Endesa's
technical director, who helped design the Benameji plant, said the
high humidity content of the olive waste _ about 50 percent _
hindered combustion and was overcome only by adding special sand to
the mix. Moreover, hauling the olive mass from distant oil-pressing
sites proved difficult and expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Hence, Endesa's future plants will be constructed near plants
that process olive oil. The residue from such plants contains about
8 percent moisture and so burns more easily. ``The ash is very
clean; there is no sulfur, so it is nontoxic,'' Argemi said. In the
next generation of plants, he added, ``we don't expect any burning
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Endesa sees potential export markets for its technology in other
olive growing countries, including Italy, Greece and Turkey.
Indeed, on the Greek island of Crete, local utilities are already
using olive pressing waste to generate small amounts of
electricity, providing extra income to farmers. In Cuba, Endesa is
helping supply similar technology to produce power from sugar cane
waste.
</P>
<P>
   And after that? Besides olive oil, wine is among Spain's
best-known agricultural products. ``Within two years,'' Argemi
said, ``we will decide whether to build a generating plant using
the waste of wine-making.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
