<HEADER>
A2520 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-METHODIST12-COX     05-11 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-METHODIST12-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Methodists vote against homosexuality
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ In a tumultuous meeting marked by demonstrations,
arrests and a near-tumble from a balcony, the United Methodist
General Conference voted Thursday to reaffirm its stand against
homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 1,000 delegates voted 2-1 to retain language in the
church's Book of Discipline that ``homosexual practice is
incompatible with Christian teaching.'' By a similar ratio, they
voted to maintain prohibitions against the ordination of gays and
lesbians and the blessing of same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   During the votes, protesters stood silently on the floor in
keeping with their agreement not to disrupt the conference.
</P>
<P>
   But afterward, they moved onto the dais behind presiding Bishop
Daniel Solomon of Baton Rouge, La. and began singing the civil
rights anthem, ``We Shall Overcome.'' Among the demonstrators were
Bishop Susan Morrison of Albany, N.Y., Bishop Joseph Sprague of
Chicago and the Rev. Gregory Dell of Chicago. Dell has been
suspended from the ministry for blessing a same-sex union.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have decided as a group to nonviolently break the covenant
we have made with Bishop Solomon because we believe the church has
broken covenant with us,'' said Randy Miller, a spokesman for a
coalition of United Methodist organizations that support gay
rights.
</P>
<P>
   At that, Solomon put his head in his hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm burying my head in prayer,'' he said. ``I cannot witness
what is about to occur.''
</P>
<P>
   Police removed the demonstrators and charged them with
disrupting a lawful meeting, an offense that carries a maximum fine
of $250 or 30 days in jail, according to police spokeswoman Lt.
Sharon MacKay.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the meeting room, Joe Whittemore, the layman who heads
the North Georgia delegation and a veteran of two previous
quadrennial General Conferences, had tears in his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have made it clear and unequivocable that the homosexual
community is welcome in the United Methodist Church,'' he said.
``But that does not mean that we can change our doctrine and our
historical position about homosexual practice being incompatible
with Christian teaching.''
</P>
<P>
   ``No one is taking any joy in this,'' said Tom Jackson from
Athens, who supported the bans on gay ordination and same-sex
unions. ``At some point, though, the church has to clearly express
its stand. It's sad any time there is a deep division in the body
of Christ.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point in the debate, after losing the first key vote,
demonstrators made their way onto the floor while others lined the
balcony. A delegate identified later as Jeanne Smile climbed to the
rail.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am gay,'' she screamed, sobbing. ``I have been gay all my
life. I have tried to be what God wants me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   She teetered above the conference floor over the tables where
the North Georgia delegation sat. Whittemore and others scurried to
catch her in case she fell. But uniformed security officers grasped
the woman, put her into a wheel chair, fitted her with an oxygen
mask and took her away to be examined by paramedics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrifying,'' said Kathryn Johnson, executive director
of the Methodist Federation for Social Action, whose 2,000 members
are part of a coalition supporting gay rights. ``I felt for her. I
think it captures her pain.''
</P>
<P>
   The clash over homosexuality resembled previous debates that
have taken place in United Methodist and other mainline Protestant
denominations for more than two decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us who believe that homosexuality is incompatible
with Christian teaching, this is not an issue on which we can
compromise,'' said the Rev. Roger Elliot of North Carolina. ``It's
doesn't mean we are bigoted or homophobic or mean-spirited.''
</P>
<P>
   Edna Brubaker of Michigan, who said some members of her family
are gay, voiced a different view: ``God is a God who has spread the
table wide, and all have a place at that table.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Miller, a delegate from New Jersey, identified himself as a
gay man born into a family of Methodist ministers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a handful of gay and lesbian delegates in here,''
he said, ``but the rest of you are heterosexual people making
decisions about us. ... I encourage you to remember that this is my
life.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Creech of Raleigh, N.C., a former United Methodist
minister who lost his credentials for performing same-sex unions in
violation of church policy, said the day's work on the convention
floor was ``an extremely painful defeat.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he said, ``it's a defeat for the moment, not for the
long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
