<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLORADO PRODUCING AN AVALANCHE OF WHINING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ What's that you're saying? Try to speak up,
OK? It's hard to hear anything at the moment. A loud, annoying
whine keeps coming in full-blast from Denver. So unpleasant. So
unmanly. Yet ...
</P>
<P>
   Here it is, still some 36 hours from initial puck-droppage in
the Western Conference finals, but the Avalanche has already earned
for itself the second annual ``Lindy-Ruff-Cry-Me-a-River'' Award.
</P>
<P>
   Presentation ceremonies will be held in Buffalo as soon as Lindy
can be talked down from the nearest ledge. Meanwhile, tears to you,
Bob Hartley. And take another bite of sour grape, Mr. Patrick Roy.
Boy, Roy, have you ever gone sensitive on us.
</P>
<P>
   In what would appear to be very welcome ear-music to the Stars,
Colorado's coach Hartley filed a restraining order this week with
the NHL high court against one Richard Matvichuk. The charge is
that brutal behavior by our man Matty occurred in the same
conference finals matchup last May.
</P>
<P>
   Let's review the X-rays. A Matvichuk check on forward Milan
Hejduk resulted in a broken collarbone. A Matvichuk check on
forward Peter Forsberg resulted in a separated shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   Hejduk said his injury came on a clean blow. Forsberg also had
nary a whine, proving once again why the Angry Swede is the best
player in the game today. Forsberg is a rare trifecta talent _
skill, toughness and meanness. Matvichuk got him only because
Forsberg didn't get Matvichuk first.
</P>
<P>
   Hit happens. And that goes double in the kind of classic series
the Avalanche and Stars gave us a year ago. But along comes Hartley
this week, squealing like an overgrown Eddie Haskell that the
referees need to collar Matvichuk. This from the same coach who had
the despicable Claude Lemieux skating on his team last season.
</P>
<P>
   It's funny that Hartley would be singling out Matvichuk and
making him a focal point before the series even starts. To each his
own, but Ken Hitchcock goes the opposite direction in these
situations. The mere mention of Bryan Marchment creates an
emotional firestorm around here, except it's all based on media and
fan reaction. In the San Jose series, Hitchcock low-keyed the
presence of Marchment, as always, due to the theory that if his
players are thinking about Marchment, then Marchment has already
won half the battle.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Hartley is inflicted with Matvichuk phobia. Does his
team make that same mistake?
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of phobia, Patty Roy has suddenly gotten himself all
geeked-up over something said by Eddie Belfour. That's funny, too,
since Belfour is a man of such few words. In the three years he's
been in town, Eddie's most memorable statement has been, ``I need a
lawyer.'' Unless it was, ``my bail is how much?''
</P>
<P>
   Where words are concerned, Belfour knows when to say when. I've
got a billion dollars of my own that says Eddie has never been
involved in a verbal conflict pertaining to hockey. Every other
kind of conflict, yes. But Belfour doesn't say enough to merit a
scratch-your-eyes-out confrontation. Unless, however, it's the Roy
ego involved.
</P>
<P>
   On a national telephone hookup with hockey writers months ago,
Eddie answered this long, rambling question by saying he considered
himself as good a goalie as Patrick, if not better. I hate to
deflate Roy, but the quote never even made print locally. It was
not considered newsworthy.
</P>
<P>
   But Roy was so insulted he actually spent an ample amount of
time in the middle of the Detroit series answering Belfour's
comment, then said he wasn't. ``I don't feel like I have to answer
because he put all the pressure on himself,'' Roy said. ``He's the
one who's got to outplay me.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, Patty boy, get yourself a memory. He already has outplayed
you.
</P>
<P>
   Remember Game 6 last May? Then Game 7? The Stars faced
elimination in both, except the Stars won both by the same 4-1
score. Belfour looked like a billion dollars under that kind of
pressure. Roy looked like he should have been working the front
desk at the Mansion Hotel. ``I've got a room with a view for you,
Mr. Keane. And you too, Mr. Langenbrunner.''
</P>
<P>
   Somebody better break this to Roy, but do it gently. He's so
tender, you know. The pressure is squarely on you, Patrick. If your
butt is bested again by Belfour, that will end the current
comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the early returns, however, do expect an endless amount
of whining over the next several weeks. The Avs have spoken. Lindy
Ruff would be proud.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
