<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Judge says court 'embraces' task
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ ``Hello, I'm Larry Edmondson,'' the man wearing the
black suit, shiny silver tie and wide grin told the table of
startled attorneys.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers in the crowded 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
courtroom sprang to their feet and shook hands with Judge J.L.
Edmondson, who was about to don his robe and join two colleagues on
the bench to hear arguments in the Elian Gonzalez case.
</P>
<P>
   It is Edmondson's custom to address the courtroom from the bench
at the start of a day's arguments. But it is almost unheard of for
him to walk into court and speak to the audience.
</P>
<P>
   He welcomed the spectators, explained his court's procedures and
asked everyone in the gallery to remain quiet during the arguments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, we don't get many visitors here,'' Edmondson
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of you may have strong views (about Elian's case),'' he
added. ``You have a right to those views....But in no way signal to
us what those views are.''
</P>
<P>
   Oral arguments, the judge said, are used by lawyers to clarify,
sharpen and underline their positions and to give judges an
opportunity to ask questions on issues that concern them.
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson, 52, is a former school board lawyer who was appointed
to the 11th Circuit Court in 1986 by President Reagan. He told the
gallery that the judges hearing the contentious case do not shy
away from their duties.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not fear that burden,'' he said. ``We embrace it. It is
the business of the U.S. Courts of Appeals to decide hard cases. We
believe we know how to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
