<HEADLINE>
BOURQUE RESTED, READY FOR OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF WILSON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENGLEWOOD, Colo. _ Defenseman Ray Bourque, who missed the final
three games of the Avalanche's playoff matchup with the Detroit Red
Wings, took part in most of Colorado's 75-minute practice
yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing my best and doing what I have to do to get back,''
he said. ``Things are going pretty well. To know exactly when or if
it's going to happen for the opening game, we don't know yet. I'm
getting pretty anxious, I would say.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, 39, who injured his left knee in Game 3 of the
conference semifinals, participated in noncontact drills with
teammates for the second time since suffering the injury in a 3-1
loss on May 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good,'' he said. ``It's something that I welcome,
giving me some time to get ready. We play Saturday, Monday and then
we don't play until Friday. ... The way it's going, hopefully I'll
be ready.'' \Nsubheds:Budding rivalry Colorado is embroiled in a
rivalry with the Detroit Red Wings, but another with the Stars
could be looming.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's starting to be pretty good,'' forward Adam Deadmarsh
said. ``We've had some great games this year, and obviously last
year, seven games in the playoffs. Two very evenly matched teams.
If you go through every aspect of a hockey game and really compare
both teams, you'll find it equal on each side.''
</P>
<P>
   Deadmarsh said the games against the Stars have the same
intensity as a game against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be ready for a war when you play against them.
They've got a big, strong `D' that loves to hit and punish you. And
we have the same situation on our blue line.'' \Nsubheds:''Slight''
home-ice edge Colorado and the Stars are a combined 12-0 at home
during the playoffs this year. Adam Deadmarsh sees only a
``slight'' edge for the team with home-ice advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always nice to have home-ice advantage. To start at home
is always the way you want to go, but we're not to worried about
it. They played really well at home, but it's a really tough
building to win in. Their fans are great; they seem to get real
excited to play in front of them, and every shift is an important
one at home.'' \Nsubheds:Nothing but time The Avalanche will have
had more than a week between closing out the Red Wings last Friday
and its first game against the Stars tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long time,'' forward Peter Forsberg said. ``We're
not going to complain. We had a lot of rest. I think it's better
than worse than less.''
</P>
<P>
   Goalie Patrick Roy is eager to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, you'd like to be playing right away and just get
going, but I don't think it'll have any affect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But facing both teams after Game 2, because of a Tina Turner
concert, is a four-day respite before Game 3 in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the middle of the series, it's a little strange to have
three days off, but I guess there's a concert at the Pepsi
Center,'' Forsberg said. ``There's nothing we can do about it.
We've got to make sure we're ready to play the first two games.''
nn
</P>
