<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2534 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-FORD-SUVS-ART-430(2TA     05-11 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-SUVS-ART-430(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
  
 IN `CORPORATE CITIZENSHIP REPORT,' FORD CONCEDES PROBLEMS OF SUVs  
(ART ADV: Photo NYT7 is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ford Motor Co., which depends on sport utility
vehicles for much of its profit, acknowledged Thursday that they
cause serious safety and environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   In its first ``corporate citizenship report,'' issued at the
company's annual shareholders' meeting in Atlanta, Ford Motor said
SUVs vehicles contributed more than cars to global warming, emitted
more smog-causing pollution and endangered other motorists. The
automaker said it would keep building them because they are so
profitable, but would seek technological solutions and look for
alternatives to the big vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor's voluntary admission that it faces a ``dilemma''
because its most profitable products are not socially responsible
has few parallels, according to Business for Social Responsibility,
a corporate group in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, William C. Ford Jr., the company's 43-year-old
chairman and a great-grandson of Henry Ford, depicted the company's
statements as a combination of altruism and long-term business
planning. He said he worried that automakers could wind up with
reputations like those of big tobacco companies if they ignored
sport utilities' problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``The court of public opinion sometimes decides before you're
ready for them to decide, and I want to make sure we're ready and
ahead of the curve,'' said Ford, who became chairman 16 months ago.
The company has sought to portray itself in recent months as the
most environmentally conscious automaker.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ford and Jacques Nasser, Ford Motor's chief executive, said
they had no plans to stop making sport utilities, including the
immense Ford Excursion, which weighs as much as two Jeep Grand
Cherokees and gets just 10 miles to the gallon in the city and 13
on the highway.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we didn't provide that vehicle, someone else would, and
they wouldn't provide it as responsibly as we do,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Nasser cautioned that while customers consistently said in
market surveys that they wanted more environmentally responsible
products, they were unwilling to pay more for them or to sacrifice
features on their sport utilities.
</P>
<P>
   For the last two years, Ford Motor has voluntarily built its
sport utilities to emit far less tailpipe pollution than allowed by
law. Ford has also voluntarily installed bars below the bumpers of
the Excursion to reduce the risk that it will override cars during
collisions, even though there are no federal regulations on this.
</P>
<P>
   The company is making progress, Ford said. ``It's sort of a
`watch this space' thing, it's going to get better as time goes
on.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   With sport utilities accounting for a fifth of Ford's sales _ up
from 5 percent in 1990 _ and the bulk of its profit, the
automaker's financial stability could be affected if the sport
utility market slumped, warns Standard &AMP; Poor's, the credit rating
agency. While Ford does not release profit margins by model,
financial analysts say that the company earns $10,000 to $15,000
apiece on Ford Expeditions and Lincoln Navigators and up to $18,000
apiece on Ford Excursions; the factory in Wayne, Mich., that builds
the Expedition and Navigator is the world's most profitable in any
industry, generating roughly $3 billion a year in pre-tax profit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Thursday's report clearly expressed the company's concern
that the big vehicles have inherent problems. ``Sustainability
concerns associated with SUVs raise issues relative to Ford's
corporate citizenship commitment,'' the report said, later adding:
``We believe that the steps Ford has taken to date are only a
beginning in addressing the issues raised by these products. Our
task is to develop additional technological solutions and identify
and implement alternative ways to satisfy customers that build a
sustainable competitive advantage while meeting our environmental,
social and economic objectives.''
</P>
<P>
   In a question-and-answer section of Thursday's report, Ford said
that it might be difficult to persuade Wall Street that it was
worthwhile for Ford Motor to take big steps to be perceived as a
progressive, environmentally friendly company. ``Analysts are
focused on the next quarter's report, and at most, your next year's
report,'' he said. ``And the kinds of issues we've been discussing
today have payoffs 5, 10, 20, 50 years down the line. I do believe
that I'm building a stronger Ford Motor Co. for my children and
grandchildren. But that's not a theme that resonates very well with
most analysts.''
</P>
<P>
   John Casesa, an analyst at Merrill Lynch, said Wall Street would
tolerate the company's emphasis on social responsibility provided
that it did not prove enormously expensive. ``It's not going to
make the stock go up, it may make the stock go down, but good
companies are respected,'' he said. ``It may take years before
consumers buy a Ford because it's a responsible company, but it
won't take years for regulatory authorities and communities to say,
`This is a company we can work with.'''
</P>
<P>
   (STORY CAN ALSO END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   The Ford family has a long tradition of public service, best
shown by the family charity, the Ford Foundation. The Ford family
controls 40 percent of the votes at Ford Motor through a special
class of shares and will cement its grip under a plan announced
last month in which most shareholders will receive a special
dividend of $20 a share but the Ford family will receive additional
common stock in the company.
</P>
<P>
   Ford's comments Thursday confirm a shift in his position on
sport utilities. An ardent fly fisherman who bought his own fly
fishing rod company, he has been active in environmental causes
since his days at prep school and then Princeton.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he was also one of the company board's most enthusiastic
supporters of the decision to introduce the Ford Expedition
full-sized sport utility vehicle in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sport utilities are three times as likely as cars to kill the
other driver in a crash, but the death rate for sport utility
occupants is just as high as for car occupants because of sport
utilities' tendency to roll over and their lack of crumple zones.
While current regulations allow large sport utilities to emit up to
5.5 times as much smog-causing pollution a mile as cars, President
Clinton announced rules in December that will require sport
utilities to meet the same standards as cars by 2009.
</P>
<P>
   Business for Social Responsibility said one parallel to Ford's
actions lay in BP Amoco's vow two years ago to reduce the global
warming caused by oil consumption, even though it is the world's
second-largest oil company. Another, less direct parallel lies in
the Liggett Group's acknowledgment in March 1997 that cigarettes
are addictive and cause cancer _ an admission that followed years
of litigation and medical studies, the group said. ``Ford's actions
today place it in a small set of companies,'' said Rebecca Calahan
Klein, the group's vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Top executives at other automakers defended their records for
social responsibility, while acknowledging that sport utility
vehicles posed problems. ``We're every bit as responsible on safety
and environmental issues'' as Ford, said James Holden, the
president of DaimlerChrysler's Chrysler unit, while adding that,
``All of the manufacturers are pursuing whatever we can do on
safety while meeting consumer demands, and sometimes those are at
odds.''
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler canceled in December its well-advanced plans to
build a full-sized Jeep. Bud Liebler, the company's vice president
for marketing, said in January that one reason for the company's
decision had been a fear that safety and environmental concerns
would sour the public on large sport utility vehicles before
Chrysler could get the vehicle to market.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, General Motors plans to increase its production of
full-size sport utilities by 20 percent next year. G.M. declined to
comment today on Ford's position. GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler are
roughly tied in global sport utility sales.
</P>
<P>
   While Ford started the sport utility boom in 1990 with the
introduction of the Ford Explorer, the company has not been as
aggressive in expanding production as its rivals since Ford took
over the leadership of the company at the beginning of last year.
And while automakers usually spend $50 million to $100 million on
advertising to promote a new model, Ford spent just $420,000 in the
fourth quarter of last year to announce the introduction of the
Excursion, according to Competitive Media Research, an ad-tracking
service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
