<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-REACT-2TA     05-11 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-REACT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGING GIULIANI: DECORUM OUTWEIGHS MORALITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-GIULIANI) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Over sandwiches and keyboards Thursday, around soda
machines and bus stops, it seemed as if New Yorkers were barely
bothering with the news: the marital problems of Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and his wife, Donna Hanover.
</P>
<P>
   ``Come on, we knew a long time ago this wasn't much of a
marriage,'' said Sidney Levitan, 89, a retired high school
administrator.
</P>
<P>
   There was even more than a bit of boredom over who was to blame.
``With the kinds of lives they lead, always busy, barely seeing
each other, I mean, how can you really hold a marriage together?''
asked Scott Howell, 24, who works in marketing for an office
products company.
</P>
<P>
   Instead _ in a world where divorce is common, where a
presidential scandal has inured people to accounts of infidelity,
where talk shows obliterate lines between public and private dozens
of times every morning _ the questions Thursday seemed to revolve
less around the dissolution of a marriage and more around the way
the husband and wife were conducting themselves as they do the
dissolving in full public view.
</P>
<P>
   Did Giuliani violate what seemed to be a longstanding agreement
with his wife that they would not discuss their marriage in front
of television cameras? Did he force Hanover into the obviously
uncomfortable position of revealing their personal problems
herself? Was it unfair of Hanover, or beneath her, to mention
publicly that the mayor had had a relationship with a member of his
staff?
</P>
<P>
   Or is either to blame for how the revelations unfolded? Instead,
were they backed into a corner by the media coverage of their
marital problems.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases Thursday, the refrain on street corners and in
Internet chat rooms contained more than hint of hypocrisy. In one
breath, people said that the drama of a political-marriage soap
opera was riveting, and they have, of course, been fixated on every
twist. In the next breath, they said they were ashamed that their
mayor and first lady seemed to have taken the media's bait,
lowering themselves to participate in a slightly more decorous
version of the Jerry Springer Show.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is clear. When it comes to assigning blame for how
that all got started, Giuliani comes in for the brunt of the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to go on TV and say he was getting a separation,
without talking to his wife ...'' said John Peterson, 44, scowling
as he finished off his fries at the Roosevelt Field Mall in Garden
City, N.Y. ``If he does this to his family, what will he do to the
people?''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson added: ``You don't do it this way. If you have a
problem, you discuss it with your wife, you discuss it with a
priest or somebody, you come to a civil agreement. You don't just
put it out in the media and crush your wife.''
</P>
<P>
   In dozens of interviews Thursday from Albany to downtown
Brooklyn, the overwhelming sentiment about Giuliani's marital
problems seemed to follow a familiar script that played out among
many voters during the impeachment battle over President Clinton's
affair with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Those interviewed said that Giuliani's actions within his
marriage should have no political consequences, because his conduct
as a husband has little bearing on his abilities to be a mayor or
even a senator.
</P>
<P>
   But for many, his handling of the announcement on Wednesday that
he was seeking a separation, one that took Hanover by surprise, did
have troubling political implications because it reminded people of
the aggressive _ some called it reckless _ way that Giuliani has
handled many other public disclosures, such as the release of the
arrest record of Patrick Dorismond, the unarmed black man who was
shot to death by the police in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that his comments when Dorismond was killed
indicated a lack of control, a lashing out,'' said Nancy Dubler,
the director of the bioethics division at Montefiore Medical
Center. ``That was the analogy that I thought of when he made this
announcement yesterday, an announcement that both his staff and his
wife were unprepared for. I find that disturbing in someone who's
in a position of power.''
</P>
<P>
   Her feelings served as an apt illustration of a theme that
played out in many interviews: criticism of Giuliani _ and to a
lesser extent of Hanover _ seemed to keep returning more to
considerations of decorum, fairness and grace under pressure than
to morality or marital infidelity.
</P>
<P>
   Dubler said she thought that the mayor's surprise announcement
``showed disregard for his wife's feelings, yes, but that seems to
miss the fact that he lost it, and their presumably carefully
negotiated positions of privacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He blew it,'' she added. ``Why, we don't know. It indicates a
lack of control over what you say in challenging situations, where
someone in the mayor's position needs more discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Carrington, an administrative secretary who works with
Dubler, echoed that view. ``Somebody's going to get hurt anyway,''
Carrington said, ``but you can do it in a way to lessen the pain as
much as possible. You can be more responsible in how you approach
it. I'm trying to be objective and not be judgmental, but she
seemed to be very hurt by it.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
