<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ford Acknowledges Risks of Sport Utility Vehicles
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor, which depends on sport utility vehicles for much of
its profits, acknowledged that they cause serious safety and
environmental problems. Ford said that the vehicles contributed
more than cars to global warming, emitted more smog-causing
pollution and endangered other motorists. Ford said that it would
keep building them because they are so profitable but would seek
technological solutions and look for alternatives to the big
vehicles. William C. Ford Jr., the company's chairman, depicted the
company's statements as a combination of altruism and long-term
business planning.
</P>
<P>
   Increase in Foreign Workers Urged
</P>
<P>
   Racing to keep up with a booming economy, President Clinton
proposed an increase of more than 85 percent in the number of
skilled foreign workers who could be admitted to the United States
to fill job openings in the high-technology industries.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch Joins the Perks Parade
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch has joined the rush of Wall Street firms offering
new perks and risk-free investment opportunities to attract young
investment bankers and prevent others from defecting to Internet
companies. Merrill is building a new fitness center for employees
and providing a concierge service. The firm also hopes to lock in
investment bankers by giving them chances to invest in new-economy
companies that are still private.
</P>
<P>
   Denver Papers in Joint Agreement
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Rocky Mountain News announced that it intended to
combine its business operations with those of The Denver Post. The
agreement, which would end the nation's fiercest newspaper war,
would leave the Denver area with two newspapers that would compete
journalistically but split their profits.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Climb, With Nasdaq Up 3.4 Percent
</P>
<P>
   Stocks climbed after a report of a slowdown in retail sales
calmed investors who have been selling stocks amid fears about
rising interest rates. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 178.19
points, or 1.7 percent, to 10,545.97. The Nasdaq composite index
jumped 114.85 points, or 3.4 percent, to 3,499.58, and the Standard
&AMP; Poor's 500-stock index increased 24.76 points, or 1.8 percent, to
1,407.81.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Rises 21 Percent at Dell Computer
</P>
<P>
   Dell Computer posted a 21 percent increase in first-quarter
profit, beating Wall Street expectations, as it benefited from a
richer mix of products, with particular strength in sales of
servers and storage devices for Internet use. Before Dell reported
its results, its shares closed down 25 cents, to $44.6875. After
hours, Dell rose as high as $47.625.
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, Olive-Fueled Electricity
</P>
<P>
   In Spain, olives are being transmuted into a fuel. For the last
three years, farmers around one olive-growing hamlet have delivered
the residue of olive oil production to a specially designed power
station, where it is burned to produce electricity, thus reducing
Spain's reliance on imported oil.
</P>
<P>
   Retail Sales Dropped 0.2 Percent in April
</P>
<P>
   Sales at the nation's retailers fell 0.2 percent in April, the
first time in a year and a half, as consumers took a breather after
three months in which they spent at the fastest rate in 17 years,
government figures showed.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Up at Gap but Down at Kmart
</P>
<P>
   Two retailers, moving in opposite directions, reported earnings.
Gap said its first-quarter earnings rose 16 percent, bolstered by
sales at new stores, while Kmart said profit plummeted 61 percent
as cool and rainy weather dampened demand for spring clothes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
