<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2549 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.S.-CHINA-ARMS-NYT &LR;      05-11 0796
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-CHINA-ARMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA LIKELY TO MODERNIZE NUCLEAR ARMS, U.S. BELIEVES
</HEADLINE>
  By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration, responding to a
detailed public warning by China against proposed national missile
defenses, said Thursday that it believed Beijing would go ahead
with modernizing its nuclear forces regardless of Washington's
plans for a new system.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether or not we proceed with national missile defense,
China's nuclear forces would expand in a way that would make this
system less threatening to China,'' said a senior administration
official who briefed reporters on arms control at the State
Department.
</P>
<P>
   The official, an expert in arms control, sounded an apparently
conciliatory note by saying that while the administration had
explained to China that the proposed system was designed to defend
against ``rogue'' states like North Korea and not against China,
there had been insufficient discussion with Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't had the kind of deep national security or
international security dialogue with China that we would like to
have for the last couple of years because of the continuing fallout
from the embassy bombing,'' the official said, referring to the
American strike against the Chinese embassy in Belgrade last May
during the air war over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on Wednesday in Beijing, China's chief arms
negotiator, Sha Zukang, said that if Washington proceeded with
deployment of missile defenses, ``we will not sit on our hands.''
He described the missile shield as a threat to China's security and
outlined several possible responses, including producing more
nuclear warheads and devising ways to erode the effectiveness of
the missile shield with decoys.
</P>
<P>
   On Capitol Hill, the strongest proponents of a missile system
interpreted Sha's warnings as confirmation of the need to proceed
with the program.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Jesse Helms, R-N.C.,
who favors a more robust defense than the limited version now under
discussion, asked how China could criticize the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``After issuing nuclear threat after nuclear threat, China now
has the nerve to complain that a U.S. missile defense is a threat
to their security?'' he said. ``To the contrary, leaving the
American people vulnerable to Beijing's nuclear blackmail is a
threat to U.S. national security.''
</P>
<P>
   Another proponent of the missile defense, Sen. Jon Kyl, R-Ariz.,
said he regretted that Sha interpreted the system as a threat to
China. ``This or any other system is purely defensive in nature,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials have only recently focused on China's
concerns about the missile program. Japan and Australia,
Washington's allies in the Pacific, have expressed concern that the
system will unsettle the relationship between the United States and
China.
</P>
<P>
   After President Clinton announced in January 1999 that he would
seek, under certain conditions, to deploy missile defenses, the
administration paid most attention to Russia. For the system to go
ahead, the 1972 Anti-Ballisitc Missile Treaty signed by the United
States and the Soviet Union needs to be amended.
</P>
<P>
   In a trip to Beijing earlier this year, Deputy Secretary of
State Strobe Talbott and a group of senior officials sought to
explain to the Chinese, including Sha, that the system was not a
threat to China and was not being built because of concerns about
China.
</P>
<P>
   But according to several accounts, the Chinese found the
American arguments unconvincing.
</P>
<P>
   This was in large part because China, unlike Russia, does not
have a large nuclear arsenal capable of overwhelming the limited
program proposed by the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, China's nuclear capacity would be sharply limited even by
the limited system that Washington insists is designed to thwart
North Korea. Western experts estimate that China has 13 to 20
land-based intercontinental ballistic missiles, with one warhead
each.
</P>
<P>
   The administration official who briefed reporters Thursday said
China had maintained ``a very small force level of some 20,
roughly, ICBM's.''
</P>
<P>
   A spirited debate has been under way among intelligence
authorities in the past year about China's nuclear missile plans
and what role Washington's missile proposal is playing the
development of those plans.
</P>
<P>
   Some experts believe that a national missile defense would
encourage China to speed up its modernization effort in ways that
it would not otherwise consider.
</P>
<P>
   One of steps China would be likely to take is building missiles
capable of carrying many warheads, each capable of being
independently programmed to hit separate targets, according to
Jonathan Pollack, an expert on the Chinese military at the Rand
Corp.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
