<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, May 12, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   PIPELINE-SAFETY (Washington) _ Federal legislation to improve
pipeline safety remains in doubt, despite the fact that the effort
has bipartisan support in Congress and is backed by the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Pope. (Story will move in the ``w'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   HANFORD-REACH (Seattle) _ Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt next
week will come to the region to explore designation of the Hanford
Reach as a national monument. The Hanford Reach is the last
free-flowing stretch of the Columbia River and home to the most
productive salmon run remaining in the United States outside
Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   By Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   DIABETES-REVERSE (Seattle) _ The first attempt to reverse a
disease that affects 1 million people nationwide is likely to get
under way in Seattle this summer when researchers try to turn off
the process that causes juvenile diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   By Carol Smith. (Story will move in the ``a'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Oakland) _ Seattle Mariners travel to Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   By John Hickey. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-KAHUNA (Undated) ``The Big Kahuna,'' produced by and
starring Kevin Spacey, is not exactly a great play, and its
enigmatic, open-ended conclusion is a bit of a letdown. But the
dialogue is delightfully acerbic and often profound, Spacey is a
delight to behold in this kind of slyly aggressive role, and he's
generous enough as a producer to allow Danny DeVito to quietly
steal the movie with the most totally appealing and seemingly
heartfelt performance of his career.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-BATTLEFIELD (Undated) _ ``Man is an endangered species,''
alerts the introductory card to ``Battlefield Earth,'' the
adaptation of L. Ron Hubbard's ``Star Wars''-inspired, epic sci-fi
novel. It should have warned us that logic was also hitting hard
times.
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-TRAFFIC (Undated) _ Justin Kerrigan knows his rave scene.
The Brit native makes his feature debut writing and directing
``Human Traffic,'' a portrait of the chemical generation in
Cardiff, Wales. But for all his flash and fantasy, Kerrigan lacks
the profane poetry and dangerous edge of ``Trainspotting'' and the
sheer sense of surprise of ``Go.'' What's left is a bubbly,
high-spirited paean to the joys of pharmaceutical phun that grooves
to a throbbing beat but constantly trips over flat, prosaic
dialogue and literal, lifeless sight gags.
</P>
<P>
   By Sean Axmaker. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HELDUP (Undated) _ ``Held Up'' is a real dud, with few
laughs, no characterization, little story, a cluster of stereotypes
and cliches and just plain nothing for star Jamie Foxx to do.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-JESUS _ With the Messiah portrayed as a party-loving,
joke-playing average guy and Satan done up like an Armani-clad,
heavily moussed Hollywood mogul, the CBS miniseries ``Jesus'' runs
little risk of being confused with anyone's idea of Sunday school.
But ``Jesus'' is more than just all right. It is enjoyable, and
director Roger Young, a veteran of such biblical TV projects as
``Joseph,'' ``Moses'' and ``Solomon,'' has made ``Jesus'' relevant
and reverent.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
