<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-SAFETY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE BROAD SUPPORT, PIPELINE SAFETY LEGISLATION UP IN THE AIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CHARLES POPE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Despite bipartisan support in Congress, the backing
of the White House and the galvanizing memory of last year's
firestorm in Washington state, prospects for passing pipeline
safety legislation anytime soon appear murky.
</P>
<P>
   That realization has spurred a renewed push to approve tougher
standards in the wake last June's pipeline explosion in Bellingham,
Wash., which killed two 10-year-boys and an 18-year-old man. The
fire was touched off after a pipeline ruptured and spilled 275,000
gallons of gasoline into a creek.
</P>
<P>
   What hope there is for quick action rests in the Senate, which
could send a pipeline bill to the floor by early next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am committed to moving a comprehensive pipeline ... bill
through the legislative process as soon as possible,'' said Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., chairman of the Commerce Committee. His
committee Tuesday heard wrenching testimony from the parents of
those killed in the June 10 fire, as well as comments from members
of congress and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must act to help improve pipeline safety and prevent future
tragedies like that which occured in Bellingham,'' McCain said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the House, the only attention has been a hearing before a
House subcommittee last year on a bill introduced by Rep. Jack
Metcalf, R-Wash., who represents Bellingham.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf wrote Wednesday to Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of
the Transportation Committee handling his bill, beseeching him to
quicken the pace. Metcalf's fear is that if progress isn't made
soon, there will not be enough time in an already shortened
legislative session to bring the bill to a vote.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Shuster acknowledged that the safety bill is not
among the committee's top priorities. The aide said there has been
no date set to consider it.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf's bill, and similar Senate versions backed by Sens.
Patty Murray, D-Wash., and Slade Gorton, R-Wash., would require
safety certification of pipeline employees, public notification of
leaks, periodic internal inspections of pipelines and a nationwide
map pinpointing the location of pipelines. That map would be
available through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   All the bills attempt to address what their authors believe is
lax oversight by the federal Office of Pipeline Safety as well as
spotty efforts by pipeline owners to maintain equipment, train
operators and ensure safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are 2.2 million miles of pipelines running across this
country,'' Murray told the Senate committee Thursday. ``We cannot
wait any longer, and we certainly cannot let this year pass without
improving our nation's inadequate pipeline safety laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorton was equally adamant. ``At tragic cost, we have obtained a
chance now that we will not have next year,'' he said. ``The
accident in Bellingham and the tireless efforts of the families of
the victims ... have catalyzed interest in this issue, interest
that I'm afraid will wane if we do not act now.''
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf has been leading the effort in the House, and is
intensifying a personal lobbying campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year's deadly pipeline accident in Bellingham ... focused
nationwide attention on the issue of pipeline safety,'' Metcalf
wrote to Shuster. ``We believe that the time is ripe'' for the
Transportation Committee to consider a bill, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Metcalf also pointed out that the Senate committee handling
similar legislation ``appears poised to move ... soon. It is
important for the House to affirm its commmitment to the safety of
our communities by passing a bill as quickly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   He also is targeting members in such states as New York, New
Jersey, Minnesota, Georgia, Ohio, Florida and California that have
endured pipeline accidents in recent years. That effort paid off
when Reps. Dennis Kucinich, D-Ohio and John Lewis, D-Ga., agreed to
support his bill.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any doubt about the human toll of pipeline
accidents it was quickly and solemly dispelled when the parents of
those killed in Bellingham spoke to the committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Mary King, whose 10-year-old son, Wade, was
killed as he played near the creek that filled with gas and then
ignited.
</P>
<P>
   ``A mother remembers, the silence is deafening,'' King said,
breaking into tears as she recited a poem she wrote in memory of
her son. ``A school bus drives by, my child is not there. ... My
son forever is 10 years old. My arms seem so empty.''
</P>
<P>
   When she finished, her husband, Frank, described how he found
his son and his son's friend, Stephen Tsorvious, who each were
burned over 90 percent of their body. ``The skin was literally
dripping off their fingers,'' said King, who was interrupted gently
by McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. King, I'm not sure that is necessary,'' McCain said of the
graphic testimony.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the four-hour hearing, little had been resolved
beyond the visceral realization of loss suffered by Bellingham and
the need for tougher standards.
</P>
<P>
   King, a car dealer who had scant experience with congressional
politics, could not predict what might happen next.
</P>
<P>
   Except for this: ``To me, it's a no-brainer. These changes are
needed. But if it doesn't happen, the next accident will bring me
back here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope a town doesn't get blown off the face of the Earth
first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
