<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-CROWD-PM0512-CO     05-11 0511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-CROWD-PM0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDS:THIS IS THE P.M. VERSION
 &HT;    Protesters vent wrath at Castro
 &HT;    By Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dan Hernandez has never been to Cuba, but his parents,
who left in 1961, have told him of the bad times.
</P>
<P>
   They have more recently criticized Juan Miguel Gonzalez, the
Cuban whose son, Elian, was found on an inner tube off the Florida
coast last fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard some stories,'' said Hernandez, a 35-year-old
college student who held up a sign Wednesday that he made on his
home computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elian's Father Is Unfit,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez was one of about 45 demonstrators who hissed, cheered,
screamed, clapped and chanted outside the 11th Circuit Court of
Appeals in Atlanta on Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers and judges stuck to dry legal language in the courtroom,
but the street outside was alive with emotion. People trembled and
cursed. They got red in the face and wagged their fingers talking
about whether Elian should live with relatives in Miami or go back
to Cuba with his dad.
</P>
<P>
   On hand to document the spectacle was an army of news reporters
and photographers strong enough to muster 23 satellite TV trucks,
18 SUVs and a helicopter or two. Dozens of police officers stood
behind barricades while colleagues on motorcycles, bikes and horses
kept an eye on the crowd. Rembe Rodriguez, 15, a 10th grader, and
his 9-year-old brother, Ignacio, held a sign that said ``Castro's
Cuba : New and Improved Apartheid.'' They were born in the United
States but said their parents and grandparents, who were born in
Cuba, taught them about Fidel Castro's regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm grateful I can be here and express myself,'' Rembe said.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators yelled encouragement in English and Spanish
when Elian's Miami relatives left the courthouse. They denounced
Gregory Craig, attorney for Juan Miguel Gonzalez, when he faced TV
cameras to read a hand-written statement.
</P>
<P>
   There were light moments.
</P>
<P>
   Restaurateur Christman Hampton strolled towards the crowd
holding a posterboard menu hawking ``Eggs Elian for $3.50'' at his
nearby Dugout Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're going to keep protesting, I have good food.''
</P>
<P>
   At a day care center near the courthouse, a handful of toddlers
pressed their faces against a window overlooking the protest. Some
pointed with chubby fingers at all the people outside. Others just
smiled.
</P>
<P>
   A half-dozen people or so showed up to support Juan Miguel
Gonzalez. Jim Wolbrink and Alice Chen held a sign urging support
for ``parental rights over politics.'' They met in an online
chatroom called the ``Elian Gonzalez Message Board'' and each paid
about $200 to fly to Atlanta from Detroit and Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Zizza, 31, said courts pay more attention to mothers than
fathers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the mother was in Cuba saying, `I want my son! I want my
son!' we would be, like, `How can we separate a mother from her
son?' Juan and fathers like myself fight for fatherhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
