<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2559 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-XEROX-CEO-460&AMP;ADD-NYT     05-11 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-XEROX-CEO-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDER IS OUT AFTER BAD YEAR AT XEROX HELM 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLAUDIA H. DEUTSCH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Xerox Corp., besieged by competition and a battered stock price,
ousted its chief executive, G. Richard Thoman, on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Anne M. Mulcahy, 47, head of the company's general markets
organization, was named president and chief operating officer.
Because those were the titles Thoman held before being named chief
executive, Mulcahy's promotion seemed to elevate her to heir
apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have not and are not going to look outside for the next
CEO,'' said Paul A. Allaire, the chairman, who has assumed the
chief executive post for now.
</P>
<P>
   The ouster apparently took Thoman, 55, by surprise. In an
interview last Friday, he acknowledged that Mulcahy ``has a good
chance at being my successor'' but made it clear that he expected
to remain chief executive for some time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board and I agreed,'' Thoman said in an interview
Thursday, ``that it made more sense to implement our strategy with
an internal team. And I'm a very big shareholder, and a lot of my
future net worth is dependent on how well Paul and Anne do.''
</P>
<P>
   Allaire, who preceded Thoman as chief executive, said the board
moved now to install the new team in time for the company's annual
meeting next Thursday. But analysts said they were concerned that
more was at play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to wonder if April's numbers turned out to be a lot
worse than they expected,'' said Gibboney Huske, an analyst with
Credit Suisse First Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman's 13-month reign at Xerox has been marked by more
troubles than triumphs. Xerox hired him away from IBM in 1997 to be
president of the company, with the clear understanding that he
would succeed Allaire as chief executive. It was the first time the
company, which is based in Stamford, Conn., had put an outsider in
its top slot, and Thoman was expected to churn out new products and
technologies and generally invigorate the stodgy culture at Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the company has had weak sales overseas, particularly
in Brazil. In the United States, fierce competition has kept prices
down for printers and lower-end copiers. Even the Xerox Docutech
line of superfast digital copiers, which command prices well over
$200,000, is facing competition: both Canon Inc. and Heidelberger
Druckmaschinen AG, which bought Eastman Kodak's copier business
last year, now have high-speed products.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Xerox, which traded in triple digits two years ago,
have been in free fall for the last year. Xerox closed Thursday at
$25.50, down $2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was convinced Thoman wouldn't survive the year,'' said Brian
L. Merriman, president of Danka Business Systems, one of Canon's
main distributors. ``If they're going to get aggressive, flexible
and fast enough to compete with the Japanese, they'll need a new
management team.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Xerox has also faced internal tumult. It has eliminated more
than 14,000 jobs in the last two years to reduce costs. It
consolidated many back-office operations last year, causing
backlogs in accounts receivables and billing problems. And it
rejiggered its sales territories, long organized by geography,
around customer industries. Chaos has resulted, as sales
representatives try to acquaint themselves with new accounts.
</P>
<P>
   The company has also been slow to increase sales on its Web
page. ``Their e-business strategy hasn't been clear to customers or
to the street,'' said Stephen Goldstein, vice president of
Renaissance Strategy, a consulting firm that has worked with Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   Mulcahy would not be her industry's first woman executive _
Carly Fiorina, the chief executive at Hewlett-Packard, to whom
Mulcahy bears an uncanny physical resemblance, got there first. But
Mulcahy has scored a number of firsts in her 24-year career with
Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   She has run sales territories in New York City and Boston that
had long been male bastions. In 1985, as head of the Xerox human
resources organization, she became the company's first female
officer. Last year, she led Xerox's first forays onto the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Now she leads the company's fastest growing new entity, the
general markets organization _ a $6 billion business, started in
January 1999, that concentrates on selling Xerox products to small
businesses and consumers. That means pushing Xerox into superstores
like CompUSA and other distribution channels that have long been
Hewlett's forte.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year Mulcahy masterminded the purchase of
Tektronix, a $1 billion business that finally gave Xerox a line of
color printers to compete with Hewlett.
</P>
<P>
   Those who know her offer laundry lists of her positive
qualities. But many question whether her experience is broad enough
to run Xerox.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anne is incredibly open and honest,'' said David A. Nadler,
chairman of Delta Consulting Group, which has done work for Xerox.
``But she's not a technologist, and she's never been heavily into
product development.''
</P>
<P>
   James W. Lundy, a research director at Gartner and a former
Xerox employee, said: ``She certainly has leadership and
motivational skills. But she's been at Xerox an awfully long time,
and that doesn't give her an outside perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   An outside perspective did not help Thoman much. ``We haven't
implemented strategies as well as we should have, and I think Rick
Thoman's being an outsider was part of the problem,'' Allaire said.
</P>
<P>
   Thoman agreed. ``It's hard when you come into a company with a
proud heritage and a long culture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For her part, Mulcahy said: ``I know the Xerox team well. I know
how to get things done, and I clearly intend to stay focused on
flawless execution.''
</P>
<P>
   She may be inheriting a company on the mend. Jonathan
Rosenzweig, an analyst with Salomon Smith Barney, said, ``It's got
two new color copiers that will be gangbuster successes, and a
platform of digital copiers that are truly cost competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, Xerox announced an alliance with the Sharp Corp. and
with FujiXerox, a joint venture with Fuji Photo Film Co., to make
inexpensive ink jet printers. Last month, Xerox and Microsoft Corp.
said they would create a joint venture company, ContentGuard, to
produce and market software that protects copyrighted materials
like books, music and video distributed over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   First-quarter earnings were a pleasant surprise, too. The
company's income before previously announced charges fell to $220
million, or 30 cents a diluted share, compared with $343 million,
or 48 cents a share, in the period a year earlier. But analysts had
not expected it to top 25 cents a share. Revenue was up 3 percent,
to $4.43 billion, which many investors took as a sign that Xerox
was finally back in growth mode.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
