<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2560 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LOS-ALAMOS-DECISION-N     05-11 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOS-ALAMOS-DECISION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANNED BLAZE IS CLOSE COUSIN OF WILDFIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (with LOS-ALAMOS-FIRE)  
 (Eds: This was eliminated earlier but is now restored)  
 By GEORGE JOHNSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The hard truth of fire management is that the conditions most
auspicious for a ``prescribed burn,'' in which dangerously dense
pine forests are purged of combustible debris, are not so very
different from those that can lead to a devastating wildfire. The
weather must be dry enough for brush, dead wood and thickets of
stunted pine trees to ignite, and there must be enough wind to
spread the flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's never completely safe,'' said Dr. Wallace Covington, a
professor at Northern Arizona University's School of Forestry in
Flagstaff. ``You offer up a little prayer and hope for the best,
because the situation might get out of control.''
</P>
<P>
   If the fires are set in the spring, when conditions in the
Southwest are hot and dry, there is a danger of losing control of
the flames. But if the fires are set in the fall, when it is cooler
and wetter, temperature inversions may trap the smoke, choking
nearby residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the devil and the deep blue sea,'' Covington said. ``More
people die of emphysema and heart disease from smoke than are ever
killed from wildfires.''
</P>
<P>
   In the worst possible case, like the one that set off the fire
around Los Alamos, N.M., the wind and heat become too intense. The
flames leap into the forest canopy causing a raging ``crown fire''
that jumps from tree to tree. Tall dry pines, loaded with sap,
explode from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   To decide whether a planned fire ``meets the prescription,''
meaning that it is likely to remain under control, foresters plug a
list of factors into a computer model: the amount of wood and other
tinder in the forest, the moisture content of the fuels, the
relative humidity and temperature of the air, the speed of the
wind. They also refer to an esoteric gauge called the Haines index.
This factor takes into account the humidity on the ground and how
fast the temperature of the air cools as it is measured higher and
higher above the terrain.
</P>
<P>
   Everything is a tradeoff. Since heat rises, a high Haines index
may mean that flames, climbing the gradient of temperatures, will
leap to form a crown fire. But the vertical motion can also quickly
get rid of suffocating smoke.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very difficult science,' said Dave Simon, Southwestern
director of the National Park Conservation Association, a nonprofit
group that monitors national parks and monuments. ``There should be
more prescribed fires going on in the national parks and forests,''
he said. ``It's absolutely essential that we inject fire back into
these ecosystems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
