<HEADER>
A2563 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BUD-ADAMS-HNS &LR;      05-11 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUD-ADAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TITANS' OWNER APOLOGIZES FOR GESTURE MEANT FOR EX-HOUSTON MAYOR &HT;    
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID BARRON 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
 &QL;
<P>
   HOUSTON _ In his zeal to take yet another swipe at old foe Bob
Lanier, Tennessee Titans owner Bud Adams waved his middle finger in
the air _ and promptly stuffed his foot in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Adams sheathed his finger and extracted his tootsies long enough
Thursday to issue an apology to Lanier, the former Houston mayor
who was at the receiving end of Adams' off-color gesture Wednesday
in Nashville, Tenn.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' blunder came at a news conference to unveil the Titans'
American Football Conference championship ring and 1999 highlight
video. The former Houston Oilers, who moved to Tennessee in 1996,
advanced to Super Bowl XXXIV in January but lost to the St. Louis
Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a moment of triumph, Adams couldn't forget his feud with
Lanier, whose opposition to a publicly financed stadium in Houston
prompted the team's move to Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   Adams placed a prototype of the new championship ring on the
ring finger of his left hand. A ring from the Oilers' American
Football League championship days in the early 1960s was on the
ring finger of his right hand. He was asked where he would wear a
Super Bowl ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I'll tell you, we're going to be there,'' he said.
``Someone said, `Where are you going to put that ring, the first
AFL championship and AFC championship ... where are they going to
put that next ring?'''
</P>
<P>
   Adams then held up his right hand and extended the middle
finger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `I'm going to put it right on this finger and say to
the mayor of Houston, ``There it is, Mayor, take a look at it,'''''
Adams said, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   A clip of Adams' comments was shown on Nashville station WKRN,
which blurred the offending digit. It was fed to KTRK, Houston's
ABC affiliate, and to ESPN, which aired it Wednesday night and
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Adams issued an apology of sorts Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologize for my gesture yesterday, which was obviously done
in jest,'' Adams said in a statement. ``I should not have displayed
in public my personal feelings toward the former Houston mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the future I will make sure I leave the past behind and
concentrate on the great organization and fans we have here in
Tennessee.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams left his Houston office Thursday afternoon for a speaking
engagement in Mississippi and was not available for further
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Lanier, who was out of town on business, said through a
spokesman, ``I appreciate the apology.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL spokesman Greg Aiello said Adams would not be disciplined
for the gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' gesture reveals the apparent depth of bitterness he feels
over his failure in 1994 to obtain Lanier's backing for a new NFL
stadium. Adams began talks in 1995 to move the team to Nashville,
and the Oilers played their last game in Houston in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After playing in temporary homes in Memphis and Nashville, the
renamed Titans moved to Nashville's new Adelphia Coliseum and rode
a wave of upsets into the franchise's first Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Adams continues to live in Houston, where his role in the city's
pro football history has been largely forgotten in the excitement
over a new NFL franchise, owned by Bob McNair, that will begin play
in 2002 at a new stadium that will be built with public and private
funds. In 1994, Adams had been willing to put millions of his own
money into a Houston stadium as well.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
