<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIABETES-REVERSE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS WILL TRY TO REVERSE PROCESS THAT CAUSES JUVENILE DIABETES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CAROL SMITH  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The first attempt to harness the immune system to
prevent a disease that affects 1 million people nationwide is
likely to get under way in Seattle this summer when doctors try to
turn off the process that causes juvenile diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major shift in approach,'' said Dr. Gerry Nepom,
director of the Virginia Mason Research Center in Seattle whose
work led to the new approach.
</P>
<P>
   The diabetes trial would test two different immune system
molecules to try to prevent the disease that occurs when the body's
immune system attacks itself, turning on islet cells in the
pancreas and destroying their ability to make insulin. Because the
body requires insulin to regulate blood sugar levels, patients rely
on daily injections of insulin for the rest of their lives.
Serious, sometimes fatal, complications can occur.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers, comprising a new consortium of immunologists, met
in Seattle Thursday night to review the clinical trial protocol.
Once approved, the trial would enroll a total of 60 patients with
newly diagnosed juvenile diabetes in two age groups _ 7 to 14, and
14 to 25. The trial would take place at multiple centers, including
Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Consortium members had their inaugural meeting just prior to the
kickoff of the American Association of Immunologists meeting, which
runs through Tuesday in Seattle. The AAI meeting, the world's
largest gathering of immunologists, will bring more than 4,000
immunology researchers to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The consortium, called the Tolerance Network, includes about 15
research sites, and recently received $170 million in startup
funding from the National Institutes of Health, the Department of
Energy and the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation. The aim is to speed
the discovery of new treatments for autoimmune and other
immunological disorders by coordinating trial protocols and sharing
data.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to Virginia Mason, four other research centers are
involved in recruiting and testing patients for the diabetes trial.
</P>
<P>
   At the time juvenile diabetes is usually diagnosed, patients
have already lost 80 to 90 percent of their islet cells and will
eventually lose them all.
</P>
<P>
   If the new treatment works, doctors hope they can prevent the
loss of the final cells. More importantly subsequent trials would
look at intervening earlier, eventually saving enough cells to
prevent patients from relying on daily injections of insulin.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is controllable, diabetes can lead to serious
complications, including blindness, kidney failure and circulatory
problems. Juvenile diabetes affects about 0.4 percent of the U.S.
population, and is the second largest autoimmune disorder in the
country, after rheumatoid arthritis, which affects about 1 percent
of the population.
</P>
<P>
   The diabetes work symbolizes a new era in the understanding and
treatment of autoimmune disease.
</P>
<P>
   Autoimmune disorders comprise about 50 diseases that attack
various parts of the body. Rheumatoid arthritis, for example,
causes painful, debilitating joint inflammation while scleroderma
causes a disabling hardening of connective tissue. Taken together,
autoimmune disorders affect about 5 percent of the population.
</P>
<P>
   Although researchers don't fully understand what triggers the
diseases, they suspect some combination of environmental and
genetic factors causes the body to turn on itself.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, all these diseases were treated differently, said
Nepom, who was one of the first researchers to discover that
juvenile diabetes is a form of autoimmune disease.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, however, scientists have discovered that despite the
wide variety of symptoms and effects, most autoimmune diseases
ultimately involve malfunctioning in some common immune system
pathways.
</P>
<P>
   The only other trial to try to prevent juvenile diabetes was in
Europe in the mid-1980s when scientists tried to use cyclosporine,
a powerful immune suppressant, to halt the disease. But the drug,
which can have toxic side effects, caused kidney failure and the
trial failed.
</P>
<P>
   In the last several years, scientists have discovered a host of
immune system molecules, called cytokines and chemokines, that tell
cells in the immune system what to do and direct them where to go
in the body. Researchers are now on the verge of understanding how
to use these immune system molecules to modify, or even reverse,
autoimmune diseases, such as rheumatoid arthritis, lupus,
sceleroderma or Crohn's disease, an inflammatory disease of the
small intestine. Such an approach could be a vast improvement over
the ``brute force'' use of powerful immune suppressants, such as
steroids or chemotherapy drugs, which can have debilitating side
effects, Nepom said.
</P>
<P>
   The common denominator is that T-cells, the body's main attack
cells for protecting it against foreign invaders, get turned on, he
said. But instead of warding off pathogens, such as bacteria or
viruses, the cells mistakenly attack normal tissue and cells in the
body.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, rheumatoid arthritis and juvenile diabetes
couldn't be more different, he said. ``You have joints versus
pancreas, kids versus adults. There are zillions of differences.
But in terms of the mechanism at the cellular level, they are very
similar.''
</P>
<P>
   If scientists can intervene to turn off or stop the spread of
T-cells at the cellular level, they could well change the course of
the disease, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Being able to use those immune cells could also have
implications for fighting infections, and for preventing rejection
of transplanted organs and tissue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good news is you can develop common therapies that (could
be) good for everything,'' he said. ``What we learn from one
disease, we can apply to others.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
