<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2574 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FRANKEL-INSURANCE-NYT     05-11 1087
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRANKEL-INSURANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN JAIL CELL INTERVIEW, FINANCIER CLAIMS INNOCENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The man accused of masterminding the largest insurance fraud in
American history, Martin R. Frankel, now insists his complex
financial dealings were a legitimate effort to feed the world's
hungry.
</P>
<P>
   In his first interview since his capture eight months ago in
Germany, Frankel portrayed himself as a victim, saying he had been
brought low by a charitable nature and a tendency to trust others
too much. ``Probably the main reason that I'm here,'' he said, from
inside the Hamburg jail where he is being held, ``is that I love
people too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have charged him with bilking insurance companies of
more than $200 million in a scheme they say involved several
priests, a high Vatican judge and a phony charity.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel was interviewed in Germany this week by Brian Ross,
chief investigative correspondent for ABC News. A videotape of the
interview, scheduled to be shown Friday night on ``20/20,'' was
made available to The New York Times under a collaborative
agreement between the news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, Frankel never directly denied the charges
against him, which include fraud, money laundering, conspiracy and
racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he said that a life sentence, which he faces, would
violate ``human dignity and human rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Appearing on camera with a scraggly beard and silver-rimmed
glasses askew, the 45-year-old former stockbroker offered a defiant
case for leniency, saying that his supposed crimes were only
financial. ``There is no violence. No one is murdered. No one is
killed. No one is physically harmed,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. prosecutors say that Frankel built an elaborate criminal
empire using a financial trust, a brokerage house and a Catholic
charity with links to the Vatican as fronts to buy small Southern
insurance companies, which he then drained of more than $200
million in assets. From his Greenwich, Conn., mansion, he used the
money to buy luxury cars, fur coats for his girlfriends, and
eventually $16 million in diamonds and gold to finance his flight
through Europe, according to a 36-count indictment issued last
October by the U.S. attorney's office in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   While Frankel declined to discuss the specific charges against
him during the interview, his remarks offer a curious psychological
portrait of an alternately grandiose, glib and self-pitying figure.
``I wish that I didn't have this incredible ability to predict
things in the markets,'' he said, ``because then I never would have
gotten into this position.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 35-minute interview, Frankel said that his goal was never
to get rich but to ``feed all the hungry people in the world;
that's the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Or at least, try to,'' he continued. ``That was my goal of my
whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he granted the interview because he wanted to make the
case that it was against German law for him to be extradited.
``Under German law,'' he said, ``no human being arrested in Germany
can be sent back to a country where they will either execute him,
or put him in jail for the rest of his life.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his German lawyers, Dirk Meinicke, when reached by phone
in Hamburg, said of Frankel's statement, ``It's his opinion.'' He
added that Frankel spoke with ABC against Meinicke's advice.
</P>
<P>
   A high state court in Hamburg has approved Frankel's
extradition, but Frankel must first stand trial next month on
charges of passport fraud and customs-tax evasion. Frankel had nine
false passports with him and a cache of diamonds when he was
arrested Sept. 4 at a luxury hotel in Hamburg.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the U.S. attorney's office, Delcie Thiebault,
said Thursday that she would not comment on Frankel's remarks but
that the process of extradition was ``under way.''
</P>
<P>
   Conditions in the Untersuchungshaften Jail, where Frankel spends
his days alone in a cell, wearing the same blue shirt and khakis in
which he was arrested, are far from the conspicuous luxury of his
past life.
</P>
<P>
   For six years, he ran a stock-trading business from his mansion,
hiring submissive female companions to do office work, indulge his
taste for sado-masochistic sex, and bait potential business
partners.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel said, however, that he was loyal and loving to these
women, and supported them financially even after he stopped dating
them. ``I wanted a woman who loved me, who respected me, who wanted
to stand by me and stick with me and be with me forever,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His scheme soon collapsed under its own weight, according to
legal documents and a diary that he maintained in the margins of a
1999 astrology guide that was turned over by a travel companion to
the FBI. The diary documents how state regulators from Mississippi
and Tennessee grew suspicious, asking to see how he had invested
the premiums from various insurance companies. He also notes death
threats and attempts at blackmail by various colleagues alongside
notes about bizarre sexual acts, scheduled haircuts and visits to
his mother in Toledo, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   To persuade Mississippi regulators of his solvency, he had a
now-retired member of the Vatican Supreme Tribunal sign a false
affidavit saying that Frankel had $1 billion in Vatican money in
the Catholic charity that he created and controlled, the St.
Francis of Assisi Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   In his interview with ABC, Frankel insisted that ``never in a
million, never in a billion years,'' was this charity a cover for
criminal activity. He said ``The most hungry people we fed. Yes, we
fed some of the most hungry people in the world.'' He declined,
however, to specify how much money was in the charity, or how it
operated.
</P>
<P>
   Last May, after failing to appease state regulators, Frankel
fled the country, leaving documents ablaze in his mansion. From the
debris, police officers recovered a ``to do'' list, in which
``launder money'' was prominently listed.
</P>
<P>
   During the last eight months _ while he has struggled in jail
with dental problems and tried, unsuccessfully, to get kosher food,
according to his lawyers _ his legal troubles have only deepened.
At least three of his former associates have cooperated with
federal prosecutors, providing information about Frankel's
transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not a financial genius,'' he said, laughing and shaking
his head during the ABC interview. ``If a financial genius would
end up in here, then they're not a genius by definition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
