<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2575 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-PRACTICAL-MAN0512-COX     05-11 1105
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRACTICAL-MAN0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    OK, I'll think `happy' - but I won't like it!
 &HT;    By The Practical Man
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ This week, the practical man has a promise to
keep.
</P>
<P>
   Be happy.
</P>
<P>
   It happened during a conversation with a reader. This woman,
peeved by his proclamation that males befriend only attractive
females, lingered at length over three pungent points: The
practical man is a) an insensitive idiot, b) an arrogant idiot and
c) merely an idiot.
</P>
<P>
   Then she got personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your whole column stinks, Practical Man.''
</P>
<P>
   Does not!
</P>
<P>
   ``All you ever do is gripe, gripe, gripe.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuh-uh!
</P>
<P>
   ``Would it kill you to say something nice? Doesn't anything make
you happy?''
</P>
<P>
   ``People who know when to shut up'' came to mind, but the
practical man held his tongue. Instead, wearied by his whupping and
desperate to drive her away, he made a fatal vow: This week he
would criticize no one, make no smart remarks and write only about
stuff he likes. It was heavy lifting, but here he goes _
gripe-free.
</P>
<P>
   THREE THINGS THAT MAKE THE PRACTICAL MAN HAPPY
</P>
<P>
   Quilting: No, the practical man doesn't make quilts, but he does
admire skill and he knows it was happiness he felt when he sat on a
porch in the mountains of North Carolina and watched somebody's
grandma work wonders with needle and thread. He bought one _ not
because he needed it, but because her expertise made him feel good
and he wanted to keep the idea of it around.
</P>
<P>
   Similar things also make the practical man happy: Hearing Pat
Metheny play guitar, watching a cabinetmaker fit a dovetail joint,
remembering how his old man _ a lifelong grocer _ could add prices
in his head faster than you could punch them into the register. The
skills smart people can develop over a lifetime of dedication are
truly inspiring, and they inevitably make the practical man smile.
</P>
<P>
   Of course _ and the practical man swears he's not going to gripe
here, but just gently point out a valuable truth _ to appreciate
those skills, you have to invest some effort of your own. A
dovetail joint fails to impress if you've never tried to make one
yourself. A mathematician's manipulations are a mystery to those
who use calculators to balance their checkbooks. And Metheny's
might means nothing to music ``lovers'' who don't know rhythm from
blues, or an E string from a G string. Your chances for happiness
are higher if you spend more time doing things yourself _ even if
you do them poorly _ and less time watching others perform.
</P>
<P>
   The Amish: Sure, the practical man has some religious issues to
work out here, and he's not sold on the eighth-grade education
limit, but you've got to give one thing to the Amish: They don't
need squat _ no malls, no TVs, no SUVs, no nothing that they can't
make or grow or build themselves, and by God, they can make and
grow and build some grade-A stuff.
</P>
<P>
   So while the practical man slaves away on the old Work Boring
Job/Buy Crap You Don't Need treadmill we've all chained ourselves
to, it gives him hope and makes him happy to think there are people
around with the brains and the balls to say screw it, to mean it
and to stick to it.
</P>
<P>
   Pounding nails: The practical man is happiest when he's working,
and he loves work of all kinds _ even the pantywaist keyboard
pecking he's doing right now. But while brain work has its
satisfactions, nothing is more rewarding than work that requires
sweat as well as smarts. Thus, the practical man's favorite jobs
are carpentry, construction, auto mechanics and the like, which can
wear him out in both body and mind, plus produce useful results.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the practical man might make a career of one of these
occupations if they didn't pay so poorly. But in our society, jobs
that require hard work and procure immediate, valuable results are
considered menial and go unrewarded. Instead, venture capitalists,
stockbrokers, bankers, athletes, talk-show hosts and other
parasites who produce nothing are the ones who get rich, while the
folks who build the country and keep it running and feed our
families get diddly.
</P>
<P>
   And that's definitely not griping. That's just the facts.
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: My 8-year-old daughter keeps pulling the old
``I can't go to school because I'm sick'' routine. Except it's
really the old ``I can't go to school because I want to play
Barbies and watch TV'' routine. I've tried to explain to her that
lying is bad, but it's not getting through. Any practical advice?
And please, don't suggest spanking. I'm not that kind of mom.
</P>
<P>
   It's old-fashioned, but you can still teach a lying child to
stop _ with Aesop. You just have to up the stakes in those
farmer-dude fables to make an impression on TV-tainted tots.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the practical man once solved your parental puzzler by
reciting a special version of ``The Boy Who Cried Wolf'' to one of
his kids. The punchline went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``And this time, when the shepherd boy hollered, no one came to
help him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the wolf get his sheeps?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yep. And then the wolf got him _ ripped him up, dipped him in
ketchup, gobbled him down, howled at the moon and drug the boy's
shepherd stick back to his cave so the baby wolves could sharpen
their teeth on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Who cares if that last part isn't in the fable? Aesop never had
to go to bat against Barbie and ``Rugrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Dear Practical Man: The other day I got cut off in traffic _
again! It really ticked me off, so I cursed the dude out and gave
him the finger like any red-blooded American driver should. But
then the guy slammed on his brakes in front of me, got behind me,
tailgated me, ran up beside me like he was going to run me off the
road and generally terrorized me for about 10 miles down I-95. I
was scared to death. How would the practical man have handled this
situation?
</P>
<P>
   Well, the next time you get cut off, instead of shouting the
same lame old cuss words, you could try swearing in Japanese, or
maybe Elizabethan style: ``Thou prating clapper-clawed manikin!
Thou villainous rough-hewn hempseed! Thou warped shag-eared
varlot!''
</P>
<P>
   The practical man learned these handy slams at The Elizabethan
Curse Generator (www.tower.org/insult/insult.html), and he thinks
they're a brilliant stroke. They get the anger off your chest but
expose you to no danger, for the other driver won't know what
you're talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Your other option is to learn to control your emotions and keep
your mouth shut, but we wouldn't want to go that far, would we?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
