u w BC-HOUSING-DISCRIM-NYT     05-11 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-DISCRIM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE SUPREMACIST AGREES TO TELEVISED APOLOGY
</HEADLINE>
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a settlement that entailed as much public
humiliation as punitive fines, the Department of Housing and Urban
Development on Thursday announced that a Pennsylvania white
supremacist must make a public apology to a woman he acknowledged
harassing and must help promote anti-discrimination efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Under the unusual settlement of a civil suit, Roy E.
Frankhouser, a self-described ``chaplain'' to the Ku Klux Klan, has
agreed to issue a televised apology to his victim, Bonnie L.
Jouhari, a former social worker who helped people file housing
discrimination complaints in Reading, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   And not on just any television show. To apply added force to the
punishment, Frankhouser must read the apology aloud on ``White
Forum,'' the public access show he hosts on the local cable system.
He must also submit copies of his apology to Jouhari, who is white,
to be published in the local newspaper and The Philadelphia
Inquirer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Frankhouser must broadcast public service
announcements informing the public about laws against
discrimination in housing, at the end of the show _ or any other
show he hosts _ for three years.
</P>
<P>
   He also must display _ on the front of his house, so that it is
visible to people on the street _ a poster supplied by HUD that
opposes bias in the sale or rental of housing. And he must attend
HUD-approved sensitivity sessions and perform 1,000 hours of
community service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this settlement makes a very loud statement, not just
to this particular case, but to anyone who would think of engaging
or involving themselves in this hideous type of behavior,'' HUD
Secretary Andrew M. Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement ends a case that began in 1997, when Frankhouser
reportedly began his campaign of harassment against Jouhari and her
daughter, Pilar Danielle Horton, who was in high school at the
time. At that time Jouhari had filed a complaint with the police
department accusing Frankhouser of possession of automatic weapons.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Jouhari said, the burley Frankhouser began sitting
on a public bench just outside her office and taking photographs of
her through the front window. He also broadcast pictures on his
show of Jouhari that were taken from the Web site of another white
supremacist, including a computer-generated video of an explosion
destroying Jouhari's office.
</P>
<P>
   At about the same time, Jouhari said, she and her daughter began
receiving threatening telephone calls and in 1998, Jouhari found a
flier placed on her car reading, ``Race Traitor Beware.''
</P>
<P>
   Jouhari said she first tried to persuade local and federal law
authorities to pursue criminal charges against Frankhouser, who is
a member of the United Klans of America and who, according to HUD
officials, had been arrested at least 142 times. But the local
police and the Justice Department reportedly declined to file
criminal charges, citing Frankhouser's First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   Jouhari said in an interview that the harassment caused her to
fear for her life and to flee with her daughter, first to a nearby
town in Pennsylvania and later to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to leave my job, my home, my career, take my child away
from everything that she knew because they elected not to enforce
the law,'' said Jouhari, who no longer lives in Seattle, but would
not identify her current residence.
</P>
<P>
   With the Justice Department reluctant to pursue a criminal case,
HUD opted to file a civil case.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement announced on Thursday also required Frankhouser
to refrain from mentioning Jouhari or her daughter _ except to
apologize _ in any public forum for the rest of his life. He must
also stay at least 100 feet away from Jouhari and her daughter for
the rest of his life.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, for the next 10 years he must pay 5 percent of his
total salary to Jouhari and 5 percent to her daughter in any year
that he earns at least $25,000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
