   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- May 11, 2000 -- PHILLIPS-AUCTION-2 -- A
Phillips auction house employee points to Picasso's ``Sleeping Nude
and Woman Washing Her Feet'' in the main gallery of the American
Craft Museum in Manhattan during Phillips's first big evening
auction, Thursday. Phillips, the world's third-largest auction
house, announced that three percent of the hammer prices would go
to the American Foundation for AIDS Research. ``Suprematist
Composition'' sold for $17 million. (Michelle V. Agins/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- May 11, 2000 -- PHILLIPS-AUCTION-1 --
Auctioneer Dan Klein, taking bids on Kasimir Malevich's oil on
canvas called ``Suprematist Composition'' in the main gallery of
the American Craft Museum in Manhattan during Phillips's first big
evening auction, Thursday. Phillips, the world's third-largest
auction house, announced that three percent of the hammer prices
would go to the American Foundation for AIDS Research.
