<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2579 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-POWER-PLANT-POLLUTION     05-11 0580
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-PLANT-POLLUTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESTIMATE OF TOXIC CHEMICAL EMISSIONS IS TRIPLED
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ohio, N.J.)  By WINNIE HU   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N. Y. _ The first national accounting of toxic chemical
emissions by electric power plants and the mining industry has
tripled the estimated volume of those releases.
</P>
<P>
   The report, which was compiled by the federal Environmental
Protection Agency, showed that in 1998 7.3 billion pounds of toxic
chemicals were reported released by eight industries including coal
mining, chemical wholesalers and petroleum terminals.
</P>
<P>
   The environmental agency said metal mining accounted for nearly
half of all discharges and that power plants released 1.1 billion
pounds of toxic chemicals in 1998, or about 15 percent of the
total. The previous year's report, which covered just
manufacturing, showed 2.7 billion pounds of toxic emissions.
</P>
<P>
   The report offers the first statistical look at not only the
volume of nationwide toxic chemical pollution but also the
extensive pollution that has become of particular concern in New
York and other Eastern states downwind of the nation's oldest and
dirtiest coal-burning power plants in the Midwest and South.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans now will have the best picture ever of the actual
amounts of toxic pollution being emitted by industry into local
communities,'' said Carol Browner, administrator of the
environmental protection agency, as she made the report public
Thursday in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The new data reflect releases in 1998 and agency officials urged
that the information be used as a guide but not an indicator of
health risk because the report provides no information on exposure.
</P>
<P>
   New York officials and environmentalists said Thursday that the
agency's findings would aid their efforts to fight a growing
pollution problem. State Attorney General Eliot Spitzer has already
sued the owners of 12 coal-fired plants in the Midwest, asserting
that they did not install federally required pollution controls and
discharged vastly more toxic chemicals than they would have
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not news that they're polluting, but it is news to the
extent that they are polluting,'' said John F. Sheehan, a spokesman
for the Adirondack Council, an environmental group that is working
to protect the state's wilderness from acid rain and other
pollution. ``In many cases, people will suddenly find that the
power company has become the biggest polluter in their community.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, New York and other Eastern states have mainly
attempted to reduce the levels of sulfur dioxide and nitrogen
oxides that are produced heavily by coal-burning plants. But the
agency's report Thursday drew attention to 641 other toxic
chemicals emitted by industries into the air, water and ground.
</P>
<P>
   The 1.1 billion pounds of toxic emissions released by the power
plants included 536 millions pounds of hydrochloric acid, 180
million pounds of barium compounds and 169 million pounds of
sulfuric acid.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not all that pollution ends up in New York, but because of the
prevailing winds, much of it does,'' said Peter Lehner, chief of
the environmental protection bureau in Spitzer's office.
</P>
<P>
   The heaviest polluters were the 27 power plants in Ohio, which
emitted 113.9 million pounds of toxic chemicals in 1998. In
comparison, the 34 power plants in New York released 18.7 million
pounds of toxic emissions, and the 15 power plants in New Jersey
released 8 million pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
