Since bursting upon the scene in 1979 with ``Black Tickets,'' a
widely-praised short story collection, the West Virginia native has
won plaudits for her haunting tales of isolation and obsession, of
unfashioned lives and unrealized dreams, of small-town traditions
pitted against contemporary cultural forces. Phillips's new novel
``MotherKind,'' closely tracks aspects of her own not-so-long-ago
life. ``The real heart of the book is the cyclical nature of time
itself and how we fit into it,'' says Phillips. (Bill Greene/Boston
Globe Photo)
