<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0437 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-ELIAN-MAIN-PM0512-COX     05-11 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELIAN-MAIN-PM0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elian's fate in hands of 3 judges
 &HT;    By Bill Rankin
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A federal appeals court panel will decide ``in a few
weeks'' whether 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez returns to Cuba with his
father or gets the political asylum hearing his Miami relatives
desire.
</P>
<P>
   During a hearing lasting an hour and fifteen minutes, three
judges of the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals hammered away with
questions from all sides of the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The judges reminded attorneys that Elian's father wants to
return his son to a totalitarian state and wondered aloud what kind
of precedent they would be setting if they don't allow that to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   And through it all, the jurists gave little indication of how
they will decide the contentious dispute.
</P>
<P>
   The case, watched by the world, was argued before a packed
courtroom inside the Elbert Parr Tuttle Courthouse on Forsyth
Street in downtown Atlanta. As lawyers pressed their cause inside,
chants could be heard from dozens of sidewalk demonstrators
outside.
</P>
<P>
   If the court determines that U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno
correctly dismissed the boy's application for political asylum,
Elian and his father could return to Cuba soon afterward, legal
scholars predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Before the hearing, Judge J.L. Edmondson told spectators the
case is on a fast track, predicting a ruling in ``a few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   During the arguments, Edmondson noted that the State Department
calls Cuba ``a Communist, totalitarian state which regularly
violates the freedoms and rights of its citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed out that U.S. law provides for a ``wide
variety'' of relatives to come into court and speak on behalf of a
child, against the parent's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   The case argued Thursday has been building since Elian was
rescued Thanksgiving Day, clinging for his life on an innertube in
the Atlantic. His mother died in their attempt to flee Cuba with
about a dozen others in a boat that sank off the coast of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Washington lawyer Gregory Craig, who represents Elian's father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, told the court he was not there to argue the
intricacies of immigration law.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the attorney said, ``knows this boy better than anyone
in this courtroom or anyone on the face of this planet. Juan
Miguel's concern about his well-being, about his happiness and
about his future take second place to no one.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Joel Dubina said he had no reason to believe that Gonzalez
was anything but a loving parent, but questioned why it took him
five months to leave Cuba and see Elian. Lawyer Kendall Coffey, who
represents Elian's Miami relatives, urged the court to grant the
boy an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   He reminded the judges that Elian's late mother is considered a
traitor in Cuba. ``This child is going to be purged of illegal
thoughts in a communist country,'' Coffey said. ``He is a
traumatized child. That kind of purging is potentially of grave and
serious harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez and cousin Marisleysis
Gonzalez sat side by side in the second row of the courtroom.
Neither Elian nor his father attended the hearing.
</P>
<P>
   The court may have to decide who is best qualified to speak on
Elian's behalf _ his father or great-uncle _ and whether the
6-year-old was competent to file his own asylum claim.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Charles Wilson, appointed to the court by President
Clinton, wondered what precedent would be set if the court decides
federal authorities do not have the discretion to dismiss the boy's
application for asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's say a teenage baby-sitter for a 2-year-old alien . . .
takes that child downtown to the INS (Immigration and
Naturalization Service) office while his parents are at the movies
and has him scribble his first name on an asylum application,''
Wilson speculated.
</P>
<P>
   The child's parents come running to the INS office screaming in
protest that they, not the baby-sitter, speak for their child, the
judge continued. ``You're telling me that the INS doesn't have any
discretion whatsoever, they have to go through the time and expense
of having a formal asylum hearing?''
</P>
<P>
   If the form is ``facially sufficient,'' INS regulations call for
a hearing, Coffey replied. And if the immigration agency believes
there is a ``baby-sitter problem,'' it should address the matter in
its own regulations, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Would the INS's hands be tied if a kidnapper with a criminal
record brings it a 6-month-old child? Wilson asked. Would they have
``to go through the time and expense of an asylum hearing?''
</P>
<P>
   Coffey responded the INS might be able to reject that
application.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, there is some discretion on the part of the INS then,''
Wilson quickly interjected.
</P>
<P>
   But Coffey shot back that the judge's hypothetical proposition
was different from the case being argued. In Elian's case, the
court must assume that the boy wants to stay in the United States
and in such instances hearings are always provided. Wilson
expressed skepticism as to whether Elian was mature enough to file
an asylum petition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that Elian Gonzalez is a very bright and intelligent
6-year-old,'' the judge said. But he noted it appeared Elian was
unable to write his last name on the asylum petition and that ``a
third party'' answered the questions.
</P>
<P>
   The judge read aloud a question on the asylum form that asks
applicants if they have been associated with various organizations
such as a political party, a labor union, a paramilitary group, a
guerrilla group or the news media.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're telling me a 6-year-old is competent to answer
questions like that?'' Wilson asked. University of Virginia law
professor David Martin, a former INS general counsel, said if the
court rules on behalf of the government it could lift its current
injunction barring Elian's removal from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   After the three-judge panel issues its ruling, the losing party
has 45 days to ask the full 12-member 11th Circuit Court to
reconsider. The ruling also can be appealed to the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   But if the injunction is lifted, Gonzalez can take his son back
to Cuba, effectively ending the case, Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very possible that if the government wins here, Elian
could be returned to Cuba in a matter of weeks,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
