<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2590 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASHION-GIRLZONE0512-     05-11 0327
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-GIRLZONE0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hangin' where the auction is
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ There aren't any perfume samples to spritz at
the cosmetics counter, greasy slices of pizza to munch in the food
court, or cute boys to scam on at Abercrombie &AMP; Fitch.
</P>
<P>
   But when mom and pop aren't loaning out the wheels, teen girls
can still shop till they log off thanks to a new auction site.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Girl Zone (www.girlzone.com _ ``where every girl is
cool'') launched an online auction aimed at adolescent shoppers.
BayBuilder of Florida, based in Boca Raton, built the auction
component and will maintain it.
</P>
<P>
   Girl Zone founder and president says bidding on Roxy dresses and
'N Sync CDs is simply one more way to bring girls together. The
site already features interactive features such as chats, bulletin
boards, surveys and a secure e-pal system.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with boys, girls are mostly looking for a sense of
community on the Internet, Mary Jo Reale says.
</P>
<P>
   An auction builds community ties ``with a selling element. Maybe
they'll get a taste for being entrepreneurs,'' Reale says. ``It's
an opportunity for them. . . . Auctions are becoming big in
general, and there aren't a lot of places for teens to do it in
their own community.''
</P>
<P>
   Girls will have the chance to sell and buy everything from art
to jewelry to capri pants. Last week, the most items were on the
block in the site's sports ``department,'' the least in dolls and
dollhouses.
</P>
<P>
   Reale doesn't think the mouse will replace the mall in
teenagers' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they're like adults who view shopping as a
chore,'' she says. ``They like to go to the mall and see their
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   An online auction ``is just going to be another fun thing for
them to do. . . . An auction implies bargains and fun and all that
kind of stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
