<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0440 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASHION-ROWAN0512-COX     05-11 1479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-ROWAN0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Designer lives in the best of both worlds
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Lisa Rowan loves the convenience of Palm Beach _ the
always good-to-go weather, the discount retailers stocked to the
ceiling with everything a home needs, the beach just down the
street from her Chilian Avenue home.
</P>
<P>
   And she loves the culture of Paris _ the art museums, the
fragrant flower stalls, the world-famous gardens and the flea
markets practically at her back door.
</P>
<P>
   So why choose between them? Rowan splits her time between the
two cities, jetting back and forth according to the school schedule
of her 6-year-old son, Krystofer Kimmel.
</P>
<P>
   Her career in the fashion industry _ she calls herself a
``creative consultant'' _ has taken Rowan around the globe. A
Pennsylvania native, Rowan became public-relations and advertising
director for the late designer Willi Smith shortly after college
graduation.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a PR job with Christian Dior in Paris. And then a
promotions position with Revlon in Tokyo. And then a job based in
Milan with Giorgio Armani, as coordinator for his Japanese market.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I got pregnant and had a baby, and became Mom,'' she
says. The need to slow down during her pregnancy took her to Palm
Beach, where her family had owned a home for years. Rowan bought
her own place, a two-story Mediterranean house built in 1925.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Palm Beach, Krystofer was soon logging frequent flyer
miles with Rowan. He learned to walk in Provence and ski in
Switzerland. But the approach of elementary school meant the pair
needed to settle down, comparatively speaking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I happen to like Europe, and my son has roots in Palm Beach,
so I'm trying to keep those roots going,'' Rowan says. ``I have
nothing against the States, but the States will always be there. I
want to take the best of both worlds and marry them.''
</P>
<P>
   In Paris, ``there's life. There's color. You grow up looking at
beauty every day,'' she says. ``Paris is cool, and it's safe. It's
much more interesting and relaxed. The people want to work hard and
do well, but it's not just about money.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Krystofer have flown between Paris and Palm Beach for
the past three years, and almost two years ago they began renting a
140-year-old house near the Luxembourg Gardens on Paris' eclectic
Left Bank, an easy walk from Krystofer's school, L'Ecole
Aujourd'hui (''School for Today'').
</P>
<P>
   It was a long search that led Rowan to her home on Boulevard de
Port Royal. She had looked at 40 apartments in two months, and then
one day saw a newspaper ad for a three-story house for rent. It had
12-foot ceilings, a working fireplace in every room and a
wood-beamed attic with natural light.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked in and said, `Oh my God,' '' she recalls. ``It was so
rare, magical and beautiful. But I was afraid I couldn't afford
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners asked Rowan what she would want to change if she
moved in. She said she'd remove the door between the kitchen and
dining room so an old plate warmer built into the wall could be
easily seen. ``This is beautiful. Why hide it?''
</P>
<P>
   It turned out that one of the owners was born in the house, and
Rowan's appreciation of its intrinsic beauty touched her. Because
of that, they agreed on a price within Rowan's range.
</P>
<P>
   ``God was looking out for me,'' she says. ``I take zero
credit.''
</P>
<P>
   On a recent Wednesday, the courtyard shared by Rowan and seven
other families was filled with the laughter of children enjoying a
sunny afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Krystofer took a break to make his friends a snack in the skylit
kitchen. ``I like French cookies a lot,'' he contributed, artfully
arranging a tray with three glasses of milk and a plate of Langue
de Chat cookies (butter cookies that are called ``cat's tongue''
because of their shape). ``This is a collage.''
</P>
<P>
   (How many first graders do you know who throw off the word
``collage'' in casual conversation? Krystofer is already bilingual,
and if Rowan has her way, he'll be multilingual by the age of 15,
adding Spanish and Italian to his French and English.)
</P>
<P>
   The secluded courtyard and each home's private garden were a
major selling point (Rowan's garden is decorated with lawn chairs
from Target). ``There are not a lot of places in Paris where he can
run out the door and play,'' Rowan says. ``You don't have to get in
the car and go somewhere else and drag the bike. It's all right
here.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all of Paris' charms, it is found lacking, too. Rowan's
kitchen, for one example, is stocked with Publix sponges and Target
mixing bowls. ``You can't find this stuff here,'' Rowan says. She
makes a list of household odds and ends and then shops for them
when she returns to the States. ``Target has saved my life.''
</P>
<P>
   So has Costco. ``When I come back here, my suitcase is filled
with Saran Wrap and aluminum foil from Costco because the foil here
falls to pieces as soon as you touch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Day to day, ``the United States functions a lot better in
practical ways,'' says Rowan, though she hastens to add that she's
had more problems with her phone lines in Palm Beach than in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look at it this way: When I walk into Publix and I think of
the market across the street from me (in Paris), I want to cry,''
Rowan says.
</P>
<P>
   But there is the sense of history in Paris: ``That little corner
restaurant will be there for the next 100 years. Look at Palm
Beach. They change every five days.''
</P>
<P>
   Living in the design capital of the world also allows Rowan, who
says she is ``closing in on 40 and reveling in it,'' to ``take all
the pieces that I know and put the puzzle together.'' She wants to
work with young artists and product designers and help put them in
touch with the contacts she's made over the years. Fashion designer
Tom Ford, now with Gucci, is a friend from her days in Milan, and
French designer Philippe Starck will attend a cocktail party at
Rowan's home this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to take what's good and unique here and take it to the
U.S.,'' she says. ``Now I'm getting into what I really want to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Highlights of Rowan's Paris home, bottom to top:
</P>
<P>
   The stone-walled basement dates to the late 1700s.
</P>
<P>
   It's where Rowan keeps her washer and dryer, and it will be the
location of ``Studio 85,'' a tongue-in-cheek re-creation of a
nightclub replete with disco balls, ponyskin butterfly chairs and,
on the way, a pingpong table from Costco.
</P>
<P>
   A red velvet rope stands ready to barricade the entrance, along
with life-size, wooden cutouts of Bahamian guards. Rowan found the
rope and the ``bouncers'' at Paris flea markets.
</P>
<P>
   She plans to throw her first costume party in Studio 85 this
summer; her friends have decided she's going as Janis Joplin.
</P>
<P>
   The living room and adjoining dining area are so airy and
photogenic that they served as a backdrop for a Christmas catalog
shoot for Marks &AMP; Spencer.
</P>
<P>
   Filled with light from French doors that open onto the garden,
the living room is an homage to Rowan's knack for decorating
inexpensively. It contains a circular, ruby red rug from Ikea, a
pair of antique taupe armchairs and '50s leather chairs from a
Paris flea market. ``The whole place is just a mishmash,'' Rowan
says.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements of irises, tulips and hydrangeas, purchased from
the neighborhood flower market and plucked from Rowan's own garden,
spring forth from tall, slender vases in the living room.
</P>
<P>
   In the dining area is a colorful glass-blown chandelier by
Washington artist Dale Chihuly. Rowan hosts regular, rambunctious
Sunday brunches at this table. The weekend before our visit,
actress Sigourney Weaver was a guest, and on Easter Sunday, 25
adults and kids showed up for an egg hunt.
</P>
<P>
   If some of the upstairs rooms _ bedrooms, office space and a
room-sized closet _ have a less-than-finished quality, that's
because Rowan doesn't like to rush the decorating process,
preferring to wait until she finds just the right piece for each
spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place was empty until September; but I knew my space and
I would just go down Dixie and find all my different stuff,'' Rowan
says. Before that, when she and Krystofer would visit the
apartment, they'd sleep on futons in the empty living room. ``We
didn't care,'' she says. ``We had our duvet and our pillows.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, some of the upper rooms feature posters and mirrors
from Paris flea markets, cozy antique beds and a blue velvet couch
from Pottery Barn.
</P>
<P>
   And here's a small remembrance of her other home: Copies of
Ocean Drive Palm Beach in a magazine rack. Rowan has tried to
create an informal, welcoming environment on each side of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both doors are always open. People come in and out,'' she
says. ``I love design, but you live your life and that's its own
design.''
</P>
<P>
