<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-ART-775(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI DUCKS QUESTIONS ABOUT PAST AFFAIR AND FUTURE CAMPAIGN
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photos NYT5 and NYT6 are being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(Eds: The name Nicholas Nicholas is CQ.) 
(With NY-GIULIANI-REACT) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joking that ``rumors of my demise are greatly
exaggerated,'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said Thursday that he had not
yet decided if he would stay in the race for U.S. Senate. But he
brushed aside repeated questions about whether he had had an affair
with his former communications director, Cristyne F.
Lategano-Nicholas, as the mayor's wife suggested this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said everything I was going to say about that a long time
ago,'' Giuliani said during a packed, raucous news conference in
which he frequently said ``shhhhhh!'' to yelling, shoving
reporters. ``Cristyne Lategano was an excellent communications
director; she did a great job for the city of New York. I've
definitively answered all those questions, and I'm not going to
drag somebody else's reputation into this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that ``what's going on right now has to do with Donna
and me, and what you're trying to do is a backdoor way of trying to
dredge this all up so you can write more salacious stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, Giuliani said that a Vanity Fair article
asserting that he had had an ``intimate'' relationship with
Lategano-Nicholas was ``scurrilous'' and ``untrue'' and that the
best thing about the article ``is that it can be thrown in the
trash.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Giuliani added that Lategano-Nicholas was doing an
``excellent job'' as president of NYC and Co., the city's tourism
bureau.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's news conference, at a public school on the Lower
East Side, was the latest public spectacle in the life of a man who
in the last two weeks announced that he has prostate cancer, has a
``very good'' woman friend, is separating from his wife of 16 years
and is still running for Senate against Hillary Rodham Clinton. But
unlike Giuliani's emotional display of sadness and regret on
Wednesday, when he abruptly announced that he and his wife were
separating, the mayor returned Thursday to his more combative, and
familiar, public persona.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani frequently berated reporters for their unruly behavior
_ ``Do you realize that you embarrass yourselves doing this in the
eyes of just about everybody?'' he said at one point _ and snapped
at others. When one reporter asked if there might be
``criminality'' involved with giving Lategano the job at the
tourist bureau, Giuliani shot back: ``Oh, get out of here. Get
lost. Get lost. That's a sneaky way of trying to invade somebody's
personal life.''
</P>
<P>
   But the mayor also displayed his new willingness to answer a
variety of questions about his personal life, and was at times
lighthearted. When one reporter asked if the mayor was
``politically dead,'' Giuliani laughed and responded: ``I'm
sensitive to that word, you know, that last word you used, in any
respect. Dead? No, I'm not dead. Rumors of my demise are greatly
exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   While many Republicans across the state continued to express
doubts that the mayor would stay in the race, others said they
believed his performance at his news conference had stanched the
political hemorrhaging, for now. In either case, most said publicly
only that they felt sadness about the mayor's situation. Giuliani
even received words of sympathy from his opponent's husband,
President Clinton, whose relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky
resulted in his impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish him and his wife and their children well on the health
front and on the domestic front,'' Clinton said in response to a
question in the Rose Garden of the White House. ``I think that's
all there is _ all anybody would want.'' The president added:
``I've always had a good personal relationship with Mayor Giuliani.
It's not been affected by the fact that I think my wife would be a
better senator. And on this, I think everybody in New York and
everybody in America ought to be rooting for the human side of this
to work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George E. Pataki, speaking to reporters in Rockland County
on Thursday, said: ``My hope is he will still run.'' Pressed on
what contingency plans the party had in place if Giuliani were to
withdraw, Pataki replied: ``We're still letting the mayor with his
family work through the decisions. And I think people should
respect that this is a difficult time for Rudy and his family.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide to Pataki told reporters not even to ask Pataki if
he himself would step in to campaign for the Senate seat. ``He's
not running,'' the aide decreed.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign advisers to the mayor, who said they had no idea on
Wednesday that Giuliani was going to announce his separation,
presented a cheerier picture Thursday, and said the mayor had told
them in the morning to proceed with all campaign plans.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But longtime critics of Giuliani criticized the mayor for his
friendship with Lategano-Nicholas and the mayor's involvement in
helping her get a $150,000-a-year post at the tourism bureau.
</P>
<P>
   ``This story has legs,'' said former Mayor Edward Koch, a
frequent critic of Giuliani's. ``I think it's an abuse of power. It
may not be a technical abuse, but in the court of opinion, it's an
abuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Lategano-Nicholas said she took the day off Thursday to
celebrate the 40th birthday of her husband, Nicholas Nicholas, whom
she married in February. She said in an interview Thursday that she
had never had a sexual relationship with Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Hanover's press secretary, Joannie Danielides, said Hanover
spent Thursday making breakfast for her two children, taking them
to school, handling correspondence at her office and then recording
voice-overs at a New York City studio for her ``House Beautiful''
show on the A&AMP;E network.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said he spent his day working in his office at City
Hall, holding his press conference and meeting with two doctors to
talk about his treatment for cancer. He said at his news conference
that he had no timetable for announcing his decision on treatment
or whether he would stay in the race. But aides said Thursday that
they expected him to think about his options over the weekend and
perhaps make an announcement next week.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he would continue to cut his campaign schedule in
half as he meets with doctors, making it unclear whether he would
attend four fund-raisers scheduled next Tuesday and Wednesday in
California. Aides said that for the time being all four events _ in
Los Angeles, San Diego, Santa Barbara and Orange County _ were
still on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said Thursday that the mayor would decide on the
race based almost solely on his health, but also said that they
would not be surprised if he took a poll in the next few days to
determine how his personal life had affected his standing with
voters.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans also said that while there was enormous sympathy for
Giuliani, there was also bewilderment among party members over why
he had announced his separation without first informing his wife _
a decision, they said, that may have caused Hanover's angry
announcement on Wednesday about Lategano-Nicholas.
</P>
<P>
   ``He essentially asked for her to go nuclear by behaving that
way,'' one top state Republican official said.
</P>
