u l BC-FASHION-ROWAN-SIDE051     05-11 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-ROWAN-SIDE0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    How to shop a brocante
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ What does it take to score the perfect
headboard or a dinette to die for?
</P>
<P>
   ``There's something that clicks, and it's just destiny,'' says
fashion consultant Lisa Rowan, who has decorated her Palm Beach and
Paris homes with purchases from flea markets and thrift stores here
and abroad. ``I don't find anything. It finds me.''
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes in the most unexpected places.
</P>
<P>
   When Rowan dropped by a St. Louis consignment shop in search of
'50s furniture, she wound up wrapped in a leopard coat from the
'60s for $800. Not bad for mint-condition fur with a Paris designer
label.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, she was shopping for shelves (which, incidentally,
she still doesn't have) when a vibrant red rug caught her eye. It's
now the visual centerpiece of her Paris living room. Which brings
us to Rowan's premiere piece of home-shopping advice: ``Luck is one
thing, and paying attention to and taking advantage of luck is the
next thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's more flea-marketing advice from Rowan and Claudia
Strasser, owner of The Paris Apartment store in New York and author
of a book by the same name:
</P>
<P>
   Break away from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Bargains can be found everywhere, but you'll have more
competition if you browse a city's most famous markets or stores.
See what treasures you find off the beaten path, Strasser suggests.
</P>
<P>
   We wanted to accompany Rowan to Porte de Clignancourt, the
oldest and largest flea market in Paris. And we wanted to go on a
Monday, the last day of the weekend market.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong, Rowan said.
</P>
<P>
   She dragged us to a brocante, a sort of traveling market of
dealers. You can find brocantes through listings in the newspaper
or by keeping your eyes peeled for fliers on the street.
</P>
<P>
   Among the boxes of old eyeglasses and crates of cracked kitchen
tile, there's an air of refinement unusual for a street market.
Shoppers rest at a picnic table with a bottle of red wine. Vendors
sell Belgian waffles, foie-gras sandwiches and crepes. German
shepherds, Irish setters and Boston terriers greet each other
between stalls packed with croquet sets and smiling Buddhas.
</P>
<P>
   Go early and often.
</P>
<P>
   Rowan persuaded us to abandon our Monday shopping plans for a
Friday visit, the first day of the annual brocante we had chosen.
Much better pickings, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dealers ``will give you a quick fix on the first day, then
they'll hold tight over the next several days and unload on the
last,'' Rowan says.
</P>
<P>
   Wake up early.
</P>
<P>
   It's best if you can get there when vendors are still unpacking,
``just so you know what's out there, what's coming out. Then you'll
know if it's going to be worth your while,'' Strasser says. ``The
best stuff gets picked right away.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour the market at least twice.
</P>
<P>
   Navigate the stalls traveling in one direction and then retrace
your steps. ``If you go around once, you only see it from one
side,'' Strasser says.
</P>
<P>
   Ask the vendor's opinion on the piece.
</P>
<P>
   Do this even if you already have a good idea of its value and
condition. If nothing else, you might learn the history behind that
chaise lounge, Strasser says.
</P>
<P>
   Look for potential.
</P>
<P>
   Some flaws can be solved easily and cheaply with refinishing,
reupholstering or rewiring. On the other hand, if a piece has
structural problems such as a broken leg, it should be very
inexpensive to make it worth your while.
</P>
<P>
   Load up.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to bargain with a dealer, pick more than one item.
``That might help you get a better overall deal,'' Strasser says.
``This gives you a little more leverage.''
</P>
<P>
   If you love it, buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Even if it's $5, $10 or $15 more than what you wanted to spend,
Strasser says. Remember how much effort it took for someone to find
the piece for you and haul it there. Consider the extra cash a
finder's fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's probably one of a kind and you're not going to see it
again, so just get it,'' Strasser says.
</P>
<P>
   Adds Rowan: ``If something catches your eye and you can afford
it, don't let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
