<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-LINES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' LAST LINE PERFORMS ITS ROLE WITH ZEAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Baseball has the relief pitcher to stop the bleeding or
retain the momentum. Hockey has the fourth line.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a lot of ways, it's kind of the fireman's role,'' said
Stars right winger Blake Sloan, who is playing on the Stars' fourth
line after spending the majority of the season on the checking
line. ``You get called, and you have to come to play. It's a job
that is an important one and one you try to embrace.''
</P>
<P>
   It's often an overlooked job. The fourth liners play the fewest
minutes, don't score much and take a back seat to the team's
scoring lines. But, an effective fourth line, one that turns up the
heat, sacrifices the body and gets the opponent's heads spinning,
can create opportunities and reduce taxing checking
responsibilities for its scoring lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives your first and second line an opportunity to rest
up,'' fourth-line left winger Kirk Muller said.
</P>
<P>
   And that can be crucial against a deep Colorado squad that
possesses a ton of team speed and high-caliber offensive players.
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said the play of his fourth line will be
critical in the best-of-seven Western Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we play the game is different than the way Colorado
plays it with the puck,'' Hitchcock said. ``We have to use four
lines. We can't win this series playing three lines and nine
forwards. It's impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Colorado uses four lines, but coach Bob Hartley tends to
interchange an array of depth players on his lines rather than
using a standard group the way the Stars do. Either way, the job
remains the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``Play with a lot of energy and enthusiasm, have a great
forecheck, be skating well, take the body; those are the real keys
of those guys' line,'' center Mike Modano said. ``Wearing the
defense out, tiring them down, and then the other lines are able to
step up, and they've got a little bit of jump.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading into tomorrow's Game 1, Aaron Gavey is expected to
continue to center the fourth line. Sloan will handle the right
wing and Muller, who has played on the second, third and fourth
line in the playoffs, will play left wing. Hitchcock also has
impressive rookie Roman Lyashenko and Grant Marshall as
possibilities on the wings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a fourth line here that is capable of playing
against anybody and being effective,'' Muller said. ``We're strong
enough defensively, and we can produce offensively.''
</P>
<P>
   Gavey, Muller and Lyashenko each have one goal in the playoffs.
Gavey scored the first goal of the San Jose series and set the tone
for that 4-0 victory. Although Lyashenko and Muller scored their
goals while playing on other lines, that group is more than a
couple of bruisers with limited offensive ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a tight series,'' Muller said, ``if we can chip in that odd
goal here and there, I think it would be huge for the team.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2230EDT &QL; 
