<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NELSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE HOPES HE FINISHES SAME WAY HE STARTED; TIGER DOESN'T 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ It has been more than two years since Davis Love
III last won a golf tournament. That is a long time for a player of
Love's caliber, long enough for confidence to slip, for frustration
to become overwhelming.
</P>
<P>
   So after a sorely needed two-week break from competition, Love
returned Thursday with a fresher outlook, hoping his new attitude
would help him break the mental barriers that have kept him from
winning. Perhaps Love is on the right track. Overcoming extremely
blustery conditions that featured 35 mph wind gusts, Love shot a
four-under-par 66, and was tied for first place with Blaine
McCallister after Thursday's opening round of the GTE Byron Nelson
Classic.
</P>
<P>
   Six players were tied for third place at 68 _ Lee Janzen, Billy
Andrade, Sergio Garcia, John Huston, Jerry Smith and Kevin
Sutherland.
</P>
<P>
   But the strong wind that howled consistently made it a miserable
day for many. Ask Tiger Woods, who struggled to a 75, including a
40 on the back nine. After reaching three under par through 10
holes, Woods bogeyed No. 11, double-bogeyed No. 14 and finished
with consecutive bogeys on the last three holes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't have the feel of my swing,'' said Woods, playing
his first tournament since the Masters. ``I couldn't hit shots the
way I wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   But hitting good shots in the wind was not a problem for Love,
who played at the TPC of Las Colinas, the more difficult of the
tournament's two courses. McCallister, Andrade, Huston, Garcia,
Smith and Sutherland all played at Cottonwood Valley Thursday, but
they will switch to Las Colinas on Friday, while Love, Janzen and
Woods will play at Cottonwood.
</P>
<P>
   Love was five under par through 17 holes, and he would have
finished alone in first place if he had not made a three-putt bogey
at No. 18. Yet, it remained to be seen if Love would finish what he
has started. Since winning the 1998 MCI Classic, Love has been in
position to win many times, only to fall short. This year alone,
Love already has five top 10 finishes, but he has stumbled in key
situations, failing to break 70 on Sunday during his last five
tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   After winning his first major at the 1997 PGA Championship, Love
expected even bigger and better things, but the last two years have
been disappointing. He is still ranked No. 6 in the world, he is
ninth on this year's PGA Tour money list and he is still only 36
years old. But as the months have passed without victories to show
for his efforts, Love admitted he has become frustrated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been trying too hard to win,'' said Love, who has 13
career victories on tour. ``It became more than a goal. It was
becoming an obsession. ``I've been at the top of the money list,
the top of the world rankings, and I haven't won. Something is
getting in the way. Sure, I've got to play to win, but not get
obsessed with it, not get obsessed with beating Tiger and obsessed
with beating David Duval. Just play golf and have fun.''
</P>
<P>
   While Love laments not having won in two years, McCallister has
not won since 1993. He let a great opportunity slip away last
weekend, when he finished second at the Compaq Classic of New
Orleans, losing to Carlos Franco on the second hole of sudden
death. McCallister bogeyed the final hole of regulation in New
Orleans, then he missed a four-foot putt for par on the first
playoff hole. Yet, instead of sulking about the loss, McCallister
responded with a solid round Thursday, and growing up in Fort
Stockton, Texas, gave McCallister experience in playing with a
strong wind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen wind,'' said McCallister. ``I've hit driver from 130
yards on a par-3. That's windy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a chance to win that golf tournament last week, and that
hurt. But last week is gone and I was very pleased about what I did
today. I came here to play well and I'm off to a good start.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
