<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0446 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2598 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-TEX     05-11 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE PUCK WARS ARE HUGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING _ Name a goal, any goal.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull's goal to win Stanley Cup Finals last season? Fine.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Primeau's goal in overtime No. 5 last week? That'll do,
too.
</P>
<P>
   You know what they, and just about any other goals, have in
common? Somebody won a faceoff to start the play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the start of every play,'' Stars defenseman Sylvain Cote
clarified. ``You either go on offense or defense. You find out by
the draw. If you never have the puck out of the draw, you know you
are not going to do well in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   No, faceoffs won and lost aren't the sexiest stats in the
Western Conference finals. But they might be among the
more-important ones in determining whether the Stars or the
Colorado Avalanche advance to the Stanley Cup Finals. In a series
featuring two very evenly matched teams, who starts with the puck
might be a big difference maker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said. ``I think
that is one of the successes of our team is that we have good puck
control because we win a lot of faceoffs. We take a lot of pride in
it as centermen.''
</P>
<P>
   Through two rounds of the playoffs, the Stars have the
second-best faceoff percentage in the NHL. Their 55.38 faceoff win
percentage puts them slightly behind the Washington Capitals
(55.59) and way ahead of the Avalanche, which is 10th at 48.05
percent. ``In the defensive zone, they're going to be huge,''
Avalanche forward Peter Forsberg said. ``And special teams, when
you win in the offensive zone, that's 30 seconds off the clock
right after that.''
</P>
<P>
   First, a little bit of information on the faceoff.
</P>
<P>
   The faceoff is to hockey what the jump ball is to basketball.
Only every time there is a stoppage in play, the faceoff is how
they start back up. Faceoffs are usually taken by centermen and
there are rules to the faceoff. They weren't really considered that
big of a deal until the NHL started distributing the numbers a
couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And when it comes to the players who take them, the Stars and
Avalanche have some of the best in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to face some of the good ones in this series,''
Nieuwendyk said not figuring he needed to mention guys like Joe
Sakic and Chris Drury.
</P>
<P>
   Ask any of the Stars, and they'll tell you Nieuwendyk is one of
the best in the league himself. He ranks second in the NHL through
two rounds of playoffs, winning 62.03 percent of his faceoffs. The
Stars' Guy Carbonneau isn't too bad at 60.6 percent, which is
fifth-best.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're very strong, and they're known to have the best team
in the league in faceoffs,'' San Jose Sharks forward Vincent
Damphousse said of the Stars. ``I know what their guys do. It's no
secret.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't a lot of secrets in the faceoff circle. Back when
it used to be a case of who could cheat the best, there were plenty
of secrets. They started enforcing the rules a couple of years ago,
and the ways to win became simple.
</P>
<P>
   Be quicker. Be stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one or the other really,'' Stars forward Kirk Muller
said. ``You try to beat them with quickness or speed or you try to
outmuscle the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   So what's the key to winning one?
</P>
<P>
   Just line up against Nieuwendyk.
</P>
<P>
   You immediately notice that he has a wide stance, a little bit
wider than shoulder width apart. The knees bend slightly as he
bends at the waist. Nieuwendyk's left hand is lower on the stick
with the top of the hand facing out. The right hand is on the top
of the stick, grabbing it from the underside.
</P>
<P>
   His head turns to the linesman who drops the puck. The key is to
read the drop, win the drop. Timing, indeed, is everything in the
world of the faceoff, and Nieuwendyk has the quickest draw on the
Stars.
</P>
<P>
   So what do Nieuwendyk's teammates notice about his faceoffs?
</P>
<P>
   ``They are usually going to be won,'' Stars winger Jamie
Langenbrunner said. ``It's such a nice thing for me and Scotty
\RThornton\S. You are not focused. You don't have to waste all that
energy chasing the puck. You are starting with the puck. You are
getting the puck to places you want to do, which is key when you
are out there for 40 seconds, to get going right away.''
</P>
<P>
   When you really think about it, the faceoff is kind of a sexy
stat.
</P>
<P>
   You can't win if you don't score. You can't score if you don't
have the puck. You don't have the puck a lot if you don't win a
fair share of faceoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So does it follow that you can't win games if you can't win
faceoffs?
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 7 against Quebec, I lost against Peter Stastny in a
faceoff,'' Carbonneau said. ``We lost the series. After that, it
was kind of ... So you either get better, or they don't ask you any
more.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2230EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0447 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2599 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITE     05-11 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUBAN-BOY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELIAN GONZALEZ CASE PRESENTED TO ATLANTA COURT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Complete write-thru for updates, revisions; now moving in 2
takes)  
(ART ADV: Photos NYT2, NYT3 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase individual rights by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In pointed questions to lawyers for both sides in the
custody battle for Elian Gonzalez, three federal judges wondered
Thursday how a 6-year-old who cannot even sign his full name could
apply for political asylum but questioned whether sending him back
to communist Cuba was in his best interests, regardless of his
father's fitness as a parent.
</P>
<P>
   Judge J.L. Edmondson, a conservative judge appointed to the 11th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals by President Ronald Reagan, noted
that it was not uncommon for courts to rule that a child's best
interests override the rights of a parent, as in the case of
parents who refuse their child a doctor's care because of their
religious beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson, who twice referred to Cuba as a ``communist,
totalitarian state,'' said it was not that such parents did not
believe they were acting in their child's behalf, but that their
actions seemed ``so conspicuously in conflict with the needs of the
child.''
</P>
<P>
   During lulls in the arguments, some 100 protesters just outside
the courtroom could be faintly heard chanting, ``Free Elian!''
Later, as lawyers for the government and for Elian's father left
the courtroom, the protesters shouted, ``Communist!'' over and
over. The outbursts, which have been commonplace in Miami for
months now, puzzled many in Atlanta as they walked past the
demonstrators.
</P>
<P>
   Edmondson, the senior member of the three-judge panel that heard
the appeal of a decision by a federal district judge in Miami that,
in effect, denied a request by Elian's relatives in that city for a
political asylum hearing, said before Thursday's hearing that a
decision would probably come in a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the Immigration and Naturalization Service have
repeatedly argued that Elian is simply not old enough to understand
the application for political asylum that he signed in a childlike
scrawl after it appeared that federal officials were planning to
send him back to Cuba to be with his father, Juan Miguel Gonzalez.
And, the lawyers for the government argued again Thursday, only the
father can speak for his son.
</P>
<P>
   This hearing may be the last chance the Miami relatives have of
keeping Elian in the United States in defiance of his father's
wishes, legal experts said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. immigration officials and the federal district court in
Miami have already rejected the request for any asylum hearing
filed on Elian's behalf by his great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez, who
took care of the boy after he was found clinging to an inner tube
in the Atlantic. Elian was rescued on Thanksgiving Day after his
mother drowned in an effort to cross from Cuba to Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure Elian Gonzalez is a very bright and intelligent
6-year-old, but he didn't even have the ability to sign his last
name on the asylum petition,'' said Judge Charles R. Wilson, an
appointee of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The panel, whose third member is Judge Joel Dubina, who was
appointed by President George Bush and is considered a moderate,
has several options, legal experts and lawyers for both sides say.
It could rule that immigration officials were correct in denying
the boy an asylum hearing based on his age, even though immigration
laws guarantee an asylum hearing for ``any alien.''
</P>
<P>
   Or it could order immigration officials to give Elian a hearing,
even though the boy is now in the legal custody of his father in a
secluded federal retreat in Maryland. The reunion followed an armed
federal raid on the relatives' home in Miami in the pre-dawn hours
of April 22.
</P>
<P>
   Or the court could ask immigration officials to speak with the
boy about his wishes, but not in a formal hearing.
</P>
<P>
   If the court rules against the Miami relatives, it could also
lift an injunction that bars Elian from leaving the country,
allowing father and son to return to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   There is no guarantee that the full court _ there are 12 active
judges on the 11th Circuit bench _ or the U.S. Supreme Court will
hear the case if the three-judge panel rules against the Miami
family.
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual address to the crowded courtroom just minutes
before the hearing, Edmondson, not yet dressed in his robe,
cautioned lawyers and onlookers that they should not try to draw
conclusions from the panel's questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is entirely possible that a judge may make a statement or
ask a question that is the exact opposite of what he is thinking,
because he may want to see how the lawyers respond to it,''
Edmondson said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the hearing, which lasted less than an hour and a half,
it seemed at least that lawyers for Lazaro Gonzalez had found a
sympathetic ear in Edmondson.
</P>
<P>
   He compared the case, in theory, to that of a child who had been
rescued from a communist country in the former Soviet Union by a
mother who gave her life to deliver him to freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Kendall Coffey, a lawyer for the Miami family, said Elian would
be paraded around Cuba, more a trophy than a boy growing up in his
old life there. His father would have little to say about his son's
life, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no parent in Cuba who controls what happens to his or
her child, and there is no power in this country,'' Coffey said of
the United States, ``that can protect this child if he is removed
to Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gregory Craig, a lawyer for Juan Miguel Gonzalez, said the
boy's father was not being manipulated by the government of
President Fidel Castro and was free to ``openly express his
feelings and his opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked by the panel why it had taken his client five months to
come to the United States to seek the return of his son, Craig said
Gonzalez tried to work through his own government to get Elian
returned to him.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Wilson seemed skeptical of how Elian could have understood a
complicated form requesting an asylum hearing.
</P>
<P>
   He also questioned whether, considering the fact that Elian is
now in the custody of his father, immigration officials could even
accept an application filed by someone who no longer has custody of
the child.
</P>
<P>
   The question of Elian's request for asylum may be moot if the
judges accept the premise that he never filed for asylum, that he
only scratched his name on the form because he was told to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really wasn't Elian who filed an asylum application; it was
Lazaro Gonzalez who filed the application for him,'' said Bernard
Perlmutter, director of the University of Miami Children and Youth
Law Clinic. ``People other than the father were making claims on
behalf of the child.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think the court has to be swayed by the paramount
interest of the child,'' Perlmutter said. ``Are the facts in this
case sufficient to warrant an intrusion in the father's rights to
speak for his son? I don't think there is sufficient evidence that
anyone other than Juan Miguel Gonzalez can speak for Elian in this
case.''
</P>
<P>
   To ultimately win, even if the case does wind up in an asylum
hearing, lawyers for the boy's Miami relatives must prove that
Elian was being persecuted for political reasons and that he was
afraid of that persecution, legal experts said.
</P>
<P>
   That, for a 6-year-old boy, would seem unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no objective basis for an independent asylum claim,''
a spokesman for the Justice Department said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
