<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0449 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2601 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-FASHION-FRANCE0512-CO     05-11 3115
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASHION-FRANCE0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    50 million French women can't be wrong
 &HT;    By Staci Sturrock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ What Switzerland is to timekeeping and Great Britain is
to ceremony, France is to fashion.
</P>
<P>
   The French didn't simply write the book on style, they built the
Librarie du Mode.
</P>
<P>
   Hermes, Chanel and Dior donated their design services. The
French language contributed entire sections to the global fashion
dictionary (see chambray, chamois, chapeau, chenille, chic,
chiffon, chignon...).
</P>
<P>
   And French women established an enviable fashion code, a sort of
Dewey Decimal system of sophisticated dressing that remains
somewhat impenetrable to admiring outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   You say you want a library card? As they say in France, bonne
chance.
</P>
<P>
   You have gone to Paris to study this foreign concept _ the way
French women dress. The way they are cheesecake, and the rest of us
are plain cream cheese.
</P>
<P>
   You have foolishly chosen to wear the internationally recognized
Official Uniform of the Tourist: Schlumpy black turtleneck. Faded
red sweatshirt. Oversized black jeans. Hiking boots that look so
ridiculous on your feet that a friend asks, ``Did you buy those
just for the trip?'' You did.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with the natives clicking down the boulevards in their
delicate heels, you are Frumpus Americanus.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, there's a dressed-down syndrome. It's so dreary,''
says interior designer and author Alexandra Stoddard, who visits
Paris four times a year. ``A Frenchwoman can be going for a root
canal, and you'd never know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another thing about a Frenchwoman: She'd rather have a root
canal than dress like the typical American.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the typical Parisian wears to the dentist, the
cafe, the museum, the office:
</P>
<P>
   Skinny, skinny pants _ To best display her skinny, skinny
figure, which defies logic in a land of croissants, brie and red
wine.
</P>
<P>
   Slim-fitting black leather jacket _ The better to say, ``I am
cool like Jean-Paul Belmondo, no?''
</P>
<P>
   High-heeled boots or pointy-toed mules _ Feminine, but not
necessarily comfortable, footwear.
</P>
<P>
   And, always, a scarf _ Effortlessly tied at the neck or tossed
over the shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   When a Frenchwoman wears a scarf, people say, ``Look how
fabulously French she is!''
</P>
<P>
   When you wear a scarf, people say, ``Oh, you're wearing a
scarf!''
</P>
<P>
   American-born Lisa Rowan, who lives in Paris and Palm Beach,
nods sympathetically. ``Frenchwomen will take a paper towel and tie
it a certain way, and they have a whole new deal.''
</P>
<P>
   She offers the example of her Paris neighbor, Beatrice. ``She
can be wearing sneakers and Bermuda shorts, and she still has her
style.''
</P>
<P>
   But why does Beatrice have her style? Why, why, why?
</P>
<P>
   You want answers. Straight from la source.
</P>
<P>
   You seek out Veronique and Virginie Morana, a mother and
daughter who own a small jewelry store on the Right Bank and
recently wrote The Parisian Woman's Guide to Style (Universe, $20).
They welcome you _ a matching madame and mademoiselle with accents
so charming and ... well, so French, that they turn the simplest of
words (''fat,'' ``bag,'' ``shoe'') into pure poetry.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, the Moranas point out that there's no such thing
as a single style of dressing in Paris, silly American.
</P>
<P>
   There are the trendy women of the Left Bank, the kind of
hipsters encountered by beatnik-seeking Audrey Hepburn in Funny
Face. Then there's the avant-garde crowd, the risk-taking women of
the hip Marais district who follow the work of young designers.
</P>
<P>
   The style we all ``ooh la la'' over, though, is referred to as
BCBG, or bon chic bon genre, (translated: good style, good
attitude). It's the look most associated with the elegant ladies of
the Right Bank. (No wonder the BCBG clothing line, which has a
store at The Gardens mall, adopted the name.)
</P>
<P>
   For the BCBG woman, ``the basic outfit is really simple and
sober and black,'' Veronique says, ``but the Parisian woman is
always looking for details to bring out,'' such as a brilliant red
necklace paired with that somber black dress. ``It's not nice to
really complicate things. You can always just add accessories. . .
. It's the accessories that make the outfits look `in'.''
</P>
<P>
   There's some strategy behind those accessories, however. If the
Frenchwoman wears an oversized necklace, she'll keep her pearl or
diamond earrings very small or leave off the earrings all together.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wouldn't wear all matching bracelets, necklaces and
rings,'' Virginie says. ``You want to keep it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   (Michael Kors, who designs for the Paris house Celine when he's
not tweaking his own line in New York, has this advice for American
women wanting to emulate the French: Before you leave the house in
the morning, remove one piece of jewelry. ``Americans have a
tendency to pile too much on,'' he says.)
</P>
<P>
   Frenchwomen also focus on their feet. ``It's the shoes that make
the outfit look good or not,'' Veronique says. ``You can have the
same black dress every year, but the shoes will make the outfit
look fashionable.''
</P>
<P>
   She adds: ``This year, it's the mule,'' slippers that cover the
toes but not the heel. The mid-heeled mules the Moranas are wearing
this season are extra-pointy with a squared-off tip.
</P>
<P>
   (Claudia Strasser, who worked in Paris before opening the Paris
Apartment design store in New York, also stresses the importance of
shoes. Compare the sneakers of the women you see in a New York
subway car to the stilettos you spot on the Paris Metro, she says.
The Parisians ``are probably all wearing Italian shoes,'' says
Strasser, who now lives in Pembroke Pines. A Parisian's shoes, in
addition to the way she emphasizes quality over quantity, set her
apart.)
</P>
<P>
   And then there's the issue of size.
</P>
<P>
   ``French clothing is very close to the body, as Parisian women
of all ages seek to maintain a young, feminine allure,'' the
Moranas write in their book.
</P>
<P>
   ``In France, you don't have extra-large,'' Virginie says. (In
France, they don't need extra-large. The chairs, the beds, the
showers, the entire population is petite compared with Super Sized,
Barcalounging, SUV-driving Americans. Ten percent of French women
are overweight; 55 percent of American women are too heavy.)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parisian woman, if her size is large, she prefers to buy a
medium,'' Virginie says. Some shop owners, conscious of their
customers' self-image, will even replace the tags of large shirts
or jackets. Or they'll simply snip them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Parisian woman doesn't like to have loose things,'' says
Virginie, a slender slip of a young woman. ``She likes to be
small.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe that's because French women ultimately have a very
specific audience in mind when they dress: French men.
</P>
<P>
   ``They go to lunch with their friends, and they like to show
off,'' to win an admiring glance from the man at the next table,
Veronique says. ``They're happy to be watched and looked at.''
</P>
<P>
   True story: The co-worker you are traveling with ducks into a
bank while you walk down the street to buy a phone card.
</P>
<P>
   You return three minutes later. He looks dazed and feverish.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? An armed robbery? A really great exchange rate?
</P>
<P>
   No, mon ami.
</P>
<P>
   A Frenchwoman smiled at him, and his day, his week, his month
has been made.
</P>
<P>
   He swears it wasn't her slim trousers or close-fitting leather
jacket that did it (although he remembered these items when you
quizzed him about her outfit weeks later, did he not?!). ``She
could have been wearing a potato sack for all I cared,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   But you know better . . .
</P>
<P>
   In the country that birthed Brigitte Bardot, the woman most
ogled these days by French men _ quite a few American fellas, too _
is Laetitia Casta.
</P>
<P>
   Last year the bodacious 22-year-old Victoria's Secret and Sports
Illustrated swimsuit model was elected the new ``Marianne,'' the
country's official symbol of beauty and virtue.
</P>
<P>
   Casta's bust _ make that, a sculptural likeness of her head _
will be displayed in town halls across France.
</P>
<P>
   As for the French women whom French women admire, these are
among the creme de la creme:
</P>
<P>
   ``Above all, Catherine Deneuve,'' says Veronique Morana.
</P>
<P>
   Considered by many to be the world's most beautiful woman, the
French actress is forever a picture of sophistication and
understated elegance. For decades she's maintained a sleek look
characterized by her blond mane, demure suits and simple gold
jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Incredibly chic, timeless, classic,'' says celebrity stylist
Phillip Bloch, whose clients include Halle Berry and Salma Hayek.
``She's a role model for a woman of any age, for any look. You
don't have to be blond and 50 or 60 to admire Catherine Deneuve's
style. She was my father's favorite, and she's still sexy.''
</P>
<P>
   Also admired, the models and actresses in Chanel advertisements
(Deneuve once shilled for Chanel No. 5). Their upper-class sense of
refinement ``corresponds very well to Parisian style,'' Veronique
says.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most well-known Chanel models was Coco Chanel
look-alike Ines de la Fressange, who served as designer Karl
Lagerfeld's muse throughout the '80s before founding her own design
house in 1991. She was also the pre-Casta ``Marianne.''
</P>
<P>
   De La Fressange, inducted into the International Best-Dressed
Hall of Fame two years ago, embodies several attributes of dressing
the French way: clean-lined clothes, simple hair and makeup, and a
reliance on a handful of wardrobe staples.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I have few clothes, I manage better than when I have a
lot, because I use my imagination,'' she once told Elle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Also putting a pretty face on French style are the women of
Lancome advertisements, such as actress Juliette Binoche, Veronique
says.
</P>
<P>
   Binoche has said that she prefers natural beauty to
contrivances. ``In Los Angeles, it's incredible how the women all
look like Barbie dolls,'' she said in a interview with a French
magazine. ``But it's a manufactured beauty: makeup, false
eyelashes, false nails, false breasts . . . It all rings false.''
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, outfit after outfit, the Frenchwomen you meet are
an endless parade of cute names, glamorous jobs and sartorial
perfection. And then there's that, how shall we say, admirable
French self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a chic suit, Marika works at Chanel. (And tells you
that you ``do not know enough about fabrics'' to call yourself a
fashion editor.)
</P>
<P>
   Tiny Claire works at the Opera Garnier and, trained as a
ballerina, dresses in the dancer's patented sloppy-yet-stylish way.
(And when you politely try to learn more about the opera after a
hasty tour, she says, ``Now is the time that you must leave!'')
</P>
<P>
   Marie Gabrielle works at Louis Vuitton and sports a scarf that
appears to have been knotted by an origami master. (She has an
uncanny way of ignoring your questions and discussing exactly what
she wants to talk about.)
</P>
<P>
   You stand there in your hiking boots, the big American galoot _
sans a snug Chanel suit, a ballerina's body, a damn scarf or an
Attitude with a capital A.
</P>
<P>
   How can you compete?
</P>
<P>
   And then you meet Alan Faye.
</P>
<P>
   Alan is a student of global fashion, having lived in New York,
Los Angeles, London and, for the past eight years, Paris. He
designs accessories for Issey Miyake and Hugo Boss, and also has
his own line of leather goods and jewelry that's sold by Neiman
Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   Alan tells you that the way Frenchwomen dress is relatively easy
to mimic. No need to feel intimidated.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, ``this is not a fashionable city,'' Alan says. ``People
who you see around town who are fashionable are not from Paris.''
</P>
<P>
   (Then again, who needs fashion? Coco Chanel once said, ``Fashion
changes but style endures.'')
</P>
<P>
   Parisians do know style, Alan admits. ``They're very
suit-oriented, they're very into established labels. They buy
things from Yves St. Laurent, Burberry and Cartier because they
can't go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   He says, ``They don't want to appear vulgar, and if you take a
risk and you don't have personal style, it can be what the French
call vulgar. . . . It's difficult to make mistakes when you don't
take any risks.''
</P>
<P>
   He outlines the safety-first uniform of the older Frenchwoman:
Navy turtleneck, navy knee-length skirt, yellow cashmere cardigan,
navy blue stockings, flat navy shoes, Cartier earrings, Cartier
watch.
</P>
<P>
   The younger generation has changed, he says, and pulls from the
closets of au courant design houses. ``They're more into Prada and
Gucci.''
</P>
<P>
   When icicles hang from the Eiffel Tower, Parisians of all ages
reach for longish parkas that cover the fanny. Alan starts pointing
out parkas as they walk down the street. ``There's one. . . .
There's two more. . . . There's another one. . . . His wife has a
matching one. . . . Look, the whole family has the same jacket.''
</P>
<P>
   While Alan frowns on the unimaginative parka, he applauds the
ubiquitous scarf.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're born knowing how to tie that scarf. It's like how do
ducks know how to fly in that direction,'' he says. ``They've been
tying that little scarf since they were 2 years old.'' (Entire
books on scarf-tying have been written for fumbling Americans. One
of the most recent: Edie Weber's How to Tie Scarves, Sterling
Publications, $10.)
</P>
<P>
   Alan is Chicken Soup for the Feeling-Inferior-to-French-Women
Soul.
</P>
<P>
   And then the wonderful Alan offers the piece de resistance:
Shopping like a Frenchwoman is easy, he says. Simply decrease the
number of things you buy while increasing the quality of the items
you do purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Here, a handy shopping guide, a List of 10 Items Every French
Woman Has in Her Closet (courtesy of Virginie and Veronique
Morana):
</P>
<P>
   1. A suit. Trousers and a fitted coat in either black or dark
gray. A suit can be worn across different seasons and can be
dressed up or down depending on the shirt underneath.
</P>
<P>
   2. A black dress. Always versatile, always in style. It can be
outfitted for evening with sparkly accessories or worn in the day
with the jacket from the black suit.
</P>
<P>
   3. A twin set. The favored colors: Beige, taupe, gray or black.
</P>
<P>
   4. A leather jacket. Preferrably in black.
</P>
<P>
   5. Leather trousers or skirt. Also in _ surprise _ black.
</P>
<P>
   (What's with all the black? The Moranas explain in their book
that neutrals ``never stand out in a crowd. The Parisian woman's
respect for classic, good taste motivates her to dress so that she
will blend into any social milieu.'')
</P>
<P>
   6. A white blouse. ``The only wardrobe element that changes with
different trends,'' the Moranas write. The current look: The
fitted, cotton T-shirt.
</P>
<P>
   7. Closed-toe pumps. For daytime wear, the heels should be under
2 inches, ``something you can trot around in,'' Veronique says.
</P>
<P>
   8. A matching bag and belt. Expensive, preferably with a logo.
``Last year it was Dior, this year it's Vuitton,'' Virginie says.
</P>
<P>
   9. A pearl necklace. Never out, a simple strand of pearls can
accessorize the suit, the black dress, the twin set ...
</P>
<P>
   10. A silk scarf. The most important accessory for French style
and one of the few non-black items in a Parisian's wardrobe. The
Moranas favor a mix of bright colors that will complement and add
pop to several outfits.
</P>
<P>
   So how do Frenchwomen know how to assemble that closet of
basics? Do they offer a course at the Sorbonne? Is it something in
the Seine?
</P>
<P>
   It's partly a matter of culture, says Jeff Stone of Chic Simple,
the lifestyle company that preaches the very French gospel of buy
less, own more.
</P>
<P>
   In the years following World War II, Europeans were forced to
learn the art of building a wardrobe, and smart shoppers sought
clothes that would look tres chic longer than a season or two.
``They had to buy things that would have a life to them,'' Stone
says. ``It's a more holistic approach to dressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The French are content with owning, and wearing, fewer pieces
than acquisitive Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not as heavy-duty a consumer as American women,'' Alan
Faye says. ``They buy two or three outfits of higher quality.
That's where the scarves come in, to accessorize and make them look
different.''
</P>
<P>
   And they believe in the basics. In Paris, women cherish a good
haircut, regular manicures and appointments with a seamstress,
designer Michael Kors says.
</P>
<P>
   American women don't like to take the extra step of getting
alterations, which can make all the difference between ``almost
fits'' and ``fits like a glove,'' Kors says. ``I think Americans
just get lazy. Even if you can't afford expensive clothes, go to
the tailor.''
</P>
<P>
   The less-is-more approach extends to a French woman's makeup,
says Laura Mercier, the Paris-born makeup artist and name on a full
line of upscale cosmetics.
</P>
<P>
   In America, she says, teenage girls dive into the world of
makeup face-first, piling on foundation and powder, blush and
beyond.
</P>
<P>
   Parisian girls, on the other hand, might use just a little
mascara or a touch of lipstick. French boys would be repelled if a
girlfriend's mug was coated in foundation, Mercier says. ``They
would say, `What is this on your face?' ''
</P>
<P>
   But more important than any number of Hermes scarves or pairs of
good shoes is a healthy sense of self.
</P>
<P>
   When Americans admire Frenchwomen, ``they're looking at the
attitude more than what they're actually wearing,'' Alan assures.
</P>
<P>
   This refrain is repeated again and again.
</P>
<P>
   ``French women have tremendous confidence,'' says Alexandra
Stoddard. ``They hold their head high. They're sassy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``French women think of clothes as accessories to a great
attitude,'' writes Veronique Vienne in French Style. ``Posture.
Poise. Presence. Put it on before you dress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not self-conscious at all,'' Alan says. ``They think
they're the biz. It's part of the culture.''
</P>
<P>
   In your impossibly tiny hotel bathroom, you practice in front of
the mirror: ``Now is the time that you must leave!'' You are
starting to get the hang of it, and all too soon it is true. Now is
the time that you must leave . . .
</P>
<P>
   You return to Miami, surrounded by shorts and sandals and
pastels. You sweat in your black turtleneck and your
two-sizes-too-big jeans, and you're the only Tri-Rail passenger
clomping around in hiking boots.
</P>
<P>
   But you wear it all proudly, because it's impossible to go to
Paris and not come back feeling like a million francs.
</P>
<P>
   When you disembark in Lake Worth, a friend is waiting. ``You
look so Continental!'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   And in the days that follow, others ask if the gray suit and
black dress you bought last year at The Gardens mall came from
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oui,'' you say with a toss of your head. ``Oui.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
