</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves lose 6th in past 8
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The Braves' lesson in offensive futility continues and
no pitcher is too unlikely a beneficiary. The Marlins sent
23-year-old Jason Grilli and 37-year-old Joe Strong to make their
major-league debuts for an ailing pitching staff and they came out
on top.
</P>
<P>
   They teamed up to beat Kevin Millwood and the Braves 5-4 to take
the series 3-1. The Braves lost for the sixth time in their past
eight games.
</P>
<P>
   Wait.
</P>
<P>
   Who?
</P>
<P>
   Grilli was called up from AAA Calgary to replace the injured
Alex Fernandez. He came to the Marlins from the Giants in the Livan
Hernandez trade last July. He was advertised as the Giants'
top-rated prospect for 1998 and 1999 but had done little to back it
up going 1-5 with a 7.68 ERA last year in AAA Calgary and 1-3 with
a 7.34 this year in AAA. He gave up 11 hits to the Braves in 6 2/3
innings but only four runs to outpitch Millwood, who allowed five
runs, including a two-run homer to Preston Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Strong relieved Grilli in the seventh and erased the tying runs
in the seventh and eighth innings. This right-hander has taken
journeyman to new heights, spending 11 professional seasons in
places like Mexico, Korea, Taiwan as well as the minors. He became
the oldest to make his major-league debut since left-hander
Diomedes Olivo started for the Pirates in 1960 at age 41.
</P>
<P>
   Go figure.
</P>
<P>
   In a series of the bizarre, the Marlins used a walk-off balk on
Monday, a Tom Glavine baserunning blunder on Wednesday and the
first RBI of the year for leadoff hitter Luis Castillo on Thursday
to win their first series over the Braves since July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves added to the bizarre by turning their first triple
play since 1986 to get Millwood out of a two-hit mess he left for
Greg McMichael in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   With his run-support lacking, Millwood took offensive measures
into his own hands, collecting the first two hits of his 2000
season and driving in his first two runs, but it wasn't enough. It
looked like it might be that kind of night early on after the
Braves netted only one run _ on a Brian Jordan groundout _ out of
two bases-loaded opportunities in the first two innings.
</P>
<P>
   When Chipper Jones popped out to end a bases-loaded situation in
the second inning, it was the 14th time in this series the Braves
had loaded the bases and failed to get a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
