<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTOS-POLLUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT SAYS EPA UNDERESTIMATING EMISSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency's computer
model for predicting how much air pollution comes from cars and
trucks underestimates emissions and may overestimate the benefits
of some pollution-control strategies, the National Academy of
Sciences said in a report on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not say how far off the model is, but it said
that the model ``substantially'' underestimates emissions of
unburned fuel from cars and nitrogen oxides from trucks, both major
ingredients of smog. And the model may overestimate the value of
dashboard lights to warn of pollution control problems and of the
value of ethanol and gasoline additives intended to reduce
emissions, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decisions that rely on the results of this model are of
tremendous importance to human health, the environment and the
economy,'' the report said in explaining the value of accurate
computer predictions.
</P>
<P>
   One member of the committee that wrote the report, Dr. Laurence
S. Caretto, dean of the College of Engineering and Computer Science
at California State University at Northridge, said the
investigators questioned whether the EPA was ``looking at the right
things'' in creating a model. A more accurate model would indicate
which pollution-control strategies to pursue, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency developed the program, the Mobile Source Emissions
Factor Model, known as Mobile, in 1978 and has revised it
intermittently since then. The study said it was ``the central tool
used by environmental and transportation agencies to estimate
on-road mobile-emissions and to assess national, state and local
air-quality programs for controlling such emissions.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the agency, David Cohen, said the study was
``constructive, fair and balanced,'' and made good recommendations.
Agency officials noted that they were sometimes accused of setting
emissions rules that were too stringent, but that the study seemed
to say they might be too lax.
</P>
<P>
   The committee said the environmental agency was in the dark on
some crucial issues, like the reaction of drivers to what is
colloquially known as the ``idiot light,'' the federally required
warning light on the dashboard that illuminates when a car's
computer senses a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The committee is unaware of any studies conducted to assess
the motorist response to illuminated malfunction indicator lights,
although this response rate is one of the most important factors
for determining the effectiveness of on-board diagnostic systems in
reducing emissions,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency, the report said, also needs to know more about
``high-emitting vehicles'' _ cars and trucks with smoking tailpipes
_ that are believed to be the source of a large portion of
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   Pollution regulators should also pay more attention to off-road
sources of emissions, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
