<SLUG> BC-METHODISTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE PROTESTS, METHODISTS REAFFIRM ANTI-GAY STANCE  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   By RICHARD VARA 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Delegates to the United Methodist Church's General
Conference voted 2-1 Thursday to affirm that ``homosexual practice
was incompatible with Christian teaching'' despite protests that
resulted in the arrest of 30 people, including two bishops.
</P>
<P>
   The 990 delegates to national legislative assembly meeting at
the Cleveland Convention Center also voted 2-1 to forbid the
ordaining of self-declared practicing homosexuals and banning
church blessing for same-sex unions.
</P>
<P>
   The impassioned debates and votes came the day after 191 gay
rights protesters, including one bishop, were arrested for blocking
a convention center roadway.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative sessions were disrupted by gay rights protesters
who marched onto the conference floor immediately after delegates
voted 628-337 to retain the current church policy that gay behavior
was not in accordance with Christian teaching. About 50 protesters
marched onto the General Conference floor and began singing We
Shall Overcome, a hymn associated with the civil rights movement.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, a weeping woman stood on a concrete ledge
overlooking the floor yelling ``I have been gay all my life.'' As
stunned delegates below scattered, people pulled her from the ledge
and she was escorted out of the center and taken away by medical
personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call upon you prayerfully, our brothers and sisters to lift
the exclusionary policies of the Methodist Church and unite us as
one,'' said Randolph Miller, a protest leader from California. The
protesters were lead by AMAR, a coalition of United Methodist gay
rights groups. Miller asked for a moratorium on gay-related
exclusions in the church's Book of Discipline or church law.
</P>
<P>
   He said the protesters would not move and invited arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Dan Solomon recessed the tumultuous session for 20
minutes as he negotiated with the protesters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a hurting situation,'' said a teary-eyed Rev. William H.
Hinson, senior minister of First United Methodist Church of
Houston, as he left the session. ``It is sad. It is tough to hold
biblical principle when people of good conscience have another
view.``
</P>
<P>
   Delegates were stunned by the actions. Several women delegates
huddled together weeping.
</P>
<P>
   But after they reconvened, delegates voted to ban the ordination
of self-declared gays to the ministry.
</P>
<P>
   During the afternoon session and after delegates voted to ban
the blessing of same-sex unions, the protesters marched onto the
platform and refused Solomon's entreaties to peacefully leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I speak with anguish in my voice for the circumstances that
are about to unfold. I bury my head in prayer,'' said a shaken
Solomon.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward about eight Cleveland police officers moved
onto the stage and arrested the protesters. The demonstrators
peacefully left the stage and were charged with disrupting a lawful
meeting, a misdemeanor. Among those arrested were Bishops C. Joseph
Sprague of Chicago and Susan Morrison of Albany, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow protesters shouted ``Shame!'' at the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel profound sadness and profound rage that the church of
Jesus Christ would exclude people in their midst,'' said Marilyn
Alexander, director of the pro-gay Reconciling Congregations
Program.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a lot of people who will leave in disgust,''
Alexander said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is extremely painful,'' said the Rev. Jimmy Creech, a
minister who was defrocked by the church for presiding at a
same-sex union. ``The church continues to persecute and oppress
gay, lesbian, bisexual and transgendered people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously the United Methodist Church has some severe
differences of opinion but the majority by a 2-1 margin have upheld
the tradition of the church,'' said the Rev. Scott Field,
coordinator of several conservative groups.
</P>
<P>
   But few delegates or observers thought the gay rights debate was
over for the 8.5 million member denomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not over,'' said delegate. ``I wish I could say it
was.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
