<SLUG> BC-HKN-WEST-PREVIEW0512-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Party of four: Avs hungriest?
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Last season, when the Detroit Red Wings had their run
of Stanley Cups smacked to a halt, Ken Holland believed he had
caught a glimpse of the NHL's new king. Now, he is sure of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Colorado beat us in the playoffs last year, I thought
they would go on to win the Cup,'' Detroit's general manager said.
``They led Dallas, 3-2, (in the Western Conference Finals) but then
it just seemed that Dallas' desire and all those intangibles made a
difference. But I'm picking Colorado again. After watching them, it
seems like they're hungrier and more desperate, and now they have
(Ray) Bourque. I think they're the best team out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL's postseason continues this weekend when Dallas faces
Colorado in the opener of the Western Conference Finals on Saturday
night and Philadelphia visits New Jersey on Sunday in the East. The
focus in the East mostly is on who isn't there: the Flyers are
missing Eric Lindros and maybe Keith Primeau.
</P>
<P>
   But the NHL's playoff showcase is the West, as was expected when
the regular season ended. There is a marquee matchup in goal
(Patrick Roy vs. Ed Belfour), stars on both benches and a certain
Hall-of-Fame defenseman (Bourque) trying to win his first Cup.
</P>
<P>
   This also is a rematch of last season's Western Conference
Finals, when Colorado took a 3-2 series lead, only to get drilled
by a composite score of 8-2 in the next two games. Dallas beat
Colorado the same way it plans on beating the Avs this series _
physically. Defenseman Richard Matvichuk almost single-handedly
crippled the Colorado offense, knocking Milan Hedjuk out for the
last three games with a broken collarbone and rendering Peter
Forsberg harmless with a battered shoulder that required offseason
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Both were clean checks, but that didn't stop Colorado coach Bob
Hartley from jumpstarting a verbal battle this week, saying the hit
on Forsberg was ``an intent to injure,'' and adding, ``I'm just
sorry that Matvichuk did not get the Conn Smythe Trophy (playoff
MVP) last year. With all the destruction he did, maybe he should've
gotten the trophy.''
</P>
<P>
   Matvichuk denied he meant to injure Forsberg or Hedjuk, but
added, ``We want to make our physical presence known. That's my
job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, who are four victories away from getting back to the
finals despite an inordinate number of injuries, realize this
Colorado team is significantly stronger than last season's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we felt like we were destined to win the Cup, the
way we came back to beat Colorado,'' Dallas center Joe Nieuwendyk
said.
</P>
<P>
   The West winner will meet the winner of the ``Jersey Turnpike
Series.'' The Devils would seem to be a heavy favorite, coming off
lopsided series victories over Florida (4-0) and Toronto (4-2) and
holding the Leafs to a record six shots in the clincher. But few
expected the Flyers to get this far without Lindros and with coach
Roger Nielson bumped to the press box after the team got hot during
his recovery from cancer surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The series is a rematch of the 1995 conference finals, when the
Devils won en route to their lone Stanley Cup. New Jersey has had a
string of playoff failures since.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're kind of turning the page. Winning the first round was
not enough,'' goalie Martin Brodeur said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
