<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0459 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2619 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-LATEGANO-     05-11 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-LATEGANO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-COMMUNICATIONS DIRECTOR DENIES AFFAIR WITH GIULIANI
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Nicholas Nicholas is cq.) 
(With: NY-GIULIANI, NY-GIULIANI-REACT, NY-GIULIANI-CLINTON) 
 By ABBY GOODNOUGH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cristyne Lategano-Nicholas said Thursday that she had
never had a sexual relationship with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, and
that they merely had ``a very close friendship'' during the six
years they worked side by side in City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks came a day after Donna Hanover, Giuliani's wife,
announced that his relationship with Lategano-Nicholas had damaged
their marriage. Lategano-Nicholas was the mayor's closest aide for
six years, accompanying him frequently as his press secretary and
then his communications director.
</P>
<P>
   ``What needs to be clear is that the only relationship I ever
had with the mayor was a professional one,'' Lategano-Nicholas said
in a telephone interview Thursday night from Yankee Stadium, where
she was watching a baseball game with her husband, Nicholas
Nicholas. ``There is nothing to prove other than a very close
friendship and working relationship.'' She added, ``I'm happy to
say we are still friendly with each other, although obviously I
don't see him very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Hanover said on Wednesday that for several years, ``it was
difficult to participate in Rudy's public life because of a
relationship with one staff member.'' Her aides later confirmed
that she was referring to Lategano-Nicholas, 35, who left City Hall
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   She was married in February to Nicholas, a golf writer.
</P>
<P>
   Lategano-Nicholas is president of NYC and Co., the city's
tourism board, a job that one former city official said was almost
certainly arranged by Giuliani. She is paid $150,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   She left City Hall last May, after taking a leave of absence to
aid her mother, who had cancer. She returned briefly in August,
when executives at the tourism bureau made clear that she was the
front-runner as soon as she asked for the job.
</P>
<P>
   One former city official familiar with Lategano-Nicholas'
performance at the tourism bureau said that Giuliani had indeed
pressured executives there to hire her. But Giuliani is also
believed to have asked them to hire her predecessor, Fran Reiter,
who was a deputy mayor before getting the tourism job in 1997. The
city provides $5.6 million of the bureau's $13.6 million annual
budget.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Giuliani and representatives of the tourism bureau
defended Lategano-Nicholas' work at the bureau, and her hiring
there. ``Cristyne Lategano was an excellent communications
director,'' Giuliani said at his daily news conference. ``And the
reality is that she's doing an excellent job now.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether she feared that Hanover's statement would damage
her reputation, Lategano-Nicholas said, ``You're always concerned
about that,'' but added, ``This will pass, and my work stands for
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The former city official, who spoke on condition of anonymity,
said that some of the bureau's board and staff members were
initially unhappy that Lategano-Nicholas got the job. But the
official said that Lategano-Nicholas quickly won them over, in part
by working tirelessly. The official said that while people at the
tourism bureau viewed Lategano-Nicholas as a patronage employee,
they saw the situation not as ``the mayor's girlfriend being
rewarded,'' but as ``the mayor's loyal aide being rewarded.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Rubenstein, the bureau's spokesman, said Hanover's
statement would ``absolutely not'' hurt Lategano-Nicholas' career.
``She's done probably the best job in that position of any
executive they've had in recent history,'' Rubenstein said. ``She
has been very good at the trade shows and conventions. She's
strengthened the staff and they are loyal to her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2254EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
