<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0460 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 22:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-ART-     05-11 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILLIPS-AUCTION-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIRD-RANKED AUCTION HOUSE DIPS A TOE INTO COMPETITIVE WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photos NYT28 and 29 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the main gallery of the American Craft Museum in
Manhattan, an airless space with room for just 300 seats, the art
world waited to see how the first major evening auction by
Phillips, the world's third-largest auction house, would fare. And
waited. And waited.
</P>
<P>
   The auction began nearly an hour late, and then it started with
an announcement that 3 percent of the hammer prices would go to the
American Foundation for AIDS Research. Dressed in a bright orange
dress with matching lipstick, the movie star Sharon Stone, campaign
chairwoman for the charity, made a speech about AIDS. Throughout
the evening, she wandered up and down the aisles trying to drum up
excitement in the otherwise dead room.
</P>
<P>
   Was this a charity auction or a sale of serious art? several
people in the audience asked. It quickly became apparent that even
limitless pots of money can't buy a respected place in the art
world.
</P>
<P>
   The auction was not only Phillips' first time selling
multimillion-dollar Impressionist and modern art in a big evening
sale, but also its first sale since LVMH Moet Hennessy Louis
Vuitton bought the company in October. The parent company's
chairman, Bernard Arnault, had spent million of dollars trying to
make Phillips a major player in an unforgiving art world.
</P>
<P>
   About 40 percent of the works went unsold. Of the 31 offered,
only 18 sold, and of those only 4 were within or above their
estimates. The sale totaled $43.9 million.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward Arnault was upbeat about the results. ``It's the
largest sale ever for Phillips,'' he said. ``This is a good first
step. We are here for the long term, and we will make this work.
Today is a start.''
</P>
<P>
   To compete with Sotheby's and Christie's, LVMH had given sellers
some kind of financing for 30 of the 31 works offered Thursday
night, reportedly an investment of $100 million. In some cases
Phillips gave sellers a straight guarantee (an undisclosed minimum
price given to the seller regardless of a sale's outcome), an
advance, a loan or a combination of the three. Often, experts at
competing auction houses said, Arnault had paid more for the works
than their estimates reflected.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do is not different from the others,'' Arnault said
when asked about the financial arrangements he made with sellers.
</P>
<P>
   He also spent well over $1 million renting and renovating the
American Craft Museum, just four blocks from Christie's and across
the street from the Museum of Modern Art, for the sale. Phillips'
New York headquarters on East 79th Street was too small to
accommodate the curious crowd of several hundred.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the catalog was circulated to collectors last month,
the sale had been the talk of the art world. The estimates were too
high, experts said. All the negative talk affected the reaction
last night. With only a few exceptions, bidding was thin and most
often by unidentified telephone bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The final work in the sale was the most important: Malevich's
``Suprematist Composition,'' an austere abstract painting that hung
in the Museum of Modern Art until recently. Before the sale, the
painting was placed on an easel in the front of the room shrouded
by a black velvet cloth, which Stone dramatically removed when the
bidding began. But even that didn't help generate excitement. Only
two telephone bidders went for the painting, which finally sold for
$17 million. Phillips had refused to estimate the selling price,
but LVMH had reportedly bought the painting for $15 million.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Malevich's 31 heirs won a claim to get the painting back last
year, and they consigned it to Phillips to sell. While the auction
house says the painting dates from 1919, curators at the museum say
it was painted later, from 1923 to 1925. The difference in dating
is important, experts say: if it was made in 1919, it is far more
valuable.
</P>
<P>
   The other 30 works in the sale were a mixed bag, dominated by a
group of paintings that an unidentified Japanese collector bought
for high prices during the 1980s art market boom. The Wildenstein
Gallery represented the Japanese seller. Both Sotheby's and
Christie's made a play for the works, but no one was willing to pay
the $27 million that Phillips reportedly spent. The group included
works by Monet, Cezanne, Pissarro and Vuillard.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few popular works Thursday night, part of the
collection from Japan, was Sisley's ``Garden at Louveciennes (Path
to l'Etarche)'' from 1873, a lush landscape. It finally sold to an
unidentified telephone bidder for $3.5 million, double its high
estimate of $1.5 million. Picasso's ``Sleeping Nude and Woman
Washing Her Feet'' (1944) had three bidders and ended up bringing
$4.4 million, just above its $4 million high estimate.
</P>
<P>
   But a majority of works that sold went for far less than
Phillips had estimated. Take Cezanne's ``View of Gardanne,'' a
landscape from 1886-90 that was expected to bring $6 million to $8
million. Only one bidder wanted it, and it sold for $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Many drew no interest at all. Monet's ``Seine Near Bougival''
(1872) came with an estimate of $5 million to $6 million. Bidding
started at $3 million and never went higher than $3.7 million.
</P>
<P>
   Another seller last night was the Nahmads, a family of Lebanese
dealers with galleries in New York and London who have been among
the biggest buyers at Sotheby's and Christie's for the last decade.
An 1898 Renoir, ``The Loge at the Theatre des Varietes,'' one of
the artist's loge scenes, was expected to sell for $5 million to $7
million. There were no bids.
</P>
<P>
   (Final prices include Phillips' commission, 15 percent of the
first $50,000 and 10 percent of the rest. Estimates do not reflect
commissions.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After the sale, dealers and collectors milled outside the
museum, gossiping about the evening's outcome. ``I felt sorry for
them, but it was the worst combination,'' said Alexander Apsis, the
former head of Impressionist and modern art for Sotheby's in New
York, who is now a partner of C&AMP;M Arts, a Manhattan gallery. ``When
you have not-great paintings and estimates that are too high, you
can't help but get killed.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
