u a BC-RAILYARD-KILLER-HNS &LR;      05-11 1003
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAILYARD-KILLER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PSYCHIATRIST SAYS RAILYARD SUSPECT THOUGHT VICTIM LOOKED LIKE AN
ANGEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LISA TEACHEY 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A defense psychiatrist testified Thursday that Angel
Maturino Resendiz at first thought his victim looked like a
beautiful angel as she slept, but after he found signs of evil in
her house God told him to kill her.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn to the suburban West University Place home by ``evil
forces,'' he found in the study of Dr. Claudia Benton, a pediatric
geneticist, pictures of children with birth defects and an African
carving he thought depicted an evil deity who persecuted Jews, Dr.
Bruce Cohen testified.
</P>
<P>
   During the second day of defense testimony in Maturino
Resendiz's capital murder trial, his mother, Virginia Maturino
Resendiz, testified that she had given birth standing up and her
newborn son fell on his head. He also suffered several blows to the
head growing up and witnessed her being attacked by a man wielding
a machete, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Other family members testified that as a child Maturino Resendiz
was sexually abused by a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen described the Mexican national as a paranoid
schizophrenic, a condition that had been caused by a combination of
head injuries, drug abuse and a family history of mental illness.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is trying to prove those traumas led to a diminished
mental state that ultimately sent him on a mission to destroy
``evil people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of that offense, as a result of schizophrenia, he
did not know that his conduct was wrong,'' Cohen testified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up to this day I don't feel guilty,'' Maturino Resendiz told
Cohen. ``I feel for the families, but I will tell you I feel like
somebody else did it and not me. ... I know it was me, but I can't
point the finger and say it was me. ... I know the jury won't like
hearing this, but how can I feel sorry for evil.''
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz, 40, is charged with the December 1998 slaying
and rape of Benton, one of six Texans he has admitted to killing,
as well as two others in Illinois and one more in Kentucky over a
two-year period.
</P>
<P>
   The self-described ``half angel, half man'' has pleaded not
guilty by reason of insanity, claiming God had told him to destroy
abortion clinics, but along the way an evil presence led him to
kill at random.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted, he would &UR;  &LR; get the death penalty or life in prison.
Under Texas law, jurors can only find an accused person legally
insane if they believe he suffered a severe mental disorder and
could not tell right from wrong at the time of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   The state has rested its case linking Maturino Resendiz to the
Benton death through fingerprints, DNA and stolen items recovered
from his home in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Maturino Resendiz is an organized, higher-functioning
schizophrenic able to carry out his delusions by stowing away on
freight trains to move from town to town looking for abortion
clinics. At each city he spent the day searching for clinics and at
night tried to find a place to sleep near the tracks.
</P>
<P>
   That's what he was doing the night he attacked Benton, Cohen
said. He was particularly drawn to Houston, which he called Sodom.
</P>
<P>
   Maturino Resendiz was diverted that night by a sudden feeling
that he should walk along the railroad tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then I found the doctor's place,'' Cohen testified
Maturino Resendiz told him during 19 hours of examinations, and a
``cold chill'' filled his head. Earlier witnesses testified he
forced the garage door open and entered the home from there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something told me to go in and led me to the computer room and
I saw the evil pictures of experiments she was doing on babies,''
Maturino Resendiz told Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   Benton did no such experiments. She was preparing a report on
her work on Angelman syndrome, a condition that causes retardation,
and had left her computer on when she went to bed.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said Maturino Resendiz then returned to the bedroom,
bludgeoned her head with a bronze statute, turned her body face
down on the floor and wrapped her head in a plastic bag to try to
make her look like a blonde angel.
</P>
<P>
   As she lay dying, he raped her.
</P>
<P>
   In a move by the defense that backfired, lawyers for Maturino
Resendiz called his sister, Manuela Maturino Karkiewicz, in an
attempt to establish that Texas Ranger Drew Carter had tricked her
into helping persuade her brother to surrender by not discussing
the possibility he would get the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Carter, who took Maturino Resendiz into custody in July at the
Mexico-Texas border, earlier testified that he had expressly told
her that death was an option.
</P>
<P>
   During defense questioning, Karkiewicz said Carter only
guaranteed that the family would be allowed to visit her brother in
jail and he would receive psychiatric help.
</P>
<P>
   Defense attorney Allen Tanner has said the family's demand of
``humane'' treatment meant he would not be put to death. Karkiewicz
denied she had ever discussed the death penalty with Carter.
</P>
<P>
   But under cross-examination by prosecutor Devon Anderson,
Karkiewicz admitted she had asked Carter about the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson asked if it were true she had asked if she was eligible
for any reward money.
</P>
<P>
   Karkiewicz adamantly denied it, even when Anderson produced a
certified letter addressed to the sister stating that she had
helped in the capture of her brother.
</P>
<P>
   Karkiewicz said Carter had told her she would need the letter if
she wanted to use the money for her brother's defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were the ones that told me about it, but I never asked
for the money,'' Karkiewicz said
</P>
<P>
   ``But you took the money, ma'am,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the sister responded quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``How much was it,'' Anderson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-six,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eighty-six thousand dollars?'' Anderson asked. ``How much of
that has been used for the defense of your brother?''
</P>
<P>
   ``None,'' Karkiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
