 MERRILL LYNCH INVESTING IN NEEDY AREAS  &HT;     By CHRONICLE STAFF 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Investment giant Merrill Lynch said Thursday
that it will invest $159 million in low-income neighborhoods in
California during the next three years in partnership with
Greenlining Institute, a San Francisco community activist group.
</P>
<P>
   Greenlining will be Merrill's liaison to community groups and
advise the brokerage as it builds its low-income lending operation.
</P>
<P>
   The program earmarks $120 million for small-business lending,
$15 million for affordable housing, $16 million for recruiting
financial advisers from minority communities and $8 million for
supporting businesses and nonprofit groups in the state.
</P>
<P>
   The initiative is an expansion of a program Merrill started in
Southern California in 1996, shortly after Orange County went
through one of the highest-profile local-government bankruptcies in
recent U.S. history. The county cut services in low-income
neighborhoods after it went broke.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill, which had been an underwriter of the county's bonds,
responded with a $77 million investment program in Orange and Los
Angeles counties. In addition to its brokerage business, the firm
is a major small-business lender.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires banks to provide credit to all communities,
and banks have long sponsored programs to offer banking services in
low-income neighborhoods. But brokerages have been exempt from such
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time a brokerage house has made this kind of
commitment to inner cities in California, in cooperation with
community groups,'' said Bob Gnaizda, the Greenlining policy
director.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
