<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2746 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WEBBY-AWARDS-SFCHRON &LR;      05-11 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEBBY-AWARDS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEBBY AWARDS' POPULARITY GROWS
</HEADLINE>
  
 Editor's Note: This story will be updated with details on
award  winners.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By Verne Kopytoff &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 200 The San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For a few hours Thursday night, the Internet
industry forgot its recent worries about falling stock prices and
nonexistent profits to congratulate itself on a job well done.
</P>
<P>
   Company executives and designers gathered at the Masonic
Auditorium on Nob Hill in San Francisco for the 4th Annual Webby
Awards, a celebration in the tradition of the Oscars that honors
the world's best Web sites in 27 categories.
</P>
<P>
   The awards have become increasingly popular as a measure of
quality and as a source of bragging rights, especially in the Bay
Area, considered the capital of the technology industry. The rapid
growth of the Internet has propelled the Webbys from its modest
birth in a San Francisco nightclub to Thursday night's extravagant,
Hollywood-style event.
</P>
<P>
   Creating a veneer of prestige was clearly a goal of the event's
organizers. Guests entered the auditorium on a red carpet patrolled
by paparazzi, actually actors paid to shout questions and use flash
cameras that had no film.
</P>
<P>
   The event itself had some more authentic Hollywood touches. Alan
Cumming, the Tony Award winning actor who has appeared in films
like ``Eyes Wide Shut,'' was the master of ceremonies, while
actress Sandra Bernhard and Talk magazine editor Tina Brown
presented awards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think awards shows in general fulfill this primal need in
people to seek validation,'' said Tiffany Shlain, the event's
founder and director. ``And really, the Webby Awards are a large
dramatic way of saying `Good job.'''
</P>
<P>
   As has been the case throughout the Webbys' short history,
invitations were difficult to come by. Signaling how much the
Internet industry covets awards, or simply how much it enjoys a
night out, Shlain said that ticket demand exceeded the venue's
2,400-seat capacity by at least a factor of two or three.
</P>
<P>
   The Webby ceremony was a mixture of tribute, irreverence, satire
and multimedia spectacle that mimicked the tenor of the Internet.
Event organizers called it an ``antidote to the Oscars,'' and in
many ways that was true.
</P>
<P>
   As has been the Webbys' hallmark, victory speeches were limited
to five words. However, the winners still managed to include some
whimsical phrasing that made the audience laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Award presentations were juggled between animated film clips,
live music and special effects. The hall was decorated to the theme
of H.G. Wells' ``The Time Machine,'' which meant futuristic decor
like a round movie screen and flashing lights.
</P>
<P>
   Categories included arts, commerce, games, humor and kids.
Judging was done by 270 members of the International Academy of
Digital Arts and Sciences, a group that describes itself as
encouraging the ``progress of new media,'' and includes celebrities
such as actor Robin Williams and musician David Bowie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, it wasn't very difficult for me to choose a
winner,'' said Deepak Chopra, the spiritual adviser and author who
was a judge in the health category but did not attend the ceremony.
``I think the Webbys are a good way to get people interested in the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, representatives from the Webby-nominated sites
were pleased at being part of the competition. Their sentiments
ranged from pride at the recognition to the expectation of free
publicity and its residual riches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a huge validation,'' said Thomas Hale, chief executive
of  &LR; WiredPlanet.com,  &LR; a music Web site based in San Francisco.
``There are thousands of music sites out there and being picked
among the top five is key.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark Rinella, vice president and general manager of
 &LR; bluemountain.com,  &LR; a Redwood City, Calif., greeting card Web site
that was nominated in the living category, said that the
competition puts a deserved spotlight on his Web designers and
programmers, who usually ``get recognition only when something goes
wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Others had a more understated view of the event and downplayed
its significance. Michael Gough, chief creative officer for
Quokka.com, a San Francisco site that was nominated in the sports
category, debated whether to wear jeans or a tuxedo to the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the Oscars or the Emmys,'' said Gough, who decided to
wear jeans. ``But then again, we're not nominated for an Oscar or
Emmy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some categories featured relatively unknown Internet sites
rather than the multimillion dollar companies that can afford to
build fancy ones. In many cases, the operators of those small sites
had no idea how they got nominated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to get all dressed up and go to some fancy
shindig,'' said Jason Kottke, a Web designer from Minneapolis,
whose online diary,  &LR; kottke.org &LR; , was up for an award in the
personal category. ``It's an excuse to go to San Francisco.''
</P>
<P>
   One early winner was Entropy8Zuper, a graphics-intensive Web
site ( &LR; www.entropy8zuper.org &LR; ) operated by Michael Samyn, of
Belgium, and Auriea Harvey, an American living in Belgium. It won
the inaugural SFMOMA Webby Prize for Excellence in Online Art, run
in conjunction with the Webbys and the San Francisco Museum of
Modern Art.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the other Webby awards, the winners of this prize
received $30,000. The judging was also different in that it was
based on a body on work rather than a single Web site.
</P>
<P>
   The Webby ceremony was preceded by a party at Grace Cathedral
that featured ``cyber angels,'' acrobats that appeared to dangle in
the air inside the church. A party after the ceremony was held in
the cathedral's plaza and in a tent at nearby Huntington Park.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the event's satirical edge, the Webbys hired
people to roam the festivities and fuss over guests to make them
feel important. But what got much of the attention were some of the
outrageously dressed guests, including ones wearing silver insect
wings and space suits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the buzz around the Webbys, it is difficult to
measure what winning one means. Some Webby-winning sites report a
surge in visitors, while others say the benefits are unclear.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, companies try to capitalize on the event as much
as they can, judging from the number of them that issued press
releases touting their nominations. Many nominees also placed the
Webby emblem on their Internet sites and encouraged their users to
vote for them in the Webby's popularity competition, the People's
Voice.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the biggest beneficiary of the Webbys are the Webbys
themselves, which are owned by IDG, a technology market research
company in Framingham, Mass., that publishes the ``... for
Dummies'' series of books. The event has grown dramatically from
its first year in 1997, when it was held at Bimbo's nightclub in
North Beach and one of the categories was devoted to pornography,
an award that has since been discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   Chronicle staff writer Carrie Kirby contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Verne Kopytoff at  &LR; verne(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2312EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 23:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2747 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHR     05-11 1498
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NET WORTH: BAY AREA HOME BUYERS MAY GET A BREAK AS
INVENTORIES  RISE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Now that the tech-stock bubble has burst, can
the Bay Area's overinflated real estate market be far behind?
</P>
<P>
   Some agents say that in the past few weeks, insanity seems to
have slipped out of the housing market, particularly at the higher
end, and particularly in Silicon Valley, which in the late 1990s
led the Bay Area out of its real estate slump.
</P>
<P>
   The signs (don't laugh): Some houses are staying on the market
more than a week, attracting only a handful of offers, and selling
at their asking prices.
</P>
<P>
   The reasons (from Econ 101): Supply is growing and demand is
slipping.
</P>
<P>
   The number of homes for sale is increasing, partly because this
is the peak selling season, but also because many people saw their
neighbors' homes fetch unimaginable prices and decided to fling
their own houses onto the market.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of greedy sellers,'' says Lauren Lai, a broker
with Coldwell Banker in San Francisco. ``They say, `Put it out
there and see what happens.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Nasdaq's 30-percent plunge since March 10 has
driven some buyers out of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Hatvany, a broker with TRI/Coldwell Banker, says that on
the Sunday before last, there were three homes in San Francisco
ranging from $700,000 to $800,000 that were back on the market
after pending sales fell through. She heard the deals unraveled
because of the stock market.
</P>
<P>
   Lai had listed one of the homes, on Turk Street. She confirmed
that the buyer dropped out because his stock portfolio got hit and
he had trouble selling his own house. She said a new offer has been
accepted on the house that is ``comparable'' to the first one.
</P>
<P>
   Even if they haven't lost money in the stock market, some buyers
have retreated to the sidelines because they're tired of losing out
in bidding wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had folks who've said, `I'd like to stand back from the
market for a while. I'm exhausted. I'm beat up. I'm taking a
rest,''' says Susan Peterson, a broker with Pacific Union in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson says the market is not heading south, it's just
``leveling off.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Weeks, a broker with Coldwell Banker in Silicon Valley,
has a different opinion. ``I think the bubble has burst,'' she
says. ``There are 66 houses on the market in San Mateo right now.
That is roughly three times what we were seeing earlier in the
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Weeks says she welcomes the change. The market got so nutty that
her company recently started requiring buyers to sign a two-page
disclosure statement that basically says, ``I know I'm paying too
much money for this house but I'm doing it anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Carole Rodoni, president of Alain Pinel Realtors in Saratoga,
Calif., concurs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very good correction,'' she says. ``Buyers will have
more choices. Where there used to be seven, eight or nine houses on
tour in Palo Alto, now you'll see 30.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, ``We have seen the number of multiple offers come
down. Where there were 17 or 18, now you see three or four.''
Rodoni predicts that ``rapid appreciation will become more mild
appreciation.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are no statistics that suggest a slowdown. Neither
DataQuick nor the California Association of Realtors have released
their April figures for Bay Area home sales and prices.
</P>
<P>
   So I called the individual real estate associations for San
Francisco, San Mateo, Santa Clara, Alameda, Contra Costa and Marin
counties and got data on prices, days on market, inventory and
sales for the past three months.
</P>
<P>
   These figures are not always complete or comparable.
Nevertheless, they show that homes continued to sell faster in
April, and for more money, and even though inventories grew from
March, there were still fewer homes on the market last month than
there were in April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But agents point out April sales were usually started in March _
before the worst of the Nasdaq crash. Furthermore, they say that if
there is a slowdown, it only started a couple weeks ago and won't
show up in the numbers until May or June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the next two weeks will be a good indicator'' of where
the market is going, says Monica Rohrer, a broker who works in
Oakland and Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the market stalls, no one is predicting a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a very, very active market,'' says Rodoni.``It's
not a market in stress, in the toilet, or a market that has gone
down the drain.''
</P>
<P>
   For every sale that has fallen apart, agents can name at least
one that has far exceeded the asking price.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not seeing any of the indications we typically see when
the market starts to level out or dry up,'' says John Karevoll of
DataQuick, which tracks home sales.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side (if you're a seller), there is still pent-up
demand from people who desperately need a place to live. The Bay
Area unemployment rate is below 3 percent, and the number of jobs
created has far exceeded the number of homes built.
</P>
<P>
   People who are sitting on stock options that have suddenly
become worthless probably can't buy the house of their dreams. But
plenty of people with good-paying jobs can still afford a house,
especially if they're not competing against instant millionaires
who might come in with a bid 25 percent above asking price.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Bruzzone is a broker with Security Pacific who operates in
Marin and the Oakland-to-Richmond, Calif. corridor.
</P>
<P>
   Although Marin may have cooled off a degree or two, ``in
Richmond and Oakland, there's absolutely no slowdown. There are 20
to 30 offers on every house. But the houses cost $200,000,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dot-com bubble bursting has had zero impact on houses
under $400,000.'' The only way that market will be hurt is ``if
there was another 20 percent drop (in the Nasdaq index) and the
people who have a bunch of money stop employing the people who are
buying under-$400,000 houses.''
</P>
<P>
   But some experts think there is a very real chance of that
happening. John Goode, chief investment office with Davis Skaggs
Investment Management, cautions that a gargantuan amount of stock
could flood the market in the next few months as ``lockup'' periods
expire.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, when a company goes public, its employees, venture
capitalists and other insiders can't unload their stock for six
months. When this period ends, the number of shares these investors
can sell might be many times greater than the amount sold in the
IPO.
</P>
<P>
   Although few companies have gone public since March, a huge
number went public in the previous 12 months. And many analysts
believe that the enormous supply of stock coming from those
companies has hurt the market and will continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   Goode thinks that banks will be less willing to approve home
loans that are based on stock options or locked stock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who says the real estate market is independent of the
stock market is wrong,'' says Goode. ``A year from now, the real
estate market will be a far different place than it is today.
Things will take longer to sell. Probably you'll be dealing with
discounts from asking prices.''
</P>
<P>
   Buyers who wait, however, may face even bigger payments if the
Fed continues to raise interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, mortgage rates have risen by more than one
percentage point, according to Jann Van Heuver, senior loan
consultant with Advantage Financial in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   The rate on a 30-year fixed-rate mortgage is now around 8.5
percent for a loan under $240,000 and 8.75 percent for a loan over
that amount, she says. Both loans require payment of one point, or
1 percent of the loan amount.
</P>
<P>
   No matter what happens to rates or prices, Jeannette Fung says
she's never getting back into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, Fung and her family, who owned a nice home in San
Francisco west of Twin Peaks, started house hunting on the
Peninsula. They wanted to escape the fog and find a better school
for their 6-year-old boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the biggest shock of our lives,'' she says. ``We bid on
a lot in Redwood City. The guy wanted $750,000. He wanted us to
close in a week, with no due diligence.'' They lost the lot to
someone who was willing to buy without an inspection.
</P>
<P>
   They were one of 11 bidders on a 2,200-square-foot house in
Millbrae that was listed at $695,000. ``It went for $812,000,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   After that, they dropped out of the market and found a new
school for their son in the city. Today, Fung says she has no
desire to get back into the market, even if prices decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1990, we had a similar kind of superheated market. My
brother and I paid $400,000 for a two-unit place in Duboce
Triangle. We put $100,000 into rehabbing it.'' But her brother got
sick and they were forced to sell in 1996. They got $450,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that lesson now,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
