A2752 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-WELLS-INTERNET-SFCHRO     05-11 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-INTERNET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TECH LINK PLANNED AT WELLS
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By SAM ZUCKERMAN &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 2000 the San Francisco Chronicle &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Wells Fargo will unveil next week a series of
partnerships with Internet companies that will provide technology
and content for the bank's new Web site for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the San Francisco bank said that joining forces
with the seven Internet companies allows them to put together
rapidly a broad package of products and services for businesses.
These include features that have little to do with banking, such as
news and marketing software.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Internet economy, there is no way we could have moved
fast enough on our own,'' said Mark Baumli, vice president in
Wells' business Internet services unit.
</P>
<P>
   Such partnerships between established companies and Web-based
startups have become a staple feature of the Internet economy.
Established companies like Wells bring their millions of customers
to the relationships, while Web companies offer cutting-edge
technology plus online savvy.
</P>
<P>
   ``These upstart companies are not getting the brand recognition
they hoped for and they are running out of money,'' said Sutro &AMP;
Co. analyst Campbell Chaney. ``Now they are looking for strategic
partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells has more than 1 million small-business customers and is
the nation's largest lender to the sector, according to some
surveys.
</P>
<P>
   The bank's partners include DigitalWork.com, a Chicago provider
of online materials in such areas as marketing and human resources,
and NetSales, a Kansas company that sells resources for setting up
online stores. The two partners will charge Wells' customers fees
for using their products, splitting revenue with the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Other partners are Accrue Software, which will track customer
data for Wells, and Art Technology Group, which will provide its
Dynamo design tools that will allow the bank to customize its Web
site for individual customers.
</P>
<P>
   Three other companies will provide online tools and content for
Wells' small-business customers. Signio will offer online payment
processing tools; Vicinity will provide mapping and directory
services; and iSyndicate will offer news, stock quotes and other
online content.
</P>
<P>
   While Wells is a leader in Internet banking for consumers, it is
behind such rivals as Bank of America, Citibank, American Express
and financial softwaremaker Intuit in using the Web to reach
small-business customers.
</P>
<P>
   The bank presently offers several Web-based small-business
services, including access to NetSales' online sales materials. It
also provides account information over the Internet. But Wells
hasn't had an integrated small-business Internet package that
includes a variety of account-management features.
</P>
<P>
   The service Wells will begin offering next week will combine
basic banking services, such as electronic bill payment, with the
business resources provided by the bank's partners. Most online
banking services will be free, though there will be a $5 monthly
charge for bill payment, in line with most competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Wells officials say they want to establish their site both as a
banking center and as a resource businesspeople come to for a broad
range of information and services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are positioning ourselves as a small-business financial
destination site,'' Baumli said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the bank will be forced to play catch-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are late and it's very competitive,'' said Sutro's
Chaney. ``It will be expensive for them, but they will spend the
resources needed to make themselves a player.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2312EDT &QL; 
