<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 23:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2754 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-GIULIANI-CLINTON-A     05-11 0957
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GIULIANI-CLINTON-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON STAYS QUIET WHILE MAYOR IS IN THE SPOTLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(With: NY-GIULIANI, NY-GIULIANI-REACT, NY-GIULIANI-LATEGANO) 
 By ADAM NAGOURNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For the last two months, one sure way to coax Hillary
Rodham Clinton into attacking Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was to ask
about tense relations between Giuliani's police department and the
city's minority communities. But when Katie Couric asked Clinton
that question on a nationally televised town hall meeting Thursday
morning, the first lady let the pitch pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it is useful for us to point fingers at any
one person,'' Clinton said, showing uncharacteristic restraint.
</P>
<P>
   The turmoil surrounding the mayor's personal life has produced,
obviously, a challenge to his presumed campaign for a seat in the
U.S. Senate. But Giuliani's difficulties have also produced an
undeclared shift in strategy by Clinton these last few days, as her
campaign adopts a deliberately low profile while maneuvering to
adjust to an unsettled period filled with opportunities and perils.
</P>
<P>
   The result of that strategy was on display at the town meeting
from NBC studios at Rockefeller Center, where the name Giuliani
barely passed Clinton's lips during an hour of questioning by an
audience of New York voters and the hosts of the ``Today'' show. At
the direction of Clinton's senior advisers, an aide said Thursday,
the first lady and Democratic supporters have moved to shut the
spigot on almost all anti-Giuliani rhetoric, as Clinton adopts a
posture that is intended, unconventionally in this business, to
avoid trying to make news, which would have the effect of shifting
attention away from the mayor and his problems. (Even the normally
voluble state Democratic chairwoman, Judith Hope, did not return
phone calls to discuss the state of the race.)
</P>
<P>
   And next week's state Democratic convention in Albany is being
planned as a low-voltage affair, one aide said. Clinton's
acceptance speech is expected to be undramatic _ devoid of any
sweeping philosophical or policy pronouncement _ and President
Clinton is unlikely to attend, in part to lower the attention
factor, a friend of the Clintons said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason for this is that Clinton's aides believed,
even before Giuliani's recent run of difficulties, that the first
lady had hit something of a stride, with a daily mixture of attacks
on Giuliani and policy pronouncements. But the first lady's
advisers are now making a deliberate decision to avoid doing
anything that might take the spotlight away from the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're making all the news,'' one of Clinton's senior
advisers said of the Giuliani campaign. ``What do we need to make
news for? If we make news, you can bet it's the wrong kind of
news.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the first lady's advisers said, Clinton is staying
close to the ground: continuing her travels across the state, but
eschewing the daily attacks on Giuliani's temperament, which have
drawn much coverage, and focusing instead on the kind of dry policy
pronouncements that won't get much attention now. So it was, that
for 60 minutes Thursday Clinton rebuffed attempts by Couric to get
her to discuss Giuliani's problems, and instead plunged into long
discussions about health care, education and other issues that, if
informed, seemed aimed at not breaking any new ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our game plan is simply to stay on plan,'' Sen. Bob Torricelli
of New Jersey, the chairman of the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee, said in an interview. ``Hillary Clinton is beginning to
assume a commanding position. It's now just a question of
consolidating her lead.'' Torricelli's observations aside, some of
Clinton's advisers view this as a period of risks as well. For one
thing, if Giuliani does not run, they face the task of retooling a
campaign to deal with a new candidate. Clinton's advisers said they
were most concerned at the prospect of running against Gov. George
Pataki, given his fund-raising abilities and popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's advisers said that the governor had no interest in
running for the Senate. But if Giuliani decides not to run, the
governor will face strong pressure to get into this race,
Republicans said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Clinton's aides are wary about their candidate or
any of her surrogates saying anything that might be perceived as
insensitive to Giuliani's situation, particularly in such a charged
media atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the kind of period when you can make mistakes, where
you can say the wrong thing,'' a senior adviser said. ``It's easy
to make a slip of language on Rudy. You can do a lot of harm in
this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   It has been two months since Clinton _ who had been repeatedly
criticized by Democrats for running an unfocused and passionless
campaign _ turned up her attacks on Giuliani, assailing him for his
response to the police shooting of Patrick Dorismond, the same
topic that Clinton avoided discussing with Couric. And in a sense,
Clinton, in moving to the back of the stage, is responding to the
reality of Giuliani's situation; her campaign strategy is now being
driven, at least for the time being, by Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   When or if Clinton reassumes a more aggressive pose is also a
function of what Giuliani does and says. For now, though, Clinton
was described as more than happy to yield to her presumed
Republican opponent.
</P>
<P>
   ``She should continue just doing her job: talking about the
issues, visiting the entire state,'' said Sen. Charles Schumer,
D-N.Y. ``The same exact thing she is doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
