r s BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLA     05-11 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRACTICE MADE BRYANT'S SHOT PERFECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Shaquille O'Neal was an on- court spectator
for the biggest play of the Los Angeles Lakers' Game 2 victory over
the Phoenix Suns on Wednesday, but he didn't mind.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' leading man and go-to scorer in most situations was
ready to run a pick-and-roll with Kobe Bryant on the final play,
but Bryant had a choice, and he chose to go solo: He ran down the
clock, then hit the game-winner with 2.6 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kobe's probably going to take that shot seven out of 10 times.
And we don't mind him taking that shot,'' O'Neal said. ``I was
joking with him in the locker room. I told him it's about time he
hit one of those shots.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sequence Bryant has been trained for. Coach Phil Jackson
has put the ball in his hands to create a final shot at the end of
most every quarter, half and game this season. It hasn't always
produced great results, but Bryant's first career game-winner is
certain to boost his confidence _ and confidence in him by his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a redemption,'' Jackson said. ``That was a great
redemption for him and for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just don't want games to have to come down to that
situation,'' Jackson said. ``Yes, we want him to hit them. I think
he can. He has shown it in the past, he has had struggles in the
past, so it's a 50-50 proposition right now. But we think that we
can eliminate those kind of hail-Mary type opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   It was, of course, a bit Michael Jordanesque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, that's Kobe's billing,'' Jackson said. ``That's what
he's going to be as a basketball player, the kind of guy that can
do that. And we want to see him have that success.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryant himself had but one regret on the play, which gave the
Lakers the 97-96 win, and a 2-0 lead in the best-of-seven series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a little upset actually,'' he said, ``because I wanted
to hit it at the buzzer, like Larry Bird used to do.''
</P>
<P>
   __ One more thing: Although Bryant took the last shot, Jackson
said he's perfectly comfortable running a final play for O'Neal in
a similar situation. That, despite O'Neal's 46.6 percent foul
shooting in the playoffs, which Jackson said has been discussed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows the importance of it to our organization, our team,
everybody is relying on it,'' Jackson said. ``That's for him to
work on. I think he knows how to coach himself in this regard.''
</P>
<P>
   With O'Neal struggling, the Suns actually went to the
intentional foul late in the fourth quarter. O'Neal missed both
free throws and knows that will only invite further fouling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might do it,'' O'Neal said, ``but it can only get better.
It can't get no worse. . . . Usually, I hit them in situations like
that, but they're good misses. I don't have Olden Polynice-type
misses. I only have good misses, they'll be in and out, and you
know it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ The numbers: Only seven teams have ever come back from an 0-2
deficit to win a seven-game series, and no team has come back from
0-3, a fact the Lakers are conscious of as they head into Game 3 at
America West Arena tonight.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody will come off a 3-0 deficit some day,'' Jackson said,
``but it hasn't happened yet. So I mean, it's pretty obvious that
it means a hell of a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   __ One slip: That the Lakers needed a game-winning shot after
leading by 13 was irksome to all involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we just got bored after getting the 15-point lead and we
took them for granted,'' O'Neal said. ``That's probably what it
was, we probably took this team for granted. And they came down the
stretch, got a couple steals, hit a couple 3s and they're a
dangerous team that way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
