<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: BID TO SPEED LOCKERBIE TRIAL
</P>
<P>
   The trial of two Libyans in the 1988 bombing of Pan Am Flight
103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, adjourned until May 23 so the two
sides could discuss speeding up proceedings. The trial, expected to
last a year or more, might be shorter if both could agree on items
of evidence found in the tons of debris. Days have been spent on
bits of a suitcase, charred clothes and the cassette recorder
believed to have had the bomb inside.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: DEPUTY TO LONDON'S MAYOR
</P>
<P>
   Nicky Gavron, a Labor Party councilor and a supporter of Prime
Minister Tony Blair, will become the deputy to Ken Livingstone, the
new mayor of London, who was opposed by Blair. Gavron said she
accepted the post only after Livingstone dropped plans to bring a
court challenge against Blair's plan for partial privatization of
the city's subway system.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: TALK SHOW HOST FACES CENSORSHIP
</P>
<P>
   Canadian radio stations will have to censor anti-gay remarks by
Laura Schlessinger, a conservative American talk show host, under a
ruling by the Canadian Broadcast Standards Council, a
self-regulatory group. It said Schlessinger, the target of a
boycott campaign by U.S. gay groups, broke Canada's broadcasting
code by being abusively biased against homosexuals. Canadian
stations that broadcast taped versions of the call-in show are
expected to excise anti-gay commentary beforehand.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: CHINESE DEPORTED
</P>
<P>
   In one of Canada's largest mass deportations, 90 illegal
migrants returned to China in a charter jet from British Columbia.
The deportees were among nearly 600 Chinese who were detained after
arriving illegally in ships on Canada's Pacific Coast last summer.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA: U.S. DELEGATION
</P>
<P>
   In what he called a sign of ``concern about the situation'' in
Colombia, the U.S. State Department's senior political official
arrived for his third visit in nine months. The delegation led by
Undersecretary Thomas Pickering is to hold two days of meetings
with President Andres Pastrana and other top officials in a bid to
coordinate an anti-narcotics strategy they say is being hampered by
the U.S. Congress' delays in approving a $1.7 billion emergency aid
package.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: CHALLENGER GAINS
</P>
<P>
   Vicente Fox, the main opposition candidate in the July 2
presidential election, has pulled slightly ahead of the governing
party's nominee, Francisco Labastida, according to a nationwide
opinion poll. The survey, commissioned by Reuters and carried out
by Zogby International, a New York research firm, said Fox was
supported by 46.3 percent of voters and Labastida by 41.6 percent.
The margin of error was plus or minus 3.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA: CORRUPTION ACCUSATIONS
</P>
<P>
   With a general election less than three weeks away, prosecutors
recommended that the chief political aide to President Hugo Chavez
be charged with corruption. The aide, Luis Miquilena, denied he
mismanaged official accounts and used his position to obtain
government contracts. Two aides to Chavez's main rival in the
election were also accused of enriching themselves illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   SRI LANKA: WAR TAX
</P>
<P>
   As fighting between government troops and separatist Tamil
rebels continued to rage in the northern Jaffna peninsula, the
government moved to raise an additional $161 million for its war
against the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam by raising taxes,
issuing treasury bills and increasing excise duties on cigarettes
and liquor.
</P>
<P>
   MALAYSIA: LEADER AFFIRMED
</P>
<P>
   The governing party, known as UMNO, reinstated Mahathir Mohamad
as its leader, assuring that he would face no political challenge
for the remaining three years on his term as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   SINGAPORE: HAZE RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the annual smog from fires in Indonesia set mostly
by illegal loggers and planters drifted over Singapore, smudging
the skies and tinging the air with the scent of woodsmoke. So far,
the smog does not approach the choking levels reached throughout
the region in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: WITHDRAWAL PROTESTED
</P>
<P>
   The northern border town of Metulla shut down in protest at
Israel's coming withdrawal of troops from Lebanon. Residents burned
tires and marched down their main street to the Lebanese border,
chanting, ``Security, security,'' to voice their concern that their
homes will become the front line in the battle between Hezbollah,
or Party of God, guerrillas and Israel.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
