<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REPUBS-PRIMARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS TO VOTE ON NEW PRIMARY SCHEDULE
</HEADLINE>
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS _ Setting the stage for a major vote Friday on a
new presidential primary system, a Republican committee acted on
Thursday to give its national party new authority to make rules and
punish states if they break them.
</P>
<P>
   The Rules Committee of the Republican National Committee will
vote Friday on a plan to have the least-populous states hold their
primaries first and the most-populous states go last, a proposal by
Bill Brock, a former senator from Tennessee and national party
chairman, that is intended to maintain voter interest throughout
the primaries. Brock said Thursday night that he expected the plan
to be adopted.
</P>
<P>
   That plan, which Brock argued would also give lesser-known
candidates with smaller financial resources a better chance to
compete for the nomination, was hotly debated on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Hellon of Arizona argued: ``If you don't get out of ahead
of the process, you're going to get rolled over by it. This is the
time to show some leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   And Diana Adams of Indiana, where the primary came after the
nominations had been decided on March 7, said, ``We ate everybody's
dust.''
</P>
<P>
   But Barbara Alby of California complained, ``The states at the
end of the calendar would never have a chance to influence the
process.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the media would declare someone a winner before then,
even if no one had majority of delegates. Under the plan, 12 large
states with about 47 percent of all delegates would vote last.
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker for a late state, Bill Powers of New York, spoke
for ``states' rights,' saying ``let the states pick the dates.''
</P>
<P>
   If the proposal is adopted by the committee, it must still go to
the full national committee, where chairman Jim Nicholson supports
the Brock plan, and then to the national convention, where big
states wary of the plan have great voting strength.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Thursday's votes marked a significant change in
Republican attitudes, as the complaints of committee members on the
losing side showed.
</P>
<P>
   Alby objected, ``We are not a party that operates as a top down,
command and control model.''
</P>
<P>
   Morton Blackwell of Virginia said it was a conservative
principle that ``Concentration and control of power in the national
party should be avoided wherever possible.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hellon said party rules, even the modest ones already in
force, would be ``irrelevant and academic'' without enforcement
powers.
</P>
<P>
   David Norcross of New Jersey argued for giving party leaders the
flexibility to change the rules between conventions. Without the
hope of negotiating a compromise with Democrats which that
flexibility would allow, he said, ``We are going very, very shortly
to be facing a national primary.''
</P>
<P>
   The new provisions voted would allow the national committee to
strip states of up to 90 percent of their delegates if they held
their primaries or caucuses earlier than the rules allow.
</P>
<P>
   They would also allow the national committee, up until Feb. 1 of
the year before a presidential election, to change the rules about
the timing of primaries. Now only the Republican convention can
change those rules.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
