<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DENVER-PAPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DENVER PAPERS TO COMBINE BUSINESS OPERATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After losing $123 million since 1990 in an unsuccessful effort
to win the country's fiercest newspaper war, the owners of The
Denver Rocky Mountain News announced on Thursday that they intended
to combine their business operations with those of The Denver Post,
effectively ceding victory to The Post's owner, William Dean
Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement ending the war would leave the Denver area with
two newspapers that would compete journalistically but split their
profits equally. To gain its 50 percent share, the E.W. Scripps
Co., the owner of The News, is paying $60 million to Singleton's
MediaNews Group, the owner of The Post.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed joint operating agreement is subject to Justice
Department approval, under the terms of a 30-year-old law that
allows newspapers to skirt antitrust provisions in order to
maintain two editorial voices in a community. If approved, the
Denver arrangement would be the first new joint operating agreement
in 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kenneth W. Lowe, the president and chief operating officer of
Scripps, said at a news conference on Thursday that the losses,
averaging more than $12 million a year, were ``not a situation
Scripps could sustain.'' Scripps is a public company with interests
in newspapers, broadcast television stations and cable television
channels like the Food Network. MediaNews is privately held.
</P>
<P>
   The two newspapers together employ more than 3,600 people, with
1,785 at The News and 1,870 at The Post. In a news release, Scripps
said, ``It is currently anticipated that any need to eliminate
positions will be done primarily through attrition.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement brought gloom to the newsroom of The News, a
tabloid. In recent years, the newspaper has expanded its business
coverage and competed fiercely on breaking news like the murder of
JonBenet Ramsey, last year's killings at Columbine High School and
the sale of a local sports arena. ``People are upset,'' one
reporter said.
</P>
<P>
   Each newspaper won a Pulitzer Prize for Columbine coverage last
year. The Post won in the breaking news category, The News for
breaking news photography.
</P>
<P>
   The aggressive editorial competition was matched, or exceeded,
by an economic competition that led both newspapers to lower their
subscription prices to as little as a penny, cutting circulation
revenues by as much as two-thirds.
</P>
<P>
   The price drop, which began almost three years ago, helped pump
up the two newspapers' circulations; the latest daily figures _
446,465 for The News and 413,720 for The Post _ put both in the
ranks of the country's top 25 daily newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   But The News could not translate its circulation gains,
including a 25 percent increase in the most recent report from the
Audit Bureau of Circulations, into profits, Lowe said. The paper
had enjoyed only ``a modest increase in advertising.'' Scripps
also, he said, has ``not been able to turn circulation gains into
operating profits.''
</P>
<P>
   William R. Burleigh, Scripps' chief executive, was to travel to
Washington on Friday to give the Justice Department a statement
declaring The News ``in probable danger of financial failure,''
Lowe said.
</P>
<P>
   Both The News and The Post would continue their daily
publication schedules. On Saturday, the editorial staff of The News
would produce a broadsheet newspaper under both mastheads. The
Post's newsroom would produce the Sunday newspaper, the best-read
newspaper of the week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-11-00 2318EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
