<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ABOUT AN ASSIST FOR APTITUDE?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ There's always got to be a wise guy. So
right on cue, and right in character, Bobby Frankel stepped forward
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the horse racing nation is planning a coronation
parade for Kentucky Derby winner Fusaichi Pegasus. Frankel is ready
to drop a banana peel in his path.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a great, great horse, possibly,'' the Hall of
Fame trainer said in the morning at his Hollywood Park barn. ``But
he had a pretty good horse chasing him, too.''
</P>
<P>
   That pretty good horse is Aptitude, the Frankel-trained colt who
rallied for third place behind Fusaichi Pegasus in the April 15
Wood Memorial at New York's Aqueduct racetrack and second in last
Saturday's Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel reads about the Derby and wonders if he missed something
that afternoon at Churchill Downs. Was Fusaichi Pegasus the only
horse on the track?
</P>
<P>
   ``What did he beat me by, five f------ lengths?'' the
Brooklyn-born trainer said sarcastically.
</P>
<P>
   No, Fusaichi Pegasus beat Aptitude by 1 moderate lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was right on his tail,'' Frankel said with a shrug.
</P>
<P>
   This is what the 2000 Triple Crown season needed. A dissenting
view.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gotta stir it up a little bit,'' Frankel said. ``Hey, I got an
opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the victory by Fusaichi Pegasus and jockey Kent
Desormeaux, the first by a Derby favorite since Spectacular Bid in
1979, the consensus has been that only injury or bad luck can stop
the winner from the first Triple Crown sweep since Affirmed in
1978.
</P>
<P>
   It !ital!was a superb performance. And Frankel doesn't mean to
knock Fusaichi Pegasus. But he rejects some of the conventional
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Did Fusaichi Pegasus have to overcome a bad trip in the Derby as
he rallied from 15th? Frankel maintains that, on the contrary, he
benefited from running most of the race on the firmest part of the
track, next to the rail; only as he turned into the stretch did he
angle seven-wide. Meanwhile, Aptitude and jockey Alex Solis had to
go wide earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kent took the gamble and got through (traffic) all the way.
Alex took the safe way and lost ground,'' Frankel said. ``If
anybody had got in front of Kent, I'd have won. . . . I'm not
saying I should have won it. I'm saying I could have won it.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel points out that the Sheets, which rate horses'
performances based on final clockings adjusted for factors such as
ground lost on the turns, gave Fusaichi Pegasus and Aptitude
identical 1's for the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Did Fusaichi Pegasus, unwhipped in the final three-sixteenths of
a mile, win with a lot left in the tank? ``How do you run that fast
and win easy?'' Frankel said. The winner ran the sixth-fastest
Derby (1 milesin 2:01).
</P>
<P>
   Is it impossible to see how Fusaichi Pegasus can get beat at the
May 20 Preakness, in Baltimore, and the July 10 Belmont Stakes, in
New York? ``He's coming back in two weeks and he's facing some
fresh faces,'' Frankel said.
</P>
<P>
   As of Thursday, seven 3-year-olds, three of whom did not run in
the Derby, were scheduled to challenge Fusaichi Pegasus in the
Preakness: Red Bullet, Wheelaway (fifth in the Derby), Captain
Steve (eighth), High Yield (15th), Hal's Hope (16th), Snuck In
(second in the Arkansas Derby) and Hugh Hefner (the Ed Nahem-owned
California-bred who was second in the Snow Chief Stakes at
Hollywood Park last time out).
</P>
<P>
   This assumes trainer Neil Drysdale will ultimately commit to the
Preakness after making sure Fusaichi Pegasus is 100 percent healthy
following the Derby. Drysdale upgraded the horse's chances of being
at Pimlico from ``possible'' to ``probable'' on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The eight-horse field would match the smallest for the Preakness
since seven ran in 1986, the year Snow Chief and Solis bounced back
to beat Derby winners Ferdinand and Bill Shoemaker.
</P>
<P>
   For all of Frankel's bravado, Aptitude won't run in the
Preakness, waiting for the Belmont, where the trainer hopes the
extra rest and the 1-mile distance will move his colt forward and
prove his point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why should I run my horse (in the Preakness)?'' said Frankel,
who plans to train Aptitude at Hollywood Park. ``He's a young
horse. I want to have something for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, he said, it's Fusaichi Pegasus and Drysdale who have
something to gain by running in every Triple Crown event.
</P>
<P>
   In the absence of the Derby runnerup, the Preakness second
choice is likely to be the Wood Memorial runnerup. That's Red
Bullet, who skipped the Derby so trainer Joe Orseno would have a
``fresh horse.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get my horse into the race at his best,'' Orseno
said. ``If we do that, in my heart I believe we can win the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Frankel and the Derby, Orseno looks at the Wood and sees
how it might have turned out differently. Solis, riding Red Bullet
then, put the colt closer to the pace than the trainer would have
preferred.
</P>
<P>
   Orseno maintains that if he'd lagged early, Red Bullet would
have been able to stay with Fusaichi Pegasus late. He's encouraged
by Aptitude's sharp performance in the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   ``His being able to lose the ground he did, and only get beat
the margin he did, makes me feel good about my chances,'' Orseno
said on the phone from New York. ``I think my horse is better than
Aptitude.''
</P>
<P>
   But that's a debate for another day. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOLLYWOOD PARK LEADERS &QL; 
Jockeys (through Wednesday): Kent Desormeaux, 9 wins; Victor
Espinoza, 8; Tyler Baze and Garrett Gomez, 7; Laffit Pincay, 6.
Trainers: John Sadler, 7; Richard Mandella, 5; Bob Baffert, Julio
Canani, Paddy Gallagher and Cliff Sise, 3. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
PINCAY WATCH &QL; 
Laffit Pincay couldn't take advantage of the absence of many of
Hllywood Park's other top jockeys on Kentucky Derby day, finishing
second with four horses Saturday, but he came back with a $22.80
winner Sunday, his 8,913rd. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ON THE STAKES SCHEDULE &QL; 
__ At Hollywood Park: Saturday, $150,000 Mervyn LeRoy Handicap,
3-year-olds and up, 1 1/16 miles; Sunday, $100,000 Wilshire
Handicap, fillies and mares 3 and up, 1 mile on turf.
</P>
<P>
   __ At Golden Gate Fields: Saturday, $100,000 Oakland Handicap,
3-year-oldsand up, 6 furlongs.
</P>
<P>
   __ At Pimlico: Saturday, $750,000 Pimlico Special, 3-year-olds
and up, 1 3/16 miles.
</P>
<P>
   __ At Sportsman's Park: Saturday, $500,000 Illinois Derby,
3-year-olds, 1 1/8 miles. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
MILEPOSTS &QL; 
Budroyale and Alex Solis go to Baltimore for the Pimlico Special on
Saturday. They're in an eight-horse field that includes 1999
Belmont winner Lemon Drop Kid (Edgar Prado) and Breeders' Cup
Classic winner Cat Thief(Pat Day). . . . Puerto Madero (Laffit
Pincay) will try to break a six-race losing streak in Saturday's
Mervyn LeRoy. . . . Jockey Richard Migliore received a five-day
suspension from Churchill Downs stewards after allowing Wheelaway
to swerve in front of Captain Steve in the stretch of the Kentucky
Derby. There was no disqualification because Wheelaway finished
fifth, out of the Derby purse money. Captain Steve finished eighth.
. . . The California Horse Racing Board announced it has declined
to adopt the recommendations by administrative law judges that
clenbuterol medication cases against trainers Paco Gonzalez,
Darrell Vienna and Bruce Headley be thrown out. The CHRB is asking
for more evidence.
</P>
</TEXT>
