<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALL-STREET-PERKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH JOINS PUSH TO IMPROVE EMPLOYEE PERKS
</HEADLINE>
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. has joined the rush of Wall
Street firms offering perks and risk-free investment opportunities
to attract young investment bankers and prevent others from
defecting to Internet companies.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill, one of the nation's biggest securities firms, is
building a fitness center for employees near its headquarters in
lower Manhattan and providing a concierge service to handle chores
like shopping and laundry. The firm also hopes to lock in
investment bankers by giving them chances to invest _ with a
financial sweetener from the firm _ in new-economy companies that
are still private.
</P>
<P>
   The moves, some of which Merrill announced internally on
Thursday, are the latest in a series of efforts by Wall Street
firms to stem defections. The firms are still developing these
benefits despite the recent weakness in technology stocks and
rising doubts about many Internet businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the fever pitch has died down,'' said Mary Taylor, a
senior vice president at Merrill. ``People are a little more
even-keeled about it and not just saying, `I have to go to a
dot-com.'''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Wall Street executives say the competition for people
with strong analytical skills remains fierce. To compete, some
firms are simply raising salaries. But most are trying to devise
incentives that will have a minimal impact on their firms'
quarterly income if the stock market remains shaky.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's mid-level to senior investment bankers will be able to
invest as much as $1 million of their own money in a new
private-equity fund with a focus on companies in technology, media
and telecommunications. For each dollar an employee invests, the
firm will put in $2 and let the employee keep the return on the
full amount.
</P>
<P>
   Younger bankers who are not qualified to _ or cannot afford to _
invest their own money will receive options worth as much as
$100,000 on shares in the fund next month. Those options will give
bankers in their first few years out of college or business school
the chance to reap big gains without putting up any money. The
catch is that they have to stay around to collect the gains when
they are distributed.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor described those benefits are ``more cost-effective and
efficient'' than increasing salaries or cash bonuses. She declined
to say how Merrill would account for them but hinted that they were
designed to have a limited impact on the firm's reported
compensation expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group, which recently handed out shares of its own
stock to 8,000 junior employees, and Credit Suisse First Boston are
drawing up similar plans.
</P>
<P>
   Some investment banks, including Lehman Brothers Holdings and
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette, have offered senior bankers similar
leveraged investment opportunities for years. Now, they and other
firms are spreading the potential wealth more broadly to retain the
young bankers who are most likely to be enticed by the prospect of
quicker riches.
</P>
<P>
   Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette shook up the industry a few weeks
ago when it offered hefty guaranteed pay for two years to young
bankers who would sign agreements not to go to work for
competitors. But other big firms have declined to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Locking in base salaries and bonuses for two years, given the
uncertainties of the market, is not the prudent thing to do,'' said
Alicia Whitaker, a managing director at Credit Suisse First Boston.
``We continue to believe that a high percentage of variable
compensation is what's appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitaker said her firm's recent increase of base salaries to
$55,000 from $40,000 for first-year bankers, and to $65,000 from
$45,000 for second-year bankers, shows that the firm is committed
to paying some of the highest base salaries in the industry. Those
raises, in turn, will drive up salaries through the rest of the
investment bank, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm is also planning to offer private-equity investments to
bankers all the way down to the lowest levels, Whitaker said,
because the tug of war among investment banks and dot-com companies
rages on. ``We'd love to think that it's over,'' she said, ``but
our people are still getting calls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
