</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLIONMOM-MARCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPORT FOR GUN CONTROL HAS DECLINED, SURVEY SHOWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Against the political backdrop of Sunday's Million
Mom March for gun control, a new poll shows that overall support
for restrictions on guns has declined in the last two months,
mostly because men have grown increasingly sympathetic toward the
rights of gun owners.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by the Pew Research Center for The People
and The Press, found that the gender gap on the gun issue is
getting bigger. When asked what is more important, 49 percent of
the men said the rights of gun owners, while 46 percent said gun
control. In contrast, 28 percent of the women said the rights of
gun owners were more important, while 67 percent said gun control
was.
</P>
<P>
   Men over 50 were particularly supportive of gun owners' rights;
55 percent said those rights were more important than gun control,
a sharp increase from the 37 percent who said that two months ago.
The poll found that women were strong supporters of gun control
regardless of age.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, 57 percent of the public put the priority on gun
restrictions in the new poll, 38 percent on the rights of gun
owners. A Pew survey in March found that 66 percent support gun
restrictions, 29 percent gun owners' rights.
</P>
<P>
   After the shooting last year at Columbine High School, which
left 15 dead, many pollsters found support for gun control soared.
But Andrew Kohut, director of the Pew Poll, said the latest survey
hints at a pro-gun backlash among men, and suggests the
effectiveness of campaigns by groups like the National Rifle
Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Second Amendment proponents are campaigning,
they're clearly making a case with their constituents _ white men _
and it's having some effect,'' Kohut said.
</P>
<P>
   The poll also found that Americans are skeptical about the
chances of Congress passing major gun legislation this year; only
14 percent said it was very likely, 34 percent said it was somewhat
likely. And 10 percent had heard a lot about the Million Mom March,
while 42 percent had heard a little.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted May 2 to 6 and was based on a sample of
1,303 adults, with a margin of sampling error of plus or minus
three percentage points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
