<DOCNO> NYT20000511.0483 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-05-11 23:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2778 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-SENATE-DEBATE-NYT &LR;      05-11 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-SENATE-DEBATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIO PUTS CORZINE ON THE DEFENSIVE IN THEIR FIRST DEBATE
</HEADLINE>
  By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ After enduring an eight-week barrage of costly
television commercials by Jon Corzine, his opponent in the
Democratic primary, former Gov. Jim Florio, seized control of their
first debate Thursday, forcing Corzine on the defensive for a full
hour as the two men showed why theirs is perhaps the most
captivating Senate race outside New York.
</P>
<P>
   Florio, who had to wait nearly a year for the chance to debate
his rival, made the most of the opportunity, ridiculing Corzine's
proposals, likening his views to those of Republican politicians
and repeatedly attacking his main qualification for the Senate: his
record as the former co-chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co.
</P>
<P>
   But Corzine, an unpolished speaker who had seemed reluctant to
attack Florio personally, criticized the former governor for
raising taxes by $2.8 billion during the 1990 recession, a decision
that cost Florio his job and led to a Republican takeover of the
state Legislature. ``I think we took a problem and made it a
crisis,'' Corzine said.
</P>
<P>
   In his prepared opening statement, Corzine sought to cast Florio
as a bad memory best forgotten. ``People can embrace the past
without embracing its failures,'' he said. ``The voters of New
Jersey are looking to the future, and the Democratic Party should
as well.''
</P>
<P>
   But when their exchanges were extemporaneous, Florio was far
more effective. When Corzine tried to talk about the specifics of
what he calls his ``bold ideas,'' for example, Florio delivered a
withering retort: ``Words,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bold is about taking on the gun lobby,'' Florio said. ``Bold
is raising the money to finance education for our children. Bold is
going out and making sure that we have a clean environment by
taking on corporate polluters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rhetoric is rhetoric, words are words,'' he added. ``This is
not bold; this is baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate Thursday was the first chance for most New Jerseyans
to see the two Democratic candidates side by side, and it gave
Florio, who has not yet been able to afford his own television ads,
a chance to address a broad audience of voters.
</P>
<P>
   The debate was taped in Trenton for broadcast Thursday night on
the New Jersey Network, a state-owned group of public television
and radio stations that sponsored the event with The New York
Times. It will be shown again on Sunday at 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Florio held a wide lead in the polls against Corzine, a newcomer
to politics, until Corzine started his ad campaign in mid-March and
began steadily eroding that gap. Officials in both campaigns say
the former governor holds an edge of about only 6 percentage points
among likely Democratic voters, and they expect the race to be
close right up until the primary on June 6.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout Thursday's encounter, Corzine tried several times to
outline his ideas for universal health care, long-term care for the
elderly or disabled, and education, and Florio belittled them as
unrealistic and too expensive. But the two men focused far more on
their backgrounds in business and politics than on their proposals.
</P>
<P>
   When Corzine spoke in favor of gun control measures, for
example, Florio zeroed in on Goldman Sachs' links to gun
manufacturers, saying the firm had advised the makers of Smith &AMP;
Wesson, Remington and Ruger firearms in various transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine first denied he had led Goldman Sachs while it was
advising those companies, then said that the stocks of companies
that make guns occasionally ``flow through our portfolios provided
for the investors.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio responded: ``Jon is getting very good at the political
art of squirming off the hook. We're not talking about trading
stocks, we're talking about raising capital to go into gun
manufacturing companies. And through this whole last decade, Jon
was either the CEO or he was a member of the nine-member management
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   Florio's attacks were so persistent that Corzine at one point
felt compelled to defend his former employer. ``I'm proud of my
record at Goldman Sachs; I'm proud of Goldman Sachs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine offered his most extended rebuke of Florio for raising
taxes in 1990, after promising as a candidate the year before that
he would not. Had he been in Florio's shoes, Corzine said, he would
never have made such a promise. And he would not have raised the
sales tax, the ``most regressive'' kind of tax, in any case, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor, you told the New Jersey public that you would look
at the $12.6 billion state budget and find savings,'' Corzine said,
adding that Florio's actions evinced ``a ready, fire, aim
attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, Florio called Corzine's recollection ``an Orwellian
rewriting of history,'' and questioned how Corzine would have
replaced the sales tax revenue. ``Jon just took $700 million out of
the equation,'' he said. ``That's fine, but I'm still waiting for
him to say what he would have done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
