<HEADLINE>
KART GROUPS NEGOTIATING FOR WEEKLY RACING SCHEDULE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Two karting organizations are negotiating to
hold racing events at Irwindale Speedway in August. Superkarts USA
and Southern California Sprinters would like to race on the track's
asphalt infield, speedway general manager Bob DeFazio said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They liked how good the surface is,'' DeFazio said.
</P>
<P>
   The track, which is negotiating with various parties to build
and operate a world-class facility in the parking lot, held a
practice last week in the speedway infield and along turns 1 and 2
of the half-mile oval. Twenty-eight karts raced the course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we had a fabulous response,'' DeFazio said. ``It was
all word of mouth. We're trying to see if this is do-able on a
weekly basis. We're just trying to see if people like it.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio says the speedway will probably hold another practice
session next Thursday with the same format. The track would open at
some point after 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 100 kart racers live in the San Gabriel Valley,
according to driver Ken Madison of Monrovia, and a permanent
facility would be ideal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adams (in Riverside) is as rough as a cob and it's a long ways
to Willow Springs (in Rosamond),'' he said. ``Guys need a facility
that is close to here, so hopefully, they can do something.''
</P>
<P>
   DeFazio says he has been working with Italian karters on the
design of a track.
</P>
<P>
   One driver who would like to see this happen is Al Arciero. One
of the partners in the speedway, Arciero took part in last week's
practice session. But he says that even though he favors the
building of a track, he has no say in the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all what (CEO) Jim Williams wants,'' he said. ``He knows
how important it is to nurture young drivers and he knows how
important it is from a business aspect. If he puts a kart track in,
great. But he has to have the business aspect to back up a go-kart
track.''
</P>
<P>
   __ SRL returns: Davey Hamilton's Supermodified Racing League
will return to the speedway, along with the American Racing Truck
National Championship Finals.
</P>
<P>
   The SRL, which raced on April 1, will return on Oct. 21. Troy
Regier set a track record of 118.781 mph, 15.154 seconds during
qualifying.
</P>
<P>
   The ART National Championships _ also held at the speedway last
year _ will again be a two-day affair with qualifying and heat
races on Friday, Nov. 3, and the finals on Nov. 4. The series will
also race at the speedway on June 17, Aug. 26 and Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   __ Featured races: NASCAR Late Models will be the featured
series in Saturday's card, which gets underway at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Super Stocks, the MSRA Pro-4 Modifieds, USAC
three-quarter midgets and figure-8s will also be racing.
</P>
<P>
   Radio personality Rick Minyard will make his Irwindale debut in
the MSRA class. Minyard is the co-host of a nationally syndicated
talk radio show, broadcast on KRLA-1110 AM in the L.A. area.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of Mother's Day, all moms will be allowed to take a lap
around the track after Saturday's racing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
